<HEADLINE>
MAYOR SHOWS OFF HIS CITY TO BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani escorted Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas on a tour of what was clearly ``Rudy's New York'' on
Wednesday, taking the Republican presidential candidate to a Queens
welfare-turned-jobs-center, a firefighters' memorial service and an
Italian restaurant for a pizza lunch on a Bedlam-like Arthur Avenue
in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Although the mayor's aides called it ``the governor's day,'' the
itinerary, was meant to show off the mayor's strengths as he
prepares to run for the U.S. Senate against his almost-certain
opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was also accompanied on the last day of a three-day
trip to New York by Gov. George Pataki, seemed a happy participant
in the mayor's ambitions. Giuliani formally endorsed Bush last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Standing behind me are the pillars of the strength of the
Republican Party here in New York,'' Bush said at the Queens Job
Center in Long Island City while Pataki, and particularly Giuliani,
beamed periodically. After saying that he was honored that Pataki
is supporting him _ the governor endorsed Bush in May _ Bush added:
``I'm honored that the future senator is standing by my side as
well. I leave this state upbeat about my chances. I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Pataki heaped praise on Giuliani at the jobs
center, where the mayor flanked a chart showing the decline in
welfare since he took office.
</P>
<P>
   After the jobs center, the two governors and one mayor departed
for ground zero of Giuliani's constituency, some 7,000 firefighters
assembled in front of the Fireman's Monument in Riverside Park in
Manhattan. The occasion was the New York City Fire Department's
annual memorial service in honor of firefighters who have died on
the job during the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Although all three politicians spoke at the service _ Bush said
the firefighters ``have paid the cost of courage, and they have
climbed to heaven on the flames'' _ it was Giuliani who spoke the
most directly to the firefighters' families.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the ``extraordinary'' people of the Fire Department
needed heroes like those who had died, and that ``I know that the
firefighters that we're particularly remembering today didn't
become that way by accident.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't happen by luck or by good fortune,'' he said. ``It
happened because you loved them, brought them up, taught them to be
extraordinary men.''
</P>
<P>
   The next stop was billed as a ``walking tour'' of Arthur Avenue
in the Belmont section of the Bronx, but it immediately
deteriorated into a kind of moving scrimmage of television cameras
and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, hey, ho, ho, Pataki's got to go!'' shouted about two
dozen mental health attendants from Local 401 of the Civil Service
Employees Association, who said they were angry over a contract
dispute with the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the politicians had pizza at Giovanni's, where
Bridget DeSantis, 85, a Republican from the Woodlawn section of the
Bronx, was waiting outside on the sidewalk to shake Bush's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks just like his father,'' she marveled, referring to
the Texas governor's resemblance to former President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the kind of association that no doubt would be opera to
the ears of City Hall officials, she declared: ``He's going to get
my vote! George! Giuliani!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
