<HEADLINE>
POVERTY RATE PERSISTS IN CITY DESPITE BOOM
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite the strongest economy in years, nearly one
out of four New York City residents had incomes below the federal
government's poverty threshold last year, a rate that has barely
dipped since the last recession and that is twice as high as the
national average, a new analysis of poverty in the city concludes.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis, based on figures from house-to-house surveys by
the Census Bureau, was released on Wednesday by the Community
Service Society of New York, an advocacy group for the poor that
has been tracking city poverty rates for decades.
</P>
<P>
   But the finding that the city's economic boom is not lifting the
poor along with the well off echoes recent studies by the Federal
Reserve Bank of New York and the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best economy the country has seen since the late
60s,'' said Mark K. Levitan, who analyzed the census data for the
Community Service Society. ``It's not going to get any better than
this. And we're still in a situation where a quarter of the city's
population is in poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, for the third year since 1994, more than a million
Americans moved above the poverty line, defined as below $16,665 a
year for a household of four. But in New York City, where the
recovery has been gathering steam since 1996, 1.8 million are
officially poor, as many or more than in the early 1990s, during
the last recession.
</P>
<P>
   Rae Rosen, regional economist with the Federal Reserve Bank of
New York, said the Community Service Society's findings on poverty
should be understood in light of the city's 6.9 percent
unemployment rate, which remains high compared with 4.5 percent for
the nation, as well as its high rate of immigration, which adds to
a mismatch between the low level of skills and education of the
least successful job seekers and the rising demands of new service
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would agree that there are a group of people at the very
bottom that have been bypassed by this economy that has been pretty
robust,'' Ms. Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   But city officials disputed the significance of the figures,
noting the number of jobs created in recent years and their efforts
to move New Yorkers from welfare to work ``The quality of life in
New York City is higher than it's been in years,'' said Edward
Skyler, a spokesman for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. ``Three hundred and
thirty thousand new jobs have been created in the last five years,
as opposed to the 320,000 jobs that were lost in the early 90s.
People are moving from welfare to self-sufficiency in record
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Impartial observers recognize that there has been a
renaissance and revitalization in every borough that is a model for
cities around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Solidelle Wasser, a senior economist with the Bureau of
Labor Statistics, said Census Bureau data on poverty rates in the
largest metropolitan areas around the country supported the view
that New York's economy was lagging behind in lifting the incomes
of the poor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
