<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. COLUMN: A REPUBLICAN EXERCISES SOME FINESSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Rev. Floyd Flake introduced Texas Gov.
George W. Bush to this city's conservative establishment Tuesday,
it was probably the first time in the history of the Manhattan
Institute for Policy Research that a luncheon speaker was described
as ``my homeboy.'' And that was not the most incongruous moment of
the day for a Republican from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush visited an elementary school in Harlem, advocated spending
more federal money on education and sounded a little like Hillary
Rodham Clinton during his luncheon speech at the New York Sheraton.
He didn't mention anything about a village, but he did declare
passionately: ``Our nation has a moral duty to insure that no child
_ I mean  &UR; no &LR;  child _ is left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Could a Republican really be serious about education? Many
voters, especially in New York, would dismiss Bush's compassionate
rhetoric as political pandering. In a way it was, but not
necessarily in the way that voters think.
</P>
<P>
   When asked which party can do a better job of improving schools,
voters overwhelmingly prefer Democrats, according to a poll by the
Pugh Research Center. The Democrats have long been admired for
their determination to allocate more money to public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusted for inflation, spending on the average American public
school pupil has doubled in the last three decades, according to
the National Center for Education Statistics. But the money has not
brought obvious improvement. As a result, many reformers are
considering bigger changes, like the charter schools and voucher
plans that New York's Republicans have been championing.
</P>
<P>
   Local Democrats and union leaders have put up fierce resistance,
but these reforms seem to be gaining favor, especially outside New
York. The current issue of Blueprint, the journal of the centrist
Democratic Leadership Council, wholeheartedly endorses charter
schools and advises Democrats to ``stop opposing school reform
ideas just because some Republicans like them.''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of those ideas in Bush's speech: reduce
regulation of schools, make them compete for dollars and students,
finance the construction of charter schools, get money directly to
students and parents. It left the conservatives buzzing about
education as a possible new wedge issue.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Reagan Democrats who had defected over the issues of
crime and welfare, and the Republican soccer moms driven to
President Clinton by their party's stance against abortion, maybe
Democratic parents could flee to a Republican promising better
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the National Education Association could turn into the
Democrats' version of the Christian Coalition: a powerful special
interest that alienates voters. Teachers keep the party opposed to
vouchers, but they don't cast as many votes as parents and
grandparents, whose support for school vouchers has been growing.
Support is especially strong among Hispanic and black voters, whose
defection would be a major blow to Democrats. Flake's enthusiasm
for Bush may not be shared yet by many of his fellow
African-Americans, but his support for vouchers is.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to Bush's pleas, the conservative intellectuals
and business leaders could righteously believe their candidate to
be standing up for children and the working classes. But there was
an underlying problem with the speech.
</P>
<P>
   However much conservatives may want to rescue children, they
usually do not think that any president can do the job. They favor
local control of schools. After arguing for the devolution of power
_ the liberation of New York City's schools from the bureaucrats in
Albany and at Board of Education headquarters in Brooklyn _ it's
inconsistent for them to put great faith in any reform coming out
of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And however much Bush wants to reform schools as president, he
won't have the money or the power to do it. The federal government
provides only 8 percent of the money spent in public schools. Like
crime, the issue is far more important on the campaign trail than
in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps the speech was mainly an exercise in political
finesse: a demonstration that a Republican could learn the
Clintonesque art of co-copting the other side's symbolic issue.
Clinton had demonstrated how to win by sounding tough on crime. Now
Bush was looking for victory by sounding soft on education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
