<SLUG> BC-DOCUMENT-THEFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN OFFERING RARE PAPERS SERVED TIME FOR THEIR THEFT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (rk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last Friday, Basil A. Panagopulos, an autograph
dealer in Greenwich, Conn., got a phone call from a man who wanted
to sell some rare documents, including papers of Thomas Alva Edison
and presidents Thomas Jefferson and James Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said: `Can you bring them in? I'd like to see them,'''
Panagopulos said. ``He said, `Sure, I can be there in an hour and a
half.'''
</P>
<P>
   But before his visitor arrived, Panagopulos made some phone
calls, and became suspicious that the materials were valuable maps
and other documents stolen from Columbia University in 1994. A man
named Daniel Spiegelman had been arrested, convicted and sent to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The dealer's suspicions were correct.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in Manhattan said in a complaint on Monday
that the papers were indeed part of the collection stolen from
Columbia, and that the man offering to sell them in Greenwich last
week was none other than Spiegelman, who was completing his
sentence in a halfway house in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Spiegelman was arrested by the Greenwich police on Friday, and a
state Superior Court judge in Stamford on Monday ordered him held
in $250,000 bail, according to a report on Tuesday in The Greenwich
Time. The newspaper said that Spiegelman entered a plea of not
guilty to larceny and other charges.
</P>
<P>
   The federal complaint by the U.S. attorney, Mary Jo White,
charged Spiegelman with one count of interstate transportation of
stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer who represented Spiegelman at the Connecticut hearing
could not be reached Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The federal complaint, filed in District Court in Manhattan,
where Spiegelman is expected to be transferred, said the documents
were worth about $100,000, and also included letters by presidents
John Quincy Adams, Andrew Jackson and James Knox Polk.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a manuscript, circa 1504, signed by Henry VII of
England, said Jean W. Ashton, director of the Rare Book and
Manuscript Library at Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the recovery of the papers, Ms. Ashton said, roughly
one-quarter of the stolen documents are still missing. These
include medieval and Renaissance manuscripts, more than 200 maps
that had been removed with a razor from a 17th-century Dutch atlas,
and a document signed by President John Adams.
</P>
<P>
   When Spiegelman was originally sentenced to five years in prison
last year after pleading guilty to stealing the manuscripts, the
case drew widespread attention because the federal judge, Lewis A.
Kaplan, said he was imposing a harsher sentence than he might have
under federal guidelines because of the unique nature of the stolen
property, and the loss to history.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan told Spiegelman that he had ``deprived a generation of
scholars and students of the irreplaceable raw materials by which
they seek to discern the lessons of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The case was different, Kaplan said, ``from a simple theft of
money or other easily replaceable property.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
