<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9259 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS     10-07 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ Bring on Tom Glavine.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mix in a little John Smoltz and maybe even another dose of Greg
Maddux _ anyone except Kevin Millwood, who left a taste in the
Astros' mouths more bitter than any medicine Atlanta's more
celebrated pitchers could have prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Astros hope so.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood, often the forgotten man of the Braves' rotation,
turned in one of the most unforgettable pitching performances in
playoff history Wednesday, tossing a one-hitter in a 5-1 victory
over the Astros in Game 2 of their National League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves pulled even in the best-of-five series, which shifts
to the Astrodome for games Friday and Saturday. If a fifth game is
necessary, it will be played Sunday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I said we can't afford to get too carried away
after we won the first game,'' Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell
said. ``You have to remember that these are the Atlanta Braves.
There's a reason they won 103 games this season. They have a great
club, and they can throw a top-notch pitcher at you every game.''
</P>
<P>
   You could take shots at the Astros' offense, something that
became a pastime during the last two postseasons, but that would be
misguided fire. You could question some of the pitching decisions
manager Larry Dierker made late in the game, but that would be
running away from the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, the Astros weren't going to win this game _ not the way
Millwood was pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a no-hitter by one of the Braves' other pitchers, the
Astros can take solace in the fact they probably encountered the
best pitching performance they'll see in this series. Millwood
allowed the fewest hits in a postseason complete game since
Boston's Jim Lonborg pitched a one-hitter against St. Louis in the
1967 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood, 24, couldn't have spotted his fastball more accurately
with a remote control. That and his Darryl Kile-caliber curve kept
the Astros off balance.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who was surprised by the masterful display of pitching
hasn't been paying attention to Millwood, who compiled a
major-league-best .202 opponents' batting average this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, having been the victims of a seven-inning, two-hit
effort by Millwood in June, knew exactly how difficult Wednesday's
task would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people (outside baseball) might not know about this
guy, but I guarantee you every single player in the game knows what
Kevin Millwood is capable of doing,'' Bagwell said. ``The guy is
just nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   The only mistake Millwood made Wednesday wasn't much of a
mistake at all. Ken Caminiti did a good job of redirecting a
fastball over the inside portion of the plate for a solo homer in
the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood quickly regrouped, retiring the next 15 batters before
Bagwell reached on an error in the seventh. He followed that by
setting down the last eight Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't throw a one-hitter every day,'' said Millwood, who
retired 27 of the 29 batters he faced. ``It was a lot of fun.
Everything was working. My fastball was good. My curveball was
good. My slider was good.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Braves' offense was good, too. They knocked 21-game
winner Jose Lima out of the game in a three-run seventh inning that
zapped the life out of the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Lima, who was making his first postseason appearance, allowed
four runs on nine hits in 6 innings.
</P>
<P>
   He was better than his pitching line might suggest, allowing
several broken-bat or seeing-eye singles. But the Braves lumped
together enough hits to hang a loss on the Astros righthander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed that we lost the game, but I can't be too
disappointed about the way I pitched,'' Lima said. ``My goal is
always to keep the team in the game and give us a chance to win,
and I think I did that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Millwood was just unbelievable today. You have to tip your
hat to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're Astros center fielder Carl Everett, who credits
pitchers about as often as it freezes in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't knock him,'' Everett said. ``If he's not throwing
his breaking balls for strikes, he's just a typical pitcher, but he
was getting his breaking stuff over and that made him tough. He
pitched a good game, and his team gave him support. We didn't
support our pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I didn't come here for a split; I came here to
take both games. But you have to be satisfied to win one. The
Braves didn't get down after they lost the first game, and we can't
get down because we lost this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves right fielder Brian Jordan put the Astros at an early
disadvantage with an RBI single in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti's second home run of the series tied the score in the
second, and Lima then matched zeros with Millwood until Eddie
Perez's sacrifice fly gave the Braves a 2-1 lead in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to win this game no matter what,'' Astros shortstop
Ricky Gutierrez said. ``Going back to the Dome down 0-2 would have
been tough for them. They came out and did what they had to do.
Now, we have to try to get the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker replaced Lima with Scott Elarton after Jordan's
seventh-inning sacrifice fly, and Elarton gave up RBI singles to
Ryan Klesko and Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to use Elarton was somewhat curious considering the
righthander had not pitched in relief since June 29 and shoulder
tendinitis has hampered his ability to get loose quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But Elarton offered no excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called (to the bullpen) in the seventh and told me to get
ready for Jordan,'' Elarton said. ``The bottom line is that I
didn't do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   It probably wouldn't have made much difference considering the
manner in which Millwood did his.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
