<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9260 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BELMONT-TESTS-2TAKES-     10-07 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELMONT-TESTS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TESTS SHOW HIGHER LEVEL OF GAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BETH BARRETT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Potentially deadly hydrogen sulfide has been
found at several new locations and in much higher concentrations
than previously known in the ground beneath the Belmont Learning
Center, the Daily News has learned.
</P>
<P>
   The new tests, the latest in a series to determine the extent of
the gases generated by a shallow oil field under the school, found
hydrogen sulfide in three times as many monitoring wells as was
found previously.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the levels of gas detected exceeded those found during two
previous tests by as much as 10 times, according to California
Department of Toxic Substances Control officials.
</P>
<P>
   The results mean more tests are required to determine whether
the higher concentrations show the gases are shifting beneath the
school, which could make remediation far more costly and difficult
for the Los Angeles Unified School District, state officials and
toxic experts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrogen sulfide, which smells like rotten eggs, is extremely
dangerous if it migrates through cracks in the soil and reaches the
air.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the amount that's in the soil got to the surface, people
would be extremely sick, if not dead,'' said Dr. Debbie Oudiz, a
state toxics scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, how much goes through the soil and how do we
ensure it doesn't get through the soil. We're doing additional
tests on that now.''
</P>
<P>
   DTSC-monitored air testing equipment at Belmont has not detected
dangerous levels of the hydrogen sulfide in the air, Oudiz said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamid Saebfar, DTSC's chief of Southern California's cleanup
operations branch, said the new test results require further study
to determine their full implications. He noted that some of the
tests could be ``aberrations'' as the result of the monitoring
wells not yet having reached equilibrium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly true the gases are there, it is not a fluke,''
he said. ``But we are still evaluating it before we make a
definitive statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The tests detected hydrogen sulfide in 22 vapor wells _ 15 more
than in previous tests _ with concentrations ranging from traces to
33,000 parts per million at 33 feet below left center field of the
proposed baseball field, Saebfar said. Those concentrations are
about 10 times higher than previously detected in a nearby well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty high,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Toxic officials said acute health problems can occur at levels
as low as 0.03 parts per million.
</P>
<P>
   In a June article, the Daily News revealed that high levels of
hydrogen sulfide had been detected around houses adjacent to
Belmont, with residents saying the problem had grown worse as
construction crews removed a mountain of earth to begin work on the
terraced school.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, members of the district's safety team and state
officials have conceded that the removal of some 500,000 cubic
yards of earth could have changed the migration pattern of the
potentially deadly gases.
</P>
<P>
   The board is awaiting a recommendation due Oct. 20 from the
independent Belmont Commission as to whether the $200 million
school can be safely completed at a reasonable cost.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Ruben Zacarias is scheduled to make his
recommendation on the school's fate to the commission today,
including his environmental assessment.
</P>
<P>
   State toxics officials are scheduled to make their presentation
to the commission Saturday. DTSC senior geologist Craig Christmann
said commissioners will get a ``big picture'' explanation of the
toxic trends based on a series of data, including the new tests.
</P>
<P>
   Board of Education President Genethia Hayes said the
commission's recommendation should take into account all toxics
information, including the concerns of state toxics officials, even
if conclusions are not fully formed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is more fluctuation at the site, if there is
apparently more volatility to the situation, does that change
things, does that weigh differently on the decision to be made?
Sure, it does, if it tells us it is not safe,'' Hayes said, saying
she was speaking only as a board member.
</P>
<P>
   ``If DTSC says, `We don't have a definitive answer but, boy, are
we concerned,' this is a new level of concern, then I'd have a new
level of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Commission David Beckman said that on their face, the new test
results were ``stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At a minimum, they suggest the site will be more difficult to
mitigate and will become even more expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Groveman, chief Belmont investigative attorney who
initially raised questions about the oil field, said the tests
remove any confidence the district can have in the stability of the
35-acre site.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: of the 35-acre site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pointed out that this is a very dynamic field,'' Groveman
said. ``The oil deposit and natural gas are there in endless
supplies, and they are very close to the surface. The geology is
fractured and very unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is entirely unacceptable in its present condition for a
school.''
</P>
<P>
   William Panos, the district's new director of the Environmental
Health and Safety Branch, said he hadn't seen the new results and
that it would be premature to discuss them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to see the protocols and all the appendices,'' Panos
said. ``Until I can see a complete report, it's difficult to
respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Groveman said the continuing test results only underscore the
``staggering incompetency'' of district officials to have properly
characterized the site before construction began.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the district's inspector general, Don Mullinax,
found massive wrongdoing and incompetence reaching to the highest
level of the district in connection with the scandal-ridden school,
recommending disciplinary action, up to termination, for a number
of district officials. Criminal referrals of the former school
board, the developer and five environmental firms also have been
made to various law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Groveman said the growing understanding of the site's
instability has tremendous implications for the amount of testing
that remains to be done, which will translate into delays and
greater expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Those tests _ which include a seismic characterization expected
to take at least three months, in addition to more soil studies _
must be done with the view that children are involved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Acceptable exposure rates for toxics like hydrogen sulfide are
established for adults, which are not adequate ``for the unique
physiology of children,'' Groveman said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, because the entire site appears be fractured, providing
potential paths for hydrogen sulfide to reach the surface, the
entire property might need to be sealed, said Angelo Bellomo,
chairman of the district's safety team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If hydrogen sulfide shows up on a number of sites, then the
prudent course is to provide remediation as though it could show up
anywhere on the site,'' Bellomo said.
</P>
<P>
   The highest concentrations of hydrogen sulfide found in the
ground have been in the open spaces intended for the athletic
facilities, with smaller concentrations in the ground near the
school complex, toxic officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of remediating the entire 35-acre site could be
tremendous, Groveman said. Current estimates for an active
remediation system to carry off hydrogen sulfide and potentially
explosive methane gas range from $4 million to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Groveman said the current remediation estimates likely would
climb. That would cut into the $74 million the district's financial
analyst Roger Rasmussen has estimated the district would save by
completing Belmont, rather than building a new school on clean
soil. Those numbers, however, have been challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of what is being found, the testing will have to be
very conservative, and that will lead to extensive delays,''
Groveman said. ``If you see different levels of chemicals, then you
have to take more and more samples, which takes time to acquire, to
evaluate and to report on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in the middle of construction, every day is
costly.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
