<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9264 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     10-07 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ Jose Lima had finished his warm-up and was ready to go to
work, which for him means spending the afternoon alternately
tossing pitches and jumping around on the mound like a hyena with a
hot foot.
</P>
<P>
   Then third-base umpire Bruce Froemming approached him for a
little conference.
</P>
<P>
   If it's Lima Time, it must be pine tar time.
</P>
<P>
   Froemming pointed to a brown splotch about six inches long, high
up the right side of Lima's uniform ants, near the thigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Go ahead. Feel my leg if you want,''' said Lima.
```Be happy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything wrong with that.
</P>
<P>
   Another day, another manager _ this time Bobby Cox _ plays mind
games with Lima. And why not when the guy has more potentially
explosive buttons to push than the Joint Chiefs of Staff?
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been checking the side of my pants every year, all
year round, (to see) if I got pine tar,'' Lima said. ``I keep
saying if I cheat, if I put pine tar on my pants, nobody is going
to beat me. I will be nasty, nastier than I am. You know what I
mean? They just wake me up.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, maybe it's time somebody in the Astros'
dugout decided to check Craig Biggio and Jeff Bagwell for pine tar
_ or a pulse _ after another combination playoff collar of 0-for-7.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Lima is down but not out after giving up nine hits
and four runs in 6 innings in a game that was a one-run duel with
Kevin Millwood's glittering gem into the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the Lima who has been known to rattle more than the
epicenter of an earthquake at a sign of trouble. This wasn't an
immature meltdown before a national television audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Jose pitched an excellent game,'' said Astros
manager Larry Dierker. ``He never got the ball up except for the
few times that he wanted to, and he always seemed to stay within
himself. Even after they tried to get to him with having the umpire
check him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima allowed the Braves to break a 1-1 tie in the sixth on a
broken-bat single by Ryan Klesko, a double by Andruw Jones on a
ball that was one step to Ken Caminiti's left and arguably should
have been swallowed up, and a sacrifice fly by Eddie Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta began to break it open in the seventh when Bret Boone
smashed a one-out double off the wall in deep left-center. But what
really allowed a big inning by the Braves was Daryle Ward's cutting
in front of Carl Everett on the carom, misplaying the ball and
allowing Boone to go all the way to third. That was the error that
eventually allowed the dominoes to fall on Lima.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' Lima said. ``There are things that are going to
happen in every game, and they can't always go your way. They had
Millwood out there pitching a good game, and he was going to be
tough to beat anyway. But I'm not down. I'm not angry. I'm just
ready to get right back into it and get real dirty in the rest of
the series to finish this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, according to Lima, it is his desire to ``get dirty''
like his buddies Biggio, Bagwell and Caminiti that has led to the
season-long controversy about the brown spot on his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dirt,'' he said, swinging his hip around. ``That's all it
is. I see Biggio and all those other guys covered in dirt all the
time all over their uniforms, you know. So I want to be like them.
I want to be dirty, too. So I take some dirt out in the bullpen,
and I wipe it in real good on my uniform, and there it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is either livin' la vida loca or living life a few
sandwiches short of a picnic. Either way, it's Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to say I cheat,'' he said. ``Why do I cheat now in
the playoffs when everybody is around to see it? They throw me out
of the game, and what good am I then? I want to be around here when
we go to the World Series, and I'm telling you, it's going to
happen this year. You watch.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Braves' pitching staff is a collection of cool, precise
personalities you'd expect to see working on the bomb squad, Lima
is the guy who'd dance through a crowded room juggling two jars of
nitroglycerine.
</P>
<P>
   And so, while there is the pragmatist in him who would prefer to
see the Astros return home and win two straight to finish off the
Braves, there is the ham in Lima who yearns for another spotlight
dance back here on Sunday in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to pitch on Saturday in Game 4 to back up (Shane)
Reynolds, then I'm ready,'' he said. ``I will warm up. I will be
ready for anything to make this happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I really want the ball on Sunday. Give it to me in
Atlanta, in Japan, in Africa. I don't care. I am ready now. I am up
for this.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the playoffs. This is Lima Time, you know. Well, it
wasn't Lima Time today, because we lost. But you know what I
mean.''
</P>
<P>
   We think so. Which is frightening in itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
