<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUGHLIN POWER PLANT TO CLEAN UP ITS ACT 
</HEADLINE>
 PLANT-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Environmentalists and utility officials Wednesday
announced a $300 million air pollution cleanup of the coal-fired
Mohave Generating Station in Laughlin, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   The move could, by 2006, help clean up vistas at the western end
of Grand Canyon National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came the day after the Salt River Project
announced the completion of a five-year, $420 million cleanup of
the Navajo Generating Station on the Canyon's eastern end.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Southern California Edison, the plant's principal
owner, said the deal announced Wednesday will best position Mohave
to continue using coal and continue operating the plant well into
the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about protecting both the environment and the economy,''
said Bob Wyman, an attorney for the plant's owners.
</P>
<P>
   Nader Mansour, an environmental regulation manager for Edison,
said the pollution controls will allow the Mohave plant to operate
at greater efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Current environmental restrictions, intended to reduce visible
smoke from the plant, restrict output to about 60 percent of
capacity. With the new pollution controls, Mansour said, the plant
could average more than 80 percent of capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, if approved by a federal judge in Las Vegas,
would settle a lawsuit brought last year by three environmental
groups: the Sierra Club, the National Parks and Conservation
Association and the Grand Canyon Trust.
</P>
<P>
   The groups contended, and Edison denied, that the Mohave plant
exceeds federal emission standards for sulfur dioxide and for
opacity _ the measure of how clear the air is, with 100 percent
opacity being total blockage. Environmentalists contended that the
federal opacity limit was 20 percent; Edison and Nevada regulators
said it was 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Mansour said the new pollution controls would enable Edison to
drop the opacity of the Mohave plant to less than 5 percent,
significantly improving the looks of the Mohave Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time,'' said Dave Simon of the National Parks and
Conservation Association. ``This plant is an older, dirty dinosaur
plant that has been belching pollution for nearly 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Smith of the Sierra Club said that Mohave is the largest
plant in the Southwest without significant pollution controls,
adding that the installation of scrubbers would have the equivalent
effect of removing 6 million cars from the road.
</P>
<P>
   Simon said attention should now turn to reducing pollution from
Phoenix, Las Vegas and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there remains a lingering question with Wednesday's pact.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike during the cleanup at the Navajo power plant, today's
ongoing efforts to deregulate the electric power industry mean
there are no guarantees that the agreement will actually be
executed.
</P>
<P>
   Edison, or a subsequent owner, could close the plant or switch
to a different fuel source, such as natural gas, rather than clean
up its coal-burning operations. That would mean a loss of coal
mining royalties for the Hopi and Navajo tribes.
</P>
<P>
   A new contract for coal is due to be negotiated in 2005 with
Peabody Western Coal Co., the mining operations of which annually
contribute $17.1 million to the Navajo Nation (12 percent of the
tribal budget), and $3.7 million for the Hopis (26 percent of the
budget).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no guarantees on how long this plant will operate,''
Edison's John Fielder said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at (602) 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
