r a BC-DOLE-AZR &LR;      10-07 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE COMING TO STATE TO BOOST SAGGING GOP CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Aides to GOP presidential hopeful Elizabeth Dole
harpooned Sen. John McCain on Oct. 6th as she maneuvered for
Arizona votes to shore up her sagging campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Dole isn't due in the state until Friday, but her aides are
already flaunting an endorsement by Phoenix Mayor Skip Rimsza and
citing recent Arizona polls showing McCain running behind Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, all in an effort to undercut claims that
McCain's fortunes are rising as hers are plunging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have have been amazed as to how the national media have
bought this whole McCain phenomenon and ignored the fact that he is
probably going to lose his home state,'' Dole advisor Tony Fabrizio
said. `Someone suggested that to know John is to dislike John.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain spokesman Dan Schnur quickly shot back at the Dole
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell (the Dole campaign) if the mayor (Rimsza) is not
available, we would be happy to send out a tour guide so they don't
get lost at the airport,'' Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
   The jousting between Dole and McCain comes as McCain is
struggling to deal with home-state challenges not only from Bush,
the GOP race's front-runner, but from publisher Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who last week secured the endorsement of Gov. Jane Hull,
has made it clear that he will compete aggressively with McCain in
his own back yard. Forbes, who spent nearly $4 million to win
Arizona in 1996, is expected once again to pour millions into the
state.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Dole, too, will vie with McCain for his political
legacy, attending a $200-a-person fund-raiser at the Wrigley
Mansion in Phoenix, where she will officially unveil her leadership
team, headed by Rimsza.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Dole will be feted at the Phoenician by Committee 200, a
national organization of women successful in business and the
professions.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for McCain said the senator remains unfazed by the
recent forays of other candidates into his home turf, pointing out
that he is gaining ground elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last two weeks, John McCain has moved into second place
in New Hampshire, South Carolina and New York state, and we've
raised more money than any candidate besides the front-runner,''
Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's aide also downplayed the Rimsza endorsement, saying
that McCain's list of endorsements is longer and more likely to
generate votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has won three consecutive statewide elections in Arizona,
and his grass-roots organization is already at work on next year's
primary,'' Schnur said. ``But we congratulate Mrs. Dole on her
endorsement.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Dole campaign is clearly encouraged by a recent poll
showing that McCain is vulnerable to a challenge. That poll,
released last week, shows Bush leading McCain 31 percent to 22
percent. Forbes placed third with 10 percent and Dole was fourth,
at 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not going to cede any territory to McCain,'' Dole
spokeswoman Chris Hawes said. ``Arizona is by no means locked up.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to one GOP leader, the Dole campaign has sparked
little excitement among local activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not appear that she has the same campaign enthusiasm
as McCain does,'' Arizona Republican Party Chairman Mike Minnaugh
said. ``The spirit doesn't seem to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnaugh pointed out that Dole's last event in Arizona, also a
fund-raiser, drew a modest crowd and was noteworthy only because it
was primarily attended by women.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing wrong with that, but you need to attract more
than just women to win,'' Minnaugh said. ``We're talking about the
presidency of the United States. As much as we would all like a
woman or a minority in there, you have got to show that you have
what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole loyalists pointed to Arizona's recent election of women to
the state's top five statewide offices as a reason to hope that
money doesn't mean everything here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the state that elected the `Fab Five,' and I just
think that's a huge sign that Arizona could be won by a woman,''
Rimsza said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
