<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINE BROTHERS GET BABY SISTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DENNIS MCCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- First came Max, next Fred, then Brandon _ all
about a year apart.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, baby Kyle came along, and Ivan was born 17
months later.
</P>
<P>
   Five boys. No girls.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Kelli Skinner, their mother, decided to take three
years off to regroup.
</P>
<P>
   Then Russell came along in '87, Joey in '91, Stanley in '92 and
Charley in '97.
</P>
<P>
   Nine boys. Still no girls.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week.
</P>
<P>
   Say hello to Daisy Skinner. Finally.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it,'' Kelli Skinner, 42, said, sounding exhausted as
she rested in her hospital bed Wednesday at West Hills Hospital and
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm maxed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Bryan, who owns a pool plastering business in the
Northridge community of Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley, says he
isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Kelli laughs, then jokingly tells him to have the next one by
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to joke about it when we were dating,'' said Kelli,
graduated from Agoura High School in 1975. Bryan was graduated from
El Camino High in 1973, and they were married in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bryan always said he wanted 12 kids. It turns out it wasn't a
joke.''
</P>
<P>
   They come from big families, this Mormon couple. Kelli's mom,
Rene Hofer, was one of 17 children, Bryan one of nine, and Kelli
one of eight.
</P>
<P>
   Big numbers don't scare them.
</P>
<P>
   After parenting nine boys, now ranging in age from 22 months to
22 years, they finally have a girl.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much that they were trying for a girl this time,
Kelli said, as a playmate for 22-month-old Charley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost our son Fred at 17 in a car accident three years ago
and were devastated,'' Kelli said. ``We decided to have one more,
and we had Charley. Then we decided we wanted one more for Charley
to play with, and now we have Daisy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a case of going for a girl, but I knew Bryan really
wanted a daughter _ a daddy's girl to go with all the mommy's boys
around the house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Bryan admitted, although he had just about given up hope
of ever having a little girl. But they kept trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd talk to the boys and say, Mom and I are thinking about
having another, and they'd look at me like I was nuts,'' Bryan
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know what? The boys are all so excited about this. At
least they were until I explained to them that life, as they know
it, will cease to exist from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   Has to. There's going to be a girl around the house.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you're thinking that having so many kids is, well, a
handful, the Skinners want to set you straight.
</P>
<P>
   Once you pass three, they said, you hardly feel the tired
numbness anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had our third in three years, I thought we'd pull our
hair out, but from that time on, it didn't get any harder,'' Bryan
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys got older and started helping out. It just became
second nature.''
</P>
<P>
   But all that changed at 2:12 a.m. Tuesday when a 7-pound,
12-ounce baby girl named Daisy entered the world. It's no longer a
boys' world over at the Skinners' home in Agoura Hills, about 35
miles northwest of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
