u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BO     10-07 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PAINFUL START FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-INDIANS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The balance of power between the Red Sox and
Cleveland Indians was supposed to hinge on Pedro Martinez's slender
right shoulder, but no one anticipated that his back would give out
four innings into this American League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of the Sox ace, who was unable to continue
because of a muscle he strained on a 96-mile-per-hour fastball to
Jim Thome, the Indians seized the advantage against Derek Lowe, who
gave up just one hit in four innings but couldn't dodge the loss in
a 3-2 decision that left not only Martinez hurting in the
aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing,'' pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said after Travis
Fryman's single off Rich Garces, the Red Sox' third pitcher of the
ninth, scored Manny Ramirez, who took a pitch in the back from Lowe
to open the Indians' last at-bat. ``He gives up one hit and ends up
losing the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball's not fair sometimes. But against a team that scores
1,000 runs, you can't give them four outs in an inning. They're
tough to beat, boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe had retired 31 Indians batters in a row, including the
regular season, until John Valentin threw away Ramirez's two-out
grounder in the sixth. ``It wasn't a hard-hit ground ball to me,''
Valentin said. ``I was looking for the big hop, and I got it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I threw it hard enough to get it over there, but I
underthrew it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thome followed by blasting a 434-foot home run over the
right-center field fence to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' Lowe said. ``What can I say? They got one hit,
but it was a very big hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very potent lineup. You can't let your guard down for
one pitch. I did, and it cost us the game. I was trying to throw a
first-pitch curveball for a strike. It wasn't my best pitch or my
worst, but he did what he was supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Thome's home run was the only ball Lowe allowed out of the
infield. It was his misfortune that it left the outfield, too.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't cost the Sox the game, only tied it on a night
when the only offense Boston generated was when the Indians gave
Nomar Garciaparra a chance to swing the bat.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, playing for the first time in eight days because of
a bruised tendon in his right wrist, homered in his first at-bat
off Bartolo Colon to open the second inning. He doubled and scored
on Mike Stanley's single in the fourth, one of Stanley's three hits
on the night.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd of 45,182 at Jacobs Field roared its approval
when Colon walked Garciaparra in the sixth, after which he was
doubled off first on Troy O'Leary's liner that was grabbed at the
fence by left fielder David Justice. Garciaparra, with the play in
front of him, was around second base when Justice made the catch
and was doubled up easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good time for me to be aggressive,'' Garciaparra
said.
</P>
<P>
   Colon squashed what little aggression the Sox mounted against
him, striking out a season-high 11 batters before giving way to
Paul Shuey to start the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Shuey then did what Colon was unable to do, he got Garciaparra
out to start the inning, thrusting his arms skyward after
Garciaparra went down swinging on a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox finished with five hits, all by two players _
Garciaparra's double and home run and Stanley's three singles.
Rookie Brian Daubach, last seen here whiffing four times on Sept.
15, struck out three more times. So did Jason Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   And Lowe, coming out for a fifth inning of work for the first
time this season, could not afford the mistake he made in the
ninth, when he hit Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams then summoned lefthander Rheal Cormier, who
retired old hunting buddy Thome on a liner to left, then gave up a
single to pinch hitter Wilfredo Cordero. Two years ago, Cordero was
cast as the villain in a Boston morality play involving domestic
abuse, but has come back as No. 1 on the scorecards of Cleveland
fans, if not in their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Garces entered and walked another pinch hitter, Richie Sexson,
on four pitches, before Fryman rifled his winning single on a line
to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a situation today where everything went wrong for
us,'' said Garces, who was consoled by catcher Varitek and last
season's closer, Tom Gordon. ``The guy (Fryman) hit a pretty good
pitch. I threw him a fastball in, then a curveball that he swung
and missed at. I tried to come back again on the inside corner. I
thought it was a good pitch. What can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who gave up three singles in his four innings, decided
he could do no more after pitching a 1-2-3 fourth, the only inning
in which he retired the Indians in order.
</P>
<P>
   He hurt his back whiffing Thome, the first batter of the fourth,
but retired Harold Baines on a pop and Justice on a bouncer to
first before informing Williams and Kerrigan of his injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt a little pinch in his back,'' Kerrigan said. ``We went
down in the tunnel, where (trainer) Jim Rowe examined him. Ramon
(Martinez, Pedro's brother) came down, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cut and dry. He just couldn't continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan wouldn't even guess as to when Martinez would pitch,
though he said it was ``out of the question'' for Lowe to see any
work this afternoon in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a short series, you really don't think about it,'' Kerrigan
said of when Martinez might pitch again. ``We're thinking about
(Bret) Saberhagen and the bullpen tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Pedro comes in tomorrow and feels better, everybody will
feel a lot better, but you can't guess on these things, or wish on
these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor should you despair, according to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a team,'' he said. ``We rebound. We have other good
pitchers and we bounced back from other situations and challenges
during the season. So we come out and play hard tomorrow. See what
happens. We've got Saberhagen going.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez opted for the braveheart, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can win with me, or without me,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
