<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATES PULL A FAST ONE ON RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ It's the playoffs. These are the Red Sox. Bad things
happen.
</P>
<P>
   When Boston's baseball team plays in October, the Larger Forces
always seem to be at work. At a time when optimism was running amok
in New England, Pedro Martinez Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night sustained a back
injury and Boston lost its 17th playoff game in 18 tries, a 3-2
bottom-of-the-ninth job against the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro, the Man Who Would Be Koufax, lasted only four innings in
his Game 1 Division Series start against the Tribe. The Sox led,
2-0, and appeared to have things in hand when Pedro failed to come
out for the fifth because of a muscle strain in his back.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was testy after the game and said, ``Don't scare our
fans. Write it in the right way. I'll be back in the house. Don't
get our fans against us. I'm going to be back in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Pedro. It's hard to put this gently. Boston's ace is on
the shelf, at least until Sunday, Derek Lowe is burned out for a
couple of days, and the depleted Sox staff has to face the mighty
Tribe _ the first major league team to score 1,000 runs in 49
years. Bret Saberhagen gets the ball Thursday. Lucky fella.
</P>
<P>
   Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said there was no question about
removing Martinez from Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no choice,'' said Kerrigan. ``He did it on a pitch
to (Jim) Thome in the fourth. After that, his fastball dropped to
90 miles per hour. It looked like a batting practice fastball and
he was throwing almost all changeups to (Harold) Baines and (David)
Justice. I thought it was kind of strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go up to him after every inning. When I did after the
fourth, he grabbed me and said he felt a pinch in his back. We went
inside and Ramon came with us and (trainer Jim) Rowe examined him.
(Manager) Jimy (Williams) said, `That's enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro said, ``I didn't throw hard after feeling it. I didn't
want to be stupid. I wanted to come out one more inning, but I
wanted to have it checked out before I went out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could re-hab it. I'm a quick healer. It's a burning I've got
back there. It's gonna be there for the next few hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez threw only 58 pitches in four innings. The sellout
Cleveland crowd when wild when Lowe came on to pitch the bottom of
the fifth. Lowe was spectacular, allowing only one hit in four
innings _ a game-tying two-run homer by Thome in the sixth.
Naturally, the homer came after a two-out error by John Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   It's the playoffs. These are the Red Sox. Bad things happen.
</P>
<P>
   There was some question about Boston's clubhouse karma before
the game even started. The Sox were slightly rocked by Reggie
Jefferson's abrupt departure after learning he was not part of the
playoff roster.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the surprising sight of Mark Portugal _ appearing
like Roland the headless Thompson gunner _ in the lobby of the Sox
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Williams countered the bad vibes with his trusty Baby Ruth candy
bar. The manager seems to think the chocolate treat is some kind of
antidote for the Curse of the Bambino and carried it with him all
the way through the Sox' 8-4, make-or-break road trip. He also had
it on his desk when the Sox swept the Yankees in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got it with me,'' Williams said before Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro, who is kind of a Baby Ruth himself, threw 21 pitches in
the first inning, which ended when he fanned Manny ``165 RBIs''
Ramirez on a 3-and-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In the press box, 80-year-old Bob Feller, wearing a Tribe tie,
said, ``I've seen him quite a bit. He's not Sandy Koufax yet, but
he had a great year, a great couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was on an unbelievable roll coming into the game. Many
considered him unbeatable. But he was beaten by 49-degree
temperatures and a pinch in his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt in command,'' said Martinez. ``I felt we could have won
that game. But we didn't lose yet. There's plenty of games left. We
have to come back and win the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis Fryman, who got the winning hit off Rich Garces, said,
``When it happened (Martinez left the game), I said, `Hey, we've
got a chance to get back into the ballgame.' And it gives you a
sense of confidence to win the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan would not speculate on when Martinez might be ready to
pitch again, but Saturday's Game 3 would seem to be out of the
question. The Sox can only hope there is a Game 4 Sunday. Let's
face it, folks: any injury to Pedro effectively smothers the Red
Sox' postseason hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saberhagen has pitched big games before,'' Williams said.
``He's going to go out and compete the best he can tomorrow. We
have a team. We rebound. We have other good pitchers. We've bounced
back from other challenges during the course of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   They have. But an injury to Pedro increases the likelihood that
Boston's postseason woes will continue. The 1999 Red Sox have been
resilient, but it's difficult to imagine them overcoming the loss
of their Cy Young/MVP ace.
</P>
<P>
   Why should we have expected things to be any different? It's the
playoffs. These are the Red Sox. Bad things happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
