<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I GOT YOUR `WASTELAND' RIGHT HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - In addition to the New York Mets, their coaches, agents,
bodyguards and parole officers, several writers from the New York
papers and their therapists are visiting Phoenix.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among them is one from the New York Post, who produced a story
for Wednesday's paper under the head line, ``Phoenix has never
risen from the ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   The reporter's name is Gersh Kuntzman.
</P>
<P>
   I swear.
</P>
<P>
   From his downtown hotel room, Gersh declared Phoenix ``a city
that needs to be slapped in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   He described residents here as ``dull'' and ``not . . . the
brightest bunch of baseball fans.''
</P>
<P>
   He informed Post readers that Phoenix is a ``dusty, desert waste
land,'' a ``nightmare city'' that looks ``like a neutron bomb
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Dusty desert wasteland? Night mare city? Dull?
</P>
<P>
   If I could say one thing about re porter Gersh Kuntzman to all
the New Yorkers who may have read his article, it would be this:
</P>
<P>
   He overestimates us. &QL; 
HORRIBLE PLACE
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix is WAY worse than that.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers, please, don't let the pictures from the Snoopy
blimp fool you, particularly those showing what looks like a
beautiful new ball park at night, with city lights spread over the
desert like diamonds on black velvet.
</P>
<P>
   They take those pictures after the sun goes down for a reason,
you know.
</P>
<P>
   It's the media's way of keeping you from seeing the SNAKES that
are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   And the SCORPIONS.
</P>
<P>
   And the ground that's completely covered with sharp, poisonous
CACTI _ except for the playing field at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be duped by that place, ei ther. Shea Stadium is much
nicer, or will be once they clear out the in festation of roaches,
which is to say, once the Diamondbacks win the se ries and Mets
fans are forced to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Gersh.
</P>
<P>
   Too many New Yorkers have failed to heed dire warnings about
Arizona and moved here.
</P>
<P>
   SO, PLEASE, STAY HOME
</P>
<P>
   The rest of you, please, don't do it. Particularly if you happen
to be Donald Trump or Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   Or Howard Stern.
</P>
<P>
   Or Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   You won't like it here.
</P>
<P>
   Stick with Marv Albert. Our sportscasters aren't nearly as
biting.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't feel safe on our streets, anyway. Police here don't
understand the tactical need to fire 41 shots at an unarmed
immigrant, as yours do, and have no training in the creative use of
a broken broom stick during interrogations.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, culturally, we simply cannot compare to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   That's evident to anyone who's ever set foot on a New York City
street.
</P>
<P>
   I'll never forget the first time I opened the door of a taxi in
mid-town Manhattan, looked around at the majestic skyscrapers
rising like canyon walls, and stepped out of the cab into a big
mound of what folks in Arizona might call ``gersh.''
</P>
<P>
   Out here, among people the Post says are ``overwhelmed by the
very idea of deli sandwich,'' we'd simply just scrape off the nasty
stuff and move on.
</P>
<P>
   What a waste! As they say. &QL; 
WASTELAND FOR ART
</P>
<P>
   Near as I can tell, and I've done some checking, there's not a
single museum in the Phoenix metropolitan area featuring a painting
of the Blessed Virgin Mary with a wad of dung stuck onto it.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, you can get that kind of artistic enlightenment only
in a place like New York.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I read recently that the Brooklyn Museum of Art is
drawing very large crowds of New Yorkers, each one anxious to stare
at the doo-doo on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Which explains why the city has so many Mets fans.
</P>
<P>
   Also, New York, if you're going to send one of your thugs down
here to try to slap us in the face, you gotta come up with somebody
tougher-sounding than Gersh.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, fagetaboudit. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
