<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE FINE EFFORT, LOWE FEELS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-LOWE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ As he strode to the mound at Jacobs Field
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, he was saluted with a deafening cheer as 45,182
delirious patrons rose to their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lowe had never heard such an unpleasant sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``First time I ever got a standing ovation on the road,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And that meant trouble. Lowe knew that the crowd wasn't paying
tribute to his presence so much as celebrating the absence of Pedro
Martinez. In their Division Series opener, the Red Sox' Cy
Young-elect had stymied the Indians on three hits, while the Sox'
bats had delivered a 2-0 lead through four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Then Martinez had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   All the stunned Lowe knew when the bullpen phone rang was what
coach John Cumberland told him: ``You got the fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew something was wrong, obviously,'' said Lowe. ``But
they're not going to explain to me what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   What was going on was that the Red Sox had lost their ace with a
strained muscle in the middle of his back and that the versatile
Lowe _ spot starter, steady setup man, promising closer _ had been
entrusted with salvaging the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue mission failed, but it was a gallant attempt
nonetheless. In four-plus innings, Lowe struck out four, walked
none, and allowed only two hits. Unfortunately for him, one of
those hits was a two-run homer to Jim Thome that tied the game in
the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   And the other was a hit batsman, Manny Ramirez, leading off the
ninth. The last man Lowe faced wound up scoring on Travis Fryman's
bases-loaded single as the Indians pulled out an unlikely 3-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe was in no mood to give himself an ovation despite his
gritty 911 work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost the game,'' he said. ``How can I give myself credit for
that? I gave up only one hit, but it was a homer. And then I hit a
guy who scored the winning run.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe didn't mention it, but he just as easily could have been a
2-0 winner. With two out in the sixth, third baseman John Valentin
short-hopped a throw to first on Ramirez's grounder. Thome then
launched a 434-foot rocket into the right-field seats. Lowe should
have been out of the inning unscathed, but he wouldn't take himself
off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no reason to give up a home run in that situation,''
he said. ``I tip my cap to Thome. I threw him a curveball. It
wasn't my best curve, but it wasn't my worst, and he jumped on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, Lowe had an idea of what dire straits the Red Sox'
pitching was in. After working a perfect fifth, he came into the
visitors' clubhouse and found Martinez being treated in the
trainer's room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was sore,'' recalled Lowe. ``He wasn't going to
give me a complete rundown, but obviously, he was hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as much as Lowe was after he nailed Ramirez in the back with
a 2-2 pitch, then trudged disconsolately to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fastball and I was trying to get it inside,'' he
said. ``But when your body gets a little tired, you tend to throw
too much with your body. I must have missed by 10 feet with that
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   After such a shattering result and a taxing effort, Lowe is
looking forward to some time off _ until Game 2 this afternoon,
when he vows he can give an inning or two if requested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, this is the playoffs,'' he said. ``This is when you want
to be in there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
