</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-`TOMB'-INDEPENDENT-350&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT IS UTTER DEVASTATION...IT MUST HAVE BEEN DREADFUL'  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This graphic ``separate buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS TWO HELPFUL OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 450 _ AT 350 AND 800.
TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,050 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By KIM SENGUPTA  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The strands of twisted, blackened metal jut out like
surreal pieces of a charred sculpture. There is the smell of burned
things in the air, the rest is just ashes, knee deep. This was a
First-Class carriage, with seating for 48 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   It is still not known exactly how many perished in carriage H of
the InterCity 125 as it was wrenched off the rest of the train and
flung aside in the crash. The fire sparked by the impact spread in
seconds and then raged on for the next 20 minutes, reaching a
staggering 1,000C. Everything inside was incinerated.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn yesterday firemen, police officers and forensic
scientists began sifting through the debris. What remained of the
bodies under the sea of ashes could be ashes themselves. They will
have to be sieved and gathered together. It is horrifying.
</P>
<P>
   The men from Scotland Yard's body recovery team have been to
Cambodia, Bosnia and Kosovo, but even they say they have never seen
anything quite like this. Each rescuer was carefully monitored for
signs of stress.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Tony Thompson of the British Transport Police, a
man of vast experience, could only say quietly: ``It is utter
devastation, utter devastation. One can imagine what happened. It
must have been dreadful.''
</P>
<P>
   The one clear forecast being made amid the mayhem, confusion and
recriminations surrounding the accident is that the body count is
going to rise and rise and rise.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Assistant Commissioner Andy Trotter, the senior police
officer for this area of west London, said he feared it will be
``considerably higher'' than the official figure so far. He pointed
out that there was a large ``gap'' between the hundreds thought to
be travelling on the two trains and those accounted for, either
alive or dead.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the ones trapped and killed in the burned carriage,
there are believed to be bodies hidden under other carriages and
the engines of the trains. One was found early yesterday stuck in
an undercarriage. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 225 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 350) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lifting needed to get to these bodies cannot take place
until heavier equipment is brought in, including a 100-ton crane,
which was being assembled yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   A road will have to be built to bring it on to the site from a
parking lot and some buildings beside the track will be demolished
to position it.
</P>
<P>
   Specialist cutting equipment is also needed. Some of the tools
used by the firefighters could not cope with the metal fused by the
intense fire.
</P>
<P>
   But other recovery work continued yesterday, mostly centered
around the shell of carriage H, draped in a thick blue-and-yellow
tarpaulin.
</P>
<P>
   Markings had been made, in fluorescent green paint, on the sides
and the emergency workers, in their white boiler suits, delicately
began to pick their way through the ash and metal inside.
</P>
<P>
   What they gathered was being carefully bagged and stored to be
examined by the forensic specialists. The firemen, dressed in
brown, stood by to cut through any obstacles in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering was also taking place outside. The force of the blast
had thrown some of the debris into gardens 150 feet away, and the
bits were being collected. House-to-house inquiries were also
taking place. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Immediately outside the carriage, there were everyday reminders
of the lives of those who died _ coats and shoes, briefcases and
magazines and paperbacks, coffee cups and chocolate wrappers and a
railway timetable.
</P>
<P>
   In one carriage, you could see a photo of a smiling, fair-haired
boy, no more than a year old, holding up a ball. It probably fell
out of someone's wallet. Also being collected were mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   The sprawling area of the accident, now an official crime scene,
has been sectioned off by blue-and-white police tape, within which
a fingertip search is being carried out. The evidence brought
together will be used to establish identities. DNA tests, dental
records and fingerprints will be crucial.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies found so far have been tagged, photographed and
videoed. This will be needed for the inquests and any criminal
prosecution that may follow. ``This is the only chance we have to
do this,'' Supt. Thompson said. ``Once the bulldozers move in and
the carriages are lifted away this will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to place every person exactly where they were on the
train. We more or less did this in King's Cross. It is vital to do
this if we are to find out what happened. We owe it to the victims
and their families as well as the law.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 800. OPTIONAL COPY FOLLOWS TO 1,050) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   One of the ``black box'' recorders from the commuter train has
been recovered, but another one situated at the front has not. The
recorders, each the size of a small suitcase, should show how fast
the Thames train was travelling _ and whether or not the driver
applied the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   The InterCity 125 did not carry such a recorder, being built
before they became standard for safety reasons. ``This is a big
blow,'' said one investigator. ``They're invaluable for finding out
what actually occurred, what signals came on, what action was taken
by the driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Normal life was returning to this stretch of west London
yesterday. The Sainsbury's supermarket, a makeshift refuge the
previous day, was busy with shoppers. The staff of the store, who
had been the first to arrive at the scene, were busy behind their
tills. Occasionally the shoppers would ask each other if they knew
the latest number of dead.
</P>
<P>
   The work continued for the emergency services. Andy, a young
fireman, pained and exhausted, with tiredness etched on his face,
was drinking coffee from a Styrofoam cup, standing in the sunshine
looking down at the broken trains.
</P>
<P>
   Will he be leaving? ``I don't know, I suppose I should. I
couldn't have slept last night even if I had wanted to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose one ought to get hardened to these things but I
can't. I think about the families of those who died. Who do they
blame? When a bomb goes off one can blame the people who planted
it. Here, even if human error was involved, it wasn't done on
purpose, was it? Who do you blame, God?'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this timely article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
