<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9276 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARR     10-07 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA RETURNS AND DOESN'T MISS A BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Another year, another Division Series, same old
stuff for Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox shortstop picked up where he left off in last year's
playoffs, slamming a home run Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night against the Indians,
essentially teaming with first baseman Mike Stanley to shape the
entire Boston offense.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the second inning, the 26-year-old Garciaparra broke
a scoreless tie when he strong-armed a Bartolo Colon fastball over
the wall in right center. The ball landed 418 feet from home plate,
impressive considering that Garciaparra wheeled around on Colon's
delivery virtually without stepping into the pitch. All but
flat-footed, Garciaparra flicked his titanium wrists (did someone
say sore?) into the offering and sent it rocketing into the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flat-footed? I've never heard that before,'' said Garciaparra,
smirking. ``I hit it. It went out. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Garciaparra belted another Colon pitch, a shot to
left, that just missed being another homer. The ball hit off the
wall for an easy double, and two batters later Garciaparra chugged
home with the sox second run on Stanley's single to left _ one of
three singles for the Sox first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox finished with five hits againt Colon. Garciaparra had
two. Stanley had three. The rest of the lineup went 0-for-Colon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched great _ he did a good job,'' said Garciaparra, who
went 5 for 15 in the playoffs last year, when the Sox fell to the
Indians in four games. ``He's not going to be giving any
freebies.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the rest of the Sox lineup was dormant, Cleveland
manager Mike Hargrove didn't see the need to pitch around
Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garciaparra is a good hitter,'' he said. ``I don't think with
nobody on, you don't pitch around people. I'm not going to sit here
(and put) Nomar Garciaparra on base to face (Troy) O'Leary and
Stanley and those guys hitting behind him. That's not the idea of
pitching around people . . . there are times you have to pitch to
people no matter how good they are, and if there's nobody on, and
that guy is at the plate, I'm not going to sit there and pitch
around him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox still had a 2-0 lead in the sixth when an overzealous
Garciparra got carried away on the basepaths on Troy O'Leary's deep
fly ball to left. Anticipating that the ball would leave the yard
or hit the wall, Garciaparra raced around second base and was well
on his way to third when left fielder David Justice made the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, halfway home when Justice came down with the ball ,
raced back to first. But second baseman Roberto Alomar gathered in
Justice's relay, turned and tossed a soft lob to first baseman Jim
Thome. Garciaparra was doubled off first. The inning was over. In
the bottom of the sixth, Thome drilled a two-run bomb to right,
tying the score, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it hits the wall, I score,'' said Garciaparra. ``I thought
it was a good time to be aggressive on the basepaths. But, he made
a nice catch.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Sox are going to get by the Indians and make their way to
the American League Championship Series, they need more than a
Garciaparra-Stanley offense. Seven dead bats have to come back to
life. The Sox also face the possiblity of losing their ace, Pedro
Martinez, who exited with a muscle burning in the middle of his
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro can't pitch everyday, we know that,'' said Garciaparra.
``We can't be worried about it carrying over, psychologically. I
don't know his problem, we'll have to see what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra sounded upbeat. The Sox had a two-run lead, but left
losers, and history reminded the shorstop that an opening playoff
loss doesn't necessarily spell series defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it's not like we're out of it,'' said Garciaparra. ``Last
year we won the first game _ and then we went home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
