<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9279 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-STANLEY-BO     10-07 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY MISSED WITH PICK 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-STANLEY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ By all accounts, the ball fell into unfortunate
territory. It bounced in the dirt just a few inches short of the
first baseman's glove. It was one of those difficult hops _ too far
to reach, too close to nab on a hop. Mike Stanley was left with
what he called an ``ole' ,'' a ball he needed to swipe out of the
dirt _ like the motion of a matador _ for the third out in the
sixth inning. But even that proved difficult. Stanley did not know
whether to pick the ball or try a backhanded grab.
</P>
<P>
   And unfortunately, a leather glove cuts a much smaller swath
than a red cape. The ball never got swept into Stanley's glove, and
Manny Ramirez reached first. Third baseman John Valentin accepted
the error on the throw. The failed ``ole' '' and the underthrown
ball would haunt the Red Sox. Jim Thome belted a home run to right
center on the next pitch, evening the score at 2-2, which led to a
ninth-inning, 3-2 Cleveland victory Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive lapses by Boston and spectacular fielding plays by the
Indians, complemented by the pitching of Bartolo Colon, resulted in
the Red Sox downfall. While the Indians made catches when it
mattered most, the Red Sox were relying on an ``ole' '' at first
and luck at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those where you don't ole' one way or backhand
ole' the other,'' said Stanley. ``It was kind of in the middle. I
just kind of tried to come up with it. I'd come up with it before.
I just didn't do it this time. You just try to come up and pick it.
Sometimes the ones that are right in the middle of your body are
the toughest . . . I guess it's all for not, if Thome doesn't come
up with a big home run. But he did. Obviously, that puts a bigger
mark on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians did the job at the plate, and the defense held the
Red Sox at bay. In the ill-fated sixth, Troy O'Leary hit a long fly
ball to left. The Indians' David Justice made a catch at the wall
and his relay to the infield doubled-up Garciaparra at first. Other
defensive highlights for the Indians included a diving stab and
across-the-body throw by second baseman Roberto Alomar in the
seventh inning, and an eighth-inning catch by shortstop Omar
Vizquel with his back to the infield.
</P>
<P>
   But the strength of the defense started with the Colon, who
fooled Red Sox hitters with strong pitches all night. The Cleveland
starter finished with a season-high 11 strikeouts in eight innings.
Many of those K's came courtesy of a fastball that reached 100
miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley had a productive night, going 3 for 4 with an RBI in the
fourth inning. All of Stanley's hits were singles off Colon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to maintain some time of focus and trust the
abilities I was given,'' said Stanley. ``I've been trying to do
that for the last week or so, just trusting in what you have. I
tried to relax a little bit and make the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Colon was absolutely nasty. He was tough. When you're going
against a guy throwing 99-100 miles an hour, sharp breaking ball
and locating his fastball as well as he did with good movement, it
makes it very tough . . . I just got lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Stanley would be the first to admit, the one piece of
luck he needed Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night didn't fall into place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
