<HEADER>
A9281 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-B     10-07 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ EXIT WAS MUSIC TO INDIANS' EARS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ They will never admit they were scared
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night. They were looking at Pedro Martinez and his 2-0
lead, and the Cleveland Indians didn't believe they could win their
Division Series opener. Now they are not only thinking about
winning the series, they believe they can sweep it.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't quite say that Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night at Jacobs Field,
because baseball tradition is that you neither acknowledge
vulnerability nor embrace the obvious. But by watching and
listening to the Indians after their 3-2 win over the Red Sox, you
could tell they were thrilled to have something they didn't expect.
It's the same feeling you get when you find a $50 bill in your
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez left the game after the fourth with what the Sox
described as a muscle strain in his mid-back. The Indians said they
had noticed that his velocity had dropped during the game, from his
usual high 90s to high 80s. But his presence on the mound still
shook them. When they saw him leave, they were jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in (for the fifth inning) and I heard Omar (Vizquel)
say, `Hey, new pitcher guys.' I thought he was joking around to
kind of lighten the guys up a little bit,'' said Indians third
baseman Travis Fryman, who had the winning single in the ninth
inning. ``I looked out there and I saw (Derek) Lowe walking in and
for me, personally, it was kind of, `Hey, we got a chance to get
back in the ballgame, too.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Think about that statement. It was only the fifth inning and the
Indians' view of themselves was that they were out of the game. It
was 2-0. This is the same team that scored more than 1,000 runs in
the regular season. It once trailed a game by eight runs and came
back to win by nine. But the Indians know Martinez treats them with
irreverence. He has never delivered safe, conservative comments
about their lineup. He has mocked them, talked trashed to them, and
dominated them. They knew they were going to lose. They were
scared. They aren't scared anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Pedro out of the game was huge for us,'' said Jim
Thome, who hit a monstrous, 434-foot home run off Lowe to tie the
game in the sixth. So if Martinez's exit was a huge psychological
boost for the Indians, what was it for the Red Sox? Thome said he
could understand the shock of losing your best pitcher in the first
game of the playoffs, but the series is not over. He said the
Indians have just as much respect for Bret Saberhagen and Ramon
Martinez as they do for Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   You know that isn't true.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, you would have thought the Indians' clubhouse
was a Lansdowne Street club. The players blasted their music over
the posh stereo system. When one lowered the volume, a group
sitting at a table shouted in unison, ``Hey!'' So the music went
back up. Over that consistent bass, player after player recounted
Pedro stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great win for us,'' said winning pitcher Paul Shuey.
``When it was 2-2, it was almost like we were winning. Pedro was
out of the game at that point . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, Roberto Alomar said he knew something was wrong
with his friend Pedro. ``But they have a great bullpen, so there is
no guarantee that you'll win with him out. The other guy (Lowe) did
a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   The only mistake Lowe made was in the sixth, to Thome. The
slugger was looking for a breaking ball and that's what Lowe gave
him. And he gave it to him high.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the very loud clubhouse, Martinez was walking out of
the stadium. He saw Indians closer Mike Jackson, who asked how he
was doing. He also saw Indians coach Luis Isaac and spoke with him.
He walked cautiously, the softest way you can walk without doing so
on tiptoes. It is not the way the Indians are used to seeing
Martinez. Because they saw him like this, they are no longer
scared. And remember, no matter what they say, they were
frightened.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Lowe's 1-for-30 performance against the Indians coming
into the game, the fans here cheered when they learned Martinez had
left. Many of them had spent the day calling radio talk shows,
offering Pedro theories. Some said that manager Mike Hargrove
should try to get in Martinez's head by complaining about his cut
uniform sleeves. They said the Indians should work the count and
tire him out. They were panicking before the first pitch was
thrown. Their team wasn't panicking, but it wasn't confident.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Indians are awake. Maybe Saberhagen can reach back to
1985 and capture a bit of his Cy Young residue. The Indians say
they know that can happen and they say the Sox are a great team.
But just as much as baseball players dismiss weakness, they also
don't tell the truth about any advantages they might have.
</P>
<P>
   They have an advantage. They went from a whimpering team to a
supremely confident one with a single announcement: ``Ladies and
gentlemen, the new Red Sox pitcher . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   As Martinez, wearing a brown sport jacket and black slacks,
quietly left the stadium, many Indians were still in the clubhouse
wearing their uniforms. They didn't say they were feeling good.
They simply laughed and turned up their music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
