<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9282 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ABDULLAH-HAMAS-PURGE-     10-07 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABDULLAH-HAMAS-PURGE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN'S NEW KING TARGETS OLD NEMESIS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: TIMELY for King Abdullah's U.S. visit)   (This 800-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By PHIL REEVES  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, JORDAN _ He is glossy, affable, short _ the unkind would
say squat _ and has the sort of heavy facial features that hint at
a prize fighter. And now, eight months after assuming the throne of
the Hashemite kingdom, King Abdullah II of Jordan has thrown his
first big punch.
</P>
<P>
   The target of the youthful new king's uppercut is Hamas, the
militant Islamic group which has long been active among Jordan's
Palestinian population, and which is now reeling after the
detention of 21 members. Among them are two of the organization's
senior figures.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old king, who took over the throne after the death
from cancer of his father, King Hussein, spelled out his strategy
in a conversation with a small group of correspondents Wednesday,
before he set off for a trip to the United States where he will
meet Bill Clinton next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jordan has made itself clear that Hamas offices will be shut
down in Jordan and that is what will happen,'' he said, over brunch
in palace offices in Amman.
</P>
<P>
   The Sandhurst (English military academy)-educated king, who
formerly commanded the Jordanian army's Special Operations, appears
to enjoy using the logic of a military man: ``A soldier has to pick
his battles, rather than let other people chose them for him.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, two prominent Hamas leaders are now behind bars _
Khalid Mashaal, head of its ``politburo,'' and Ibrahim Ghosheh, a
senior publicity official.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the men, both Jordanian citizens, were taken into
custody as they arrived in Jordan from a trip to Iran, along with
their four bodyguards. At the time, Jordanian officials said the
two had been gathering security-related information on Jordan,
training militant cadres, and stockpiling caches of arms. The two
Hamas men denied it.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests followed a swoop in late August when Jordanian
police also raided Hamas offices, closing them down and detaining
15 staff. Since then public figures have been warned against
advocating pro-Hamas views, and a Muslim cleric, who made pro-Hamas
sermons was arrested and held for six days..
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's crackdown has fuelled speculation that the new king is
not so much flexing his own muscles as acting on the behest of the
Israelis or the United States, both of whom relish the spectacle of
militant Palestinians being sent packing from Amman (almost
certainly to Syria).
</P>
<P>
   Whether that is fair or not, the purge suggests that the king _
who, in the past, has openly criticized the U.S. enemy-in-chief,
Iran _ leans more unambiguously towards Washington than his
brilliantly pragmatic father, King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   The latter _ whose grizzled, twinkling features still adorn
banners and posters throughout his desert kingdom, and whose name
is repeatedly summoned up by his devoted heir _ was also
pro-western. But powerful elements of the Arab world have yet to
forget how King Hussein adopted what they saw as an excessively
pro-Iraqi stance in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the new king has some cause to please the Americans,
who have been increasing their already substantial aid to Jordan,
and are next year expected to pay out $125 million in military aid
alone.
</P>
<P>
   But the crackdown on Hamas also benefits Yasser Arafat, who
views it as a thorn in the side which threatens to disrupt the
already precarious Middle East peace process. The Palestinian
leader has been privately pressuring the Jordanians to act.
</P>
<P>
   The king's tactics entail significant risks. Although Hamas does
not enjoy strong public support in Jordan, surveys suggest that
many of the population share its opposition to making a peace
treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a chance that the jailed Hamas leaders will seize
on the possibility of a trial to publicize their cause _ a risk
which suggests Jordan's best ploy would be to strike a deal in
which they are released and exiled.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is part of a larger bid by Jordan's leader to breathe
air into the cinders of the Oslo peace process, which fizzled
during the stagnant rule of Israel's Benjamin Netanyahu but is now
showing signs of new life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there is a great sense of euphoria in the Middle East,''
King Abdullah said Wednesday, ``My greatest fear is what happens if
nothing takes place over the next six months.''
</P>
<P>
   This approach is unlikely to do much to endear the new king _
who speaks limited Arabic but is as slick and as persuasive in
English as an international financier _ to much of his country,
burdened as it is by high unemployment, sparse natural resources,
and a hefty foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   But it will strengthen his claim on his father's other title;
that of ``plucky little king.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 800-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
