u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-VALENTIN-B     10-07 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERROR BELIES VALENTIN'S PRESENCE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-VALENTIN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ When the criticism came, John Valentin took it like
a veteran. And therein lies the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox third baseman was placed on the 15-day disabled list
with left patella tendinitis the last day of August. During his
absence, some questioned Valentin's commitment. He was activated
Sept. 23, but in a move that raised more questions, manager Jimy
Williams kept rookie Wilton Veras in the starting lineup. Valentin
took the decision in stride, betraying no concern and announcing
the day off was part of a plan to bring him back slowly.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Veras had played admirably in place of the
32-year-old Valentin. The young infielder had impressed after his
recall from Double A Trenton in late June and again showed great
promise in early September.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, Valentin took his playoff experience into
Game 1 of the Division Series while Veras was left on the ``also
traveling'' list. It was an interesting call by the manager and a
troubling night for Valentin, whose throwing error proved to be a
turning point as the Indians rallied for a 3-2 win.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin went 0 for 4 at the plate, hitting into a double play
in the fifth inning. But his most regrettable play came in the
bottom of the sixth with two outs. He made an error on a throw to
first, allowing Manny Ramirez to reach base. Jim Thome followed the
error with a home run to right-center on reliever Derek Lowe's
first pitch. The homer tied the game, 2-2, and set the stage for
the Indians' ninth-inning victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go out there and you try to make every play perfect,''
said Valentin. ``It wasn't a hard-hit ground ball, and I waited
back to get a good hop. I just underthrew it. I thought I threw it
good enough to reach (Mike) Stanley, and it didn't make it.
Obviously it was a bad throw, and the rest is history.''
</P>
<P>
   The error overshadowed a stellar defensive play that Valentin
made in the eighth. With Omar Vizquel at bat, the third baseman was
playing in close to protect against a possible bunt. The Indians
shortstop tried to whack the ball past Valentin, but Valentin
snagged it with a backhanded catch as he stretched toward the foul
line. This time, he made a successful throw to first for the out.
But there was no joy in his expression after the play. And no joy
in the clubhouse after the game.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to discuss the catch, Valentin said, ``It really
doesn't matter, does it?''
</P>
<P>
   Williams may reward regular players and veterans with spots on
the playoff roster. But during the game, it doesn't matter how
steady you are or whether you make a spectacular play in the
eighth. The most important thing is making the right throw when it
matters. And Valentin, the veteran, knows it.
</P>
</TEXT>
