Wednesday night's talk at the Conservative party conference by
former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher announced, ``She's back,''
but the Tories learned with a mixture of delight and dismay that
she never really went away. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN-FAMILY (Omsk, Russia) _ Leonid Dyachenko,
son-in-law of President Boris Yeltsin and husband of Yeltsin's
daughter and strategist, Tatiyana Dyachenko, was once so anonymous
that even prying reporters were unsure of his first name. But
Dyachenko turns out to have a colorful life. He is a participant,
if not a key figure, in a network of politically blessed companies
that ship Siberian oil products to Ukraine and to eastern Europe.
The disclosure of his dealings is at the least embarrassing to the
Kremlin. At worst, it could plunge the Yeltsin family into a
corruption sinkhole. By Michael Wines.
</P>
