r a BC-DOLE-AZR &LR;      10-07 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE COMING TO STATE TO BOOST SAGGING GOP CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STAFF  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
NEW YORK _ Arizona, Arkan sas, what's the difference?
<TEXT>
<P>
   As every Mets fan'll tell ya, they're both miles from the Center
of the Universe, which we all know stretches roughly from Verrazano
Narrows to Hastings-on-Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   So we should forgive Brad Schrader, 47, a savvy corporate
investor and civil engineer from Chatham, N.J., for his tortured
stab at being modest about the Mets: `Anything can happen with
those guys. They've had flashes of bril liance before, and it'll be
amazing if they get past the Razorbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   We yokels west of the Jersey Turnpike know, of course, that he
meant the Diamondbacks, not some well-known Arkansas college team.
We also assume he knows a snake from a pig. But by and large, those
are the sort of insightful comments lobbed at the Diamondbacks by
New Yorkers everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got a swimming pool in your stadium, you're crazy,''
Brian Doughney, 27, a stockbroker from Queens, announced from his
perch at the ESPN Zone, a mega-sports bar at Times Square. ``We're
not some frilly-frally luxury kind of place. We're not there for
vacation. We've got ballplayers, and we're there to win. How can
you have a swimming pool in your ballpark?''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Apple's press is equally a-dither over Arizona's
laid-back lifestyle and its luxurious baseball digs, while the
average Mets fan is living 43 years in the past with talk about an
all-NYC World Series. (For Arizonans who might not know it, the New
York Yankees are the city's other baseball team, and they're also
in the World Series chase).
</P>
<P>
   Do any of them give Arizona a chance in the National League
playoffs? Fagetaboudit! They're not even sure where it is on the
map.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about the Arizona Razorbacks, right?'' said
Blair How ell, 36, assistant conductor for Amtrak's
Washington-to-New York Metroliner. All Howell knows about Arizona
is, ``It's dry, and there's a lot of gun-totin' kind of people out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Mike Jaycock, 53, a Pennsylvanian, ``Yeah, I hear women
take semiautomatic rifles to the grocery store out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He must have been reading Ari zona's press clippings. One New
York Daily News columnist de scribed Phoenix as ``Boca Raton with
cactus and Gila monsters,'' and suggested Mayor Skip Rimsza was a
rube.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, a New York Post headline dubbed Arizo
na's Big Unit ``small potatoes.'' Not everyone was so hard on the
D-Backs, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta give them credit,'' said Joel Schindler, 48, a
marketing research executive. `They went out and bought a good ball
team.'' In a moment of unbridled honesty, he added, `If you're a
Mets fan, you never have any expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Irishman Pat McAuliffe, 41, of Long Island, said the Mets ``got
their chest puffed up pretty good now that they beat Randy
Johnson.'' But he hasn't forgotten their skids this season, and he
isn't willing to buy Series tickets just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mets fans know enough not to take any team lightly, after they
way they've played,'' McAuliffe said. ``They showed us not to be
over confident.''
</P>
<P>
   The lessons were lost on Ronald Joseph, 24, of Brooklyn, who was
asked about Arizona's chances while hanging out at Manhattan's All
Star Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   `They're going down _ there's no ifs, ands or buts about it,''
Joseph said.
</P>
<P>
   Cafe worker Cliff Cadet, 23, of Queens, said, ``Even Yankee fans
would like to the Mets go all the way this year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gonna be a Subway Series,'' stockbroker Paul Amerigo, 35,
pre dicted. ``The Diamondbacks are just standing in their way _ and
just for a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   The trash talkin' doesn't stop with the teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Arizona is a nice place, but as far as sports are
concerned, they don't know very much there,'' said Kevin Chambers,
24, a New York City accountant.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Schoniedeberg, 29, a New Jersey native who's lived in
Arizona for six months, complained about Bank One Ballpark and its
fans as he prepared to watch the game at BOB on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stadium is a little too comfortable,'' he said. ``It's
like sitting in an easy chair in your living room. People cheer
louder for the mustard, ketchup and relish race (on the stadium
screen) than they do for their own player's home run that ties up
the game. They come here to eat, and then they leave here in the
sixth inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Segreto, 26, of Long Island said Diamondbackers ``are
spoiled for what they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent Congdon, 29, of Chester, N.J., who showed up at BOB even
though he's a Yankees fan, chided the genial ``country club'' atmos
phere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing like the Bronx,'' Congdon said (in the
understate ment of the night). ``If you went to the bleachers in
any other garb but Yankees, you'd be hassled and probably have to
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks fan Tom Gammill, 53, of Prescott took all this
Gotham City nonsense with a grain of salt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the best stadium,'' he said. ``They're just
jealous.'' Republic writer Alicia A. Caldwell contributed to this
article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
