<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9291 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-NFL-LADN     10-07 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. LOSES NFL BID TO HOUSTON
</HEADLINE>
 (SLANG -- Attn. Sports) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NFL may want to return to Los Angeles, but
Wednesday morning they embraced something even closer to their
hearts _ money.
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners put their arms around a $700 million winning
expansion bid from Houston, finally granting the 32nd franchise and
leaving Los Angeles scrambling to decide what its next move would
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about money at the end of the day, and I didn't
believe it would be,'' said Michael Ovitz. ``I thought it would
also be about location. But it's their league, they can do what
they want. We did what we could.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz and Ron Burkle bid $550 million, with $150 million to be
repaid through future revenues. Ed Roski Jr. and Eli Broad bid $500
million.
</P>
<P>
   Both were respectable offers and in the vicinity of the $530
million Cleveland paid for its expansion franchise last year, but
all dwarfed by Bob McNair's bid for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put the money on the table, and you get the votes,'' Broad
said. ``It was just an offer the league couldn't refuse. In the
final analysis, it came down to price.''
</P>
<P>
   It made for a persuasive argument. The league expansion
committee voted unanimously to support the Houston bid in the
morning, and barely an hour later, the full membership had voted
29-0 with two abstensions to award the franchise to Houston and
realign the league into eight, four-team divisions when the team
begins play in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Taglibue said there had been some committee
support on Tuesday night to wait another month before taking action
_ giving Ovitz-Burkle more time to work out their belated move to
Hollywood Park and Roski-Broad more to demonstrate their added
political support _ but by Wednesday morning, $700 million looked
like all they needed to consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to differentiate ourselves,'' McNair said.
``That was what we were attempting to do. We wanted to do something
so outstanding that we would break through this period of
indecision, so that it would be clear to everyone it was a superior
proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was bitter for the L.A. groups, and it left them
uncertain how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really disappointed,'' Roski said. ``We put a lot of
effort and a lot of time into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to continue to pursue NFL football in Los Angeles
at the Coliseum. We're going to have to start from scratch, because
we have not pursued that option before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That option'' would be having an existing team relocate to Los
Angeles. Coliseum general manager Pat Lynch said L.A.'s NFL
proponents will need time to gather themselves after a frustrating
end to their long expansion saga.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been years and years of hard effort,'' Lynch said.
``We're seriously disappointed. We believed we are the stadium for
Los Angeles and the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's time to just catch our breath, sort out where things
are, watch what plays out in Houston. They still have a lot of work
to do. And start to plan a new future.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is now in its fifth year without an NFL team, and
counting. The NFL has no other plans to expand, and Los Angeles'
hope of the league returning now rests with a team relocating.
</P>
<P>
   Roski said he would work to attract an owner to the Coliseum and
would be willing to take a minority role to return the NFL to Los
Angeles. Broad said he would also aid in the effort, but if he was
required to invest, would likely want control.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz said last week he expected to return from Atlanta with the
expansion team, and still seemed stunned Houston had won the day
after returning to Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very optimistic going in,'' he said. ``I had high hopes
and am very disappointed. I really thought we would come back with
the expansion franchise and Houston would get a relocated team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made them a very attractive offer. I can't compete with a
$300 million overbid.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz holds an option to purchase the nearly 100 acres at
Hollywood Park across from the Forum, but it expires on Friday.
It's doubtful Ovitz would want to purchase the property for $55
million and hold the non-revenue site in hopes of working out a
deal with another owner, but Ovitz said he had yet to decide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you after a couple of full nights' sleep,'' he
said. ``I don't like to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's $260 million in public funding for a retractable-roof
stadium gave McNair a major edge. If the stadium comes in at $350
million and they are as successful at selling PSLs as anticipated,
McNair and his investors will have to take on almost no doubt for
the stadium construction.
</P>
<P>
   But Los Angeles' inability to generate public funding to support
stadium construction doesn't figure to end here. Any existing owner
now eyeing the L.A. market will likely be met with the same
hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites remain possibilities in Southern California, but all
with their drawbacks. Carson, Anaheim and Dodger Stadium have all
been considered by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL had lobbied for added parking at the Coliseum and
demanded _ and maybe expected _ public assistance that never came.
Ovitz said it proved a learning experience for the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't match Houston's offer without public financing, and
in L.A. you're not going to get public support,'' Ovitz said.
``They (NFL) are not going to get it. They know that now. Paul told
me the miscalculated.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said the league still wanted to be in the nation's
second largest market, but had not developed a plan should Los
Angeles fail to win the expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   He said the league's current focus was to aid teams in older
stadiums to get state-of-the art stadiums in their existing cities,
not in relocating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're in the business of keeping teams where they
are, committing them to their current fan bases, and getting
stadiums built in our existing markets,'' Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Tagliabue also downplayed the significance of
Houston's $700 million bid, instead claiming it won the owners over
because of superior stadium design, organizational plans, fan base
and ownership. He said even if one of the L.A. groups had come in
at $600 million, it might not have been enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that was clear, we were not just making a
decision based upon a price,'' he said. ``We were making a decision
based upon price, the quality in terms of the stadium, the
franchise operation and ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would have had different prices in Los Angeles and fewer
uncertainties in terms of where we are to get a state-of-the-art
stadium built, I'm sure we would have had more discussion. But
that's all speculative.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz had gambled that McNair's offer would come in $100 million
less, a gamble he lost badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected them to come in a $600 million, and then we'd
close the gap,'' he said. ``It didn't work out that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told we would not have to equal their bid. But I mean,
$700 million?''
</P>
</TEXT>
