<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9292 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-CANDIDATE-LADN     10-07 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CANDIDATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHAPPY TEAMS CAN NOW TARGET L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now that Los Angeles knows who's not coming to its NFL
party, is it time to expect a former invitee back?
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders are still under the control of Al Davis, who as
ever, is unhappy with his stadium situation, and as ever, is mired
in multiple lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   With Houston capturing the NFL's new expansion franchise
Wednesday, Los Angeles now becomes the desired site of every team
currently unhappy with its stadium situation.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least every team looking for leverage to squeeze out a new
stadium deal.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, Minnesota, New Orleans, Buffalo, San Francisco and
Oakland are all NFL teams lusting for new $400-million, luxury-box
lined stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is the only NFL team that plays in a college stadium
(Arizona State). The Cardinals had a new stadium plan voted down
last year by a populace that's grown weary of publicly supporting
the financing of the new ballpark for the Diamondbacks, the arena
for the Suns and several new spring training stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, though, could be at the center of any new movement in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is currently suing the NFL over territorial rights to the
Los Angeles market he left after the 1994 season, when he fled back
to Oakland after the league wanted to put an NFC expansion team to
share his planned stadium at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland and Alameda County, which owns the Oakland Coliseum, got
tired of Davis _ embittered over the failure to sell luxury box
suites and Personal Seat Licenses _ threatening to break his lease
and abandon the city. They've sued to validate his lease. It has 12
years remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Davis responded by _ countersuing and asking that the lease be
voided. The lawsuit is expected to reach trial early next year.
</P>
<P>
   But with Davis seeming to want out of Oakland _ two weeks ago he
was talking about how Chicago could support two NFL teams _ it
seems too logical to some that he not fill the void in Los Angeles,
even if he did help create it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I think that's a good possibility,'' said Cowboys owner
Jerry Jones. ``That could take care of a lot of problems. That
could work out well for the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, however, has a lot of bad memories of Davis' first
venture into Southern California, and few are eager for his return.
When Councilman Nate Holden talked of trying to bring the Raiders
back early last year, the city almost went into shock.
</P>
<P>
   City officials scampered to assure Oakland it wanted no part of
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He treated Los Angeles shabbily, atrociously,'' Mayor Richard
Riordan said at the time. ``He's treated Oakland atrociously. Do we
want to give him another chance? We'd have to be pure masochists to
have him back.''
</P>
<P>
   When Marvin Davis bowed out of Hollywood Park last week, Davis
reportedly made several calls to inquire about picking up the
option that ultimately was given to Ron Burkle and Michael Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
   Al Davis voted to approve the $700 million sale of the 32nd
expansion franchise to Houston on Wednesday, but afterward would
not discuss the NFL's future in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it would be appropriate for me to comment
right now,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL was in control of the Los Angeles movement when it was
lobbying for an expansion franchise. But David Carter, who teaches
the business of sports at USC and owns a Los Angeles sports
marketing company, said Los Angeles may gain control with a team
trying to relocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL wanted to maintain control over the Los Angeles
market,'' Carter said. ``Any team that relocates here means they
will have less control over the venue, less control of the
ownership group and no way to make money off the deal as they would
have through expansion. And, you can expect lawsuits that will sour
everybody and turn out to be ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Lynch, general manager of the Coliseum, said the negotiating
process would probably be easier with a single owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll find that out now,'' Lynch said. ``We've proven to
ourselves we have (major renovation) plans that will work. When
you're trying to convince one party, it's a helluva lot easier than
trying to convince 31 parties.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Raiders and Cardinals, Minnesota and New
Orleans play in bad domed stadiums, Buffalo is in an old and dated
stadium and San Francisco has had its new stadium plans squashed by
scandal. Few doubt, however, that someone will try to move to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt Los Angeles will have an NFL team soon,''
Jones said. ``The NFL needs to find a way to return to Los Angeles.
As sure as I'm in the NFL, there will be a team in the NFL soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Coliseum Commission President Sheldon Sloan said he was
disappointed, but remained prepared to open talks with the NFL
about bringing football back to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still believe Southern California is a strategically
important market for professional football, and that the Coliseum
remains the best location and facility for an NFL team in this
region,'' Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing that happened today changes the fundamental truth that
the Coliseum remains the best choice for the future location of an
NFL franchise in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Rick Orlov contributed to this report
</P>
<P>
   !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
