<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9294 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-EXPANSION-REALIGN     10-07 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-EXPANSION-REALIGNMENT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ When they awarded the 32nd franchise to Houston on
Wednesday, NFL owners also passed a resolution to realign for the
2002 season when Bob McNair's team begins play.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The league will realign into eight divisions of four teams each.
There will still be an AFC and NFC, and the same number of teams
(12) will make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be in for a big fight on realignment,'' said
Buffalo's Ralph Wilson, an original American Football League owner.
``Agreeing on realignment might be tougher than deciding to expand
to Houston or Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners will try to formulate and approve a plan that
appeases as many of them as possible. All McNair knows is that his
team will play in the AFC. Houston could be placed in the AFC
Central or, more than likely, in a new division that might be
called the AFC South.
</P>
<P>
   After the expansion committee recommended Houston by a 14-0 vote
Wednesday, 31 owners or their representatives spent more time in a
two-hour meeting discussing realignment rather than McNair's $700
million offer.
</P>
<P>
   One owner said the Houston vote was such a sure thing, it had
become a formality and that realignment was the hot topic that is
sure to get hotter as the NFL gets closer to 2001 and when it will
need to realign.
</P>
<P>
   After the league realigns, one proposal will be made to change
the scheduling format to take advantage of natural rivalries such
as Dallas/Houston, Miami/Tampa, San Francisco/Oakland, Giants/Jets
and Jacksonville/Carolina. Under that format, natural rivals would
play a home-and-home series every season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do everything we can to have the Cowboys and
Houston competing annually,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said.
``What a good thing that would be for the fans as well as the
NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners also want to preserve traditional rivalries like
Dallas/Washington, Green Bay/Minn-esota, Pittsburgh/Cleveland,
Oakland/Kansas City, Chicago/Detroit and New Orleans/Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The owners have discussed expansion at almost every meeting for
years, but they haven't been in a situation like this in which they
passed the resolution to realign. Now they have to get serious.
</P>
<P>
   The owners don't want to ask more than a couple of teams to
switch conferences. They do want to get New Orleans, Carolina and
Atlanta out of the NFC West. They also know they may have to pay
millions to persuade some owners to switch conferences or
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   One owner suggested that a team without a natural or traditional
rival should be made to switch conferences. He used Tennessee as an
example.
</P>
<P>
   One NFL executive said that everyone can speculate about changes
in divisions, but no one has come close to making a proposal that
satisfies all of the owners.
</P>
<P>
   Some plans make sense. Let's present a plan in the NFC that
looks like this:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NFC East:  &LR; Dallas, Washington, Philadelphia and the New York
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NFC Central:  &LR; Green Bay, Chicago, Minnesota and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NFC West:  &LR; San Francisco, St. Louis, Arizona and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NFC South:  &LR; New Orleans, Atlanta, Tampa Bay, Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In this plan, there are two problems. Seattle would have to
switch to the NFC, and Arizona would have to leave the NFC East.
Seahawks owner Paul Allen, who never attends an NFL meeting, will
have a new stadium and might be open to the possibility. Cardinals
owner Bill Bidwill is expected to put up a fight because he doesn't
want to leave his division and a guaranteed sellout for the Dallas
game each year.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis would have to remain in the NFC West, but the Rams
wouldn't protest.
</P>
<P>
   The newly created NFC South would keep the Saints and Falcons
together, add the Panthers and give the Buccaneers an easier
schedule, at least based on perennial records.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's look at an AFC plan:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFC East:  &LR; Miami, New England, Buffalo and the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFC Central:  &LR; Pittsburgh, Cleveland, Cincinnati, Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFC West:  &LR; Denver, San Diego, Oakland, Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFC South:  &LR; Houston, Tennessee, Jacksonville, Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few questions in the AFC but none that would be as
difficult as trying to get Bidwill to leave the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Houston fans might want their new team to return
to the AFC Central in place of Baltimore or Cincinnati. Don't
expect it to happen. Ravens owner Art Modell and Bengals owner Mike
Brown have been in the NFL for decades, and their partners aren't
going to vote for McNair over them, even if McNair did pay a $700
million entry fee.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the newly created AFC South would be interesting. Colts
quarterback Peyton Manning would be entering his fifth season.
There is no reason to believe the Jaguars wouldn't remain an elite
team as they have been since 1996, their second season of
existence.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps best of all, Houston and Tennessee would play every
season. Now that could become quite a rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Modell, who has vowed to never return to Cleveland
because he fears for his life, Titans owner Bud Adams would have
the courage to attend games in Houston's new stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
