<HEADLINE>
PINCAY 40 SHORT OF SHOEMAKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Jockey Laffit Pincay Jr. entered the week 40
wins from tying Bill Shoemaker's all-time record.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker's record is 8,833. Pincay entered Wednesday with
8,793. He won Saturday aboard Golden Tassel at 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to ride four mounts today.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Tree leaders: Entering the week, David Flores leads all
jockeys with seven wins at Oak Tree. Gary Stevens is second through
Sunday with five wins. Stevens in the money percentage is an
impressive 59 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Flores won the riding crown at Del Mar with 38 wins from 208
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Cerin leads all trainers with a remarkable four wins in
10 starts. Cerin had just eight wins in 43 starts at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   Scott joins fair circuit: If you are looking for jockey Joy
Scott, she's moved on _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime fixture on the Southern California thoroughbred
horseracing scene, Scott is currently on the fair circuit. She had
two mounts at Fresno on Wednesday, Creates in the seventh and
Pouring Down Rain in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back: Gary Stevens may be wishing he was back in merry
olde England. The jockey, who returned here after leaving for Great
Britain last spring, got nailed with a five-day suspension this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension was leveled on Stevens on Tuesday for his ride
aboard Wealth of Nations in Saturday's fifth race.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens moved Wealth of Nations to the outside for a clear path
but instead caused several horses to bump one another.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who finished sixth in the race, is suspended through
Sunday. He will be allowed to ride in designated races.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9296 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     10-07 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ On the downside, we lost five seasons worth of cheers _
surely a few jeers, too _ and a nickname most people loved, some
negative connotations notwithstanding. We also lost Steve McNair
and Eddie George in the prime of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, getting a new NFL team is going to cost the community
roughly $50 million more than keeping the old team.
</P>
<P>
   The upside? No more Bud-bashing. No more Columbia blue. A new
stadium that Steve Patterson, Bob McNair's point man, promises will
be ``the finest on the planet.'' Plus, of course, McNair himself, a
prince of a fellow who will surely at some point in constructing
his new franchise will make a mistake _ something, amazingly, he
hasn't done yet.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget a Super Bowl _ perhaps XXXVIII in 2004 _ with
its estimated $450 million impact on the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Adams never fielded an NFL champion in all the years the
Oilers represented Houston. That failure was not necessarily his
fault, but the buck stopped with him. And his image in the
community, combined with the Oilers' travails on the field, created
an environment ultimately so poisoned that his departure to
Nashville's greener pastures became inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   And, it must be said, beneficial, as of Wednesday morning's
decision to pass on Los Angeles' squabbling, disorganized,
underfunded factions and award McNair the NFL's 32nd franchise, not
to mention the aforementioned Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It was a no-brainer, to say the least. McNair's willingness to
part with the staggering sum of $700 million and a stadium to end
all retractable-roof, real-grass stadiums was tantamount to a
roundhouse right to the bridge of LA's nose.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bud, whatever anger and hurt he may feel for how Houston _
in his mind, anyway _ wronged him, knew what had to be done. Adams,
who still lives and works among us, supported McNair both in the
expansion committee vote and in the general vote by all the owners,
none of whom could say ``nay'' to a man who clearly deserved to
join their, ahem, august fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, money talks, Ovitz walks. Broad and Roski, too.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles blew a bigger lead than the Oilers did in Buffalo by
failing to secure public funding on any front and never reaching a
consensus on a suitable venue. Michael Ovitz, Eli Broad and Ed
Roski were the Three Stooges incarnate, squabbling and ducking the
core issues right up to the very end. As badly as the NFL wanted to
reclaim the nation's No. 2 TV market, it couldn't crunch the
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Not with McNair sitting there, a bird, a veritable peacock, in
hand.
</P>
<P>
   McNair sold his energy company, Cogen Technologies, to raise
capital for his football venture. He worked his tail off to close
the massive and complicated deal, finally staying up almost all
night Tuesday fine-tuning the most minute details before the
expansion committee reconvened at 7 a.m. Houston time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now,'' he conceded, ``comes the hard part.''
</P>
<P>
   First, McNair needs a sales/marketing department to begin
pushing luxury boxes. Seventy-five of the planned-for 110, at an
average price of $145,000, must be sold by mid-January. Otherwise,
McNair will be in violation of his freshly signed agreement with
the NFL and, as Patterson said, ``We don't want to get off on the
wrong foot.''
</P>
<P>
   A nickname and team colors also are a high priority because they
identify the product to the fans. You will, by the way, help him
choose the former, if not necessarily the latter, which figure to
include some shade of green.
</P>
<P>
   Bob is Irish, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium construction is a super-high priority as well. It must
begin as soon as the rodeo ends in February to be ready for the
2002 season, and there will surely be cost issues to confront. The
$310 million price tag was set 18 months ago, and you know how
those things go. Somebody, be it McNair or the Harris
County-Houston Sports Authority, the city and/or the county, will
have to sign off on covering the anticipated overruns.
</P>
<P>
   It behooves all parties, however, to join hands and maintain a
united front. McNair must get the utmost cooperation from every
government entity in reciprocation for his remarkable efforts, for
which we lack a sufficient variety of laudatory adjectives.
</P>
<P>
   If sports matter, and they seem to, no grander civic gesture has
ever been made on Houston's behalf. While one might argue Bob's
immense fortune could be better spent on more noble causes, that's
hardly the point. McNair made himself a billionaire fairly and
squarely, and he has every right to choose how he spends his money.
</P>
<P>
   He won't profit hugely from this investment. He may not profit
at all for many years. But the city will, and for this he deserves
a thank-you from the bottom of our hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, too, actually. If Bud hadn't left, the story couldn't
have had such a happy ending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
