<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THERE'S MONEY TO BURN, LET IT BURN IN HOUSTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Football fans in Houston will be talking about
Wednesday's big win for years. Between bites at the Goode Company
BBQ and the Cadillac Cafe they'll get giddy recounting how, in the
first month of overtime in the Expansion Bowl between Houston and
L.A., Bob McNair caught Michael Ovitz flat-footed with his Hail
Mary pass to the NFL owners.
</P>
<P>
   He threw them $700 million, McNair did, after maneuvering
Houston into position on the strength of a $195 million pledge of
public monies for a $310 million stadium, $9 million in city funds
for a parking lot and a new $300 million rail line.
</P>
<P>
   By today's gold standards, it was a textbook-perfect drive. To
those with the spoils goes the victory. We in L.A. applaud McNair's
effort and execution.
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations, Houston. The NFL is your problem.
</P>
<P>
   Better you than us.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing pro football back to Houston was such a priority,
McNair bid $170 million over the sale price of the expansion
franchise in Cleveland, which began play this season. For that kind
of outlay, Houston should get a football team and also have its
overtaxed thoroughfares swept of traffic and its summers siphoned
of humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz's last-minute drive came up a few hundred million dollars
short. He's so vain, he probably thinks Angelenos feel his pain.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Wednesday's slap in the face hurts Ovitz a lot
more than it does L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Our Sundays aren't going to be wasted on the NFL's diluted
product and neither are our tax dollars. It's all good for us.
</P>
<P>
   Let Ovitz grow his ego at somebody else's expense. That's all
the NFL is to its billionaire owners: an anabolic steroid for their
egos.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. already flexes a mean muscle in sports, entertainment and
industry. The city doesn't need a boost, it doesn't need any more
megalomaniacs masquerading as civic boosters.
</P>
<P>
   If L.A. needs anything, it's for its denizens to make like
Denver linebacker Bill Romanowski and spit on the next person who
tries to wed us to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   It's insulting for Angelenos to be told we need the NFL to
complete us. Yeah, right. That's why a recently published U.S.
travel guide devoted 23 pages to L.A. attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's charms were summed up in five pages and if that
doesn't sufficiently explain why the city was desperate to
re-acquire an NFL team, there's this: one of the points of interest
is the American Funeral Service Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Houston's victory does not mean the NFL is dead in L.A. To
the contrary, somebody somewhere _ maybe in Minneapolis, perhaps in
Phoenix _ will look at L.A. and next thing we know he'll be
flirting with us shamelessly.
</P>
<P>
   Owners will want to dance with us, if for no other reason than
to make their jealous cities collapse in a heap of costly
concessions. L.A. has been a willing partner in these tawdry
affairs before, charming the Dodgers out of Brooklyn, the Lakers
out of Minneapolis and the Clippers out of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   That was before we lost both our NFL teams to sweet-talking
cities. L.A. is wiser and warier for having gotten trampled by its
own stiletto heels. We are less inclined to give our hearts, our
souls and our discretionary income to a league that exudes all the
emotional warm of a steel bank vault.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL, so unaccustomed to rejection, probably will try to spin
the story so L.A. comes out looking like a ditzy, glitzy city that
just couldn't get its act together. That's OK. To live in L.A. is
to know we have never been more level-headed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
