<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF HE COULD DO IT OVER ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ Mattias Norstrom stood between Ray Whitney and
the end of the Los Angeles Kings winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   The club's top defensive defenseman had helped limit Florida to
just three shots in the third period Wednesday night, but he was
defenseless when caught between Whitney and Viktor Kozlov on the
Panthers' 2-1 break with 1:51 left. Whitney slipped the pass past
Norstrom and Kozlov beat goalie Stephane Fiset for the tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers wound up winning 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Andy Murray said there was little Norstrom could have
done, but Norstrom was clearly upset. He didn't feel tired after
missing all of training camp in a contract dispute, but couldn't
help but wonder if he could have done more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I could have been in better game shape,'' said
Norstrom, who signed a four-year deal last Thursday. ``I know we
played well for 58 minutes, but right now I wish I had stopped that
puck. We just broke down at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Second fiddle: Overlooked in season-opening victories at
Nashville and St. Louis, the Kings' second line of Donald Audette,
Bryan Smolinski and Glen Murray did not score for the third
consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Rob Blake is the only player besides Luc Robitaille,
Ziggy Palffy and Jozef Stumpel to score for the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray was encouraged that the second line got plenty of
chances Wednesday. That did not happen in the first two games.
Audette, who has 13 career goals against the Panthers, got just one
first-period shot. Smolinski had three and Murray two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously looking for more balance,'' Murray said. ``The
first line has come together great, but the second line had some
chances tonight. They'll get theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenna out: Steve McKenna, a left-winger on the Kings fourth
line, will undergo laser surgery today to repair a partially torn
retina in his left eye suffered Monday night in St. Louis. He is
expected to miss one to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna, who missed 56 games last season with an abdominal
injury, returned to Los Angeles on Wednesday morning for an
examination by team eye doctor Howard Lazerson.
</P>
<P>
   McKenna, 26, was struck on the left cheekbone by the butt of
Ricard Persson's stick in the second period and quickly rushed off
the ice. He received five stitches and did not return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
