r s BC-FBN-TORTURE-LADN     10-07 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TORTURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAILED L.A. BID WAS `TORTURUOS EXPERIENCE`
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The people trying to bring an expansion team to
Los Angeles were forced to play the NFL's game, and in the end came
out battered, bruised and on the losing end.
</P>
<P>
   When Houston was awarded the league's 32nd franchise over two
rival groups from L.A., it left disappointed feelings among those
who came up on the short end.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got involved eight months ago, somebody told me it
would be a laborious, torturous experience,'' said billionaire Eli
Broad, who with partner Ed Roski Jr., tried to get a team at the
Coliseum. ``That was accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas, the chief proponent of the
Coliseum, agreed, saying, ``They put everyone through torture.
That's their game.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad said he and Roski had put up ``several million dollars''
in developing their proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ovitz, the former superagent who teamed with grocery
magnate Ron Burkle, has said they spent millions on plans and land
options in trying to join the NFL club.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a long, arduous ordeal,'' Ovitz said. ``I
started at the Coliseum, they asked me to go to Carson and I did,
they asked me to go back to the Coliseum and I did, then they asked
me to go to Hollywood Park. I've done everything they asked. I
played by their rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules, of course, kept changing. Roski and Broad thought
their bid started to slip away when they gave up their exclusive at
the Coliseum, leaving officials unsure of who to negotiate with and
further muddling an already confusing process.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you confuse a project like this, bouncing it around,
going to different locations and different individuals, it gives an
undue burden on a project that could be done fairly simple, if
approached differently,'' Roski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether that made any difference at the end, I don't know. I
don't think given our restraints in California, in particular Los
Angeles, we could have matched the offer Houston made.''
</P>
<P>
   Some city officials said they resented the NFL's tactic of
pitting cities against each other to boost bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL absolutely, positively used Los Angeles to stage a
bidding war to the the $700 million from Houston,'' said councilman
Joel Wachs, a leader in opposing use of any tax money for
professional football.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Coupal of the Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association said the
Houston choice was good news for Los Angeles taxpayers and
described the league as behaving ``like a burglar that keeps
circling the house hoping to find an unlocked window.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about sports any more.'' said Wachs. ``This is
about money and how much money the NFL can squeeze out of a city.
You're not talking about even millionaires anymore. You're talking
about billionaires.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
