<HEADER>
A9301 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     10-07 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANSION VOTE A WIN-WIN-WIN DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The morning after Houston got the nod, Los Angeles
awakens with bloodshot eyes, a pounding headache, a sour stomach
and the vaguest sense of melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   Too much champagne will do that to a town.
</P>
<P>
   Champagne? After losing the bid for the NFL's 32nd franchise by
a practically unanimous vote of the other club owners?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, champagne. Because _ congratulations _ Los Angeles had a
victory to celebrate Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   There are three winners at the end of this long, messy,
downright ridiculous process of selecting an NFL expansion city.
Everybody got what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Football-mad Houston is a winner because it gets to replace the
Oilers, gone to Tennessee in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The money-mad NFL is a winner because it gets a $700 million
franchise fee from Houston power-plant operator Bob McNair, a
record sum that raises the value of each existing team.
</P>
<P>
   And Los Angeles is a winner because it set its priorities and
stuck to them, a rare accomplishment anymore in the overlapping
worlds of pro sports and politics.
</P>
<P>
   We don't have a pro football team, but we have the deed to City
Hall. We don't have a pro football team, but we have pride in
knowing we'll get along fine without it.
</P>
<P>
   This might sound like sour grapes: City loses football team and
local columnist says, ``We didn't really want it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what I'm saying.
</P>
<P>
   A football team would have been nice. Good for Monday-morning
conversations at the fax machine. A rallying point for a
disconnected city.
</P>
<P>
   Don't fall for this notion that Los Angeles is not a pro
football town. It had the Rams for 49 years. They're still our most
enduring franchise. The Dodgers just finished their 42nd season
here. The Lakers are beginning their 40th.
</P>
<P>
   We gave up on the Rams and Raiders at the end not because we
dislike pro football but because they were bad teams being run into
the ground by front offices insensitive to the fans. Neither team
has posted a winning season since leaving.
</P>
<P>
   And don't believe the people of Los Angeles weren't dead set
against the return of pro football. It's just that not enough
people were dead set in favor.
</P>
<P>
   That meant insufficient support for spending tax money to build
a new stadium or refurbish the Coliseum. So we drew the line short
of giving public money to owners and players who didn't need our
charity. Then, like few cities, we resisted the temptation to step
over the line.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is different in this regard from Houston, which is
putting $195 million in public money into a retractable-roof
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   We're pretty savvy about the business behind entertainment and
sports. We make movies, television and music here. We have eight
major pro franchises and two major sports universities. We've seen
teams come and go.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen the man behind the curtain. We know he's a man in a
pinstripe suit who might not have the best interests of the city at
heart.
</P>
<P>
   So when a guy like that wants to put a stadium and a team here,
most people's attitude is the same as when Walgreens plans to build
a drug store in the neighborhood. Fine, just don't expect me to
drive the crane and don't count on me shopping there.
</P>
<P>
   We could have broken our promise to ourselves and mailed our tax
checks to the NFL. By making the acquisition of a football team a
civic priority, we could have put in a unified bid and might have
succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   We knew the consequences if we refused the sugar-coated tax
plans: Instead of speaking to the NFL with one voice about one
proposed site, Los Angeles would be represented by rival
billionaires playing musical stadiums. We were a football team with
two head coaches, running two playbooks at once.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the league kept delaying a choice between cities, hoping
Los Angeles would cave in, embarrassed by the thought of losing out
to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't cave in. And messy as the process was, as it turned
out, we didn't lose.
</P>
<P>
   In the hard game of achieving public consensus, we won. Ugly,
but we won.
</P>
<P>
   So celebrate. Just leave some champagne for Houston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
