<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPS MAKE CLOSE CALLS, AND BOTH GO DIAMONDBACKS' WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The tone of the second game of the division series
between the New York Mets and the Arizona Diamondbacks on Wednesday
night was set by two early plays that were thisclose. Each call
went the Diamondbacks' way, and that's why they made their way to
New York tied with the Mets at 1-1. The plays, however, easily
could have been called in the Mets' favor had the umpires been
watching television replays.
</P>
<P>
   Replays, however, are not a part of the umpires' lexicon. They
certainly are a major no-no after Frank Pulli, now a former
National League umpire, actually used a replay earlier this season
to determine whether a home run was a home run. Pulli, a veteran
umpire, who was rated among the league's top half dozen in a 1998
players' survey, was one of 22 umpires whose resignations were
accepted in a labor dispute, and his replay reprimand was seen as
an element in that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Coleman, the N.L. president, was seated in the second
row next to the Diamondbacks' dugout when Wally Bell and Dana
DeMuth made the close calls on Wednesday night, Bell at home plate,
DeMuth at second base. On the play at the plate, with two out in
the Arizona third inning, Bell called Matt Williams safe. On the
play at second base, with no one out in the Mets' fourth, DeMuth
called Robin Ventura out.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' run, the second that scored on Steve Finley's single,
gave the Diamondbacks a 3-1 lead. Ventura's out, quickly followed
by a double play, undermined a threat that might have enabled the
Mets to tie the game or take the lead. Bobby Valentine, the Mets'
manager, only mildly argued the call at the plate; he did not
emerge from the dugout after the call at second.
</P>
<P>
   Both plays were so close that repeated replays did not settle
them beyond a shadow of doubt. When that happens, umpires cannot be
faulted even if subsequent television angles show they were wrong.
Umpires get to make the call once, when they see the play live.
Television viewers have an advantage by having the benefit of
replays, and they often still can't agree on what they're seeing.
</P>
<P>
   In the matter of the Williams run, he slid home as Mike Piazza
caught the throw from Roger Cedeno, who had fielded Finley's single
in right field. Williams slid right leg first and appeared ready to
be safe. But just before his right foot reached the plate, his leg
went up in the air and became Piazza's target. Piazza also tried to
block the plate with his own leg, but he left a bit of the front
uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza tagged Williams' lead leg, and he appeared to do that an
instant before Williams' trailing leg, the left one, made contact
with the exposed part of the plate, although one replay was
inconclusive as to whether Piazza tagged the leg at all.
</P>
<P>
   Unperturbed by Finley's two-run single or the call at the plate,
Kenny Rogers retired the next batter, Bernard Gilkey, on a grounder
to third for the third out. The Mets immediately mounted their
threat.
</P>
<P>
   If there's one thing a manager hates to see, it's his pitcher
walking the leadoff batter in the opposing team's turn at bat
immediately after his team has scored, especially when the run or
runs give the team a tie or a lead. But Todd Stottlemyre threw four
pitches to Ventura and all were balls. Runner at first.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton, with two balls and one strike, then hit a
grounder to Jay Bell that had double play written on it. But when
the second baseman seemed to want to throw the ball before he had
it, he lost the ball for an error. Runners at first and second.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno was the next batter, and after taking the first pitch for
a ball, he tried to bunt and sacrifice the runners to second and
third. But Cedeno missed the pitch, and Ventura, having taken a
running start on his way to third, was caught too far off second.
Catcher Kelly Stinnett fired the ball to shortstop Tony Womack as
Ventura scrambled back toward the bag and dived in headfirst.
</P>
<P>
   The ball beat Ventura to the base, but Womack's tag _ if he
tagged him _didn't necessarily beat Ventura. In going to tag the
runner, Womack fell over him and, replays seemed to indicate, might
have missed him with his glove, which held the ball. But umpires
often give the play at second to the fielder if the ball beats the
runner there.
</P>
<P>
   As if the out at second didn't put a damper on the Mets' threat,
the next play extinguished it altogether. After taking a second
ball, Cedeno hit a grounder to the first base side of second. Bell
fielded this one cleanly and went to tag Hamilton coming from
first. Bell's idea was to tag Hamilton for one out, then flip to
first for the completion of the double play.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, however, didn't want to be tagged so he ducked around
Bell, who then ignored him and threw to first to get Cedeno. But
even before Bell released the ball, DeMuth raised his right arm,
signaling that Hamilton got himself out by going out of the
baseline. The Diamondbacks had the double play, and the Mets had
spoiled their last chance to make a game of it.
</P>
<P>
   Finley drilled a two-run double to right-center field in the
fifth inning, raising the Arizona lead to 5-1, and Stottlemyre
continued to baffle the Mets' batters. The night before they
battered Randy Johnson. This night they stroked three singles
against Stottlemyre in the first six innings. With that kind of
production, they are not going to get to play in the World Series
against the team Stottlemyre's father coaches for. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
