<SLUG> BC-BKN-BUSS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' BUSS EXPLAINS DOLLARS, CENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ A palatial downtown arena promises to
fill Jerry Buss' bank account with millions of dollars in new
revenue this season. He's wasted no time deciding how to spend it
all.
</P>
<P>
   He hired the best coach money could buy this summer _ $6 million
a year for Phil Jackson _ and has committed to a payroll in the $60
million range.
</P>
<P>
   But he passed on acquiring one high-priced star (Scottie Pippen)
in order to have the money needed to retain another (Glen Rice)
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even without Pippen to run Jackson's offense, or the
bruising power forward Buss coveted (Charles Oakley), the Los
Angeles Lakers' owner believes his team can win the NBA
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the best team we've had in the last four or
five years,'' Buss said Wednesday in an informal meeting with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at length for the first time since February, Buss said
he never seriously considered bringing back Rodman. He also said he
never got past the discussion stage regarding a trade for Pippen,
the ex-Chicago Bull recently dealt from Houston to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, a Jackson favorite, wanted a reunion with his old coach.
But the $54 million and four years remaining on Pippen's contract
made him an unattractive acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we ever really came close to getting Scottie at
all,'' Buss said. ``It's something that always comes up in a
conversation ... but it really would make it impossible for us
because his salary a couple of years hence would deny you any
opportunity whatsoever to pick up any kind of a good free agent. So
when you take him, you're basically saying, `This is our personnel
for the next four years.' Right now we have a lot more (roster
flexibility), and I think we should maintain that.''
</P>
<P>
   Buss said reports of the Lakers offering Rice, Robert Horry and
possibly Travis Knight to Houston for Pippen were ``not true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie is just a great player, and certainly, for a year or
two, it would have been the right thing to do,'' Buss said. ``We
probably would have done it had he not had a four-year contract.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no such temptation when it came to Rodman, the
troublemaking rebounder who disrupted the Lakers often during his
23-game stopover last season. Rodman, still unemployed, has lobbied
to return and has even predicted he would. But even his friendship
with Buss and relationship with Jackson won't open that door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody's really seriously considered bringing
back Dennis,'' said Buss, who nevertheless claimed he has no
regrets about any personnel decisions made last season _ from the
firing of Del Harris to the trade for Rice to the signing of
Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers will once again rely on a power forward by committee
to support the starring trio of Shaquille O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and
Rice. If Jackson's system can, as promised, weave a championship
season from that group, Rice stands to profit.
</P>
<P>
   A free agent next summer, Rice is seeking a contract starting at
the NBA maximum of $14 million, a figure he can only get from the
Lakers. Buss already has committed $70.9 million to Bryant and $120
million to O'Neal, but indicated he'll pay whatever Rice is worth
to keep him here in the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's pretty much what's on Jerry (West)'s mind,''
Buss said. ``My understanding of Jerry's thinking is I think he
wants to watch him play this year.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for the big contract? ``I think we're going to have to
pay the market price for the personnel that we want.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he deserves that money, we would have to pay it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jackson's case, the decision was almost a no-brainer, even
for an owner who's never paid a coach more than $2 million. But
when faced with bringing back unproven Kurt Rambis or hiring a
coach with six championships in the 1990s, Buss didn't hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that after the season was over, it became obvious to
us that we probably would have a better chance if we had a real
big-name coach who would command the kind of respect that Phil
does,'' Buss said. ``I think part of it had to do with the triangle
offense. That was very successful with Michael Jordan, of course.
And, with Kobe and with Shaq, I thought that was something that
would probably improve our performance on the court a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Buss also felt the Lakers' high-salaried superstars needed an
equally high-paid, high-profile coach to command their attention,
something Rambis and Del Harris sometimes could not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult for somebody making one-tenth of what the
player he's talking to (makes) and get that kind of respect,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers may yet make a move for an established power forward,
but Buss is confident the group he has can catch the NBA champion
San Antonio Spurs, who knocked his team out of the playoffs in a
second-round sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we came reasonably close to San Antonio last year
... so hopefully the triangle offense and some more work and
maturity from the players will make us a better team,'' he said.
``I think we have a excellent chance with the personnel we have
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Rice was held out of most of the morning practice at UC
Santa Barbara because of tendinitis in his left knee but was able
to participate fully in the evening practice.... O'Neal weighed in
at about 340 pounds, missing an unspecified goal Jackson set for
him. ``But I'm not unhappy about it,'' Jackson said. ``I think he's
in condition. I think (the desired weight) is something we can get
to during the season.''.... General manager Mitch Kupchak said the
team still hopes to sign former Bulls guard Ron Harper....
First-round pick Devean George dislocated his left pinky but was
able to practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
