<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISIONS OF CBA KEEP HUDSON WELL MOTIVATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After conceding their staggering mismatch at the
position of team owner, the Los Angeles Clippers' most critically
disclaimed job description is point guard.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of rebuttal, the floor now belongs to Troy Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come to the games and watch the performance,'' said Hudson,
who will co-star with recently acquired veteran Eric Murdock as
Clipper playmakers.
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics who missed Hudson's audition last season, have
predicted a point-guard horror show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take it personally,'' Hudson said while winding down
after a spirited training-camp workout at L.A. Southwest College.
``I just go out and try to prove them wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He began gathering evidence at the University of Missouri, where
rare playing time inspired Hudson's transfer to Southern Illinois
University in his hometown of Carbondale.
</P>
<P>
   After averaging 21 points per game in his junior season, Hudson
entered the NBA Draft and couldn't find his way out. With an assist
from a training-camp injury to John Stockton, he made the Utah Jazz
as an undrafted rookie. When Stockton returned, Hudson took his
eight-game NBA resume all the way to the CBA.
</P>
<P>
   He remained stuck there in his second pro season, until being
rescued by the Clippers midway through the post-lockout disaster of
1999. In 25 games, Hudson produced 6.8 points, 3.7 assists and
enough fearlessness per game to hang around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy's a guy who just competes all out,'' said Clippers coach
Chris Ford. ``That's the energy I love.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hudson, vivid memories of CBA life make it easy to stay
motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were more down times than good times in the CBA,'' he
admitted. ``But I always thought I could play here. To stay here, I
have to continue to play hard and be a leader on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   And his objective review on the state of Clippers point guards?
</P>
<P>
   ``Between myself and Eric Murdock, we have a solid backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, they don't seem to be grooming owners in the CBA.
</P>
<P>
   Fast breaks: When charted with rookies in the NBA's rookie class
of 1999, undrafted Clipper Tyrone Nesby ranked among the top 10 in
nine statistical categories. But he still doesn't have a sneaker
deal. Converse soon may change that.... Murdock, who played at
Providence College, holds the NCAA career record for steals (376 in
117 games). He averaged 25 points per game as a senior
(1990-'91).... Kebu Stewart, the star of the Clippers' Summer Pro
League entry at the Pyramid, is camping with the Dallas Mavericks.
Stewart, who led that league in scoring and took the silver in
rebounding, didn't impress the coaching staff enough to warrant a
guaranteed contract. He wasn't offered a guaranteed deal in Dallas,
either....
</P>
<P>
   The search for a backup center continues, but may not yield a
plausible alternative until league rosters are trimmed....
According to strength coach Johnny Doyle, one of the mightiest
Clippers pound for pound is 6-foot-5, 195-pound shooting guard
Derek Anderson. His surgically repaired knees also have received
ringing endorsements from team physician Dr. Tony Daly. Anderson,
acquired from Cleveland in the sign-and-trade deal that made Lamond
Murray a Cavalier, missed a dozen games last season, but currently
is moving around the court like a missile under factory warranty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
