<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH GAME TAPES, THERE'S NO TRUSTING IN FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC wanted to scout Arizona by reviewing tapes of
every Wildcats game this season. But when a courtesy call was
placed to Penn State requesting a copy of the Pigskin Classic, the
Trojans were told to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe (Paterno) didn't offer the game to us,'' USC coach Paul
Hackett said. ``They wouldn't send it to anybody. When you have an
extra game, you don't send it to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it's common practice for teams playing in early
games to make agreements not to send out tapes to future opponents.
The theory is that Arizona would open up its entire playbook
against the Nittany Lions, compared to a later game, against, say,
Middle Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   But would Penn State have sent it to USC anyway? The Nittany
Lions' series with Pitt ended in 1993, which was Hackett's last
season. His last game before being fired was a 57-13 loss to Penn
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us pretty good,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery man: Backup quarterback John Fox is eager to show he's
ready to play in a game, but is as curious as fans to see how much
has changed since he last started a game in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't lost much of a step. I'm older, more mature,
although I haven't had game experience,'' Fox said. ``It's a
mystery to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox also knows that he is one injury (to Mike Van Raaphorst)
away from becoming USC's quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything can happen. I don't go in expecting Mike to get hurt
and I pray that he doesn't,'' Fox said. ``But I prepare to play 70
snaps in a game whether I can get in or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes progressing: Wide receiver Windrell Hayes practiced
Wednesday and appears fit to play. He'll sit out today's practice
to rest his sore ankle. Hackett was also pleased with tailback
Malaefou MacKenzie's recovery from a sore hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw some of the cutting from the old Malaefou,'' he said.
``I don't imagine he'll get a lot of work but we'll ease him in.''
</P>
<P>
   Less likely to play large roles are center Eric Denmon (knee)
and guard Donta Kendrick (ankle). Both will be available but won't
be 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno raises profile: Linebacker Zeke Moreno was named the
season's first winner of the Bronko Nagurski National Defensive
Player of the Week award.
</P>
<P>
   The award is given to the top player each week by the Charlotte
Touchdown Club, for the nation's top defensive player.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more interesting, the Butkus Award committee is debating
whether to put Moreno on its watch list of the nation's top
linebackers, which would lead to placing his name on the ballot
sent to voters. A decision will be made next week.
</P>
<P>
   On the case: USC will go to the Coliseum today to investigate
why the headphones malfunctioned last Saturday. It's believed that
a stadium employee may have plugged the 110-volt headsets into a
220-volt socket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
