<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MORE WORRIES FOR CSUN SAFETY SPARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even though he didn't lose hope, Rahman Sparks
wondered if he was ever going to make an impact on the Cal State
Northridge football team.
</P>
<P>
   He's not worrying anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks, a senior safety who played sparingly last season, leads
CSUN in tackles entering the Matadors' Big Sky Conference game
Saturday at Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks has 31 tackles, including 18 solo, and five pass
deflections. He was supposed to back up Hassan Abdul-Malik at free
safety to start the season but Abdul-Malik pulled his hamstring
early in fall camp and is now going to redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to work hard if (Abdul-Malik) was here or not,'' said
Sparks, who played the first two games at cornerback before moving
to safety. ``I just had to tell myself that as soon as I got the
opportunity, I had to step up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks transferred to CSUN from L.A. Southwest College prior to
the 1998 season. He had seven tackles in three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing behind a big-time dude,'' Sparks said, referring
to Vito Clemente, who had 68 tackles and three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks would have made Clemente proud against Eastern Washington
on Sept. 25; despite missing most of the fourth quarter with sore
ribs, Sparks had 12 tackles, forced a fumble and had a sack.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy who figured to be a backup this season after
Abdul-Malik earned the starting job in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I needed to work harder,'' he said. ``I dropped a
few pounds over the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Relieving pressure: The Matadors have already had three players
start at left guard on the offensive line, but the latest _
sophomore Javier Ortiz _ seems to have nailed down the job for the
rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stepped into that role, and he's done a good job,''
offensive line coach Bob Connelly said of Ortiz, a 6-3, 285-pound
transfer from Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   Another new starter on the line is freshman Nick Longshore, a
left tackle from Canyon High. Longshore has been Johnny Acosta's
backup through the first four games.
</P>
<P>
   Battling back: Julio Alcala, CSUN's starting center, isn't
participating in every drill in practice to protect his sore lower
back from getting worse. But after sitting out a few practices a
few weeks ago, Alcala thought his technique wasn't sharp in games
and requested more action.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches agreed, but Alcala is playing only with the
first-team offense and not in scout drills.``(Alcala) not
practicing and still playing Saturdays doesn't frighten me too
much,'' Connelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Middle man: After an early-season slump, middle linebacker Cos
Abercrombie has 20 tackles in his past two games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
