<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9308 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-PARKINSON'S-AZR &LR;      10-07 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKINSON'S-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE IN PARKINSON'S FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Fred Forbes' voice is weak and hard to make out over
the phone, a telltale sign of Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   But when talk turns to a recent federal court ruling that allows
fetal tissue research in Arizona, the 64-year-old Tucson resident
be comes clear as a bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be in the front of the line,'' said Forbes, a retired
electrical engineer and one of 10 plaintiffs who challenged a state
ban on using fetal tissue in research.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes now wants to be the first Arizona volunteer injected with
fetal brain cells, a procedure that could help reverse the
debilitating effects of Parkinson's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to participating as a patient and giving myself
up as a guinea pig,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fetal tissue research also may help patients with spinal cord
inju ries, epilepsy and other neuro-de generative diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the medical promise, the use of fetal tissue poses grave
ethical questions. And last month's ruling may face an appeal by
Arizona Attorney General Janet Napolitano.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we need to take a look at what options we have,
if any,'' said Pati Urias, a spokes woman for Napolitano. ``It's a
really complicated issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers in other states have found limited success using
fetal cells to restore the adult brain cells that produce dopamine,
a chemical that controls movement and coordi nation.
</P>
<P>
   But a 24-year ban on such research has stymied doctors from
using any tissues and fluids from aborted fetuses in Arizona. The
ban was overturned Sept. 30 by U.S. District Judge William Browning
in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   The ban was challenged by the New York-based Center for Repro
ductive Law and Policy, which represented four people with Parkin
son's, two people affiliated with Planned Parenthood Inc. and four
other Arizonans.
</P>
<P>
   For Forbes, who has given up night driving and recently had to
buy a walking cane, the ruling offers hope that fetal cell Parkin
son's researchers will consider com ing to Arizona, and that those
who left when the ban went into effect in 1975 may return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that produces the dopamine that I need is fetal
cells, and I'm scraping the bottom of the barrel right now,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are equally enthusi astic about the ruling, although
they caution patients that fetal cell thera pies may not provide a
cure for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that the fetal implants are the most hopeful, but
it's an area that we should have open to us to learn how to help
patients,'' said Dr. Barry Hendin, a Phoenix neurolo gist and
clinical professor at the University of Arizona's medical school
campus in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Current treatment for most Par kinson's patients is medication
and sometimes surgery to stimulate pro duction of dopamine in an
area of the middle brain known as the substantia nigra.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers are always on the lookout for more aggressive
treat ments that could lead to a cure for the disease, which
affects 1.5 mil lion Americans. The disease is characterized by
tremors, stiffness in the limbs, loss of balance, a weaker voice
and episodes of ``freezing,'' in which patients feel stuck in place
and unable to move.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to Arizona's ban on fetal tissue research began in
1996 with the Center for Reproduc tive Law and Policy. The center
moved to overturn the state law because of the number of Parkin
son's patients in Arizona and be cause of new clinical trials that
proposed using fetal brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   Bebe Anderson, a staff attorney for the center, said the
Legislature shouldn't block the evolution of medical techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't surprised in that I do believe that these laws are
unconsti tutionally vague,'' she said. ``Cer tainly, I was very
pleased with the ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the issue repre sents a slippery slope for medical
science, Anderson said that certain safeguards can protect against
fe tuses being aborted for the sole purpose of providing research
tis sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite an argument that's unfair both to Parkinson's
patients and women who are considering whether to carry a pregnancy
to term,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The use of fetal tissue is not new in medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't realize that the polio vaccine was developed
in the 1950s by work on dead fetuses,'' said Dr. Charles Daschbach,
chair man of medical ethics education at St. Joseph's Hospital and
Medical Center in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many other cases where learning about fetuses has
helped the human condition. We wouldn't have had amniocentesis and
some of the ultrasound findings that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Daschbach cautions that fetal tissue research is a mine
field of ethical dilemmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibilities for alleviating suffering and preventing
disease are phenomenal, but we always have to ask the fundamental
question of what are we sacrificing to get there.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kerry Fehr-Snyder can be reached at (602) 444-8975 or at
kerry.fehr-snyder &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
