<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS TIE SERIES WITH 7-1 VICTORY OVER METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The predictions should be tossed aside, the
expectations shelved. The New York Mets were supposed to be in the
post-season but had to scurry to unearth their invitation from the
trash heap hours before the party began.
</P>
<P>
   They were expected to be too weary from their one-game playoff
against Cincinnati to keep their bleary eyes focused on Randy
Johnson's fastballs on Tuesday night. But they managed to stay
awake long enough to batter one of the most dominant pitchers in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   And then, with a 1-0 lead in the three-of-five-game division
series against Arizona, the Mets were prepared to cruise against a
pitcher for whom each start is a testament to modern sports injury
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But following the Mets is like trying to balance on a surfboard.
The Mets can beat up on a pitcher that most opponents fear and then
be subdued by a pitcher who, less than five months ago, feared his
career might be over.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Stottlemyre and the Arizona Diamondbacks throttled the Mets
on Wednesday night, delivering a 7-1 loss to tie the series at 1-1
as it heads to New York for Games 3 and 4 on Friday night and
Saturday afternoon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This was a battle of two scarred pitchers: Kenny Rogers by his
Yankees experience and Todd Stottlemyre by a debilitating shoulder
injury that put him out of action for three months this season.
</P>
<P>
   In his five starts leading to the post-season, Stottlemyre had
not lasted more than six innings. On Wednesday night the Mets,
still riding the emotional high of their ninth-inning victory in
Game 1, struck first, scoring a run in the third when Rickey
Henderson hit a leadoff single, stole second base, went to third on
a fly ball and scored on a John Olerud grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, though, then began to roll. He struck out Mike
Piazza in the third and sixth innings. At that point, Piazza had
only one hit in eight post-season at-bats with four strikeouts.
Stottlemyre also held the sizzling Edgardo Alfonzo, who hit
Tuesday's game-winning grand slam, hitless. He lasted six and
two-thirds innings, and allowed only one run on four hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had their best opportunity to score again in the
seventh inning, when Rey Ordonez hit a one-out double off the
left-field fence with the pinch-hitter Bobby Bonilla up next.
Bonilla made the post-season roster precisely because he still
presents a power threat from both sides of the plate, but this time
he popped out in foul territory for the second out. Henderson
walked, and he and Ordonez pulled a double steal to put them at
second and third. However, Alfonzo grounded out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who was superb since returning to New York in a
midseason trade, would need more help than that. Entering the game,
he had a 5-1 record with a 4.03 earned run average in 12 starts for
the Mets, but in his previous four starts his era had jumped by
almost a full run. In his most recent start, though, which was also
the most important one, he allowed only two runs and struck out 10
in seven and a third innings against Pittsburgh, in the first game
of what was a must-win sweep that kept the Mets' playoff hopes
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He surprises me with his curveball, something I didn't know he
had developed so well,'' said Manager Bobby Valentine, who managed
Rogers in Texas. ``He's a much better pitcher than I remember. He's
everything that we had hoped for.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday night Rogers, who was still bothered by a
tweaked hamstring and back spasms, faced a team that is
particularly tough on left-handers. Arizona had the best record in
the majors against lefty starters this season, going 32-16. And
Rogers has a famously abysmal history in the post-season. While
with the Yankees in 1996, he went 0-0 with a 14.14 era in three
starts and one relief appearance.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, the Diamondbacks created fresh misery for
Rogers, who has insisted that he feels he has nothing to prove in
New York. With two out, Rogers appeared to be cruising through
another inning, when he allowed a single to left field by Jay Bell.
Then, Rogers, a control pitcher, unraveled. He hit Luis Gonzalez
with a pitch in the back. Matt Williams followed with a high
chopper that bounced in the dirt in front of home plate and drew
Rogers in to field it. He did, but by then he had nowhere to throw.
The bases were loaded for Greg Colbrunn. This season, Colbrunn was
.343 (12 for 35) with 18 runs batted in with men in scoring
position. This time, he drew a walk that brought in Bell to tie the
score at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Finley's numbers with the bases loaded this season were
impressive: he was 5 for 12 with 19 rbi. He smacked a 1-2 pitch for
a single to right field that scored Gonzalez and had Williams
racing for home plate. But right fielder Roger Cedeno made a
perfect throw to the plate and Williams slid. As he came in, his
lead leg _ the right one _ lifted in the air and his lower leg
appeared to have been tagged by Piazza, who had the plate blocked
with his left shin. But Williams was ruled safe and the Mets
trailed for the first time in the division series, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers remained in the game, but the fifth inning finally sent
him to the clubhouse. He allowed a leadoff single to Bell and then
struck out Gonzalez. Valentine brought in the reliever Pat Mahomes,
who was 8-0 with a 3.68 era in the regular season and whom Arizona
Manager Buck Showalter said may be pitching as well as anybody the
Mets have in their bullpen. But Mahomes was facing Williams first,
and he laced a single to center to put runners at first and second.
Mahomes struck out Greg Colbrunn, but Finley was back. He doubled
to left center to score Bell and Williams, increasing Arizona's
lead to 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   In four and a third innings, Rogers allowed four runs on five
hits, with two walks and six strikeouts. It was the briefest _ and
most damaging _ start by a Mets pitcher since they began their
climb six days ago out of the hole their collapse had created.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night was the first reminder the Mets had that while
that climb had been dramatic and thrilling, it could not always
remain free of treachery.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson stole three bases on Wednesday night, a
single-game record for a division series, and he now has five
steals in this series. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
