<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL TEAMS ARE A KICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The offense is inconsistent and the defense can't
stop big plays, but in this season of turmoil, UCLA's special teams
have been, well, special. If the defense covered receivers like the
kickoff unit covers returners, the Bruins would be in first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kickoffs are fun to watch,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
``We're splattering people right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, UCLA's opponents averaged 26.6 yards per
kickoff return. This year, 19. Although the Bruins have better
athletes than they did in 1996, Nate Fikse's booming kickoffs are
the primary reason for their success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Sailer was a great kicker, but he didn't get quite the
hang time that Fikse does,'' said assistant Marc Dove, who coaches
the kickoff unit. ``That's allowed us to cover the field better.
But we'll face some talented return teams in the coming weeks, so
we have a big challenge ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's opponent, Oregon, is third in the league in kickoff
returns (23.7), and Cal, which visits the Rose Bowl in 10 days, is
second (23.9).
</P>
<P>
   Add special: Walk-on freshman Chris Griffith has made 8 of 9
field goals, with a long of 46 yards, and ranks second in the
Pacific-10 in field goals per game (1.6).
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins lead the Pac-10 in kickoff returns with a 24-yard
average, courtesy of Lovell Houston's 95-yard return against
Stanford
</P>
<P>
   The weakest special teams unit is punt return. UCLA averages 6.4
yards per return (ninth in the league), and Ryan Roques's longest
return is 16 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Foster update: UCLA tailback DeShaun Foster has been downgraded
from questionable to doubtful because of a sprained right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look good, but we'll wait until game time,'' Toledo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting update: UCLA landed its 10th recruit Tuesday when
receiver Craig Bragg, of Bellarmine Prep in San Jose, gave the
Bruins an oral commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Bragg, 6-foot and 185 pounds, is expected to inject much-needed
speed into UCLA's receiving corps. He selected the Bruins over
Oregon and Michigan State, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have 18 scholarships available and hope to sign at
least two receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling good: One of the biggest surprises in the Pac-10 this
season is the play of Oregon quarterback A.J. Feeley, who spent two
seasons on the bench watching Akili Smith run the Ducks'
high-powered offense.
</P>
<P>
   Feeley leads the league in passing (278 yards per game) and is
fourth in passing efficiency. He has completed 61 percent of his
passes, with 11 touchdowns and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, UCLA's pass defense is eighth in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lacked game experience, but he's always had a strong arm,
and he's becoming a great leader,'' Ducks coach Mike Bellotti said.
``He's probably exceeded my expectations. With our top-two running
backs down, more of the burden falls on his shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting tailback Reuben Droughns (separated ribs) and
second-stringer Herman Ho-Ching (sprained foot) are doubtful for
Saturday's game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
