<SLUG> BC-WILSON-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T TAKE BETS ON PROHIBITION OF ONLINE GAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(UNDATED) - Sometime not too many years from now, you or I will be
able to roll out of bed, power up our computer and legally play a
few hands of blackjack on a Web site before heading to work.
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the lunch break, we might get on a computer to wager on a
horse race or two. When we come home, we may call up a sports
betting site and place some money on that night's baseball games.
In the evening, we could play video poker in a cybercasino while
relaxing in an easy chair.
</P>
<P>
   Tom W. Bell, a law professor at Chapman University in Orange,
Calif., expects that the law will allow us to do all those things
within the next decade. Writing in the current issue of Reason
magazine, he argues that demand for online gambling will soon
overcome the opposition now lined up against it.
</P>
<P>
   I hope he's wrong, but I fear he's right.
</P>
<P>
   Bell makes a strong case why efforts to stop online gambling
will fail, including those in Congress led by Sen. Jon Kyl, sponsor
of the Internet Gambling Prohibition Act. That measure enjoys
bipartisan support and was approved by a Senate vote of 90-10 last
year. Time ran out before the House could act last session, so the
bill was reintroduced this year, and Kyl is confident it will
become law.
</P>
<P>
   Besides having the support of both political parties, the
measure is backed by interest groups ranging from the Christian
Coalition to Ralph Nader's Public Citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl says his bill is primarily meant to bring the current
prohibitions up to date with evolving technology. But he also
believes that legal wagering on the Internet would have a heavily
negative social impact, producing more gambling addicts and feeding
other social pathologies.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, a libertarian, concedes that some people would be tempted
to gamble too much. But he doesn't think that justifies such a
broad ban on Internet bets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gambling has long been a part of the American ethos,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who first sailed across the ocean to live here took
a big gamble. Declaring our nation's independence was a gamble.
George Washington regularly bet on horses and in card games. Many
of the founders liked to gamble. They embraced gambling as part of
their inalienable right to the pursuit of happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell contends that federal laws and other attempts to stop
online wagering will fail for three reasons:
</P>
<P>
   (1) The Internet's open architecture makes prohibition futile,
and relentless innovation will make it all the harder. Imagine if
the U.S. Postal Service were required to check all correspondence
to stop gambling. That impossible task will be a thousand times
tougher on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   (2) Since the Internet is international, domestic efforts to ban
gambling won't work. Internet sites abroad will offer plenty of
options to Americans. Worldwide, the revenues of online casinos
doubled from 1997 to '98 and are predicted to reach $2.3 billion in
the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
   (3) Consumer demand for online gambling, together with
government demand for millions of dollars in tax revenue, will
create political pressure for legalization.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl disagrees that the Internet's complexity makes enforcement a
hopeless task. Besides, the fact that a law isn't easy to enforce
doesn't mean you don't try to enforce it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also thinks it will be possible to stop gambling on sites
outside this country, noting that many foreign sites today respect
our laws and don't allow U.S. citizens to play. As for the day when
a majority of Americans want Internet gambling made legal, Kyl
doesn't expect to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Bell predicts that public demand will bring legalization in the
next five to 10 years, adding that Americans have ``a natural
desire to take risks and seek fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right about that; the sharp rise in stock market
day-trading shows as much. But the consequences of creating a
culture so thoroughly saturated with gambling would be
far-reaching. Could the values of hard work, personal
responsibility and perseverance hold up against sheer luck? Could
the ethic of earning money survive the seductive ease of online
wagering?
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't take those bets. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Wilson can be reached at (602) 444-8775, or at
steve.wilson &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 02:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9313 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     10-07 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA HURT BY LACK OF EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Early last week, as the evening mist caressed
Spaulding Field, UCLA coach Bob Toledo gathered his seniors for a
post-practice meeting. After a close loss at Stanford, the Bruins
faced a pivotal game at Arizona State _ a Rose Bowl elimination
game _ and Toledo needed leadership.
</P>
<P>
   He waited in the middle of the field as dusk fell and the
seniors shuffled over. He knew exactly what to say: They must lead
by example on the field, they must inspire off it, and, above all,
they must convince the underclassmen that hope remained despite the
Stanford loss.
</P>
<P>
   The players arrived and formed a semi-circle around Toledo. He
was about to begin one of the most important speeches of the season
when, scanning his tiny audience, a strange thought popped into his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this it?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that was it.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to UCLA '99 _ also known as where have all the seniors
gone?
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have 12 healthy seniors, tied with Washington for the
second-lowest total in the Pacific-10 behind Stanford's 11. What
happened to the Bruins at Arizona State _ the late-game mistakes,
the blown fourth-quarter lead, the inability to win on the road _
is typical of a team heavy on underclassmen and light on seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that happened last year, when we won (close games)
because of our experience, is becoming the opposite this year, when
we lose (close games) because of our inexperience,'' senior
fullback Durell Price said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins oozed leadership last year. They had a senior
quarterback, Cade McNown, who would berate, cajole or inspire the
moment he sniffed trouble. They had two senior offensive linemen,
Shawn Stuart and Andy Meyers, who barked like dobermans when
necessary. They had two senior tight ends, Mike Grieb and Ryan
Neufeld, a senior kicker, Chris Sailer, and a senior safety, Larry
Atkins, who specialized in quiet inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo couldn't have asked for more. The seniors did not lose
their cool in close games _ in fact, they thrived on pressure _ and
they did not hesitate to speak their minds in the locker room, on
the sideline or in the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the case this year. Six seniors were involved in
the handicapped parking scandal and suspended for two games.
All-American receiver Danny Farmer missed two games because of an
ankle injury. Defensive end Travor Turner is out for the season
with a knee injury. Vocal cornerback Jason Bell hasn't played in
weeks _ and may redshirt _ because of a bad heel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmer's been hurt, so how's he going to lead?'' Toledo said.
``Look at the guys who have been injured, suspended or aren't
playing, and it's hard to be a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the five remaining seniors, three are reserves, one's a
former walk-on (safety Joey Strycula) and one's a junior college
transfer (tight end Randy Hakes). Only defensive tackle Pete
Holland has the health, personality, credibility and experience to
lead like a member of the class of '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team dominated by guys who are young,'' Holland
said. ``We've got some seniors playing, but they aren't as much of
a presence (as last year).
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's remembering your assignments better or being
poised in crunch time, you can definitely tell a senior team. It
takes being in big games, and (the ASU loss) showed we have more
guys who need that experience than have it.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior shortage began 4{ years ago, with former coach Terry
Donahue's final recruiting class. It had talent at the top (McNown,
Sailer, Kris Farris) but lacked quality depth and staying power. Of
the 17 signees, only six remain. (Farmer and Strycula were
walk-ons.)
</P>
<P>
   Three players left the program _ Jason Bendinelli, Matt
Pentecost and Langston Woodberry. Three more retired because of
injuries _ Ramogi Huma, Mike Wiley and Turner. Four exhausted their
eligibility last season _ McNown, Sailer, Craig Walendy and Cheyane
Caldwell.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue resigned 10 months later and Toledo was hired Jan. 4,
1996 _ with just 3{ weeks left in the recruiting season. His
hastily compiled class featured 18 signees, of which only 11
remain.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo was a junior college transfer who
departed last year. Cornerback Damian Allen quit to run track.
Tight end Aaron Ladd, defensive lineman David Plenty Hawk and
receiver Ahmad Hebert left school for various reasons. Quarterback
Dylan Aquino retired for medical reasons and gifted linebacker
Anselmo Zamano suffered a career-ending knee injury in the third
game of his first season.
</P>
<P>
   The final count says more about UCLA's current struggles than
disabled-parking suspensions or quarterback questions. Of the 35
recruits signed in 1995-96, 17 remain.
</P>
<P>
   Most top-25 programs can absorb one subpar recruiting season,
but few can survive two without feeling a talent and leadership
crunch. For UCLA, the squeeze is on.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a generation gap,'' Holland said. ``At the
start of every season, you look around and see how many seniors
there are, guys that are good players and leaders that you hope
will play every week. We've lost a lot of key guys.''
</P>
<P>
   After Toledo's post-practice meeting last week, the seniors
gathered to plot their course. They discussed the painful ending to
'98 and the turbulent start to '99. They bemoaned the breakdowns at
Stanford and the wasted opportunities at Arizona State. Mostly,
they talked about salvaging their final season, about turning
nothing into something.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about this at the start of the season,'' Toledo
said. ``We knew there would be problems being as young as we are.
It's not an excuse. It's a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many options. The Bruins are loaded with freshmen
at the three most difficult positions in football: quarterback,
offensive line and cornerback. They can't turn rookies into
veterans overnight. They can't will Bell and Turner back to health,
and they can't bring McNown and Atkins back from the NFL. All they
can do is inspire, cajole _ and endure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
