<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA, LSU EMOTION ARE STIRRING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ And now, our latest installment in the backward
behavior that dominates the Southeastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   With Florida playing at Louisiana State this week, a mystery man
faxed the following letter to media outlets in Louisiana on Sunday
afternoon from a Kinko's copy store:
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the nasty, vulgar treatment our team received from
LSU fans during our last visit to Baton Rouge, we have decided that
from now on, we will wear the traditional white jersey on the road
and dark jersey at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely,
</P>
<P>
   Steve Spurrier
</P>
<P>
   Football Coach
</P>
<P>
   No one knows who faxed the letter. When contacted Monday, LSU
sports information director Herb Vincent said LSU coach Gerry
DiNardo confirmed the letter is authentic and is from Florida coach
Spurrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach DiNardo pulled the original letter out of his file and
showed it to me,'' Vincent said. ``It was postmarked Jan. 14, 1999.
So somebody, either at our end or at Florida's end, wanted to stir
things up this week with the fax.''
</P>
<P>
   After Florida's practice Monday night, Spurrier did not shy away
from the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get them real mad,'' Spurrier said. ``We play
better when the other guys are mad at us. I found that out. Alabama
came in here and said all the nice things and we all sat back and
read it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we can get LSU talking nasty about us. That makes us
play a little better, it seems.''
</P>
<P>
   Sportswriter Glenn Guilbeau of The (Baton Rouge) Advocate, one
of the recipients of the fax, posed a question: ``Could DiNardo
have dispatched someone to Kinko's Sunday afternoon?''
</P>
<P>
   The jersey issue is one of DiNardo's favorite topics. Raising it
diverts attention from his growing problems at LSU.
</P>
<P>
   When he came to LSU in 1995, DiNardo successfully lobbied the
NCAA for a rule change so the Tigers could wear their favorite
white jerseys at home if the opponent agreed to wear dark jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   So far the only team to deny LSU's request to wear white at home
was Vanderbilt in 1996. DiNardo responded by unveiling new gold
jerseys for LSU and his team ripped the Commodores 35-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the gold jerseys,'' Spurrier said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Florida wore blue and the white-clad Tigers pulled off
a 28-21 upset victory.
</P>
<P>
   LSU won't be wearing its white jerseys Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Devil in the details: Florida State coach Bobby Bowden signed a
new contract this week. Bowden, who turns 70 on Nov. 8, will see
his deal extended for another five years. His contract, which pays
him approximately $1 million per year, was set to expire after the
2000 season. He will get a raise to the $1.3 million-$1.5 million
neighborhood and his deal will go through the 2004 season, when he
will be 75.
</P>
<P>
   In case you wondered about the priorities in college athletics,
here's a couple of details from Bowden's deal.
</P>
<P>
   If the Seminoles reach the national championship game, he makes
$75,000. If Bowden's team has an 80 percent graduation rate, he
gets $19,000.
</P>
<P>
   Purple paranoia: At practice last week, as his team prepared to
face Washington, Oregon coach Mike Bellotti got one of his security
men to ask an onlooker wearing a purple jacket to remove said
garment.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Because his Ducks were preparing for a game against the hated
Huskies, whose main color is purple.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out the guy was a scout for the Minnesota Vikings,
and, offended, he opted to leave practice rather than set aside his
coat.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bellotti: ``I thought at first it was a Husky fan trying to
make some kind of a statement, and I thought our players and
coaches might be very uneasy with someone in that purple jacket
standing there watching us. When I found out he was a scout, I just
wanted him to take the coat off. I said, `We'll get him another
coat.' But I guess he got upset about it and left.''
</P>
<P>
   Ugly duckling: Michigan and Michigan State will play for the
Paul Bunyan Trophy, which isn't to be confused with the Paul Bunyan
Axe, which goes to the Wisconsin-Minnesota winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Bunyan Trophy is the ugly stepchild of college trophies,
ranking behind the Axe, Floyd of Rosedale and the Old Oaken Bucket
within the Big Ten as far as prestige goes.
</P>
<P>
   That could be because Michigan has won the Bunyan Trophy 22 of
28 times since 1970, or it could be because the trophy is _ well,
we'll let Wolverines coach Lloyd Carr tell it:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ugly trophy,'' Carr said of the contraption that
features a five-foot replica of the legendary lumberjack standing
on the State of Michigan between both a UM and MSU flag. ``I always
tell the players, `This is the ugliest trophy in college football.'
''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
