<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 02:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9315 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1SS     10-07 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1SSTLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A BUMP ON THE ROAD FOR VALENTINE'S BAND
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Mets return to New York on Thursday after an
exhilarating three days on the road that saw them accomplish most
of want they wanted. Despite Wednesday night's 7-1 loss to Arizona,
the Mets got more than they bargained for. They defeated Cincinnati
in a playoff on Monday to gain the National League wild card, then
took Game 1 of their three-of-five-game division series with the
Diamondbacks on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gives us a chance to win another one, go home, and we at least
had a split here,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine had said before
Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets didn't just split, they beat Randy Johnson, the
Diamondbacks' ace and one of baseball's premier pitchers. The Mets
didn't simply beat Johnson, they knocked him around.
</P>
<P>
   As catcher Mike Piazza said diplomatically, ``I'm not going to
say we pounded him, but we hit him pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets also discovered a new star, a new force. Edgardo
Alfonzo, their low-key second baseman, emerged from the shadows to
propel the Mets when they needed a lift: on Monday, a home run in
Cincinnati; on Tuesday, a leadoff home run in the first inning
against Johnson, then a crushing game-winning grand slam in the
ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks clinched the division so long ago that they had
time to sit and watch the Mets' soap opera drama unfold in the last
two weeks. Little did Arizona know that it would soon become part
of the Mets' script.
</P>
<P>
   That script invariably includes a knock at the door. In Game 1
of the division series, the stranger at the door was the
25-year-old Alfonzo. In his first at-bat against the indomitable
Johnson, Alfonzo, down no balls and two strikes, cracked a home run
over the left-center-field wall. The confidence spread immediately.
</P>
<P>
   After that, every Met battled Johnson, refusing to be cowed by
his reputation. The Mets had great at-bats, not all resulting in
hits, but they set Johnson on the defensive early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo's homer signaled an early turning point.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the Mets' bats and timely hitting were not
so loud. Twice, Alfonzo failed to drive in or advance Rickey
Henderson. In the seventh inning, with men on second and third and
two out, Alfonzo grounded to third and the Mets lapsed into their
pre-resurrection habit of leaving runners stranded.
</P>
<P>
   Where do the Mets go from here? Will they be stranded with one
victory in the post season?
</P>
<P>
   The team must be fatigued. Three emotional games at home against
Pittsburgh, a flight to the Midwest, a night game in Cincinnati for
the wild-card playoff, another flight halfway across the country,
and across three time zones, to face the 6-foot-10-inch Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beyond tired,'' Piazza said. ``We're physically tired.
We're not thinking, we're just playing baseball. That was our
attitude in the Pittsburgh series because of the fact that we were
left for dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine said that the Mets' loss had nothing to
do with fatigue. But nonetheless, the team will take Thursday off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a day off tomorrow, and we'll take it,'' he said.
``Our guys can use it.''
</P>
<P>
   The luster of the last few days has faded and the series they
struggled so mightily to get into is tied, 1-1. The Diamondbacks
feel that Game 1 was an aberration, that the series will eventually
move back here for Game 5 with Randy Johnson pitching.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's victory, Piazza talked as if the Mets were
invincible. ``We just feel like we're not thinking about who we're
playing against and who's pitching,'' Piazza said. ``There's not a
hitter you can't pitch to and get out. There's not pitcher who's
unhittable.''
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday night's sobering loss, the Mets, and Piazza,
were less euphoric. Wednesday night, Todd Stottlemyre did what
Johnson couldn't do in Game 1. He wasn't unhittable, but he
repeatedly handcuffed the Mets when it mattered.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Alfonzo filled a great divide. But on Wednesday
night, the team hit a wall. At a point in the season when attitude
is so important, the Mets' frame of mind comes into play more than
ever. It seems like ages ago that the Mets had nearly caught
Atlanta and were leaving Cincinnati behind; the Mets players spoke
of a cushion. Since they survived the free fall, now they speak of
feeling no pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any sense of urgency or do they see anything from this
point on as gravy?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the attitude now that everything is icing on the
cake,'' Piazza said. ``We never thought we'd be here. I don't think
we feel like were going out there pressing. We're having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't seem that they were having fun on Wednesday night. As
the Mets know, only a thin line separates good and bad fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, Alfonzo seemed ambivalent when someone asked if he
minded obscurity in a news-media-driven town where notoriety can
often mean dollars. He said that anonymity is fine at one level
``because I'm able to go out.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I can go out with my wife and not worry.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same breath he expressed hope for a change, and that some
celebrity would come his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometime, it's going to happen and, hopefully, that will be
pretty soon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Change doesn't just happen. You have to force change, and force
transformation. What better way to do it than to homer three times
in two games in October on a New York baseball team?
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo's transformation began this week. The Mets'
transformation is still under review. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
