<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-CLINTON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BLASTS SENATE OVER COURT DELAYS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ Decrying the Senate's record on judicial
confirmations as ``disgraceful,'' President Clinton called
Wednesday for a prompt vote on the nomination of a San Francisco
attorney and a Los Angeles judge whose appointments to federal
posts have been languishing for years.
<P>
   The appeal came one day after the Senate rejected Clinton's
nomination of Ronnie White, the first black justice on the Missouri
Supreme Court, to serve on the federal District Court. It was the
Senate's first rejection of a federal judicial nomination since the
1987 defeat of conservative jurist Robert Bork, who was nominated
to the Supreme Court by President Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the vote ``a disgraceful act of partisan
politics'' in a sharply delivered Rose Garden statement that echoed
the complaints of many Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican-controlled Senate is adding credence to the
perceptions that they treat minority and women judicial nominees
unfairly and unequally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are 42 judicial nominees awaiting confirmation by the
Senate, including six chosen for the Ninth Circuit U.S. Court of
Appeals in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton singled out Marsha Berzon, a San Francisco attorney, and
Richard Paez, a U.S. District Court judge in Los Angeles, in his
Rose Garden statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are both excellent candidates for the Ninth Circuit and
have been waiting for some time to receive a vote from the
Senate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paez was originally nominated in January 1997. Berzon was
nominated in January 1998. Another Ninth Circuit court nominee,
Raymond Fisher, was confirmed by the Senate on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., did not respond to
Clinton's call for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The vacancies on the Ninth Circuit _ which has jurisdiction over
nine Western states, including California _ have contributed to a
long backlog of cases. The court receives about 9,000 cases a year.
Though it is alloted 28 judges, it has been between five and 10
judges short for the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a huge hole in that court,'' charged Sen. Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Court spokesman Mark Mendenhall suggested that the Ninth
Circuit's reputation for being too liberal _ and too large _ may be
part of what ``stands in the way of the fast approval of judges in
our court.'' A few years ago, Republicans in the Northeast tried
unsuccessfully to break the Ninth Circuit into two jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer had another explanation, suggesting that the race and
gender of the nominees is a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a bad feeling about this Senate about the way they are
treating women (and) minorities,'' Boxer said. Of the jurists she
has recommended to the court, white males have had a far easier
time being confirmed than either women or minorities, Boxer said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans denied that race or gender has played any part in
their actions. Several insisted they did not even know White's race
when they voted Tuesday. Lott noted that nine of the last 21 judges
confirmed have been minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their record and the kind of judge that the men and women
would make is the only thing that has been a factor,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   The vacancies have forced the Ninth Circuit to rely on retired
jurists or visiting judges from other areas. Still, the average
time for disposition of the cases is about two months longer than
the national average.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by Citizens for an Independent Court, a
nonpartisan judicial watchdog group, found that the Senate takes
163 more days, on average, to act on judicial nominations than it
did 20 years ago. It also found that Clinton has taken 75 more
days, on average, to nominate candidates than President Jimmy
Carter took 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The study also confirmed the allegation by Boxer and other
Democrats that the number of days between nomination and final
action for women candidates is greater than for men. Data were not
available to make the same comparisons based on race, the group
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
