<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 03:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9319 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-HEARST-PARDON-SFCHRON     10-07 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-PARDON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTY HEARST STILL FACES LEGAL TROUBLES, DECADES AFTER
HER  TERRORIST DAYS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MICHAEL TAYLOR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Despite the fact that she now has former
President Carter on her side in a bid for a presidential pardon,
Patty Hearst Shaw still has legal problems from her days as a
radical bank-robbing terrorist that may well cloud her efforts to
clear her name.
</P>
<P>
   The retired prosecutor responsible for Hearst's San Francisco
bank robbery conviction is firmly convinced of her guilt, and she
must also contend with her involvement in a Sacramento bank holdup
that left a customer dead. She may also be called to testify in the
trial of her onetime radical chum, Kathleen Soliah, now known as
Sara Jane Olson.
</P>
<P>
   The White House declined comment on the potential pardon, but
Hearst's attorney, George Martinez, said his client ``is obviously
very moved by President Carter's support. She's been a model
citizen, and she deserves a pardon.''
</P>
<P>
   Several key figures in the saga said enough time has gone by to
allow her to be pardoned, including Olson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very sympathetic to Patty Hearst and wish her only the
best,'' Olson said through her San Francisco attorney, Stuart
Hanlon. ``I hope the pardon goes through.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson was an associate of Hearst 25 years ago, during the days
when the radical group called the Symbionese Liberation Army had
kidnapped newspaper heiress Hearst from her Berkeley apartment in
February 1974. Over a period of a few months, the SLA converted her
to their cause, and she helped them rob banks and was a fugitive
for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst was captured in September 1975, convicted of bank robbery
in March 1976 and sent to federal prison. In February 1979,
President Carter commuted her sentence to time served, and she was
freed.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has married her former bodyguard, produced two
children, written a couple of books and appeared in a few movies.
She lives in a wealthy Connecticut suburb of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Olson, once a hanger-on to the SLA and, for the past 23 years, a
fugitive on bomb-related charges, was captured on June 16 in St.
Paul, Minn., where she was living an upscale life _ similar to
Hearst's _ as a doctor's wife, acting in local plays and cooking
gourmet meals.
</P>
<P>
   Olson, now free on bail, is scheduled to go on trial in Los
Angeles in January on explosives and murder conspiracy charges. The
Los Angeles County district attorney has asked a Connecticut judge
to compel Hearst to be a witness in the Olson case, and her
attorney says ``it's no secret that she doesn't want to give
testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst is also implicated in the April 21, 1975, robbery of a
Crocker Bank branch in the Sacramento suburb of Carmichael. Hearst
admitted in her book that she had been driving the getaway car.
During the robbery, Myrna Lee Opsahl, 42, the wife of a Sacramento
surgeon, was shot to death. Hearst says SLA member Emily Harris
pulled the trigger, but Sacramento County authorities say they
still want to talk to Hearst about the robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Olson's brother, Steven, was the only person charged in the
case. He was acquitted in a 1976 federal court trial.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the dead woman's husband, Dr. Trygve Opsahl, revealed
that more than 20 years ago, the Hearst family, along with the
bank, quietly paid a substantial amount of money to settle a
lawsuit the Opsahl family had filed against the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she claims she wasn't directly involved in the Carmichael
(robbery), why would her family pay to help settle a lawsuit?''
Opsahl said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst first applied to the Department of Justice for a
presidential pardon in August 1988, according to Martinez. A
spokeswoman for the Justice Department would not comment on the
specifics of Hearst's application, but said, in general, pardon
requests are reviewed by government investigators and attorneys who
go out and interview all the principals in the criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Hearst, that would mean talking to, among others,
James L. Browning. Browning was the chief federal prosecutor who
secured a conviction against Hearst in March 1976 for robbing a
branch of the Hibernia Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Browning, who has always been convinced that
Hearst was guilty, said, ``Her defense was physical duress, but it
never squared with the facts. When she was in that bank, she acted
with verve and great purpose, and she avoided apprehension for a
year and a half, when she had plenty of opportunities to walk away
and come home. The fact is she had joined them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's attorney, Martinez, said, however, referring to
Hearst's claim that she was brainwashed and tortured by the SLA,
that ``people don't understand what happens if you are put in a
closet for two months and raped and beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson's attorney, Hanlon, said that while ``Patty Hearst
deserves a pardon,'' the possibility ``raises some issues of
inequities in justice, issues of class and money. She could be the
first armed robber in the history of the United States to get a
pardon. I certainly feel bad for Patty Hearst, and she deserves
this, but so many others deserve this, and they don't have money.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest flurry over a possible presidential pardon for Hearst
came this week when Carter, who commuted her prison sentence 20
years ago, again called for a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   Carter had earlier broached the idea on CNN's ``Larry King
Live'' TV show in mid-September, when he and King were discussing
President Clinton's clemency deal allowing 11 militant Puerto Rican
nationalists to be freed from federal prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Carter told King that he thought President Clinton has ``been
very rare in the granting of pardons,'' referring to Clinton's
clemency for the Puerto Ricans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The particular pardon that I have been pursuing for the last
six or seven, or even more, years is Patty Hearst,'' Carter said.
``She has led a model life. ... She's been a perfect American
citizen. I commuted her sentence (in 1979), so she could get out of
jail, but I would like to see her get a pardon.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst is the daughter of Randolph A. Hearst who, at the time
she was kidnapped, was publisher of the San Francisco Examiner, a
paper still owned by the New York-based Hearst Corp., which
recently announced its intention to buy The Chronicle for a
reported $660 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
