<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LET THEM EAT CAKE _ BUT NOT THE FROSTING  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Remember Robocop? Forget him, he's a wimp.
</P>
<P>
   Make way for Logocop.
</P>
<P>
   If Logocop catches you eating the Bank of America's new logo,
you're going to wind up with more than indigestion, my friend.
</P>
<P>
   The furor started back in Charlotte, N.C., the headquarters of
the BofA. There was an employee get-together, the purpose being to
hammer them for donations to United Way.
</P>
<P>
   Cake was served. The frosting was decorated with the new BofA
logo. Folks ate the cake.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong! The bank's Brand Council, the department I refer to as
Logocop, fired off a stern memo warning employees that ``the logo
cannot be eaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Observer columnist Doug Robarchek said he wasn't sure
what the Bank would do to the ``logovores,'' but suggested Other
Things You Can't Do With the BofA Logo: Tattoo it on chickens ...
Think about it naked ... Fraudulently misrepresent it as a sandwich
spread, building product or cure for the hives.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, out here in the BofA hinterlands, no cake-scarfing
scandal. But S.F. employees have received copies of the ``Branding
Manual,'' about 60 pages on how to respectfully and properly deal
with The Logo.
</P>
<P>
   You know, like the proper etiquette during mass nude bonfire
BofA logo-worship ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   DOES DA MAYOR have an official campaign song?
</P>
<P>
   If not, he might want to have a listen to ``Poor Willie Brown,''
written in 1919 by C.R. Morse. It was performed in the old days by
the Cal Glee Club, and was recently unearthed by
archaeologist/cartoonist Phil Frank.
</P>
<P>
   First verse: ``There was a boy named Willie Brown who always was
in error/He cussed and swore with all his might, he was a holy
terror.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be exactly the traditional type of campaign song,
but it would show Willie's whimsical, self-deprecating side.
</P>
<P>
   BUSTED by the grammar posse: Yes, I made a mistake in a recent
column.
</P>
<P>
   ``Criteria,'' it turns out, is no longer a singular noun. I
never got the memo. Must have been the decade my fax machine was
out of paper.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, I shoulda knowd better, especially since I once drove
a Ford Criterion, which required plural mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   MARTHA STEWART would be proud. Now we've got geographically
correct food for NFL watching:
</P>
<P>
   At Knuckles sports bar in Palo Alto, owner Laurie Paulson is
thinking of serving Wisconsin bratwurst for the 49ers-Packers game.
</P>
<P>
   Then, who knows? Maybe Philly cheesesteak, Baltimore crab cakes,
Carolina cornpone?
</P>
<P>
   Claude Beaver heard of the plan and wonders what to serve for
the Washington Redskins game. Barrelled Pork? Curried Crow?
</P>
<P>
   For sure, after-dinner cigars.
</P>
<P>
   What about next time the 49ers play the Raiders? I'd go with
tailpipe-smoked ribs and Jack Daniel's Popsicles.
</P>
<P>
   YOU KNOW you're in Berkeley when you see (as Darleen Dhillon
did) a Ford Wrangler with the following sign painted neatly on the
door: ``INCAHOOTS _ Importer of fine owls from Peru.''
</P>
<P>
   NOT SURE if this is good news or bad, but in the Compass Rose at
the St. Francis, the 1906 signature dish Celery Victor is back on
the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Some things from '06 we just don't want to see again, so here's
hoping the new Celery Victor is not an earthshaking dish.
</P>
<P>
   FLEET WEEK is here, with all the noise (Blue Angels, thousands
of sailors invading North Beach) and pageantry. But there will be
quieter moments.
</P>
<P>
   The submarine San Francisco will be docked at Alameda, and
Sunday at 10 a.m., the crew will head to San Francisco and out to
Lands End.
</P>
<P>
   They'll hold a memorial and lay a wreath on the shell-pocked
bridge from the first vessel named San Francisco, a warship that
suffered fatal damage at Guadalcanal in '42.
</P>
<P>
   That original San Francisco produced five Medal of Honor
recipients in the long and bloody fight, and hundreds of heroes,
alive and dead; on Sunday, some new sailors from a new ship will
remember.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
