<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUITING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS GENERATING MUCH INTEREST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The business cards piling up in Mike Fitch's desk at Mayfair
High tell the story of the interest that Mike Williams and several
other Monsoon seniors have generated among college coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be 45 of them,'' Fitch said mentioning USC's Paul
Hackett, Arizona's State's Bruce Snyder, UCLA's Bob Toledo, UNLV's
John Robinson and Washington State's Mike Price among the head
coaches who have stopped by since last spring. ``Some of them have
been head coaches and some have been assistant coaches, but pretty
much everybody has stopped by.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot, 195-pound Williams is the player drawing the most
attention. According to Fitch, Williams has already been offered
scholarships by nearly every Pac-10 school, including USC and UCLA,
as well as Michigan, Notre Dame, Texas A&AMP;M, Nebraska, Tennessee and
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The favorites, at least now, seem to be Arizona State or
Michigan, if he decides to leave Southern California. However, UCLA
and USC are also at the top of his list. Williams has former
Mayfair teammates at Arizona State (fullback Darrell Turner) and
USC (offensive guard Zach Wilson).
</P>
<P>
   Williams has the ability to play several positions in college,
including cornerback, safety and receiver. But, according to Fitch,
there is one position that colleges should want him to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smart ones will recruit him at tailback,'' said Fitch.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who took an unofficial visit to Arizona State this
past Saturday to see the Sun Devils play UCLA, has shown his
offensive versatility this season with touchdowns receiving,
rushing and kick returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``His ability to catch the ball separates him from anyone
else,'' Fitch said.
</P>
<P>
   Another strength for Williams, who may consider studying
medicine, is academics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a kid that will go (to a college) to party and have
fun,'' Fitch said. ``He's a kid who'll get his degree in four
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The other Mayfair players drawing interest from college coaches
include two way-linemen Marcus Johnson and Jesse Bender,
fullback-linebacker Terrence Young and receiver Joe Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who is 6-foot-3 and 291 pounds, has trips planned to
Arizona State, Washington and Kansas. Other trips could come to
Washington State, UNLV or Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are looking at him as a defensive tackle who
can get up the field and go,'' Fitch said. ``He's really into
karate, which makes him very flexible. He also has good feet for a
big man.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender, who is 6-foot-3 and 285 pounds, will probably take a
trip to Arizona State and Washington with Johnson. Other schools
he's considering include Idaho State, UNLV, Utah, Utah State and
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bender and Johnson bench press more than 350 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Young, a 5-foot-11, 230-pounder with a top bench press of 370
pounds, was offered in the spring by UNLV and Idaho State.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, who is 5-foot-11 and 160 pounds, has been approached by
Arizona State, Kansas, Idaho State, Cal State Northridge, Utah and
Utah State.
</P>
<P>
   Fitch and his coaching staff have built a program that college
scouts have become familiar with over the past few years. In
addition to Turner at ASU and Wilson at USC, Mayfair, which won the
CIF Southern Section Division IX title last season, also sent
quarterback Mike Harrison to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   But Fitch has never been busier when it comes to selling his
players. One of the most time-consuming chores is making copies of
game films to send to colleges, which has become a daily
after-practice task for the Mayfair coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Mr. AV (audio-visual) man,'' Fitch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
