<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON, WATCH OUT FOR NFL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston, you've got a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League is coming to your town, and it
wants something like $1.75 billion. Preferably in small, unmarked
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Houston, how does it feel to be shaken down by the greatest
extortionists in sports? Better check to see if the NFL took your
watches; we know they got your wallets.
</P>
<P>
   The short-sighted and simple-minded celebrated in Houston last
night after the NFL awarded them its 32nd franchise, an expansion
team to begin play in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   For the privilege of watching a hapless team fall face-first in
its town eight times a year, a Houston businessman will give the
NFL $700 million in cash, the city will build a $310 million
stadium and, an NFL owner gloated, the city, county and state will
ante up something like $900 million for infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an ownership group comes together with local and state
government to the tune of $1.75 billion to bring the NFL to a
city,'' New Orleans Saints owner Tom Benson said, ``it demonstrates
the many positives of having an NFL team in your city.''
</P>
<P>
   Hah! It demonstrates the great gullibility of football-crazed
Houstonians, who apparently are so flush in cash they don't need
nearly $2 billion of it.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Houston, for saving Los Angeles from this folly.
</P>
<P>
   Not that L.A. was ready to make a mistake of that magnitude.
Michael Ovitz had scraped together a franchise fee of, maybe, $550
million, and there was no public money for a stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL dismissed that bid as sadly inadequate, and jumped on
Bob McNair's offer of $700 mill _ primarily because each of the 31
existing franchises gets $4.8 million more from Houston than it
would from L.A.
</P>
<P>
   For the umpteenth time, Los Angeles proved it is not some
pathetic wannabe-great metropolis that feels naked without an NFL
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Some will criticize Los Angeles city, county and state officials
for not pursuing the expansion team more vigorously. Mayor Richard
Riordan seems to come in for heavy criticism.
</P>
<P>
   That is wrong. The politicians in this case should be commended,
for they perfectly read the sentiment of city and state voters _ no
public money for NFL billionaires.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is not worth $1.75 billion. No sports franchise is.
</P>
<P>
   Politicos also picked up on the apathy of SoCal sports fans for
the NFL. Even NFL commission Paul Tagliabue felt it. He said the
Houston franchise was ``virtually certain to be a guaranteed
success, and that we didn't have that kind of pulse in Los
Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's the NFL that barely has a pulse in increasingly
unconcerned Los Angeles, and instead of dealing with this emergency
the league is going to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL still hasn't diagnosed the cancer in its guts _ no team
in the entertainment capital of the world _ because it is chasing
the fattest franchise fees it can find.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, SoCal sports fans care a little less every day.
Houston got a franchise? Cool for them. Wanna go roller-blading?
</P>
<P>
   What's next? It's up the NFL. It has several teams that want
bigger and better stadiums. If one of them wants to come here (with
no franchise fee), fine. Maybe SoCal will help build a stadium.
Don't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, we might even consider Al Davis and the Raiders. If he'll
play in the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was a red-letter day in L.A. sports history. It had a
chance to make a huge, expensive mistake, but its resolve to be
fiscally responsible never failed.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, meanwhile, mortgaged the farm, the oil wells and the
Astrodome. Hope they really enjoy that team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 0349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
