<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MONTOYA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE MONTOYA DRIVING TO STARDOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG PADILLA  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ The high speeds and fast lifestyle that go
with being a successful CART driver provide enough of a thrill for
rookie sensation Juan Montoya.
</P>
<P>
   Proving he has no sense of theater, the series points leader is
hoping that the season-ending Marlboro 500 at California Speedway
on Oct.31 is reduced to a glorified exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old Colombia native would rather wrap up the series
points title in Australia next weekend than see it all on the line
during the last lap at Fontana.
</P>
<P>
   A neck-and-neck battle to the finish _ and the championship _
with Dario Franchitti would do wonders for open-wheel racing in
general and CART in particular.
</P>
<P>
   But Montoya can do without the high drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no, nobody wants that,'' Montoya said Wednesday between
practice runs at California Speedway. ``I'm sure the public wants
that, but we don't want it. Drivers and teams don't want that. We
prefer to win it in a different way.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Target/Chip Ganassi driver prefers is a signed and
sealed points title, and he laments the fact that it isn't. The
next best scenario is that he rides a championship wave out of
Surfer's Paradise, CART's next-to-last stop on Oct.17.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya is nearing the end of the best rookie season in CART
history. His seven victories are a rookie record. He has won seven
poles and twice this season has won three consecutive races. He has
a 13-point lead in the standings over Franchitti. (A race victory
is worth 20 points.)
</P>
<P>
   He learned of his newfound fame last week, when he was mobbed
everywhere he went on a visit to his home in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the expectations at the beginning of the season were
high, but I don't think anybody would have said or thought that he
would have the success that he has had,'' team managing director
Tom Anderson said. ``I think we thought his learning curve would be
longer. The fact is, you only have to show him something once and
he's got it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing stuff from a young man who seems older than his
years on the track and much younger off it.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Montoya rode a gas-powered scooter around the
garage and pit areas, was showing off a giant portfolio of his
uncle's auto-racing photos, and even took a German luxury car for a
spin on California Speedway's 2-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   Yet put him in his 800-horsepower Reynard 99I Honda, and the kid
becomes as focused as any racing veteran.
</P>
<P>
   While team owner Chip Ganassi had been told of a Montoya's
potential over a year ago, it was team chief engineer Morris Nunn
who eventually gave the approval to sign the driver. Montoya had
competed in Formula 3000 in Europe the previous three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ganassi and Morris went to Barcelona, Spain, just over a
year ago, to watch Montoya on a test track. The team needed to
replace Alex Zanardi, who moved to Formula One this year after
winning the last two CART championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed raw speed, car control and confidence'' said the
61-year-old Nunn, who has worked on Champ cars since 1984. ``I
never heard of him before I went to Barcelona, I had never seen him
or heard of him. We judged it solely on what we saw in Barcelona
and we were very impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Just after signing with Ganassi's team a year ago, Montoya was
at Fontana to watch practice for last year's Marlboro 500. A road
and street racer by nature, Montoya wanted to see what oval racing
was all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first time and I thought it was really quick,''
Montoya said. ``It was something new and it was interesting. I went
to Turn1, on the outside, to watch and (my eyes) were pretty big, I
can tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Montoya long to get used to driving in circles.
His first victory came at the street race in Long Beach earlier
this year. He won the following week at Nazareth, Pa., in just his
third career race on an oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to win on ovals, but now, I like them,''
Montoya said. ``If you feel comfortable and like to drive it, then
you are at an advantage already. That's the most difficult part, to
get comfortable as you drive it. I knew it was going to be tough. I
just wanted to get a bit better and a bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   He even has devised a philosophy for driving in 500-mile races,
and it might be something he could apply to everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to relax yourself and enjoy the ride,'' he said.
``It's a long ride, so enjoy it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
