<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9343 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN-$AD     10-07 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENTISTS WILL TRY TO DUPLICATE EXTINCT SPECIES
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Oct. 10.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many scientists believe that in the coming century, thousands of
species will disappear from the Earth in a wave of mass
extinctions, similar to the death spasm that wiped out dinosaurs
about 65 million years ago. Pollution, destruction of trees, global
warming and other man-made problems will trigger these extinctions,
ecologists say.
</P>
<P>
   The elimination process appears to be well under way, with
hundreds of species already having been certified extinct in the
past hundred years. Indeed, humans may have set off the first
ripple of this long wave of extinctions some 11,000 years ago, give
or take a millennium. That's when people got good at hunting large
animals, including the once-flourishing mastodons, saber-toothed
tigers, giant ground sloths, North American camels and lions.
</P>
<P>
   With the human population now soaring above 6 billion,
ecologists say the loss of forests, wetlands and other habitats
will further reduce the number of large animals, such as giraffes,
pandas and tigers, leaving us with only ``weedy'' species that
procreate under almost any circumstances. In other words, the fauna
of the future will be cockroaches, pigeons and rats.
</P>
<P>
   But ironically, while most humans are inadvertently contributing
to the thinning of the four-legged ranks, a few are looking for
ways to restore species that have been extinct for eons. If they
are successful, humans in the 21st century may witness both mass
extinctions and astonishing revivals, as different species from
different eras meet opposite fates.
</P>
<P>
   One international team of scientists is trying to breathe new
life into the woolly mammoth with the help of ancient DNA and
modern cloning methods. They hope to duplicate a male mammoth,
discovered two years ago by a young reindeer herder in Siberia, by
removing its ice-encapsulated carcass from the Taimyr Peninsula.
The body will be flown more than 200 miles to the city of Khatanga,
where it will be kept frozen in an underground tunnel as
researchers conduct tests.
</P>
<P>
   When alive about 23,000 years ago, the hairy beast stood 11 feet
tall. If the scientists can pull off a biological miracle, a chip
off the old mammoth will reach that height again. They plan to take
DNA from the extinct creature and put it into an Asian elephant's
egg, which will be stripped of its elephant genes. Then when the
elephant gives birth, out will pop a perfect replica of the big
beast that died in the ice field.
</P>
<P>
   Many scientists say the plan won't work because cloning requires
live nuclei. Developers who want to start planning the first real
``Jurassic Park'' for once-extinct animals may want to wait and see
whether the revival is a success. But given the advances science
already has made with cloning sheep, some believe it won't be long
before extinct species can be resurrected.
</P>
<P>
   Given how quickly species may be disappearing in the 21st
century, the ability to raise the dead could come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
