<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9382 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-MILNER08-COX     10-07 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MILNER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book of King's correspondence a good read
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most people's do, I suppose, but Texas writer Larry L. King's
career seems to go in cycles.
</P>
<P>
   In the last letter in King's new book, ``A Life in Letters, or,
Reflections from a Bloodshot Eye'' (TCU Press), the East Texas
native who has lived in Washington, D.C., for a number of years,
chats with his friend, Dr. Stanley Gilbert of Dallas, about his
up-and-down career.
</P>
<P>
   King writes ``Pat Oliphant (the political cartoonist) said to me
at lunch on Friday, `Your career seems to go in cycles. Have you
ever noticed that?' Well, yes, I have and thank Sweet Jesus, it is
on an up-cycle now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oliphant was reacting to the fresh news that (1) The Executive
Committee at Ford's Theater has newly offered me their mid-January
through February slot next year for my play `The Dead President's
Club.' (2) Both Texas Monthly and The Washington Magazine ... want
to buy excerpts from my Letters book coming in October from TCU
Press and (3) that I am writing a `funny' about living in the
Nation's Capital for Crown Publishing of New York ... Some things
can't be explained easily. Why, suddenly, are more people
interested in doing the original 'Whorehouse,' 'The Night Hank
Williams Died' and even the old 1979 play 'The Kingfish'? And why
is New York interested in me again after years of indifference? And
why are more people asking me to speak or read? All this after a
long period when it seemed to me I somehow couldn't get arrested?''
</P>
<P>
   King, as you may or may not recall, was, way back in the 1960s,
a former congressional administrative aide who had given up that
semi-comfortable career to become a writer. For years he was one of
the few full-time magazine writers in the United States who made a
living at it. He used to travel from coast-to-coast interviewing
this and that celebrity or kook or politician, or what have you,
for magazines such as Harpers, Life and Esquire. Along the way, he
published a novel titled ``The One Eyed Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, he was persuaded by a New York playwright to join him in
writing a play based on an article King had written for Esquire
about a famous whorehouse in South Texas called ``The Chicken
Ranch.'' They called it ``The Best Little Whorehouse in Texas.''
The rest, as they say, is history. King and his cohort made
millions on the play which became a big hit on Broadway, then a
movie that wasn't a hit but made some money, and even today is
being produced by high school and college groups to add even more
to King's bank account.
</P>
<P>
   He has since written several books, including my favorite ``The
Whorehouse Papers,'' a memoir about writing and going through the
rigors of getting the play ready for Broadway audiences that reads
like a suspenseful novel.
</P>
<P>
   He has also continued to write magazine pieces, other plays and
a sequel to ``The Best Little Whorehouse in Texas'' that wasn't
exactly a hit, but did open on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Being a compulsive writer, King also during those years typed
out letters to friends around the country, telling us what he'd
been up to and what he thought about just about everything. This
month, the Texas Christian University Press has released a hardback
copy of more than 400 pages of those letters, with comments by the
editor, Richard A. Holland, an Austin scholar who until recently,
was curator of the University of Southwest Texas Southwestern
Writers Collection of manuscripts and photographs.
</P>
<P>
   As indicated above, a number of the letters in this new,
anxiously awaited book are to yours truly, since King and I have
been friends since the middle 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the reason I call your attention to this book.
The reason for that is that it is a book that does a number of
enjoyable and provocative things for and to its readers. It is
funny, extremely informative about the life and times of a Texas
writer and his friends and relatives _ including that famous rabble
of Texas writers and picker poets, the members of Maddog Inc.
(''Doing indefinable services to mankind.''). The group is
chronicled in a recent book titled ``Confessions of a Maddog'' by
Jay Dunston Milner (University of North Texas Press) that is
available at your friendly neighborhood bookstore as well as on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Books of letters are not always the most fun volumes to read,
but trust me folks, this one is. Besides yours truly, King's
correspondence is aimed at former Congressman Morris Udal, a
longtime buddy in our nation's capitol; Frank Rich, New York Times
columnist; the editors of various magazines he wrote for; H. Allen
Smith, the Yankee writer who moved to southwest Texas because he
felt he would love it there but didn't; his agent; and on and on,
the famous, infamous, and just ordinary people, if there be such as
that in King's Rolodex.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement of the letters, from the early '60s to 1999
tells the story of much more than Larry L. King's life. This is a
good one, one you'll be reading snippets and chapters from for a
long time, and reading some of them over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
