<TEXT>
<P>
   A look at festivals throughout the southeast
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Crouch Thrasher
</P>
<P>
   Hiawassee, Ga. _ The Georgia Mountain Fall Festival at the
Georgia Mountain Fairgrounds opens Friday with kiddie rides, music
shows, Fiddlers Convention, Pioneer Village, mountain skills
demonstrations and arts and crafts. Concerts by Dixie Melody Boys,
Brian Free and Joel and LaBreeska Hemphill (Sunday), Jim Ed Brown
and Helen Cornelius (Monday), Bill Anderson and Southwind
(Tuesday), Connie Smith (Oct. 13) and Gene Watson and Gene Wood
(Oct. 14). Through Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   706-896-4191 or www
</P>
<P>
   .georgia-mountain-fair.com.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton, Ga. _ The Prater's Mill Country Fair on Saturday and
Sunday focuses on mountain music, Southern foods, living history
exhibits and hand-crafted arts and crafts. Also craft
demonstrations, canoeing on Coahulla Creek, pony rides, self-guided
tours of the historic buildings and grounds, a clothesline exhibit
of hand-tufted bedspreads and a Civil War encampment and field
hospital. 706-694-6455.
</P>
<P>
   Gulf Shores, Ala. _ The 28th Annual National Shrimp Festival
Thursday through Sunday includes fine arts and crafts, music,
children's art village, sandcastle contest and seafood.
334-968-6904.
</P>
<P>
   Panama City Beach, Fla. _ Indian Summer Seafood Festival on
Friday through Sunday includes country acts and fresh seafood.
</P>
<P>
   1-800-722-3224.
</P>
<P>
   Black Mountain, N.C. _ The Lake Eden Arts Festival at Camp
Rockmont on Friday through Sunday features music, dancing, poetry,
handcrafts, healing arts, children's activities and workshops.
828-686-8742 or www.theLEAF
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   Asheville, N.C. _ Michaelmas: An English Harvest Fair continues
weekends through Oct. 24 at Biltmore Estate, which is reviving the
traditional feast day celebration dating to sixth-century England.
The event includes music and theatrical performances in the Italian
garden, crafts demonstrations and jazz concerts at the Winery.
828-255-1174 or www.biltmore.com.
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga, Tenn. _ The Bluff View Art District's fourth annual
Oktoberfest is Friday through Sunday, featuring German music, polka
dancing, Bavarian food court, Bluff View Biergarten, River Gallery
Outdoor Art Market, Clothesline Art Show, Kinderland, boccie games
and Der Markt Platz Bread and Gift Mart. 423-265-5033, Ext. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Gatlinburg, Tenn. _ The Gatlinburg Craftsmen's Fair through Oct.
24 features the work of 150 craftsmen working in such traditional
art forms as quilting, woodcarving, pottery, broom and dulcimer
making, candle dipping and metal work. 423-436-7479 or
www.craftsmenfair.com.
</P>
<P>
   Pigeon Forge, Tenn. _ The Harvest Celebration at Dollywood
continues through October. The outdoor festivities feature
craftspeople from around the country, fall foods, autumn
decorations and the Southern Gospel Jubilee, the country's largest
Southern gospel event. 423-428-9488.
</P>
<P>
   Norris, Tenn. _ The Tennessee Fall Homecoming is Thursday
through Sunday at the Museum of Appalachia. The homecoming is a
celebration of the culture and heritage of Appalachia with more
than 400 old-time musicians, singers, craftspeople and
demonstrations of rural activities such as molasses making,
sheepherding, sawmilling and apple butter making. 423-494-7680.
</P>
<P>
   Pawleys Island, S.C. _ The fourth annual Pawley's Island Tour of
Homes Saturday will feature 13 beach homes, both historic and
contemporary. 843-237-8454.
</P>
<P>
   Natchitoches, La. _ The 45th annual Natchitoches Pilgrimage of
Historic Homes and Plantations is Friday through Sunday.
1-800-259-1714.
</P>
<P>
   Natchez, Miss. _ The Natchez Fall Pilgrimage through Saturday
features 18 pre-Civil War mansions open for daily tours, displaying
antique furnishings and decorative arts. 1-800-647-6742 or
www.natchezpilgrimage.com.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans _ Audubon Zoo's 15th anniversary Louisiana Swamp
Fest, continuing Saturday and Sunday, includes zydeco music,
Louisiana food and crafts, and Cajun lifestyle presentations
including boat builders, weavers and woodcarvers. 1-800-774-7394 or
www.auduboninstitute.org.
</P>
<P>
   Winston-Salem, N.C. _ ``The Pleasure of Your Company:
Presidential China 1789-1999'' will be at the Gallery of Old Salem
through March 26. In addition to china services used in the White
House, there will be samples from Air Force One and the
presidential yacht. 336-721-7300.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Beach _ The Jewish Museum of Florida presents ``Yeast of
Eden: Ethnic Breads in Florida,'' through Jan. 30. The exhibition
features a ``House of Bread,'' made from loaves of various ethnic
breads, and celebrates the universal role of bread in the
multicultural society of Florida. 305-672-5044.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
