<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9386 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN08-COX     10-07 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The visit of a very special niece of mine
 &HT;    By GARY BORDERS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ My youngest niece came to visit the other
day, accompanied by the rest of her doting brood: my brother, his
wife, and their other two children. My parents made the trip down,
too, along with an aunt visiting from California. Ostensibly, they
were down to visit us, but really, Christina was the main
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Christina is what's called these days a special child. She has
Down syndrome. The doctors say she is testing well on intelligence
measures, and though she has the round face and distinctive eyes of
a Down child, she appears in most ways to be a normal 2
1/2-year-old child, with long blond hair, chubby cheeks and blue
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   I take that back. She's far from normal. Christina is
extraordinarily sweet-natured, a child that smiles constantly,
rarely if ever cries, and is content watching ``Sesame Street'' and
flipping through her picture books. She has turned into quite the
ham since I last saw her around Christmas. She's learned to walk,
says a few words, and loves to give high-fives, to play peek-a-boo,
to dance with the Teletubbies _ and to get into anything that's
within arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   She discovered the cat bowl first off and immediately began
chunking handfuls of dry cat food across the wooden floor while
jabbering excitedly to herself. I moved her away and cleaned up the
food, but it's been a while since I've had to babyproof a house, so
I didn't move the cat bowl. Five minutes later, she was back
hurling the cat food like she was tossing rice at a wedding.
Finally, I wised up and put the bowl outside.
</P>
<P>
   Christina kept us entertained for an afternoon, going from
relative to relative, exchanging high fives and playful punches on
the leg. When her mom exhorted her to ``Be nice,'' she immediately
puckered up to give a kiss to whoever _ or whatever _ was closest.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't say much yet, though she obviously understands a
lot. One of her favorite phrases is ``All right!'' I'd say,
``Christina, are you all right?'' and she'd pipe up immediately,
``I'M ALL RIGHT!'' We would all clap and smile, and she'd clap
back, basking in the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Her young life hasn't always been easy. Like many Down children,
she had serious health problems not long after birth, and spent too
much time in the hospital. Happily, save for an occasional cold,
she seems to be a healthy little girl now.
</P>
<P>
   When I heard my brother's youngest daughter had Down syndrome,
my heart sank. What a burden, I thought, but I didn't say that, of
course. I learned quickly that my brother and his wife didn't view
it that way. Christina was their daughter, and they would love and
raise her as best they could. Thus far, they have done an admirable
job.
</P>
<P>
   When I first saw her, I finally understood how they could handle
this so well. She has been adorable from day one. As a baby, she
enjoyed snuggling up on my chest and promptly going to sleep as I
sat in the recliner.
</P>
<P>
   Her two older siblings, Matthew, 9, and Stephanie, 14, dote on
Christina. You can see her eyes light up whenever they're around,
and now that she's perambulating, she toddles behind them, looking
for whatever mischief she can get into. Stephanie in particular has
matured in a hurry to help out her parents in keeping an eye on the
baby. I worry that she's given up a piece of her own childhood, but
certainly what she's gained in learning about responsibility is
worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Christina begins public school next year at age 3 in order to
give her as much of a head start as possible on learning things
that won't come as easily to her as to others. Since I haven't seen
her in nine months or so, the changes I see are probably more
marked than what her parents see, dealing with her every day. Her
ability to communicate and to understand has increased
dramatically. You say ``No,'' and she shakes her head and at least
temporarily quits trying to pull all the CDs out of the rack,
though really she's just waiting for you to get distracted _ just
like any 2-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the road ahead for Christina is uncertain and will be
more difficult than it might be for a so-called ``normal'' child.
But if the love of her parents and family has anything to do with
success, and I believe it does, then she'll do just fine. She's a
winner already, in my book.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
