<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9389 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN08-COX     10-07 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    That buzzing sound is Ross Perot
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Well, here we go again.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Vice President Al Gore is moving his campaign to
Tennessee in an attempt to get it focused on the very real
challenge from former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, the Bushes
again are having to fool with Pat Buchanan and Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Buchanan proved a persistent and pesky opponent for
President Bush's effort to keep the GOP nomination. Simultaneously,
Bush's minions were trying to talk multibillionaire Perot out of
mounting a third-party campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't work. And Texas Gov. George W. Bush, among others,
blames Perot for Bush's dad losing the White House to Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday in California, George W. was still trying to keep
Buchanan from bolting the Republican Party _ even while saying
Buchanan is wrong in contending Hitler posed no direct military
threat to the United States until Germany declared war in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Perot is playing footsie with Buchanan, as the former
Richard Nixon speechwriter and TV talk-show personality eyes the
Reform Party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   With it would go $13 million in taxpayer campaign funds. But
Bush folks say there's enough distrust of Buchanan within the
Reform Party that he's unlikely to get their nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Bushes obviously hope Buchanan and Perot don't sting
the son as badly as they did the dad. George W. himself reminded
reporters in California of the grief the Buchanan-Perot combo
caused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought the 1992 campaign was hard for my dad to
get traction in the race because of, first, Patrick J. Buchanan,
and then Ross Perot inflicted a series of cuts,'' Bush said.``If
the adage is true _ you die a death of a thousand cuts in politics
_ Ross Perot was a part of the thousand cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes remain suspicious of Perot _ whose personal wealth
dwarfs Bush's campaign swag.
</P>
<P>
   Perot's 1992 run against President Bush was driven partly by his
feeling that years earlier, Vice President Bush had undermined
Perot's campaign to find MIAs in Vietnam _ something the elder Bush
vehemently denied.
</P>
<P>
   But when Perot quit the 1992 race in July, his campaign manager,
Dallas lawyer Tom Luce, went to Washington at Bush's invitation and
spent a night in the White House. Perot got extremely angry.
</P>
<P>
   Perot later re-entered the race _ without Luce. Despite
providing his own campaign speed bump, Perot got 19 percent _ three
times the margin of difference between Democrat Bill Clinton's 43
percent and George Bush's 37 percent. And George W. thinks most of
the votes Perot got otherwise would have gone to Bush's dad.
</P>
<P>
   Perot's grudge passed on to George W. two years later. When he
was trying to unseat incumbent Democratic Gov. Ann Richards, Bush
recalled, ``about one week before the 1994 election, up pops Mr.
Perot, and he endorsed my opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Bush camp in 1999 doesn't seem overly worried about
either Buchanan or Perot in 2000, a third-party effort can be a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck McDonald, a press aide for Richards in both of her
gubernatorial campaigns, said Bush in 1994 was fortunate not to be
bled as badly by a Libertarian gubernatorial candidate as
Republican Clayton Williams Jr. was against Richards in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Richards got less than a majority _ 49.5 percent _ but
beat Williams anyway because Libertarian Jeff Daiell got 3.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' foot-in-mouth statements on a variety of subjects
irked voters enough that some who would have voted Republican chose
the Libertarian as a protest, McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, when Bush challenged Richards, Libertarian
Kerry Ehlers got just six-tenths of a percent _ even while
Libertarians in other statewide races were getting five times as
much.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, even if Bush had lost an additional 3 percent, as
Williams had in 1990, he still would have won; he had gotten 53.5
percent to Richards' 45.9 percent. But if the third-party candidate
had gotten 8 percent _ as Perot did in his much lamer re-run for
president in 1996 _ and it had all come off the GOP candidate,
Richards would have stayed in the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   So Bush says he wants the well-known Buchanan to stay in the
party, where Bush can crush him _ rather than be a fly in the
ointment in Perot's third party.
</P>
<P>
   As for Perot, the Bushes keep hoping he'll sit down and shut up.
But he never does.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
