<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Learn fron Texas' education successes, and shortcomings
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The editorial was in the Honolulu Advertiser this
April. It could have been written in Texas in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii is time zones removed from Texas as the day breaks, and
at least a decade removed in education reform.
</P>
<P>
   The editorial congratulated Hawaii lawmakers for agreeing to
``set up a task force that would create a statewide program of
strong academic standards, accompanied by specific testing of
achievement on those standards and accountability ...''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing these proposals in '99 makes a Texan rub his eyes. They
are, in short, the story of the last 14 years in Texas public
schools. In 1985, the legislature adopted reforms including a
teacher pay raise, lower teacher-student ratios in grade school,
stricter eligibility requirements for extracurricular activities
and a basic competency test for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Most fundamentally, the '85 reforms set up a basic skills test
in reading, writing and math.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to requiring students to pass an exit-level test to
graduate, the system set up basic skills tests throughout schooling
as well as ratings of schools based on scores.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii has an exit-level test but otherwise lacks comprehensive
student assessment tools. It has hired a new education commissioner
to place proposals before lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that Hawaii just now is sticking its toe into the issue
of statewide student assessment, I feel pity and envy in equal
parts.
</P>
<P>
   We can pity Hawaii because we know now that swarms of Texas
students were drifting along with scandalously weak basic skills.
Today, those students would have a brighter spotlight shown on
their deficiencies. That's one good reason why other states are
emulating Texas.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, we can envy Hawaii because it can set up a
system that avoids what Texas does too commonly: flat-line the
sights of students who would soar without the basics drumbeat.
</P>
<P>
   The key asset, and key curse, of the Texas Assessment of
Academic Skills is spelled out in the '85 legislation:
``criterion-referenced.'' That means testing everyone on certain
things everyone should know, to which everyone has been exposed.
</P>
<P>
   A criterion-based test is distinct from a ``norm-referenced''
test like the Iowa Test of Basic Skills or the SAT, which challenge
every student, no matter how skilled.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that when ``what everyone should know'' becomes
the fulcrum of education, those who already know are left to doze
beside the see-saw.
</P>
<P>
   Please, Hawaii, for your own good, do this. (You should listen,
too, Texas.) Devise a criterion-based test _ an entry-level test
for each grade. Use it to test every student to find those below
grade level. For students at grade level or beyond, exempt them
from the criterion-based test for the rest of the year. Test them
instead with something that challenges, stretches and really
assesses every child, like ITBS.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has gotten high marks nationwide for bringing up low
achievers. I fear, however, that in doing so, it stunts some high
achievers or makes average achievers resolutely average. TAAS
emphasis should be for students below grade level, no one else. If
that means segregating _ ``tracking'' _ students to focus on the
basics, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Texas got high marks in eighth-grade writing on the
National Asssessment of Education Progress, supposedly an
endorsement of the TAAS writing assessment. I'm guessing that this
made a lot of college English professors blanch. Writing skills
that ring the bell on TAAS are not the same as good writing. In
fact, English professors far and wide will say that they first have
to ``un-teach'' formulas learned to ace the TAAS writing portion.
</P>
<P>
   The ``back to basics'' movement is a two-edged sword. On one
hand it brings some people out of academic squalor. On the other it
is a big step ``back'' from the real essence of education, which is
to bring out the best in every child. All the best, Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
