<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Friday, October 8, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   EMURRAY-COLUMN _ Ever have the feeling that the time you spend
at work is like serving a jail term? This E-mail from a friend may
help you put your office experience in perspective. (Ernest Murray
is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News) MOVED. EMBARGOED for
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ My youngest niece came to
visit the other day, accompanied by the rest of her doting brood.
My parents made the trip down, too, along with an aunt visiting
from California. Ostensibly, they were down to visit us, but
really, Christina was the main attraction. Christina is what's
called these days a special child. She has Down's Syndrome. (Gary
Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.)
MOVED. EMBARGOED for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Well, here we go again. Just as
Vice President Al Gore is moving his campaign to Tennessee in an
attempt to get it focused on the very real challenge from former
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, the Bushes again are having to fool
with Pat Buchanan and Ross Perot. (McNeely, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Texas has gotten high marks
nationwide for bringing up low achievers. I fear, however, that in
so doing so, it stunts some high achievers or makes average
achievers resolutely average. (John Young is opinion page editor of
the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
