<SLUG> BC-R-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THOSE CHINESE AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Chinese Embassy here sent two of its senior
commercial ministers to Capitol Hill last week to impugn the
testimony of a Chinese citizen now resident in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Jianwei Ding worked for a subsidiary of Cofco, the agricultural
giant that also runs the big Chinese Cultural Center in Phoenix. He
came to the House Reform and Oversight Committee with a charge that
his former boss, Ning Yu _ now named Elizabeth Mann _ had a
gift-giving relationship with the man who gives out visas at the
U.S. Embassy in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Our State Department yanked out our visa-giver, but Ding's
internal whistle-blowing did not sit well with his company's
officers. They won a lawsuit against him and seek his deportation
home, where his clues to kickbacks can be squelched.
</P>
<P>
   ``The embassy officials kept insisting that `this bad man is a
small potato,' '' reports James Wilson, chief counsel to Dan
Burton's committee, ``but then pointed out, almost as a threat,
that the company imports 18 million tons of corn and barley from
the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   China has registered not a peep of protest to Congress about
inquiries into corrupt dealings in money and politics by Clinton
friends Charlie Trie, Johnny Chung and John Huang. But curiously,
Ding upsets them greatly, and the People's Republic is spending
bundles on lawyer's fees to get our Immigration officials to reject
asylum. (Over to you, Tony Lewis.)
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of John Huang, who was the Indonesian Riady family's
money man at the Commerce Department and the DNC: President Clinton
had good news for James Riady when he greeted him last month in
Auckland. Reno Justice let Huang off with a fine and probation for
his millions in illegal fund-raising. Now Janet Reno won't let the
committee immunize him to get his testimony about higher-ups,
pretending a ``continuing espionage investigation'' exists.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Charlie Trie, Little Rock's man in Beijing? Over in
the Senate, Fred Thompson's Oversight Committee heard from four FBI
agents assigned to the task force Reno used to block independent
investigation of ``the Asian connection'' with the 1996 Clinton
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI witnesses revealed that the cover-up crew at Reno
Justice knew of the systematic destruction of subpoenaed evidence
by Trie's assistant _ and refused for four months to allow agents
to obtain a search warrant to seize remaining documents.
</P>
<P>
   After a lawful Senate subpoena to Justice for the lead FBI
agent's notebook detailing this obstruction, 27 pages of Roberta
Parker's notebook were destroyed inside Reno Justice. That's a
federal crime. Reno shrugged this scandal over to Marshall Jarrett,
her in-house shoo-fly who can be trusted never to find the perp in
their midst.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents have testified how Justice deliberately impeded lines
of inquiry into the White House. Senator Thompson, now deposing
Justice witnesses, says: ``Theirs was a hapless, incompetent,
possibly corrupt investigation into Asian fund-raising. We're going
into this now more deeply than Justice is.''
</P>
<P>
   China's contributions to Clinton went hand in hand with its
espionage. Looking into that end is a new Senate task force headed
by Arlen Specter, former Intelligence Committee chairman. He's
interested in the technical transfers of ballistic-missile data by
Loral and Hughes, companies headed by two big Clinton fund-raisers
and trade influencers.
</P>
<P>
   Today Senate Judiciary will vote to arm Specter's newly
recruited team of serious investigators with subpoenas on Justice
officials to find out what went into Reno's cozy plea bargains with
Trie, Huang and Chung _ and why no espionage counts were included
in the prosecution of Peter Lee.
</P>
<P>
   In closed hearings next week, Specter's group will examine the
inspectors general of the CIA and the Department of Energy, and
customs officials critical of the dangerous sale of secrets.
``Nobody's peeled back the covers,'' says the former Pennsylvania
prosecutor. ``I'm determined to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he will. Maybe Thompson and Burton will flip over rocks as
well. If Justice's stone wall cracks, Americans might yet discover
the connection between unpunished Chinese illegal contributions and
unpublished stories of Chinese espionage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-06-99 2045EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9424 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-MEXICO-FUNDRAISING-$A     10-07 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FUNDRAISING-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BIG REFORMS DON'T STOP OUTCRY OVER DUBIOUS POLITICAL CAMPAIGN
DONATIONS, SPENDING IN MEXICO
 &HT;    EDs: Carlos Cabal Peniche may be spelled incorrectly in the
accompanying photo cutline. It is correct in the story.
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Oct. 9 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ It makes Bill Clinton's fund-raising scandals look
tame.
</P>
<P>
   Before Mexico's 1994 presidential election, Mexican banker
Carlos Cabal Peniche claims, he funneled $25 million into the
campaign coffers of this country's ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Cabal Peniche's bank, the Union Bank, later went belly up along
with other Mexican financial institutions. Mexicans have since been
saddled with an $80 billion taxpayer bail out of banks --
including, perhaps, that $25 million ``donation'' to the PRI,
outraged opposition parties here say.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's July 2000 presidential election will test whether 1996
reforms that shifted about 90 percent of campaign financing to
public funding will help prevent future scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Already, however, complaints about dirty donations and illicit
spending are fast and furious.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, one of the most persistent gripers has been Humberto
Roque Villanueva, a PRI insider. Roque is trailing dead last in the
polls in a four-man race to win the PRI's first-ever presidential
nomination in a Nov. 7 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's 1996 campaign reforms failed to take into account
primaries. So the PRI _ not the independent Federal Elections
Institute, or IFE _ is monitoring its own primary spending cap of
about $4.8 million in cash and $1.4 million in in-kind
contributions per candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Roque, once a PRI party president, says his party is not minding
the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are donations out of control, spending that's out of
control, excessive publicity . . . direct payments to people who
organize events, direct payments for attending rallies and payments
for transportation to rallies,'' Roque fumed in an interview this
week with Cox Newspapers. ``I'm waiting to see whether all of this
is included in (his rivals') accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Without honest audits, Roque said, the PRI risks losing even
more credibility. The party set no caps on donations in its
upcoming primary, and could later it find itself embarrassed once
again if its candidates take dubious donations from people like
Cabal Peniche. The former bank president has been a fugitive for
four years. Mexico is now attempting to extradite him from
Australia on charges of embezzling $700 million from his bank.
</P>
<P>
   Roque accuses Francisco Labastida and Roberto Madrazo, the two
leading PRI presidential candidates, of violating the party's rules
most egregiously.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's campaign recently informed the party that it has
spent well more than half the $4.8 million cap because of advance
payments to media for commercial ad time. But Roque says that the
blitz of costly prime-time television spots that Labastida and
Madrazo have both mounted has surely surpassed the limit with a
month to go before the primary election.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's opposition agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think even their grandmothers believe them,'' said
Lino Korrodi, fund-raising director for Friends of Vicente Fox, a
candidate of the opposition National Action Party, or PAN.
</P>
<P>
   Korrodi said a prime-time TV spot of 20 seconds can cost ``no
less'' than $27,000. Arturo Sanchez Gutierrez, who monitors
political parties for the IFE, said a spot can cost nearly double
that. Mexican TV networks declined to reveal their fee structure.
</P>
<P>
   Dolores Padierna of the opposition Democratic Revolution Party _
a fierce critic of Mexico's bank bail-out _ said she concurs with
Roque's claim that PRI candidates are violating their own rules.
But because of Roque's previous high position in the PRI she finds
his outrage disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a victim of his own party's dynamic,'' she said. ``But
it's something that has happened to us (in the opposition) for
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI says it will audit its candidates' expenditures this
month and punish violators by prohibiting them from campaigning for
15 days.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's campaign is under special pressure to show it is
sticking to rules.
</P>
<P>
   A former interior minister under current President Ernesto
Zedillo, he is perceived as a candidate the PRI elite favors.
Labastida has been accused of receiving help from state governors
who organize rallies and events on his behalf using public
resources; a charge he denies.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to show he's not being bankrolled by wealthy
businessmen alone, Labastida's campaign set its own cap on
individual donations at about $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Displaying a sample receipt, Labastida campaign finance director
Eduardo Bours said the system is also designed to prevent the
campaign from unwittingly taking donations from undesirable
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a drug trafficker tries to donate money,'' he said, ``it
won't be more than $1,500.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's opponents scoff at these self-imposed limits. The same
party that has controlled the Mexican presidency for 70 years can't
be trusted to police itself, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just trying to fool Mexicans,'' Korrodi said.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-January, when Mexico's presidential campaign season
officially opens, the rules of campaign finance change
dramatically. Before mid-January, parties are officially forbidden
from using their substantial cash reserves to promote nominees in
the media.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates have skirted the prohibition, however, by setting up
``friends'' groups that raise money, sponsor events and buys ads
for candidates as individuals.
</P>
<P>
   In Vicente Fox's TV ads, for example, he is still portrayed as
an individual candidate rather than the PAN's official nominee,
said Sanchez of the IFE.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1996 reforms, the activities of Mexico's political
parties are supposed to be supported mostly by public money whose
distribution is based mainly on how many votes each party received
in the last election. About 90 percent of the presidential
candidates' campaigns will be paid for by public money.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, about $300 million in federal money will be given to
Mexico's parties for political campaigns. They also receive public
money from states.
</P>
<P>
   The parties are also allowed to raise money by charging members
dues. Under the current rules, individual sympathizers or
businesses cannot donate more than about $64,800 per year to a
party.
</P>
<P>
   Money raised for the PRI's primary candidates or for Friends of
Fox, said Sanchez, can be rolled over after January into the
presidential campaign. But it has to be divided among individuals
whose donations don't exceed the $64,800 limit, which will be
adjusted for inflation next year.
</P>
<P>
   The system, Sanchez conceded, is not designed for complicated
investigations into whether parties are taking massive donations
from a wealthy supporter and dividing it up to mask the size of the
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Equally troubling are difficulties the IFE anticipates when it
has to audit the parties' expenditures next year, Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   The cap for individual parties' presidential campaigns in 2000
is set at about $50 million right now, according to IFE documents,
but that cap will probably increase to account for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   One area to watch to catch overspending, Sanchez said, is the
media.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, only 25 percent of most political campaigns' budgets
went to the media. In 1997, the percentage had jumped to 55
percent. Next year, even more spending is expected to be devoted to
TV and radio ad spots.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanchez said Mexico's law doesn't give him the power to
request records from media outlets to check on whether parties are
violating limits. The IFE is stuck monitoring the airwaves to count
commercials and make estimates.
</P>
<P>
   After the campaign is over next July, the law requires the
parties to turn over records showing donations and expenditures.
But that's not fool-proof either, Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first problem is that I can only review whatever it is
they've been willing to give me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have access to checkbooks,'' he added, ``and they have to
prove every expense they've incurred. But when we're talking about
an election like the one in 2000 _ in which you've got the whole
Congress up for election as well as the presidency _ there are
powerful interests at work.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
