w e BC-IVOR-BRUCE-WILLIS-IN-     10-07 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-BRUCE-WILLIS-IN-THE-STORY-OF-US-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUCE WILLIS' BEST AND WORST OF TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Bruce Willis
with Michelle Pfeiffer in a scene from ``The Story of Us.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    These are bittersweet times for Bruce Willis, one of the most
prolific of Hollywood's $20 million men.
 &HT;    On the one hand, Willis _ who has long balanced big-box-office
action pictures with much-admired-but-less-lucrative dramatic turns
_ managed to combine the two with ``The Sixth Sense,'' which opened
in August and not only impressed critics with his sensitive
performance but also turned into a surprise box-office hit. The
intriguing ghost story with a twist has rung up almost $200 million
at the domestic box office and become the sleeper smash of the
summer and into the fall.
 &HT;    He's also currently onscreen in ``Breakfast of Champions,'' an
art-house adaptation of Kurt Vonnegut's 1973 novel that he
personally financed, co-starring Albert Finney, Nick Nolte and
Barbara Hershey.
 &HT;    Completing this impressive trifecta is ``The Story of Us,''
opening on Oct. 15. In it, Willis returns to his romantic-comedy
persona, rarely seen since his days in the 1980s television hit
``Moonlighting.'' He's cast opposite Michelle Pfeiffer in a tale
about a couple whose once-perfect 15-year marriage is on the rocks
_ a topic that Willis himself understands all too well.
 &HT;    While his professional life has rarely been better, Willis is
currently caught up in personal trauma. After 11 years of an
up-and-down marriage to Demi Moore, whose career for a while looked
as if it might eclipse her husband's in a ``Star Is Born''
scenario, the 44-year-old actor finally split with his 36-year-old,
glamour-queen wife last year.
 &HT;    Willis has been dodging the media ever since. He did virtually
no interviews to promote ``The Sixth Sense,'' plugged ``Breakfast
of Champions'' only at the Toronto Film Festival and wasn't
scheduled to attend the press junket for ``The Story of Us.''
 &HT;    But out of the blue, who should drop into the Beverly Hills
hotel room where director Rob Reiner is holding court but Willis
himself?
 &HT;    ``Don't ask me any questions,'' the bald-domed, trim-looking
star declares. ``I'm just here to learn.''
 &HT;    But, predictably, it isn't long before Willis is off and
running, savoring the upturn in a career which, until the mega-hit
success of ``Armageddon'' (l998) and ``The Sixth Sense,'' seemed to
be faltering.
 &HT;    ``I feel good,'' Willis says cheerfully. ``I just think the
wheel has turned for me a little bit _ I've been through times when
they throw rocks and say my work sucks and my movie could have been
better.
 &HT;    ``I take responsibility for my choices,'' he says with a shrug.
``I've done some films I probably shouldn't have done _ I got
involved when the script wasn't done _ they were mistakes. You
shouldn't turn the camera on until the script is on the page and
it's a readable, fascinating story.''
 &HT;    ``The Sixth Sense'' was definitely on the page, he adds.
 &HT;    ``It was completely done,'' Willis says. ``I read it and said
yes the next day. Same thing with `Story of Us' _ I said, `I gotta
do this.'
 &HT;    ``I'm just really happy that the `Sixth Sense' made what it
did,'' he adds. ``It was phenomenal, coming along at the end of
summer and making a bunch of dough.''
 &HT;    ``The Story of Us'' hit closer to home, however. Willis' and
Pfeiffer's characters decide on a trial separation, just as Willis
and Moore were in real life separating as the film was being made.
 &HT;    While they have not officially divorced, one of Hollywood's
highest-profile marriages appears to be over, after 11 years and
three children _ 11-year-old Rumer, 8-year-old Scout and 5-year-old
Tallulah. Willis has been photographed in Spain with a new
girlfriend, 27-year-old Maria Bravo, a Spanish financial broker,
while Moore has been linked in the media with Oliver Whitcomb, her
daughters' 29-year-old karate instructor.
 &HT;    It would be understandable if, under the circumstances, Willis'
share in ``The Story of Us'' had been bleak and agonizing, but the
film is actually surprisingly upbeat. In fact, he says, he thinks
it's a great date movie.
 &HT;    ``Did you cry at the end?'' he asks. ``I think it appeals to a
broad spectrum. I don't think there's anyone around, married or
not, who hasn't gone through these kind of things. A lot of people
can relate to it _ it's got a lot of humor in it.''
 &HT;    It was his first film with Pfeiffer, who like him has mixed
commercial blockbusters such as ``Batman Returns'' (1992) and
``Wolf'' (1994) with dramatic turns in such more serious fare as
``Love Field'' (1992) and ``The Age of Innocence'' (1993).
 &HT;    ``We were challenging each other,'' he says. ``It's really a
game of professionals at that point. I could do an hour with her _
she's so talented and fields anything. Nothing scares her, nothing
throws her _ she just killed everybody with that. She was so
strong. It was difficult to stand there and be my cool self.''
 &HT;    Director Reiner, whose romantic-comedy hits include ``When Harry
Met Sally'' (1989) and ``The American President'' (1996), was the
ideal choice for his return to comedy, Willis believes.
 &HT;    ``He's my favorite kind of director,'' the actor says, ``a great
storyteller with his own acting history. Actors feel comfortable
knowing he's been in their shoes _ he's not going to ask us to go
anyplace he wouldn't go.
 &HT;    ``There are scenes where I had to be vulnerable, and he helped
me through those.''
 &HT;    To those who know him best as the battered-but-unstoppable
heroes of the ``Die Hard'' films, ``Pulp Fiction'' (1994) and
``Armageddon,'' it's hard to imagine that Willis first achieved
stardom through his deft comic interplay with Cybill Shepherd on
their 1985-1989 television hit, ``Moonlighting.'' But that's
actually why he was so eager to do ``The Story of Us,'' the actor
says.
 &HT;    ``I've been waiting to do a comedy,'' Willis says. ``I haven't
done one since l989. It was so much fun, because you use a
different set of muscles. It's much harder to be funny and to take
funny dialogue and try to make human jokes out of it.
 &HT;    ``It's certainly much more fun than running down the street with
a gun and screaming.''
 &HT;    Actually, he adds, his ``Story of Us'' character _ a laid-back,
impractical writer _ is a lot closer to the real Bruce Willis than
his action-movie persona.
 &HT;    ``Yeah, that's me,'' says Willis, whose next film, ``The Whole
Nine Yards,'' is another comedy, this time about a retired hit man
who falls in love with his next-door neighbor. ``As I get older I
get quieter and more philosophical. I've stopped yelling in real
life.
 &HT;    ``That's the whole thing about being an actor,'' he concludes.
``You get to do it all.''
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Story of Us,'' consult the
official Website at www.thestoryofus.net. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
