<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENIGMATIC-ICON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAGAN WAS NOT THE FIRST ENIGMATIC AMERICAN ICON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DIANA BUTLER BASS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the release of Edmund Morris's controversial
``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan,'' C-SPAN aired a speech by
former first daughter, Maureen Reagan. In it, she recalled riding
horseback with her father through the Camp David woods.
</P>
<P>
   During their conversation, the president mentioned that he had
recently memorized a poem.
</P>
<P>
   She asked, ``Would you like an audience?'' Happy with the
prospect, Reagan recited it for her.
</P>
<P>
   Although Maureen Reagan has criticized the new book, her story
supports Morris's argument -- without an audience, Ronald Reagan
could not exist. Morris spent more than a decade researching this
biography. The more evidence he examined, however, the less he
knew. Like an old movie hero, Reagan kept riding off into the
sunset. To use Morris's own term, he ``dissolved.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Morris, when the young Reagan found his vocation as
an actor the future president began to emerge. Only with an
audience in place -- whether in college, on radio, in Hollywood, or
in politics -- could Reagan stride onto stage as savior of the
American dream.
</P>
<P>
   Morris's Reagan calls to mind another American icon: George
Whitefield. A revivalist preacher, Whitefield was the eighteenth
century's Billy Graham. Spurred by his oratory, colonial churches
were engulfed by spiritual fervor.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of this revival, Whitefield came to represent
emerging national unity. ``It is easy to forget,'' writes Harry
Stout, Yale professor and Whitefield biographer, ``that America's
first ... hero was a preacher, not a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Reagan, George Whitefield ``was his mother's son.'' Each
followed the path of his mother's ambitions. And both fell in love
with the theater. For them, acting hid troubled pasts and provided
them with new identities.
</P>
<P>
   Masters of speech, they commanded vast crowds who, in turn,
breathed life into the actors themselves. On stage, they both
embodied popular democracy while envisioning a mythic, biblical
America.
</P>
<P>
   Whitefield, however, never worked as an actor. He was a
preacher. Observers reported that when he said the word,
``Mesopotamia,'' crowds swooned and cried. David Garrick, the
leading man of English theater, used to watch Whitefield to sharpen
his own stage skills. Hundreds of thousands of colonists --
including the rich and skeptical like Benjamin Franklin -- would
turn out to hear him preach.
</P>
<P>
   He was the biggest show in town. ``Whitefield was not content
simply to talk about the New Birth,'' according to Stout, ``he had
to sell it with all the dramatic artifice of a huckster.'' And sell
he did. Whitefield was America's first celebrity -- a religious
hero who gave the colonists a sense of national identity and paved
the way for the Revolution. When he died in 1770, Americans decked
their homes in blacks and mourned him in public services and
sermons.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Whitefield has proved enigmatic to his biographers.
Everything he wrote, he intended for the public. Even his personal
diary appeared as a newspaper serial. As author, actor, and
director, he scripted his own life. After years studying
Whitefield, Stout concluded, ``I became convinced that Whitefield
lived his life almost exclusively for public performance ... his
public career ... reveal(s) his innermost biography.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitefield left his imprint deep on the American soul. Not
surprisingly, generations of evangelical Christians enshrined him
as their hero. Deeper still, however, is that all of us --
believers and skeptics alike -- still unconsciously gravitate
toward those who embody his legacy. American soulfulness inclines
toward theatrical hucksters who offer salvation -- telling us who
we wish we were while making us cry.
</P>
<P>
   Whether George Whitefield's New Birth or Ronald Reagan's New
Morning in America, Americans are simultaneously attracted and
repelled by the performances of actor-preacher-politicians.
</P>
<P>
   When reading ``Dutch,'' I thought: ``He doesn't get it. Morris
doesn't get it because he isn't really an American'' (Morris was
born and reared in Africa). He misses the nuances of American
religion, small town sports, midwestern reserve and middle-class
nostalgia. He does not get it.
</P>
<P>
   But his distance from American sentimentality enables him to tap
into a disturbing part of the national psyche -- Americans love
being an audience. Especially for an ``essentially decent'' and
not-very-bright actor like Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   And, while we watch, our actors transfigure themselves into
saviors. In American religion and politics, the play's the only
thing.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
