<SLUG> BC-TREK-DINA-MEYER-IN-BATS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINA MEYER GOES `BATS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Dina Meyer
with Leon and Lou Diamond Phillips in a scene from ``Bats.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Ready to go batty?
 &HT;    Dina Meyer is, and just in time for Halloween, too. Last seen
battling killer arachnids as Dizzy in 1997's ``Starship Troopers,''
Meyer co-stars with Lou Diamond Phillips in the sci-fi-tinged
thriller ``Bats,'' which descends upon theaters on Oct. 22.
 &HT;    ``Genetically enhanced bats are tormenting Texas, and it's up to
Lou and me to save the entire world,'' says Meyer, who portrays
intrepid zoologist Sheila Cooper. ``And we've got 48 hours to do
it.''
 &HT;    Meyer loved that basic premise, but what she really liked was
the idea of playing a fully formed female character and working
with Phillips, star of the 1987 hit ``La Bamba.''
 &HT;    ``I was surprised, because when you get a script for any action
movie you think it will be a typical action script,'' the actress
says by telephone from Vancouver, B.C., after a day of shooting
``Secret Agent Man,'' her upcoming UPN series. ``Sheila is a
wonderful character who's strong yet vulnerable, smart but a little
naive, and different from the other characters I've played.
 &HT;    ``After `Starship Troopers' I said, `I'm done with this CGI
stuff. I want to work with actors,''' she adds. ``When I heard Lou
was interested in doing `Bats,' that put the final nail in the
coffin for me. I said, `Wow, how lucky am I?'
 &HT;    ``Lou is a wonderful actor, and we're lucky to have him,'' Meyer
says. ``The only bad thing I can say about Lou is that I don't
think I'll ever meet anyone as nice as he is.''
 &HT;    Making ``Bats,'' however, proved as tough as Phillips was nice.
The cast and crew routinely worked 12-to-14-hour days, alternating
five-day and six-day weeks while shooting on location near Salt
Lake City. The days were hot, the nights were cold and in an
instant rain could pour from the heavens.
 &HT;    Then there were the bats and _ holy guano, Batman! _ the bat
caves.
 &HT;    ``Our bats were mostly puppets,'' Meyer says. ``We had bats on a
string, wind-up bats, wrap-around bats, stick-on bats and some bats
that were put in later with CGI. I even had to attack myself with a
puppet bat.
 &HT;    ``It was insane to do scenes in our bat caves, which were the
equivalent of the bug tunnels in `Starship Troopers,''' she says.
``I was Batgirl. We were up to our necks in this stuff that was
supposed to be bat guano.
 &HT;    ``After a week of people working in it, sloshing through it,
spitting chewing tobacco in it and doing whatever, I had to lay in
it.''
 &HT;    OK. Enough. So how's the film?
 &HT;    ``It looks enormous,'' Meyer says enthusiastically. ``We had a
small budget, about $12 million, but the film looks like it cost
five times more than that.
 &HT;    ``It looks really big _ but then again, what the hell do I
know?'' she says with a laugh. ``Thrillers seem to be very hot
right now, so hopefully we'll ride the wave.''
 &HT;    While ``Bats'' invades darkened movie houses across the country,
Meyer will still be up in Vancouver toiling on ``Secret Agent
Man,'' a superspy-adventure series from ``Men in Black'' maestro
Barry Sonnenfeld that will hit the airwaves in 2000 as a midseason
replacement. Think ``Man from U.N.C.L.E.,'' ``The Avengers,'' ``Get
Smart'' and the Bond films all rolled into one.
 &HT;    ``It's handsome people looking great and saving the world in
style, but we don't take ourselves too seriously,'' says Meyer, who
co-stars with Costas Mandylor and Dondre T. Whitfield. ``We're five
episodes into it, and it's been a friggin' blast.
 &HT;    ``The scripts are getting better and better. We're coming into
our own with our characters and their relationships. And right now
there's nothing on television like it.''
 &HT;    Hmm ... ``Starship Troopers,'' 1995's ``Johnny Mnemonic,''
1996's ``Dragonheart'' and now ``Bats'' and ``Secret Agent Man.''
It sounds as if Meyer is fast becoming Genre Girl.
 &HT;    ``I've never really thought of it that way,'' Meyer says with a
laugh. ``I know I've done a bunch of these sci-fi/special-effects
movies. I've dealt with bugs, bats, dragons and virtual reality.
 &HT;    ``Now on `Secret Agent Man' I'm dealing with all these neat
little gadgets. I don't know if I'm becoming Genre Girl or if it's
just the next wave.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Bats,'' consult the
Destination Films Website at www.destinationfilms.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
