<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9491 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-07 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES DID HIS PART _ NOW IT'S GOVERNMENT'S TURN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Philadelphia and all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As buoyant as he is about Bill Gates's $1 billion gift of
college scholarships to low-income students of color, Bill Gray is
adamant about what the rest of the country has to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see no effort at the federal or state level to expand
financial help to get low-income students into college,'' said
Gray, the former US representative and now president of the United
Negro College Fund. ``The current loan and development programs to
get kids into college are all for the middle class. The expansion
of education opportunity is driven by the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to talk about how this expansion is more money
being spent on the education of suburban kids. But they keep saying
how money won't solve the problem for minorities. For us, they say
it's a value problem, it's your dysfunctional families.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray was the man behind the scenes who got Gates to value the
future of low-income children of color. Gray had gotten to know
Gates through visits to Microsoft. About two years ago, Bill and
Belinda Gates began asking Gray what was the top difficulty for
low-income achievers to go to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that for so many kids, it simply was money,'' Gray
said. ``You have a lot of students who have never had money who are
completely intimidated by what they have to face. Harvard might
give them scholarships and grants, but they still might face $8,000
in loans. That might not be a big deal to an upper-class or
middle-class kid, but that is scary to someone who has never dealt
with that kind of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Many months later, Gates told Gray that he wanted to establish a
scholarship fund and wanted the UNCF to run it. The $1 billion
would be spent over 20 years to allow low-income high school
seniors with a B-plus grade point average to seek degrees at the
colleges of their choice to pursue careers in mathematics, science,
engineering, computer technology, education, and library science.
</P>
<P>
   In creating a 20-year program, it was clear Gates had listened
to something Gray had advised in their earlier talk. Gray said,
``If you want to bring about change, you have to sustain it.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the rest of the country is interested in
change, let alone sustaining it. Gates's money will cover full
scholarships for about 1,000 students a year. As impressive as that
is, it is the first step on a steep mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Nettles, an education professor at the University of
Michigan and research director of the UNCF's Frederick Patterson
Research Institute, estimates that there are between 70,000 and
100,000 students of color who have at least a B-plus grade point
average and come from families that earn $25,000 or less a year.
</P>
<P>
   Nettles's estimate comes from a review of data from the College
Board. These are students who are at particular risk of not going
to college as skyrocketing campus costs eat up a far higher
percentage of the income of low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   For a family at the 20th percentile of income, the average
annual tuition, room and board at a public university now equals a
33 percent of the family's income, according to the US Department
of Education. The costs at a private college now equal 90 percent,
or nearly all of the family's income.
</P>
<P>
   Those costs are up from 27 and 69 percent, respectively, for
public and private colleges in 1986. For families at the 80th
percentile of income, the cost for public and private college
equals 9 and 24 percent of income, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The UNCF is unsure how many B-plus students are not attending
college because of cost, but the Department of Education said that
even after factoring in financial aid programs, lower-income
students in general have higher unmet financial need than higher
income students. The department said that at a certain level of
unmet need, low-income students are more likely than higher income
students to be deterred from attending college. It said that each
increase of $150 in the net price of college decreases the
enrollment of low income students by about 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Bill is doing is taking 1,000 of the best,'' Gray said of
Gates. ``But there are so many more kids in the pool. When I say
how many are in the pool, I usually get a gasp from the audience.
They say, `You mean there's that many?' But right now, there's no
political interest in them. People have bought so much into the
stereotypes of low-income families that they think they're all
sitting around having babies and gang-banging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we have a lot of bad schools. But you don't hear about
how hard black people are trying, graduating from high school at
the highest rates ever (87 percent of African-Americans aged 25 to
29 completed high school in 1997, compared with 59 percent in
1971). The problem is not the kids. The aspiration is there. The
ability is there. What we need are the resources.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
