<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9495 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-07 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR STUFF IS EATING AWAY AT US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After my column on the pleasures of having just enough, I
received a letter from friends. They'd been looking for a simple
family hideaway where they could get away and enjoy life together
when they stumbled upon an amazing piece of property.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a magnificent tract of land,'' Steve says. ``Sitting in
the hot tub, you could see the most dramatic view of Mount
Monadnock on one side and a lovely secluded private pond on the
other. Besides a big, up-to-date main house, there was a garage
with a workroom and a small beach house by the water. Our immediate
response was, `This is not what we'd imagined, but why shouldn't we
shoot high?' We were dazzled.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Steve and Katrina walked away from this seductive
piece of real estate. They decided that not only didn't they want
to duplicate the house they had at home, they didn't want to
improve upon it, either. They wanted something more like, well _ a
shack.
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone who could afford it turn their backs on all
that luxury? These guys must be crazy, right?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   My husband Jack and I have friends with gorgeous second houses
in Vermont who occasionally invite us to dinner. One day I decided
to help our hostess get ready. As I hiked up the road to her house,
I could hear the sound of her vacuum cleaner. By the time I reached
the front door, she was using the Cuisinart. Norma had spent her
day shopping for groceries, and the bags were still partially
unpacked. With a half-hour to go, she still had to empty the
dishwasher, set the table, and finish the avocado dip. When I asked
what I could do to help, she burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   Some ``vacation'' house!
</P>
<P>
   We've all been tricked into thinking that we can buy peace of
mind, but the truth is that eventually you become a slave to all
the expensive things you bought to pamper you. A fancy house
requires a lot _ pictures on the walls, attractive furniture,
color-coordinated accessories, a host of appliances, and a certain
degree of cleanliness. To get those things, you have to plan and
shop and spend money. To maintain them, you have to scour and wash
and polish. When they break down, you need to hire carpenters who
won't show up, plumbers who don't call back, and appliance repair
men who make you stay home all day waiting for them.
</P>
<P>
   I'm in no position to criticize. God knows, I've spent an
obscene portion of my life looking after my possessions, but
there's a reason people don't take vacations at home. Although we
take our slavish guardianship of things for granted, we intuitively
sense there's too much to do at home. It's even harder with a
second house at a distance.
</P>
<P>
   This is the magic of our simple shelter in Vermont: It expects
very little from us. Raw pine walls ask for nothing more than
thumbtacks and a few maps, or pictures the children have drawn with
crayons. An unfinished floor requires nothing more than sweeping. A
meadow, instead of crying out for mowing, spends its energy
becoming the perfect habitat for fireflies. While a decent stove
insists you serve a decent meal, our campfire gives us permission
to say to guests, ``Here's a stick for cooking your chicken hot
dog.'' People appreciate that it's the best we can do.
</P>
<P>
   Possessions are deceitful and manipulative. A hot tub pretends
it will indulge you while giving out orders: ``Wash this scum off.
Fix my leak. Check the pH balance. I'm too hot. Secure the cover.
Don't just sit there: Drain me before the cold weather arrives.''
</P>
<P>
   The demands never stop. Most of us can't resist them.
</P>
<P>
   If I had cabinets, I know I'd line them instead of throwing a
few plastic dishes into a plastic milk carton, as I've done. If we
hadn't made our own beds and sofas by placing mats on homemade
four-legged tables, I know I'd pour my energy into buying nice
furniture and then protecting it. I have high standards, and I
maintain them when I can. It's only when I've given up all hope of
improving anything that I can allow myself to spend afternoons in
the hammock and twilights watching beavers.
</P>
<P>
   Steve and Katrina want a place where family comes first, where
there's very little to do except focus on one another, where you
make do with what you have and what you find and what you can make
with your own hands. They want a place where things don't rule, and
where the true luxury is having time for the things that matter.
</P>
<P>
   This is the dirty little secret of a consumer society: The
things we work so hard to possess end up consuming us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0104 </DOCNO>
