<HEADER>
A9498 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      10-07 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDATION THE SOLUTION TO SAGGING BRICK STAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am getting brick steps fixed and replaced. They are
sagging, sinking, and uneven, and undergoing a general malaise.
They are quite old, but I wonder why they are sagging and sinking
so much. Is the earth under them unstable? Or are they not on a
proper foundation? Would they need to be completely rebuilt, or can
they be shored up?
</P>
<P>
   A.B., Brighton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think it is a matter of unstable earth under them; it
is rare for earth to be unstable, unless it is freshly filled earth
that was not compacted properly. And since it took so long for the
steps to go into their malaise, I think it is because they have no
foundation, a structure that goes at least 3 feet into the ground
to prevent heaving from winter frost. It is the heaving, which is
an irresistible force, that causes the malaise.
</P>
<P>
   It would not do much good to shore up the steps. I think they
should be taken apart and removed, a proper foundation should be
put in (poured concrete or concrete blocks going at least 3 feet
into the ground), and new steps should be installed. You can
certainly use the old brick, but it does not sound as if the old
steps can be removed in one piece and put back on the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   If you do that, it will not move in winter or summer, and will
last indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I took up the carpeting in my foyer, revealing a parquet
floor, but with a lot of nails driven into the wood and not
countersunk. There are black marks around each nail head, which is
flush with the wood. The living room has a similar parquet floor,
but no nails showing. Why are the floors so different, and why did
they let the nails show in the foyer?
</P>
<P>
   ELLEN COUGHLIN, Lynn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Sounds to me like carelessness, ineptitude, or a thought that
a foyer is less formal than anyplace else, so anything went. Who
knows, really, what lurks in the minds of floor layers. Actually,
sometimes parquet floors were face-nailed (with the nail head
showing) on purpose; when the nails corroded, they created those
black spots, and the whole thing was considered decorative.
</P>
<P>
   But hope springs eternal: You can refinish the foyer floors and
no one will notice the difference. Countersink the nails, if indeed
their heads are not too big; the heads must be very small, like a
finish nail or cut nail, in order for them to be countersunk in
hardwood. Fill the holes with a wood filler of the same color as
the wood, then sand and finish.
</P>
<P>
   If the nails have big heads, I have no good answer for you
except to live with the black marks. Since you said the nails are
impossible to pull out without messing up the wood, that is as good
a motive as any to live with the black marks if you can't do
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I enclosed my porch, putting in windows and a ceramic tile
floor over about a 2-foot crawl space. I put insulation under the
floor with the paper vapor barrier down, facing the crawl space. I
realize that the vapor barrier is facing in the wrong direction.
Will that hurt? And what should I do to alleviate it? Someone
suggested I screw 1-inch rigid polyisocyanurate on the bottom of
the joists. Is there anything else I should do?
</P>
<P>
   BILL KELLEY, Georgetown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are several things you should do, but I would not worry
too much about the wrong-way vapor barrier. It has been done many
times, and while it is wrong according to the state-of-the-art
rules, it may be OK for years. The only danger from such a
situation is trapping moisture between the vapor barrier and the
floor above. To keep an eye on that, inspect the insulation
occasionally; if it is not wet, then you have nothing to worry
about. If it is damp or wet, then take it down and reverse it.
</P>
<P>
   And do not put the rigid insulation up; that would seal the
cavity even more, which I don't think is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Three things that you should do are:
</P>
<P>
   1. Staple Tyvek to the bottom of the joists; this stops the
passage of air but allows water vapor to pass through it in both
directions, which you want to happen. Perforate that insulation
backing paper before putting up the Tyvek.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cover the crawl space ground with polyethylene plastic. This
will keep water vapor from coming up through the ground and into
the crawl space.
</P>
<P>
   3. Ventilate the crawl space; open windows, if any (unlikely in
a 2-foot crawl space), but make sure there are vents that you can
open and close. Keep those vents open from April to October; they
can be closed in winter, but will help keep down moisture for the
rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have hot-water heat and plan to replace my boiler. Can I
put in central air at the same time?
</P>
<P>
   TRACY SLUICER, Millis, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You can put in central air any time you please, but there is
no advantage to doing it at the same time as you replace the
boiler, because the boiler and the a/c have nothing to do with each
other. The a/c will require putting in ducts as well as the
compressor and coils, which adds to the cost, so it might be a good
idea to postpone the a/c for a while, and concentrate on paying for
the new boiler before being hit with the a/c bill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
