<HEADER>
A9503 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-COLETTE-BOS &LR;      10-07 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-COLETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW COLETTE SINNED, THEN REDEEMED HERSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
CREATING COLETTE 
From Baroness to Woman of Letters, 1912-1954 
By Claude Francis and Fernande Gontier 
Steerforth Press, 298 pp., illustrated, $27 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is 1913 as the second volume of this exhaustive biography of
Colette, the famed French writer, begins. She has shed her user of
a husband, Henry Gauthier-Villars, who claimed much of her early
work as his own, and has moved on to her second (but not last)
husband, newsman and politician Henry de Jouvenel. With her
marriage have come respectability and the title of baroness.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a woman determined not to go quietly into anyone's
good night. She has spent her first 40 years in a gauzy whirl of
fabulous parties and lovers of both sexes, and is high-stepping
into middle age with nary a sign that time has dulled her voracious
lust for life. Though married, she continues her relationships with
women and men, including renowned actress Musidora and Bertrand de
Jouvenel, her 16-year-old stepson, with whom she had a five-year
affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colette herself . . . renounced nothing,'' write her
biographers Claude Francis and Fernande Gontier, and for the rest
of her inimitable life she would continue to ``soar toward a law
written by herself for herself.''
</P>
<P>
   This concluding volume of ``Creating Colette,'' which spans the
last 41 years of the writer's life, is no less involving than its
predecessor, which began this definitive work. But there is
something decidedly less admirable about its subject. In the first
book, the woman born Sidonie-Gabrielle Colette sashayed into the
reader's consciousness as a sort of Tante Mame, a devil-may-care
firebrand with an expansive view of life and love. But in this
volume, the reader is confronted with Colette's brutalizing
selfishness. She fully enjoyed life, but often at the expense of
those around her _ her mother, her daughter, her lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Especially discomforting is the section dealing with the death
of her mother, Adele Eugenie Sidonie ``Sido'' Landois. Sido had
endured a double mastectomy, and for a year begged her daughter to
come see her. Colette would promise to visit, then never show up.
Her mother's failing health coincided with Colette's burgeoning
affair with the elder de Jouvenel, the editor of Le Matin. Colette
was already angling to marry him, wanting ``the artistocratic title
and the standing it would give her in society.'' Jouvenel was a
blindly ambitious womanizer, yet Colette had no desire to leave him
even to tend to a dying parent.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Colette even believed the gravity of her mother's
condition. In a letter, she called Sido ``insufferable,'' and said
her mother was ailing from nothing more dire than ``a fit of `I
want to see my daughter.' '' Colette, however, sought her mother's
approval of Jouvenel; she would never get it. When Sido died,
Colette did not attend the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   She displays an equal lack of sympathy to the nascent feminist
movement. While women were fighting for economic and political
equality, Colette found their interest in such matters unseemly.
Women involving themselves in politics undermined what she believed
were the feminine virtues of ``incompetence, timidity, silence.''
In this book, Colette is revealed in all her contradictions _ a
woman who demanded her freedom above all else, yet denounced women
who publicly campaigned for social independence. But Francis and
Gontier are not as apt in analyzing such inconsistencies as they
are in detailing Colette's actions and saucy observations.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Colette's self-centeredness threatens to overcome
the book, there comes the true centerpiece of Colette's story. It
is not found in her writings, though the inspirations and
influences of such acclaimed works as ``Gigi,'' ``The Break of
Day,'' and ``The Pure and the Impure'' are thoroughly discussed.
(On the event of her 80th birthday, the New Yorker hails her as
``France's writing genius.'') It comes in her relationship with
Maurice Goudeket, whom she met in 1925 and with whom she would
remain for the rest of his life. In 1941, Goudeket, who was Jewish,
was arrested by the Nazis in Paris. It was Colette, then suffering
from debilitating arthritis, who worked tirelessly to gain his
release. When told Goudeket could be saved from a trip to Auschwitz
if he accepted a job as a detention-camp snitch, Colette said, ``We
both choose death.'' This display of selflessness and integrity,
absent from much of the rest of Colette's life, redeems her, and
restores her to the feisty, even endearing woman of this
biography's first volume.
</P>
<P>
   Colette died in 1954, at 81. She was the first woman writer
honored with a state funeral _ though Goudeket's request for a
religious ceremony as well was denied by the archbishop, who was
dismayed that she never showed ``repentance for her sins.'' So
instead of the cross he wanted on her granite tomb in Paris's Pere
Lachaise cemetery, Goudeket instead summed up the complicated life
of the woman he (and countless others) loved with the simple
inscription: ``Here Lies Colette.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
