<HEADLINE>
ENJOY ADS FOR `DOT COM' UNTIL THE SHAKEOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't turn on the television, listen to the radio or drive
down the highway without being bombarded by advertisements for
``dot com'' companies.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage firms, banks, toy companies, and job-finding services
are spending money at a furious clip. The wave of e-spending has
been wonderful for anyone with ad space to sell, including The
Boston Globe. It has also been fun for viewers, because much of the
e-advertising is very clever.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Is it good for investors who have made bets on
the e-commerce sector? Is all the spending a sign of strength or a
signal that the brutally competitive world of the Internet is
getting even more brutal and unprofitable?
</P>
<P>
   It isn't hard to figure out why we are seeing the explosion of
``dot com'' advertising. ``It used to be that you could build a
brand name over time. Now you have to do it overnight,'' said
Edward Boches, executive creative director at Mullen, an
advertising agency based in Wenham that handles many ``dot com''
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Brand name is everything in the Internet era. ``Dot com'' firms
need to build brand names to create customer loyalty, and they have
to do it fast, before the competition catches up. Advertising is
the obvious solution. The ``dot com'' companies can afford it. Many
have raised tens or even hundreds of millions of dollars from
venture capitalists and initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   MotherNature.com, a Concord, Mass. company that sells natural
products on line, has raised $61 million in venture financing. The
company expects to spend $25 million on promotion this year, much
of it on radio ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``By talking to people through media they know, you convince
them that you are for real,'' Michael Barach, the firm's chief
executive, said in an interview this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens if everyone in the business has the exact same
strategy? The electronic brokerage industry is a perfect example.
According to The New York Times, the top 10 players in the industry
will spend $1.5 billion in advertising over the next year. E-Trade
was the first to the airwaves with a zippy ad campaign, but since
then Charles Schwab, Ameritrade, and others have followed with
campaigns of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The e-brokerage companies say they are spending $400 to $500 to
attract each new customer. The numbers are probably smaller in
other businesses, but the basic trend is the same. ``Customer
acquisition costs are skyrocketing,'' said Nick Moore, a money
manager with Jurika &AMP; Voyles in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Leary, who follows retailing for State Street Research,
looks at the same numbers and worries about profitability. ``You
could spend $100 to get a customer who spends $50 a year,'' she
said. If the customer stays loyal for 10 years, the investment
might make sense, she says. But who can say how loyal customers
will remain in a world with so many choices?
</P>
<P>
   Rising advertising budgets are also driving up the cost of
advertising. A 30-second spot on next year's Super Bowl will cost
$2 million, up 25 percent from a year ago. Demand for the spots is
intense, especially from ``dot com'' companies. Boches says
television and radio stations are getting premium prices for
advertising this Christmas season. The culprit? The same
e-companies.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the ``dot com'' companies are in an arms race. They
keep spending more on advertising because they have to keep up with
the competition. They can't afford to stop, but many probably can't
afford to keep going.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Darwinian business,'' Barach said. ``There are only
going to be a few electronic winners in each category. Everyone
else will die or merge.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it's hard to see how things can play out any other
way. The Internet is a marvelous medium, but it has virtually no
barriers to entry. Categories can get crowded very quickly with
competitors who make the same product or offer the same service.
Clever advertising is one way to distinguish yourself from the
crowd, but when everyone else is running clever ad campaigns, who
is going to remember yours?
</P>
<P>
   ``The shakeout is coming,'' predicted Ned Riley, chief
investment officer at BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, investors should enjoy those witty ``dot com''
commercials. In some cases, that may be the only return on
investment they ever see.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
