<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO FAR, A DISAPPOINTING SEASON FOR ALL-PRO TY LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The gray T-shirt was darkened by a free flow
of sweat running down Ty Law's head, face, and neck. The water
cooler in the back of the locker room was chugging down as Law kept
reaching for more cups of water to replenish his fluids.
</P>
<P>
   After a morning practice walkthrough, the Patriots cornerback
stayed behind and ran 100-yard sprints. After that, he ran up and
down the stadium stairs, reminisicent of ``Rocky.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he headed out to practice in full pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to get into better shape,'' said Law, an astonishing
statement. ``Maybe people think I'm in great shape, but it's not
good enough for me. I've got to keep running until I'm not tired
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   In Law's eyes, the season is a 15-round heavyweight fight.
There's no cheating, no room for rest and relaxation. He doesn't
like the way he's played in the Patriots' 4-0 start. He doesn't
particularly care for the zone defenses the Patriots have been
playing, which have taken him out of his true element: man-on-man
coverage. But he's not mad at anyone but himself, because he feels
he simply hasn't played as well as he should have.
</P>
<P>
   He describes his play as ``average.''
</P>
<P>
   Law, an All-Pro, hates average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played average and I'm not going to stand for being
mediocre,'' said Law. ``In zone coverage I was an average
cornerback. I didn't do anything poor; I didn't do anything great.
I didn't play up to my expectations. The coaches are saying you're
playing well, don't get mad or frustrated. But I've been average
and I'm not going to stand for it. I always wanted to be an
above-average corner and player, and that's what I'm gonna do.''
</P>
<P>
   When you're considered the league's second-best cornerback based
on nine interceptions the previous season, have shut down each
opponent's best receiver, and draw the second-highest paycheck at
your position (seven years, $50 million), what's happened thus far
has to be aggravating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Deion (Sanders) in the offseason and he said,
`Don't get frustrated.' He said nine interceptions are gonna be
hard to come by again. Coach (Pete) Carroll told me the same thing.
It's all about making plays. If I could put a patch on one of the
quarterback's eyes and minimize the opportunities, I've done my
job. If I'm playing average and winning, it's better than getting a
lot of interceptions and losing,'' said Law.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll claims Law is seeing as many balls thrown his way as he
did a year ago. But Law said he hasn't noticed that teams are
trying to beat him, per se.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're trying to throw it at me,'' he said.
``As you can see, we haven't been playing bump and run. They pick
and chose. I take a lot of pride in my man-to-man coverage, but I
have to seize the opportunity when I'm playing zone. If they attack
me, I welcome it because I'm eager to make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the second half of Week 2's 31-28 win over the
Indianapolis Colts, Law has not received the same man-to-man
chances as a year ago. The Patriots' staff has been trying not to
coach so predictably, switching to a zone and forcing the
opposition to change its plan of attack. But it seems the Patriots
are most effective in man-to-man.
</P>
<P>
   Law made that clear when the Patriots were down, 28-7, at the
half to Indianapolis. Marvin Harrison had caught six first-half
passes for 100 yards. In the second half, the Patriots switched to
a man-to-man, and Harrison caught one pass for 5 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were more effective when we switched to the man coverage,''
said Law. ``I was having a hissy fit at halftime because I didn't
like the way things were going. Hopefully I get to do it more
often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always look forward to playing one on one, but I have to
play what the coaches call. I got to do some things last year I
never got a chance to do. I know we can't do the same things all
the time because the other teams watch the film, too. I'm not
saying I'm frustrated by it, but you give up too many easy passes
when you're playing off on zones and stuff. If a guy catches a ball
off me, I'd rather make him earn it and make him play tough for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he knows that people who don't understand the Patriots'
defense are going to think the catches made by Keyshawn Johnson,
Harrison, and Kevin Johnson are his fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing, people are gonna think because of last year
I'm going to match up man to man all the time,'' he said. ``I can
handle it. I know I can play. My teammates know we've had different
responsibilities from last year, when I had someone man to man
80-90 percent of the time. But I have to do a better job doing my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Law said some responsibilities have shifted because Chris Carter
is new to free safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a factor because we have Chris Carter, who is a great
talent and a great physical specimen. Like anybody, it takes time
to learn and play with the guys who have been out there. With
Willie Clay, he had been there and we could do certain things,''
said Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we take a different approach when Lawyer (Milloy) is on
your side and when Chris is on your side. We simplify it a bit with
Chris. Willie was Einstein back there; he was able to do so much.
Chris is coming along well and playing great ball, but pretty soon
we're going to throw the kitchen sink at him and say, `Take
control.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Law said he needs to do more, especially this week against
Kansas City. In a 40-10 Patriots victory last year, he shut down
Andre Rison, holding him to one catch for 5 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is gonna be a great matchup physically and mentally.
Kansas City is 28-6 the last four years at home, they have fan
support, and they have players who can beat you on both sides of
the ball. I played against (wide receiver) Derrick Alexander in
college for two years and I know his capabilities. He can burn you.
He's fast, strong, and quick, and he's probably the most underrated
receiver in the league. Andre Rison knows who he is. He's been
around the league. We're going to have our work cut out,'' said
Law.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody really knows whom Law will match up against most of the
time Sunday. All Law knows is he'll be there for Round 5 when the
bell rings. And this week, he's looking for a knockout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
