<HEADLINE>
HOPING THE NEW ENQUIRER KEEPS ITS ODDBALL APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's the new, revamped National Enquirer hot off the
supermarket newsstand and the change is . . . am I missing
something? This week's new Enquirer appears to be much the same as
last week's old one.
</P>
<P>
   The type on the cover is slightly larger. They've added a
definite article to the name, so now it's The National Enquirer.
That's a big change. Inside the layout looks cleaner, the
photographs brighter. That seems to be about all, change-wise.
</P>
<P>
   A story in Friday's Wall Street Journal reported that the
Enquirer's new owners, Evercore Capital Partners, are ``aiming to
gain respectability and new readers'' by creating a fresh look for
the tabloid and increasing its credibility.
</P>
<P>
   New publisher David Pecker told the WSJ, ``In a year's time, I
want people to think of the National Enquirer as a credible
newspaper and a credible news-gathering force where everything you
read is absolutely true.''
</P>
<P>
   You mean until now everything I've read in the Enquirer hasn't
been absolutely true? Why, I'm shocked.
</P>
<P>
   The new emphasis on credibility must be why the editors chose to
run another JonBenet Ramsey-related story on the cover, this one
headlined ``Mental Disorder Made Mom Kill.'' Says who? Say a couple
of ``mental health experts'' who've never met the woman.
</P>
<P>
   Sensational? Sleazy? Of course. But as an Enquirer devotee I
find the story perversely heartening. The Enquirer may be
undergoing an identity crisis, but it hasn't yet gone completely
mainstream. I hope it never does.
</P>
<P>
   The WSJ story seemed to confuse the Enquirer with its sister
organ, The Weekly World News, because the headline on the story
read, ``Reincarnated Supermarket Tabloid Kills Elvis!'' Any tabloid
addict knows the Enquirer gave up resurrecting Elvis long ago. You
have to read The Weekly World News to keep abreast of the latest
sightings. There are no Elvis-related bulletins in the current
issue, but there is a most compelling story headlined, ``Washington
Think Tanks are Riddled With Space Aliens.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as I've always suspected. But back to the Enquirer. The
space alien story is the sort of piece we won't be reading in the
new Enquirer, but we wouldn't have read it in the old Enquirer
either, not in recent years. The Enquirer has gradually shed much
of its old weirdness. It's becoming a celebrity-driven gossip
magazine. In the transition it's losing some of its peculiar
appeal, and perhaps not coincidentally, its circulation.
</P>
<P>
   According to the WSJ story, the new Enquirer is trying to
compete for readers and advertising with People. So is every other
publication. People and its ilk are fine, if you like that sort of
thing, but the celebrity-lifestyle magazine genre is a crowded
field. I hate to see the Enquirer completely abandon its eccentric
editorial personality to become just another People clone.
</P>
<P>
   When I turn to the Enquirer, I don't want to read yet another
fawning profile of Gwyneth Paltrow or Kevin Spacey or whichever
celebrity is ``hot'' on a given week. I open the Enquirer hoping to
find the odd stories I won't read elsewhere. This week, tucked away
among the celebrity gossip (``Monica's $ Million Diet''), the
celebrity lifestyle pieces (``Inside Rosie's Mansion''), the
uplifting celebrity human interest stories (``Welfare Mom Finds
Fame &AMP; Fortune as Best-Selling Author''), I found a classic
supermarket tabloid story: ``The Tomato Patch Murder: Family Blows
Away Grandpa and Turns Him into Fertilizer.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Enquirer hasn't totally abandoned its strange mission. I
hope it never does.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
