<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-TULIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TULIP TIME: HERE, NOW, DUSTY AND SWEATY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's tulip time in Holland in the spring. And there's tulip
time here and now.
</P>
<P>
   Then and there is famously gorgeous. What I'm up to is dusty and
sweaty, but digging is good exercise and will lead to at least one
season of outstanding display.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way of it with tulips. Put in the work to plant them,
and almost without fail you will get one season of incredible
bloom. That's because when you buy a bulb, the flower is already
formed inside. Unless the bulb rots in soil that's too soggy (don't
plant it there), is ``blasted'' by heat because you don't plant it
upon receipt (get digging), or is devoured by wildlife (get the
shotgun, Maude), you will have a flower.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe you'll have one the following year as well, and maybe
not. Tulips have a reputation as being short-lived perennials,
though it is somewhat exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   The Darwin hybrids are the most reliable repeaters, though
Pieter Messelaar of the Messelaar Bulb Co. in Ipswich, Mass.
cautioned that ``it depends a lot on the garden situation, too. You
don't want an acid soil, for example.''
</P>
<P>
   Does burying tulips extra deep (a few inches, don't go crazy)
work? ``I haven't found that it does,'' Messelaar said. ``Some
people believe that.'' I have believed that, but then my reliable
returners, planted extra deep, have been Kaufmannianas and
Greigeiis, which are more likely than some others to repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's botanical species that are pretty good, too, the
little multiflowering ones,'' Messelaar said, referring to the many
species of small tulips. He likes Tulipa bakeri ``Lilac Wonder,''
which has rosy lilac flowers with yellow bases, and Tulipa
dasystemon, which is whitish with golden centers and naturalizes
just great in sunny, gravelly spots, such as where I grow it amid
cactus and yuccas.
</P>
<P>
   Dirk Visser of Dirk Visser's Holland Bulbs, also in Ipswich,
said cottage tulips and Triumphs will return a few times, which is
good, since I just planted 300 of them.
</P>
<P>
   He likes Darwin hybrids for their repetition but also for their
overall strength. ``They're strong growers, strong stems, they last
a good while, and there are some real nice colors in there,'' said
Visser, who has both a catalog- and Internet-based retail business,
as well as a wholesale operation, supplying parks, college,
landscapers, and other large consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional users often go for the show, dig up the spent
bulbs afterward, and replace them in the fall. Which is fine with
Visser, noting with a laugh, ``otherwise we'd be out of business
pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Messelaar spoke of the Parrots, which have showy, fringed
flowers with striking striations: ``They're very, very beautiful,
they're great cut flowers, but they don't tend to come back at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   His advice is to have a cut-flower garden. Put the ``spent''
tulips in there. If some don't flower again, so what? If some do,
you have a source of tulips for inside.
</P>
<P>
   Visser said it is difficult to project trends in tulips, and he
simply carries hundreds of varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Messelaar, whose bulb company is a family-run retail operation,
selling from a barn in Ipswich, said he had noticed that species
tulips are becoming very popular. Also, ``Apricot Beauty,'' a
Triumph, is still very popular, ``and then there's the one called
`Angelique,' which is a double pink that is very popular.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Angelique'' is a double late tulip, a beautiful delicate pink
with a creamy pink edge. I grew it until the neighboring cherry
tree and clerodendron shaded it out. Its flowers were like small
peonies, and ``Carnaval de Nice,'' which I just planted under a
rose off the back deck, should be similar, except white with
brilliant red flames.
</P>
<P>
   Also part of this year's planting are two species tulips,
``Little Beauty'' (scented, cherry-red with a blue center) and
``Little Princess'' (orange and yellow with a black center). They
went in two spots, mixed, and should return reliably and may well
naturalize.
</P>
<P>
   The big planting was the Triumphs. My wife and I came up with a
blend too delicious to resist, and if they peter out in two or
three years, we'll dig them up and replace them with something
else. But around the first of May, in a bed along the driveway, we
should have a swath of ``Meissner Porzellan,'' a rose and creamy
white flower, surrounded by a mix of deep purple ``Negrita'' and
soft pink ``Jo Ann.''
</P>
<P>
   Tulips are special. They are worth the trouble at tulip time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
