<HEADLINE>
NO AUCTION SITE IS AN ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have never bought or sold anything at the eBay Internet
auction site, but I'm beginning to like those guys.
</P>
<P>
   I've been terrified of eBay because I work at a newspaper. Web
sites that hand out free news still aren't much of a threat; given
the real cost of producing newspapers, we practically give away
information too. No, the real threat comes from Web services that
devour the advertising that makes up our chief source of income.
And eBay does just that. How would you rather sell your stamp
collection _ with a costly newspaper ad that reaches just a few
people in one city, or an eBay auction that reaches collectors
worldwide, with bidders driving the price higher and higher?
</P>
<P>
   The growing popularity of eBay is scary for newspapers, which
get a third or more of their revenues from classified ads. Never
mind the motherly visage of eBay chief executive Meg Whitman
surrounded by Beanie Babies. EBay is The Enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not. Perhaps I've misjudged the folks at eBay. Suddenly
it seems that they're not at all interested in gobbling up the
maximum amount of auction business. The eBayers are actually taking
steps to drive business away.
</P>
<P>
   The company has declared war on a number of Internet sites that
strike me as eBay's natural allies. You might call them auction
search engines. These sites let you punch in a particular item,
like ``Pedro Martinez baseball cards,'' and find hundreds of
ongoing auctions among dozens of Internet auction sites. A single
Web page displays the latest auctions on uBid, Yahoo Auctions,
Amazon.com and eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not eBay. It hates this idea, and is demanding that
auction search engines stop listing eBay auctions. According to
eBay, the constant hits from the search engines were slowing down
eBay's servers.
</P>
<P>
   The chief of one of the search engines says this is bunk, but he
has knuckled under anyway _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a technical issue,'' says James Carney of
Burlington-based Bidder's Edge Inc. Carney claims his system grabs
only a few bytes of data from each of eBay's 3 million auctions,
and does this gradually over the course of a day.
</P>
<P>
   So why did eBay demand to be removed from the Bidder's Edge
service? Carney thinks the company is terrified of competition. New
auction sites are rearing up all over the landscape and services
like Bidder's Edge put them all on an equal footing.
</P>
<P>
   So eBay issued a cease-and-desist demand to Bidder's Edge. And
Bidder's Edge, a start-up with little money to waste on lawyers,
meekly complied. But maybe not for long. ``We're not going to
guarantee we're going to stop forever,'' says Carney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues at stake here are larger than auctions,'' he warns,
noting that eBay's position is a threat to all kinds of Internet
search services. ``You've got all these people doing searching
without express approval'' _ Yahoo, Lycos, AltaVista and so forth.
``So all of a sudden somebody says no, and you stop?''
</P>
<P>
   AuctionWatch.com Inc. of San Bruno, Calif., operator of another
auction search engine, also got a shutdown demand from eBay but so
far has thumbed its nose at it. ``We believe that we are in
compliance with all applicable laws,'' says vice president of
marketing, Dan Neary. ``A library does not need to get the
permission of all the books in the library to index them.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he says eBay is threatening to program its computers to
block all search requests from AuctionWatch. If that happens,
there's little the company can do.
</P>
<P>
   I'd have loved to get eBay's view of the matter, but they didn't
return my calls. That's unusual for them, but perhaps this is part
of their new ``Fortress eBay'' policy. While rival auction firms
happily list their steals and deals on AuctionWatch and Bidder's
Edge, eBay sails on in sovereign isolation _ a recipe for corporate
stagnation on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   This Pat Buchanan-esque strategy may be good for their market
share in the short run, but as rival auctions catch on, eBay will
miss out on thousands of likely customers. We newspaper folk will
still have reason to fear on-line auctions. But by driving off the
search engines, eBay could make itself the least threatening
company in the business. Thanks, guys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
