<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREA MASSACRE STORY PRODUCED STRIFE AT THE AP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trail began with a small April 1998 Associated Press feature
from South Korea mentioning claims of a wartime massacre. It ended
Sept. 30, when a solidly documented AP investigation detailed how
in the early days of the Korean War, US servicemen slaughtered
perhaps hundreds of Korean civilians at a bridge in the hamlet of
No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
   News of a civilian massacre second only to the infamous 1968 My
Lai case exploded in the American media, generating headlines,
front page stories in papers like The New York Times and The
Washington Post, and a government investigation. Only a week old,
the story _ by AP staffers Sang-Hun Choe, Charles J. Hanley, Martha
Mendoza, and researcher Randy Herschaft _ is already creating a
Pulitzer Prize buzz inside the news industry.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the AP is deservedly basking in journalistic kudos. But
according to the former head of the investigative unit that
produced the story, the 17 months between April 1998 and last
week's release of the story represented a time of fierce turmoil
within the news organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Port, who left the AP in mid-June after his investigative
unit was disbanded, says that top AP executives were very reluctant
to give the go-ahead to the highly sensitive story, delayed its
publication for months, and put reporters through ``journalistic
hell'' before their work saw the light of day. AP officials say
they were just applying due diligence to a very difficult story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became a question of what do we stand for,'' says Port.
``When the facts are put in front of you, you shouldn't run away
from it. . . . I'm sad that it was so difficult. I'm sad they
didn't want to do investigative reporting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The piece took a long time to put together for obvious and
sensible reasons,'' responds AP managing editor Jonathan Wolman.
``It can be a cantankerous process and it can be an argumentative
process. But the commitment to the project was absolute.'' Asked
whether AP was reluctant to release the story he says: ``Reluctance
to put out a story before it was ready, sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the AP was being timid or prudent, observers say the
dramatic story is atypical fare for an outfit more accustomed to
basic, nose-to-the-grindstone reportage and that it placed strains
on a conservative corporate culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story was not AP's cup of tea,'' says Kevin Noblet, AP's
deputy international editor, who is on leave as a visiting
professor at Ohio University. ``I think an organization more
accustomed to being out in front on such a big story could have
handled these concerns more quicky and smoothly than we did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It involved a lot of pain and a lot of bitter fighting,'' he
continues. ``But how can you be too prudent?''
</P>
<P>
   According to a time line recounted by Port, his investigative
unit began digging into the massacre story in the spring of 1998
and quickly began hitting pay dirt. Port says that ``we felt we had
the essence of it nailed down'' quickly and by July, the team had
produced an early rough draft.
</P>
<P>
   But despite what Port insists was solid reporting, he says the
top AP brass _ including executive editor William Ahearn and
president Louis Boccardi _ expressed grave and what he considered
unfounded reservations. The final months of 1998 were spent
``arguing'' over the story, he adds. ``There was a great skepticism
and fear that we were (getting) carried away. I did not see that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Boccardi met with Port early this year to discuss the
matter, the AP president ``said our story belonged in Rolling Stone
magazine,'' according to Port. Wolman, the AP official who
responded to questions about Boccardi and Ahearn, says, ``A lot of
frustration is going to set in when something is simmering on the
stove for this long,'' says Wolman. ``We felt like the end result
speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid Miller, a recently retired AP Seoul bureau chief, says, ``I
think AP management quite properly initially wanted to be damn
careful with this story.'' But he says he was ``surprised and
disturbed'' by the delay before publishing. ``I didn't feel that it
needed that long. All the essential details were there in July
1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Two crucial factors most likely influenced AP's internal
handling of the story. As evidence of this military massacre was
being amassed by its reporters, CNN's ill-fated Operation Tailwind
story _ alleging US use of illegal nerve gas during the Vietnam War
_ was blowing up in the network's face and proving to be a
cautionary tale. Significantly, retired Air Force major general
Perry Smith, who resigned as CNN's military adviser out of anger
with the Tailwind story, gives his blessing to No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling was it most likely happened. Then I did some
research and talked to some people and I'm even more convinced that
it happened,'' says Smith, who spoke at Tufts University's Fletcher
School of Law and Diplomacy on Tuesday. ``This has the ring of
credibility to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is AP's reputation as a rock-solid but cautious
organization that is not really comfortable with investigative
blockbusters. ``The culture of the AP is one where you tend to
follow, but not lead,' says investigative journalist Robert Parry,
who did some groundbreaking work on the Iran-contra scandal for AP
in the '80s. ``They also don't want
</P>
<P>
   to show up the clients. . . . There's a culture of journalistic
conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolman counters that at AP, the ``small `c' stands for careful
and we try to be that.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as he and others point out, the bottom line is that the AP
produced a powerful piece of journalism. Even Port acknowledges
that the wire service ``deserves credit for running that story.
They should have said it a little more strongly than they chose to.
But it got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The writers should be incredibly proud of putting up with all
our crap,'' adds Noblet. ``In the end, it was a triumph.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
