<HEADLINE>
RACEWAY PUTS CARS -- AND DRIVERS -- TO THE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   POCONO, Pa. _ The cars are lined up in the pits at Pocono
Raceway, and on this early morning in September, it is hard not to
feel like a kid at Christmas, a kid opening that first slot race
car track and fighting with brothers and sisters over who gets
which car when we race.
</P>
<P>
   But these are real cars, queued up for the taking: Vipers and
Porsches and 'Vettes and souped-up Subarus (the surprise of the
test fleet) and Jaguars and trucks and vans and big American cars
with big horsepower under the hood.
</P>
<P>
   It is International Motor Press Association test day and we'll
be driving as many cars as we can slip into through a road course
that meanders over much of the expansive infield, forcing 90-degree
turns, hairpin turns, and lots of shifting; and for that pure rush
of adrenalin, we'll break onto the three-turn NASCAR track and rip
down the backstretch as fast as the cars will go and their brakes
will stop them for a snap turn back onto the road course at the end
of the straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cars are better suited for the straight. Others for
the road course. Some for both. Some for neither.
</P>
<P>
   To find out which is which, grab one. And since we don't know
the course yet, we grab an Audi Quattro first, hoping for the
stability of all-wheel drive and a certain snap to the car as we
explore.
</P>
<P>
   The track officials launch you from a two-line staging area at
the end of the pits, cars going off at about 20-second intervals
(lengthened if, say, a Viper will be following a Miata off the
line).
</P>
<P>
   There are waiting lists to get into some cars: the Viper; the
Porsche Carrera 4; the new screamer, the Honda S2000, which
redlined at nine honkin' grand (we drove it down here on civilian
roads, and the car is a total blast).
</P>
<P>
   Other cars sit waiting as you roll in from each circuit of the
course. So many cars. Only one day to drive as many as
concentration and stamina allow.
</P>
<P>
   Some quick-test highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Audi Quattro _ Maybe it's because the course is new to me, but I
find the Audi spongy in the corners of the road course. Am I
jerking it through the turns, or is it really that soft? And, on
the straightaway its power is unimpressive.
</P>
<P>
   Plymouth Prowler _ Its look _ open cockpit, open front wheels
capped with fenders _ screams Hot Rod. But it's not. It doesn't
have the requisite muscle. It behaves more like a sports car.
Still, it is eye-catching.
</P>
<P>
   Lexus GS400 _ Smooth, powerful, a sports sedan with one
troubling characteristic: a strange delayed response when you get
on the gas pedal to accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   The Viper RT/10 _ Scary when you first get in to drive. Wants to
leap ahead. Even the burble of the motor sends a warning chill
through you as you sit in the staging area. How will all this power
do on the turns? Had to be very careful, owing as much to my
unfamiliarity with the car as to any traits of its own. How will it
do on the straightaway? Came out of the banked turn at an
effortless 89 miles per hour, drifted up to the wall of the
straightaway and hit 127 before it was time to start slowing
(again, unfamiliarity played a role here) for the snap turn that I
knew was coming. This can be a dangerous car in the wrong hands.
Ask the guy who drove it not long after me, came off the road
course, and got into the gas too much. He fishtailed, spun, and hit
the wall. The Viper? Totaled.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen VR6 GTI _ A sure-footed screamer. Ate up the road
course with its front wheels grabbing for purchase all the way.
Good but not remarkable acceleration out of the banked raceway turn
and down the straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguar XK8 _ Great looking. Plenty of power on the straight.
Unsettling on the road course as it seemed to unweight up front in
sharp corners.
</P>
<P>
   Oldsmobile Allero _ For a $17,000 car (cheap these days) a truly
surprising drive. Throaty sound. Quick on the corners and stable,
too. Steady surge down the straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac GTX Ram Air _ Think 1970s muscle car. Alto gurgle from
the exhaust. Tops 100 on the straightaway with not much effort. On
the road course, it reminds you why so many muscle cars and pony
cars got wrecked over the years not on big highways but on local
roads with sharp curves.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet Corvette _ Fancy pewter-colored job. Lots of power.
Stiff on the corners and feeling like the back wants to break away
at any moment. Powerful down the straightaway. But what's that
Subaru doing screaming by me as I hug the wall?
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Eclipse _ Careful, the Mitsubishi guy told me as I
climbed in, don't want to knock my competitors, but this car, when
you punch the gas, responds immediately. I found it disappointing.
At 205 horsepower this buggy shouldn't bog the way it does. I felt
I was in the way of other drivers out there.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Mustang _ Pony car power. Pony car speed. A squeal through
every corner of the road course.
</P>
<P>
   Buick Regal _ Supercharged. 260 horses. Powerful, fairly fast,
but one unsettling quirk. You can drive this as an automatic or
shift it yourself. I chose to do my own shifting. Scorching down
the straightaway, I slowed, downshifted, and tried to power through
the first turn, stomping the gas in second gear. The car shifted up
automatically, and what should have been a power-dig through the
turn became a soft, unsettling drift.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Tiburon _ The loneliest looking car in the pits. Sat
there unused most of the day. Inside, it's a knockoff of the Audi
TT's distinctive dimpled-chrome look. On the track, it was quick
and a better car than I expected.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, that Subaru 2.5 RS Imprezza all-wheel drive. Stiff
race suspension. Turbocharged. Racing seats so tight you had to be
surgically removed after a test drive. What a car. Screamed through
the road course, redlined most of the way. Second and third gear,
tops. Whipped out of the corner onto the big track and ran right up
to the wall, almost kissing it down the backstretch, eating up
pavement at well over 100 and snapping back onto the road course
without missing a beat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
