<HEADLINE>
HOOKED ON THE EASY DIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As one of America's most vociferous and
relentless critics of cellular phones, I must make a confession:
Last month, during a three-week working vacation in Italy, I used a
cell phone and it felt really, really good.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, I used it during a meal in a public restaurant, an act
for which I once suggested prison time.
</P>
<P>
   I ask not for mercy _ cell phone abuse remains a blight on
civilized society _ but I would at least like to explain what in
the world came over me.
</P>
<P>
   You see, I was sitting in the sun in a tiny trattoria that
fairly hangs from a cliff on the Isle of Capri. I was in my
swimming suit (this was the vacated part of the working vacation),
which was still wet with my first-ever dive into the Mediterranean
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Although I'd been prepared for the beauty of the Mediterranean,
that dive and subsequent swim dazzled me. The water off Capri is a
spectacular blue on the surface, clear as a mountain spring once
you are in it, and so salty that one need only lie back and breathe
normally to float forever.
</P>
<P>
   If that were not enough, on this particular day a small band of
60-something, sun-bathing women sat upon the dark rocks that lie
just below the little restaurant and sang Neapolitan folk songs.
</P>
<P>
   Their four-part harmonies and spirited tunes conjured up images
of 20th Century Sirens, sent not to entice sailors to doom but to
delight a handful of folks who dined above or sunned on the
surrounding rocks.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out the women were a company of professional
entertainers, but it was their day off. Their music was free for
anyone in earshot to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   The eatery I have mentioned actually looked more like a shack
than a restaurant and had a visible staff of one old man _ the
owner _ and an amiable young waitress. When my companion suggested
we lunch there, I assumed we would get cellophane-wrapped
sandwiches, bags of chips and _ if we were lucky _ a warm can of
beer.
</P>
<P>
   I had forgotten this was Italy. Out came the tablecloth and
napkins (cotton, not paper), the cold liter of crisp white wine,
the antipasto of grilled vegetables and prawns, the perfectly al
dente pasta with fresh tomatoes and basil, then the main course of
grilled and fried fresh fish.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, during the second liter of wine, my friend picked up
the cell phone he'd bought in Italy for his work portion of the
working vacation and handed it to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ought to call your parents and say hi,'' he said. ``Just
dial 001 and the number.''
</P>
<P>
   I looked out at the blue sea and down at the singing Neapolitan
grandmas. I took another sip of wine and dialed.
</P>
<P>
   It was 7:30 a.m. in Indiana and my dad answered in a voice still
fuzzy with morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm calling you from a restaurant hanging over the
Mediterranean on the Isle of Capri,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're kidding,'' Dad said. ``You sound like you're across the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he began singing the '40s song about the Isle of Capri.
</P>
<P>
   My mom got on the extension phone and listened as I tried to
describe everything I could see, taste and hear. I even held the
phone out toward the rocks so the singing ladies could register in
the Hoosier state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just lying in bed thinking about you and wondering if
you were having a good time,'' Mom said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she burst into tears and said what a marvel modern life is
that we could share such a moment so many thousands of miles apart.
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes more, we said ``I love you'' about 50 times
and finally hung up. I pushed the antenna of the little green phone
back into its hard little plastic body and held the whole thing in
my hand. It felt like a candy bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a miracle,'' I told my friend, as I handed him back his
phone. No wonder half the Western world is hooked.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
