<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON SNOOPING, SLANG AND TALK ABOUT DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I often read my daughter's diary as a way to keep in touch
with what she's thinking. She's 12. When I mentioned this to other
mothers with daughters the same age, some said they do the same
thing, but others were appalled. We'd like some guidance.
</P>
<P>
   A. Reading your daughter's diary definitely comes under the
category of snooping. In other words, a no-no. Despite that, there
may be times when snooping is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never endorse a parent routinely reading a diary,''
says clinical psychologist Roni Cohen-Sandler of Weston, Conn.,
whose practice specializes in adolescent girls. For one thing, she
says, if you gain information you are morally obligated to act on_
that your daughter's best friend is being sexually abused, for
instance _ you help the friend but hurt your daughter by violating
her trust.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that the information you act on may not be
true. ``Girls this age are melodramatic, and their feelings change
rapidly,'' says Cohen-Sandler. ``What a girl writes is not
necessarily what she believes; she may just be trying on ideas.
Plus, what she writes one moment may not be what she feels the
next. You have no way of knowing that.''
</P>
<P>
   If, however, you are concerned about her safety _ you find drug
paraphernalia, smell alcohol, notice unusual behavior _ then the
diary is a valid source, she says. In fact, if you find the diary
in a public place in the house where your daughter knows you'll see
it, consider it her subconscious invitation for you to read it.
``At some level, she wants you to find out what's going on so you
can rescue her,'' says Cohen-Sandler.
</P>
<P>
   If you learn something worrisome, work it into a conversation:
``I'm wondering if you know any kids who steal liquor from their
parents . . . '' If she asks you if you've read the diary, don't
lie, but also don't get bogged down on that. ``Some mothers feel so
guilty, they're apologetic, and the discussion ends up focused on
Mom-how-could-you-do-this while the dangerous behavior, which is
the more important issue, gets sidetracked,'' says Cohen-Sandler.
She is a coauthor of `` `I'm Not Mad, I Just Hate You': A New
Understanding of Mother-Daughter Conflict'' (Viking).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My question is about language: How do you know what's
appropriate and what's not? By this I mean slang, especially body
slang and expletives. There's ``butt'' and ``weiner'' that I hear
now. When I start to hear the f-word, which is a staple now and may
be deflated in its overuse, what can I do? My son is 6.
</P>
<P>
   A. As with so many things in our culture, there's been a lot of
slippage. Language once unimaginable in the mouth of a 6-year-old _
``That sucks'' comes to mind _ is now widely socially accepted.
That doesn't mean you have to accept it, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you hear language you don't like, make it clear
this is not an acceptable word in your family,'' says Debra
Haffner, president of the Sexuality Information and Education
Council of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That's doable, of course, only if you don't use the word.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons young children use slang and expletives is to
imitate what they hear in the culture from older kids and from us,
especially if they perceive it as more grown-up, like swearing when
they're angry. If you realize you're guilty, make a point of
saying, ``It's not a nice word, and I'm going to stop saying it
myself.'' Haffner suggests a fine box, where you drop a quarter
every time you say it.
</P>
<P>
   Children frequently use a word without knowing what it means.
Haffner's advice is threefold. ``Ask: `I'm wondering if you know
what it means'; clarify: `The f-word is a very ugly word for when
two married people make love'; and place your value around it:
`It's not a word parents or adults like to hear children use.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A pitfall to avoid is getting caught up in its meaning, for
instance, a discussion of intercourse. Stay focused instead on
values around language and public versus private behavior: ``This
is a word you can think in private in your head. It's not a word to
speak in public.'' If language gets out of hand, Haffner suggests
immediate consequences, such as removing TV or computer game
privileges for that day.
</P>
<P>
   You can legislate language at home but not with friends. Talk
about that, she says: `` `I know your friends use this word. I
can't control what you say with them, but I still don't like it,
and you'll get in trouble using it at home or with other adults.''
Haffner has written several books for parents, including ``From
Diapers to Dating: A Parent's Guide to Raising Sexually Healthy
Children'' (Newmarket).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am the grandmother of a 2 1/2-year-old boy. Last week, my
father-in-law died. We went to my mother-in-law's, and within two
minutes, Joshua asked where his great-grandpa was, because he was
not sitting in the den where he always found him. Needless to say,
my daughter and I were floored that he made the connection between
the empty chair and his great-grandpa. My response was simply,
``He's not home.'' Can you suggest a book for Joshua?
</P>
<P>
   A. Children this age are very literal, taking our words at face
value. As a result, when someone dies, we inadvertently create
problems if we use euphemisms to soften the blow, says children's
grief specialist Maria Trozzi, director of the Good Grief Program
at Boston Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but when children have inaccurate or incomplete
information, they embellish it with their imagination. Joshua, for
instance, may think great-grandpa isn't home because he chose to
leave, and maybe he left because he's mad at someone in the family.
Because young children are so egocentric, he could easily make the
leap to this thought: ``I wonder what I did that he doesn't want to
come home anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   Trozzi recommends a simple but truthful explanation, even after
the fact: ``Great-grandpa isn't in his chair because he died. That
means his body has totally stopped working. Every single part of
his body has stopped. His body doesn't get hungry or thirsty, his
body doesn't have to go to the bathroom or get sleepy. When the
body dies, it doesn't come alive again. I'm glad we will always
have memories of great-grandpa.''
</P>
<P>
   If you believe in heaven, Trozzi suggests talking about it after
your concrete explanation. ``Otherwise, what does heaven mean? He
went to California, he went to heaven, what's the difference? He'll
still think he's coming back,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She also tells parents not to say, ``He died because he was
sick.'' ``The next time he's sick, he'll worry he's going to die,
too. You need to distance this sickness from what happens every day
to children: `Great-grandpa was very very very very very sick,' ''
says Trozzi. She is the author of ``Talking with Children about
Loss'' (Perigee Paperback).
</P>
<P>
   A book the Good Grief Program recommends for young children is,
ironically, ``Daddy's Chair'' by Sandy Lanton (Kar-Ben, 1991),
about a young boy who won't let anyone sit in his father's chair
after the father dies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are trying to figure out a structure for
allowance. We have a son who just started second grade and
unfortunately is motivated by money.
</P>
<P>
   A. Take advantage of it! ``The younger children learn how to
manage money, the better,'' says Debra Sherwin. She is an associate
professor of economics and money management at Goucher College in
Baltimore and counsels parents on helping children handle money.
</P>
<P>
   Her advice is to start off slow and low: ``If you give too much,
undoing it feels like a punishment. But you can always increase.''
For a 7-year-old, she suggests $2.50 or $3 a week. The amount
depends on what peers get (better to be in the middle of the group
than on the high or low end); on your finances (even if you can
afford more, don't be out of proportion to what he can handle
developmentally); and on your expectations for his spending (if he
has to pay for lunch, $3 may not be enough).
</P>
<P>
   Problems occur when parents aren't clear about how money should
be spent and then get angry over foolish spending. ``Once it's his
money, you can't tell him how to spend it,'' says Sherwin. ``Your
chance to shape spending habits comes from negotiating in advance
what is and isn't appropriate spending.''
</P>
<P>
   She says a good question to start with is, ``What do you think
an allowance is for?'' Even a 7-year-old may have an agenda. ``What
if he wants to save for something big that you won't buy, like
Nintendo? If you don't know that up front, it's harder to deal
with.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of family values whether allowance is tied to
chores, but Sherwin is against it: ``You do chores because you are
part of the family, not because we pay you. Also as part of this
family, you are entitled to an allowance.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Seventy-four percent of male characters on TV
programs and movies that boys most typically watch regularly engage
in antisocial behavior such as ridiculing, lying, aggression, and
defiance, according to a survey by Children Now, a national child
advocacy organization.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz welcomes letters and comments and can be reached
via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
