<HEADLINE>
EPICURES FIND SAN FRANCISCO IRRESISTIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They'll drive more than 50 miles for foie gras.
They want a fine wine, not fries, with that. They don't necessarily
make more money than other people, but they spend more on food.
</P>
<P>
   They think San Francisco is an absolutely fabulous restaurant
town _ the nation's best, even better than runner-up New York.
</P>
<P>
   These are among the key findings in a new nationwide study of
epicures. The study was released Wednesday by the San Francisco
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau, which commissioned an Ohio research
firm to quiz 3,000 American adults about their eating and traveling
habits.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has been recognized before for its fine
restaurants, notably by Conde Nast Traveler, Gourmet and other
magazines. But tourism officials say the new study is the most
broadly representative poll ever done.
</P>
<P>
   David Bratton, the bureau's vice president for research, said
the poll confirmed numerically what San Franciscans have long heard
anecdotally. The survey also helps restaurateurs get their arms
around trends. For example, microscopic portions and heavy foods
are currently out, while lighter, flavorful foods and vegetarian
dishes are in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us a better sense of where to dig for tourists,''
Bratton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to study and pursue foodies the way Las Vegas
studies and pursues gamblers,'' said Laurie Armstrong, the bureau's
vice president for public relations.
</P>
<P>
   A surprisingly high 38 percent of the randomly selected adults
identified themselves as epicures _ a person who enjoys food and
has a discriminating taste.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau, which promotes San Francisco worldwide as a business
and leisure destination, wanted to know more about the travel
habits of pleasure-loving, free-spending epicures, according to the
vice president for marketing, Brian Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said epicures spend more per meal, are more likely to
order wine with their meals and are more likely to complain if they
feel something is off. They also put an especially high value on
professional service.
</P>
<P>
   Citing figures compiled from three-page questionnaires mailed
over the summer by National Family Opinion Inc. of Toledo, Baker
said that epicures took an average of 3.2 leisure trips in the past
year; that compares with 2.6 trips for non-epicures. Epicures also
took 1.7 business trips a year, compared with just 1.0 for others.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the bureau actively touts the city's gastronomic
delights to travel agents, tour operators, conventioneers and
others wondering where to deposit their travel dollars.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco edged out New York in the survey, which the bureau
said was the first major national study of roadwise gourmets. Among
the respondents, 53.2 percent said San Francisco was a great
restaurant town, compared with 53.1 percent for New York. New
Orleans placed third, Chicago fourth and surging Las Vegas fifth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
