<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-LAPTOP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 NOT A BAD LAPTOP, iBOOK ALSO IS A PEOPLE MAGNET  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Can I touch it?''
</P>
<P>
   Not the usual sort of reaction you get when carrying around a
laptop computer, but that is pretty much the response I got with
the iBook, Apple Computer Inc.'s stylish new laptop.
</P>
<P>
   The iBook is Apple's final piece of a four-part strategy. As
Apple chief executive Steve Jobs has said over and over, the
computer maker has radically pared down its once-chaotic product
line to four basic categories of machines.
</P>
<P>
   The G3/G4 desktop boxes and the Powerbook laptops are muscle
machines intended for the publishing and graphics industry.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, former bathroom sink designer Jonathon Ive and
his Apple team have created the iMac line. The iMac theme has been
an industry success story, with its able-bodied computers in
translucent candy-color plastic covers.
</P>
<P>
   The iMacs have been credited with bringing the Cupertino company
back from the brink.
</P>
<P>
   The new iBook completes Apple's latest marketing campaign. And
though it is no earth-shaking event like the iMac, the iBook does
succeed in some ways.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing really outstanding about any one iBook spec.
There are plenty of PC laptops with oomph enough to keep up with
the iBook's 300 MHz PowerPC G3 chip. The machine's 12.5-inch screen
is a somewhat paltry portable landscape, considering the sprawling
14-inch displays of, say, the 14.1-inch, top-of-the-line IBM
Thinkpads.
</P>
<P>
   There are now plenty of machines, including the ultra slim
3.5-pound Sony VAIO notebooks, that easily beat the iBook's hefty
6.6 pounds. It's the same all the way down the list of technical
features: 3.2 GB hard drive, 24x CD-ROM drive, included 32MB SDRAM.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when gathered together and wrapped up in a blue or tangerine
rubberized skin, the iBook becomes one incredible machine.
</P>
<P>
   It is a collection of the little touches that make the iBook
almost a sensual object of desire.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when you put the iBook to sleep, either by closing
the lid or picking that function from an on-screen powerbar, the
screen goes blank and a small greenish light pulses slowly, like a
resting heartbeat. The small socket where you plug in the power
cord is ringed in a glowing light. Red for recharging, green for
charged.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly clear-white plastic keyboard is soft to touch. The
power cord comes wrapped around a slick little flying-saucer-shaped
reel. There also is a strong plastic handle that folds out from the
iBook's hinge.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the iMac theme of an easy out of-the-box set-up,
the iBook comes fully charged. It includes an array of connections
on-board and ready to go, such as an Ethernet port for network
hookups (including DSL) and a USB port for adding a mouse or other
peripherals. It comes with a good array of software and a few
games.
</P>
<P>
   Some minor quibbles: The single speaker is teeny tiny, so don't
count on using this as a boom box. Speaking of which, the CD tray,
like those in the iMac, is pretty fragile, especially for a machine
intended for road work. The new iMac models, slated for this
Christmas, will sport a CD drive that is just a slot that you feed
disks into. The iBook could benefit from this improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the trackpad is not my favorite way of moving a cursor
around the screen, though some prefer it. But the keyboard-mounted
button that substitutes for the button on the mouse takes more than
the usual effort to push down. Be prepared to build up some thumb
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern: The recent earthquake in Taiwan has disrupted
the production of computer processor chips, including those slated
for the iBook. Jobs said earlier this week that production has
resumed on the iBook. But expect some scarcity of iBooks in the
short term.
</P>
<P>
   With a retail price of $1,599, the iBook is not the cheapest
laptop. But as a complete package, you would be hard pressed to
find a cooler, more functional machine.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you don't like people feeling your iBook.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
