r a BC-POLICE-D.A.-HNS &LR;      10-07 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-D.A.-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICERS VOICE OPPOSITION TO PROSECUTOR IN UNION VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nearly all of the San Francisco police officers
who chose a candidate in their union's endorsement poll this week
want to oust District Attorney Terence Hallinan and replace him
with former prosecutor Bill Fazio in the Nov. 2 election.
</P>
<P>
   Sources within the San Francisco Police Officers Association
said that out of 2,100 eligible members, 983 voted for Fazio, 18
voted for Hallinan, and one for Matt Gonzalez, a public defender
who is attacking the incumbent from the left. An undetermined
percentage of officers returned ballots that declined to endorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a staggering vote of no confidence in Hallinan,'' Fazio
said of the endorsement vote by the police union. ``I'm elated.
This may be the biggest thing for my campaign. It tells me that the
men and women who protect the streets of San Francisco have no
faith in the current district attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallinan campaign manager Ross Mirkarimi said his boss was not
surprised by the endorsement since the police union backed Fazio in
1995. He also noted that most officers live outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The POA vote does not reflect the vast majority of San
Francisco citizens,'' Mirkarimi said.
</P>
<P>
   Hallinan was not immediately available for comment, but before
the endorsement vote was announced he said, ``I have a great
working relationship with the Police Department and I expect that
to continue. I have nothing but respect for the police officers who
protect this city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The rank and file have made it clear that they want Bill Fazio
to be the next district attorney,'' union president Chris Cunnie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fazio, who worked as an assistant district attorney for 20 years
until he was fired in 1995 by Hallinan's predecessor, Arlo Smith,
noted that he has received support from a variety of groups who
work in the criminal justice system, including the deputy sheriffs'
union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's cops on the street who arrest criminals,
attorneys who defend them or deputies who keep them in jail, they
all think I can do a better job,'' Fazio said.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement of Fazio was widely expected. Four years ago,
the police union endorsed him by a vote of 90 percent, snubbing
Smith, the incumbent, and challenger Hallinan, who at the time was
a member of the Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   The union did not invite candidates to make their case to the
rank and file officers. Gonzalez and Steve Castleman, another
former prosecutor and a candidate for the job, said they wished
they had had the opportunity to address the police union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted to have received one vote,'' Gonzalez said.
``It's not surprising to me. Bill Fazio is taking the more
conservative position on issues. I wonder what would happen if you
took Fazio out of the equation and it was between me and Hallinan.
I'm the only candidate who is talking about the problem of police
brutality, so it doesn't surprise me not to be endorsed by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers have complained that Hallinan is too soft on drug
cases. They say that he should go for jail time instead of offering
probation or pretrial diversion programs for small-scale dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Police Sgt. Reno Rapagnani, a Hallinan supporter, said he was
not surprised at the endorsement vote. He said there is a natural
tension between street officers and prosecutors that can be
particularly frustrating in a liberal city such as San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our work product is making arrests,'' Rapagnani said. ``We
take a lot of pride in our arrests, and when we see that a case is
not prosecuted, it gets officers really angry. ... But in the
bigger picture, DAs have to look at other things. They simply
cannot prosecute every case. There isn't room in the courts. There
isn't room in the jails and the voters have made it clear they
don't want more jails.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1353EDT &QL; 
