<SLUG> BC-MEDICINE-GRANT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERKELEY GETS $50M FOR MEDICAL RESEARCH PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ The University of California at Berkeley has
received $50 million, its largest gift ever, to help construct one
of two new buildings for a program to bring together physical and
biological scientists in pursuit of medical innovations.
</P>
<P>
   University officials announced the anonymous gift and the
school's new Health Sciences Initiative on Wednesday. Envisioned as
a $500 million program, the initiative will unite scientists from
fields such as mathematics, engineering, physics and computer
science to work on increasingly complex problems in biology and
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   UC-Berkeley is one of a handful of large universities that are
trying to bring the physical and biomedical sciences more closely
together. For instance, a Nobel-winning physicist at Stanford
University and one of its top biochemists are proposing a research
center that would house 50 faculty members. Similar ideas are being
pursued at Harvard, the University of Chicago and the University of
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The projects envisioned at Berkeley include designing artificial
tissues and joints, advancing computer imaging of the living brain,
figuring out better diagnostic tests and extracting useful
information from the mountain of data coming from sequencing the
human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Some cross-disciplinary collaborations are already under way,
such as joint programs on bioengineering with the University of
California at Francisco School of Medicine, and between UC-Berkeley
chemists and UC-San Francisco's pharmacology department.
</P>
<P>
   University officials expect more will follow as new technology
and understanding of molecular mechanisms in the body revolutionize
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, the truly breakthrough technologies that drive
better health are coming from fundamental sciences like physics,
chemistry and engineering,'' said Edward Penhoet, dean of the
School of Public Health at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Without a medical school to focus research, and tagged with a
highly regarded reputation in the physical sciences, Berkeley is
rarely thought of as a hotbed of medical research. But it has
strong programs in neuroscience and immunology, and scientists
there and at the nearby Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory are
playing leading roles in sequencing the human genome, or complete
set of chromosones.
</P>
<P>
   The ambitious program at Berkeley has already attracted $100
million in private donations and $24 million from the state. In
addition to the $50 million gift made this summer, $20 million has
come from William V. Power, co-founder of the insurance brokerage
company Power and Dalziel, to support the neuroscience portion of
the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   That program will be named after Helen Wills Moody, the late
tennis star and Berkeley alum, whose estate is donating $10
million. Another $10 million is from an anonymous source.
</P>
<P>
   On the engineering side, Intel Corp. co-founder Gordon Moore has
donated $10 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1355EDT &QL; 
