r e BC-HARSH-REALM-REVIEW-LA     10-07 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARSH-REALM-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL REALITY   FLESHED OUT IN   CARTER'S NEW TV VISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chris Carter's batting .500 to date. After making
paranoia sexy with ``The X-Files,'' he managed to drag the
convoluted, dreary ``Millennium'' through three seasons _ but not
up to the new millennium itself.
</P>
<P>
   His new series, the comic-book-inspired ``Harsh Realm,'' is more
a straightforward action series, with the requisite Y2K twist _ it
all takes place inside a virtual-reality game developed by the
military. Scott Bairstow stars as Tom Hobbes, an Army lieutenant
recruited _ just before he is about to leave the service and marry
his sweetheart, Sophie (Samantha Mathis) _ to enter the game, Harsh
Realm, and make the cyber-world once again safe for geeks.
</P>
<P>
   Seems the game has been hijacked by Omar Santiago (Terry
O'Quinn), a decorated soldier who has apparently gone mad, taken
over the world inside the game and brought it up to his own
fascistic standards. The many soldiers dispatched to within the
game's cyberscapes invariably give up and focus on their own
survival. Hobbes meets Mike Pinocchio (D.B. Sweeney), one of those
soldiers, and rekindles his passion for the mission, as well as the
mute Florence (Rachel Haywood): They believe Hobbes is ``The One''
who will restore peace within Harsh Realm.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so we have a computer game controlled by an enemy _ it
certainly seems a problem we need to worry about out here in the
real world, huh? And maybe whatever danger there is could be
averted by, oh, say, (ITAL)unplugging the game?(END ITAL) And, once
again _ this game is supposed to help stop terrorism in the real
world how?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Carter makes the show exciting, smart and edgy
enough that, for the time being, viewers should be willing to
suspend their disbelief over such matters and be intrigued enough
to see how this ordeal will play out. Carter should, however, also
eschew slow-motion action sequences _ they only underscore how
unlikely his characters' escapes truly are.
</P>
<P>
   He could also lay off the dopey, small-world plot twists _ a man
Hobbes saved in combat just (ITAL)happens(END ITAL), in the game,
to be allied with Santiago and married to Sophie. (The series'
opening sequence in 1994 Sarajevo is pointless and, really, not all
that interesting _ two lines of dialogue could filled us in on the
back-story, given how indifferently rendered these plot twists play
out).
</P>
<P>
   Since Carter's likely to be heavily invested in making what is
probably ``The X-Files' '' final season a memorable one, the
question is whether he'll have enough energy to likewise imbue
``Harsh Realm'' with a sense of focus and urgent melodrama. Its
premise is rife with potentially maddening narrative
inconsistencies, and the Hobbes-Sophie relationship could get
unduly mopey. But Carter has a feature film-quality cast, a talent
for making his shows belie their TV budgets and a way of absorbing
viewers into worlds a mere step removed from our own _ don't expect
that plug to be pulled on ``Harsh Realm'' any time too soon. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The show: ``Harsh Realm.'' &QL; 
What: Chris Carter's new cyber-paranoid action-drama.  &QL; 
Who: Scott Bairstow, D.B. Sweeney, Terry O'Quinn, Samantha Mathis. &QL; 
Where: Fox  &QL; 
When: 9 tonight. &QL; 
Rating: 3 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
