r a BC-SOUTH-POLE-RESCUE-HNS     10-07 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-POLE-RESCUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARD CREW TO ATTEMPT SOUTH POLE RESCUE MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LINDA TRISCHITTA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ A New York Air National Guard crew will try
to make an unprecedented landing at the South Pole next week,
braving extreme weather conditions to evacuate an ailing physician
who discovered a lump in her breast earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, two C-130 cargo planes operated by members of the
109th Airlift Wing began a five-day journey from the Schenectady
County Airport to a region of the world where current temperatures
are around 85 degrees below zero. Dr. Jerri Nielsen, a researcher
working at the National Science Foundation's Amundsen-Scott South
Pole Station, has been trapped by the extreme environment, unable
to obtain medical care other than treatment she could administer to
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, 47, received worldwide attention in July when the U.S.
Air Force delivered medical supplies to her in a dramatic airdrop
made in darkness and severe cold. Nielsen is the lone physician to
the 41 employees of the research facility who discovered a hole in
the ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
   The National Guard planes are scheduled to arrive at
Christchurch, New Zealand, this weekend after making several stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could be at the South Pole on the fifth day (Sunday) if
they have good weather,'' said Maj. Bob Bullock, spokesman for the
109th Airlift Wing.
</P>
<P>
   The flight crews will wait at Christchurch, and at McMurdo
Station, located on an ice shelf on the southern coast of
Antarctica, until the mercury climbs to 58 degrees below zero
before they attempt a rendezvous that should last about half an
hour, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock tried to downplay any risk with cautious optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technically it's classified as a medical evacuation and we're
trying to underscore that there is almost a routine nature about
this,'' he said. ``But, we are doing this mission at a time of year
when the world does not have a lot of experience flying into the
South Pole. It's two weeks early, and without precedent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
