<HEADER>
A9542 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-VENTURA-HARVARD-NYTSF     10-07 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURA-HARVARD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESSE VENTURA, OAFISH VULGARIAN, WOWS HARVARD ...? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   No wonder so many people can't stand the national media, often
ranking ``journalist'' below ``sewage maintenance technician'' on
those lists of the most desirable occupations.
</P>
<P>
   So many big guns in the media seem to be completely out of touch
with mainstream America. They get so worked up over stuff the rest
of the country hardly cares about.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Jesse ``The Oddity'' Ventura, the
refrigerator-sized novelty act who continues to dazzle the New York
and Washington press corps, even as the rest of us are yawning and
thinking, ``Stone Cold Steve Austin has a better act than this
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   If you were watching any of the network morning talk shows on
the morning of Oct. 7, you could not avoid Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   On CBS's ``This Morning,'' they were showing footage of
Ventura's appearance the day before at Harvard University, where he
wowed the brainy kids with his forthright style and happily signed
copies of Playboy, which of course features the now-famous
interview in which he said organized religion is a ``crutch for
weak-minded people,'' defined gun control as being able to hit a
target twice from 25 meters, mocked overweight people, claimed John
F. Kennedy was assassinated by the military-industrial complex and
said he'd like to be reincarnated as a 38DD bra.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the same stuff you'd hear if you were sitting in
a bar named McDrunky's with a couple of overserved guys wearing
construction boots and John Deere baseball caps.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the effete elite in the media are still in the
honeymoon phase with Ventura. Isn't he the cuddliest? What'll he
say next? I wonder if I can hire him out for my next holiday party.
</P>
<P>
   On NBC's ``Today,'' they showed highlights from Ventura's
appearance on a special edition of ``Hardball'' with Chris
Matthews. And then Matt Lauer interviewed Matthews about his
interview with Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   On ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' they played excerpts from a
Q-and-A session featuring George Stephanopoulos and Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Just think, a few years ago that would have meant a Democratic
consultant was talking with a wrestler/actor. Now Georgey's a
journalist and Jesse's a governor.
</P>
<P>
   Progress? You decide.
</P>
<P>
   In the same manner in which NBC's Lauer queried his colleague
Matthews about the experience of questioning Ventura, ABC's Sawyer
asked fellow reporter Stephanopoulos about his experience with the
big bald blowhard.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about overkill. You would have thought these guys had
scored a one-on-one with the pope, rather than yet another in a
seemingly endless series of media splashes by the new poster boy
for the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   (By the way, members of the Reform Party are said to be furious
with Ventura about that Playboy interview because it hurts their
credibility. This from an organization founded by Ross Perot, who
is from Mars.)
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulous concluded his chat with Sawyer by giving her a
scooplet: That very night, Ventura planned to be dining with Donald
Trump, presumably to talk about which oafish vulgarian would best
represent the Reform Party in the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd buy a ticket to that,'' said a giddy Sawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Sure you would. With those two guys, one could expect topics
like, ``Arena Football: A Good Idea?'', ``When It Comes to Rating
Broads, Are You a Chest Man or a Legs Man?'' and ``Think We've Ever
Slept With the Same Bimbo?''
</P>
<P>
   What fun for the media. And why spoil the party by pointing out
that in a recent Newsweek poll, a grand total of 2 percent said
they'd vote for Trump in a presidential race? (To be fair, in an
appearance on ``Dateline,'' Trump proudly pointed out that he did
win the consensus of National Enquirer readers in a recent poll. Go
Donald!)
</P>
<P>
   The current frenzy about potential ``celebrity candidates,'' of
course, doesn't just stop at Jesse the Oaf. It ranges from Warren
Beatty to Donald Trump to Oprah Winfrey _ whose name has been
bandied about as presidential timber even though the woman has
expressed less than zero interest in running for the job. (And why
would she? It'd be a demotion from her current reign as Queen of
the Country.)
</P>
<P>
   But, in fact, let's not mention that none of these would-be
candidates _ not Ventura, not Trump, not Beatty, not Winfrey, not
Cybill Shepard, not the cast of ``Three Kings,'' none of them _ has
a snowball's chance in Aruba of actually contending for national
office.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not admit that we know these fringe characters could never
get as much as 20 percent from the actual voting public. It's too
much fun gabbing and writing about them. We've got to fill space
somehow when the real contenders are three stiffs, and the blasted
election is still a full year away.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
