<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9546 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-REVIEWS-LADN     10-07 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use or after by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `LOVE &AMP; MONEY' &QL; 
``Love &AMP; Money'' has a premise that could've played at any point in
the history of television, which means it seems awfully musty in
1999: A young woman from a rich family who lives in the penthouse
of a tony New York residential building (Allison, played by Paget
Brewster) is in love with the working-class superintendent (Eamon,
played by Brian Van Holt).
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's pilot relies upon the hackneyed, artificial drama of
Eamon disrupting Allison's impending marriage to a man she doesn't
love; next week, Allison tries to get her family to share their
true feelings, with antiquated comic results.
</P>
<P>
   Van Holt and Brewster make for an appealing enough couple, but
they're surrounded by disapproving cartoon cutouts: David Ogden
Stiers as her stuffed-shirt stiff of a dad, Swoosie Kurtz as her
blowsy souse of a mom and Brian Doyle Murray as his dad, whose
philosophy seems to be, if something's worth saying, it's worth
barking out at top volume. John Livingston, as Allison's slacker
brother, gets what few funny lines the writers can muster; needless
to say, he doesn't turn up much. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The show: ``Love &AMP; Money.'' &QL; 
What: Sitcom about a wealthy young woman, her working-class
boyfriend and their disapproving families. &QL; 
Who: Brian Van Holt, Paget Brewster, Swoosie Kurtz, David Ogden
Stiers, Brian Doyle Murray. &QL; 
Where: CBS  &QL; 
When: 8:30 tonight. &QL; 
Rating: 3 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`THE CHRIS ROCK SHOW'
</P>
<P>
   Apologies to Dennis Miller and Bill Maher, but Chris Rock may be
the smartest comedian on TV these days. He's certainly the
funniest, as viewers of his HBO stand-up specials can readily
attest. And on ``The Chris Rock Show,'' he pokes, gently yet
insistently, at pernicious racial issues still tormenting America
(he went down South to suggest to supporters of the Confederate
flag that they replace the stars with faces of stars on the WB).
And he maintains a modest public face, repeatedly paying homage to
Richard Pryor and other comics who inspired him and, upon winning
an Emmy for writing last month, declaring that Conan O'Brien's
staff deserved the trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Where Miller and Maher make their points with joke-laced
harangues, Rock does so more tactfully, with inspired absurdist wit
_ gun violence was skewered with reports of an attacker entering a
building and hitting people upside the head.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other talk-show hosts, he's not afraid to
thrust-and-parry with his interview subjects. Thus far this season,
Rock's asked Spike Lee why most black-themed films stink, told
basketball star Allan Iverson that his staff locked up its
valuables when they saw his entourage and observed to the Rev. Al
Sharpton that he actually seems sane compared to New York Mayor
Rudy Giuliani. Rock has gone from languishing during one of
``Saturday Night Live's'' routine lousy eras to making anything he
does worth investigating. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The show: ``The Chris Rock Show.'' &QL; 
What: Talk show starring the hot comic.  &QL; 
Where: HBO. &QL; 
When: 11:30 tonight. &QL; 
Rating: 3 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`SPACE GHOST COAST TO COAST'
</P>
<P>
   TV simply doesn't get much more dadaist than ``Space Ghost Coast
to Coast,'' a semi-animated and repurposed (and much more inspired
than David E. Kelley's ``Ally'') concoction returning for a fourth
season tonight on the Cartoon Network. Space Ghost, a former
Saturday-morning star-turned-self-satisfied hack, lords over his
talk-show realm with two of his embittered villains as lackeys _
Zorak on keyboards, Moltar in the control room.
</P>
<P>
   Space Ghost insults or, more frequently, ignores his guests
(this month's include Bob Costas, Steven Wright and Hanson) to
reflect, insipidly, on matters imbecilic. S.G. once asked a guest,
``If I hugged you, would you realize that I was simply being
European?'' Long, embarrassed pauses are part of the shtick. It's
as whacked-out as TV gets, but it's also very funny. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The show: ``Space Ghost Coast to Coast'' &QL; 
What: Talk show starring the has-been cartoon hero.  &QL; 
Where: Cartoon Network. &QL; 
When: 11 tonight. &QL; 
Rating: 3 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
