<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG LIKELY TO SIT OUT GAME FOR 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Jeff Garcia will in all likelihood get his
second start for the San Francisco 49ers while Steve Young gives
his head a second week of rest from its Sept. 27 concussion.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear the 49ers are preparing Garcia to start the game in
the Trans World Dome. He got most of the practice time with the
first offense. As for Young, he's scheduled to see his neurologist,
Dr. Gary Steinberg of Stanford Medical Center, on Friday before the
team leaves for St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly the stuff of intrigue. It simply makes sense to sit
Young for another week, especially since the game is on artificial
turf, which is to the head what a windshield is to a bug. The 49ers
want to avoid a big splat
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff is getting most of the snaps to get ready in case he's
the starter,'' coach Steve Mariucci said. ``Steve is getting snaps
here and there. He will be ready to play. He feels better than he
did last week, but we're going to get Jeff ready.''
</P>
<P>
   While all backups theoretically have to be prepared to play,
there's more urgency with Garcia. This is an NFC West game against
a 3-0 Rams team eager to put an end to San Francisco's 17-game
winning streak against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm approaching it as if I'll start,'' Garcia said. ``That's
the only approach I can take. I'm going to put my head into the
game plan, prepare hard and let everything fall into place. ... It
would be good to play two in a row. I'm here because I'm a
competitor. It's fun to be out there making plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg examined Young on Tuesday and saw nothing to indicate
a problem, but nevertheless he wants a return visit Friday to see
if the quarterback has improved from earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be ready to play,'' Young said. ``I want to make
sure I'm ready. I feel better. I just know we'll talk about the
process of healing. That's what I'm most interested in. I tell him
how I'm feeling, he'll say, `That sounds about right.' That's what
I'm looking for. It's all that post-concussion stuff, the
headaches, the sleepiness, the haziness.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said ``there's a certain severity'' to every concussion he
suffers and he is well aware that people are calling for him to
retire. However, ``I hope I'm the best judge, with the experiences
I've had.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci said he hoped to have a definitive answer about his
team's quarterback situation by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Young if he does play? Several scenarios could
unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Young could be active for the game as the No. 3 quarterback; he
could be inactive and in street clothes as the third quarterback;
or, with a roster spot available, the 49ers could sign another
quarterback, as they did Pat Barnes last week before releasing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve has to go through the meeting on Friday,'' Mariucci
said. ``It's another evaluation. He's making progress every day. He
(Steinberg) feels he will be better Friday than he was early in the
week. He seems fine to me. Last week he seemed to be a little
tired. He seems to be livelier, more energetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's enough to be named the starting quarterback,
well, that's a secret.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
