<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDY VIBURNUMS ADAPT WELL TO REGION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ I moved to Humble, Texas, from Michigan two years ago.
I had beautiful, fragrant, 8-foot tall viburnums there. I bought a
viburnum here, but it does not bloom. Are these plants hardy here,
and where can I find the fragrant variety?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, there are viburnums that work fine in our area. This
versatile group of deciduous and evergreen shrubs is underused in
our growing area. Heights vary, as do the leaf textures. Some have
fragrant blooms, and some have good fall color. Birds love the
berries. Some are excellent candidates for a hedge, while others
serve better as specimens.
</P>
<P>
   Viburnums adaptable to our area include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Walter's viburnum (V. obovatum), an evergreen/semievergreen
that matures to 10 or more feet, but it can be kept shorter. The
foliage is dense, small and dark green, contrasting nicely with
large clusters of small white blooms in spring. The birds are drawn
to the purple berries in fall. You'll like the maroon fall color.
Plant in sun or partial sun in a well-draining, organically
enriched soil. Good as a hedge or specimen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rusty blackhaw (V. rufidulum) is a deciduous Texas native that
is excellent for this area. Mature height can reach 25 feet, or it
can be kept as a 10-foot shrub. The foliage is dark and glossy and
finely toothed, and turns red, orange, yellow and purple in fall.
The white flower clusters in spring are showy; the blue-purple
berries draw birds to the garden.
</P>
<P>
   _ Possumhaw (V. nudum) produces olive-green to dark-green,
glossy foliage that turns red in fall and drops in winter. The
spring flowers are white; the fruit is a bluish-black and
attractive to several species of birds. This native tolerates poor
drainage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Arrowwood (V. dentatum) is an upright, multibranched 10-foot
shrub with foliage that turns red, orange, yellow and/or purple in
fall. The small, whitish flowers appear in spring, followed by
bluish-black fruits that attract birds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sweet viburnum (V. odoratissimum) is an evergreen that can
reach a height of about 10 feet. It prefers partial shade and
produces fragrant white flower clusters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Burkwood viburnum (V. x burkwoodi) is a deciduous 6-foot shrub
with pink buds that open to fragrant white flowers. Plant in sun or
partial shade. This one is linked to your favorite, V. carlesii,
supposedly the most fragrant viburnum, but unfortunately not one we
see here. Burkwood viburnum just squeezes into our growing area.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laurustinus (V. tinus) has leathery, dark-green foliage. New
stems are a wine-red; pink buds open to lightly fragrant white
flowers. Some say this is not as summer hardy as other viburnums.
</P>
<P>
   Ask your nurseryman to help you track down one or more of these
species.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the scaly white stuff on my three hibiscus? There are
lots of flakes on the buds; some may fall off before opening. I
have used a pesticide to no avail and have clipped and destroyed
many of the infected buds. Many leaves on one have fallen off.
</P>
<P>
   A: I asked hibiscus experts Pat and Roz Merritt for their advice
on your problem. They think snow scale is the problem, as this pest
has been particularly bothersome this year. But we can't overlook
the possibility of mealy bugs. To determine which of the two is
bugging your plants, consider the following:
</P>
<P>
   Is the scale on the trunk and/or branches sometimes extending up
the stems and onto the leaves _ and on occasion to the buds? If so,
and it resembles powdered sugar or the stuff people spray on their
windows at Christmas for decoration, the pest is snow scale and can
be treated several ways, the Merritts say.
</P>
<P>
   The least toxic, they add, but most time-consuming, is a hard
stream of water actually blasting the insects off. This process
must be repeated until scale is eradicated.
</P>
<P>
   A mixture of equal parts of baby oil and rubbing alcohol,
applied with a toothbrush, is a good treatment, too. Scrub the
pests off, then hose the plant down after waiting 30 minutes. Keep
the plant out of the sun during treatment and at least until hosing
off. Leave the plant in shade much longer if possible. Applications
on cloudy days are ideal.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest treatment is the one the Merritts use _ a vegetable
cooking spray, applied with a light hand and at a spraying distance
of at least 12 inches from the affected area. Be careful. This,
too, must be sprayed in the shade, with the plant kept in the shade
until it can be washed off about 30 minutes after application.
</P>
<P>
   The cooking spray works like a dormant oil and smothers the
scales, but will also fry the plant if left in the sun. Don't kill
what's not there. Spray only where you see the scale.
</P>
<P>
   While snow scale is smooth, mealy bugs look like fuzzy cotton.
Mealy bugs appear on stems and buds and sometimes on succulent
stems. If the infestation is not too severe, dip a cotton swab in
rubbing alcohol and scrub the mealies off.
</P>
<P>
   Note on mushrooms: Gardeners with mushrooms in your lawns _
don't worry. These fungal growths are feeding on decomposing
organic matter, so I take that as a good sign. Organically enriched
soil is one component of a healthy garden.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the mushrooms we find in our gardens are
mycorrhizal. These have a beneficial relationship with green
plants. One such mushroom is the ash bolete, which like many
boletes, are associated with specific trees. The ash bolete has a
gill-like pore structure and light-brown caps that darken with age.
The stalks are short and range from yellow to a deep brown.
</P>
<P>
   This bolete, like many, is edible. In fact, boletes are rated
tops among edible wild mushrooms. Do not eat any mushroom unless
identification is confirmed by a mushroom expert.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There are eight sagos growing on my property. I did not plant
the specimens, but I love their prehistoric look. Unfortunately,
the tips of all the plants but one are brown. They appear healthy
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   A: Brown tips or margins are usually a sign of moisture stress.
These edges are farthest from the plant's roots, so they dry out
first and get water last.
</P>
<P>
   Either your sagos have gotten too dry (at least once), been
overfertilized, or there's some damage to a plant part that's
preventing water from reaching the tips. Hot winds can also burn
leaf tips.
</P>
<P>
   I might guess, however, that with the terrible long dry spells
we've experienced the past three years, your plants are reacting
accordingly. Just try to maintain good moisture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to each unpublished letter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
