<SLUG> BC-HEARST-GEOCAST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST-ARGYLE AND GEOCAST JOIN IN DIGITAL TV SERVICE FOR PCS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hearst-Argyle Television, Inc. and Geocast Network
Systems, Inc., announced Thursday that they plan to deliver
over-the-air digital broadcasting to desktop computers in the 24
U.S. markets served by Hearst-Argyle.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage of digital TV with computers is a major step in
media convergence and means that PC users would be able to easily
download broadcast TV into their desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Hearst-Argyle, the second largest
independent station group owner in the United States, will allow
Geocast to use a portion of Hearst-Argyle television stations'
digital broadcast spectrum to deliver programming such as
personalized news clips, live video traffic reports, real-time
stock quotes and sports highlights, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Geocast is developing the hardware, software and network
infrastructure to deliver the service based on a ``black box''
device that includes an antenna and that connects directly to a PC.
This device will accept live feeds and will also contain hard drive
capacity to store programming for on-demand retrieval.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is believed to be the first arrangement involving
a television broadcaster's expanded use of the digital broadcast
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst-Argyle said it will invest ``up to $10 million'' for an
equity interest in Geocast, a privately held company based in Menlo
Park, Calif. Geocast was formed earlier this year with backing from
three venture capital firms, the Mayfield Fund, Kleiner Perkins
Caufield &AMP; Byers, and Institutional Venture Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst-Argyle Television is a leader in the development of
advanced digital television (DTV) and high-definition digital
television (HDTV). The company's station KITV in Honolulu was the
first U.S. commercially licensed DTV station and Hearst-Argyle now
has four additional DTV stations currently on the air.
</P>
<P>
   All U.S. commercial television stations are required to be
DTV-ready by November 2002, with those serving the top 30 TV
markets to be upgraded by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This marks the creation of a new, convergence-based business
for us,'' said Bob Marbut, chairman and co-chief executive officer
of Hearst-Argyle Television, who will join the Geocast board of
directors. He said the combination would open new revenue streams
for Hearst-Argyle, such as e-commerce, to supplement traditional
broadcast advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Geocast Chief Executive Officer Joe Horowitz said the
partnership enables Geocast to make programming with full-motion
video and CD-quality sound instantly available to PC users. The
Geocast device also allows the PC user to access the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Horowitz, who is a 20-year veteran venture
capitalist, Geocast's principals include Tom Paquin, vice president
of software development; Charles Jablonski, vice president of
network engineering and operations; John Abel, vice president of
business development; Anita Wallgren, vice president, business
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Geocast's directors include Kleiner Perkins partner William
Randolph Hearst III, who is also a Hearst-Argyle director.
</P>
</TEXT>
