<HEADER>
A9600 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-HAPPY-PROFILE-HN     10-07 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HAPPY-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HAPPY' CREW TALKS OF LOVE AND COMEDY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO: A movie about a sleepy little Texas town could be one
of the sleeper comedy hits of the year.
</P>
<P>
   That's the bet Miramax Films made on ``Happy, Texas,'' which
opens this weekend. After this independent film with a cast of
top-flight character actors was shown at the Sundance Festival
early this year, Miramax snapped it up for national distribution.
The studio even paid for reshoots and new scenes the director
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the rousing audience response the revised movie
received at the Toronto International Film Festival last month, the
gamble could pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being shot for a bare-bones $1.7 million, the movie
stars William H. Macy (Fargo), Steve Zahn (Out of Sight), Jeremy
Northam (An Ideal Husband), Illeanna Douglas (Action) and Ally
Walker (Profiler). Needless to say, none of them got their usual
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If `Happy, Texas' goes over the way I think it's going to,
it's money in my pocket at some point (because it will lead to
other things),'' said Macy, who read the script and asked the
thrilled filmmakers to let him be in the film. ``The only rule that
makes sense to me is, do the good stuff, and don't do the bad
stuff. If you do the good stuff, you make a fortune (down the
line).''
</P>
<P>
   Two small-time criminals escape from a Texas prison. They end up
in a small Panhandle town, mistaken for a gay couple that has been
hired to help the town's girls do well in an upcoming pageant.
</P>
<P>
   What is intended as a short-term charade turns into a longtime
commitment, complete with several romances, a bungled bank robbery,
a road trip to a gay dance hall, a Texas sheriff with a broken
heart and some affectionate humor about small-town life.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hate about a lot of films is, we portray middle America
as being dumb, which this movie doesn't,'' Zahn said the day after
the Toronto screening. Zahn, one of Hollywood's hottest comedic
character actors (That Thing You Do, You've Got Mail) had come to
Toronto straight from his farm in New Jersey, where he'd been
cutting hay the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in Happy is pretty smart,'' said Zahn, who plays a
feisty little scrapper named Wayne Wayne Wayne Jr. ``They treat
these complete strangers who are supposedly a homosexual couple by
how they do their work. That's what small towns are kind of like.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be an over-idealized vision, but it plays well in
``Happy, Texas.'' First-time screenwriters and co-producers Ed
Stone and Mark Illsley (who also directed) were careful not to mock
the town natives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to work in Plainview and Lubbock,'' Stone said. ``I
went to school in Plainview and Lubbock. I drove to Amarillo a lot,
and I'd drive though Happy (on Interstate 27, 40 miles south of
Amarillo). I just loved the town. A long time ago one of the grain
elevators was painted pink, so it became one of the landmarks in
the distance.''
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers admitted they also picked the town because they
thought its name would sound great in the title. They wanted to
shoot the movie there, too, but that was not to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real town of Happy was great, just what I wanted,''
Illsley said on a recent visit to Houston. ``I took photos of it _
put the photos on the wall. Every time Ed would write he would
imagine the characters in those locations.''
</P>
<P>
   But budget restrictions forced them to stay in California, where
the town of Piru stood in for Happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to be really careful with my money,'' said Illsley, who
has worked as a stuntman and as second-unit director on films such
as ``Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves'' and ``Rapa Nui.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shooting in Happy would have added $100,000 to $150,000 to my
budget. I said I want to shoot there, but really, I would rather
have an extra day of shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie was shot in 26 days, a short schedule for a feature
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day we did over 50 (camera) setups,'' Zahn said. ``That's
incredible. I was like, `What are we doing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Zahn's character has facial hair at the beginning of the movie
but not the end. He was always trying to remember in which scenes
he needed to put it on or take it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `Mustache? No mustache?' Independent films are
crazy. Jeremy and I were literally on set doing each other's hair,
doing each other's makeup. `OK, get this scar.'''
</P>
<P>
   Zahn and Macy, who plays Chappy, the town sheriff, wanted to do
the film because they loved the script and the affection it had for
the characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed Stone loves all the characters in this movie,'' Macy said.
``He even loves the bad guys. I think that's the key to its
success. They are all so lovingly drawn. It kind of suckers you
into the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially Chappy. I love this guy so much. I wept myself when
I saw it last night. It's a great feeling when your own scene makes
you weepy.''
</P>
<P>
   Macy had another reason for doing the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm way sick of homophobia in the movies and on television,
and this was refreshingly void of that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Illsley and Stone originally had problems getting
the movie financed and cast because no one would read the script.
They spent a frustrating year trying. Finally, they decided to just
lie, telling actors' agents it was already fully financed and they
were ready to start casting. Then the agents started reading the
script and showing it to their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the script that sold the actors,'' Illsley said. ``We
did not make an offer to Bill Macy. The part was written for a
300-pound man. His people called and asked if we would consider
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Macy said, `I'll be in this little body, but when I walk in a
room, I'm going to be the biggest, fattest guy around.'''
</P>
<P>
   Zahn, who was just beginning to make an impact in films at the
time, sent the filmmakers an audition tape that his wife shot in
their kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started the tape by introducing himself and his three dogs,
and had a five-minute conversation about his dogs,'' Stone said.
``We said that's Wayne Wayne Wayne Jr. That's the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Zahn had been auditioning for the other convict, Harry Sawyer, a
part that was eventually played by the tall, handsome and very
English Northam. But that was not how the writers envisioned that
part, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had looked at a lot of American actors, a lot of comics,''
Illsley said.
</P>
<P>
   The part called for Harry to have two romances, one intentional,
one sort of, well, accidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important scene for that character is when he has to
break (another character's) heart,'' Illsley said. ``I needed an
actor that you could see the harder he was pushing to get rid of
(the lover), the more it was killing him. He's hating it.''
</P>
<P>
   They saw Northam romancing Gwyneth Paltrow in ``Emma'' and knew
he was the right guy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `` &LR; Jeremy was the bravest of the actors in our movie,'' Illsley
said. ``Bill Macy read the script and said, `I can do that part.'
Steve Zahn read the script and said, `I can do that part.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeremy Northam reads this script about two escaped convicts in
a small town in Texas in a comedy? e used to come up to us on the
set and go, `Now, why was it you guys wanted me in this?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy, Texas'' is a good example of how small changes can have
a big impact on a movie. Though response to the film was generally
good at Sundance, Illsley and Stone felt it needed improvements
they just couldn't afford to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``In post-production we realized not everything worked as we
imagined it. We noticed one relationship, between Jeremy and Ally
Walker, wasn't working like the rest of the movie. It was very
somber.''
</P>
<P>
   The off-tone took the air out of the movie's high spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scenes Jeremy and Ally shot before were great scenes, but
they didn't work with the movie,'' Zahn said. ``It was a tiny
fine-tuning, and it truly changes everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone and Illsley kept telling Miramax head guys Harvey and Bob
Weinstein that they should reshoot the scenes. To their delight,
the Weinsteins agreed. They reshot about 80 percent of the troubled
relationship, making it more buoyant. They also trimmed a long,
slapstick car chase at the end of the movie and finally reshot the
opening escape, making it faster and funnier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to start the movie quickly, but we also wanted to
start it with a laugh as early as possible so you understood the
movie was a comedy,'' Illsley said.
</P>
<P>
   They had only one day to reshoot the opening _ Zahn had to fly
in overnight from another film set in Canada and do it with no
sleep _ so they tossed subtlety out the window and started with a
dead-armadillo sight gag and a knock-knock joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' Stone said in shameless self-mockery, ``that's genius
writing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
