<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS FACE A HAPLESS DENVER TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK FAINARU-WADA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ They're throwing coins or batteries _ or
battery-powered coins? _ at their own players. They're being given
the bird by the backup quarterback. They're booing incessantly,
they're shredding their once-genius coach on all the call-in shows
and, for goodness sakes, they're leaving early.
</P>
<P>
   These things happen everywhere because, frankly, these are the
things fans do because, frankly, fans are nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Except in Denver, where they're not supposed to be nuts because,
frankly, they're supposed to be giddy over back-to-back Super Bowls
and, at the very least, understanding that you just don't replace
John Elway every day.
</P>
<P>
   But, a funny thing has happened in the land of Mile High.
</P>
<P>
   Funny strange, not funny ha-ha. The fans are revolting _
figuratively and literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been one of the very weirdest stories in Denver
sports history,'' said Sandy Clough, a popular radio personality
who has been on the scene for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Simply, the Broncos are bad right now. And seemingly getting
worse as they head to Oakland for a Sunday meeting against the
Raiders that just doesn't feel right: Oakland looking formidable
and hopeful in the AFC West, Denver looking futile and hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   First, Elway retired. Then coach Mike ``The Mastermind``
Shanahan stirred things up with a preseason yanking of veteran
Bubby Brister in favor of 24-year-old Brian Griese, who threw all
of three passes during his rookie season last year; Brister
responded by ripping Shanahan in the news media. Then last week,
running back Terrell Davis, the man most responsible for finally
getting Elway a Super Bowl ring, was lost for the season with a
knee injury. And, finally, just Wednesday, Shanahan reversed field
and decided Brister should be his starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Said Brister, hours after being named the new starter: ``Terrell
Davis is out, we're 0-4, we're at the Raiders this week. ... It
doesn't get much tougher than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a thought: Maybe the Raiders are exactly what the Broncos
need right now. Maybe a little genuine hatred and bitterness,
wrapped in a tidy package of bile, are just what Shanahan and his
team need to begin to revive themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe the Broncos can't even muster that much. In a
Sports Illustrated story this week, the ubiquitous anonymous player
on a team whose wheels are coming off was quoted saying that the
Broncos are finished for the season and they could wind up 0-8 by
the time they hit November.
</P>
<P>
   To which Shanahan responded, ``I don't know if someone said
that, but if someone feels like we're gonna be 0-8 or we're gonna
wind up 3-13, please let me know. I'll send you outta here so
quick, I don't care if it's a bus ticket or a plane ticket, just
let me know.''
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed in Denver, where eight months ago the town
was an extra mile high over its second consecutive Super Bowl win
and clinging to hopes that Elway would try for a three-peat.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Elway opted for the serenity of his 5-iron, and now
the Broncos are everybody's fodder. Really, 0-8 doesn't sound so
ludicrous when you consider the next four: At Oakland, home vs.
Green Bay, at New England, home vs. Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   As Raiders linebacker Richard Harvey said, ``They had a machine
for the last two years. Now they're just a team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
