<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARR WENT FAR, THANKS TO `FRANK' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, after a decade in show business, Teri Garr
hadn't gone far.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, she'd graduated from being a dancer in Elvis movies to
being an actress.
</P>
<P>
   But most of her gigs were guest spots on TV shows (``Batman,''
``Star Trek''), and she had only one line in ``Head,'' the Monkees
movie co-written by a friend from her acting class, Jack Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   Then Garr joined a ``cattle call'' to play Inga, a scientist's
assistant in Mel Brooks' ``Young Frankenstein.''
</P>
<P>
   She won the part, the comedy was a smash, and her career finally
took off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first big movie,'' Garr said. ``I can't say if I'd
have gotten (roles in) `Close Encounters' or `Tootsie' without it.
There are a million girls who come to Hollywood every day trying to
get into movies. I just finally got my chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Garr hadn't seen ``Young Frankenstein'' in years until she heard
it was getting a reissue on video. Then she caught it on cable with
her 5-year-old daughter and felt it ``still holds up. It's still
funny.''
</P>
<P>
   In stores this week, the video ($14.98 on VHS, $34.98 on DVD)
adds 17 minutes of unused scenes and five minutes of outtakes at
the end of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   In one such scene, Baron Frankenstein's will is read for eager
relatives. In another, his scientist grandson (Gene Wilder) meets a
street violinist playing a melody that affects him strangely.
</P>
<P>
   After he moves to his granddad's castle to carry on his work _
animating dead tissue _ Wilder is seen in new footage slyly wooing
Garr outside her door at night. Later they embrace as she asks _ as
if it's a sexy question _ ``How fast is the speed of light?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even remember those scenes,'' Garr said. ``It's like a
dream. Is that me?''
</P>
<P>
   But she does recall favorite scenes, such as when Wilder enlists
her help in opening a trapdoor. (``Put _ the candle _ back!'')
</P>
<P>
   Wilder wrote the script, but Brooks improvised while directing
and got partial credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel did a great job,'' Garr said. ``But Gene deserves a lot of
credit. He kind of held back Mel's pie-in-the-face humor to do a
more witty story.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge was keeping a straight face.
</P>
<P>
   One outtake shows the cast breaking up as Madeline Kahn arrives
and Igor (Marty Feldman) bites her fur. Another shows the cast
traipsing down stairs in a curtain call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laughed a lot,'' Garr said. ``Mel would have us doing all
this funny business, then expect us to work without laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept having to say, `Can we just do this scene? Will
everyone please stop laughing?' And that just made us laugh
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its zany humor, Brooks gave ``Young Frankenstein'' a
strong feel for the original 1931 horror movie starring Boris
Karloff.
</P>
<P>
   On a Fox soundstage, Brooks reproduced the original castle sets,
complete with props. (Their designer had kept them for years in his
garage.) He also shot in black-and-white, a commercial no-no even
in '74.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Brooks didn't have to fight the studio to get
black-and-white, Garr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd just done `Blazing Saddles,' a big hit, and Mel pretty
much got what he wanted,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox playfully calls this the ``25 1/2 anniversary'' of ``Young
Frankenstein.'' Actually, it premiered at the end of 1974, making
this the 24 3/4 anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Garr, 49, has been performing since she joined a dance company
at age 14.
</P>
<P>
   Other credits include ``Dumb &AMP; Dumber,'' ``Michael'' and ``Full
Moon in Blue Water.''
</P>
<P>
   She also co-starred with Hilary Duff in ``Casper Meets Wendy'';
appeared in this year's Watergate comedy, ``Dick''; and provides a
computer's voice for the upcoming sci-fi film ``Supernova.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about it for now _ just being a parent keeps me busy,''
said Garr, who is divorced. ``I'm one of those people who had a
career first and then decided to have children.''
</P>
<P>
   She often sees Brooks, who's a neighbor, and sometimes runs into
fellow cast members Peter Boyle or Cloris Leachman (Frau Bluecher).
But Garr hasn't seen Wilder in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got along fine, though,'' she said. ``We had fun. We
laughed so hard making that movie that we almost couldn't do the
scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`THE THIRTEENTH FLOOR' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1999, R, Columbia TriStar, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD priced
for sales &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hall has a problem.
</P>
<P>
   His boss, who created a computer-reality existence set in 1937
Los Angeles, has been murdered, and it looks like Doug did it.
Seeking answers, he explores the cyberworld like a computer-geek
gumshoe.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Thirteenth Floor'' also has a problem: It's dull.
</P>
<P>
   As Douglas, Craig Bierko has all the charisma of a flat tire,
and the flimsy plot is stretched over a premise that lacks much
meaning or even cheap thrills.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Dark City,'' ``The Thirteenth Floor'' fashions a handsome
otherworld, and Vincent D'Onofrio is reliably sinister as a '30s
bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   But Gretchen Mol is wasted in a love-interest part, and none of
the equation adds up to much. Try ``The Matrix'' for better
cyberthrills, or ``The Maltese Falcon'' for a better noirish
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MUSIC ON DVD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now that Depeche Mode has hit the big time _ getting its music
on a Gap ad _ the band hits DVD with its ``The Videos 86-98''
collection, running two hours and costing $24.99.
</P>
<P>
   The Depeche Mode work was formerly issued on tape.
</P>
<P>
   And Madonna has a brand-spanking new ``Video Collection 92-99,''
with 14 music videos.
</P>
<P>
   They include ``Beautiful Stranger,'' ``Erotica,'' ``Ray of
Light'' and ``Drowned World/Substitute for Love,'' previously not
available in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On tape the 68-minute array costs $19.98; on DVD it's $24.99.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
