<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, Oct. 8
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-MOMA-MILLENIUM (New York) _ The Museum of Modern Art has
launched its contribution to the millenium furor: a 17-month series
of exhibitions under the umbrella title ``MOMA 2000.'' In addition
to being a summing up of this venerable institution's past, it is
also a rehearsal for its future. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENTE-GUGGENHEIM (New York) _ Francesco Clemente is the
youngest artist to be given the full-rotunda treatment by the
Guggenheim Museum. In recent years, Claes Oldenburg, Ellsworth
Kelly and Robert Rauschenberg have filled the place to overflowing
and, in particular have imprinted the rotunda with an indelible
sense of their different styles. Now Clemente, the Italian painter
of East-meets-West dream images that delve into the mind, the body
and many forms of love, is taking his turn. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   INGRES-FRENCH-ART (Undated) _ Before he was the great man of
French art, Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres drew pencil portraits to
make money. They were souvenirs on letter-size sheets of paper. He
was living in Italy. He hoped the drawings would lead to more
important commissions, and sometimes they did. He also drew friends
for pleasure, but generally he regarded portrait drawing of this
sort as a waste of time. The people who commissioned him often had
no idea who he was or what they had bought, and many of the
portraits disappeared or turned up years later in the hands of
families who didn't realize that they had inherited works of value.
By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
