<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLASTIC-SURGEON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLASTIC SURGEON SAYS CASE HAS RUINED HIS PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Following the post-op death of a patient, the
once flourishing practice of prominent San Francisco plastic
surgeon John Emery has dwindled to the point where he now wants to
close his clinic, which pioneered outpatient cosmetic surgery in
Northern California, and become what he calls a ``country doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   In a disciplinary hearing this week to determine his
professional future, Emery testified that he was devastated
professionally, personally and financially by the baffling death of
Myra Ruskin, who died overnight in Emery's clinic after face-lift
surgery in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Her death was caused by a massive overdose of Demerol, the
medical examiner ruled, but authorities could not establish how she
got the lethal dose or who administered it.
</P>
<P>
   Emery testified that he feels no responsibility for Ruskin's
death.
</P>
<P>
   The physician, who has practiced in San Francisco for more than
three decades, testified that fellow doctors had stopped referring
patients to him and that patients had stopped seeking his care. So
far this year, he said, he has operated on only 11 patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I were very high profile in the community,''
Emery, 67, said. ``It's been very difficult for us to adjust to the
social discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Once society fixtures and charity fund-raisers, Emery and his
wife, Deborah, a former beauty queen, are now undergoing the
indignity of being in ``extensive debt'' of hundreds of thousands
of dollars, Emery said. His malpractice carrier has a $300,000
claim against him, he said, and he owes $24,609 in back rent for
his clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an incredible experience to see how society that
once loved you abandons you,'' said Emery, who voiced pride in his
years of community service. ``We've lost our friends, our social
contacts, respect in the community both in San Francisco and in
Marin County. ... I've lost a lot of my dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   In its case against the physician, the Medical Board of
California says Emery's care of Ruskin, ``constituted repeated acts
of negligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruskin, a licensed family therapist, sought the $21,900 face
lift for her 57th birthday. Her four-hour surgery seemed
uneventful, but Ruskin died during the night as the medical
assistant slept in a bed next to her. Ruskin had paid extra for the
overnight stay.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Emery settled a civil lawsuit filed by
Ruskin's family. The terms of the settlement are confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy attorney general Lawrence Mercer said Emery violated
regulations concerning the use of medical assistants. During the
hearing, the assistant testified that she used her discretion,
based on ``standing orders,'' to give Ruskin a 75 milligram
injection of Demerol. The assistant said she could give between 50
and 100 mg of the painkiller depending on her assessment of a
patient's discomfort. Emery was not at the clinic when she gave the
injection, she testified.
</P>
<P>
   Emery also violated accreditation rules, standard of care
regulations and medical record-keeping statutes, Mercer charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is concerned that plastic surgery is not safe, that
plastic surgery clinics are not safe,'' Mercer told the court.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, Emery agreed not to challenge two of the
state's three accusations: that he committed gross negligence in
his care of Ruskin, and that he aided and abetted in the unlicensed
practice of medicine by allowing an unlicensed medical assistant to
serve as overnight caretaker for Ruskin.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he had mitigating evidence, presenting other doctors
who touted Emery's surgical skills and testified they too were
unaware of regulations requiring the presence of a physician when
medical assistants give injections.
</P>
<P>
   They also bolstered Emery's argument that medication logs were
not exempt of ``human error.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As surgeons, we believe we are God, but we are frequently
proven not to be,'' said Dr. Charles Allen Wall, a cardiovascular
surgeon who practices in Emery's medical building.
</P>
<P>
   He attributed discrepancies in his drug records, and missing
records, to clerical errors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
