<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9622 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-JAMES-BROWN-HNS     10-07 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-JAMES-BROWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ORIGINAL FUNK SOUL BROTHER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Brown is a man with a lot on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   During the course of a roughly 20-minute interview, he offers
often-unprovoked musings on education (``We gotta give those
teachers a pat on the back''); the Vietnam War (``We're all people
that got a stake in America, and we love it, and we fight for
it''); and how today's performers should go to music school before
thinking about making records.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the 66-year-old Godfather of Soul is also ready to
offer plenty of thoughts on his own music, even before the first
question is asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papa's got a brand new bag! It's a man's world!'' he exclaims,
calling from his offices in Augusta, Ga. ``You know `Try Me' was
voted the No. 1 love song of all time? That's a great honor. I love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh, OK. So Brown is a decidedly happy camper, and why not? He
has plenty of reasons to be: Soul Brother No. 1 is among pop
music's undisputed great influences, one of the most important
musicians in the rock era.
</P>
<P>
   With his stamina and impeccable timing on display in front of an
audience, Brown's live shows are known to sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy (performing) because God has been good to me and the
people have been good to me. I still get excited 'cause I'm human
and the good Lord keeps me human,'' Brown said. ``The countries and
the cities need me to perform because it puts you in an `up' mode.
I perform because it's a need. Financially, I don't have to work,
but all the input I can give to this country, I'm gonna give it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such patriotism! Such pride! Guess Brown really meant every word
when he sang the 1986 Top 10 hit ``Living in America.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't always been an easy road, however. Brown's career has
been marked by legal and personal troubles since the mid-'70s.
There have been problems with the IRS, a prison sentence in the
late '80s for illegal possession of drugs and firearms, and
hospitalization in 1998 for an addiction to pain-killers.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown doesn't want to talk about all that. He'd rather
reminisce about his early days in Houston, when he played such
venues as the Coliseum, Rockefeller's, the Continental Ballroom, El
Dorado Ballroom and Jones Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go waaaay back when nothin' was built in Houston,'' Brown
said. ``I used to live in the Third Ward and all those places.
Houston's always been one of my pet places. I always wanna say
thanks to people in Texas for lookin' out for me and helpin' me
through those rough years.''
</P>
<P>
   The rough years included a time before hits such as ``Good Good
Lovin','' ``I'll Go Crazy,'' ``Think,'' ``Night Train'' and ``I Got
You'' (I Feel Good), when Brown worked as a janitor at a school in
Georgia. It was then when he recorded his first hit, ``Please,
Please, Please.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A janitor,'' Brown said with disbelief. ``What could ya do
with a seventh-grade education? Nothing. Every mornin' at 8 o'clock
... I'd play for the kids before they got to school. When I got a
decent meal and got my rent paid, that way I could buy a car, I
knew (music) was the thing for me. I thank God for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since music became the thing for him, Brown has influenced
countless artists over the decades, many of whom sampled Brown's
hooks and drew on his sounds for their own music. Brown insists
that he doesn't mind, even if he doesn't always get credited for
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I really took over with `Papa's Bag' in 1965, from that
time on it's been all James Brown. Ninety-five percent of the music
_ country, gospel, everything _ is using my licks,'' Brown said.
``That changed all the music around.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got that James Brown lick in almost everything you do. I
don't care whether they like me or not. If I was a greedy man, I
would throw a patent on anything from '65 on and collect zillions
of dollars. But I don't want that. I don't need it. I'm fine with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that does bother Brown is the overall state of today's
music. In the gospel according to Brown, America's sound lags far
behind the music coming from England, Germany and Japan, where he
can still pack in arena-size crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm familiar with all the artists (today), but I tell ya, I'm
not gonna talk about anybody, bein' the Godfather,'' Brown said.
``We're gonna bring back records that make sense. Stop the cursin'
and degrading the ladies. They (today's musicians) need some
hands-on training, and they ain't got that. They take one note and
make a whole song. You can't do that. They really don't know
anything about music _ can't play and dealin' with these
synthesizers. They need to go to music school.''
</P>
<P>
   From here, the inevitable (at least in Brown's mind) segue into
education comes into focus. Academics first, then music, then
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to put music back in the school 'cause music is not a
way of life but the way of life right now,'' Brown said. ``It
should be the first thing to give you a second shot at life. I tell
no kid to quit school and go to music, but I tell 'em to take music
in school 'cause you got 'em like a sponge at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, it seems, has soaked up plenty himself. But alas, the
time has come to say good-bye. As expected, he offers a last-minute
parting thought:
</P>
<P>
   ``May I close out by sayin',`God Bless America'?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you may.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
