<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LESBIAN-COPS-ART-NYT &LR;      10-07 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LESBIAN-COPS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A GAY OFFICER, FIRST LOVE, THEN MALICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JOYCE WADLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It wasn't actually their idea to tell the newspapers
about what they call their wedding, say New York City Police
Officers Elizabeth Bryant and Marilyn Trapanotto. The president of
the Gay Officers' Action League approached them a couple of days
before the ceremony in June 1997, saying it would be a good thing,
so they agreed. As it turned out, Ms. Bryant and Ms. Trapanotto
liked the New York Post article about two lady cops who ``tied the
lavender knot'' so much, they framed it.
</P>
<P>
   A week later the honeymoon, you might say, was over.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Trapanotto, then working the Manhattan North scooter
task force in Central Park, had no problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee, Trap, back so soon? How was the honeymoon?'' Or, ``You're
married? That's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Officer Bryant was not so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to work in the 42d Precinct in the Bronx, she found an
obscene poster of a male bodybuilder on which someone had
superimposed Officer Bryant's face. The harassment, Officer Bryant
says, went on for more than a year; officers refused to ride with
her, and at one point an officer put his hands around her throat.
When she complained to her superiors, she says, she was cited for
bad behavior. Now Ms. Bryant, claiming her civil rights were
violated, has brought a $5 million lawsuit against the city, the
department, three officers and Commissioner Howard Safir.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did the Police Department turn their backs on her,
they punished her for coming forward,'' says her lawyer, Joseph
Tacopina.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy Police Commissioner for Public Information, Marilyn
Mode, says she cannot comment on the suit, but did say:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to point out that it was Police Commissioner Safir who
said `Why shouldn't gay police officers be allowed to march in
uniform at the Gay Pride parade?' We recruit vigorously in the gay
community. And actually _ I'm happy to fax it to you _ in the Sept.
27 issue of Newsweek, the NYPD was listed as one of the
gay-friendly police forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people have the stomach for bringing a lawsuit, some don't,
and if you had to choose who would prefer not to sue, you would
probably pick Police Officer Bryant, 34, a woman who goes out of
her way to please.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's offensive, I can take it down,'' she says of a Picasso
poster of a nude woman in her apartment, in the Gravesend section
of Brooklyn, as the photographer is deciding where to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Trapanotto, 35, is the more aggressive and protective.
She wears the short, slicked-back hair favored by juvenile
delinquents of the 50's, she chain-smokes Marlboros, and her accent
is pure Brooklyn _ so powerful that her Southern-born companion has
picked it up. It is sometimes difficult for her to restrain herself
from answering for Officer Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   When Officer Bryant found the obscene poster, it was Officer
Trapanotto who sagely told her to save the evidence. She loves the
department, Officer Trapanotto says, but she couldn't take what the
harassment was doing to her partner.
</P>
<P>
   What is the more important question for this couple: When did
you know you wanted to be a police officer, or when did you know
the nature of your sexuality?
</P>
<P>
   Both women, at any rate, knew they were gay when they were still
in elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Trapanotto, whose strict Sicilian-born father was a
construction worker, reports that three of the five children in her
family were gay. She married at 19 ``to get out of the house,''
divorced, had a stint in the Navy, then joined the force in 1994.
There were occasional comments, and when there were, Officer
Trapanotto confronted them on the spot. ``Oh, she's a dyke'' she
might hear during roll call. ``And what's the problem with that?''
she'd snap back.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Bryant grew up in a Baptist household in the small Smoky
Mountain city of Franklin, N.C. Her father had a five-and-dime
store, her mother kept the books. She hoped to be an actress. After
graduating from high school, she told her family she was gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lousy experience, to be honest,'' she says. ``They
kicked me out of the house. I said: `OK, no problem. I understand
this makes you uncomfortable, I'll move out.' It wasn't as bad as
it sounds. I still went home on vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   The career in acting was brief _ if you look carefully, you'll
see her in a crowd scene in ``Weekend at Bernie's'' _ but it led to
undercover work rooting out theft in New York City department
stores. That led to the police force. Officer Bryant met Officer
Trapanotto in a coffee bar in Greenwich Village four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just about to graduate from the Academy; she was a
cop,'' Officer Bryant says. ``You know how it is when you're about
to graduate; you can't stop talking about it, and she listened, she
was terrific. I was on my way to meet a blind date and I never got
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Why did they feel they had to have the wedding ceremony?
</P>
<P>
   ``I love her,'' Officer Trapanotto says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The week we got married was very uplifting,'' Officer Bryant
says. ``It was Gay Pride week, we marched for the very first time
in uniform ..'' Officer Trapanotto, interrupting again:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very, very special to show you're proud to be a gay
police officer, not only a gay couple.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1519EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
