<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9666 &Cx1f; taf-z
* u 7 &LR;      10-07 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMEY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT8 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7  
 `THE   LIMEY'9: TOURING SHOW-BUSINESS ROYALTY AND ITS UNDERWORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (  Eds10: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (  af11)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The flinty modernism that looked so bold on screen in John
Boorman's &UR; 12 &LR;  1967 nouveau-noir classic ``Point Blank'' has become
innocently nostalgic in Steven Soderbergh's hands. ``The
Limey &UR; 9 &LR; ,'' which could be called the latest directorial oddity
from Soderbergh if that were not such a redundancy, is a piquant
throwback to that style.
</P>
<P>
   And among Soderbergh's widely varied films (``sex, lies and
videotape,'' ``Kafka,'' ``The Underneath,'' ``Schizopolis &UR; 13 &LR; ,''
``Out of Sight''), this one actually has the best chance of
becoming anyone's sentimental favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the revenge plot: this film's real goal is revisiting
two charismatic stars of the '60s &UR; 14 &LR; , Terence (``Billy Budd'')
Stamp and Peter ``Easy Rider'' Fonda. For walking Proustian
evocations of the era, you can't get much more iconic than this.
</P>
<P>
   Stamp plays the title role furiously, with single-minded
intensity, wild blue eyes and a stentorian roar shown off in the
film's early moments. Having already made a memorable drag comeback
in ``The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert,'' he takes a
more traditional route this time.
</P>
<P>
   Stamp is cast as an English ex-convict named Wilson, a name that
is a holdover of the character he played while starring with Julie
Christie &UR; 15 &LR;  in Ken Loach's &UR; 16 &LR;  1967 ``Poor Cow.'' Glimpses of
young, dreamily beautiful Stamp and his no less imposing latter-day
presence are used by Soderbergh with touching efficacy.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay by Lem &UR; 17 &LR;  Dobbs sends Wilson on the trail of a
super-sleek record producer named Terry Valentine. Fonda plays that
role with what seems to be a sense memory of every Hollywood-style
rich hipster he ever encountered, which is to say that he gets
right into the spirit of things.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth mentioning that both these actors are extremely
engaging memoirists, and that Stamp, whose tales of being on top of
the world in Austin Powers' London are particularly vivid, has a
cookbook to his credit too.
</P>
<P>
   What pits Wilson and Valentine against one another is the death
of Wilson's daughter, Jennifer, who was one of Valentine's many
young girlfriends. Like each of the film's characters, she is
studied by Soderbergh from every possible angle, seen back and
forth through time and from assorted perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   The film's dissecting tactics are so relentless that Stamp
delivers one monologue with a different shot for each sentence,
which ought to be terribly distracting. The filmmaker's &UR; 18 &LR; 
technical experiments do intrude, but they suit the meticulously
hard, distant tone of the material.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Point Blank'' and those tactics of Jean-Luc Godard that
are also echoed here, sharp juxtapositions and architecturally
daunting settings can be as memorable as the people. As shot with
cool panache by Ed Lachman &UR; 19 &LR; , ``The Limey' &UR; 9 &LR; ' offers a guided
tour through the upper echelons of show-business royalty, and into
the underworld where their dirty work gets done.
</P>
<P>
   Enlivening the periphery of the film are Barry Newman as
Valentine's lawyer and fixer, Nicky &UR; 20 &LR;  Katt &UR; 21 &LR;  as a
ponytailed &UR; 22 &LR;  hit man, Luis Guzman &UR; 23 &LR;  as a reluctant accomplice
and Amelia Heinle &UR; 24 &LR;  as Valentine's latest arm candy. Stamp's
sardonic, relentless Limey &UR; 9 &LR;  is enough to make mincemeat of them
all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   THE LIMEY
</P>
<P>
   Rating: `The Limey'9 is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity, violence and
partial nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Steven Soderbergh; written by Lem &UR; 17 &LR;  Dobbs;
director of photography, Ed Lachman &UR; 19 &LR; ; edited by Sarah Flack &UR; 25 &LR; ;
music by Cliff Martinez; production designer, Gary Frutkoff &UR; 26 &LR; ;
produced by John Hardy and Scott Kramer &UR; 27 &LR; ; released by Artisan
Entertainment. Running time: 89 minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Terence Stamp (Wilson), Lesley Ann Warren (Elaine), Luis
Guzman &UR; 23 &LR;  (Ed), Barry Newman (Avery), Joe Dallesandro &UR; 28 &LR;  (Uncle
John), Nicky &UR; 20 &LR;  Katt &UR; 21 &LR;  (Stacy), Peter Fonda (Valentine), Amelia
Heinle &UR; 24 &LR;  (Adhara &UR; 29 &LR; ) and Melissa George (Jennifer). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1602EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WIVES-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     10-07 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIVES-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIVE WIVES, THREE SECRETARIES AND ME:' THE MAN, THE TEXAN AND THE 
 MULTIMILLIONAIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (Production notes at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By ANITA GATES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time Thomas Blake is seen on screen, in what appears
to be a tiny office, he looks like an elderly small-city insurance
salesman, the kind of guy who never got the promotion he deserved
and can't afford to retire. In fact, he's an 89-year-old Texas
multimillionaire with a photograph on the wall of himself with
Clark Gable and Gary Cooper on a hunting trip in Mexico. This
information lends a lot of weight to Blake's business advice to his
daughter: ``Whatever you do, make money. Because that's the only
recognition you're ever going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake is the subject of ``Five Wives, Three Secretaries and
Me,'' an oddly charming documentary written and directed by his
daughter Tessa, whose motives may not all have been noble.
</P>
<P>
   Blake's self-satisfied tone is clear from the first scene, when
he starts telling Tessa how to do her job (making the movie). When
asked if he has any regrets in life, he says with a grin, ``A few
girls I missed along the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Of those he didn't miss, four of his five wives aren't talking
(Ms. Blake's mother, Sandra Tessman Blake, the fourth wife, is the
exception) but the secretaries are.
</P>
<P>
   The other wives are shown, in photographs or filmed at parties.
The current Mrs. Blake, Muffet (whom people keep accidentally
calling Muffin), is a baby-faced blonde of a certain age, seen at a
family Christmas gathering. Sandra, who married 56-year-old Tommy
when she was 22, is a self-proclaimed character who put Tessa into
boarding school in Scotland when she was 7 and neglected to tell
her when she and Blakie, as she calls her ex-husband, got a
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Blake, the filmmaker, sees all of her father's marrying and
remarrying and the resulting extended family as comical, at least
on one level. A relative is introduced as ``my
ex-half-sister-in-law.'' People in the film have superimposed ID's
on screen like ``my father's fifth wife's ex-husband.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, ``Five Wives'' could be seen as a childish project
intended to do nothing more than expose Daddy for what he is:
womanizing and apparently racist. In fact, Blake disapprovingly
refers to ``the mixing of the races'' and says of blacks, ``They
don't assimilate very well.'' He even defends a relative who was a
member of the Ku Klux Klan and, as one might guess, does not
approve of Tessa's longtime boyfriend, who is black. But Ms.
Blake's film does convey a sense of the man and, without overt
commentary, a sense of the wealthy Texas culture in which she grew
up.
</P>
<P>
   The film loses energy at times, but it maintains its point of
view, and there's something impressive, playful back-and-forth
editing in which one person starts a sentence and another person
(in another setting and time) appears to finish it. Blake, despite
having agreed to be filmed almost naked doing his daily exercises,
emerges with a certain amount of dignity intact. Or is it just
because we know he's filthy rich?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `FIVE WIVES, THREE SECRETARIES AND ME'
</P>
<P>
   Directed and produced by Tessa Blake; released by Castle Hill
Productions. Running time: 80 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Muffet Criner Adickes Blake, Sandra Tessman Blake, Betty
``Boop'' Blake, Sharon Simons, Harriet Leasey, Louise Turner,
Barbara Tucker, Virginia Keasling and Chelo Maris.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
