<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMEY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LIMEY': TOURING SHOW-BUSINESS ROYALTY AND ITS UNDERWORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The flinty modernism that looked so bold on screen in John
Boorman's 1967 nouveau-noir classic ``Point Blank'' has become
innocently nostalgic in Steven Soderbergh's hands. ``The Limey,''
which could be called the latest directorial oddity from Soderbergh
if that were not such a redundancy, is a piquant throwback to that
style.
</P>
<P>
   And among Soderbergh's widely varied films (``sex, lies and
videotape,'' ``Kafka,'' ``The Underneath,'' ``Schizopolis,'' ``Out
of Sight''), this one actually has the best chance of becoming
anyone's sentimental favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the revenge plot: this film's real goal is revisiting
two charismatic stars of the '60s, Terence (``Billy Budd'') Stamp
and Peter ``Easy Rider'' Fonda. For walking Proustian evocations of
the era, you can't get much more iconic than this.
</P>
<P>
   Stamp plays the title role furiously, with single-minded
intensity, wild blue eyes and a stentorian roar shown off in the
film's early moments. Having already made a memorable drag comeback
in ``The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert,'' he takes a
more traditional route this time.
</P>
<P>
   Stamp is cast as an English ex-convict named Wilson, a name that
is a holdover of the character he played while starring with Julie
Christie in Ken Loach's 1967 ``Poor Cow.'' Glimpses of young,
dreamily beautiful Stamp and his no less imposing latter-day
presence are used by Soderbergh with touching efficacy.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay by Lem Dobbs sends Wilson on the trail of a
super-sleek record producer named Terry Valentine. Fonda plays that
role with what seems to be a sense memory of every Hollywood-style
rich hipster he ever encountered, which is to say that he gets
right into the spirit of things.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth mentioning that both these actors are extremely
engaging memoirists, and that Stamp, whose tales of being on top of
the world in Austin Powers' London are particularly vivid, has a
cookbook to his credit too.
</P>
<P>
   What pits Wilson and Valentine against one another is the death
of Wilson's daughter, Jennifer, who was one of Valentine's many
young girlfriends. Like each of the film's characters, she is
studied by Soderbergh from every possible angle, seen back and
forth through time and from assorted perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   The film's dissecting tactics are so relentless that Stamp
delivers one monologue with a different shot for each sentence,
which ought to be terribly distracting. The filmmaker's technical
experiments do intrude, but they suit the meticulously hard,
distant tone of the material.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Point Blank'' and those tactics of Jean-Luc Godard that
are also echoed here, sharp juxtapositions and architecturally
daunting settings can be as memorable as the people. As shot with
cool panache by Ed Lachman, ``The Limey'' offers a guided tour
through the upper echelons of show-business royalty, and into the
underworld where their dirty work gets done.
</P>
<P>
   Enlivening the periphery of the film are Barry Newman as
Valentine's lawyer and fixer, Nicky Katt as a ponytailed hit man,
Luis Guzman as a reluctant accomplice and Amelia Heinle as
Valentine's latest arm candy. Stamp's sardonic, relentless Limey is
enough to make mincemeat of them all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   THE LIMEY
</P>
<P>
   Rating: `The Limey' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity, violence and
partial nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Steven Soderbergh; written by Lem Dobbs; director of
photography, Ed Lachman; edited by Sarah Flack; music by Cliff
Martinez; production designer, Gary Frutkoff; produced by John
Hardy and Scott Kramer; released by Artisan Entertainment. Running
time: 89 minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Terence Stamp (Wilson), Lesley Ann Warren (Elaine), Luis
Guzman (Ed), Barry Newman (Avery), Joe Dallesandro (Uncle John),
Nicky Katt (Stacy), Peter Fonda (Valentine), Amelia Heinle (Adhara)
and Melissa George (Jennifer). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
