<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9672 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-HEARTS-SPI &LR;      10-07 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HEARTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUNKY `RANDOM HEARTS' MISSES MANY A BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, director Sydney Pollack kept us laughing, on
the edge of our seats and grabbing for the Kleenex with masterful
cinematic creations such as ``Out of Africa,'' ``Tootsie,'' ``Three
Days of the Condor,'' ``The Way We Were'' and ``They Shoot Horses,
Don't They?''
</P>
<P>
   One thread that linked a number of his movies was that reluctant
movie idol, Robert Redford, who was a frequent Pollack leading man
(the pair made seven films together over three decades).
</P>
<P>
   In the '90s, Pollack gravitated toward a new star, Harrison
Ford, who first stoically forged through a static remake of the
Billy Wilder classic ``Sabrina'' for the director. And if you're
one of the few who hasn't glimpsed the thousands of TV commercials
that tell us everything we need to know (and more) about ``Random
Hearts,'' well, Ford stars in it as well.
</P>
<P>
   Word had it that the film was a yawn prior to its preview
screening earlier this week, and word on the street has proved
correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Random Hearts'' is a long, clunky, slow-paced, talky film that
could have been an insightful look at how different people respond
to sudden tragedy and the ghosts that result, but as scripted by
the usually reliable Kurt Luedtke (he won an Oscar for the ``Out of
Africa'' screenplay), it doesn't have much to say.
</P>
<P>
   It depends purely on the star power of its leads, Ford and
English actor Kristin Scott Thomas who, try as they may, don't
generate much heat outside of a single scene that's set in a car
and comes, almost humorously, right out of the blue.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Random Hearts'' Ford is Dutch van den Broeck, a sergeant in
the D.C. Internal Affairs Department who lives a nice life with his
beautiful wife, Peyton (Susanna Thompson). She's the top catalog
designer for Saks Fifth Avenue and has suddenly been called away to
Miami because a photo shoot isn't going well. Across town, busy
U.S. Rep. Kay Chandler (Scott Thomas) is saying goodbye to her
husband, high-powered lawyer Cullen (Peter Coyote), who is about to
fly to New York on business.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch and Kay go through their day trying to, respectively,
thwart a standoff and raise money for re-election. But their
spouses have deceived them; these two apparent strangers have been
having an affair for some time and are jetting off to a hotel in
Miami for an illicit weekend. But they never arrive because the
plane they're on crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world they would have never met,'' says the
film's tagline. But Dutch and Kay do meet and, bound by
incomprehension and grief, have an unlikely romance that helps them
sort through not only the twisted metal of the plane, but also the
twisted mettle of their marriages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Random Hearts'' inhabits that world of civilized perfection.
These are perfect-looking people with great jobs, stylishly neat
apartments and gorgeous clothes. And it's easy to be distracted by
all that gloss and polish because it's an attractive, sophisticated
veneer. But in truth, ``Random Hearts'' is a sloppily scripted film
that contains a silly and superfluous subplot about a crooked cop.
It's also creakily constructed and seems to be running on slow
speed.
</P>
<P>
   That may be intentional for the characters, who are shocked by
their mates' infidelities and could be suffering from some sort of
delayed reaction, but for the audience, it is numbing.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ford, who rarely seems comfortable onscreen, and Scott
Thomas, who is saddled with some truly dumb lines, can't make the
loose threads and gaps of logic come together. They look great,
sure, but they're given so little to work with that even they can't
rescue ``Random Hearts.'' It resembles the wreckage of the downed
plane more than a tale of redemptive romance.
</P>
<P>
   It looks great but there's little logical resolution to this
talky, slow and unsatisfying film that purports to delve into how
people respond to tragedy and the ghosts that result.
</P>
<P>
   Random Hearts. Directed by Sydney Pollack. Written by Kurt
Luedtke. Cast: Harrison Ford, Kristin Scott Thomas. Columbia
Pictures. 131 Minutes. Rated R for nudity, violence and language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
