<HEADER>
A9676 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-HARSHREALM-REVIEW-     10-07 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HARSHREALM-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER'S `HARSH REALM' IS RIDDLED WITH MYSTERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Reviews of CBS' ``Love &AMP; Money'' and PBS' ``Aristocrats'' 
 follow.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What happens inside ``Harsh Realm'' really matters, somehow, and
the show's creator, Chris Carter, promises to explain why,
sometime.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, ``Harsh Realm,'' premiering Friday on Fox, is about
as appealing as spit on a stick.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's latest enigma, after ``The X-Files'' and
``Millennium,'' features a virtual-reality war game the Pentagon
has designed because ... uh, because ... well, for some excellent
reason, you can be sure.
</P>
<P>
   Ace Army Lieutenant Thomas Hobbes (series star Scott Bairstow)
is eager to get on with his life and marry his fiancee, Sophie
(Samantha Mathis), but is persuaded first to take a little crack at
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Zap, he wakes up inside Harsh Realm, which is what the
computer-driven game is called, and other soldiers are shooting at
him.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbes' mission is to find the game's high scorer, a Vietnam
veteran named Omar Santiago (Terry O'Quinn), and terminate him.
Virtually, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Hobbes forms a shaky alliance with another
warrior, Mike Pinocchio (D.B. Sweeney) _ they're forever
threatening to shoot each other _ and briefly encounters a version
of Sophie, his real-life love.
</P>
<P>
   The main pieces of information he picks up are that Santiago
runs the world within the game and that Harsh Realm isn't easily
escaped.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a comic book, ``Harsh Realm'' is an ambitious TV
program but also dark, violent and massively confusing.
</P>
<P>
   What are all those little glitches in the Harsh Realm computer
software? Who is the mysterious presence that heals Hobbes' gunshot
wound? Why are some ``virtual characters'' cognizant of their
dilemma, while others are clueless? What's the point of the game
and its tie to real life? Why are characters named Thomas Hobbes
and Pinocchio? Has Carter ever met a damp, murky British Columbia
setting he didn't like?
</P>
<P>
   For answers to these and other questions, Carter and Fox are
asking for your faith, your patience and your weekly allegiance.
It's a steep price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Love &AMP; Money,'' premiering Friday on CBS, is a nicely cast,
moderately funny sitcom that seems instantly old and shopworn.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to explain why an ordinary sitcom should suddenly seem
so dated. Perhaps it's because the presence of a few older stars is
so startlingly out of whack with the season's tilt toward teens and
20s. Or maybe TV's most hallowed program genre really is tapped
out.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, ``Love &AMP; Money'' is apt to elicit a few
chuckles and a lot of shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   Former San Franciscan Paget Brewster, who was starring on a
local cable access show barely four years ago, is the show's
central character.
</P>
<P>
   She plays the daughter of a billionaire couple (David Ogden
Stiers and Swoosie Kurtz) who, on her wedding day, jilts her
bridegroom in favor of the janitor (Brian Van Holt) at her New York
luxury highrise.
</P>
<P>
   Brewster and Van Holt are likable in the ``Love'' half of the
comedy, but Stiers and Kurtz get most of the laughs as the
``Money'' figures.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz counts on fine comic timing and puts an aristocratic
stretch into her vowels. Stiers can play a rich, pompous WASP in
his sleep, and may be doing exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Greer and John Livingston play Brewster's siblings, and
veteran character actor Brian Doyle-Murphy is Van Holt's father,
the doorman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   After thousands of miles of exquisite costume dramas, our
British cousins finally puncture a tire with ``Aristocrats,'' a
``Masterpiece Theatre'' three-parter beginning Sunday on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   A co-production of the BBC and WGBH-TV in Boston,
``Aristocrats'' is adapted from a novel by Stella Tillyard. Her
novel, in turn, was based on the true lives of four 18th century
sisters, the great-granddaughters of King Charles II.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Lennox (Serena Gordon) enrages her aristocratic father
(Julian Fellowes) by eloping with a free-thinking, middle-aged
politician (Alun Armstrong). Her sister Emily (Geraldine
Somerville) marries an Irish lord (Ben Daniels) with an apparent
foot fetish.
</P>
<P>
   (The mere mention of women's stockings makes him feel ``what is
not to be expressed.'' The phrase ``shake your booty'' would
probably send him through the roof.)
</P>
<P>
   The next sister, Louisa (Anne-Marie Duff) marries a rich
simpleton (Tom Mullion). And then sister Sarah (Jodhi May), after
briefly catching the eye of the future King George III (Luke De
Lacy), ends up instead embroiled in sexual scandal and banished
from English society.
</P>
<P>
   It's frothy stuff, and seemingly a perfect PBS complement to all
those sex-saturated network shows this fall. If common Americans
can breed like monkeys on network TV, the English ought to be
allowed to get down and wiggle in the muck too, albeit with far
more delicacy.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from Sarah's scandalous saga, ``Aristocrats'' never
hits on a satisfying story line. It just trudges along ornately,
with the sisters aging in a strange leapfrog fashion. Wink once,
and one of them is a young mother. Wink again, and she's a matron
contemplating old age.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the middle-aged Emily is making discreet glances at
her children's tutor (George Anton) and wondering aloud to us ``if
marriage should be a hindrance to desire,'' the miniseries seems
out of story and out of steam.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are all those beautiful silk dresses, elevated
bosoms and lovely country settings. ``Aristocrats'' was filmed in
Ireland; some scenes were shot at the estate where the real Emily
lived.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
