<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SMOKE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     10-07 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOLY SMOKE': FOR ENLIGHTENMENT, HER HEART WILL GO ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the trippy opening moments of Jane Campion's ``Holy Smoke,''
Kate Winslet can be found in the midst of another bohemian
rhapsody. Having roamed so gorgeously through North Africa as a
young hippie mother in ``Hideous Kinky,'' Ms. Winslet this time
appears in India as Ruth Barron, a headstrong young Australian
seeking enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   And the film's delirious credit sequence, complete with the
film's title written in blow-away smoke letters, captures the full
ecstasy of Ruth's adventure. Among the more lovable things about
Ms. Campion's new film is its knowing why a grandiose Neil Diamond
hit on the soundtrack will make this voluptuous, giddy sequence
complete.
</P>
<P>
   But all is not well in the Sydney suburb of Sans Souci, where
Ruth's relatives are wringing their hands about her spiritual
awakening. Miriam (Julie Hamilton), Ruth's timid mother, actually
ventures to India to coax her daughter back home.
</P>
<P>
   The mother's Indian visit ends badly, to the point where she
exclaims ``Thank God it's Quantas!'' while being hoisted on a
stretcher onto the airplane home.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth accompanies her mother back to Sydney, and it is here that
the film's battle of wills begins. Ruth's family has hired a
self-styled ``cult exiter,'' played by Harvey Keitel in cowboy
garb, to wean Ruth away from her Indian guru.
</P>
<P>
   Retreating to the outback, to the picturesque environs of ``Mt.
Emu Farm, Wee Waa'' (the film's identifying titles are nothing if
not fun-loving), the two of them square off for a mighty struggle.
Assorted emus and oddball relatives are assembled there to keep the
film fizzing as they watch Ruth come around.
</P>
<P>
   But as ``Holy Smoke'' moves from its early mix of rapture and
humor into this more serious, confrontational stage, it runs into
trouble. For one thing, the characters as written are an
impressionable young woman and a tough older man. There are two
fine actors here, but it doesn't help the story that Ms. Winslet's
obvious strength and beauty leave Keitel's P.J. Waters looking
overmatched. (Ms. Winslet is stunning in this role all the same.)
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't help that the screenplay, by Ms. Campion and her
sister, Anna Campion, threatens to become heavy-handedly
ideological beneath its outward whimsy. This is a movie in which
Keitel winds up in lipstick and a red dress, and in which that is
seen as just deserts for his tyrannical machismo.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Holy Smoke'' bears a surface resemblance to
``Sweetie,'' with its willful, misunderstood heroine and its
engaging quirks, it turns out to be more fundamentally conventional
than might be expected.
</P>
<P>
   The balance of power shifts schematically as Ruth starts
rattling P.J. in ways he had not anticipated. Ms. Winslet's
powerfully carnal presence dominates their scenes together, to the
point where P.J. is eventually drawn to violate whatever code of
ethics cult exiters have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to be comforting,'' he later explains. As a
smart, outspoken heroine of Ms. Campion's, Ruth is not about to
fall for that.
</P>
<P>
   Shot so beautifully by Dion Beebe that it seems bathed in divine
light, ``Holy Smoke'' has a sensual allure that transcends its
deep-seated ponderousness. The richly colored Indian scenes have a
hallucinogenic magic, while exquisite desert vistas radiate an
attunement with nature.
</P>
<P>
   And the steamily claustrophobic look of the intense scenes
between Ms. Winslet and Keitel have an eroticism that will not
surprise viewers of ``The Piano.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there are some lovely flashes of visual wit here,
as when Ruth insists that she has had spiritually meaningful
relationships in the past. Ms. Campion flashes on a desperately
funny glimpse of high school Romeos who are forced to sparkle in
Ruth's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The underpinnings of ``Holy Smoke'' can be found in a none too
readable current novel by the Campion sisters, which does not
benefit from any such directorial magic. Nor is the book graced by
Pam Grier in a tiny but piquant role, the zany crowd that
constitutes Ruth's extended family or the kewpie-doll sister-in-law
(Sophie Lee) who finds Keitel's character tempting.
</P>
<P>
   She engages with him in one memorably unorthodox breathing
exercise that may be intended as a feminist indictment, but plays
very nicely as a comic scene. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `HOLY SMOKE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jane Campion; written by Anna Campion and Jane
Campion; director of photography, Dion Beebe; edited by Veronika
Jenet; music by Angelo Badalamenti; production designer, Janet
Patterson; produced by Jan Chapman; released by Miramax Films.
Running time: 120 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Kate Winslet (Ruth Barron), Harvey Keitel (P.J. Waters),
Paul Goddard (Tim Barron), Pam Grier (Carol), Julie Hamilton
(Miriam Barron), Sophie Lee (Yvonne Barron), Tim Robertson (Gilbert
Barron), Austen Tayshus (Stan), Kerry Walker (Aunt Puss), and
Daniel Wyllie (Robbie Barron). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9681 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-07 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL-RINGING IDIOM DOESN'T COMPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the usage game, even the simplest question is often more
complicated _ and more interesting _ than it looks. Take this query
from Art McDevitt, who writes from Flower Mound, Texas, to ask
whether All told, all totaled, or all tolled is the preferred
idiom.
</P>
<P>
   ``A case can be made for the first example, meaning when
everything is said,'' notes McDevitt. ``The second example could
mean when everything is added up.'' But his favorite is the third
version, which would derive from ``the tolling of a bell counting
the hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Preference has nothing to do with it, of course _ all told is
the correct version, a synonym for in all or in sum. But unless
you're an etymology buff, you may not have noticed that it doesn't
really mean ``when everything is said.'' Yes, all told has the same
verb as ``Daddy told the bedtime story yesterday,'' but that verb
has a boatload of other meanings, and the one in all told relates
to counting, not chatting.
</P>
<P>
   Tell meant enumerate as early as the ninth century, and we still
use it that way when we speak of bank tellers _ though few of us
see them in their human form these days. The teller in the ATM is
supposed to be counting out your cash, not spinning a yarn.
</P>
<P>
   A related sense of tell shows up in blood will tell, meaning
that good breeding (in horses or humans) will make a difference,
will count for something. It's a proposition more often invoked at
the racetrack than on the street, at least in our sneaker-shod
democracy. But it's familiar enough still as an aristocratic
slogan: Tarzan, writes a Dallas Morning News reviewer, ``reassures
modern audiences that, down deep, there is still a natural order to
things. Blood will tell. Tarzan was raised by apes, but he is still
Lord Greystoke.''
</P>
<P>
   All told is still used mostly in counting contexts _ ``All told,
the Democratic Party returned $2.8 million in questionable
donations that year'' _ but it does show up in non-numerical
environments as well. Theodore Bernstein, who was an etymology
buff, may be the only usage authority who has bothered to object to
this extension: In ``The Careful Writer,'' he declares that ``All
told, it took a lot of skill'' is incorrect, while ``All told,
fifty-two men worked on the garment'' is correct. But even writers
who've never heard of the ``rule'' seem to follow it most of the
time: ``All told, they took two weekends pulling the stunt off,''
wrote one journalist of ``The Blair Witch Project.'' Sometimes,
it's true, all told is just filler: ``All told, enough synergistic
opportunity exists that we believe it is possible to entirely
offset the dilutive effect of the additional Motorola shares to be
issued,'' said Motorola's president last month. But that whole
sentence begs to be translated into English; a meaningless opening
is the least of its problems.
</P>
<P>
   Total, whose origins are Latin rather than Germanic, tells
another story. It arrived in English as an adjective, then became a
noun in the 16th century and a verb in the 18th _ though it wasn't
till the 1950s that you could slangily total your dad's
fin-bedecked Oldsmobile. Total is also the origin of totalizator,
the long name for the tote board you see out at the track, where
blood will (or won't) tell. (The 18th century shortened total to
tot and the verb to tot up, but these variants never caught on in
US English. And don't even ask about tote bags: That tote is a
mystery, perhaps an import from West Africa.)
</P>
<P>
   As for tolled, those church bells also count, no question about
it _ they even tell time. But tolled is a different verb entirely
from told _ it's a 15th-century extension of an Old English verb
meaning ``pull,'' since the ringer had to pull the bell-rope to
toll the bell. (And the toll the turnpike takes, literally and
figuratively, is still another word, probably with Latin ancestry.)
</P>
<P>
   If there were no historical record, a plausible folk etymology
could justify any of McDevitt's three versions _ all told, all
totaled, all tolled. For that matter, facts don't always stop the
tall tales: E-mailers have been circulating a document called
``Life in the 1500s,'' a potpourri of folk etymology
``explaining,'' for instance, that ``raining cats and dogs'' comes
from the shower of housepets sliding off the thatched roofs that
turned slippery when wet. (For a thorough treatment of the
``etymological spooks'' haunting ``Life in the 1500s,'' see Richard
Lederer's Verbivore Web site,
http://pw1.netcom.com/rlederer/index.htm).
</P>
<P>
   But in the matter of told vs. totaled vs. tolled, the historical
record is reasonably complete. All told has an airtight case, and
if the bell tolls, it tolls for two alternative proposals that just
didn't add up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to her
at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include your hometown.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
