</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANDOM-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RANDOM HEARTS': TOGETHER BY A TWIST OF FATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end )  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a nutshell, Sydney Pollack's new film, ``Random Hearts,'' is
about two people from different worlds, a Washington policeman
played by Harrison Ford and a New Hampshire congresswoman played by
Kristin Scott Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   They meet when their spouses die in the same plane crash. Then
they discover that the spouses were having an affair. Then they
have an affair of their own.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Random Hearts'' is the kind of movie that won't fit into a
nutshell. Pollack's films, from ``They Shoot Horses, Don't They?''
to ``Three Days of the Condor'' to ``Tootsie'' to ``Out of
Africa,'' have always refused to work that way.
</P>
<P>
   They have managed to be linear while also drifting thoughtfully
through the nuances of their characters' behavior, with a stylistic
polish and keenness of observation not often found in American
films any more. The ostensibly high-concept ``Tootsie'' is probably
the only film of Pollack's that could easily be made today.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the liability of a certain sogginess accompanies
Pollack's brand of thinking-man's romanticism (as it did in
``Havana''). And there is a sizable segment of the moviegoing
audience with no interest in watching Ford go through the agonies
of a cuckolded husband.
</P>
<P>
   But the tough, laconic Ford is wrenchingly effective throughout
most of ``Random Hearts,'' and the story in which he figures is a
strong one. As a hard-boiled middle-aged character who took his
marriage for granted and now finds himself wondering which was the
last honest moment he and his wife actually spent together, he has
quite a lot to work with this time.
</P>
<P>
   The film is at its best in its first hour, as it details the
busy lives of its star-crossed principals and watches disaster
inexorably approach. Ms. Scott Thomas' businesslike Kay Chandler is
so busy that she considers it good planning to arrange being in the
same state with her husband (Peter Coyote) for their teen-age
daughter's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ford's Van Den Broeck (``They call me Dutch _ it's
easier'') is a mean cuss when it comes to Internal Affairs at the
Police Department, but a domesticated specimen at home. Sweaty in
the morning after a long run, he feels entirely confident of the
devotion of his wife (Susanna Thompson).
</P>
<P>
   She, meanwhile, casually tells him that she has to be in Miami
for a department-store catalog shoot and winds up side by side with
her lover on an airplane, nicely dressed, perfectly groomed and
deep under water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Random Hearts'' watches as news of the plane crash creeps into
the dramatic foreground. It takes a while for either Dutch or Kay
to notice the bulletins on television and feel connected to the
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a scene that mixes Pollack's instinct for the ineffable
and his skill with the mundane, Dutch finds himself incongruously
at the dress department where his wife worked, asking about her
business in Miami and finding out that she had none. ``We think we
know,'' says a saleswoman sadly. ``Nobody knows. You just don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   The film watches Dutch fall into a baleful rage, as when a plane
crash investigator sensitively tells him that he shouldn't be alone
at such a time. ``Oh yeah?'' growls Dutch. ``I was alone before you
got here.'' And it watches as he crosses paths with Ms. Thomas'
briskly efficient widow, who happens to be in the midst of a
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   (Pollack makes an amusing appearance as her media consultant.)
At first, he decides not to tell her what he knows. Then he can't
help it, and the two of them are drawn together in ways not even
the movie can explain.
</P>
<P>
   The latter part of the film, in which Ford is forced to say
things like ``I was thinking of your mouth,'' is a good deal iffier
than the first. It's not much of a stretch to imagine Dutch and
Kay's consoling each other, but the film confines them to an affair
that is the sexual equivalent of Easy Listening.
</P>
<P>
   And it saddles them with a lot of talk. Having already gone this
route in ``The Horse Whisperer,'' Ms. Scott Thomas must struggle
with both an uneven American accent and a strong sense of deja vu
in the audience. Ford, who gives one of his best and most intense
recent performances, remains more plausible and affecting.
</P>
<P>
   Handsomely photographed by Philippe Rousselot and with its minor
roles notably well cast (Dennis Haysbert, Edie Falco, Lynne
Thigpen, Brooke Smith and Richard Jenkins are among the secondary
players), ``Random Hearts'' has a screenplay by Kurt Luedtke and is
adapted by Darryl Ponicsan from a novel by Warren Adler.
</P>
<P>
   It incorporates a full reserve of hard-won wisdom about the
perils that can befall a marriage. One woman speaks of having found
her husband in flagrante delicto in their bedroom one afternoon.
``I kept my mouth shut,'' she says of the aftermath. ``And I never
went home again without calling first.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `RANDOM HEARTS'
</P>
<P>
   Rating: `Random Hearts' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity,
brief nudity and sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sydney Pollack; written by Kurt Luedtke and adapted
by Darryl Ponicsan, based on the novel by Warren Adler; director of
photography, Philippe Rousselot; edited by William Steinkamp; music
by Dave Grusin; production designer, Barbara Ling; produced by
Pollack and Marykay Powell; released by Columbia Pictures. Running
time: 131 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Harrison Ford (Dutch Van Den Broeck), Kristin Scott Thomas
(Kay Chandler), Charles S. Dutton (Alcee), Bonnie Hunt (Wendy
Judd), Dennis Haysbert (Detective George Beaufort), Edie Falco
(Janice), Lynne Thigpen (Phyllis Bonaparte), Brooke Smith (Sarah),
Richard Jenkins (Truman Trainor), Paul Guilfoyle (Dick Montoya),
Susanna Thompson (Peyton Van Den Broeck) and Peter Coyote (Cullen
Chandler). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
