<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9685 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-Y2KCHEMICAL08-COX     10-07 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KCHEMICAL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POST-BHOPAL REFORMS PREPARE U.S. FOR Y2K
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fifteen years ago this December, a Union Carbide
pesticides plant in Bhopal, India, spewed out a toxic gas that
killed more than 6,000 people. That terrible tragedy triggered the
industry reforms that may help protect lives at this year's end
when managers at U.S. chemical plants face the Y2K computer bug,
according to the director of chemical emergency preparedness and
prevention for the federal Environmental Protection Agency (EPA).
</P>
<P>
   Jim Makris, speaking Thursday on a panel assembled by the
President's Council on Year 2000 Conversion, said the 85 million
Americans living within five miles of chemical plants have less to
fear now because of reforms, such as the 1986 Emergency Planning
and Community Right-to-Know Act, and new technologies that make
plants safer. ``The last 15 years have made a difference,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Y2K software flaw will create some risks by causing
older computers and embedded chips to misread the date 00 as 1900,
rather than 2000. That seemingly small problem could lead to
equipment malfunctions on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid problems, many chemical plants have announced they will
not operate Dec. 31 and Jan. 1. Others with continuous
manufacturing processes say they will operate, but with extra staff
on duty and contingency plans in place for emergencies. Texas,
Illinois and California, in that order, are home to the highest
concentrations of the roughly 14,000 plants regulated by the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   President's Council Chairman John Koskinen said that, while a
single Y2K failure within a chemical plant is not likely to cause
safety problems, multiple failures or other Y2K-related problems,
such as a loss of electricity, could combine to create hazards.
``The stakes are very large,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Poje, a member of the Chemical Safety and Hazard
Investigation Board, agreed that the greatest fear is a cascade of
equipment failures. ``You can withstand a single bee sting, but if
you get 100 bee stings,'' you could be facing a catastrophy, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Panel participants generally agreed that large manufacturers
have made enough progress against Y2K that such cascading failures
should not occur. But relatively little information has been
gathered about the readiness of small chemical companies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Makris said that enough precautions are taken by small
firms every day, regardless of Y2K, that safety levels are high.
``Systems fail all the time'' because of earthquakes, ice storms,
power surges and other problems, he said. But those disturbances at
chemical plants do ``not result in catastrophic releases,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
