<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9689 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     10-07 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUDE `ACTION' TURNS OFF VIEWERS _ BUT IF IT WERE ON CABLE ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Action?'' None for Anne Edie, thank you. She finds Jay Mohr's
Peter Dragon interesting ``but crude,'' Illeana Douglas' Wendy
funny ``but sleazy,'' the bleeped-out profanity ``unnecessary, a
gimmick, a turnoff.''
</P>
<P>
   But she likes the Fox comedy, airing Thursdays on Fox, in all
its loudmouth, speedy glory. Loved the pilot, in fact. ``Laughed
out loud,'' she says by e-mail. ``Haven't done that since my
husband declared his wishes to cook Thanksgiving dinner for 12.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Action'' ``leaves me wondering if this is something I
should support. I've never considered myself to be conservative or
a prude, but to watch each week people conniving in the name of
money is simply something I don't want to digest, whether I find it
interesting or not. Is it true that certain things get in our
psyche and stay there? I think about that when I watch this show.''
</P>
<P>
   Praised by critics and even given the greenlight by advertisers,
``Action,'' which zeros in on an unscrupulous Hollywood film
producer navigating an unscrupulous town, has been surprising in
its inability to attract an audience.
</P>
<P>
   It's still early, but ``Action'' is being hammered by NBC's
``Stark Raving Mad,'' the lifeless Neil Patrick Harris sitcom, and
hasn't shown much of a ratings pulse in three airings, falling from
No. 53 in the Nielsen ratings to 72 and then to 95.
</P>
<P>
   That means trouble, which would suit Robert Sargeant just fine.
``I think it's a funny show, actually,'' he said by e-mail. ``I
lived in Los Angeles for five years and while I didn't work in the
film business, I knew many who did. The backstabbing, the absence
of integrity and morals, is right on. But I had to say that I felt
like taking a shower afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   From Louise Stammers, by e-mail: ``My friends have watched and
enjoyed `Action,' but none of us came back to it the second time.
We talked about it, remembering lines and everything, and laughing
our heads off. But there comes a time when crudeness shouldn't be
rewarded. I watched Craig Kilborn on Comedy Central, but now that
he's on CBS, I don't watch as much. He's one of those snide
smart-----, and what's odd is that it was OK for him to do it on
Comedy Central but not OK for CBS, where, for some reason, even
late at night, I think impressionable minds are watching. It's
almost as if I feel that the people who watch network TV need to be
protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Some consider it the sensibility gap between network and cable
television. This issue came into sharper focus during the
nominations for the coveted Emmys, when ``The Sopranos'' racked up
16 nominations. Pay cable doesn't have to worry about bleeping its
profanity (a clear example of cable's freedom was last week during
``The Chris Rock Show,'' when basketball star Allen Iverson asked
Chris Rock, ``I can curse, right, this is cable?'' and then did
just that). So the networks, concerned with advertiser response and
special interest groups, consider their position a disadvantaged
one.
</P>
<P>
   A disadvantage to what? Not being able to give viewers
profanity, violence and sex?
</P>
<P>
   ``Action'' arrives at a time when network television is
desperately trying to join, not fight, its cable competition, by
offering more adult subject matter and moving away from the
traditional half-hour series of setup, punch line, setup, punch
line way of doing things. It's no surprise that this series was
conceived with cable sensibilities or that it ended up on a network
whose programming division is now headed by the former head of
Comedy Central.
</P>
<P>
   At its core, ``Action'' is exactly what we've been yelling for.
Its renewed energy is exhilarating to watch, because it has been
accomplished with a certain amount of conceptual daring. By this I
mean some of the biggest laughs of the season thus far have come
from situations in which Peter Dragon is behaving badly.
</P>
<P>
   A young woman I ran into recently said she'd found the series
``offensive,'' though not to her personally. That sort of thing
``shouldn't be on TV. It's like teaching bad behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Another example is e-mailer Henri Alexander, who said she was a
rabid watcher of HBO's ``The Sopranos,'' where, like ``Action,''
backstabbing, literally and figuratively, in the name of money, is
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Having watched the first two episodes of ``Action,'' ``I thought
it was clever,'' Alexander wrote, ``but it felt out of place. I
suppose it had something to do with it being on Fox and not HBO.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing Alexander back, I asked whether she'd watch ``Action''
if it were on HBO. ``This sounds strange,'' she replied. ``But I
probably would. And after thinking about your question a bit, this
is why. `Action' on Fox makes me feel like it's a gimmick and less
real. That it's just something trying to be bad for the sake of
being bad. There's a dishonesty in that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if it were on HBO, it would be what it is. Just a clever
series that, by and large, goes after the film industry system, and
does so in a terrific way.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this the disadvantage the networks are screaming about?
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
