<P>
   HOUSE-PATIENTS (Washington) _ The House defeats a
Republican-backed rights bill for patients and now must vote on a
Democratic plan giving Americans broader rights to sue health
insurance plans. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-BAN (Washington) _ Wrangling between the Senate and White
House continues over the possible withdrawal of the nuclear test
ban treaty from Senate consideration. President Clinton says
approval of the treaty is ``a moral responsibility'' but the
international agreement lacks sufficient support for ratification
in the Senate. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   SOLOMON-MILK (Washington) _ Former House Rules Chairman Gerald
Solomon (R-N.Y.) is said to have discussed dairy issues with at
least two members of Congress although he is barred by federal law
from lobbying his former colleagues. Solomon denies discussing the
issues. But Republican Reps. John Sweeney and Tom Reynolds of New
York say he did talk to them about the issues although they say he
didn't lobby them. By MARK HELM.
</P>
