<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAINSONG-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PLAINSONG:' EVERYONE'S A NEIGHBOR IN A SMALL PRAIRIE TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title ``Plainsong,'' Kent Haruf explains in an epigraph to
his new novel, refers to those simple, vocal melodies used in the
Christian church from earliest times. As it turns out, it is a
wonderfully fitting title for this plainspoken and moving novel _ a
novel that weaves together the voices of half a dozen people living
in a small Colorado town and turns their overlapping stories into a
powerful portrait of a community bound together by history, memory
and the simple bonds of neighborly responsibility and affection.
</P>
<P>
   The novel begins by giving us three seemingly separate tales of
people caught up in their own domestic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Guthrie, a teacher at the local high school, is trying to
raise his two young boys, Ike and Bobby, by himself: his wife has
withdrawn into a lingering depression and decided to move to Denver
to live with her sister.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen-year-old Victoria Roubideaux, a high school student,
is trying to cope with the news that she is pregnant and on her
own: her mother has kicked her out of the house, and she has not
seen the baby's father in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As for elderly Harold McPheron and his brother, Raymond, they
have long since grown accustomed to a solitary existence: since
their parents died in a truck accident many decades ago, they have
lived quietly by themselves on the family ranch, tending to the
cattle and their pastures and rarely venturing into town.
</P>
<P>
   Although the intersection of these three sets of lonely lives
might normally have all the melodramatic makings of a provincial
soap opera, Haruf orchestrates their convergence with such
authority and grace that their stories materialize before the
reader's eyes without a shred of contrivance. As his critically
acclaimed first novel, ``The Tie That Binds'' (1985), demonstrated,
he possesses an intimate knowledge of farm and small town life, and
in this novel, he uses that knowledge to immerse the reader in the
daily rhythms of life in Holt, Colo. His language borrows the
spareness and measured cadences of Hemingway, but it has a folksy,
down-home inflection, the sound of the prairies and great plains.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, we quickly learn, is the kind of small town where
everybody knows everybody else, if not intimately then at least by
sight or rumor. When Bobby and Ike's mother moves out, everyone _
from the local barber to people on their paper route _ knows what
happened. And when their father clashes with one of his students _
a notorious bully named Russell Beckman _ everyone knows that, too.
</P>
<P>
   It is this sort of small-town closeness that enables the
homeless Victoria to seek refuge with one of her teachers, Maggie
Jones. And it is that same sort of small-town closeness that
impells Maggie to ask Harold and Raymond McPheron to take Victoria
in at their farm: she knows the brothers well enough to know that
they will be kind to the frightened girl and that Victoria will, in
turn, help alleviate the loneliness in the old men's lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``She needs a home for these months,'' Maggie tells them. ``And
you'' _ she smiled at them _ ``you old solitary bastards need
somebody too. Somebody or something besides an old red cow to care
about and worry over. It's too lonesome out here. Well, look at
you. You're going to die some day without ever having had enough
trouble in your life. Not of the right kind anyway. This is your
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   As ``Plainsong'' progresses, it becomes something of an echo
chamber. The shared experience of familial loss that binds the
McPheron brothers together is mirrored by the experience of Ike and
Bobby Guthrie, as they attempt to cope with their mother's
leave-taking, just as the loss of innocence they suffer in their
9th and 10th years is mirrored by Victoria's painful initiation
into the disillusionments of grown-up life. Victoria's acrimonious
relationship with the father of her baby is echoed by Tom Guthrie's
painful separation from his wife, just as her determination to
build a new life is echoed by Maggie Jones' steady resolve to
pursue a romance with Tom.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments of shocking brutality in ``Plainsong'' _ the
brutality of life on a farm (the death of a horse, the breech birth
of a calf) and the brutality of people being cruel or callous to
one another. Ike and Bobby witness a malicious sexual assault
through the window of a neighbor's house, and they will be beaten
and humiliated by Russell Beckman, the student their father is
feuding with at school.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Russell Beckman's behavior sometimes seems over the top,
if the McPheron brothers' good-natured good-old-boy routine
sometimes seems like an outtake from a Bartles &AMP; Jaymes commercial,
such missteps on Haruf's part are easily enough overlooked, given
his sheer assurance as a storyteller. With ``Plainsong,'' he has
conjured up an entire community, and ineluctably immersed the
reader in its dramas. He has written a compelling and compassionate
novel.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PLAINSONG'
</P>
<P>
   By Kent Haruf
</P>
<P>
   301 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
