<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-MOMA-MILLENNIUM-2T     10-07 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MOMA-MILLENNIUM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOMA 2000: JUMPING THE TRACK FROM PAST TO PRESENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Museum of Modern Art has cut the ribbon on its
contribution to the millennium furor: a 17-month series of
exhibitions under the umbrella title ``MOMA 2000.'' In addition to
being a summing up of this venerable institution's past, it is (or
so we are told) a rehearsal for its future.
</P>
<P>
   The completed project will mix hundreds of objects from the
permanent collection _ some of them chestnuts (Rodin's ``Balzac,''
Picasso's ``Three Musicians,'' Gaugin's ``Moon and the Earth (Hina
Tefatou),'' others unfamiliar _ into three successive chronological
chunks. Those chunks will be subdivided into thematic units titled
``People,'' ``Places'' and ``Things,'' each of which will fill a
floor of the museum for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   That's the big picture; the final results are still in the
stars. But from the first increment, which is called ``Modern
Starts: People'' and focuses on the human figure in art from 1880
to 1920, one can glean some hint of what to expect from the whole.
</P>
<P>
   The main idea is to cast an impressionistic glance backward at
modern art as a phenomenon, and at the museum that has done much to
create and promote that phenomenon, or at least a somewhat Olympian
version of it. But the real news may lie in what the show says
about the shape of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   In 2001 the Modern is scheduled to break ground on a building
that will house, among other things, permanent-collection
galleries. Such galleries are a museum's core identity, its
official statement about how it sees art: what it deems important,
what goes with what. Any tinkering with this statement, never mind
a complete overhaul, demands hard, subtle, consensual thought.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true after critical theory in the last few
decades has thrown the very terms ``museum,'' ``modern'' and
``art'' into question. By now, it seems, everyone knows that art
institutions are impure, driven by social and economic agendas.
Every collection and installation is an interpretation. And any
historical account based on a linear progression of one era's
notion of main events is, at best, provisional.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern, for its part, has long been in the canon-making
business. Its curatorial house style might be summed up in the
phrase ``neatness counts.'' Its view of 20th-century art as a
carefully calibrated flow chart of successive avant-garde movements
has, until recently, been unswerving, some would say doctrinaire.
</P>
<P>
   On the evidence of ``Modern Starts'' _ which has been organized
by the curatorial team of John Elderfield, Peter Reed, Maria del
Carmen Gonzalez, Mary Chan and Elizabeth Levine _ efforts are being
made, however cautiously, to give such certainties a shake.
</P>
<P>
   Right off the escalator to the second floor it is clear that
something is up. A mural-like drawing by Sol LeWitt suggests that
the show's historic time frame isn't hard and fast. Inside the
galleries the pristine white walls that have always framed the
permanent collection are painted in greens, browns and grays.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the art. The opening image _ a life-size
undated painting by Leon Bakst of the dancer Nijinsky as a
strapping young man in scarlet trunks, one hand raised in salute _
is bound to be a novelty even to die-hard Modern denizens. The
portrait has been in the collection for years, but the Modern has
never shown it.
</P>
<P>
   You can see why. A cross between a 19th-century academic study
and a Hollywood hunk, a little heroic and a little absurd, this
figure is too far outside the mainstream to fit any aesthetic
pigeonhole. But the work is an ideal lead-in for a show that has
declared its intention to bring together diverse and unexpected
art.
</P>
<P>
   Eclecticism of style, date and medium pervades the first
galleries of ``Modern Starts,'' devoted to the theme ``Actors,
Dancers, Bathers.'' Picasso's 1915 ``Harlequin'' hangs beside a
``Hamlet'' poster produced around 1884 by the British designers who
called themselves the Beggarstaffs (real names: William Nicholson
and James Pryde). Cezanne's seminude male ``Bather'' (circa 1885)
is accompanied by a 1993 photograph by the Dutch artist Rineke
Dijkstra of a boy in a swimsuit on a beach.
</P>
<P>
   The pairing is a neat demonstration of how a single classic
pictorial motif can recur, which is nice to see, in a textbooky
way. The pictures are far more interesting, though, as studies in
the eroticized male body, a subject that might easily have been
pushed a lot further but, in a show that in general treads timidly
over potentially risky ground, it is not.
</P>
<P>
   Eroticism is explored more forcefully in images of the reclining
female nude in an adjoining gallery. These range from Erich
Heckel's woodcut portrait of his feral-looking 12-year-old model
Fraenzi, to Paul Klee's grotesque ``Virgin in the Tree,'' to a
magnetic Titianesque Modigliani nude stretched across a red ground
that looks like swiped-on blood.
</P>
<P>
   The overall effect is striking and theatrical. The gallery, with
its gray-brown walls, has a penumbral, sickroom feel. A sense of
the neurasthenic mystery of early modernism _ feverish and creepy _
comes through. And one realizes afresh how much this art is a
product of male-generated sexual fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fantastic or otherwise, the modern body is an organism under
transformation, and this is the main theme of the rest of the show.
Change can occur through metamorphosis, as in Matisse's series of
five bronze heads of a young woman named Jeanette: in the first,
she looks more or less like you and me; in the last, done six years
later, she is a conflation of abstract swells and bumps, like a
pileup of breakfast rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes figures dissolve like ectoplasm into their
environment: Vuillard depicts his sister being sucked into the
wallpaper behind her. Most often, though, the figure is fragmented:
shattered into bits, truncated, scrambled.
</P>
<P>
   The result can look comedic in a proto-Junk Art sculpture by
Vladimir Baranoff-Rossine. It turns slightly brutish in Francis
Picabia's little painting, ``Conversation II,' with its limbless
torsos lying about like chops on a grill. The effect is somewhere
in between these two poles in a 1990 video by Gary Hill in which a
male body is carved up among several screens, tummy here, nose
there.
</P>
<P>
   The title of the final section, ``Composing With the Figure,''
implies that what comes apart can be reassembled, although
radically changed. Entered in evidence are three big paintings:
Picabia's wild-and-crazy ``I See Again in My Memory My Dear Udnie''
(1914), all nozzles and fleshy polyps; Leger's ``Three Women''
(1921), with their sheet-metal hair and stainless-steel limbs, and
Picasso's ``Desmoiselles d'Avignon,'' which is, in essence, the
restitched and revivified post-mortem corpse of the premodern human
form.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we arrive at this monument, displayed like an
altarpiece, where have we been? Through a series of stylishly
installed, atmospheric installations. And through a number of
perceptive thematic groupings, some of which set up extended
rhythms that run through the show. (Remember the raised hand of the
Bakst Nijinsky? It is there again in ``Desmoiselles.'')
</P>
<P>
   But has the standard view of modernism, the one delivered for
generations from on high in authoritative MOMA-ese, been revised?
Not really. To be sure, the museum has made a point of saying that
``MOMA 2000,'' in sum and in parts, is not intended as a grand,
definitive statement. So if this first installment looks more like
a cosmetic make over than a structural shift, we have been warned.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one can still not help asking for something different, and
more. Bland, old-fashioned formalist and iconographic themes still
prevail. And the mix of artists is not all that much of a mix.
Mostly it is major work by famous artists and minor works by famous
artists, often the same artists.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree this is dictated by the shape of the Modern's
holdings. But surely the museum has oddball material tucked away,
stuff that must have seemed decent enough when it was acquired but
later got the ``reject'' stamp and might not look half-bad now.
</P>
<P>
   The cornucopian ``Art of the '40s'' exhibition in 1991 suggested
as much. It would be good if a few more early-modern unknowns and
irregulars had been brought out to join the fray, or to create a
fray, which is exactly what's missing.
</P>
<P>
   But there are very promising things, too. One, predictably,
comes in a section devoted to photography. Here voices otherwise
absent are heard, including those of women, from Frances Benjamin
Johnston to Tina Barney, and non-Europeans like Martin Chambi of
Peru and Seydou Keita of Mali. One assumes many more such
inclusions are planned for coming installations, which will carry
the modernist saga beyond 1920 and into the present.
</P>
<P>
   And at least one section, a compact minishow of work by James
Ensor (1860-1949) and Jose Guadalupe Posada (1852-1913), points to
depths in the museum's holdings that could, if explored,
significantly broaden the historical picture while remaining within
the parameters of the collection.
</P>
<P>
   These two artists lived on opposite sides of the world, Ensor in
Belgium, Posada in Mexico. They probably never saw each other's
work, although their moralizing, politically pointed, death-riddled
humor is close in form and spirit. Shown together, the evoke a kind
of transcultural Day of the Dead, and they have much to say about
institutionally redefining early modernism as an international
phenomenon, with popular roots and diverse audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Ensor was connected with the European Symbolist avant-garde;
Posada emerged from a regional art tradition. While Ensor worked in
relative isolation and in small print editions, Posada produced
more than 20,000 engravings in a broadsheet medium that appealed to
a mass audience, rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
   The influences of both artists can, to varying degrees, be found
in Latin American art to this day. And their pairing here proposes
a widening view of modernism, past and present, only sporadically
suggested in the surrounding galleries.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern has suggested that the new permanent-collection
galleries, which are several years down the line, will incorporate
pocket-size installations like this one; and that's a promise we
should hold it to. As the museum expands, it only makes sense that
its view of art should expand, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern Starts: People'' tiptoes in this direction and gets by
more on new style than on new substance. But as the larger canvas
of ``MOMA 2000'' unfolds, this first step could turn out to be the
start of something new.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern Starts: People'' remains at the Museum of Modern Art,
11 West 53rd St., (212) 708-9480, through Feb. 1. ``Modern Starts:
Places'' opens on Oct. 28; ``Modern Starts: Things'' on Nov. 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
