<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-HARSH-SPI &LR;      10-07 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HARSH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X-PHILES WILL APPRECIATE INTRICATE `REALM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Army has lost control of its virtual-reality war simulator
and Lt. Thomas Hobbes is the game boy du jour, ordered to win back
the game from the renegade major who has been operating it for his
own personal amusement.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbes learns soon enough that he's not in New Jersey anymore.
Harsh Realm isn't on any maps _ military, Rand McNally or Yahoo.
He's on his own in a world that seems familiar but doesn't quite
behave like the one he left behind, the one where his fiancee is
planning their wedding and awaiting his imminent release from
military service.
</P>
<P>
   In this odd new world, his fiancee or the woman who looks like
his fiancee, is married to the guy who was his best friend on the
outside, a soldier whose life he saved in Sarajevo but who is now
sworn to kill Hobbes inside Harsh Realm.
</P>
<P>
   But are these real people, or are they very convincing products
of this virtual-reality construct? It's the sort of disquieting
question that, if mulled too long, can give you a headache. Or get
you killed.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone expecting a quick answer shouldn't bother tuning in.
``Harsh Realm,'' premiering Friday on Fox, is from Chris Carter,
creator of ``The X-Files,'' where reasonable questions go to die.
The truth may be out there, but Carter won't say where.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who like Carter's government-conspiracy paranoia and his
penchant for confusing plots will embrace ``Harsh Realm.'' It
requires close attention to details that propel the story, and it
has instantly likable characters in Hobbes (Scott Bairstow) and
Mike Pinocchio (D.B. Sweeney).
</P>
<P>
   Pinocchio, another soldier who was sent into Harsh Realm to
wrest control of it from Omar Santiago (Terry O'Quinn), now leads a
sort of freedom-fighter existence, trying to stay a step ahead of
Santiago, a megalomaniac who makes sure all threats to his
supremacy are eliminated with prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   Before entering Harsh Realm, Hobbes is told that it's only a
game, that all he has to do is beat Santiago's ``score'' and he can
leave the Army a winner. Trouble is, Santiago is the Army's most
decorated soldier. And he's nuts.
</P>
<P>
   As escapism, ``Harsh Realm'' is more accessible than Carter's
Friday night effort of the past two years, ``Millennium.'' Not as
dark and seemingly less cynical, it's a simple _ well, not that
simple _ man-against-machine saga with a little theology thrown in.
(Residents of Harsh Realm speak of a legendary ``savior'' who will
rescue them from Santiago.) Better still, if this is to be the last
season for ``The X-Files,'' ``Harsh Realm'' may provide Fox and
X-philes with a reasonable substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Harsh Realm. Hourlong drama series about a soldier stuck inside
a virtual-reality war game. Starring Scott Bairstow, D.B. Sweeney,
Rachel Hayward, Terry O'Quinn, Maximilian Martini, Sarah-Jane
Redmond and Samantha Mathis. Series premiere Friday night on Fox.
Parental guideline rating TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
