<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST-MOVING AMAZON.COM CHURNING TOWARD TOP OF E-COMMERCE FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the mighty river it was named after, Amazon.com is forging
a wide path in electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   For those who know the Web retailer only as the largest
bookseller in the world, with a $6 billion book value that exceeds
that of Barnes &AMP; Noble and Borders combined, it's time to take
another look.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com is now a drugstore, a pet supply store and a
supermarket. Last year, the company bought two more technology
companies to further its retailing abilities: Junglee Corp., which
has developed comparison-shopping technologies, and PlanetAll, an
Internet site that helps people stay in touch with friends.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com is quickly becoming a leader in the $43 billion
e-commerce business. Some are comparing it to the giant Wal-Mart in
terms of retailing clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon has become the default name when you think of buying on
the Net. ... They are the poster child of Internet commerce,'' an
analyst with BancAmerica Robertson Stephens said back in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the company succeeds with its ambitions or not _ it has
yet to post a profit _ Amazon.com is a big player in defining how
retailing, or e-tailing as the industry jargon goes, will work on
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Mentioned in countless management books on the latest ways to
best treat employees, Amazon.com is now the sole subject of a book
by Rebecca Saunders. It's called ``Business the Amazon.com Way:
Secrets of the World's Most Astonishing Web Business'' (Capstone,
213 pages, $21.95).
</P>
<P>
   This is no doubt the first of a series of books on Amazon.com,
if Microsoft is any indication of what sells in the book world.
Indeed, the author admits upfront that she could not get an
interview with Amazon.com founder and Chief Executive Jeff Bezos,
possibly because he's working with another author.
</P>
<P>
   But Saunders has done her research, and in addition to a lively
history of a company destined to lead in the next century, she has
developed a number of lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, she observes that people developing business on the
Web are literally doing the impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web allows entrepreneurs to do what wouldn't work in the
real world,'' she writes. ``The opportunities would seem to be
limited only by your imagination and business acumen.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Bezos has both of those in spades.
</P>
<P>
   A former New York hedge fund manager, Bezos ditched it all in
1994 when he came across a statistic that would forever change his
life: He read that Web usage was growing 2,300 percent monthly.
</P>
<P>
   Within two months, Bezos had packed up his wife and dog and was
heading West to launch an Internet company, not even sure of his
destination.
</P>
<P>
   He ended up in Seattle and started his company in his garage
with three other people. Amazon.com went public in 1997 with an IPO
price of $9 a share. The stock is now trading around $66, although
it was as high as $209 this year. Bezos is predicting that by 2000,
his company will have $1 billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief corporate history, Saunders takes off on 10
strategy ``secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Most are the regular fodder of management books, such as finding
and retaining customers by offering value, being frugal, branding,
constantly reinventing and so on. Those broad business rules are
often talked about, but Saunders shows how Bezos implements them,
which is far more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   For example, visitors to Amazon.com have helped finish a chapter
of a book by John Updike and helped write the first ``Doonesbury''
comic strip created online. Children looking in on the Amazon.com
kids section can enter the ``Be a Poet'' contest.
</P>
<P>
   Although the book is not as complete as I would have liked,
Saunders does have a good feel for what makes Amazon.com and its
leader so important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bezos is likely to have the same impact that Sears' catalog
had on the retail industry, and his online store may grow into the
Sears or Woolworth of the new millennium,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
