<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-INGRES-FRENCH-ART-NYT     10-07 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INGRES-FRENCH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INGRES: AN ICY EYE FOR PEOPLE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy)   By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before he was the great man of French art,
Jean-Auguste-Dominique Ingres drew pencil portraits to make money.
They were souvenirs on letter-size sheets of paper. He was living
in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   He hoped the drawings would lead to more important commissions,
and sometimes they did. He also drew friends for pleasure, but
generally he regarded portrait drawing of this sort as a waste of
time. The people who commissioned him often had no idea who he was
or what they had bought, and many of the portraits disappeared or
turned up years later in the hands of families who didn't realize
that they had inherited works of value.
</P>
<P>
   His sitters were foreigners: people in the French community in
Rome, and then, after Napoleon's administration was expelled,
British tourists. Ingres, a student of Jacques-Louis David, had won
the Grand Prix de Rome in 1801 and arrived in Italy triumphant in
1806, only to learn that the works he had exhibited at the Paris
Salon that year, in particular a giant portrait of Napoleon
enthroned, had been savaged by the critics. Devastated, he finished
his term at the French Academy in 1810 and, partly to avoid
returning to France, he stayed in Italy for 14 more years, moving
from Rome to Florence in 1820.
</P>
<P>
   Along with his portrait paintings, the exhibition of Ingres'
portraits now at the Metropolitan Museum through Jan. 2 includes
several dozen drawings from throughout his career. Ingres would be
appalled. He took pride in his painted portraits, which are some of
the greatest ever made. But like other academics he wanted to be
remembered above all as a history painter, not a portraitist. Least
of all would he have imagined that posterity might admire his
portrait drawings as much as, if not more than, his history
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   But tastes change. His drawings are attuned to modern
sensibilities and look even more impressive than many of the
paintings, among other reasons because they suggest what Ingres
could do when he was not really trying.
</P>
<P>
   There is very little like them in history. He almost never
corrected himself or hesitated in the middle of a line.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing after drawing is perfect: perfect not only in the sense
that there isn't a false step but also in that each one looks true.
We assume these people must have looked exactly like this, because
we know that Ingres could be brutally honest about a sitter. (His
famous drawing of an obese, mustachioed Madame Bertin, for example,
is one of the memorable curiosities of 19th-century art.)
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there is something inhuman and unbelievable
about the pictures. Technique on Ingres' level is always
discomforting and spooky at first. Ingres, to use a familiar
metaphor, seems to breathe the air of some icy summit of art where
normal humans gasp, which is clearly what he expected people
looking at his work to do. Even Degas can seem down to earth by
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   So it takes a while to realize that these are not all cold
pictures, at least the best of them are not _ including the one of
Madame Bertin, which, after the shock, we see is respectful for not
dissembling. When he had the right subjects, like friends and other
artists whom he admired, his portraits convey a clear warmth and
humor that belies the usual tendency to equate mechanical precision
with lack of emotion. The equation makes no more sense with Ingres
than the standard art historical split in early 19th-century French
art between the advocates of Classicism and line (Ingres) versus
the exponents of Romanticism and color (Delacroix).
</P>
<P>
   Ingres was, like other perfectionists, egomaniacal, insecure,
intolerant and easily upset, to the point that he could become
physically ill in times of stress. There are stories about his
developing boils while he was painting ``The Apotheosis of Homer.''
Art critics drove him mad, and who can blame him? During most of
his career he was attacked for the predictable reasons (chilliness,
fussiness, exaggeration of form) by critics, whose words he stewed
over for years and whose attacks sometimes made it painful for him
to work.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he described being ``love struck by painting _
I don't possess it, it possesses me.'' His habits were regular. The
antithesis of a bohemian, he embraced every bourgeois comfort,
which he expected his wife to provide for him at home, in return
for which he was a devoted husband. He had no children. When he
became the director of the French Academy in Rome, he played the
part of the stern parent. Even his relatives were supposed to call
him Monsieur Ingres.
</P>
<P>
   He was also a social climber, obsessed about awards and titles
(``I am devoured by ambition,'' he said), but never more content
than when he was making or listening to music with a few friends at
home. He kept friends for life, unless one crossed him. A friend
described him as ``choleric, impatient, obstinate, good, naive,
righteous and lazy.''
</P>
<P>
   We look for signs of the vulnerable and touching Ingres behind a
few of the implacable portraits in this exhibition. He peeks out in
the very early paintings, dogged and endearingly precise, like
early American pictures, and in some of the mature works, like the
portrait of Jeanne-Suzanne-Catherine Gonin, the daughter of a
friend, whom he presents intimately and as if without artifice.
</P>
<P>
   The most touching thing about Ingres' art is the degree to which
all of it survives under the impossible pressure of his own
expectations. He was a laborious artist burdened by what he
perceived to be the gap between himself and his heroes, whom he
nonetheless believed he could exceed. His famous portrait of the
seated Madame Paul-Sigisbert Moitessier is more psychologically
fascinating in terms of the artist than of his sitter: the pose is
based on the figure of an enthroned goddess in an ancient Roman
painting, the sitter's reflection in a mirror echoing a
self-portrait by Poussin, her flowered silk dress, the height of
fashion in 1856, and a riot of flabbergasting trompe l'oeil effects
meant to convey her wealth and Ingres' own even greater wealth of
talent.
</P>
<P>
   With 40 paintings and 92 drawings, the show at the Met spans six
decades, from the works Ingres did as a prodigy in Montauban and
Toulouse through the celebrated portrait he did of the newspaperman
Louis-Francois Bertin (Madame Bertin's husband), in 1832, which was
his first popular success. (The critics still hated it.) The
exhibition ends, in a shimmer of satin and jewels, with the late
portraits of Madame Moitessier, the Vicomtesse d'Haussonville and
the Princesse Albert de Broglie, and with his last work, a
self-portrait, calculatedly humble, which he finished in 1865, two
years before he died, at 87.
</P>
<P>
   The portrait of Monsieur Bertin, massive with claw hands clamped
to knees, one eyebrow raised, has come to symbolize bourgeois power
generally and in particular the no-nonsense reign of the July
Monarchy, which Bertin's newspaper supported. Bertin seems as
immediate and human as Napoleon does not in that early portrait of
him, enthroned like God the Father in a Gothic altarpiece, although
one shouldn't overstate the difference.
</P>
<P>
   There is the same shallow space, a kind of flat, nowhere zone,
and the same fetish with dazzling the eye (David called it Ingres'
``tendency toward exaggeration''), which pushes even Bertin's
picture toward a kind of abstraction that takes the form of
hyper-realism. It's often said that the Bertin portrait looks like
an early photograph, down to the sepia-toned background, but really
it goes farther than any photograph could in creating the illusion
of a figure. It's intensity of optical fireworks, distilled and
concentrated, actually puts us back in a realm of disbelief, where
we always end up with Ingres.
</P>
<P>
   Critics finally, mostly, came around to Ingres in his last
years, having decided that he represented the only remaining hope
against the deluge of Degas, Cezanne and company. This didn't stop
Degas, Cezanne and almost every other thinking modernist from
revering Ingres.
</P>
<P>
   Degas at one time even owned five of the portraits in the Met's
exhibition. He paid the most extraordinary tribute to Ingres in
1911, when as an old man he went every day to visit an Ingres
exhibition at the Galerie Georges Petit in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Degas was blind. He went to run his hands over the pictures.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHINA-PHOTOGRAPHY-REV     10-07 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PHOTOGRAPHY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHINA: FIFTY YEARS INSIDE THE PEOPLE'S REPUBLIC:' A MOST
APOLITICAL CHINA  
 (EDITORS: ORIGINALLY SKEDDED AS CHINA-ART-REVIEW)  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mass., Calif., Brazil, The Czech Republic)   By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's a little hard to imagine that a photographic
show pegged to the 50th anniversary of the People's Republic of
China could give no idea of Communist misrule. But the organizers
of ``China: Fifty Years Inside the People's Republic'' at the Asia
Society have accomplished that feat.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the aim is not to offer a documentary but _ in the
words of Vishakha N. Desai, senior vice president for cultural
programs and director of the Asia Society Galleries _ ``a highly
personal, engaged, insiders' view of China and the Chinese during a
time of unprecedented change.'' So this group of images by 33
photographers _ ranging from those as well-known as Robert Capa and
Eve Arnold to native-born Chinese whose work has rarely been seen
outside of the country _ is a misleadingly low-key representation.
It gives no hint of the violence at times engendered by the zeal of
``Communist reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   There is in fact a curious discrepancy between the show's
discreet visuals and the candid text for its catalog by Rae Yang.
Ms. Yang, 49 and the chairwoman of the East Asian studies program
at Dickinson College in Carlisle, Pa., was a Red Guard in her youth
and she freely discusses the excesses of the Mao-decreed 1960s
Cultural Revolution and her own (small) role in them.
</P>
<P>
   But from this show, you would scarcely know that the Cultural
Revolution and other depredations occurred causing the death of
millions.In fact, the only photograph of Tiananmen Square _ which
achieved international notoriety in 1989 when government soldiers
fired on reformist supporters gathered there _ is a 1981 view by
Liu Heung Shing. It shows students studying in its vastness at
night to prepare for high school entrance exams, which were allowed
after years of official education-bashing that made learning a
dirty word.
</P>
<P>
   So aside from the work of Antonin Kratochvil, a Czech
photographer whose five exhibited pictures from 1978, taken in
Guangdong Province , could be said to mildly reflect the angst and
despair of the Cultural Revolution's aftermath (compare these with
Eve Arnold's upbeat views on the same subject, taken around the
same time), the show is squeaky clean of politically embarrassing
material.
</P>
<P>
   Even operating under Ms. Desai's rubric, one would think that in
a half-century of lensed images there might be a few that more
sharply reflected the down side of the Chinese government. The
show, incidentally, is sponsored by the Ford Motor Co., which does
extensive business with China. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It begins strongly with a historical section, a cluster of
black-and-white images made before the founding of the People's
Republic in 1949 (including a rare close-up of the young Mao Zedong
and Zhou Enlai, already plotting revolution in Yan'an, taken in
1937 by Owen Lattimore, a Far East scholar who was a target of Sen.
Joseph R. McCarthy in the 1950s. There are poignant photographs of
refugees displaced by the civil war between Mao's forces and those
of Chiang Kai-shek, and Communist victory celebrations and even a
shot of a smiling Mao presiding at a swimming party with members of
the Communist Youth League in the late 195Os.
</P>
<P>
   But there Mao's visibility all but ends. The show shifts to
become an often fascinating essay on the China of later years, but
without much edge. Grouped by individual photographers and
unconcerned with chronological order, it concentrates more on
China's recent years, with many works dating from the 1990's. They
range from a 1998 essay on ``Parents'' by a young Chinese painter
and photographer, Wang Jinsong, a look at older couples of
differing social status whose children have flown the nest, to
views of paintinglike landscapes in starkly beautiful black and
white, taken from 1984 to 1995 by Lois Conner, an American
photographer. Several of the photographic essays here, by Reagan
Louie, Mark Leong and Richard Yee, deal with the return of
Chinese-Americans to the haunts of their immediate ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian-born photographer Sebastiao Salgado is represented
by one of the liveliest ``takes:'' nearly a dozen black-and-white
views of Shanghai, made in 1998. Skyscraper panoramas, street
scenes, huge factory interiors, old-style markets and the day and
night life of its people show a city of vast ambition, future-bound
at a dizzying rate. The frantic pace and sprawling reach of cities
is also forcefully portrayed by Macduff Everton, an American, in
his big photo of a crowd crossing a garish Hong Kong street (1997)
and the broad boulevards of Shenzhen (Special Economic Zone) in
Guangdong Province (1995).
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Robert Glenn Ketchum's beautiful explorations
of the Grand Canal and affiliated waterways of Suzhou (1986-95),
show a Venice-like city whose canal network forms one of the great
industrial transportation systems of Western China, but whose
ancient houses, bridges and culture still resist the modernization
that creeps in relentlessly.
</P>
<P>
   The persistence of tradition is cherished by Richard Yee, born
in Guangzhou and living in Massachusetts since 1952. He keeps
returning to document old ways, and his 1997 essay on Yunnan
Province shows the land and people unchanged: an infant slung over
its young mother's shoulder, both dressed in richly embroidered
central Asian garments; a straw basket roped to a man's back, a
gunny sack worn by a walker in the rain, a delicate snowy landscape
that could have been painted a thousand years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Born in California in 1966, Mark Leong also revisits his family
turf in Guangdong Province (1989-97) to record an ancestor worship
ritual, his oldest living relative in China the life of a grungy
street and the home of a village chief. More attuned to the
present, Brian Palmer, an American who lives in Beijing, has
photographed some American-style rites (1996-97), including the
crush at a subway stop and svelte young things at a modeling
competition.
</P>
<P>
   To prove that religion is still alive in China, Xiao-Ming Li, a
Bejing-based Magnum photographer, searched out pockets of secret
Catholicism (1993-95): a nun preparing rice cakes for Mass in
Shaanxi Province; a cluster of congregants saying funeral prayers
aboard a fishing boat in Jiangsu Province, a man carrying a statue
of the Virgin through an ancient, rubble-strewn courtyard in Yunnan
Province.
</P>
<P>
   Few countries are as photogenic as China, and the infectious
empathy with which most of the photographers view their subjects
makes for some compelling images. In short, the show undemonizes
China, giving a very human dimension to the struggles of a vast
population adapting to a tidal wave of change. But in leaving out
direct references to authoritarian brutality over the half-century,
it weakens itself, revealing only part of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1645EDT &QL; 
