<HEADLINE>
`LOVE &AMP; MONEY' WON'T APPEAL TO MUCH OF ANYBODY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's too bad ``The Mike O'Malley Show'' won the trophy as first
new fall series to be canceled. CBS's ``Love &AMP; Money'' deserved the
chance.
</P>
<P>
   If ever a comedy was put on the air without hope of a future,
this is it. Sandwiched between ``Kids Say the Darndest Things,''
which targets a family audience, and ``Now and Again,'' which skews
smarter than the average CBS drama, ``Love &AMP; Money'' is your basic
dumb comedy that isn't likely to appeal to either audience. Or to
anyone else, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Its premise of mismatched lovers is as fresh as anything on the
day-old rack. Worse, its execution is standard, by-the-numbers
sitcom. Even the laughter sounds half-hearted.
</P>
<P>
   Paget Brewster plays a rich young woman who leaves her rich
young husband-to-be at the altar so she can be with her true love,
who happens to be the superintendent of her family's apartment
building. Her family is stuffy and rich, his family isn't (his
father is the doorman), and if you really like this idea, go watch
``Dharma &AMP; Greg.''
</P>
<P>
   Love &AMP; Money. Half-hour comedy series about an heiress who's in
love with the superintendent of her apartment building. Starring
Paget Brewster, Brian Van Holt, Swoosie Kurtz, David Ogden Stiers,
Judy Greer, John Livingston and Brian Doyle-Murray. Premieres
Friday on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
