<HEADER>
A9718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TANDEM-BIKES-ART-2TAK     10-07 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANDEM-BIKES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT JUST SPEED ON A TANDEM; IT'S CONVERSATION, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
(Eds: Allen St. John is the author of ``Bicycling for Dummies.'') 
 
 By ALLEN ST. JOHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Stanley Kubrick trivia question. In ``2001: A Space Odyssey,''
what's the last thing that HAL the computer does? Give up? As the
astronaut Dave performs the final shutdown of the rogue computer,
HAL experiences a moment of childhood regression and haltingly
sings an old-fashioned ditty it learned when it was only a
microchip, which carries the refrain: ``But you'll look sweet upon
the seat, of a bicycle built for two.''
</P>
<P>
   Always a master of detail, Kubrick reached back to the turn of
the century for an ironic counterpoint, a reference to a technology
that's quaint and outdated, but particularly human in scale.
</P>
<P>
   As I donned my helmet and gloves in the parking lot at the
Country Inn in Millville, N.J., I remembered this scene and came to
the conclusion that Kubrick wouldn't have believed his eyes. In a
minute, 40 bicycles built for two, or more, would roll out, kicking
off the annual Tandem Weekend sponsored by Tandems East, a local
bicycle shop.
</P>
<P>
   But the bikes that took off into the South Jersey countryside
weren't the kind of slow, stately boardwalk cruisers Kubrick had in
mind. No, these were sleek, special-purpose fin-de-millenium
machines.
</P>
<P>
   A good road tandem bike features a frame precision-welded of
high-tensile steel or aircraft-grade aluminum and components of
space-age alloys that keep the weight down to under 40 pounds, a
little more than some department-store single bikes. To handle the
hills, a quality tandem has more gears than a tractor-trailer, 27
in all. This kind of technology doesn't come without a price: a
quality road tandem starts at more than $2,000, and the best models
run $5,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   I began Tandem Weekend as a spectator. For the first segment of
the 53-mile excursion _ a loop of rural roads that start and end in
Millville _ I tagged along on my single bike. ,
</P>
<P>
   It afforded me a firsthand look at a little-known truth: tandems
are fast. It's simple physics. Twice the horsepower plus only about
25 percent more wind resistance equals an aerodynamic advantage
that can offset a lot of training miles. ``A good tandem team can
hit 25, even 30 miles an hour on the flats,'' said Mel Cornbluh,
owner of Tandems East and organizer of the event. This is almost 10
miles per hour faster than a fit single rider can do. Even average
teams roll along at almost 20 mph. The faster tandems left me in
the dust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, you forgot someone,'' one team said, cheerfully passing
me as though I were standing still. ``I lost my second engine,'' I
replied, slightly out of breath. But, thankfully, this was a ride
and not a race, so I hung with the slower teams, drafting as close
as I could to their rear wheels to gain aerodynamic advantage _
racers derisively call it wheel sucking _ and observing tandem
teamwork firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the teams on the ride were mixed-gender couples with the
man riding in the captain's position and the woman in back as the
stoker. This is because most tandems are designed to put the taller
rider in the front. For many, tandeming becomes a way for couples
of unequal ability to ride together without having to shout, ``Wait
up!''
</P>
<P>
   Tandems encourage, and even demand, conversation. ``The money we
spent on the bike was originally slated for my patio,'' one stoker
confessed with hardly a trace of regret. Who needs marriage
counseling when you can ride a bicycle built for two?
</P>
<P>
   At the lunch stop, I transferred to a triple _ three pedalers on
two sets of wheels _ ridden that morning by Steve and Cindy
Malriat, a young couple from outside Philadelphia. Their 6-year-old
son, Jonathan, pedaled in the center stoker position with the aid
of special cranks designed for his short legs, while 18-month-old
Daniel was towed along in a bike trailer mounted on the back. (For
the second leg of the trip, they allowed me to be the man in the
middle.)
</P>
<P>
   The triple offered me an extraordinary perspective. I could see
what the captain does. I could see what the stoker does. My only
responsibilities were to pedal and carry a map in my rear jersey
pocket where Cindy could reach it.
</P>
<P>
   My first reaction? I was reminded of that old dog-sledding
adage, ``Unless you're the lead dog, the view never changes.'' From
my obstructed-view seat, all I could see was Steve's Ferrari-red
jersey. But after a couple of miles, I realized I could peer over
Steve's shoulder or even turn to the side without shirking my
steering duties, since I had none. Still, I'm told, it's customary
for the stoker to choose the captain's jersey, since it makes up so
much of the view.
</P>
<P>
   The economist Adam Smith would have loved tandeming because it
is division of labor come to life. Steve did all the steering and
braking and balancing, while Cindy and I provided propulsion and
navigation. With my additional thrust, we really motored. When all
three of us pounded hard, we would flex the back end of the bike
enough so that the chain rubbed the derailleur cage with every
pedal stroke.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   We consistently topped 25 mph on the flats, easily hitting 30 on
short downhills, and powered up the short grades as if they weren't
there. Before long, we began catching tandem teams that we had
spotted a 15-minute head start.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a tandem, and especially a triple, also demands
communication, so we chattered more than a sailboat crew getting
ready to tack. ``Right turn ahead, on the brakes, coasting,'' Steve
said. ``Car back,'' Cindy countered. ``Now it's clear.''
</P>
<P>
   As captain, Steve would let us know every time he shifted up or
down, tapped the brakes, or even if he reached for a water bottle.
He would also inform the stokers when there was broken pavement
ahead, although Cindy confessed that he sometimes forgot, which
resulted in her fillings' getting rattled by an unexpected pothole.
Cindy would check for passing cars, apprise drivers of our stops
and turns with hand signals, and check the maps and cue sheets so
we avoided wrong turns.
</P>
<P>
   When Jonathan is riding the middle stoker position, Cindy also
serves as the entertainment committee, playing ``Itsy Bitsy
Spider'' on his back. The view and the big bike's speed provided
sufficient amusement for me. But tandeming (and tripling), I soon
discovered, takes more than simple communication. It takes blind
faith.
</P>
<P>
   Our initial trial of trust took place at the first stoplight.
When the bike came to a full stop, Steve straddles the bike,
supporting more than 300 pounds of bike and rider while we stokers
stayed clipped into the pedals. If he slipped or stumbled, we would
all go down.
</P>
<P>
   The real test came when it was snap decision time. As we headed
for home, an oncoming Chevy tried an ill-advised pass of another
car across the center line on the two-way road. So we found
ourselves facing a Cavalier going 65 mph, flashing its lights, its
left fender aimed directly at our left handlebar.
</P>
<P>
   My first instinct was to turn my handlebars right, except that
they're there strictly for show. Steve stayed the course, inching
the bike to the right, and the car whizzed by, its door handle
coming within 18 inches of my left hip.
</P>
<P>
   I gained new respect for Steve's captaining skills the next
morning, when I went out on the front of a tandem with Norman
Toplosky, a Connecticut engineer. A 20-year veteran of tandeming,
he had brought two tandems to the event _ for his wife and two
children _ including one he had built himself. He had toured Europe
on tandem, but he rarely rode stoker, so this was a new experience
for him too.
</P>
<P>
   At first, steering the big bike felt a little like driving a
Ryder truck. The controls were heavy, and when Norman and I really
pounded, the rear end felt as if it had a mind of its own. It
wasn't unlike learning to ride all over again, albeit at 25 mph.
</P>
<P>
   But I soon began to trust the bike more _ understanding that the
rhythmic swaying of the back end was a sign of power, not a threat
to our balance _ and loosened my death grip on the bars. As I
enjoyed the uncharacteristically rapid rush of breeze across my
cheeks, I thought, ``Hey, this is kind of like riding a single bike
on steroids.'' Except, of course, for the running commentary:
``Down one, left turn ahead, cars back?''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the ride, my throat was almost as tired as my
legs. The urge to communicate, I'm embarrassed to say, became so
ingrained that even after Tandem Weekend was over and I was back on
my single bike, I occasionally found myself calling out turns and
shifts to a nonexistent stoker, eliciting strange looks from
passing motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Ready for a new verse, HAL? ``You're not complete, upon the
seat, of a bicycle built for one.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
