<HEADLINE>
BROTHER SENTENCED IN BORDER SMUGGLING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ A federal judge on Thursday sentenced three
brothers to prison and scolded their elderly parents for a family
operation that for years helped thousands of illegal immigrants
sneak into the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a family-run enterprise. The chickens have come home to
roost,'' U.S. District Judge Hilda Tagle said as she pronounced
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The parents _ Abel Contreras Sr., a former Raymondville city
commissioner, and his wife, Olga _ face sentencing later for their
parts in the scheme that lasted about 15 years before their arrests
in July. They and the others pleaded guilty to charges of
conspiracy to harbor undocumented immigrants as part of plea
bargains with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Tagle delayed sentencing the parents and one daughter until the
ownership of an apartment complex and a motel in Raymondville could
be resolved so the federal government can level them with
bulldozers. The buildings were way stations for illegal immigrants
who crossed the border into Texas illegally and were awaiting
transportation to the interior of the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Tagle sent Abel Jr., David and Daniel Contreras to prison
for terms of slightly more than one year to slightly less then
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your parents took everybody under their wing and said it is OK
to break the law, we are all making money,'' Tagle told the
brothers as she encouraged them to set better examples for their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sentences here do not do justice to what has been
happening for years,'' Tagle said. ``It has stopped and hopefully
won't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Contreras family was arrested after a two-year initiative
known as ``Operation Snake Pit,'' which was spearhead by undercover
Border Patrol agents.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about the Contrerases had circulated in Raymondville for
years before federal authorities began investigating and launched
the undercover operation. Agents posed as illegal immigrants and
smugglers as they infiltrated an underground network that pumped
people through Raymondville, a city of 9,400 people about 50 miles
north of Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in its investigation, the Border Patrol discovered
356 illegal immigrants in shacks owned by the Contreras family in
Raymondville.
</P>
<P>
   Abel Contreras Sr., 61, and Olga, 60, sat silently in the front
row at the federal courthouse as their sons were ordered to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very sorry about what happened. It will never happen
again,'' a solemn Abel Contreras Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   Abel Contreras Jr., whom prosecutors said played a minor role in
the outfit, was sentenced to 14 months in federal prison and 200
hours of community service upon his release. Daniel Contreras
received 24 months in prison, and David was sentenced to 33 months.
</P>
<P>
   Their sister, Yolanda Hernandez, whose sentencing also was
delayed, wiped tears from here eyes as Tagle sent her brothers to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hoping to God that things work in our favor,''
Hernandez said before the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Others who have been sentenced include two cooperating
witnesses, who led illegal immigrants to the Contreras compound,
and a cook.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
