<HEADLINE>
TANG HORSES ARE OUT IN FULL FORCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to the Chinese zodiac, this is not the Year of the
Horse. But it should be. Ancient Chinese horse sculptures are
showing up all over.
</P>
<P>
   There are four life-size terra-cotta chariot horses from the Qin
dynasty (221-207 B.C.) in ``The Golden Age of Chinese Archeology,''
a show at the National Gallery of Art in Washington that opened on
Sept. 19 and runs through Jan. 2. These horses, with ears forward
and nostrils dilated, are part of a group of 500 horses and
soldiers excavated from tombs in Shaanxi province in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Ten horses from the Tang dynasty (618-906 A.D.) are among the
works in ``Abstraction and Reality: Chinese Art From the Warring
States to the Liao,'' which opened two days ago at the Chinese
Porcelain Company, a gallery at Park Avenue and 58th Street. Some
of the horses are glazed, in glorious blue, green, amber and cream,
with tasseled bridles and elaborate saddle blankets. Others are
unglazed, which makes them look modern to Western sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   One unglazed pale taupe horse has its head raised, neighing.
Another twists its neck to catch a fly. Still another has its
muzzle to the ground. They are subtly modeled to catch the light
and create shadows.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very rare models,'' said Jim Lally, who runs J.J.
Lally, at 41 East 57th St., and specializes in ancient Chinese art.
``The Tang was a moment in Chinese art when there was a strong move
toward realism and a strong decorative impulse. Horses imported
from the Near East were precious. In Tang China, the horse was the
emblem of wealth and power. They are meant to embody rank and
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lally, who sells Tang horse sculptures, currently has a classic
example in pale green glaze with an amber saddle cloth, for
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is a herd of nine Tang horses for sale at E.&AMP;
J. Frankel Oriental Art at 1040 Madison Ave. and there are a few
more at the Alvin Lo Gallery, 5 East 57th St.
</P>
<P>
   China's love affair with the horse probably began in the Shang
dynasty (circa 1600 to 1100 B.C.), when real horses and human
charioteers were interred with Shang emperors. Initially, the
Chinese had only small, sturdy horses they used as draft animals.
After the Chinese were attacked by enemies riding larger, stronger
horses, they began importing horses from the Middle East, breeding
them and training them for warfare and sport.
</P>
<P>
   This all came together in the Tang dynasty. Mario Prodan wrote
in ``The Art of the Tang Potter'' (Viking, 1961), ``This is China's
moment of greatness, artistic, political, military and cultural.''
He continued, ``Whenever the Chinese dream of imitating nature, of
achieving the unbroken line, may have begun, it is certain that it
is at last fulfilled in the art of the Tang potter.''
</P>
<P>
   The horse was a favorite subject of these artists, but the horse
has always been a source of inspiration in China. Chinese composers
and poets wrote songs and poems about horses, and artists painted
them, carved their portraits in stone and created pottery
sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Tang pottery pieces are the most valued of Chinese horse
sculptures. They range in price from a few thousand dollars to
millions. Unlike jade, a Tang horse offers a buyer a certain
comfort level because thermoluminescence tests can prove its age
and fakes can be detected.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of these works was proved again in Christie's New
York sale of Chinese sculpture on Sept. 16. One horse, which was
estimated to sell for $60,000 to $80,000, went for $266,500.
</P>
<P>
   Unglazed, it had its head lowered toward its left foreleg, which
was slightly raised. There was a grooved channel running the length
of the arched neck, where a real horsehair mane would have been
inserted, and there was a hole for a horsehair tail.
</P>
<P>
   An amber glazed horse with a textured fur saddle blanket glazed
green went for $310,000. It was not unlike one that Sotheby's
London sold in 1989 for the British Rail Pension Fund for $6.1
million, the world record for a Chinese work of art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tang horses are the most widely popular image of Chinese
art,'' Lally said, ``because they are immediately accessible to
everyone. You don't have to read a book on Chinese art to love a
Tang horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the horses in the Chinese Porcelain Company show is a
cream-colored, glazed one decorated with splashes of cobalt blue.
Khalil Rizk, co-owner of the gallery, said: ``Only 5 percent of
Tang horses have blue glaze. Cobalt was put on during the last
firing. Cobalt was a treasured commodity imported from the Middle
East; it was more valuable than gold. Its use means the horse was
for someone of the highest rank.''
</P>
<P>
   This horse is 15 inches tall and turns its head to the left. It
has an ornamental harness and bridle. Originally, Rizk said, it
would have had bronze decorations as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, glazed horses used to be more sought
after, especially in Japan,'' Rizk said. ``But some horses were so
well sculpted they may have been deliberately left unglazed.''
</P>
<P>
   One unglazed horse at the show has bent its head back toward its
left shoulder in a natural pose. It would be considered a fine work
of art in any culture.
</P>
<P>
   The show continues through Oct. 28. Prices for the horses are
$35,000 to $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   CHAIRS WITH CURVES
</P>
<P>
   American antique chairs can have more curves than Marilyn
Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   As the American furniture sale at Christie's New York, set for
Thursday, approaches, Christie's experts are touting the virtues of
a high-style, finely carved Philadelphia mahogany side chair
commissioned by Gen. John Cadwalader about 1769. It is magnificent,
but the star of the sale may be Lot 185, a Queen Anne carved walnut
armchair that has been on display in the Diplomatic Reception Rooms
of the State Department for the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The chair, circa 1740-1760, belongs to George G. Meade Easby, a
descendant of its original owner, Robert Waln, a Quaker merchant in
Philadelphia. It is a study in well-executed, bold S-curves.
</P>
<P>
   The arms have knuckle grips that look like fiddlehead ferns. The
cabriole legs have shells carved on the knees. The crest has double
scrolls, and the elbow rests are rounded and concave. The estimate
is $600,000 to $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   The chair is marked No. 1, and thought to be part of a set that
is represented in the Chipstone Foundation and the Kaufman
collection, two important American furniture repositories.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen Anne chair could be paired with a handsome Queen Anne
carved walnut games table, circa 1740, in Sotheby's sale of
American furniture next Friday. The table has rounded ``turret''
corners, carved shells on its knees, and claw and ball feet. The
estimate is $30,000 to $50,000. This pair could really make a
statement in the right environment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
