<SLUG> BC-WEB-TRAFFIC-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY HAS EQUATION TO SOLVE LIVE CONCERT, NET CONGESTION WOES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Saturday beginning at 3 p.m. Eastern standard time, millions
of people worldwide are expected to log on to their computers for a
seven-hour concert billed by its promoters as the largest Internet
event in history.
</P>
<P>
   The concert's Web site _ NetAid.org _ is poised to handle one
million hits per minute, delivering 125,000 streams of live video
per second of music megastars from David Bowie to Sheryl Crow
performing in New York, London, and Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, sites for the 1998 Winter Olympic games and World
Cup soccer matches were each configured to handle less than
one-tenth of the traffic expected for NetAid, which, in addition to
being a benefit for poverty eradication programs worldwide, is also
meant to be the ultimate test of the Internet's capacity.
</P>
<P>
   What's expected to keep NetAid's Webcast from melting under the
intense heat of unpredictable surges of traffic? The ``secret
sauce'' is a mathematical equation developed by professors and
students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   That equation, now embodied in a mindboggling computer program
tens of thousands of lines long, belongs to Akamai Technologies
Inc., a small startup nestled in Cambridge's Technology Square and
founded by MIT whizzes.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works. Traffic for any Web site is handled through
computers called servers that can be located anywhere. Generally,
however, each Web site's traffic and its servers are centrally
coordinated by a single traffic cop. Akamai's algorithm
dramatically multiplies the number of traffic cops by giving each
server the ability to direct data by independently calculating a
workable route. This helps to keep information flowing and prevent
flash crowds from crushing the site.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds simple. But the ability to accommodate uncontrollable,
unpredictable, massive flows of traffic is tremendously complex
because it involves an infinite number of constantly changing
variables.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, events such as the Victoria's Secret Webcast
fashion show in February and the Olympics site crumpled un-
</P>
<P>
   der the burden of unforeseen traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, computer scientists have been stymied over the
problem of figuring out the best way to prevent crashes on the Web.
That dilemma prompted a conversation on the topic in 1995 between
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, and Tom
Leighton, a tenured math professor at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the best answer is not the most perfect answer,
according to Paul Sagan, president of Akamai and a second cousin of
Carl Sagan, the late astronomer. So instead of relying on an
equation that required knowledge of all variables, the Akamai
network functions on computers that require a far more limited
amount of information to make routing decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A partial answer based on limited information works just as
well as a perfect answer based on all the information,'' Sagan
said. ``Now what you have is a global solution that can fix
Internet traffic problems now demonstrated in what will be the
largest Internet event ever.''
</P>
<P>
   So on Saturday, all hands will be on deck at Akamai for NetAid,
the most public test thus far of the company's abilities.
Technicians will huddle in Akamai's network operations center, a
room that resembles a NASA command control center. Filled with
about 30 monitors, the room's computers function as air-traffic
control for the entire Internet, monitoring data flows, checking on
the status of the Internet, and calculating the capacity of any
given node on the 'net _ all in real time. (On any given day,
Akamai's network manages Internet traffic flows for megasites such
as CNN, Yahoo!, and Go Network, sometimes steering as much as half
a billion hits in just 24 hours.)
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the concert, the NetAid site is set up to handle
1,000 donations per second in a virtual marriage of e-commerce and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The site's sponsors, Cisco Systems Inc., Akamai, KPMG Peat
Marwick, and the United Nations Development Programme, won't say
how much money is likely to be raised to combat poverty. But every
dollar donated will go directly into a foundation, rather than be
used to help pay for the event. Cisco, which spearheaded the event
as a way to show off its technological prowess, is donating 1,500
servers housed in 90 data centers in 15 countries. Akamai will
donate its ``secret sauce,'' as Sagan puts it, to keep data flowing
at the Web site, which was desgined gratis by KPMG.
</P>
<P>
   The concert is expected to culminate in a simultaneous crooning
by dozens of pop artists of ``New Day,'' a song by Wyclef Jean and
Bono.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, making sure that Internet surfers catch every
note, will be Sagan and his crew of programmers. Asked what it was
like to be involved in the event, Sagan recalled a day in August
when the site was announced and he found himself sitting on a dais
for a press conference with Kofi Annan, secretary general of the
United Nations, rap musician Puff Daddy, and rock star David Bowie.
The glue for his brief conversations with the celebrities turned
out to be the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common ground, it turned out, wasn't politics or
Hollywood. It was the Internet,'' said a star-struck Sagan. ``It
was being Web-aware.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
