<SLUG> BC-DEPRESSION08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOST ELDERLY NOT TREATED FOR DEPRESSION
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most of the nearly 2 million elderly Americans who
suffer from severe depression are not treated, the National
Institute of Mental Health reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Left untreated, depression has major implications for the
elderly, whose rates of suicide in 1996 were more than five times
the national average of 10.8 per 100,000 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depression often goes undetected because few people recognize
that it is a real, common, and diagnosable illness that can be
effectively treated,'' said Michael Faenza, president and chief
executive officer of the National Mental Health Association.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, 19 million Americans experience depression each year,
but the nation's senior citizens are the hardest hit. Only 10
percent of the elderly with depression receive treatment, Faenza
said.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors who suffer from heart disease, strokes, cancer, chronic
lung disease, arthritis, Alzheimer's and Parkinson's disease are
more likely to suffer from depression, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elderly represent a population where the hidden symptoms
of depression can unfortunately be even further hidden behind other
illnesses that commonly occur with increasing age,'' Faenza said.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeon General David Satcher said that while the elderly make
up 13 percent of the nation's population, they account for 20
percent of all suicides.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the surgeon general showed that the highest rate of
suicide occurs in white males over the age of 85 and that suicide
rates tend to be higher among senior citizens who are divorced or
widowed. The report also found that nearly three-fourths of elderly
suicide victims had visited a doctor within a month before their
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of older Americans treated for mental illnesses
received care from general physicians, while 3 percent were treated
by mental health professionals, according to Faenza.
</P>
<P>
   The National Mental Health Association and other health
organizations offered educational meetings and screening sites
throughout the country at local senior centers, churches, and many
businesses Thursday, which was National Depression Screening Day.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
