<HEADLINE>
`SENSATION' IN A CHILD'S EYES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the inception of ``Sensation: Young British
Artists From the Saatchi Collection,'' the Brooklyn Museum of Art
has planned extensive educational programs to explain to the public
_ and to schoolchildren _ what this show of young British artists'
work is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Although the museum always offers educational programs pegged to
specific exhibitions, given the provocative nature of ``Sensation''
and the fact that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani declared that the show
includes ``sick stuff'' and cut off the museum's financing,
decoding the art seems more important than ever.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a comprehensive array of lectures and films with
artists, critics and curators, the museum also has what it calls
its ``Ask Me Team,'' volunteers, many of them graduate students in
art history, who are visible in the galleries wearing T-shirts that
say ``Ask Me'' on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never done this before,'' said Deborah Schwartz, the
museum's vice director for education and program development. ``But
this show just cried out for it.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to be part of the ``Ask Me Team,'' Ms. Schwartz said,
the volunteers were briefed by curators and made to read critical
articles pertaining to the artists' works. They discussed with
museum experts the kinds of questions they should expect and how to
respond.
</P>
<P>
   The curators also wrote different kinds of labels than they
would have for a tamer show. ``They're not the predictable
art-historical labels,'' Ms. Schwartz said. ``Besides giving the
background of the works, each label is riddled with questions that
throw the ball back in the viewer's court.''
</P>
<P>
   Educating educators is also part of the museum's agenda. On Oct.
21, it is holding an open house for college students and faculty to
explain the exhibition. So far, Ms. Schwartz said, the museum has
had a handful of high school groups scheduled to see the show and
have received inquiries from about 25 more schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just revving up,'' she said, adding that the museum makes
sure the teachers have seen either the exhibition or the catalog
before taking their classes. They have also drafted a letter for
teachers to send to parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a recommendation on how to deal with all of this,''
Ms. Schwartz said. ``Often schools want to take children to this
show to discuss the art, but some teachers are interested in seeing
it as a current affairs trip, given all they've read in the
newspaper.'' All school tours are guided by a museum educator.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is also implementing a student critics' program,
where interested high school students will have the chance to
explore the exhibition in an eight-week after-school course that
will teach them not only how to look at art, but also how to write
about it and criticize it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel these programs are particularly important,'' Ms.
Schwartz said. ``This is a special exhibition. It's not
`Impressionists in Winter.''' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Test for Lead
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 27, the New York City Department of Health received a
complaint about ``144 Lead Squares'' a 1969 sculpture by the
minimalist artist Carl Andre that was displayed on view on the
Museum of Modern Art's third floor.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 28, inspectors went to the museum to look at the piece
and performed what they called a ``dust wipe test.'' The test
revealed that the sculpture contained in excess of 1,000 micrograms
of lead per square foot, which could be dangerous if children
touched the sculpture and then put their hands in their mouthes.
</P>
<P>
   So the Health Department asked the Modern to change the label on
the sculpture, which had read, `This may be walked on.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Addison, the Modern's deputy director for marketing
and communications, said that after the inspection, curators
removed the label that had encouraged visitors to walk on the
sculpture and posted a guard nearby.
</P>
<P>
   After all the fuss, the museum closed the third floor as planned
so it could install ``Modern Starts: Places,'' a show that opens
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was in response to a mother and her child who were in the
museum,'' said Sandra Mullen, a spokeswoman for the health
department. ``Obviously we're in the business of monitoring
situations where lead dust could pose a hazard. We worked out an
agreeable solution with the museum.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Rauschenberg Gift
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Museum of Modern Art's recent acquisitions all
come from trustees. Except one: Robert Rauschenberg's ``Hiccups,''
a 1978 work consisting of 97 drawings on sheets of handmade paper
that extends nearly 63 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Although a collector had approached Arne Glimcher, Rauchenberg's
dealer, wanting to buy ``Hiccups,'' the artist gave the work to the
San Francisco museum in honor of its greatest benefactor, Phyllis
Wattis.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wattis, a museum trustee, has helped the board buy countless
artworks. Most recently, she was the driving force that enabled the
institution to acquire Eva Hesse's ``Sans II,'' from 1968, and
``Cold Mountain 6 (Bridge),'' a 1989-91 painting by Brice Marden,
which comes from the artist's own collection.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has also been given a fractional gift of 19 works by
contemporary British artists. They are being given over time by
Vicki and Kent Logan, Bay Area collectors who have already donated
works from their vast contemporary art collection to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Many artists that make up the gift are currently in the
``Sensation'' show at the Brooklyn Museum. Included in the group is
Damien Hirst's ``Philip (The Twelve Disciples),'' a 1994 work of a
skinned bull's head suspended in formaldehyde in a white-framed
vitrine.
</P>
<P>
   There are also works from other young British artists like
Tracey Emin, who is a finalist for this year's Turner Prize, along
with Gary Hume, Marc Quinn and Rachel Whiteread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus on contemporary collecting remains rather intense,''
said David A. Ross, the museum's director. ``It's one area where we
can still compete with other museums.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
