<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Final Bow? Not for Now &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The end, it seems, is not quite nigh for ``Epic
Proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, things didn't look good for the Larry
Coen-David Crane comedy that opened last week at the Helen Hayes
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The play, about the filming of a 1930s biblical epic, received
some scathing reviews, a lukewarm box office during previews and
speculation was rife that the intermission had been cut to keep
audiences from fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   But this week its producers were maintaining a beatific outlook,
saying that those expecting a quick exit would be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' said Mark Schwartz, a producer, when asked
if the show would close soon. ``We have no intention of closing at
all. We have every indication that we'll run.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the positive signs that Schwartz cited are the
consistent increase in daily sales, or wraps, from about $18,000 on
Oct. 1, the day after opening, up to about $26,000 on Tuesday.
While those figures are peanuts by Broadway standards, Schwartz
says they signal a strong word of mouth for the show.
</P>
<P>
   Good television reviews and kind words from Rosie O'Donnell were
helping the box office, he said, as was Crane's reputation as a
creator of the television show ``Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd gone the other way, if we took any steps backward,
that would be a signal to worry,'' Schwartz said. ``But that didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the show's favor, he said, is a low running cost _ about
$130,000 a week _ plus generally fawning reviews for Kristin
Chenoweth, the show's star. (A review in Variety described her as
``charm incarnate.'')
</P>
<P>
   The good spin notwithstanding, the Broadway community doesn't
seem to be betting on ``Proportions.'' Martin Markinson, who owns
the theater, said that the day the play's reviews came out he was
approached by at least half a dozen producers looking for homes for
their shows if ``Proportions'' closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's no indication to me at all that they're leaving,''
he said. ``They seem to be sticking around.''
</P>
<P>
   A Space Problem
</P>
<P>
   Things were not so upbeat for the thriller ``Voices in the
Dark,'' the first show of the season and its first casualty; it
will close on Sunday. Like the ``Proportions'' people, the
producers of ``Voices'' said they had hoped their play would
overcome its generally poor reviews with good word of mouth. That
didn't happen. Crews will start striking the play's hot tub, fake
snow and stage blood on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The closing makes the Longacre Theater available and by all
accounts a strong contender for the theater is ``Jar the Floor,''
Cheryl West's comedy about four generations of African-American
women.
</P>
<P>
   The play finished a monthlong run at Second Stage in
mid-September, and the producer, Elizabeth McCann, is to meet with
the Longacre's owner, the Shubert Organization, next week. Ms.
McCann was making no predictions, but said on Wednesday that she
had ``a sneaking hunch'' the play would get a green light.
</P>
<P>
   But Broadway was not the first choice. Ms. McCann had approached
the Promenade, which is Off Broadway, but that theater was promised
to ``If Memory Serves,'' a play by Jonathan Tolins.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there aren't any other Off Broadway theaters available,''
Ms. McCann said.
</P>
<P>
   That is a complaint echoing across the city, as producers
scramble to shift well-reviewed, good-selling shows to larger
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   In the East Village, for example, ``Do You Come Here Often?,''
by the British comedy duo the Right Size, will close at Performance
Space 122 this weekend. Despite positive response from ticket
buyers and critics, a transfer to another theater has not
materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Sprecher, owner of the Promenade and Variety Arts and
manager of the Lucille Lortel, said there were a dozen shows
financed and ready to go that could not find theaters.
</P>
<P>
   And that even with new spaces emerging. The Salon, a 270-seat
house at 49 Bleecker Street in Greenwich Village, opened last month
with an adaptation of ``Tale of Two Cities.'' The theater was built
over the summer in a space previously occupied by a lumberyard. In
November it will be home to the performance group Squonk, which
finished a successful run at Performance Space 122 in August.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some veterans of the Off Broadway scene say a surfeit
does not guarantee satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there an enormous glut of shows?'' said Alan Schuster, the
manager of three Off Broadway theaters. ``Yes, but not quality
shows. If I had empty theaters, I wouldn't be rushing to book
them.''
</P>
<P>
   And She Bakes
</P>
<P>
   Well, just call her Betty Crocker.
</P>
<P>
   For the last month, Amy Sedaris has been serving double duty on
the set of ``The Country Club,'' Douglas Carter Beane's play at the
Greenwich House Theater. First, she acts. Then, every night after
the show, she helps to sell her homemade vanilla cupcakes in the
lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' Ms. Sedaris said, in her typically high (OK,
atmospheric) spirits. ``And I go home with 25 bucks in my pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this kooky comic demeanor that Ms. Sedaris is channeling
into the character of Froggy, an uptight, unhinged party planner.
In particular, critics have adored Ms. Sedaris' use of her jaw,
which juts and ruts throughout her performance. ``It's called ...
`mugging,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The role is a departure for Ms. Sedaris, who generally performs
in shows written by herself and her brother, the writer David
Sedaris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so used to making it all up in my head,'' she said. ``This
is like, `No pressure.'''
</P>
<P>
   She leaves the show on Oct. 23 to continue work on her Comedy
Central show, ``Strangers With Candy,'' in which she plays a
46-year-old high schooler. She says she'll miss the play. ``It's
nice,'' she said. ``I get to wear clothes that fit me and play a
grown-up.''
</P>
<P>
   A Hit
</P>
<P>
   A candidate for Off Broadway's first commercial hit of the
season: ``The Vagina Monologues,'' Eve Ensler's one-woman show,
which opened on Sunday on the downstairs stage at the Westside
Theater. The advance has topped $200,000, said David Stone, the
show's producer.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
