<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: FOR HALLOWEEN, UNIVERSAL STUDIOS HORROR, OLD AND NEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It Was Dark And Stormy. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Call it horror for the whole family. ``For the collector and the
nostalgia buff, we've got these classic monsters,'' said Craig
Kornblau, president of Universal Studios Home Video. ``For the
broad audience we've got `The Mummy,' and then we have a new
direct-to-video title, `Alvin and the Chipmunks Meet Frankenstein,'
for the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Video has opened the Halloween spigot. From New Line comes a DVD
set of all seven ``Nightmare on Elm Street'' films; from Anchor
Bay, John Carpenter's ``Halloween'' (1978) and Sam Raimi's ``Army
of Darkness'' (1993). From Artisan there are ``The Blair Witch
Project'' and ``Curse of the Blair Witch Project,'' the 44-minute
fictional documentary, a hit on the Sci-Fi Channel, that follows up
on the disappearance of the three filmmakers in the original film.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's Classic Monster Collection (on tape, no DVD)
includes ``Dracula'' (1931), ``The Wolf Man'' (1941), ``Phantom of
the Opera'' (1943), ``Creature From the Black Lagoon'' (1954),
``The Invisible Man'' (1933), ``The Mummy'' (of 1932 and not to be
confused with the 1999 ``Mummy'' mentioned above by Kornblau, which
is currently a best seller), ``Frankenstein'' (1931) and ``The
Bride of Frankenstein'' (1935).
</P>
<P>
   The last three films starred Boris Karloff. ``He was the typical
English gentleman,'' said his daughter, Sara Karloff, this week.
``Well educated, articulate, very conservative in his life style, a
very gentle human being.'' One of Karloff's last films was Peter
Bogdanovich's ``Targets'' (1968), about a horror star who quits
because he and his films can't compete with real life. ``There was
more horror on the streets than on screen,'' Ms. Karloff said.
</P>
<P>
   Karloff's 1930s horror, of course, reflected a gentler time, and
horror then and now mix interestingly in this Halloween's video
releases. ``There wasn't the promotion of violence then,'' Ms.
Karloff said. ``I would wonder about the longevity of some of
today's films 65 years later.'' However that works out, today's
horror, perhaps best exemplified by ``The Blair Witch Project,'' is
definitely of the moment. ``The classics aren't getting a new
audience,'' said critic Joe Kane, a student of the genre and editor
of the magazine Phantom of the Movies' Videoscope. ``There's
another generation now that's ripe for a certain kind of horror.
It's horror about them.''
</P>
<P>
   He dates the movement to ``Scream'' in 1996. ``We've gone to
youth horror, away from Gothic into this kind of out-there-alone
horror for a sheltered generation,'' he said. This is youth brought
up by the media, for whom reality is scary and unreal to begin
with. Fiction and nonfiction tend to blur as they do with the Blair
witch tale. ``It's sort of a mood almost,'' Kane said.
</P>
<P>
   Often it leads to extreme violence. ``I just close my eyes,''
Ms. Karloff said. ``I don't have to ride on outside elevators, and
I don't have to have to be discomfited in a movie theater.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   CHAMBERMAID ON THE TITANIC
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting a down-market offshoot of James Cameron's
blockbuster, Bigas Luna's film actually stays ashore. An
impoverished foundry worker named Horty (Olivier Martinez) goes to
Southampton, England, to watch the Titanic depart. At his hotel he
is approached by a beautiful young French chambermaid (Aitana
Sanchez Gijon, above) from the ship who needs a place to stay
before embarkation. Later in his room she tries to seduce him, but
he refuses. After the sinking, though, his recollection of that
night takes on such embroidered proportions that it draws crowds
and eventually becomes a theater production. Stephen Holden wrote
in the New York Times that the movie ``never finds a visual
vocabulary to match the elegance of its ideas.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. New Yorker. $89.95. 96 minutes. French with English
subtitles. No rating. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10 THINGS I HATE ABOUT YOU
</P>
<P>
   Fed up with the conformism and idiocy of teen-age social life,
Katrina Stratford (Julia Stiles) is the shrew of affluent Padua
High School (somewhere around Seattle). Yes, it's an adolescent
turn for Shakespeare's Kate, and in this taming she'll finally
succumb to a local rogue named Patrick Verona (Heath Ledger). Until
then it's one annoyance after another for a heroine who is ``a
breath of fresh air in the stifling materialistic atmosphere of
today's Hollywood teen-age movies'' (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Touchstone. $107.37. 97 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   THE EMPEROR'S SHADOW
</P>
<P>
   After an assassination attempt, the Chinese Emperor Ying Zheng
(Jiang Wen) orders that everyone within three miles of his retinue
be put to death. Of another bent entirely is Gao Jianli (Ge You),
Ying's boyhood friend and a musical genius who is opposed to any
form of violence. Ying would like to make Gao his court composer,
but Gao would rather die. Faced with an intractable power struggle,
``this heaving, nostril-flaring historical drama asks big questions
about imperial ambition and art, about the value of friendship
versus loyalty to one's principles'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Fox Lorber. $79.98. 116 minutes. Mandarin with English
subtitles. No rating. Release date: Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   JUST A LITTLE HARMLESS SEX
</P>
<P>
   Out of their customary sitcom setting, the travails of 20- and
30-somethings reach for a movie twist. After a night in a topless
bar, Alan (Robert Mailhouse) is driving home to his wife (Alison
Eastwood) when he gives a lift to a woman with car problems. She
turns out to be a prostitute and gives him oral sex. He gets
arrested and the film settles in for the battle between him and his
wife and his friends and her friends. ``But on the big screen,
`Just a Little Harmless Sex' looks like just a little more
television'' (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   1999. PM. $102. 98 minutes. R. Release date: Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   THE INHERITORS
</P>
<P>
   A somber rural allegory with the palette and compositional sense
of the Dutch masters, Stefan Ruzowitzky's film creates an
interesting situation when a landowner in the 1930s leaves his
property divided among seven workers who have labored on it. As if
organizing themselves into a new order weren't enough of a problem,
a mysterious old lady turns up. But, Janet Maslin wrote in The New
York Times, ``what starts out as an arrestingly sharp film with
strong political undercurrents winds up increasingly unfocused as
it goes along.'' 1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 93 minutes.
Closed captioned. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   LADIES AND GENTLEMEN . . . MR. LEONARD COHEN
</P>
<P>
   Released in 1965 by the National Film Board of Canada, Donald
Brittain and Don Owen's film features early work of the poet and
songwriter, including readings from ``A Spice Box of Earth'' and
``Flowers for Hitler.'' Winstar. $19.98. 78 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   THE FILMS OF HARUN FAROCKI
</P>
<P>
   Four titles by the German filmmaker include ``How to Live in the
German Federal Republic'' (1990, 83 minutes), 32 short scenes
designed to show a country where nothing happens without being
rehearsed or prepared; ``Videograms of a Revolution'' (1992, 107
minutes), about the fall of Romanian dictator Nicolai Ceaucescu in
1989; ``Still Life'' (1997, 56 minutes), comparing still lifes of
Dutch painters with advertising photographs, and ``Images of the
World and the Inscription of War'' (1988, 75 minutes), which
explores the failure of the Allies to bomb Auschwitz after it had
been photographed and identified from aloft by pilots. All are in
German with English subtitles. Facets. Information: (800) 331-6197
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
