<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE: ANNE STEPHENSON'S BOOK REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   ``OLD MAN IN A BASEBALL CAP'' &QL; 
By Fred Rochlin (HarperCollins, $20)
</P>
<P>
   Fred Rochlin was born and raised in Nogales, Ariz. In 1942, when
he was 19, he went to Italy with the Army Air Forces and became
navigator on a B-24 bomber, flying hideously dangerous missions
over Germany. He survived (many of his crewmates did not), and
after the war, he moved to California and became an architect,
husband and father. Years passed, until in 1994, at age 70, Rochlin
took a storytelling workshop with actor/author Spalding Gray
(``Swimming'' ``to Cambodi''a). The result is this memoir _ a
collection of stories about what happened to Rochlin during World
War II _ and a one-man show of the same name, which Rochlin has
performed in cities throughout California. There's no great finesse
to the way these stories are written nor is there any sign that
Rochlin pulls punches in offering his memories of a war that was
fought by young men in circumstances that were often as surreal as
they were horrifying. New &AMP; Notable read the book in one sitting,
which was a mistake because each story is better when it is taken
on its own terms. Some contain simple scenes that steal the thunder
of any philosophical questions that Rochlin raises. His description
of his participation in the emergency delivery of an Italian baby
is funny, moving and far more effective than the young Rochlin's
subsequent discussion with an American medic about the insanity of
war. The best moments are mere flashes _ of a young man far from
home, staying alive while his friends die and craving women,
craving sleep and doing what he's told. Today that soldier is an
old man in a baseball cap, and he has stories to tell. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``BLUE DOG MAN'' &QL; 
By George Rodrigue &UR; (STC, $50) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Explain it to us. What do you see in this little blue dog? We
know what Rodrigue sees. Dollar signs. Easy Street. He was an
established artist in Louisiana before he began painting Blue Dog
15 years ago (inspired, he says, by his deceased terrier, Tiffany,
who was black and white _ go figure), but nothing brought in the
paying customers like this stunned-looking little yipper. The
financial power of Blue Dog has become legendary: A Japanese buyer
is said to have paid $250,000 for one canvas (they start at
$10,000). Whoopi Goldberg owns one. Tom Brokaw owns one. YOU can't
own one unless you have a spare fortune sitting around, BUT YOU CAN
BUY THIS BOOK. It contains 70 new Blue Dog paintings as well as a
Blue Dog mask and some Blue Dog postcards, and darned if the dog
doesn't look pretty much the same in all of them. She is, after
all, a visual mantra, a prop dropped into changing circumstances.
The paintings are paired with Rodrigue's schlocky, autobiographical
narration, in which he tries to impart some mystical meaning to
Blue Dog and to his art. ``Deep in Blue Dog's eyes,'' he writes,
``will always lurk the hopes and longings of a melancholy people,
but, like the Cajuns, who always trained their eyes on the future,
Blue Dog must move forward.'' We don't get it, and from the look in
Blue Dog's eyes, we'd say she doesn't either. &QL; 
``THE CODE BOOK'' &QL; 
By Simon Singh (Doubleday, $24.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Singh (``Fermat's Enigma'') provides an irresistible opportunity
at the end of this volume about codes and their role in history: He
invites readers to try ``The Cipher Challenge,'' a 10-stage
progression of ciphers that will test your code-cracking skills.
The first person to submit correct answers to all stages of the
cipher will win a $15,000 prize offered by Singh, who is apparently
using his own money. As you might guess, triumph will not come
easy. Singh anticipates it will take up to a year for a winner to
emerge (New &AMP; Notable was out of the running early, left utterly
confused by the contest rules). The rest of Singh's book is
challenging reading but fascinating. He includes a section on the
Navajo code talkers of World War II, whose code was one of the very
few in history never broken. Singh also details the work of Alan
Turing, a mathematical genius whose contributions as a code breaker
during World War II were unparalleled. As with that of the code
talkers, Turing's work was kept secret for years. And although the
Navajo men eventually were honored for their efforts, Turing never
received the recognition he deserved. Instead he was persecuted for
his homosexuality, and he committed suicide at age 46. Singh traces
the human drama of secret writing from ancient Greek military
espionage to present-day computer science. Code breakers, he says,
are ``literary alchemists, a mystical tribe attempting to conjure
sensible words out of meaningless symbols.' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``POP GOES THE WEASEL'' &QL; 
By James Patterson &UR; (Little, Brown, $26.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This, we'd guess, is how James Patterson starts a novel: He
imagines the worst possible thing that can be done to a human body,
then assigns a villain to the task. In this book, there are lots of
bodies. Patterson must be exhausted. If violent death disturbs you,
it helps to imagine Morgan Freeman as Patterson's deeply moral,
likable hero, Detective Alex Cross (Freeman played Cross in the
film version of Patterson's ``Kiss the Girls''). Here Cross
investigates a series of murders and proposes marriage to his lady
friend, Christine. We know the villain is Geoffrey Shafer, a
British diplomat with a wealthy and connected wife, a computer and
a taste for what he likes to call ``fantasy murder.'' We also know
that Christine is at risk. Far be it from us to tell you what
happens, but we bet you can guess. Patterson will sign books at two
Valley stores on Oct. 27 _ the Poisoned Pen in Scottsdale and
Waldenbooks &AMP; more at 302 E. Bell Road in Phoenix. Watch the Books
calendar for details. &QL; 
You can reach Anne Stephenson at amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net,
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9759 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-SILM-SUPERSTAR-SPI &LR;      10-07 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILM-SUPERSTAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANNON'S SCHOOLGIRL STRIKES UNIVERSAL CHORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, a comedy for lapsed Catholics. ``Superstar'' finds
laughs in the trauma and ordeal of Catholic school, its repression
and, most of all, its bad plaid uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Shannon reprises her ``Saturday Night Live'' character,
plain Jane Irish Catholic school girl Mary Katherine Gallagher, who
energetically dreams of being a superstar and receiving her very
first grown-up kiss in this often hilarious, always yearning vision
of adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Katherine knows she is destined for something better than
the confines of her small town.
</P>
<P>
   Nightly she flops into bed breathily whispering ``superstar'' as
she hits the mattress. She practices kissing with the corner stop
sign and the big tree on her Catholic high school campus.
</P>
<P>
   It's at the local video store, where she works part time as a
rewinder, that Mary Katherine's big screen dreams originate.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the splendor of Hollywood with its epic, grand romances
and satisfying tales of high school vengeance in films like
``Carrie,'' Mary Katherine redefines her own life.
</P>
<P>
   And when she spies campus jock Sky (Will Ferrell), she knows
he's the one she wants for that initiating kiss.
</P>
<P>
   But Sky's popular, pretty girlfriend, Evian (Elaine Hendrix),
stands in the way. And lurking in the wings is a mysterious
stranger who rides into town on a Harley (Harland Williams) and who
has a tie to Mary Katherine's murky past.
</P>
<P>
   Director Bruce McCulloch, who made his directorial debut with
``Dog Park'' and his mark in comedy as a part of the troupe Kids In
the Hall, pushes all the irreverent buttons to keep ``Superstar''
just a bit on the edge while still exploring the sweet fantasies of
every misfit, guilt-laden Catholic school girl.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Shannon, who created the character when she attended New
York University, gives Mary Katherine a spine of steel that allows
her to break free from her soft-spoken, insecure veneer.
</P>
<P>
   There are the predictable lags in ``Superstar,'' the result of
taking a ``skit'' that works well within a 3-minute TV segment and
trying to flesh it out into a feature film.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everything that doesn't deal directly with Mary Katherine
herself _ such as her life with her grandmother, played by veteran
actress Glynis Johns _ feels tacked on, incidental and unfunny.
</P>
<P>
   While fellow ``Saturday Night Live'' actor Ferrell (``A Night At
the Roxbury'') helps with his prissy characterization of a popular
jock, it's Shannon who reigns over the 80-minute running time.
</P>
<P>
   Her Mary Katherine is so full of belief in herself, and so
unwilling to give up despite obstacles galore, that she moved the
preview audience (mostly female) to interact and talk back to the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superstar'' strikes a universal chord, no matter what rung of
the popularity ladder we were on in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Superstar. Directed by Bruce McCulloch. Written by Steven Wayne
Koren. Cast: Molly Shannon, Will Ferrell, Elaine Hendrix, Harland
Williams. Paramount Pictures. 82 minutes. Rated PG-13 for sexual
content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
