<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9767 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t BC-BAHAMAS08-COX     10-07 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAHAMAS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Damage report: Islands bouncing back
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASSAU _ The Bahamas' colonial capital is quiet now.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Floyd's 150-plus-mph winds have ceased; the seas are
as calm as a lake, and at most hotels it's business as usual,
although the pools and beaches are far from crowded.
</P>
<P>
   But evidence of Floyd's visit Sept. 14 is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   White sand, heaved onto land by a 15-foot ocean surge, was
shoveled off West Bay Street and piled 2 feet high along the sides
of the road, like snow on a Minnesota winter day.
</P>
<P>
   Trees with 5-foot-thick trunks, ripped out of the ground and
flung into front yards and parking lots, wait to be hauled off.
Most standing trees are stripped of leaves.
</P>
<P>
   On the popular esplanade west of Arawak Cay, sunbathers have to
walk around two freighters and a fishing boat that were tossed onto
the beach.
</P>
<P>
   But the bumper-to-bumper traffic is back on downtown Bay Street,
the straw market is open, and the yachts are docked in the marinas.
</P>
<P>
   Most hotels had landscape and cosmetic damage, and many had
minor roof damage, but only the Sheraton Grand is closed until next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis, the country's largest resort, is open, but the
resort's exclusive Ocean Club, hideout for celebrities such as
Denzel Washington and the setting for Cindy Crawford's wedding,
won't open until Dec. 22. Hotel officials say there was no
structural damage but a lot of downed trees and some beach erosion.
</P>
<P>
   Usually 90 percent full, Atlantis had plenty of rooms available
in all price categories last week, but there were no discounts, and
rooms were being filled for the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Compass Point, the exuberantly colored complex of cottages 12
miles west of town, was open, and rooms were booked. Some of the
cottages had saltwater damage but have been repaired.
</P>
<P>
   At Cable Beach, the Radisson and Marriott resorts were welcoming
conventions into their ballrooms, and the casino had plenty of
business.
</P>
<P>
   The Yoga Retreat on Paradise Island is open, but there was
substantial damage to the dock and to some of the cabins on the
beach.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem during my visit was an aborted trip on the new
Bahamas Fast Ferries' 177-passenger catamaran that makes daily
trips from Nassau to Eleuthera and Harbour Island. We had to turn
back because the debris in the ocean caused problems in one of the
engines.
</P>
<P>
   All cruise ships have returned to Nassau, and duty-free shops
are filled with passengers buying liquor, perfume and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Paradise Island Airport closed the day before the hurricane hit
and will not reopen. Sun International, owner of the airport, plans
to build condominiums on the site of the runways and terminal.
Nassau International Airport is open and busy.
</P>
<P>
   The only inconvenience tourists may experience is the noise
workmen make as they repair roofs and railings. The phone service
is working, but lines are often busy, and some hotel swimming pools
are being resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
   When making reservations, ask about the extent of the work being
done.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the Bahamas, call (800) 4-BAHAMA.
</P>
<P>
   ISLAND BY ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Bahamas Out Islands had little damage from Hurricane
Floyd, although power and phone service are a problem in many
places.
</P>
<P>
   The Abacos were extremely damaged, and Eleuthera and Harbour
Island were damaged, although not as bad as when Hurricane Andrew
swept through in 1992 and took the roofs off most of the houses.
</P>
<P>
   Here is an island-by-island update.
</P>
<P>
   GRAND BAHAMA ISLAND AND FREEPORT
</P>
<P>
   The airport was flooded for several days following Hurricane
Floyd but is open to emergency flights, domestic flights and small
aircraft. Parts of the island are still without phone service, but
power has been restored.
</P>
<P>
   Most hotels and resorts, including the big Bahamas Princess and
the newly renovated Lucayan Hotel, are up and running. The only
damage was downed trees and landscape burned by wind and saltwater.
The Royal Islander hotel is still being evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   The Island Palm Resort had some roof damage, but all facilities
are open to guests.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the island's beaches were eroded.
</P>
<P>
   ABACOS
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the Abacos islands had extreme damage, and reports are
still coming in. Both airports are open.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all hotels are closed. The goal for most inns and resorts
is to be open by Nov. 15, but the millennium is the most important
target because every room is booked.
</P>
<P>
   The phones are still down, and there is no electricity in
Hopetown. All hotels that are open are operating on generators.
</P>
<P>
   The Abaco Beach Resort is open but is filled with work crews.
</P>
<P>
   These hotels and inns had little damage and are open to guests:
The Ambassador Motel, D's Guest House, Island Breezes Motel, and
Marsh Harbour Airport Inn in Marsh Harbour; Hopetown Hideaways,
Turtle Hill Cottages and the Dolphin Beach Hotel in Hopetown; and
Walker's Cay Hotel in Walker's Cay.
</P>
<P>
   BIMINI
</P>
<P>
   This small island had little or no damage. All hotels are open.
</P>
<P>
   CAT ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   Both airports are open, but the island still has no power or
phone service.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the hotels are still being evaluated. Most hotels are
closed except for Hawksnest Resort.
</P>
<P>
   CROOKED ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   Information is still coming in. The two main hotels, Crooked
Island Beach Inn and Pittstown Landings, are closed. The extent of
the damage is being evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   ELEUTHERA
</P>
<P>
   The airport at North Eleuthera is open, as is the Governor's
Harbour airport although the customs and immigration building was
damaged. The Rock Sound airport is closed and being evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Governor's Harbour had severe damage, and the Glass
Window bridge is impassable.
</P>
<P>
   The Club Med here is closed until Nov. 13. Most hotels are
closed but slated to reopen in October and November. The hotels and
resorts that are open include Cambridge Villas, the Duck Inn, the
Tuckaway Hotel and Ethel's Cottages.
</P>
<P>
   HARBOUR ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   The island, which was hit hard by Hurricane Andrew in 1992, had
damage to houses, hotels and roads.
</P>
<P>
   Some hotels, including the Coral Sand Hotels, the Dunmore Beach
Hotel and the Pink Sands Hotel, had little damage but are closed
for seasonal maintenance and will open at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   Romora Bay Hotel is open. Valentine's Resort and Marina had
severe damage and has extended its regular seasonal closing from
October until Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-mile-long, pink beach, made of crushed coral, is intact,
with little erosion.
</P>
<P>
   INAGUA
</P>
<P>
   Far from Hurricane Floyd's winds, this island had no damage. The
Crystal Beach View Hotel is open for guests.
</P>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR
</P>
<P>
   The Club Med Resort had some damage and will be closed until
today. The Riding Rock Inn also was damaged and is scheduled to
open by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   LONG ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   The airport at Stella Maris is open, and power and phone service
have been restored to the island. All roads and harbors are open.
</P>
<P>
   The Stella Maris Resort and the Cape Santa Maria Beach Resort
had no major damage and are open to guests.
</P>
<P>
   EXUMA
</P>
<P>
   The airport at Georgetown is open; the island has power, and
phone service is being restored.
</P>
<P>
   Most hotels had no damage except for Club Peace and Plenty,
which lost some of its dock. The Palms at Three Sisters Hotel had
minimal damage and is expected to open today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
