<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Friday, October 8, 1999, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DELL _ The future according to Dell. Dell executives entertain
dozens of Wall Street analysts and industry experts at the Four
Seasons during the company's annual fall event. They'll update
Internet strategies, as well as plans to gain marketshare in every
customer group and region where they are competing. Analyst
response. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   KOCH-TRIAL _ The Koch brothers, two of whom are twins, are suing
each other over funds from the company. Koch Industries, the second
largest privately owned company in the country with annual revenues
of $30-35 billion. (Cohen, Palm Beach Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   w/KOCH-FAMILY _ TULSA _ Based in Wichita, Kan., Koch Industries
is the second-largest privately held company in the United States,
after Cargill. According to a December article in Forbes magazine,
it is a $35 billion business with estimated profits of $700
million. The company ranks 18th on the Forbes 500, right behind
Chevron, Procter &AMP; Gamble and DuPont. The company's main business
is oil and gas. It has refineries in Corpus Christi, Texas, and
near St. Paul, Minn., and is among the world's largest oil traders.
(Cohen, Palm Beach Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WIRED-CITIES _ Atlanta ranks fifth among the nation's most
Internet-accessible cities, and thus is well-positioned to grow
economically in the coming years, according to a study by geography
specialists at Ohio State University. The other top five cities, in
order, are Washington, Chicago, Dallas, and New York The rest of
the top ten are San Jose, Los Angeles, Houston, San Francisco and
Phoenix. Researchers measured accessibility by the number of
Internet connections to and from each city through 31 major
commercial Internet backbones, ranging from giants like AT&AMP;T and
Sprint as well as ISPs like Mindspring. Cities with the most
connections were rated as most accessible. According to the survey,
``In general, cities with more linkages to the Internet backbone
will have faster access and more reliable connections to global
information. This enhanced access results in a comparative
advantage will grow in importance with the continuing global
computerization of information.'' (Holsendolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WEBVAN _ Online grocer Webvan gets slapped by the SEC for
violating its quiet period by talking to the press. Atlanta
residents can't buy tomatoes online yet, but there are plenty of
other dry goods available for purchase from several online grocery
purveyors including Peapod Netgrocer and even Walmart. A look at
the viability and long term outlook for this vertical industry.
(Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   FRITOLAY _ ATLANTA _ The 34-year-old Frito-Lay plant on
Peachtree Industrial is closing Friday. When Lay's Potato Chip Co.
founder Herman Warden Lay opened it in 1965, it represented both
state-of-the-art food manufacturing technology and the prosperity
that enveloped Atlanta after World War II. (Harte, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
