<HEADER>
A9769 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-ROPES08-COX     10-07 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-ROPES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Ropes' portrays game of life as a fight to the finish
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``On the Ropes'' is a powerful inner-city
melodrama, whose central subject, boxing, is a self-contained
metaphor for bare-knuckling it out of the projects. Set in
Brooklyn, the engrossing documentary follows three young fighters
and a gentle trainer on their common pilgrimage to bootstrap
redemption. ``The street is tougher than any gym,'' one of them
says, and there you have it.
</P>
<P>
   In Nanette Burstein and Brett Morgen's deft film,
sweat-and-blood pugilism takes ringside, as the human stories bound
into high-relief with each triumph, setback, disappointment and, in
one boxer's case, dream-shattering tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Ropes'' describes the wavering arcs of its four
subjects over the course of about a year. There's George Walton, a
Golden Gloves winner, whose life is in reasonably good shape as he
aims for the pros. Welterweight Noel Santiago is a flaky,
opaque-eyed teen, who's repeated the ninth grade three times and
lives with his formerly crack-addicted mom. Unlike the others, his
eyes are innocent of fire.
</P>
<P>
   The sole woman, Tyrene Manson, is a fierce, talented boxer
saddled by her duties to her teen sisters and drug-addicted,
AIDS-riven uncle. And trainer Harry Keitt is a former crack-addict
and convicted murderer who hopes to ride one of their stars to
deliverance. When this second-chancer says, ``I want to go forward
so bad,'' it's a jab to the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Bashing bags and crunching abs, the fighters weave through the
Bed-Stuy Boxing Club to train and receive counsel from the stolid
Keitt, who's as much pastor as prodder.
</P>
<P>
   Some situations are out of his hands. Noel cuts school and skips
the gym. George drops Harry for a slick new manager. And Tyrene, in
the film's most compelling plotline, might have to sacrifice her
Golden Gloves bout _ and a chunk of her life _ if she's convicted
of possession of and intent to sell crack. (The filmmakers try to
sway us, but they present a porous case for her innocence. They do,
though, provide a horrifying look at an inner-city court
procedure.)
</P>
<P>
   With all its inherent trials and glints of uplift, ``On the
Ropes'' dispenses the warm satisfaction of full-bodied fiction. A
nit: Some scenes are obviously set up and vaguely choreographed for
narrative fluidity. It amounts to sabotage in a pure documentary,
and makes you wonder what else the filmmakers conveniently
manipulated. Such dishonesty is a bit of raging bull in what's
otherwise a frank and moving knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
