<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9772 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS &LR;      10-07 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON COMPLETES LEGAL REQUIREMENT FOR N.Y. CANDIDACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton completed the
legal requirements to run for the Senate from New York Thursday by
filing a ``statement of candidacy'' that enables her to double the
amount of money she can legally raise from campaign donors and
political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   While the first lady was traveling in Europe, her lawyer mailed
the legal document to the secretary of the U.S. Senate. The
document is automatically relayed to the Federal Election
Commission (FEC).
</P>
<P>
   The low key approach relying on the U.S. Postal Service was in
sharp contrast to the hoopla that accompanied Clinton's submission
of paperwork to the FEC on July 6 announcing that she was forming
an exploratory campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signed her statement of candidacy on Sunday before
leaving for a six-day trip to Poland, Slovakia, Italy and Iceland.
She returns to the United States on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Clinton's Senate campaign spokesman, called the
filing ``another step forward in the process'' of running for the
Senate, adding: ``Hillary Clinton gets more and more excited about
the possibility of running every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson said Clinton has not made a decision on the timing of a
public declaration of candidacy _ an announcement that would
trigger the legal requirement that news media outlets provide equal
time to rival candidates.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of her statement of candidacy, Clinton will be
required to submit campaign finance reports to the FEC by Jan. 31
accounting for six months of fund raising between July 1 and Dec.
31.
</P>
<P>
   Since Labor Day she has raised more than $2 million for her
prospective Senate campaign, according to campaign officials, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans an ambitious schedule of fund raising after
returning from Europe, with fund-raising events for Democratic
organizations in three New York counties followed by a $1
million-plus ``Broadway for Hillary'' birthday bash on Oct. 25
hosted by talk show host Rosie O'Donnell and actor Nathan Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a native of Illinois and former first lady of Arkansas,
will celebrate her 52nd birthday on Oct. 26. She and her husband
are buying a $1.7 million five-bedroom home in Chappaqua, N.Y.,
with closing set for Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's expected Republican rival, New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, took the same formal steps of candidacy in April in a
move that required him to submit campaign spending reports to the
FEC on June 30. That report showed that he had raised $2.8 million
in the first six months of 1999 and had $2.6 million on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Experts forecast that each candidate in the showcase Senate race
of 2000 will spend $25 million _ making the $50 million battle to
succeed retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., the most
expensive U.S. Senate race in history.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration of candidacy ``puts us in the same situation as
Giuliani,'' Wolfson said. ``It's what other Senate candidates have
typically done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By submitting statements of candidacy, Clinton and Giuliani
become free to double their fund raising take from each donor.
During the exploratory phase of a Senate campaign, each candidate
is limited to accepting $1,000 from each donor for a prospective
Senate primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But by filing a statement of candidacy for the general election,
each candidate can then raise $1,000 from each contributor for the
prospective primary contest and another $1,000 for the general
election in November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Each candidate also can also double the amount of money
permitted to be raised from a political action committee, with
$5,000 for a theoretical primary fight and another $5,000 for the
final campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton nor Giuliani is expected to face a serious
challenger in New York state's primary next September.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's statement of candidacy came amid continuing evidence
in public opinion polls that the Clinton-Giuliani race remains a
statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion reported Thursday
that a statewide telephone poll of 702 registered voters completed
Monday showed Giuliani leading Clinton, 46 percent to 42 percent.
The survey's margin of error was plus or minus 4 percentage points,
meaning that the two candidates are locked in a statistical dead
heat _ a finding replicated by other recent statewide surveys.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
