<P>
   The declaration of candidacy ``puts us in the same situation as
Giuliani,'' Wolfson said. ``It's what other Senate candidates have
typically done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By submitting statements of candidacy, Clinton and Giuliani
become free to double their fund raising take from each donor.
During the exploratory phase of a Senate campaign, each candidate
is limited to accepting $1,000 from each donor for a prospective
Senate primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But by filing a statement of candidacy for the general election,
each candidate can then raise $1,000 from each contributor for the
prospective primary contest and another $1,000 for the general
election in November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Each candidate also can also double the amount of money
permitted to be raised from a political action committee, with
$5,000 for a theoretical primary fight and another $5,000 for the
final campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton nor Giuliani is expected to face a serious
challenger in New York state's primary next September.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's statement of candidacy came amid continuing evidence
in public opinion polls that the Clinton-Giuliani race remains a
statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion reported Thursday
that a statewide telephone poll of 702 registered voters completed
Monday showed Giuliani leading Clinton, 46 percent to 42 percent.
The survey's margin of error was plus or minus 4 percentage points,
meaning that the two candidates are locked in a statistical dead
heat _ a finding replicated by other recent statewide surveys.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
