<SLUG> BC-FILM-LIMEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIMEY' FEATURES KNOCK-OUT PERFORMANCES BY STAMP, FONDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word is that Steven Soderbergh had so much fun adapting
Elmore Leonard's novel, ``Out of Sight,'' into an Oscar-nominated
critical hit last summer that he decided to try it again _ only
this time without a Leonard novel as his source material.
</P>
<P>
   The result _ ``The Limey'' _ isn't as much fun as Soderbergh's
last sojourn into the Leonard-esque land of small-time hoods and
low-life losers: the dialogue is not as snappy, the plot not as
enjoyably convoluted or emotionally satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the movie works, and is noteworthy for its daring,
non-linear, story-telling style, and its knock-out performances
from two icon stars of the '60s, who happen to be in the midst of
impressive career comebacks in their 60s _ Terence Stamp and Peter
Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   Stamp plays Wilson, an aging, Cockney ex-con who, after a decade
behind bars, leaves London for Los Angeles, where his beloved
daughter, Jenny, has recently died, according to a letter from one
of her friends, ``under mysterious circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   In L.A., Wilson quickly concludes that the man responsible for
Jenny's death is wealthy record producer Terry Valentine (Fonda),
who, despite a lavish lifestyle, is financially over-extended and
currently involved in a big drug deal.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the movie follows Wilson _ at first, very much the
fish out of water _ as he adapts to his new jungle environment, and
soon proves brutally effective in it, making his own set of allies
and consistently besting the killers sent to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   As written by Lem Dobbs, it's a familiar enough formula-revenge
piece, and the script lacks both the structural tightness and comic
unity of the Leonard novels, and of the more entertaining of the
Leonard movie adaptations _ ``Get Shorty,'' ``Stick'' and ``Out of
Sight.''
</P>
<P>
   But Soderbergh heightens the material with the kind of fractured
storytelling approach that he hasn't really used much since his
``sex, lies &AMP; videotape'' days _ constantly flashing backward and
forward in time, and deconstructing scenes as we're watching them.
</P>
<P>
   Much more than ``Out of Sight,'' this Soderbergh film is an
actor's movie, and works off the inspired performances from Stamp,
a marvelously determined hero (and totally convincing in his
natural Cockney dialect); and Fonda, as a shallow, charming, rather
silly villain stuck in his glory days of the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   In another of the film's innovations, Soderbergh uses cuts of
the 28 year-old Stamp from the 1967 Ken Loach film, ``Poor Cow''
(in which Stamp also plays a crook named Wilson) as flashbacks and
parts of the character's stream-of-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   It's a risky device that, in lesser hands, might have seemed a
clumsy gimmick. But Soderbergh makes it work, and it not only gives
his movie a thrilling authenticity, it makes ``The Limey'' a subtle
tribute to Stamp's special contribution to the movies of the past
four decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Limey. Directed by Steven Soderbergh. Written by Lem Dobbs.
Cast: Terence Stamp, Peter Fonda, Barry Newman, Luis Guzman, Lesley
Ann Warren. Artisan. 89 minutes. Rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1733EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CLEMENTE-GUGGENHEIM-9     10-07 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEMENTE-GUGGENHEIM-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DREAMY SENSUALITY BRIDGES TIME AND CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, India)  (js) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Francesco Clemente is the youngest artist to be given
the full-rotunda treatment by the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum. In
recent years Claes Oldenburg, Ellsworth Kelly and Robert
Rauschenberg have filled the place to overflowing and, in
particular, have imprinted the rotunda with an indelible sense of
their styles.
</P>
<P>
   Now Clemente, the Italian painter of East-meets-West dream
images that delve into the mind, the body and many forms of love,
is taking his turn. The show has been organized by Lisa Dennison,
the museum's deputy director and chief curator, and spans 25 years
in more than 400 works. It ranges restlessly from oil-on-canvas to
fresco to pastel and beyond, including clusters of small drawings
and paintings as well as examples of the artist's collaborations.
The work reflects a life divided between New York, Italy and India,
and is by turns mystical, anguished, stylish, simplistically
illustrational and conventionally beautiful; an extended suite of
luscious little watercolors from 1985, for example, could have been
made by almost anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting show is, overall, a sweet, meandering affair that
suggests Clemente as a people-pleasing cross between Andy Warhol
and David Hockney. It is impossible to dislike, but hard to get
passionate about. While the show contains more than its share of
orifices, they rarely shock or disrupt the prevailing gentility.
</P>
<P>
   What would have helped? Judicious editing, a traditionally
chronological rather than thematic installation and a serious
catalog. The existing catalog weighs a ton but is mostly fluff; the
best read is Rene Ricard's doting, dotty but detailed chronology
with its useful outline of the artist's development, interactions
with poets, artists and musicians and many travels.
</P>
<P>
   But a little strangeness counts. Clemente is among the few
figurative painters to be set loose in the rotunda recently, and
his work gives the place a pleasantly old-fashioned feeling, like a
retrospective of Klee or Chagall. (Not surprising, as their
schematized, dreamy images are among his precedents.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clemente is an artist without a formal invention
that one can easily point to or that makes his art sing out in
unison from the museum's spiral. What he has achieved is unusual: a
carefully modulated cacophony of disparate mergers and bridgings
between cultures, periods, media, ways of thought and life. At
their best his works can be richly suggestive as well as
startlingly seamless.
</P>
<P>
   An oil painting like ``Name'' (1983) is a good example. It
depicts a monumental head of the artist, his eyes, ears, nostrils
and mouth filled with at least one small version of the same head.
The Gorgonian suggestion of souls trapped in a larger being
resonates with Eastern philosophy and Western angst, and the
duality seems reiterated by the background. To one side is a vivid
blue sky seen through a horizontal window that suggests a train
barreling across India, to the other side a classical column,
redolent of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Clemente is that almost unheard of hybrid, a 1980s art
star for the '90s. Unlike many of his contemporaries, among them
David Salle, Julian Schnabel and Anselm Kiefer, he recalls some of
the decade's excitement but is relatively untainted by its
excesses.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Naples in 1952, Clemente grew up in a 17th-century
palazzo, wrote poetry as a child, and at 22 went to Rome to study
architecture. Attracted to the art of Joseph Beuys and Cy Twombly,
he began to draw incessantly, making notational autobiographical
works of a conceptual bent. His chief mentor was Alighiero e
Boetti, an Arte Povera artist who hit on the idea of having maps
and blocky alphabets converted into lavish embroideries or
tapestries by craftsmen in Afghanistan. This arrangement helped
inspire Clemente's early travels to India in the mid 1970s, when he
began to find himself as an artist.
</P>
<P>
   Clemente emerged in the late 1970s and early '80s, first in
Europe and then in the United States, in the ``return to the
figure'' that soon coalesced into Neo-Expressionism. He was a major
player in that swashbuckling episode, but there was always a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   A superficial clue is found in photographs of the artist, who
has melancholic good looks of a wan poet model and impeccable
sartorial instincts. Undoubtedly choreographed, these images tend
to show him against relatively ascetic backgrounds, in quiet,
yogalike poses or with a visionary wideness to the eyes _ a holy
man in a well-tailored suit. (He had a cameo role as a hypnotist in
Gus van Sant's ``Good Will Hunting.'')
</P>
<P>
   Compared with most Neo-Expressionist painting, Clemente's work
has always tended to be a less manly art: kinder, gentler, more
contemplative and inward. He shunned the strategies of
fragmentation, juxtaposition and overt appropriation that became
the stylistic hallmarks of so much art of the 1980s. There is a sly
wit but little irony in his work. Instead such '90s concerns as the
body, sexual ambiguity, otherness, sincerity and a longing for the
feminine guide many of its moods and motifs.
</P>
<P>
   The self-portrait may be Clemente's primary vehicle _ like such
artists as Carolee Schneemann, Hannah Wilke and Lucas Samaras, he
has certainly taken advantage of his own physical beauty. But his
work is also oddly egoless, drawing on timeless symbols and themes,
many non-Western. This has placed him well ahead of the nomadic,
transcultural tendencies of the '90s and reflects his prolonged
stays in India, where he has studied Eastern religion and thought,
been influenced by religious and popular art, and enlisted the
skills of different artisans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The fruits of his labors with Indian painters and papermakers
include some of his best efforts: suites of finely wrought Indian
miniatures that tackle contemporary themes, big posterish paintings
on handmade paper inspired by the bazaar painters of Madras and at
least one handmade paper environment, his lulling ``Indigo Room''
(1983-84), installed in one of the Guggenheim's tower galleries. A
peculiar blend of painting and decoration, Western avant-garde and
Eastern tradition, it evokes a nocturnal garden. Its expanses of
dark-blue paper painted with ghostly images are finished off with
plant forms of silver that seem touched by moonlight.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a signature look, Clemente has given the Guggenheim
what might be called a signature atmosphere of somnolent
laissez-faire sensuality conveyed by simplified forms, elegant
lines, uncluttered compositions and dense aromatic colors. His
figures and faces continually evoke notions of a consciousness
evolving through love. They embrace one another, meditate, perform
obscure rites or are subjected to them, merge with animals, are
pushed toward hieroglyph or symbol or simply drift across the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   The best levitating image may be ``Semen,'' a spare painting
from 1983-84 in which a simple foreshortened outline of the naked
artist floats on an expanse of raw linen, his eyes closed, his
skull defined by a mysterious wire that ends in an arrowhead. In
more Expressionistic moments, Clemente's figures virtually explode
in thick patches of oil paint and wax laid on so frantically as to
seem clawed or thickly furred. This dual animism is apparent in a
1983 painting of the artist's wife, Alba Clemente, a frequent
subject, in which her torso fills the canvas with an almost savage
power.
</P>
<P>
   The show's thematic arrangement proceeds under headings like I,
Unborn, Bestiary, Conversion to Her, Prayers and Amulets and Sky.
It is strongest in the beginning, tends to wane toward the center
and picks up again toward the upper levels and in the side
galleries. These contain the ``Indigo Room'' as well as ``Francesco
Clemente Pinxit,'' his first series of Indian miniatures (1980-91);
frescoes like ``Priapea'' (1980), where the artist seems to be
gently torn apart by plump putti, and eight paintings from his
highly personal ``Stations of the Cross'' series from 1980-81.
</P>
<P>
   The hyperventilating surfaces of these works, again in oil and
wax, suggest an intense reaction to New York life and New York
painting. Full of garish figures and faces, great gusts of color
and nightmarish urban settings, they are both demonic and
intoxicated, as if painted by someone who couldn't quite believe
what he was seeing, either in the city's streets or the studios of
his fellow artists.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to choose carefully. The first section, for
example, includes a number of small early paintings that are some
of the show's best, among them ``Self-Portrait with a Hole in the
Head'' (1981), in which both the artist and the white Rymanesque
background present bullet wounds. Nearby hang the ``New York
Muses,'' a 1993 series of portraits of women with long necks, big
eyes and bee-stung lips that seem destined for a fashion magazine.
Still, a series of somber self-portraits from 1996 has occasional
moments of emotional power, like the staring, tear-stained face of
``Grisaille Self-Portrait.''
</P>
<P>
   While the show's organization is intended to mimic Clemente's
peripatetic working methods and the multiple strands of his art, it
doesn't work. It obscures a development that personifies the way
many young artists in the late 1970s escaped the attenuated
strategies fostered by Conceptualism to actively re-engage art and
its processes and traditions. It also seems designed to distract us
from the increasing superficiality of Clemente's work after 1990,
if not 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He may have been an idiosyncratic '90s-style Neo-Expressionist,
but he seems to have done his best work during the style's feverish
heyday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9779 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HARRISON-FORD-LADN     10-07 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRISON-FORD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTOR EXPECTS TO BE AROUND AWHILE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Harrison Ford questions himself incessantly. He
can go along blissfully confident for, say, a good 15 or 20 seconds
before the doubts begin to dog his mind. The misgivings are many
and varied. He wonders about his ability as an actor. He's
skeptical about the lasting quality of his work. Here, at this very
moment, he's dubious about his ability to answer a reporter's
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capacity is always an issue,'' the reticent Ford says grimly.
</P>
<P>
   But for a man plagued by questions, Ford seems absolutely
certain about at least one thing _ his longevity. He has often
talked about how he likes to make movies and then ``go away,'' his
preferred method of skirting the machinery and self-absorption of
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   He has no plans, however, to take a permanent leave of absence
from moviemaking. Sure, he may question his capacity. But he has no
doubts about his durability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I have never been fashionable, I can never be
unfashionable,'' Ford says matter-of-factly. ``It seems I'm lucky,
too, in that even though we're in this youth-culture thing right
now, there does seem to be enough support for a few of us
geezers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is ready to label Ford, 57, a geezer, least of all Ford
himself. (He sported a somber smile when making the above comment.)
Ford continues to sport a gold stud in one ear and wears his
graying hair in an upswept, spiked style. The earring, Ford's
``favorite'' fashion accessory, was added two years ago on a whim
(``I just always wanted a pierced ear,'' he says) and wasn't an act
borne out of a late midlife crisis.
</P>
<P>
   That he wears the earring in his new romantic drama, ``Random
Hearts,'' may be part of an ongoing campaign to unsettle his
audience's perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want people to have a particular expectation of me,''
Ford says. ``I think you can see that in the movies I choose. For
me, there's always been a couple of parameters: I don't want to do
something too close to what I've done lately, and I want to do
something with ambition. And I like to skip genres, too. It keeps
people guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Sydney Pollack, who directed Ford in ``Random Hearts'' and
his earlier remake of ``Sabrina'': ``Harrison doesn't get his due
as an actor, often because the roles he chooses don't tap into the
range he's capable of showing. After all, there are only so many
ways you can run from something in a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of Ford's biggest roles have him taking flight,
whether it's from the law (``The Fugitive''), society (``The
Mosquito Coast'') or evil (``Witness''). (And let's not forget that
tenacious bounty hunter who kept following him throughout the
``Star Wars'' series.) In ``Random Hearts,'' he plays a man running
from his own perceived failures, both as a husband and as a police
officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty grown-up concept for a movie,'' Ford says.
</P>
<P>
   He'll keep that mature mood going with his next film, ``What
Lies Beneath,'' a supernatural thriller he's currently shooting
with Michelle Pfeiffer. But despite this raft of character work,
Ford says he isn't ready to turn in his running shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does he necessarily agree with Pollack in assessing his film
work. Ford, Hollywood's most famous former carpenter, approaches
each movie looking to submit himself to the role's particular
logic. It all comes down to detail and problem solving. And, to
Ford, ``Random Hearts'' was no more challenge than ``Air Force
One'' in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   Ford will likely reprise his role as Tom Clancy action hero
(sans earring) Jack Ryan sometime in the near future (probably next
year) and hopes to do another ``Indiana Jones'' movie, despite the
fact the series' producer, George Lucas, won't be free from his
``Star Wars'' commitments until 2004. That would put Ford's Indy at
62 and more likely to wear a fedora to cover a bald spot than to
make a fashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   But if Ford has any reservations about a sexagenarian Jones,
he's keeping them _ like so many other things _ to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm capable of faking all the things I've faked before,'' Ford
said. ``I mean, I don't want to come to the point where it becomes
ludicrous, but I think we're far from that at this time. There are
a lot of examples of people near my age doing that sort of thing.
Sean (Connery) is one who leaps to mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Scott Thomas, who remembers thrilling to Ford's heroics
in ``Star Wars'' when she was a 16-year-old girl, says, that as far
as she's concerned, Ford could play Indiana Jones as an 80-year-old
and still bring something to the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are magical on screen sort of stay that way
forever,'' says Scott Thomas, who also played Robert Redford's love
interest last year in ``The Horse Whisperer.'' ``Think about Cary
Grant. When he was ancient, he was still, oooooh, so fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant was 62 when he walked away from film, bored by the paucity
of challenging roles coming his way. That's not a problem at the
moment for Ford. He makes only one movie a year and tries to work
after his two children, Georgia, 9, and Malcolm, 12, have returned
to school. His 16-year marriage to screenwriter Melissa Mathison
rates as such a priority that Ford will turn down movies he feels
would take away too much time from home. Thus, Ford reportedly
passed when friend Steven Spielberg asked him to go off to Europe
and make ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Ford has famously turned down leads in
``JFK,'' ``The Hunt for Red October,'' ``Ghost,'' ``The Mirror Has
Two Faces,'' and (wisely) ``I Love Trouble.'' Limiting his schedule
has not limited his options, however. Oprah Winfrey made that
presumption once, producing the following exchange:
</P>
<P>
   Oprah: Do you accept films that don't have a lot of action in
them? I mean, when they come, do you look for as much action as you
can find?
</P>
<P>
   Ford: Did you ever see me beat Sabrina?
</P>
<P>
   That's where Ford finds himself today _ throwing fewer punches,
dishing out the occasional punch line, but mostly steering himself
toward the sort of decent, distant and cautious characters that
have marked his career. He has always believed himself to be an
actor, not an icon, an ``assistant storyteller,'' if you will.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being a waiter or a gas station attendant, only I'm
waiting on 6 million people a week _ if I'm lucky,'' Ford says,
again flashing that sad smile.
</P>
<P>
   And if the attractive roles stop coming his way, if he can't
find one script that interests him each year, Ford has an easy
solution. He'll take longer breaks between projects. He'll spend
more time flying his airplanes, watching his two youngest children
navigate through their high school years and enjoying his grandson.
(Ford has two older sons from his first marriage.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a grand plan for my career, never have,'' Ford
says. ``I just make it up as I go along. But, in the end, it's
work. It's not my life. It's just what I do for a living. There are
a lot more important things to worry about.'' &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
