r a !bbox! &LR; !bold! &UR; Thefilm: &LR; !     10-07 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 !bbox! !bold! The film: !off! ``The Mating Habits of the
Earthbound Human'' (R; strong sexuality and language).  
!bbox! !bold! The stars: !off! Mackenzie Astin, Carmen Electra and
David Hyde Pierce.  
!bbox! !bold! Behind the scenes: !off! Written and directed Jeff
Abugov. Released by Independent Artists.  
!bbox! !bold! Running time: !off! One hour, 30 minutes.  
!bbox! !bold! Playing: !off! Mann Westwood.  
!bbox! !bold! Our rating: !off! {!dlim!!capt!``The Mating Habits of
the Earthbound Human'' charts the progression of a relationship
between Carmen Electra and Mackenzie Astin.!dlim!!head!! `Mating
Habits' does delicate dance of opposite sexes !dlim!!by1! By  Glenn
Whipp  
!by2! Film Critic !dlim!
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !text! &LR;  ``The Mating Habits of the Earthbound Human'' (try
saying  &UR; !ital! &LR; that &UR; !off! &LR;  when you buy your ticket _ then again,
don't) attempts to appeal to people who like to watch animals do
the wild thing on the Discovery Channel. But, at the very least,
nature documentaries have a sense of wonder and surprise, two
qualities in short supply in this drab comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mating Habits'' purports to be a documentary filmed by
extraterrestrials interested in human behavior. Glibly narrated by
``Frasier's'' David Hyde Pierce, this innocuous movie follows the
relationship of The Male (Mackenzie Astin) and The Female (Carmen
Electra) from their introduction at a ``sacred meeting place''
(nightclub) through courtship and various attempts to perpetuate
the species.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the film's humor is based on the fact that the alien
narrator accepts everything he sees at face value. Thus, birth
control is seen as a natural barrier (there are several too many
shots of men _ dressed up as sperm _ running into a padded wall)
and the humans' moaning and groaning during sex is taken as pain
endured for the sake of reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   As written and directed by sitcom veteran Jeff Abugov (he has
worked as story editor on ``Cheers,'' ``My Two Dads'' and ``The
Golden Girls), ``Mating Habits'' is intermittently amusing, with
Hyde Pierce's droll narration scoring a few points before
eventually becoming tedious. The film doesn't take itself
seriously, but, because it lacks much in the way of fresh insight,
its situations too often play like a bad episode of ``Beverly Hills
90210.''
</P>
<P>
   The two leads are perfectly adequate, although they never rise
above the undemanding material. ``Mating Habits'' features them in
numerous, discretely shot sex scenes, the tameness of which will
likely disappoint nature-loving adolescent boys _ no matter what
galaxy they hail from. &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
