A9781 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-KENNEWICK-MAN-AZR &LR;      10-07 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEWICK-MAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUCSON, ARIZ., LAB TO HELP SETTLE KENNEWICK MAN CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ((EDITORS: RETRANSMITTING THIS INTERESTING PIECE - A SHORT
SIDEBAR, `MAN,'
 &UR; HAS BEEN ADDED AT THE END OF THIS STORY)
</P>
<P>
   TUCSON _ It's just a tiny pile of bone shavings, snug inside a
Tupperware bowl in a University of Arizona file drawer.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also a clue to one of the biggest controversies facing
American anthropology:
</P>
<P>
   Were ancestors of American Indians alone as the first humans in
North America? Or were there also Caucasoids _ people with physical
features generally associated with Europeans _ living here about
the same time?
</P>
<P>
   The scientific, political and legal furor raging over the
skeletal remains called Kennewick Man goes to the heart of humans'
earliest history in North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be really placed in the present and future unless
we're rooted in the past,'' said Alan Schneider, an attorney who
represents scientists demanding a full study of the skeleton.
</P>
<P>
   The battle has reached the highest levels. Last year, the
Clinton administration opposed a bill to allow study of Kennewick
Man. Last week, however, a federal judge ordered that the study go
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since 1996, when two students found the skull to the
10,000-year-old skeleton on the Columbia River near Kennewick,
Wash., the remains have been caught in a tug of war.
</P>
<P>
   On one side are Native Americans and federal officials who are
blocking further study of the skeleton, claiming it should be
reburied under the Native American Graves Protection Act of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that any human remains determined to have lived
``prior to the documented arrival of Europeans,'' or nearly 507
years ago with the arrival of Christopher Columbus, be considered
indigenous to the United States and therefore, ancestors of modern
Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side is a group of eight scientists, including
Arizona State University anthropologist Christy Turner.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the scientists filed suit in federal court, asserting
that the skeleton, found on federal land, should be studied to
better understand human development and migration in North America.
</P>
<P>
   In connection with the suit, a federal judge has ordered further
testing to confirm earlier findings that Kennewick Man lived about
10,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's where UA comes in. Its Arizona Accelerated Mass
Spectrometry Facility, renowned for its radiocarbon dating methods,
was picked among three labs in the world to analyze the Shroud of
Turin in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The Tucson lab, in the basement of the UA's physics building, is
one of three U.S. facilities now testing Kennewick Man.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Donahue, director of the UA lab, said the spectrometer
will measure the ratio of stable carbon to carbon-14 in 6.5 grams
of bone from the skeleton's left tibia.
</P>
<P>
   All living organisms absorb the element carbon from the
atmosphere until they die, when they begin to emit it. Because
carbon-14 isotopes decay at a known rate, scientists can measure
the amount of carbon in ancient remains to determine the date an
organism died.
</P>
<P>
   The testing will occur over a series of weeks, with the results
being sent to the U.S. Department of Interior by November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until it's done, we're keeping it (the testing) as low-key as
possible,'' Donahue said, adding that he plans to publish the
results later in a scientific journal.
</P>
<P>
   But radiocarbon dating is only the first step in determining the
real roots of Kennewick Man, researchers agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``DNA testing needs to be done to see what the lineage is,''
said Donna Kirner, an anthropologist who initially tested the
skeleton at the University of California-Riverside. ``A date is
just a date. It doesn't tell you anything other than a time
frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Department of Interior officials haven't made any promises to
allow DNA testing of Kennewick Man, but it appears a federal judge
will push for it.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, U.S. District Judge John Jelderks ordered that the
government finish the radiocarbon analysis and conduct a
cultural-affiliation assessment, possibly including DNA testing, in
the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively tight deadline is troubling to federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very tough,'' said Stephanie Hanna, a
spokeswoman for the Department of Interior. ``The Justice
Department explained it takes a least a year to do
cultural-affiliation studies, and now we're looking at less than a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jelderks didn't buy the argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``In sum, the court is concerned by what appears to be a pattern
of unnecessary delay in this action,'' he wrote in his Sept. 21
order.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is a victory for the scientists, but only in part.
They had requested that the judge rule immediately on their request
for full study of Kennewick Man.
</P>
<P>
   But even a partial victory is sweet for Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early prehistory of this country is as important as
anything else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the truth about the radiocarbon dating and the Kennewick
Man is (that) the government should not be involved in the history
and the prehistory of science.'' &QL; 
Kerry Fehr-Snyder can be reached at (602) 444-8975 or at
kerry.fehr-snyder(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MAN (SIDEBAR, also by Kerry Fehr-Snyder)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Artist's &QL; 
view likely &QL; 
incorrect &QL; 
Shortly after the remains of Kennewick Man were found, a forensic
anthropologist noted that the skeleton had Caucasoid features. An
artist's clay ren dering even depicted a Kirk Douglas-style chin
and an overall resemblance to Star Trek's Jean-Luc Picard.
</P>
<P>
   But the anthropologist prob ably got it wrong when he said the
bones belonged to an early White settler.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists caution that, de spite the similarity in words,
``Caucasoid'' is a scientific designation that differs dramat
ically from the popularly used term ``Caucasian.''
</P>
<P>
   Caucasian usually refers to skin color. But Caucasoid is an
anthropological description generally applied to the physi cal
features and skeletal types of people of North Africa and Asia as
well as Europe, accord ing to Christy Turner, an an thropologist at
Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are dark-skinned and light-skinned Caucasians,'' he
explained. ``It is really a geographical designation.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists won't know for sure whether Kennewick Man was
Caucasoid or related to modern-day Native Americans. Such a
determination will re quire a ``cultural affiliation'' analysis _
possibly including DNA testing _ on the skele ton. A federal judge
has or dered the analysis take place before March. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
