<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A BABY-SITTING COOPERATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   NYT Regional Newspapers   c.1999 N.Y. Times
News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the first month into our baby-sitting co-op, and things are
going swimmingly.
</P>
<P>
   Well, as swimmingly as any situation can that involves four
active boys and a trio of toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   My neighbors and I had often swapped baby-sitting woes,
complaining that our teen-age sitters had more active social lives
than we did (with the corollary being that they didn't have much
time left over to baby-sit.)
</P>
<P>
   So a few of us decided to use the old ``it takes a village''
approach and pool our resources. Here's how it works, for those
daring enough to try this at home:
</P>
<P>
   Take three families. Family A has two boys, 9 and 12, and a
girl, 2. Family B (us) has one boy, 8, and one girl, 3. And Family
C has one boy, 9, and one girl, 1.
</P>
<P>
   We found it helps to have similar breakdowns in ages and sexes.
Also, all the children _ and parents _ knew each other from school
and Scouts and day care, which made for an easier blending.
</P>
<P>
   Each family took the children from 5 to 8:30 p.m. one Saturday a
month, with one Saturday left for each family to stay together.
</P>
<P>
   My part in the first weekend consisted of dropping my two
darlings off at the appointed hour with Couple A.
</P>
<P>
   Couple B (us) and Couple C (Bruce and Amy) made a hasty retreat,
since we had dinner reservations at 6:00.
</P>
<P>
   As we settled in to dine on lobster and red snapper, Amy raised
her glass in a simple toast: ``Here's to being out.'' Indeed, we
were all pretty glad to be there amid the wine glasses clinking and
the starched linen tablecloths, with no high chairs in our general
vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, came the pay back. Weekend No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   First, I had to do a sweep of the house, since baby-proofing for
my 3-year-old is a bit more lax than for the younger girls that
would be there.
</P>
<P>
   I arranged an area for the boys in the basement, with the TV,
play tent, computer and action figures, and pulled a lot of my
daughter's toys up to the living room for the girls (Duplos, push
toys, stuffed animals and playhouse.) This fell under the theory of
Separate Domains.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, because my husband was away at a business
conference, and I am a chicken, I hired our baby sitter to help
out. Smart move. Two caretakers with seven young charges was a much
better ratio.
</P>
<P>
   The kids ate in shifts, girls first, and the basement strategy
kept the big brothers contained for the entire three hours.
Everybody enjoyed making their sundaes, even if chocolate sauce and
sprinkles did end up spread over several rooms of the house.
</P>
<P>
   But before long, 8:30 rolled around, and the couples dutifully
returned to claim their children _ one with a favorable review of
``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' and the other from an evening of
pressure washing the house and taking in a Tupperware party.
</P>
<P>
   The next weekend, Amy called to confirm.
</P>
<P>
   When I arrived, the boys were playing badminton, and the girls
were in the sandbox. Amy had a racquet and was looking optimistic.
``Have fun,'' I said, smiling, as I dropped a backpack, change of
clothes and sippy cup beside a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Then I walked out the side gate and climbed into my minivan,
three hours of unplanned time stretching ahead of me like an
uncharted highway.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a features writer for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers. She has master's and specialist degrees in
marriage and family counseling.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
