<HEADER>
A9783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NFL-MATCHUPS-NYT &LR;      10-07 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-MATCHUPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 1 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (0-4) at New Orleans (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   Falcons Coach Dan Reeves and Saints Coach Mike Ditka are close
buds. So they will likely commiserate about what has been an awful
season, especially for the Falcons. Reeves is paying for what was a
terrible mistake this offseason in not getting a qualified backup
for the injury-prone Chris Chandler. He will play this week, but
his hamstring will be a continuing problem. Like last week, he
probably won't finish the game.
</P>
<P>
   Saints, 20-19
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (2-2) at Minnesota (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tell which way the Vikings are headed. They had a
nice 21-point, first-half explosion last week against Tampa Bay,
then were held scoreless for the rest of the game. So is the glass
half full or empty? Are the Vikings back on track or still having
problems with their offense? Let's be optimistic and say Minnesota
is due for a 30-point explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings, 31-10
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati (0-4) at Cleveland (0-4)
</P>
<P>
   Someone please put Bengals Coach Bruce Coslet out his misery. It
is only a matter of time before he is fired. If his team loses to
the expansion Browns, that day will come sooner rather than later.
Coslet made the smart move to start rookie Akili Smith, who is
still angry at the Browns for misleading him during draft-day
contract talks. So Smith will want to prove the Browns made a
mistake in drafting Tim Couch over him. Cleveland has won five
straight home games against the Bengals but that was the old Browns
team. Even Coslet can't mess this game up.
</P>
<P>
   Bengals, 20-3
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (3-0) at Philadelphia (0-4)
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are off to their best start since going 4-0 in 1995,
the season they went to Super Bowl XXX. Philadelphia won't put up
much of a fight. They have a terrible offense and average defense.
Running back Emmitt Smith averages 109.3 yards a game against the
Eagles, his highest average against any NFC East team. This game
Smith is good for at least 120 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys, 35-7
</P>
<P>
   New England (4-0) at Kansas City (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   The NFL keeps waiting for the Patriots to crash. It won't
happen. This team is for real, mainly because quarterback Drew
Bledsoe is playing great. He has a 93.6 passer rating and has
thrown 120 passes without an interception. They will go 5-0 for the
first time since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots, 28-21
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh (2-2) at Buffalo (3-1)
</P>
<P>
   The Bills might be a tired group following their emotional
Monday night victory at Miami. It was one of the most important
triumphs in years because Buffalo had struggled against Miami. But
the Bills, contrary to what one might think, will still be ready.
In the 1990s, they are 13-5 following games on Monday night. And
Doug Flutie continues to be impressive as a starter for the Bills,
since he is 10-4. Because of Pittsburgh's offensive woes _
quarterback Kordell Stewart has a dismal 57.6 rating _ they won't
be able to keep up with Flutie and the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   Bills, 24-13
</P>
<P>
   San Diego (2-1) at Detroit (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   The home team in this game has won all six meetings. If that
isn't indication enough of a Lions win, Coach Bobby Ross, who
coached the Chargers to Super Bowl XXIX, and then was fired, is
extra motivated to beat his old team. San Diego won't make it easy
since they rarely beat themselves. The Chargers have only three
turnovers, tied for the fewest in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Lions, 19-13
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco (3-1) at St. Louis (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   Incredible as it may seem, the Rams _ the Rams, for goodness
sake _ are in first place in the NFC West. What's next? Aliens land
in Washington? But for St. Louis this is their first big test. The
49ers have always dominated the Rams franchise, winning 12 straight
on the road against them. The last time San Francisco lost to St.
Louis on the road was 1986. That is a daunting history to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   49ers, 30-28
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 4 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Giants (2-2) at Arizona (1-3)
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have good defenses. The Giants are ranked third in
the conference while the Cardinals are fourth. And both offenses
have struggled. For the Giants, don't expect Kerry Collins to be a
savior. The true savior, in addition to Michael Strahan and Jessie
Armstead, may be wide receiver Amani Toomer. He is blossoming into
a quality player and Giants coaches plan to get Toomer even more
involved in the offense against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Giants, 21-20
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore (2-2) at Tennessee (3-1)
</P>
<P>
   This is about the time for one of those Neil O'Donnell
meltdowns. It is true that O'Donnell is 25-12 as a starter against
the AFC Central and equally true that he leads the conference with
a 133.3 passer rating. But the reason the Jets got rid of him was
that he bounced up and down like a yo-yo. Baltimore defensive back
Rod Woodson has six career interceptions against Tennessee. He and
the secondary will have a good day.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens, 16-13
</P>
<P>
   Denver (0-4) at Oakland (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Bubby Brister gets the start over Brian Griese.
Shanahan benched Brister in the preseason because he believed he
was better coming off the bench. Now Shanahan gets to see if his
theory was correct. But there is nothing Shanahan can do to
overcome the loss of Terrell Davis to a season-ending knee injury.
Meanwhile, former Giant Tyrone Wheatley is having the best season
of his professional career. Denver won't be able to stop him;
they'll go to an unbelievable 0-5.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders, 21-10
</P>
<P>
   Miami (2-1) at Indianapolis (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the most intriguing games of the weekend.
Dolphins Coach Jimmy Johnson took some serious shots at his offense
this week after their average performance against Buffalo on Monday
night. How the Dolphins respond _ especially quarterback Dan Marino
_ will be interesting to watch. More importantly, offensive tackle
Richmond Webb is out with a bruised knee. Miami historically
dominates the Colts. That will continue.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins, 24-16
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 8 P.M. GAME
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (2-2) at Green Bay (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   It is in big games like this one where Tampa Bay has a dramatic
disadvantage. Two words: Trent Dilfer. Or those two words could be
Brett Favre. One is a dud, the other a difference maker. Tampa Bay
does have a tremendous defense, anchored by Warren Sapp, who
returns after missing last week with an injured hand. Tampa Bay
still has not allowed a rushing touchdown. But as long as Dilfer is
the quarterback _ especially when he goes against Favre _ the
Buccaneers will not take that big step forward.
</P>
<P>
   Packers, 21-14
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT GAME
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville (3-1) at Jets (1-3)
</P>
<P>
   Against the Broncos last week, Rick Mirer actually played fairly
well, and that was a result of the Jets finally just getting wide
receiver Keyshawn Johnson the ball. As much as possible. He and
Mirer finally seemed to find some sort of chemistry. Look for that
to continue against Jacksonville. As for the Jaguars, the stories
about the rift between Coach Tom Coughlin and quarterback Mark
Brunell are not exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Jets, 24-23
</P>
</TEXT>
