<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9788 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-AIRLINES08-COX     10-07 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIRLINES SPENT MILLIONS IN CAMPAIGN AGAINST PASSENGER RIGHTS LAW
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a year of soaring customer complaints, U.S.
airlines grounded a passenger bill of rights movement with help
from a $3 million lobbying effort and $1.3 million in political
donations, says a study by the group Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines, which had been the target of protests from
passengers for holding packed planes on runways last winter, alone
spent $1.3 million for lobbying during the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta Airlines made $38,000 in political donations
during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The Common Cause analysis tracked political spending at a time
when public outrage over treatment by the airlines prompted
promises of new legislation on Capitol Hill. Passengers told of
being held prisoner for hours aboard packed planes that were stuck
on runways by winter blizzards and spring storms.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints filed against airlines doubled to 5,000 compared with
a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   However, the push for new customer protections faded in June,
when the major airlines persuaded Congress to accept their offer to
set up a voluntary improvement plan.
</P>
<P>
   The major airlines issued their so-called ``customers first''
proposals last month.
</P>
<P>
   Critics charged that the plans were weak and unenforceable. Sen.
Ron Wyden, D-Ore., called the airline plans ``legalistic
gobbledygook which do nothing to protect passengers.'' A study by
the General Accounting Office, the investigating arm of Congress,
concluded that most of the rights listed in the airlines' plans do
not go beyond existing legal requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines defend the program as better than one run by the
government. ``It's not weak at all,'' said David Fuscus, spokesman
for the Air Transport Association. ``It's in the the implementation
phase.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Congress has ordered the Department of
Transportation's inspector general to review the results and report
back next June.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Transport Association, which is the trade group for the
major carriers, spent nearly $1 million for its lobbying effort
during the first half of this year, according to the Common Cause
study.
</P>
<P>
   Political donations by the industry shot up January-June of this
year, said Common Cause. The airlines contributed $1.3 million to
political parties and candidates in the first half of 1999. In a
comparable period in 1997, they donated $630,000, and in the first
half of 1995, the contributions totalled $306,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any industry, we participate fully in the political
process,'' Fuscus said. ``There's nothing unusual about that .
We've always been very politically active no matter what the
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that matters involving service ``should be handled by
the free market.''
</P>
<P>
   Common Cause president Scott Harshbarger countered that airlines
are currently not required to meet consumer protections because
they are exempt from state controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that we're asking here is that the airlines be held to the
same consumer protection standards as any other business,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airline industry has been given first-class treatment by
Congress while the consumers are given third-class treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
