A9789 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-HARSHREALM-TEX     10-07 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HARSHREALM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SERIES FROM `X-FILES' CREATOR FILLED WITH ALL THE OLD MOVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seems like Chris Carter's ``X-Files'' credo _ ``Trust No One'' _
is quickly becoming the core theme in all his work.
</P>
<P>
   On the ``Files,'' a dark syndicate works within the world's
governments to keep the general public (and especially agents
Mulder and Scully) from discovering the truth about the existence
of extraterrestrial life. On the now-defunct ``Millennium,'' a
shadowy organization called the Millennium Group operating outside
of law enforcement manipulates serial-killer hunter Frank Black for
its own mysterious agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In Carter's new series ``Harsh Realm'' (8 p.m. Thursday on Fox),
the military is his latest target of villainy. Lt. Thomas Hobbes
(Scott Bairstow), a decorated soldier who fought in Sarajevo, is
recruited to test a new military combat-training program _ a
top-secret, virtual-reality simulation game code-named ``Harsh
Realm.''
</P>
<P>
   His mission is to take out the game's highest-scoring player,
Omar Santiago (''Millennium'''s Terry O'Quinn), but as Hobbes
quickly learns, nothing in Harsh Realm is as it seems, and
according to his new companions, this game never ends.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbes becomes the reluctant ally of Mike Pinocchio (D.B.
Sweeney), a grizzled Realmer who knows how to navigate the glitches
in the program allowing access to off-limits areas, and the
mysterious Florence (Rachel Hayward) who's convinced that Hobbes is
the savior they've all been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   The series premiere has almost all the Carterisms intact: It's
filled with familiar faces (O'Quinn and Lance Henriksen from
``Millennium,'' while ``The X-Files''' Gillian Anderson makes a
cameo in a film voice-over). The hero has an almost blinding
passion to do the ``right'' thing: First you had Mulder's truth,
then Black's justice and now Hobbes' American way. And the whole
thing wraps up with about 50 unanswered questions, leaving viewers
wondering what will happen next. It ends with a typical
``X-Files''-esque shot, an overhead pull-back to reveal hundreds of
soldiers with wires coming out of their heads lying on gurneys in
some top-secret bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Its derivative nature aside, ``Harsh Realm'' isn't to be taken
lightly. Carter has a lot at stake on this new series, especially
with ``Millennium'' canceled and ``The X-Files'' starting its final
season (David Duchovny's leaving the series to pursue a movie
career ... ``Playing God 2'' perhaps?).
</P>
<P>
   But an idealistic soldier battling for control of _ quite
frankly _ a rather ``uninteresting'' alternate reality isn't the
kind of groundbreaking material we've come to expect from a talent
like Carter. It's all stuff that movies (like ``The Matrix'') have
traditionally been better at than television. (Remember ``VR5?)''
</P>
<P>
   In the plus column is Carter's knack for sticking with top
talent. You'll recognize a lot of names from his other shows in the
behind-the-scenes credits _ Frank Spotnitz, Daniel Sackheim, Vince
Gilligan, Tony To _ all of whom have either written or directed
some of the most memorable episodes of Carter's other two series.
There is also the unmistakable atmospheric music of composer Mark
Snow.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the camera, the underappreciated O'Quinn is always
terrific, and Sweeney and Bairstow's gruff chemistry should pay off
in future episodes. The effects are decent, and until Hollywood
successfully beats the VR horse to death (probably sometime next
year), these stories should remain intriguing to a generation
currently under the spell of the Sega Dreamcast.
</P>
<P>
   But if it doesn't work, Carter is sure to have another project
up his sleeve. Perhaps something about a sinister consortium
working within network television, conspiring to sabotage the TV
shows of an idealistic writer who only wants to tell ... the truth.
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
