<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH STIRS THE WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's bold move to capture
the philosophical middle and distance himself from conservative
congressional Republicans not only strengthens his independent
image but exposes the party's far right wing as something of a
paper tiger.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans screamed that Bush was undercutting their
crusade to retain control of that body next year, but there doesn't
seem to be much they can do about it. Bush is holding a powerful
political hand and he is not afraid to use it.
</P>
<P>
   He can get away with a lot in these days of heady polls,
fantastic fund-raising and weak opposition.
</P>
<P>
   You can't beat somebody with nobody. The religious right that
has dominated internal Republican politics for 20 years has no
single star to rally around this time. Too many insubstantial guys
are out there espousing an identical ideology and chasing the same
clump of voters. And the one major rival with real potential,
Arizona Sen. John McCain, has few friends on the far right.
</P>
<P>
   That's why 20 of the 54 GOP senators, 23 of 31 GOP governors and
148 of 222 GOP House members have already endorsed Bush. They may
be sorry now that Bush is proving to be his own man instead of
theirs, but it's too late. They made their choice prematurely and
they are stuck with it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush feels so confident of winning that he is already running a
general election campaign, risking the ire of right-wing primary
voters who are the party's traditional base. This is nervy, because
he is counting his chickens before the eggs have hatched. As one
disgruntled Republican observed ominously, ``He doesn't have the
nomination yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he deliberately broke the spirit of an earlier promise
to GOP members of Congress that he would not campaign against them.
The happy scenario of a unified party riding to victory on his
coattails seems suddenly to be developing a tear here and there.
</P>
<P>
   Having criticized his party twice in a week, Bush then backed
off the confrontation by trying to mollify his angry targets. But
if he meant what he initially said, it is an important development
for his candidacy and the country. It was music to ears deadened by
years of partisan cacophony over the role of the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Bush complained that his party has spent too much time
``speaking a sterile language of rates and numbers. Too often my
party has confused the need for limited government with a disdain
for government itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hooray. This is the kind of common sense, centrist politics that
President Clinton has practiced brilliantly and that is important
to continue into the next century. When Clinton announced that the
era of big government was dead _ to be replaced by a smaller but
still activist government _ he moved public perceptions of the
Democratic party from the left fringes into the political
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans learned anything from the government shutdowns of
1995 and 1996, it should be that voters don't think government is
always the problem. They want basic services that only government
can provide but they want them delivered fairly and efficiently,
without ideological cant.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is trying to pull his party away from the right, as Clinton
pulled his from the left. Hopefully, this means the 2000
presidential campaign may focus on substantive issues of where the
country is going rather than the hateful wedge issues that
preoccupy the zealots.
</P>
<P>
   A classic example of this philosophical shift is Bush's blunt
rejection of the House GOP's desperate scheme to stay within budget
spending limits by delaying government payments to the working
poor. ``I don't think they ought to balance their budget on the
backs of the poor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The transparent gimmick was already dying, but after Bush spoke,
the wretched thing was finished.
</P>
<P>
   Bush went further, denouncing a Republican tendency to take a
sour view of our national standards and our culture.``Too often on
social issues my party has painted an image of America slouching
toward Gomorrah,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was repeating the title of a negative, carping book by Robert
Bork, a Supreme Court nominee defeated in the Senate because of his
nutty interpretation of constitutional rights. As much as anyone in
public life, Bork symbolizes radical right-wing fringe thinking.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush does not seem prepared to go much beyond what he said
recently. He is not challenging the gun lobby or the anti-abortion
crowd. He stands with his party in its basic objection to campaign
finance overhaul. He wants to shave off the unpopular edges but not
destabilize the Republican structure, which he must run on.
</P>
<P>
   This is good thinking, so long as he remains the unchallenged
frontrunner. If he falters, however, he may find that conservatives
have long memories and a few teeth after all.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
