<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEACHING-SCULPTURE-AR     10-07 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHING-SCULPTURE-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCULPTURE WHOSE AUDIENCE IS ENGINEERING STUDENTS  
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BRIAN GELLER    
 The Gainesville Sun    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Buildings have three dimensions. Pictures of
a building, however, have two.
</P>
<P>
   That posed a challenge for Duane Ellifritt, a University of
Florida civil engineering professor. More than a decade ago,
Ellifritt was searching for a way to help his students get a sense
of how things are built.
</P>
<P>
   His idea: to build a 14-foot high teaching sculpture that shows
how pieces of steel can be shaped and connected. In the 13 years
since it went up, almost 100 universities have copied Ellifritt's
idea. On Thursday, the University of Florida honored the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a simple idea,'' said Ellifritt, 64. ``I'm surprised
no one ever thought of it before I did.''
</P>
<P>
   A tall, red column stands at the center of the 10-ton red
sculpture. Smaller beams poke out from the column, illustrating the
different connections engineers use to bring steel pieces together.
With no two pieces exactly alike on the sculpture, it also shows
the variety of sizes and shapes steel can take.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are channels, angles, rods, pipes, I-beams,'' Ellifritt
said.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture sat for years behind Weil Hall before the
university moved it this spring to a more visible location on the
building's west side. A formal dedication in the new location was
held Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture grew out of the difficulty students said they had
visualizing some objects in three dimensions, Ellifritt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a textbook, it's always seen in two-dimensional view,'' he
said. ``So it was hard for them to visualize some of these
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking to remedy this, Ellifritt had several ideas. He likes to
take his classes on field trips, but Gainesville does not always
have a construction site that students can visit. He said he also
thought about building models and carrying them into class, ``but
the stuff is heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he thought of building the teaching sculpture. After
the idea gained administrators' support, Steel Fabricators Inc. of
Fort Lauderdale built and donated it.
</P>
<P>
   Since the sculpture was first erected at the university in
October 1986, other schools have used the idea. Borrowing plans
from the original, universities in Canada, Mexico and across United
States have built sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got one here,'' said Chuck Moretti, civil engineering chair
at the University of North Dakota in Grand Forks. ``We like it.''
</P>
<P>
   A metal construction firm in Fargo, N.D., 80 miles to the south,
built and donated it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We poured a concrete slab and set it up ourselves,'' he said.
``We've got it sitting out by our building. It's kind of almost an
art sculpture.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun is part of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
