<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9800 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     10-07 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPSULE REVIEWS OF SOME CURRENT MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of
new or noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in
New York City. (Star) denotes a highly recommended film or series.
Ratings and running times are in parentheses.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now Playing &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``AMERICAN BEAUTY,'' starring Kevin Spacey, Annette
Bening, Chris Cooper, Wes Bentley and Thora Birch. Written by Alan
Ball. Directed by Sam Mendes (R, 116 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   With heavenly finesse, Spacey plays a buttoned-down 42-year-old
suburbanite who flips his lid for a teen-age cheerleader. And he
never gets it back on. The midlife crisis motif is familiar, but
the stage director Sam Mendes brings terrific visual flair and dry
humor to this barbecuing of the bourgeoisie. All the actors display
coolly expert timing, especially Ms. Bening as the antihero's
grasping wife.
</P>
<P>
   Although the story spreads itself thin among many characters,
the film coalesces for a devastating finale (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``DOUBLE JEOPARDY,'' starring Ashley Judd, Tommy Lee Jones and
Bruce Greenwood. Directed by Bruce Beresford (R, 106 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   In a touristy thriller that roams from the coastline of
Washington State to New Orleans' French Quarter, Ms. Judd plays a
woman who's free to kill her husband because she's already gone to
prison for the crime (see title).
</P>
<P>
   Not even she is beautiful enough to get away with rote acting
and a far-fetched plot, but she perks up as her character becomes
less of a victim. In this co-ed homage to ``The Fugitive,'' Jones
is on hand as another weathered sourpuss with a knack for barking
orders. Beresford directs so unremarkably that it takes a line like
``I feel like I've grown in the last six years'' to signal the
passage of time (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``EARTH,'' starring Aamir Khan, Nandita Das, Rahul Khanna
and Maia Sethna. Directed by Deepa Mehta (not rated, 99 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   It is 1947, and India is about to explode into ethnic violence
as British colonial rule ends and the country is partitioned into
two nations, mostly Hindu India and mostly Muslim Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   These momentous changes are observed by Lenny (Ms. Sethna), the
8-year-old daughter of a well-to-do Parsi family in Lahore. As
Hindus, Muslims and Sikhs slaughter one another in the streets, old
friends become deadly enemies. Caught in the middle is Shanta (Ms.
Das), Lenny's beautiful Hindu nanny, who has two Muslim suitors.
The movie's child's-eye view somewhat mutes its dramatic sweep
(Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``FOR LOVE OF THE GAME,'' starring Kevin Costner and Kelly
Preston. Directed by Sam Raimi (PG-13, 140 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This film, starring Costner as Billy Chapel, an aging Detroit
Tigers pitcher, is a baseball movie the way ``You've Got Mail'' was
a movie about the retail book business. Deep down the film is
really about the love of a difficult man for a good woman, played
by Ms. Preston. The baseball story, thanks to Costner's athletic
credibility (see ``Bull Durham'' and ``Field of Dreams'') and a
complement of real ballplayers, works better than the romance.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, they add up to routine entertainment, because
the overloaded love story doesn't really tug the heartstrings.
Underlying the story of Chapel's crucial game is the story of his
five-year romance with Jane (Ms. Preston), seen in flashbacks, as
he tries to coax one more win out of a worn-out arm. Is it time for
Chapel to quit?
</P>
<P>
   Filmmaking, like baseball, is a team game, and sometimes even a
talented lineup produces unexceptional results (Lawrence Van
Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   ``GUINEVERE,'' starring Sarah Polley and Stephen Rea. Written
and directed by Audrey Wells (R, 104 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Polley shines as a shy, rebellious 21-year-old involved in
an affair with an older man. Escaping her chilly family, she moves
into the well-populated space beneath the wing of a bohemian
photographer, played with great charm by Rea. This coming-of-age
film takes a knowing, intimate view of the dynamics of such a
relationship and watches its heroine blossom. So does Ms. Polley,
as a luminous, mysterious young actress capable of exceptionally
subtle shadings (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``HAPPY, TEXAS,'' starring Jeremy Northam, Steve Zahn and
William H. Macy. Directed by Mark Illsley (R, 96 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The zany comedy follows two escaped convicts (Northam and Zahn)
who pose as a pair of gay pageant producers in a small Texas town
that is grooming its little girls for the Little Miss Squeezed
Pageant. Macy is poignant as the discreetly gay, doe-eyed sheriff
who shyly pursues Northam (who's only posing as gay). Zahn has his
amusing moments as an oaf improvising ludicrous dance routines. But
the movie is so desperate to be liked that its satire is risk-free
and toothless, and its laughs widely scattered (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``JAKOB THE LIAR,'' starring Robin Williams, Alan Arkin, Liev
Schreiber and Armin Mueller-Stahl. Directed by Peter Kassovitz
(PG-13, 114 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   In a Holocaust story to make Roberto Benigni look like Primo
Levi, Williams plays a man who brightens life in a Polish ghetto
with imaginary good news about the imminent end of the war.
Surrounded by a strong supporting cast (with Arkin giving the
film's only genuinely funny performance), he again indulges that
unfortunate yen to play the clown who cried.
</P>
<P>
   The direction is sincere but sloppy. Watch the microphone make
repeated, unwelcome entrances from the top of the frame (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``LUCIE AUBRAC,'' starring Carole Bouquet and Daniel
Auteuil. Produced, written and directed by Claude Berri (R, 116
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   What lifts this taut World War II thriller based on a true story
above the ordinary are the impassioned performances of Ms. Bouquet
and Auteuil as Lucie and Raymond, a married couple who are fighters
in the French Resistance. When Raymond is arrested by the Nazis and
convicted of war crimes, Lucie conceives an outrageously audacious
plan for his escape.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bouquet and Auteuil are as romantically intense as Bogey and
Bergman in ``Casablanca,'' but here the woman is the one who ends
up doing the thinking for both of them (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``MUMFORD,'' starring Loren Dean, Hope Davis, Jason Lee,
Alfre Woodard and Mary McDonnell. Written and directed by Lawrence
Kasdan (R, 115 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   An immensely likable semiscrewball comedy from the director of
``The Big Chill,'' ``Mumford'' follows the adventures of an
engaging charlatan psychotherapist (Dean) fleeing a sleazy former
life, who names himself after the town (Mumford) in which he
settles and helps a lot of troubled people, even though he is
without credentials.
</P>
<P>
   His most endearing client ( Lee) is a warm, fuzzy billionaire
computer nerd who loves to skateboard but finds it's lonely at the
top. Mumford's moral ambiguity (he's both a hero and a fraud) keeps
this delightful Frank Capraesque fable of self-invention from
becoming too sappy (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``MYSTERY, ALASKA,'' starring Russell Crowe, Hank Azaria, Ryan
Northcott, Mary McCormack and Burt Reynolds. Directed by Jay Roach
(R, 119 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The king of television drama David E. Kelley co-produced and
helped write the satirically edged meat-and-potatoes story of a
legendary ice hockey team in the small town of Mystery, Alaska,
that is persuaded to play the New York Rangers in a televised
exhibition match.
</P>
<P>
   With its skillfully interwoven personal dramas of assorted
townspeople, the movie is a convincingly likable portrait of a
modern pioneer community under siege from the media. But it begins
to lose its punch when the story settles into the all-too-familiar
``Rocky'' formula. It includes strong performances by Crowe (as the
town sheriff) and Reynolds (as an imperious local judge) (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``PLUNKETT AND MACLEANE,'' starring Jonny Lee Miller and Robert
Carlyle. Directed by Jake Scott (R, 102 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Carlyle, who were co-stars in ``Trainspotting,'' are
a pair of dashing 18th-century highwaymen who scandalize (and
titillate) the aristocracy with their daring robberies of rich
people in carriages. Although the overdirected movie has many weak
moments (an impenetrable opening sequence and far too many
close-ups), its portrayal of the English aristocracy as a bunch of
voracious, corrupt gargoyles living out an 18th-century version of
a Studio 54 life style carries a nasty satirical bite (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``ROMANCE,'' starring Caroline Ducey, Sagamore Stevenin,
Francois Berleand and Rocco Siffredi. Written and directed by
Catherine Breillat (not rated, 93 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   A solemn, sexually graphic exploration of the nature of a
woman's need for male attention and erotic love, even if its
insights are already familiar to readers of Cosmopolitan and the
Marquis de Sade. And it's doubtful that the film's intellectual
aspects would command the same attention if its camera did not make
the actors' genitals as familiar as their faces.
</P>
<P>
   The carnal and cerebral erotica here have already achieved the
considerable feat of shocking France, but the film is often stilted
and methodical to the point of tediousness. It hovers between
passion and philosophical argument without often achieving Ms.
Breillat's ambition to fuse the two (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE SIXTH SENSE,'' starring Bruce Willis and Haley Joel
Osment. Written and directed by M. Night Shyamalan (PG-13, 107
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   What starts out as a horror movie about a troubled 8-year-old
boy ( Osment) who claims to see dead people, and the child
psychologist ( Willis) determined to cure him, eventually turns
into New Age mush (think ``What Dreams May Come'' and ``Simon
Birch'').
</P>
<P>
   When you trace the plot backward after its big secret is
revealed, the story doesn't begin to add up. Willis gives his usual
smirking one-note performance. What empathy the movie generates
comes from Osment's intense portrayal of the tormented child
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``STIGMATA,'' starring Patricia Arquette, Gabriel Byrne and
Jonathan Pryce. Directed by Rupert Wainwright (R, 102 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   When Frankie Paige (Ms. Arquette), a vapid Pittsburgh
hairdresser, receives the present of a rosary lifted from the dead
body of a Brazilian priest, her life becomes a supernatural horror
show. Byrne is the Vatican cleric who investigates the case and
Pryce the evil cardinal who wants to cover up evidence that could
damage the church.
</P>
<P>
   The seizures in this poorly acted melange of shock effects and
religious imagery are bargain-basement ``Exorcist.'' Instead of pea
soup and spinning heads, we get breaking glass, dripping blood and
flurries of feathers from agitated doves (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``STIR OF ECHOES,'' starring Kevin Bacon and Kathryn Erbe.
Directed by David Koepp (R, 99 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Another little boy talks to a ghost at the start of this
thriller, but it isn't an instant ``Sixth Sense'' sequel. Instead
it shows what happens when the boy's closed-minded father lets
himself be hypnotized and awakens to find himself receiving
otherworldly stimuli. Bacon gives a grippingly intense performance
as a man terrified by his new extrasensory powers. And Koepp
conveys a potent sense of what it means to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its strong, spooky start and early momentum, the film
winds up with too earthbound an explanation for the havoc it
unleashes (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THREE KINGS,'' starring George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg and Ice
Cube. Written and directed by David O. Russell (R, 105 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The prodigiously talented writer-director of ``Spanking the
Monkey'' and ``Flirting With Disaster'' has made a much more
ambitious film, with mixed results. His gimlet-eyed Persian Gulf
War film has a ``Catch-22'' absurdist edge, but it also has an
oversupply of visual affectations.
</P>
<P>
   Vertiginous music-video camera tricks jazz up the otherwise
straightforward story of American soldiers who have larcenous
designs on Saddam Hussein's captured gold and then develop
conscience pangs about their own roles in Iraq. There are many
clever peripheral touches, but there's something tamely
conventional at the film's core (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
