<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAZI CAMP WORKERS REJECT NEW GERMAN SETTLEMENT OFFER
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ German negotiators Thursday offered $3.3 billion to
Nazi-era victims of slave labor, but lawyers for the aging
survivors rejected the offer.
</P>
<P>
   The latest offer _ 6 billion Deutsche marks _ is three times
higher than the amount offered earlier this year to settle more
than 40 cases in U.S. federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   How many victims might be eligible is still undetermined. German
negotiators put the figure at roughly 1 million, while survivor
advocates put it at about 2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Weiss, lead attorney representing the victims, said he was
``appalled'' by the latest German offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despicable is too weak a word to describe it,'' Weiss said
after two days of talks here at the U.S. State Department.
Negotiations are scheduled to resume next month in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The amount that German companies have offered to pay survivors
of slave labor is about five times less than comparable settlements
reached in Germany, Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   The German offer, two-thirds of which would be paid by 35 major
corporations and the remaining third by the German government,
translates to about $5,263 per slave laborer _ those who worked in
concentration camps or similar facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Forced laborers, who worked under slightly less onerous
conditions, would receive about $1,548, while those who suffered
other injuries, such as being used for medical experiments, would
receive about $1,400.
</P>
<P>
   German government envoy Otto Lambsdorff called the $3.3 billion
offer ``a considerable amount given the budget constraints in
Germany.'' Lambsdorff said it was not easy to convince the German
people to make such reparations at a time when services to German
citizens were being reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Stuart Eizenstat said the German offer
``represents a basis for serious discussion,'' but he warned that
``in order for this to succeed, both sides are going to have to be
flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
