<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Oct. 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The day will begin bright and cold across the Northeast on
Friday. Amid plentiful sunshine, breezes from the south will bring
noticeably milder air to the region by the afternoon. Farther west,
a strong difference between high pressure near the New England
coast and low pressure over Ontario will cause brisk, warm winds
from the southwest to buffet the Great Lakes. Indeed, gusts will
exceed 30 mph near Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   Moist air will surge north through the Mississippi Valley,
setting the stage for heavy showers and thunderstorms from
Louisiana to Arkansas. Though the region has been dry recently,
local flooding is possible. Additional rain will occur Friday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, a broken line of potent thunderstorms will affect
eastern New Mexico and western Texas on Friday as a potent jet
stream disturbance intercepts a flow of humid air from the Gulf of
Mexico. Meanwhile, winds shifting direction with increasing
altitude will induce a few of the storms to rotate. These rotating
thunderstorms, called supercells, are capable of producing
tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Subsiding currents of air associated with high pressure over the
Great Basin will bring abundant sun to much of the West on Friday.
Offshore breezes in California will promote unseasonable warmth at
the coast. Further north, moist winds from the Pacific Ocean will
cause scattered showers across northern Washington. As the moist
winds ascend the higher terrain to the east, showers will dampen
the Bitterroots.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TIME-RELEASED FLOODS
</P>
<P>
   Serious river flooding is like time-released weather _ brimming
waters recede back between their banks slowly. Thursday, several
rivers in North Carolina remained above flood stage in the
aftermath of heavy rains from Hurricane Floyd more than two weeks
ago. It takes time for water in streams and tributaries to drain
into the main river system and then more time for the river to
crest and recede. During the Great Midwest Flood of 1993, the
Mississippi River stayed above flood stage for 80 consecutive days
at St. Louis and above record stage for more than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
