<HEADLINE>
`HARSH REALM': WHEN LIFE BECOMES A NIGHTMARISH VIDEO-GAME WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warning: Chris Carter wants to hijack your brain. Again. And
after shuddering through Friday night's premiere of ``Harsh Realm''
on Fox, you may be ready to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, the creator of ``The X-Files'' and ``Millennium,'' has
concocted another nightmare world. This time he plunks you down
inside a virtual-reality simulation that's virtually impossible to
understand. No matter. You're not supposed to understand it. You're
only supposed to watch it, and to empathize with the series'
boyishly appealing hero, Lt. Thomas Hobbes, played by Scott
Bairstow.
</P>
<P>
   As things begin, Hobbes is about to complete his Army service in
New Jersey, marry his beloved Sophie (Samantha Mathis) and start a
new life in California with her and his little dog, Dexter. But the
Army has one last order: He must try his hand at a top-secret
virtual-reality training game, Harsh Realm, attempting to beat the
reigning high scorer, a guy named Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   In the blink of a horrified eye Hobbes finds himself submerged
in a bleak, war-torn landscape ruled by an evil dictator named
Santiago (Terry O'Quinn). Being high scorer obviously has its
perks.
</P>
<P>
   There are some familiar faces in this place, but only Dexter has
retained his original identity. (See, Hobbes and his little dog
aren't in New Jersey anymore.) Sophie is here, but she doesn't know
Hobbes. In this place she is married to Hobbes' pal, Lt. Mel Waters
(Maximilian Martini), who is the commander of Santiago's forces.
</P>
<P>
   But Waters does know his friend, and he delivers some unsettling
news: ``The game _ get in, get out, get Santiago _ it's all a lie,
Hobbes. There is no game. No gettin' out. No goin' home.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters says that he, too, was sent to beat Santiago, but had no
choice but to join him. Hobbes isn't in a joining mood. Instead, he
falls in with some shadowy rebels, including a resourceful fellow
named Pinocchio (D.B. Sweeney). They are convinced that Hobbes is
the savior they have been hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   You begin to see that this spiraling story is built with
familiar elements whose sources range from cinema to Scripture.
Still, you quickly join Hobbes in accepting an environment you can
neither believe nor understand.
</P>
<P>
   Carter has provided another tale of a good person in a bad
world. But by giving Hobbes a more personal quest _ to complete his
assignment and get home; to preserve his dream, not save the world
_ he is giving his latest dark fable a heart full of hope as well
as a head full of fear.
</P>
<P>
   Each twist in the story asks more disturbing questions. Is
Hobbes in a game? Can he trust anyone he meets? Can he trust his
own senses? Can he ever get home? Does home still exist? How many
conspiracy theories can dance on the head of a pin?
</P>
<P>
   Based on Carter's track record, the answers will not be easy to
come by. But that shouldn't prevent you from following Hobbes
willingly along his twisted road, even if it isn't paved with
yellow bricks. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOVE AND MONEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Friday night at 8:30 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 2 in New York) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In her new television role the dependable Swoosie Kurtz plays
Effie Conklin, an alcoholic matron trapped in a gilt-edged world
with her cold, bombastic husband and their three foolish,
overeducated children. The look of bone-deep misery on her face
could break your heart. At least until the laugh track starts
howling. David Ogden Stiers, as her husband, Nicholas, howls, too,
through one more stuffed-shirt role. The other actors mostly
whimper.
</P>
<P>
   The Conklins are the money of the title. The love is the romance
between their daughter Allison (Paget Brewster) and Eamon McBride
(Brian Van Holt).
</P>
<P>
   Allison has degrees from Yale and Harvard and teaches
kindergarten in the Bronx. Eamon is the handsome superintendent who
lives with his dad the doorman (Brian Doyle-Murray) in the basement
of the swanky Manhattan building where the Conklins have a duplex
penthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Allison's brother, Nicky (John Livingston), who describes
himself as the ``jobless son,'' and her sister, Puff (Judy Greer),
who describes herself as the ``blond nympho,'' complete the
upstairs family.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday night's first episode, a household emergency rekindles
the long-ago fire between Eamon and Allison, scuttling her wedding
to a rich twit. Next week's installment finds everyone trying
unsuccessfully to cope. The script is no help.
</P>
<P>
   Allison: ``So, you're my boyfriend now?''
</P>
<P>
   Eamon: ``Yeah. Of course I am. I mean, uh, we just did it in the
elevator.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kurtz gives her scenes some class. But the tragic look in
her eye says it all: This is hopeless. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HARSH REALM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOX, Friday night at 9. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 5 in New York) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Created by Chris Carter. Produced by Ten Thirteen Productions in
association with 20th Century Fox Television. Carter, Frank
Spotnitz and Daniel Sackheim, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Scott Bairstow (Lt. Thomas Hobbes), Samantha Mathis
(Sophie), D.B. Sweeney (Mike Pinocchio), Terry O'Quinn (Omar
Santiago), Rachel Hayward (Florence), Maximilian Martini (Lieut.
Mel Waters) and Sarah-Jane Redmond (Inga Fossa). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
