<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Oct. 8, 1999. The NYT frontpage advisory, with
layout description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News
Service Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH (Washington) _ Developments. The House approves
bipartisan legislation granting new rights to patients, including a
broad ability to sue their health insurance companies for denying
care. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush's public
statements suggest a willingness to use his commanding position in
the Republican presidential race to challenge some of the party's
assumptions about what it stands for. But as he starts to set out
specific positions, particularly on high visibility issues like
taxes and economic policy, Bush is by no means abandoning the basic
conservative principles that have defined the party at least since
the Reagan administration. By Richard W. Stevenson and Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-POLITICS (New Delhi, India) _ The verdict of some 360
million Indian voters is announced: The Hindu nationalist Bharatiya
Janata Party, once seen as the ugly, anti-Muslim face of Hindu
revivalism, wins a clear victory as the leader of a centrist
coalition of 24 parties that appears likely to offer India its most
durable government in several years. By Celia W. Dugger. 1,700
words.
</P>
<P>
   FENPHEN-SUIT (Undated) _ American Home Products will pay $3.75
billion to settle claims over fen-phen, its diet drug combination.
As part of the settlement, American Home will pay for medical
monitoring and make cash injury awards of up to $1.5 million. By
David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   SWEDEN-ECON (Stockholm, Sweden) _ At a time when world leaders
are fixated on the United States' economic success and its credo of
less government and unfettered competition, Sweden suddenly appears
to be defying gravity. In a turnaround that has surprised Swedes as
much as anybody else, this largely unreconstructed welfare state is
suddenly one of Europe's most vibrant economies. And after nearly
three decades of sluggishness in which the output per person
slumped from third highest in the world to 18th, just behind Italy,
the Swedish economy is in the midst of a powerful transformation.
By Edmund L. Andrews. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-BAN-REACT (Vienna, Austria) _ Speakers at a conference
convene to press for ratification of the nuclear test-ban treaty,
including Russia and China, make clear that the most critical
factor for the treaty's fate was the debates underway in the U.S.
Senate. By Donald G. McNeil Jr. 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGES-ECONOMY (Cambridge, Mass.) _ The much-trumpeted
``knowledge'' (or information or innovation) economy consists of
much more than Silicon Valley. Across America, researchers say,
high-tech is creating localized boomlets like the one here in
Kendall Square, which houses not only biotech but software and
other companies. And if there is one never-fail factor at work on
these silicon corners, it is the nearness of a research university
shifting from ivory tower to revving economic engine. By Carey
Goldberg. 2,300 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
