<SLUG> BC-TRAFFIC-SAFETY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO SAFETY: ROAD WORK MAY NEVER MAKE UP FOR LOST TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Drivers suffering through highway construction
projects may console themselves with the thought that when the work
is done the traffic will flow faster and their trips will be
shorter. But that is not always so, according to the Surface
Transportation Policy Project, a group that favors other methods to
cut traffic, like mass transit and land-use planning.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit group, which is based in Washington, issued a
report in September that analyzed several large highway projects
and calculated how many years a commuter driving through the
construction zone every day would have to keep driving after the
work was finished to break even on the time lost to work delays.
</P>
<P>
   For a $85 million project in Trenton, N.J., to turn a two-lane
stretch of Route 29 into a four-lane road with full shoulders, the
job will delay the average commuter about 10 minutes a trip, or
more than 80 hours a year. Work began a year ago and is expected to
last for two more years, The finished road will save drivers 25
hours a year, the report said, basing its estimates on figures from
the New Jersey Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the break-even point _ the date at which the Trenton
commuter recoups the time lost because of the construction _ will
come in 2012.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem in New Jersey and elsewhere is what the
study calls induced travel, which, it said, ``occurs when road
capacity is expanded and drivers flock to the new facility hoping
to save time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, the new roadways tend to draw people who would otherwise
avoid congested conditions or take alternative modes to their
destinations,'' the study said. ``In the long run, this encourages
additional development nearby, and that leads to even more
traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is bad for New Jersey, it is even worse for Virginia,
where a project to rebuild the intersection of the Washington
Beltway and Interstates 95 and 395 began this year. By late fall,
the construction work will cause delays of 30 to 60 minutes, unless
some commuters take other routes or switch to trains, state
officials say. As a result, drivers in Virginia who wait that long
in traffic every day will never win back the lost time, the report
said. That is another way of saying that the traffic will get worse
even faster than the roads will get better.
</P>
<P>
   The road-building lobby, of course, had a different take. The
American Highway Users Alliance said it was wrong to suggest that
the new roads had no benefit, because they served a population that
the study itself acknowledged was ``choosing to drive more cars
more miles than population growth would indicate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you build a new transit system and it eventually fills up,
everyone considers it a success,'' said William Fay, president of
the alliance. ``Why isn't the same standard used for new
highways?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drivers More Sober; Older, Too
</P>
<P>
   The rate of drunken driving arrests is falling sharply, perhaps
for the same reason that crime is down over all: The population is
getting older and thus more law-abiding, according to the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   A study released in June found that from 1986 to 1997, the
number of people arrested for driving under the influence of
alcohol or drugs (the majority of whom had been drinking) fell to
1.5 million from 1.8 million, while the number of licensed drivers
increased 15 percent. The rate of arrests per 100,000 drivers fell
to 809 from 1,124.
</P>
<P>
   But the number in jail, in prison or on probation soared, to
513,200, nearly double the 270,100 in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   In both years, older drivers were arrested less often than
younger ones. In 1997, 54 percent of licensed drivers were 40 or
older, up from 46 percent in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The study can be viewed on the Web site of the department's
Bureau of Justice Statistics: http://www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs.
</P>
<P>
   The findings paint a bleak picture of those who are in jail or
on probation. Of those on probation, 37 percent showed signs of
alcohol dependency, the study said; for those in jail, the figure
was 47 percent. Among probationers, 46 percent said they had
received treatment from a professional for alcohol abuse since they
were sentenced. Such treatment is often a condition of probation.
</P>
<P>
   But only 4 percent of those in jail said they were currently in
treatment, the Justice Department study found.
</P>
</TEXT>
