<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFF GORDON PROVED A POINT WITH MARTINSVILLE WIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was not Jeff Gordon's biggest win. It may have been his most
important.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday at Martinsville, Va., running for the first time
without crew chief Ray Evernham calling the shots, Gordon gambled
with 15 laps to go and won for the his sixth time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Only days earlier, Evernham had ended months of speculation
about his future by announcing he was leaving Hendrick Motorsports,
which owns Gordon's car, to form his own team.
</P>
<P>
   Since they came up together at the end of the 1992 season,
Gordon and Evernham have developed into the most powerful
combination in Winston Cup racing. Gordon's rapid rise was
attributed to Evernham's brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday in the NAPA AutoCare 500, with new crew chief Brian
Whitesell making an Evernham-like call at the end of the race,
Gordon proved he can win without the master, something Evernham has
been saying for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   With 15 laps to go, while all the other fast cars pitted, Gordon
stayed out and finished first.
</P>
<P>
   ``That answers a lot of questions, doesn't it?'' Gordon asked
after the race.
</P>
<P>
   Whitesell was the team's engineer before being picked by
Evernham as his replacement. Although Evernham was still there
looking over his shoulder, Whitesell's ability to make decisions
under pressure has given Gordon a boost.
</P>
<P>
   It says something about the level of excellence Gordon has
achieved that, despite winning six races this season, Gordon is
considered to be having an off year.
</P>
<P>
   That's because he hasn't been as consistently superior as he has
in the past, seeming to run either really well or very poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effort has been there, the performance has been there, but
the finishes haven't been there,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, his situation this year is similar to 1995,
when he struggled early, made a strong midseason run and then held
off Dale Earnhardt at the end to win his first Winston Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1995, Gordon led at least one lap in 29 of the 31 races,
and he has not been able to do that this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's really the same,'' Gordon said. ``In
1995, we had the new Monte Carlo. It was a very dominant race car
and our team took that dominance a step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dominance of the Monte Carlo at so many different tracks
made up for the bad finishes,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   If Evernham had to go, this is probably as good a time as any,
from the team's standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, a new Monte Carlo is being built, set to debut at
Daytona in 2000 with Hendrick Motorsports on the cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   New body styles mean new chassis setups, and while it wouldn't
have been pushed back to square one, Gordon's team will have to go
through a learning curve, and that would have been true even if
Evernham had stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a guy on our team who doesn't believe in what
we're doing,'' Gordon said. ``We don't second guess ourselves or
point fingers, and team attitude goes a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
