<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-HARVEST-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE-GRAPE HARVESTERS RUSH TO MEET THE CRUSH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDI ROSSMANN   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ This year's grape harvest was late to start
but may be quick to finish as wineries hustle to bring in the $600
million wine grape crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The harvest is going very rapidly, they're taking out the
grapes en masse,'' said Nick Frey, executive director of the Sonoma
County Grape Growers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a quick, short harvest. We're rocking and rolling and
could be done next week,'' said Jim Caudill, spokesman for
Kendall-Jackson Winery.
</P>
<P>
   Slight precipitation Tuesday evening caused the crush to slow
somewhat in wetter areas, but the weather has cleared and
forecasters are calling for sunny, warm days through the end of the
week.
</P>
<P>
   The crush appears to be at least halfway over for most of
northern California, said Pierre Gadd, Sonoma County's chief deputy
agriculture commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The county's grape harvest started out two to three weeks later
than normal because of the cool summer. Then two weeks ago, rain
caused some concern among growers as only 10 percent of the
county's 153,000-ton wine grape crop had been harvested.
</P>
<P>
   But last week's warmer weather brought up the sugar level in the
grapes. ``Since then they've been going pretty much full bore,''
Gadd said.
</P>
<P>
   The wineries are bursting at the seams with ripened grapes and
many growers are gathering their crop round the clock, Caudill
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hot weather caused everything to ripen pretty quickly,
rather unexpectedly,'' he said. ``We were sort of prepared for
everything because the weather has been so screwy this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The return to cooler weather early this week helped stabilize
the sugar levels, said Caudill, who didn't see the trace of rain
Tuesday as a problem at this point. ``As long as it's a little bit
it really doesn't do much but shuffle the dust around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
