<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEBOYS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHITEBOYS:' RAPPING IN THE HEARTLAND, EAGER TO SHED HIS SKIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flip Dogg is phat. He's a hip-hop kind of guy. ``I got so much
juice/I'm getting loose,'' he raps in the privacy of his bedroom _
until his mother calls him for dinner. Did we mention that although
Flip deals cocaine from the men's room at a local club, it's really
baking soda? Did we mention that Flip lives in rural Iowa,
surrounded by cornfields, barns, pickup trucks and birdsong? Did we
mention that Flip is white?
</P>
<P>
   The idea of white-bread teen-age boys in the heartland affecting
a black ghetto sensibility is innately comical, but is it also sad,
deadly dangerous, an inspiring harbinger of racial harmony or some
combination of the three?
</P>
<P>
   The strength of Danny Hoch's deceptively silly, ultimately
intelligent film ``Whiteboys'' is that it keeps moviegoers thinking
and rethinking those questions, even after they've left the
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Hoch, the performance artist who sold out Performance Space 122
in the East Village for 14 weeks last year, plays Flip. In fact,
Flip _ who says, ``Even though I live in Iowa, I've still got the
ghetto in my heart'' and likes to practice his future talk-show
patter, explaining to an imagined Jay Leno that he has ``this rare
skin disorder'' that makes him look white although he's black
inside _ began as a character in that show.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Whiteboys,'' Flip has two close white friends, James (Dash
Mihok) and Trevor (Mark Webber), who are equally enamored of the
hip-hop fantasy and walk around their small town dressed and
talking like the urban rappers they see on MTV. He has a white
girlfriend, Sara (Piper Perabo), who is headed for college and
works in the meantime as a telemarketer for a long-distance
service. Flip has her name sort of branded on his arm, probably
because there are no tattoo parlors nearby. He even has a black
friend, Khalid (Eugene Byrd), whose look, attitude and home life
are more like ``The Cosby Show Meets Martha Stewart'' than the
ghetto. Most of all, Flip has fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly colorful one is a big rap number with Flip and
his friends in monochromatic clothes, accompanied by booze, guns
and babes in bikinis in convertibles, all in front of a cornfield
that eventually catches fire. A black-and-white fantasy set in a
prison that serves champagne and huge platters of shrimp features
Snoop Doggy Dogg in a musical cameo.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, Flip desperately wants to get to Chicago, where he
dreams of living in Cabrini Green, the notoriously dangerous
housing project, and being a drug dealer. Eventually he and his
friends pile into the car, drive to the big city and get an
unfortunate taste of reality.
</P>
<P>
   Hoch wrote the film with Marc Levin (who also directed), Garth
Belcon and Richard Stratton. The literalness of film drains some of
the power from Hoch's message, but the brashness and the occasional
``Kids''-like intensity of ``Whiteboys'' may also attract a lot of
young moviegoers who would never have turned up at avant-garde
theater in the East Village.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   WHITEBOYS
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Marc Levin; written by Garth Belcon, Danny Hoch,
Levin and Richard Stratton, based on a story by Belcon and Hoch;
director of photography, Mark Benjamin; edited by Emir Lewis; music
by Che Guevara; production designer, David Doernberg; produced by
Henri Kessler, Stratton and Ezra Swerdlow; released by Fox
Searchlight Pictures. Running time: 89 minutes. This film is rated
R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Danny Hoch (Flip), Dash Mihok (James), Mark Webber
(Trevor), Piper Perabo (Sara), Eugene Byrd (Khalid), Bonz Malone
(Darius) and Dr. Dre (Don Flip Crew No. 1).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
