<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SUPERSTAR-FILM-REVIEW     10-07 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERSTAR-FILM-REVIEW-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUPERSTAR:' THE THINGS SHE'LL DO FOR FAME AND A DATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easier to understand Mary Katherine Gallagher when you know
about her family. Her parents were killed in a tragic Irish
step-dancing accident at a talent show. She lives in the quiet town
of Besamee Heights with her grandmother (Glynis Johns), who once
danced on Broadway in ``Gypsy'' but is now in a wheelchair and
absolutely forbids her granddaughter to go into show business. No
wonder dear Mary Katherine walks around St. Monica's Catholic High
School in a plaid uniform skirt that barely covers her white
underpants. No wonder she practices her kissing skills and
sweet-nothings patter on trees. No wonder she dreams of being a
star.
</P>
<P>
   By now, just about everybody knows how hard it is to make a good
movie out of a ``Saturday Night Live'' sketch character (Wayne and
Garth and the Blues Brothers notwithstanding), but they keep
trying. Mary Katherine (played by Molly Shannon, who created the
character), television's most endearing insecure extrovert, is the
focus of ``Superstar,'' a comedy with several good laughs but no
convincing cohesion.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is twofold: Mary Katherine sets out to win a venereal
disease benefit talent contest sponsored by Catholic Teen magazine,
so she can go to Hollywood and begin achieving the international
fame she knows she deserves. And she sets out to be kissed by her
school's biggest dreamboat, Sky Corrigan (Will Ferrell). Having
Ferrell play Sky with the same goofy, misguided confidence that he
gives to many of his ``Saturday Night Live'' characters is a joke
that works. Having him double as Jesus _ or at least Mary
Katherine's psychological manifestation of Him (she has a lot of
fantasy sequences) _ is funny in the first scene but wears a little
thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superstar'' gives us characters like Evian (Elaine Hendrix),
Sky's blond cheerleader girlfriend, her pals Autum and Summer
(Natalie Radford and Karen Dwyer), and Slater (Harland Williams),
the guy in special ed who never talks. It gives us a few terrific
scenes, like the huge robot-dance number in the cafeteria (almost
as good as those Gap television ads) and an appropriately inane
``Armageddon'' fantasy involving the song ``Leaving on a Jet
Plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shannon herself is in fine form as the heroine, telling it
like it is (``Your intense energy is making me feel a little
bombarded'') and responding to simple questions by acting out
scenes from various television movies, even in the confessional.
Many of her finest moments take place in Mary Katherine's bedroom,
even if some seem stolen from Gilda Radner. But the majority of the
jokes fall flat, and in the end Mary Katherine has proved (and she
would have trouble accepting this) that she's a joy only for five
minutes or so at a time.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SUPERSTAR'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bruce McCulloch; written by Steven Wayne Koren,
based on a character created by Molly Shannon; director of
photography, Walt Lloyd; edited by Malcolm Campbell; music by
Michael Gore; production designer, Gregory Keen; produced by Lorne
Michaels; released by Paramount Pictures. Running time: 88 minutes.
This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Molly Shannon (Mary Katherine Gallagher), Will Ferrell
(Sky Corrigan/Jesus), Glynis Johns (Grandma), Elaine Hendrix
(Evian), Harland Williams (Slater), Natalie Radford (Autum), Karen
Dwyer (Summer) and Mark McKinney (Father Ritley).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
