<HEADLINE>
SOLOMON DISMISSES QUESTIONS OF IMPROPER LOBBYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Rep. Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., joined by his
successor Rep. John Sweeney, vehemently denied claims Thursday that
the ex-lawmaker may have violated a federal law barring former
members of Congress from lobbying current members.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all so ridiculous,'' said Bill Teator, a public
relations specialist at Solomon Group LLC, Solomon's lobbying firm
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The issue arose from an article by the Capitol Hill newspaper
Roll Call that said Solomon, ex-chairman of the powerful House
Rules Committee, may have violated the lobbying law when he
discussed dairy issues with Sweeney and Rep. Thomas Reynolds, both
of whom are also New York Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon's lobbying firm works for the National Milk Producers
Federation and the States Ratification Committee, both of which are
pushing for the continuation of dairy price supports being debated
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The law on the conduct of former members, enacted as part of the
Ethics Reform Act of 1989, prevents them from lobbying current
members of Congress for one year after retiring. For Solomon the
bar against lobbying expires in January.
</P>
<P>
   In the Roll Call article, Sweeney and Reynolds are quoted as
saying that Solomon talked with them about dairy issues and
agricultural legislation. The story also quotes Solomon as denying
that he spoke with either of them about the current dairy fight.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney and Reynolds, who both strongly favor the milk price
supports, said they did talk with Solomon about dairy issues but
that they spoke about ``past dairy legislation'' and how Solomon
had worked with other members of Congress to push through that
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never, not once, talked about the current dairy
legislation, and he has never tried to lobby me on this issue or
any other,'' Sweeney said. ``Besides, why in the world would Gerry
waste his time lobbying me, one of the leaders of the side that he
is on? It's absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Brady, spokesman for Reynolds, said: ``It's crazy, and I
have to wonder if the (Roll Call) reporter wasn't just looking for
a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Teator said Solomon never denied talking with Sweeney or
Reynolds about past dairy legislation. ``It's perfectly acceptable
for Sweeney or Reynolds to discuss with Gerry dairy bills that have
gone through in the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Teator also noted that Solomon talked with Sweeney and Reynolds
about the dairy issues only after the two congressmen called him
and asked for his advice.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Potter, a Washington lawyer who is an expert on lobbying
law, said it was not improper for Solomon to discuss his experience
in Congress or the history of dairy issues with Sweeney or
Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
