<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVILIANS SUFFER HIGH RATE OF CASUALTIES IN CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ Two Chechen sisters lay side by side in the
Ninth City Hospital, barely able to talk. Their bodies were riddled
with shrapnel wounds and stained green with disinfectant. One
woman, Zina Kardayeva, 42, could just lift her head to recount what
happened. The other, Aisha Nur Magomeda, 27, who was wounded in the
head, could barely whisper.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters were among the busload of people killed and wounded
on Tuesday when an artillery shell, apparently Russian, caught them
with a direct hit. In one of the worst incidents since Russia began
its invasion of Chechnya several weeks ago, 40 people were killed,
mostly women and children; 18 wounded were brought to Grozny, the
capital of the secessionist republic.
</P>
<P>
   Along dim corridors, thick with the smell of sickness and blood,
the hospital staff is struggling under an increasingly heavy load
of civilian casualties. Some patients have no sheets; one lay on
the bare springs of the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Few stay long. Relatives, anxious that Grozny might be bombed
again, are taking their wounded home again or to neighboring
republics. But those in the wards tell a tale of indiscriminate
bombing that is taking a far greater toll among the civilian
population than among any fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all civilians,'' Ms. Kardayeva said. ``We hung out a
white flag. We knew the Russians were there, but people said they
were not shooting. Two or three buses had come up that road already
that morning.''
</P>
<P>
   The bus was full; many passengers were women and children trying
to return to Chervlyonnaya, just north of Grozny, she said. They
had fled their homes when Russian forces first advanced into
Chechnya two weeks ago, but had heard that it was now safe to
return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 2 p.m. and we went over the Terek River and turned
toward Chervlyonnaya when they started to shell,'' Ms. Kardayeva
said. ``The bus turned back, and suddenly we were hit from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people started to arrive to help, they bombed more. In
the end a red Lada car came and took us away. There was blood
everywhere. And we lost all our documents.''
</P>
<P>
   By some fluke, Ms. Magomeda's two children escaped unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   A commission at Chechnya's Parliament now says 500 people have
died since Russian forces began their air and artillery bombardment
in early September. The figures are difficult to verify. There is
no city morgue or coroner who registers the dead in Grozny, and
Chechens tend to bury their dead immediately. But the number of
casualties arriving at Grozny's hospitals suggest the death toll is
in the hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   The Ninth City Hospital, Chechnya's main hospital, has treated
677 wounded to date, the chief surgeon, Aslanbek Atsalayev, said.
Thirty-five died, he added. Across town at the children's hospital,
doctors say they have treated 30 children since the bombardments
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have all been trauma cases from bomb blasts,'' said
Ruslan Aslanbekov, the chief trauma surgeon. ``All of them have had
shrapnel wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had yet to see any bullet wounds among the children.
``We had mixed cases in the previous war,'' he added, ``but this
time it is all coming from above.''
</P>
<P>
   In his wards lay four children wounded in a missile attack on
Mesketi on Sept. 23. Elita, aged 11, lay pale and thin, her legs
peppered with dark wounds. Her cousin, Ramzan, 10, cried and shook
with pain as he clutched his broken leg with both hands.
</P>
<P>
   Their uncle, Umar Haji Visambayev, 38, a bearded farmer, was
sitting with them. ``Out of the blue they started shelling at one
in the afternoon,'' he said. ``We got scared so I loaded everyone
up in into my truck, and then suddenly three mortars landed just 20
yards away.'' .
</P>
<P>
   His wife, a niece and a neighbor, still standing on the ground,
were killed instantly, he said. Eleven of the people in the cab of
the truck and piled into the open back were wounded, he said; nine
were children.
</P>
<P>
   Visambayev said he knew the high level of crime and banditry in
Chechnya had turned the world against the Chechens, but he also
appealed for understanding. ``We know we are not worthy of help
because of all the kidnapping,'' he said. ``But even so, to kill
civilians in such a way is a breach of human rights. We also have a
right to live.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the civilian casualties, the number of fighters
killed or wounded remains low. Atsalayev said he had seen only 15
wounded fighters, and those reported killed number a few dozen at
the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians keep saying how many fighters they have killed,''
he continued, ``but the fighters know how to fight and avoid the
shells. The civilians don't.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even as he spoke, news came of 30 civilians killed in Elistanzhi
in heavy bombing during the night. The evening news showed pictures
of the dead, wrapped in white shrouds for burial. There faces were
bare, showing that some victims were young children, and one was a
baby.
</P>
<P>
   What most concerns doctors is their lack of facilities. ``I
don't have the equipment or the drugs I need for them,'' Atsalayev
said. During the last war , ``the Red Cross saved 90 percent of our
patients,'' he added. ``All the humanitarian organizations gave us
a colossal amount of assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   But virtually all the aid agencies have left Chechnya in the
last three years, forced out by the wave of kidnappings and
killings, many of which were directed at foreigners. Six workers
with the International Committee of the Red Cross were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechens are now dependent on the small amounts of aid that
the Russian authorities let through. ``Very little gets through,''
Atsalayev said. ``It's going to be very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
