<HEADER>
A9833 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-LOMBARDI-COX     10-07 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LOMBARDI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Famed coach Lombardi's family life wasn't in the same
league as Packers and the game
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one in American life is more overvalued than football
coaches, and no football coach has been revered like Vince
Lombardi. It was Lombardi who said winning wasn't everything; it
was the only thing. Yet the reverence for the man hints at values
not recorded on the scoreboard _ values gone by the wayside in a
less valorous time.
</P>
<P>
   ``His bronze bust at the Pro Football Hall of Fame in Canton,
Ohio,'' David Maraniss writes in ``When Pride Still Mattered: A
Life of Vince Lombardi,'' ``has the shiniest nose, touched more
than any other by the faithful, the sporting world equivalent to
rubbing St. Peter's foot in Rome.''
</P>
<P>
   Dead nearly three decades, Lombardi lives on as a
near-mythological figure in a trench coat, roaring and thundering
from the sidelines, driving us onward, onward like Gen. Patton
racing his boys across frozen France to smite the Germans at
Bastogne.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Bay Packers of the mid-'60s became pro football's
dominant team at precisely the moment the sport was achieving
parity with baseball in popularity, and no single player was as
visible as the team's coach. The San Francisco 49ers have been Joe
Montana and the New York Jets Joe Namath. The Packers were
Lombardi, a onetime high school coach and physics teacher in
Elizabeth, N.J., who became all but synonymous with the National
Football League, the Super Bowl and the American ethos of winning.
</P>
<P>
   It's what's lost in the winning that is usually out of public
view. Just as Lombardi seemed larger than the game itself,
Maraniss' sympathetic yet unsparing portrayal of a sports legend
and his family _ religious, committed to hard work, undergirded by
all the right values _ transcends the narrow world of yard markers
and end zones. In Maraniss' deft hands, it is an American tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   God, family and the Green Bay Packers _ these were the
cornerstones of Vince Lombardi's life, and Americans hungered to
see a hero so genuine in the old-fashioned ways. But family
relationships are rarely what they seem from the outside, and the
Lombardis were no different. They were, for all their apparent
solidity, a family of strangers: wife Marie, whose only life was
her husband and his football team; daughter Susan, fun-loving in a
funless home, overweight and ignored; son Vincent Jr., unable to
live up to his father's expectations, trying all his life to reach
the man Americans admired more than they did their president.
</P>
<P>
   Maraniss, who won a Pulitzer Prize as a reporter for The
Washington Post and went on to write a biography of President
Clinton, sees in Lombardi much that was worthy of admiration. But
he sees his blind spots as well. What was to be admired was
apparent enough; it was his faults that were less visible, and not
because they were small. Maraniss paints a scene of family
togetherness you'd never see on ``The NFL Today.'' It was 1960, a
year after the new coach had rejuvenated the Packers, and the
Lombardis had moved into a new home:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not just the unused fireplaces that made the new
Lombardi house feel cold. Inside, it seemed uncomfortably silent
and somber much of the week. The halls were dark and uninviting. A
friend of Susan's said that her lasting image of the home was `one
of the sadness ... It was a sad house as soon as you walked in,
empty, you could feel the family void.' The defining scene was at
the dinner table: Vincent on one side, tense and quiet; Susan on
the other, chatting away, oblivious until she realized no one was
responding to her; Marie perched at the end nearest the kitchen,
impeccably dressed, bony and uneasy, offering little visible
motherly comfort to her children, barely showing interest in the
events of their days, instead focusing her gaze on her husband
across the way, looking at him with awe and adoration as he sat
there, eyes on his plate, chewing his meat, thinking about ... who
knows what? (Bart) Starr's sore ribs? The Bears linebackers? The
Rams passing game? A new wrinkle in the belly series? When he
cleared his throat, the others stiffened with anticipation: maybe,
at last, the father would speak, his voice deep and resounding.
Pass the salt, Marie.''
</P>
<P>
   From the above, it would be easy to conclude that the Super
Bowl-winning coach was a despot at the dinner table, benevolent in
his beliefs, obtuse in his emotions. It would also be misleading.
He enforced early curfews on his children, but a friend of Susan
Lombardi's, Mary Jo Antil, remembers when their dads took them to
the father-daughter dance. ``The girls asked if they could go out
on the town afterward,'' Maraniss writes, and their fathers agreed.
``I can still see him doing the locomotion and the watusi,'' Mary
Jo Antil told Maraniss. ``He was totally out of his realm, and he
enjoyed it immensely.''
</P>
<P>
   In recounting such fleeting episodes from a life consumed by
winning football games, Maraniss displays a psychological acuity.
Lombardi was neither a hero nor a tyrant, though he had qualities
of each. As a boy, the son of an immigrant Italian butcher, he
studied under the Jesuits and his virtues were the noble ones:
loyalty, self-sacrifice, obedience to authority.
</P>
<P>
   They were qualities an older generation, wistful for better
times, saw to the exclusion of all else. After Lombardi's death in
1970, a post-Vietnam generation would see other qualities: an
excessive zeal to win, an unhealthy single-mindedness of purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Maraniss was a student at the University of Wisconsin at
Madison, one of the rowdier campuses of the '60s, and recalls that
even there Lombardi was something of a folk hero. Part of it was
geography, Wisconsin standing atop the world of pro football. But
part, too, was the sense that Lombardi lived life passionately and
was wholly without pretense or affectation. What you saw was what
you got, and the kids could respect that.
</P>
<P>
   But what we saw Sunday afternoons on television wasn't entirely
what we imagined, and the pity of it was that Lombardi, a decent
man, knew no other way. It was he, after all, who said winning was
the only thing. The tragedy of his life was that he was unable to
reckon the cost.
</P>
<P>
   When Pride Still Mattered: A Life of Vince Lombardi. By David
Maraniss. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
