A9834 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOLLYSHANNON-COX     10-07 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOLLYSHANNON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Really real' Catholic girl a bit of Shannon
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Molly Shannon is still reeling from her 35th birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, like, so much fun,'' she coos in chatter only slightly
less frenetic than if she were talking as Mary Katherine Gallagher,
her manic Catholic schoolgirl sketch character that's been a
consistent spark for ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   So there Shannon was just three weeks ago, downing margaritas
with a big group of friends at Los Angeles' Orso restaurant, the
trendy, be-seen hangout of the stars.
</P>
<P>
   It was as boisterous a group as when she would pal around with a
pack of girlfriends and play the Tree Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends and I would say, `Pretend like you're on a date and
say goodbye to that palm tree,''' she says with definitive glee.
``You had to do it really real.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Superstar,'' Shannon's new comedy movie opening today, Mary
Katherine plays several love scenes with a tall, tall tree as her
beau. And Shannon makes it look almost too real.
</P>
<P>
   She caresses the tree. Woos it. Smooches it. Some early
screening audiences have laughed themselves silly over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superstar'' has the intensely focused Mary Katherine,
Catholicism's abundantly unrestrained schoolgirl in horn-rimmed
glasses and short-short plaid skirt, wanting desperately to be
kissed. She has her eyes focused on Sky Corrigan (Will Ferrell),
St. Monica High School's most popular guy.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish her goal, she enters her school's talent contest
for a chance at a trip to Hollywood and a possible role as an extra
in a new movie ``with positive moral values.'' In other words,
she'd become a kissable ``superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon talked by telephone recently during a break while taping
an upcoming guest appearance on MTV in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Molly, it's you and the tree. What's your motivation? In your
head, who does that tree look like?
</P>
<P>
   A:I don't necessarily have a specific guy in mind for that
scene. He could look any way, I guess. What I keep thinking is that
I really like this person and I'd like to see him again.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Mary Katherine also talks _ and gets quite chummy _ with a
stop sign. Are you thinking of the same guy?
</P>
<P>
   A:That would be a different person. You know Mary Katherine.
She's a cheater. Yeah.
</P>
<P>
   Q:In ``Superstar'' some of the dialogue is intentionally lifted
from old TV movies.
</P>
<P>
   A:I am really into those. The monologues are all from movies
I've seen. You know, loser girl wants to get into a sorority.
Portrait of a teenage alcoholic. Anorexia. Bulimia. The more
dramatic and troubled the young women are, the better.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Who was your favorite nun at your old Catholic school?
</P>
<P>
   A:Sister Rosemary. She was very young and pretty, but I thought
it was so sad that she had to wear that habit. It hides her hair.
The convent was so plain. There's this simple room and this plain
bed. What kind of life was this for a lady?
</P>
<P>
   Q:Tell me about your first kiss.
</P>
<P>
   A:It was with Tom Sullivan from my hometown of Shaker Heights
(Ohio). Right after my mom died. We used to go to this place. Into
the bushes, you know, and kiss. We were, like, 6.
</P>
<P>
   Q:And where's Tom now?
</P>
<P>
   A:He's in Cleveland. He's the nicest guy. We're friends and
stuff. He got married really young.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What's Mary Katherine's intensity all about?
</P>
<P>
   A:When she wants something she can't stop until she gets it, no
matter what gets in her way. I'm sort of like that, too. We were
doing a cover shot for this movie thing once, and all these girls
were smiling and showing off. So I pushed my way up there. I'm a
pushy girl. I wanted to be in the front.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Why is it that every time Mary Katherine leaps forward with
her arms spread, you nearly tip and fall over?
</P>
<P>
   A:I'm basically a spaz.
</P>
<P>
   MOLLY SHANNON ON VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Never Been Kissed'' (1999),
</P>
<P>
   as Drew Barrymore's gal pal.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Analyze This'' (1999).
</P>
<P>
   -- ``A Night at the Roxbury'' (1998).
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Happiness'' (1998).
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Dinner and Driving'' (1997).
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Return to Two Moon Junction'' (1994).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
