<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9837 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-STYLE-PARIS08-COX     10-07 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-PARIS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Designer feels that Celine's collection is what women really
want to wear
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paris _ Some like it hot. And some, like accessories designer
Marcia Kleinberg Sherrill like it hotter. ''The hotter the
better,'' she said Thursday after viewing New York-based Michael
Kors' spring/summer collection for Celine.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of all the collections I've seen so far in Paris, (Celine's)
had the most viability,'' said Sherrill, who came to the Celine
show dressed in a silk top hat, a feather trimmed suit, knee-high
boots and a red feather coat.
</P>
<P>
   ''The other shows have been exciting and the clothes have been
fabulous, but the bottom line is they're just about fantasy. This
show was about clothes you could really wear.''
</P>
<P>
   What women want for the warm weather months, Sherrill said, is
''color.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Celine show certainly offered that in a controlled
palette. Kors successfully set out to prove that: a) there's
nothing outdated about basic black and white; b) sea-faring shades
of blue and tropical shades of green have a sunny side to them; and
c) those blues and greens also go brilliantly with grey and silver.
</P>
<P>
   Relying heavily on the ''ombre'' technique of blending darker
hues with lighter ones, this collection conjured visions of the sea
meeting the shore, the beach meeting the breakers and the
grasslands meeting the jungle. Kors also concentrated on carefree
bleached and tie-dyed effects.
</P>
<P>
   Tailoring took a back seat to relaxed _ make that very relaxed _
silhouettes. Tops were stretchy and sheer. Dresses and skirts were
slit high, skin tight, one shouldered or a size or two too small.
The jeans _ often in stretch denim or perforated leather _ were
skin tight; the cropped jackets looked sexy and sophisticated.
Kors' stated inspiration was ``Jennifer Lopez meets Jackie O.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything could detract from the collection, it would be Kors'
insistence on showing ribbed wool sweaters that looked too bulky to
serve as swimsuit cover-ups, and his unabashed use of the
opportunity to showcase Celine accessories, including lucite diving
bags, leather duffels or denim satchels. Some outfits were
complemented with all three at once.
</P>
<P>
   Purple reign
</P>
<P>
   When Nino Cerruti stuck his thumb into Donna Karan's design
staff and discovered Peter Speliopolous, he truly plucked a plum.
Three years into his stewardship over the Cerruti label,
Speliopolous has settled in as a talent capable of refinement,
romanticism and restraint. Resisting the temptation to
over-embellish and outlandishly color his clothes the way so many
European designers have, Speliopolous restricted the Cerruti
collection to sedate shades of purple, grey and green. His reliance
on embroidery was economic. His forays into the floral motif were
well cultivated.
</P>
<P>
   The new looks from Cerruti are a study in contrasts. Most of the
pieces had a boxy cut to them. But the pants were just tight
enough, the blouses and jackets cropped just short enough, and the
dresses made of chiffons just sheer enough to make them all appear
sexy. Ruffles _ a cornerstone in most designers' collections were
few. His preference was for straight-edge collars, lapels and hems.
Polka dots and perforated leathers were the only prints shown.
</P>
<P>
   On other runways
</P>
<P>
   Rock queen Patti Smith, guiding inspiration for Antwerp designer
Anne Demeulemeester, wrote the poetry that accompanied the
soundtrack that she also partly produced for the designer's show, a
rambling dirge that perfectly set the mood for this spare,
essential show. Demeulemeester has already established some
classics looks _ like double-mesh tank tops, edgy leather
redingotes or her low-slung pants with broad waistbands, cut with
added ease at the back to hide a multitude of sins. This season,
Demeulemeester added text to the pants, shirts and dresses with
words like ``Worldwide,'' or phrases like ``Serious Wishes
Feathered in the Air'' embroidered on. Anne's big idea this season
was adding aprons to a dozen passages. The show had a nonchalant
air that sometimes masked its slick professionalism. At the very
moment Patty Smith intoned: ``Bits of human spirit that got up in
an apron,'' Amber Valletta hit the catwalk attired in a white
T-shirt and trousers but wrapped in a butcher's sized black and
white apron bearing the image of a proud hawk. Demeulemeester has
finally opened her own store. And in her familiar iconoclastic
manner she's opened up in her home town of Antwerp rather than
setting up shop in New York or London. The new 6,000 square-foot
flagship is very much in the same spirit as her fashion - clean and
modern, yet also warm and human.
</P>
<P>
   _Fashion Wire Daily contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
