<HEADER>
A9838 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CDC-FLU-COX     10-07 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDC-FLU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elderly often pass on yearly flu shot
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Many elderly people who don't get an annual flu shot
say they didn't know they needed one, or thought the vaccine could
give them the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Influenza kills 20,000 Americans every year _ and 90 percent of
those deaths occur among people 65 years and older. The vaccine can
prevent many of those deaths, and it can't cause the flu.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, as Health and Human Services Secretary Donna
Shalala made an announcement urging older Americans to get flu
shots, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention released
findings from the first national study to look at why many Medicare
beneficiaries aren't vaccinated for flu and pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   The flu vaccine, which must be received annually, and the
one-time pneumococcal vaccine are free to those enrolled in
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 65 percent of adults 65 or older said they had received
a flu shot within the past year, and 45 percent said they'd been
vaccinated for pneumonia. Vaccination rates were much lower among
African-Americans than whites.
</P>
<P>
   Not knowing they needed the vaccines was the most common reason
that study participants gave for not getting the shots. Many also
worried they could get the flu from the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   It's a common misconception. The flu shot can't cause flu,
because the vaccine is made from killed virus. It is possible,
although very rare, to get briefly sick after a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might get fever, aches for 48 hours, but no more than
that,'' said Atlanta pulmonologist Eric Honig.
</P>
<P>
   Also, people may think they have the flu when they actually have
another respiratory infection with similar symptoms, said Dr.
Carolyn Buxton Bridges of the CDC.
</P>
<P>
   The flu shot must be received every year because it is
reformulated to match the viral strains expected to circulate
during the coming flu season, which will begin in November and can
peak anywhere from December through March.
</P>
<P>
   Also, antibody protection wanes over time.
</P>
<P>
   This year's vaccine contains the Beijing, Sydney and Yamanashi
strains.
</P>
<P>
   Several flu outbreaks occurred this past summer, but the viral
strains involved were not new, and are included in this year's
vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say people should receive a flu shot before mid-November
if possible, because it can take two to six weeks for the body to
build up sufficient antibody protection against the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
