<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9840 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SYPHILIS-COX     10-07 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYPHILIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Syphilis down nationwide
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Syphilis has sunk to record lows in the United States
and could soon be eliminated from the country, the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the disease continues to have hot spots, and Atlanta's
Fulton County is one of them _ the eighth-worst county in the
United States, according to CDC statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia will get $1.2 million in CDC funding as part of an $8.6
million nationwide push to eliminate the disease, CDC director
Jeffrey Koplan announced Thursday evening in Nashville. The funding
will be stretched over three years, and Fulton County will receive
80 percent of it.
</P>
<P>
   In a new report released Thursday, CDC said there were only
6,993 cases of syphilis in the United States in 1998, or 2.6 cases
for every 100,000 people. It is the lowest rate seen since the CDC
began tracking the disease in the 1950s. In 2,430 of the country's
3,115 counties, no syphilis was diagnosed last year at all.
</P>
<P>
   But in 28 counties _ 19 of them in the South _ the disease
remains a significant problem. In Fulton last year, there were 151
cases of syphilis, the CDC said. (In the hardest-hit county,
Baltimore County, Md., there were 456.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of all new cases of syphilis now come from just 28
counties,'' said Dr. Judith Wasserheit, director of CDC's division
of sexually transmitted disease prevention. ``These are the same
communities in which we see high rates of infant mortality, lower
than average life expectancy, and high rates of diseases such as
HIV.''
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers conceal other problems. Like other sexually
transmitted diseases, syphilis is a sign that safe-sex practices
aren't being followed. In addition, syphilis makes the body two to
five times more vulnerable to HIV infection. In women, untreated
syphilis can cause severe birth defects, or kill a developing
fetus.
</P>
<P>
   And syphilis is not evenly distributed through the population.
The rate of infection in African-Americans is 34 times that of
whites, CDC said.
</P>
<P>
   Public-health experts fear the remaining pockets of syphilis
could stymie the effort to eliminate it in the United States. The
incidence of the disease increases and decreases in 10-year waves.
The last peak was in 1990, when health authorities recorded the
highest rates of syphilis in 40 years. Each time the diseases
cycles back, rates of illness and death rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The window of opportunity is very narrow and closing fast,''
Wasserheit said.
</P>
<P>
   To foil the disease's return, CDC Director Jeffrey Koplan
announced a five-point national program of syphilis elimination
Thursday. Speaking at a Nashville, Tenn., demonstration project
funded by CDC, Koplan said the agency hopes to reduce cases in the
U.S. to fewer than 1,000 by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historic moments are fleeting,'' Koplan said. ``If we do not
act now, this opportunity will be lost, certainly for many years,
perhaps forever.''
</P>
<P>
   No vaccine protects against syphilis, so elimination depends on
treating those who are infected. But unlike gonorrhea, the disease
has not developed antibiotic resistance _ so it can be easily
treated, often with one dose of antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that awareness and treatment spread widely, the CDC
program will emphasize community mobilization, involving schools,
churches and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
