u i BC-FRANCE-SYMBOL-NYT &LR;      10-07 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-SYMBOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
21-YEAR-OLD CHOSEN TO BE MODEL FOR SYMBOL OF FRENCH REPUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France's mayors announced their choice Thursday: Come
the millennium, Laetitia Casta, a 21-year-old model and actress
will be the model for Marianne, the symbol of the French Republic.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Marianne was an anonymous image of beauty and virtue
that symbolized the principles of the French Constitution. In
Delacroix's ``Liberty Leading the People'' she leads the rabble
over the barricades holding a flag in one hand and a riffle in the
other. More recently, Brigitte Bardot and Catherine Deneuve _ minus
weapons _ have been among those to pose for statues of her.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, the Association of French Mayors announced they
were looking for a new pretty face to grace the city halls and
other public buildings around the country.
</P>
<P>
   It offered its 36,000 members a choice of five celebrities _ two
supermodels, a game-show hostess, a singer and a TV news anchor _
to choose from, touching off an avalanche of objections.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the process smacked of sexism and would produce a
Marianne who had none of the values of today's women. One mayor
took the association to task for turning the choice into a beauty
contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must move away from the conventional course of a Marianne
who is uniquely a symbol of feminine beauty,'' said Francoise
Cartron, the mayor of Artigues-pres-Bordeaux. ``These days women no
longer settle for the limitations that were too often forced on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Others joined in. Michele Fitousi, chief editor of Elle
magazine, the nation's leading fashion monthly, wrote, ``If
Marianne must borrow the features of a famous woman, there are
women in literature, philosophy, politics, science, economics,
theater and film who could better represent the republic.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's association _ a group composed of only 5 percent
women _didn't budge. The head of the association, Jean Paul
Delevoye, insisted the association's choices did represent today's
woman.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Casta, who is best known for starring in lingerie ads and a
recent film version of Asterix the Gaul, got 36 percent of the
15,000 votes cast. Model Estelle Hallyday, got 29 percent. Nathalie
Simon, a former game-show hostess and windsurfing champion, got 16
percent. Patricia Kass, a waiflike singer, got 14 percent. Daniela
Lumbroso, a television journalist and the only one of the
candidates who could reasonably claim to be competing less on the
ground of glamor than as a representative of modern working women,
got the fewest votes, 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A statue of Ms. Casta is to be unveiled in November. Interviewed
on television during a break in the filming of her latest movie,
she groped for words Thursday. Finally she said that being chosen
to be Marianne at the age of 21, was ``chouette, quoi.'' an
expression that meaning roughly, ``like, neat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
