<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9843 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-FRITOLAY08-COX     10-07 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRITOLAY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frito-Lay set to close Georgia plant
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By this afternoon, the last white truck will have left
the Frito-Lay plant on Peachtree Industrial Boulevard in Chamblee,
Ga. It will haul its cases of Fritos, Lay's chips, Funyuns, Doritos
and Ruffles to stores where snack foods are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the doors will be locked for good on this Atlanta landmark
that people now in their 60s remember gaping at as schoolchildren.
At its 1956 opening, Herman W. Lay's potato-chip plant was the very
essence of mass-production modernity.
</P>
<P>
   Now, CB Commercial will sell the plant and its 14 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would imagine it will be demolished and replaced with front
parcels for commercial and retail spaces, and back parcels as
residential,'' said broker Patrick Laughlin.
</P>
<P>
   Since Frito-Lay announced the Chamblee closing in January, 440
salaried and hourly workers have retired, found other jobs, or
taken advantage of outplacement services.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 90 employees are left to finish shutting down the
plant, said Lynn Markley, a spokeswoman for Frito-Lay, the Plano,
Tex.-based snack-food arm of PepsiCo.
</P>
<P>
   She declined to say how many people have found other jobs.
Frito-Lay drivers and loading personnel weren't affected by the
layoffs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The plant's closing was part of a plan to modernize and
consolidate U.S. manufacturing and distribution operations, Markley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Chamblee, facilities were closed in Massachusetts,
Mississippi and North Carolina. About 400 to 450 jobs were cut, or
about 1 percent of PepsiCo's 40,000 workforce in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The snack-making operations are being transferred to new
factories in Lynchburg, Va., Jonesboro, Ark., and Fayetteville,
Tenn., and to two other locations. One is in Perry, Ga., and the
other is in Killingly, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamblee plant closing ``has to do with efficiency,'' said
analyst Marc I. Cohen of Goldman Sachs. The reconfiguration will
help PepsiCo, he said.
</P>
<P>
   PepsiCo's earnings per share dragged in the early 1990s, but
have shown steady increases since 1996, when Roger Enrico became
chairman and chief executive. In 1997, it sold off a fast-food unit
and bought Borden's Cracker Jack brand.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the company bought Tropicana juices from Seagram's
and brought out its own lemon-lime drink. Earlier this year,
PepsiCo took public a 65 percent interest in its bottling
operations.
</P>
<P>
   PepsiCo's first chairman, Herman Lay, a North Carolinian, came
to Atlanta as a young man.
</P>
<P>
   In 1938, he founded the H.W. Lay Co. in downtown Atlanta. In
1961, he merged the company with The Frito Co. of San Antonio, and
formed Frito-Lay. Four years later, Lay and Donald M. Kendall,
president of Pepsi-Cola, merged his company with Frito-Lay to form
PepsiCo.
</P>
<P>
   Herman Lay died in Dallas in 1982 at age 73.
</P>
<P>
   Frito-Lay currently contributes more than one-third of PepsiCo's
$16 billion in annual revenues. PepsiCo closed Thursday at $33.12
1/2, down 6 1/4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
