<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9850 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WEBVAN08-COX     10-07 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBVAN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online grocer ready to deliver
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The online grocer WebVan may be the first to bring
online grocery shopping to metro Atlanta residents.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company's S-1 registration statement with the
SEC, WebVan should begin delivering groceries to area residents in
the second quarter of next year. Last spring, Intelligent Systems
for Retailing announced the lease of a 350,000-square-foot building
in Suwanee, Ga., to WebVan which could be used as a distribution
facility.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, WebVan (www.Webvan.com) said it would delay its IPO
after the Securities and Exchange Commission said WebVan executives
were spending too much time talking to the media during the
company's ``quiet period'' prior to its IPO.
</P>
<P>
   In grocery terms, you could say that online grocer WebVan was
selling produce before it was ripe.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC was particularly concerned about articles on the
California-based company in Forbes and BusinessWeek, the Wall
Street Journal reported, citing unnamed sources.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular concern was a recent BusinessWeek cover story on
the top 25 Internet personalities, which featured WebVan CEO Louis
Borders on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   WebVan also was just a little too chatty with many institutional
investors. The company reportedly was more than willing to give out
information to potential investors that was not included in its
prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   Although Atlanta residents can buy dry goods from several
competing Web sites including Peapod (www.peapod.com), NetGrocer
(www.netgrocer.com) and Whole Foods (www.wholefoods.com), which
opened its first market in Atlanta in May, WebVan would be the
first to deliver perishable goods.
</P>
<P>
   About 200,000 shoppers buy groceries online nationwide,
according to industry reports. This is a relatively small number,
but true online grocery shopping is only available in a handful of
major cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``A market like Atlanta is something we would certainly look at.
It fits a demographic,'' said Amy Larson, a Peapod spokeswoman.
``Peapod is exploring expansion into various metropolitan markets,
and when we do, we look at a wide variety of criteria. A number of
things have to fall into place,'' she said. ``Like any expanding
business, you have to have distribution facilities, some type of
partner to provide you with inventory. And, you have to have
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
