   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UN-PEACE-COST (New York) _ The UN operation in Kosovo, expected
to have $200 million by this time, has raised only $35 million so
far, an ominous sign as the United Nations gears up for new peace
missions in East Timor, Sierra Leone and Congo. By Joe Lauria. 1000
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-HEALTH-CARE (Washington) _ House rejects GOP-backed
patient-protection bill and sets the stage for a showdown vote on a
White House-endorsed plan giving Americans broad new rights to file
lawsuits against their health insurance plans. By Bob Hohler. 1200
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TEAMSTERS (New York) _ President Clinton meets with
Teamsters President James Hoffa and the head of a major local. By
Susan Milligan. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMAIGN-BRADLEY (Peterborough, N.H.) _ Bill Bradley offers a mix
of programs aimed at work-stressed baby boomer parents, promising
billions of federal dollars for everything from child care to
community colleges. By Michael Kranish. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   NH-PRIMARY (Undated) _ The N.H. primary will be held Feb. 1,
2000, exactly as Secretary of State William Gardner scheduled it.
By Jill Zuckman. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-POLL (Boston) _ UMass poll shows an electability question
seriously dogging Al Gore, even in Clinton-friendly Massachusetts.
By Frank Phillips. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GUILIANI (New York) _ From porn shops to bus advertising that
made fun of him, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has mounted challenge after
challenge to the First Amendment. By Fred Kaplan 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   HAWKING-TOUR (Boston) _ Physicist Stephen Hawking and children
with similar disabilities converse in synthesized speech from their
wheelchairs as Hawking's tour of high-tech communications labs at
Children's Hospital draws impromptu crowds. By Richard Saltus. 700
words. PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL-SALES (Undated) _ Back-to-school sales produce big
numbers for retailers in September. By Chris Reidy. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   FIDELITY-LATE (Boston) _ Fidelity Investments joins the charge
toward after-hours trading, saying customers will be able to trade
until 8 p.m. Eastern time starting in November. By Lynnley
Browning. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   RAYTHEON-MUNITIONS (Undated) _ Raytheon expects to receive
around $800 million worth of contracts to replace munitions fired
during the Kosovo air war, about 20 percent less than it previously
forecast. By Ross Kerber. 700 words.
</P>
