<HEADLINE>
BACK-TO-SCHOOL SALES GIVE RETAILERS A LIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite Hurricane Floyd and the ups and downs of the stock
market, many US retailers reported brisk sales for September, a big
back-to-school month.
</P>
<P>
   After several unseasonably warm autumns, a cool September saw
strong demand for apparel, and with consumers still spending
freely, the early signs are that most chains can expect to enjoy a
solid holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, some Wall Street analysts looked at September sales
and lowered holiday forecasts, figuring US consumers were starting
to cut back on previously exuberant spending.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little in Thursday's numbers to suggest consumers
are about to stop their shopping spree any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no longer shop-till-you-drop,'' said Kurt Barnard,
president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report. ``It's shop _ and then
shop some more.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at sales at stores open at least a year _ a measurement
known as same-store sales _ Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd.
calculated that overall retail sales rose 6.7 percent when compared
with September sales a year ago; that was a bit better than
expectations, Bloomberg News reported.
</P>
<P>
   Economists keep ``theorizing'' that consumers can't keep up this
spending pace forever, said John Hancock Funds analyst Steve
Paspal. ``But I don't see any signs of weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment and inflation rates are low. And though the Federal
Reserve twice hiked interest rates over the summer in a bid to keep
the economy from overheating, no one has been able to detect any
real evidence of a slowdown in consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending makes up about two-thirds of the total economy
and has been responsible for much of the recent boom.
</P>
<P>
   Based on September results, Barnard said he expected retailers
to post average same-store gains of 5 percent for the holiday
season, and Paspal estimated ``mid single-digit growth.''
</P>
<P>
   East Coast retailers in the path of Hurricane Floyd saw some
mixed September sales as a result of the storm. Some lost business
because they had to temporarily close stores, but others got a
boost from consumers loading up on flashlights, food, and
generators.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, discount chains generally fared better than
department stores. Consumers may be spending freely, but many of
them were still hunting for values.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc., the world's largest retailer, said
same-store sales were up 7.2 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
   Bradlees Inc., the Braintree, Mass. discount chain, said
same-store sales rose 10.2 percent for the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``September sales continue our strong sales momentum,'' said
Peter Thorner, Bradlees chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Bradlees, which has performed well since emerging from
bankruptcy protection early this year, also said it was opening two
stores, one in Philadelphia, the other in New Jersey. These are the
first store openings for the chain in four years.
</P>
<P>
   TJX Cos. of Framingham, Mass. continued its winning ways. Led by
its T.J. Maxx and Marshalls chains, the company said same-store
results for September rose 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales trends this fall continue to be robust,'' said TJX
chairman and chief executive Bernard Cammarata.
</P>
<P>
   BJ's Wholesale Club Inc. of Natick, Mass. said its monthly
same-store sales were up 6.9 percent. ``September sales reflect
strong demand for apparel, jewelry, and computer software,'' said
BJ's president and chief executive Jack Nugent.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury retailer Neiman Marcus has seen the pace of business pick
up in recent months. Though the Chestnut Hill, Mass. retailer had
easy comparisons with last September's soft sales, this year's gain
of 13.5 percent is partly because customers are willing to pay full
price for the chain's high-end apparel lines and women's
accessories, said chain spokesman Peter Farwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of momentum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A willingness to pay full price also helped Talbots Inc. of
Hingham, Mass. post big numbers. Earlier in the week, the company
said its September same-store sales rose a whopping 16.6 percent.
In recent years, Talbots had seemed to lose touch with its
customers _ middle-age women who favor classic fashions.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Talbots hired chief merchandising officer H. James
Metscher to help engineer a comeback. His first product line has
just reached stores, and customers were snapping it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customer response to our fall merchandise in both stores and
catalog was exceptional during the month'' of September, said
Arnold B. Zetcher, Talbot's president and chief executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
