<HEADLINE>
MIXED TOPICS FOR CARROLL AT PRESS CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The vastly different worlds of baseball and
football injuries converged Thursday at Pete Carroll's daily press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll announced that middle linebacker Ted Johnson's timetable
to return to practice from his torn left biceps tendon has been
accelerated to ``early November.'' He also predicted running back
Robert Edwards (knee) will make it back to football. And he spoke
passionately about the injury suffered Wednesday by Red Sox ace
Pedro Martinez in Game 1 of the AL Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was asked whether he thought Martinez should have stayed
in the game, and whether a football player would have come out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask Pedro. Do you think he'd take himself out of the game if
he couldn't play?'' Carroll said. ``This guy is a great competitor,
so there's no way. The guy couldn't perform. To think anything else
. . . What are you thinking? How can you even start to think that?
He couldn't play. I'm dead serious about it. That guy would have
been in there. You don't think he wanted to win that game? Look
what he's done. Anyone who would question that ethic is a thousand
miles off track.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is throwing the ball 100 miles per hour. With the
body he has, he has to be perfectly finely tuned. He wasn't gonna
be able to help his team. He didn't think he could because he was
hurt. He was right. Think about how hard it was for him to have to
do that. It's killing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll turned less serious when he was asked if the Patriots
staff would have rushed Martinez back. ``That's right. We'd be
rubbing him down and (having) the laying of the hands, throwing
chicken legs at him,'' quipped Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has apparently been throwing those same chicken legs at
Johnson, who this week has engaged in pre-practice drills for the
first time since his training camp injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted is encouraged and the doctors are encouraged so that makes
me feel encouarged,'' Carroll said. ``He's at practice now for the
first week doing the footwork drills, and starting to get into the
movement things we do with linebackers, working in the weight room
on a strict program. We're looking toward the day when he has full
flexibility and when he can really scale up his lifting. What this
leads to is an opitmistic date of him being able to practice in
early November.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Ted and I are looking at, and the doctors are
talking somewhat later than that. We're trying to beat it by two or
three weeks. He's doing quite well. He's at all the meetings; he's
involved with everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson realizes he'd be ``beating the odds'' if he returns to
game action by his target date of Thanksgiving, but he's going for
it. Johnson has some experience with this rehab. He suffered the
same injury to his right biceps tendon last December while trying
to tackle Steelers running back Jerome Bettis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tendon is still very sensitive,'' Johnson said. ``You can
bang it against a table and feel the pain through your arm. We have
to get full flexibility first. I still can't straighten my arm out.
We're trying to be optimistic and hope to salvage the season, but
sometimes it feels like maybe we're trying to speed something up
that won't let it be sped up.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is at the eight-week point after the surgery. Thinking
back to the eight-week period following the other biceps injury,
Johnson said, ``I was sitting at home on my couch not doing
anything. I was told to rest it. At the time, it was the offseason
and there was no reason to rush it, because if you just let it heal
on its own for five months it'll heal on its own. But you won't
have the muscle definition nor mass you need to play football.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Johnson has begun the other aspects of training. He's
been working on his legs, abdominals, back, and even his ``good
arm.'' Johnson said that when the time comes, he hopes to be able
to step right back on the field.
</P>
<P>
   It's an optimism Carroll has inspired in Johnson. It is an
optimism Carroll still feels for Edwards, who has made great
progress after suffering a severe left knee dislocation during a
rookie event during Pro Bowl weekend in February. Edwards is still
working out at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Robert Edwards is gonna make it back,'' said Carroll.
``Robert Edwards thinks he's gonna make it back. Not many people on
the other side think that. How else can you have a miraculous
recovery? How else can you have a rehab that's off the charts if
you don't think that way? If you get back when they tell you to get
back, you have a normal rehab. Well, we ain't going for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how fortunate Ted's recovery is without setbacks. If
it goes on track, maybe he will be back by then. I don't care what
they (doctors) think right now. I consciously want to be very
optimistic. I'm just telling you what we're shooting for. If it
stays on course, then we'll just back it up and continue to try and
accelerate that date.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain his stance, Carroll said, ``I'm a coach and
they're the doctors. They want him to heal and I want him to play.
I don't like the time frames on any of these injuries. I'm not
satisfied with `it's a two-week injury, get back when you can get
back.' Get back on the field as soon as possible. That's how we
approach injuries. Sometimes we come back too early, sometimes we
come back too late. I'm at odds with the doctors all the time over
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he's lifting light weight, ``about the amount of a
can of coffee. . . . I'm doing everything I can do in the meantime,
so there won't be much else to catch up on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson the tutor
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has continued in his role as mentor to Andy Katzenmoyer.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Carroll pulled him into the office to go over the
defensive game plan for Kansas City. The coach got Johnson's input
on what he feels Katzenmoyer would be comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew when I was younger the game plans were sometimes
too much for me to comprehend,'' said Johnson. ``I just think if
you simplify things for a young guy they're much better off.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sky's the limit for Cloud
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City coach Gunther Cunningham didn't know whether former
Boston College running back Mike Cloud would be active after
dressing for the first time last week. ``His character and work
ethic are nothing but tremendous for him,'' he said. ``With Kimble
Anders out, he started dressing this week. He played a lot on our
special teams. I hope he'll play this week. I think he will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs will enter Sunday's game a bit banged up. The biggest
concern is left tackle, where veteran Glenn Parker (elbow) will not
play. There is a possibility the Chiefs may activate John Tait,
their first-round pick from Brigham Young, for the first time. Tait
held out and was a late arrival at camp. Also questionable are
running back Bam Morris (hamstring) and defensive tackle Ty Parten
(shoulder).
</P>
</TEXT>
