<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-LATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY GETTING INTO LATE-TRADING GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Betting that stock market-crazed Americans want to buy
and sell shares well into the night, Fidelity Investments will let
ordinary investors trade securities outside traditional market
hours beginning next month.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Fidelity, the nation's biggest mutual fund firm,
said Thursday it would extend its trading hours for on-line
investors to include a 4:30 p.m.-to-8 p.m. slot.
</P>
<P>
   The steps by Fidelity, which is also the nation's second largest
discount brokerage, follow similar moves by competitors in recent
months. Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., the San Francisco-based fund purveyor
and the leading discount brokerage, announced after-hours trading
plans earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The race is to capture the allegiance and wallets of wealthy,
do-it-yourself investors, who account for the lion's share of
revenues at on-line brokerages. The bet is that investors can't get
enough of Wall Street's record-breaking bull market and will want
to monitor their portfolios, research companies, and trade stocks
well into the evening. The hope is that extended hours will appeal
to West Coast investors, who are three hours behind the New
York-based markets and practically unable to trade after lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Web brokerages also want to offer clients who work during
regular market hours the opportunity to trade once they get home.
</P>
<P>
   ``After-hours trading is a service that is of great interest to
our involved, active traders,'' said Tracey Curvey, executive vice
president of Fidelity's on-line brokerage, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's main exchanges _ the New York Stock Exchange and
the Nasdaq over-the-counter market _ open at 9 a.m. The NYSE sounds
its closing bell at 4 p.m.; its cousin, under a new schedule, two
and a half hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional, or professional, investors have long been able to
trade stocks through the night, using alternative, round-the-clock
exchanges known as electronic communications networks. Most ECNs
shut down sometime during the 30 minutes following the NYSE's close
to regroup for extended trading.
</P>
<P>
   But do ordinary investors really want to skip dinner to buy
Microsoft?
</P>
<P>
   Dan Burke, an on-line brokerage analyst at Gomez Advisers, said
the after-hours market was quite small and would take a while to
grow. ``The volumes are just not there yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After-hours trading is likely to appeal less to day traders _
investors who frantically buy and sell stocks dozens of times a day
_ and more to active but serious investors who trade dozens of
times a year.
</P>
<P>
   The boom in on-line brokerages has attracted millions of such
investors in recent years. ``Serious investors now dominate the
Internet investing landscape,'' Burke said, adding that people
trading from 80 to 100 times a year _ so-called hyperactive traders
_ now account for only 10 percent of the on-line investing market,
compared with 50 percent two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Under its after-hours trading program, to start in early
November, Fidelity will allow clients to place limit orders _
commands to buy securities at or below a set price _ for Nasdaq
stocks and a limited number of NYSE stocks. Investors must buy
round lots of at least 100 shares.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Fidelity would offer 24-hour trading, spokesman
James Griffin said, ``This is a start; we'll look at things as we
move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Datek Online Holdings, a Web-only brokerage, began the
after-hours craze for ordinary investors in August. Soon, ETrade
Group, a competitor, teamed up with Reuters' Instinet, one of the
biggest ECNs, to do the same. Traditional Wall Street brokerages,
including Citigroup's Salomon Smith Barney and Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, followed suit. Even the NYSE is considering extended hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's potentially a growth market,'' said Amar Mehta, an
industry analyst at CIBC World Markets. ``But after a while, people
are going to want to do something other than trade stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of ECNs and various extended-hours trading
programs has industry regulators worried that the after-hours
market is fragmented, chaotic, and potentially unable to provide
investors with the best prices.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity will process after-hours trades through REDIBook, an
ECN it co-owns with Schwab; Spear, Leeds &AMP; Kellogg; and Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. The latter, a Wall Street investment bank and
brokerage, also announced extended trading hours Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
