<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9881 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-OBIT-DACUS-TEX     10-07 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DACUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELVIN O. DACUS: CO-FOUNDER OF CASA MANANA MUSICALS IN FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: If available typographically, the first ``n'' in Manana takes
a tilde), (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PERRY STEWART 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Melvin O. Dacus _ a singer, actor and
producer who co-founded Casa Manana Musicals and symbolized musical
theater in North Texas for four decades _ died Wednesday of
congestive heart failure at his Fort Worth home. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   Family members, including Katy Dacus, his wife of 50 years and
frequent co-star on stage, were with him when he died.
</P>
<P>
   Entombment will be private. Visitation will be until noon Monday
at Greenwood Funeral Home in Fort Worth. A memorial service will be
at 3 p.m. Monday at University Christian Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   During the Dacus era as vice president or producer/general
manager of the theater-in-the-round, the Casa stage was a summer
proving ground for many performers who would become famous, among
them Betty Buckley, Beverly Sills, Morgan Fairchild, Cindy Pickett
and Brent Spiner.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Dacus' tenure at Casa also saw the introduction to Fort
Worth audiences of Ruta Lee, arguably the most popular performer in
that theater's history.
</P>
<P>
   To one generation of theatergoers, Mr. Dacus was known as
producer/general manager of Casa. To those of a later era, he was
the white-bearded character actor known for a range of portrayals
including Tevye in ``Fiddler on the Roof,'' crotchety Sheridan
Whiteside in ``The Man Who Came to Dinner,'' the grandfather in the
religious pageant ``The Promise'' and an elderly ex-rodeo rider in
``The Golden Shadows Old West Museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Dacus' many appearances as Santa Claus in TV commercials and
live productions established him in the minds of many as the next
best thing to the Jolly Old Elf himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I wrote my novel, The Autobiography of Santa Claus, the
voice I kept hearing in my head was Mel's,'' said Star-Telegram
books editor Jeff Guinn. ``It was a thrill for me when Mel provided
Santa's voice on the audiobook version.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Dacus was born March 15, 1923, in Fort Worth. His father,
James Alexander Dacus, was head of the Texas Christian University
business school when it moved to Fort Worth. The elder Dacus helped
select the site of the current campus.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Dacus graduated from TCU in 1944 and had a longtime
association with the university. Friends and family have
established a performance award in his memory at TCU.
</P>
<P>
   His last major stage appearance was in 1995 as the philosophical
furniture dealer in ``The Price'' at Theatre Three in Dallas. In a
Star-Telegram interview a few weeks before his death, Mr. Dacus
said it was one of his favorite roles.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mr. Dacus was weak and confined to bed, he raised up to
greet the reporter in his familiar robust baritone. His eldest
daughter, a nurse, cautioned him: ``You're not on stage, Daddy.
Don't try to project. It'll tire you out.''
</P>
<P>
   In that final interview, Mr. Dacus reflected on many aspects of
his life, including the World War II combat experience that few of
his show business friends knew about. He was a young lieutenant
among the second wave of Marines to land on Iwo Jima. Although he
rarely talked about the war in later years, the experience had a
profound influence on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there when they raised the flag the second time on
Iwo,'' he recalled. ``I couldn't really see it because I was
hunkered down in a foxhole. But I heard the other men up closer
cheering _ kind of a guttural cheer, almost a growl. I'll never
forget the sound.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Dacus and Fort Worth oilman James H. Snowden formed the
nonprofit corporation that built Casa Manana in 1958 on the Fort
Worth site of the Casa Manana amphitheater, which showman Billy
Rose created for the 1936 Texas Centennial. For several years Mr.
Dacus served as vice president of Casa Manana Musicals. He became
producer/general manager in 1966, holding that post until 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The family suggests that expressions of sympathy be in the form
of contributions to the Melvin O. Dacus Performance Award in care
of Adam Baggs, University Advancement Office, TCU P.O. Box 297044,
Fort Worth, TX 76129.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Katy Dacus, who appeared in many
productions with her husband; daughter Kim Dacus Reynolds and son,
Brent Dacus, all of Fort Worth; daughter Mindy Dacus Fabiano of Los
Angeles; a brother, James Alexander Dacus Jr. of Fort Worth; and a
sister, Maude Englantine Bennett of Dallas.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
