<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9883 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTONLAB08-COX     10-07 1576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTONLAB08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TRIES TO WOO LABOR FOR GORE
 &HT;    Eds: Retopping a story that originally moved for Sept. 24.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Thursday became the first
chief executive since Franklin D. Roosevelt to address members of
the Teamsters' union.
</P>
<P>
   The timing was no accident.
</P>
<P>
   With Vice President Al Gore locked in a battle with former U.S.
Sen. Bill Bradley over the Democratic presidential nomination,
organized labor has become a key battleground.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a meeting in New York with James Hoffa, president
of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters, Clinton wouldn't say
whether he came out and asked the labor leader to endorse Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, we didn't talk much about that,'' Clinton told
reporters, adding that much of the conversation centered on Hoffa's
concern over international trading agreements and the growing
imbalance between the United States and its global trading
partners.
</P>
<P>
   `` We had a good talk about golf,'' said Clinton. ``We didn't
talk too much about other politics.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech later to 1,000 labor officials and analysts at a
dinner honoring Hoffa, Clinton ticked off the litany of initiatives
he's pressed on behalf of American workers: raising the minimum
wage, fighting for improved health care coverage and shoring up
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   It was his standard rhetorical message, but this time with a
special appeal: anyone happy with Clinton's agenda should vote to
replace him with the next best thing - Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been seeking labor's endorsement since February but has
been countered so far by Bradley, who has trudged through union
halls across the country seeking the support of leaders and rank
and file workers.
</P>
<P>
   With the nation's labor organizations _ a traditional Democratic
stronghold _ yet to endorse Gore, Clinton has raised his profile
among worker unions over the past week.
</P>
<P>
   He delivered a eulogy for the late AFL-CIO icon Lane Kirkland
last week in Washington. And on Thursday he journeyed to New York
to address the dinner honoring Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkland's funeral, naturally, was unforseen, but there was
nothing accidental in the timing of Thursday's address.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO, a federation of labor unions, including the
powerful Teamsters, holds its annual convention next week in Los
Angeles. Clinton is pressing the group, the largest labor
organization in the country, to step forward and cast its lot with
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   It's not an easy sell. Organized labor is still smarting from
Clinton's work five years ago to pass the North American Free Trade
Agreement, or NAFTA. The controversial treaty essentially wedded
the U.S., Canadian and Mexican economies, putting millions of
American workers in direct competition with their low-wage rivals
south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa took Clinton to task over the issue again on Thursday, and
no card-carrying union member has forgotten that it was Gore who
defended the treaty in a widely viewed televised debate against
NAFTA opponent Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   As in his appeal to organized labor, Clinton faces complications
in his efforts to help Gore more broadly.
</P>
<P>
   His own presidency is indelibly stained by scandal. There are
signs that the public is weary of Clinton and his political and
personal entourage. And when he plays to his rhetorical strengths,
it often highlights Gore's own limitations in connecting with
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Clinton can help him only in a very careful sort of
way,'' said Darrell West, a Brown University political science
professor. ``He can't be heavy-handed about helping him.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidents have a natural tendency to be cautious in promoting
their number-twos, whether because of petty jealousy, professional
egotism or reservations borne of working closely with them for four
or more years.
</P>
<P>
   Few vice presidents have won election to replace their bosses.
In 1988, George Bush became the first sitting vice president to be
elected to the top job since Martin Van Buren's win 152 years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The White House insists that Clinton very much wants Gore to be
the next president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you with 100 percent certainty that he's not
ambivalent,'' said Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said Lockhart, Clinton views Gore's campaign as
something of a mission, one key to the Clinton legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He honestly believes that we've changed the way we do business
in this town,'' said Lockhart. ``It's very important to him that we
build on this success, rather than undo many of the steps we've
taken to move forward, and he thinks that the vice president's the
best person to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore can take credit, too, for many successes _ including an
economy that has grown by nearly 40 percent on Clinton's watch _
stemming from Clinton, who still enjoys a 59 percent job approval
rating, according to a two-week-old Gallup poll.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the best way to translate that into gains for Gore,
though, is dicey.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things any vice president seeking the
presidency must do is convince the public that, after years of
playing a supporting role, he's suddenly ready to lead.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton to take an aggressive approach in the selling of Al
Gore might only underscore Clinton's leadership abilities, not
Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem for a vice president always is to establish
themselves as their own person without repudiating their boss,''
said Jonathan Siegel, director of the Harris Interactive Election
2000, a project of the Rochester, N.Y.,-based Harris polling
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to Al Gore to both have the message and the ability to
communicate it,'' said Siegel. ``Bill Clinton can't do it for him,
his handlers can't do it and his advisers can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore appears to suffer, moreover, in areas where Clinton is
strong.
</P>
<P>
   A poll taken Sept. 10-14 among 1,698 Americans by the Gallup
Organization shows Gore trailing George W. Bush by 19 points in
people's perceptions of Gore's effectiveness as a manager; by 16
points in his ability to affect change; and by 20 points in his
ability to inspire others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the same things that Clinton has done well on
historically,'' said Frank Newport, editor in chief of the Gallup
Polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Bill Clinton transfers those kinds of characteristics onto
Gore is a real challenge,'' said Newport. ``I don't think that you
can do that by osmosis.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore-Clinton equation is further complicated by Clinton's
impeachment-marred conduct in office. Enough Americans from both
parties still regard Clinton's behavior as sufficiently
reprehensible, and his impact on the office as sufficiently
corrosive, that Gore stands to suffer, in some quarters at least,
by association.
</P>
<P>
   At best, Clinton polarized much of the nation, splitting the
electorate into Clinton supporters and Clinton despisers. That's
left precious little of the ideological middle ground over which
presidential campaigns are fought.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were Al Gore, would I really want Bill Clinton going
around and campaigning for me,'' wondered Roger Hartley, who
teaches government at Roanoke College in Salem, Va. ``The president
is kind of a lightning rod.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from those who feel strongly one way or the other about
Clinton, there appears to be a substantial portion of the American
public that has simply overdosed on the rich media diet of Clinton
fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this phenomenon out there, Clinton fatigue, that
makes it hard for Clinton to go out there and help Gore,'' said Dan
Thomas, professor of political science at Warburg College in
Waverly, Iowa. ``It could amount to the kiss of death.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One group that is anything but fatigued, however, consists of
the long-term Democratic Party stalwarts who recall with a shudder
the party's pre-Clinton malaise. They credit the president, despite
his faults, for having reinvented and reinvigorated the entire
party.
</P>
<P>
   These backers turn out en masse at fund-raisers and rallies,
where Clinton invariably receives a rock star's reception. He
remains able to electrify a crowd like no other politician of his
generation. To the extent that's useful to Gore, Clinton is
prepared to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If going out and raising money is helpful he's going to do
that. If going and making appearances is helpful he's going to do
that,'' said Lockhart. ``If staying here and concentrating on
getting things done is helpful he's going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   As a backdrop for appearing presidential, it's hard to beat the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   West said he would expect to see Clinton do everything possible
in the months ahead to portray Gore as a co-partner in the
administration's achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do it by sharing credit, making sure the vice president
gets a lot of press, giving him positive announcements to make and
sending him to foreign funerals, where he can look presidential and
meet with foreign leaders,'' said West.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Clinton and Gore will both face the limits on what
one man can do for another. Public perceptions aren't always easily
swayed and no amount of praise from a figure of boundless charisma
can create the same persona in another.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's hurting Gore currently,'' said Newport, ``is Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
