<HEADER>
A9888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HONDURAS-GUERRILLAS-A     10-07 0284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-GUERRILLAS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EL AGUACATE, Honduras: national interest.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet, eager to take advantage of the planting season and
emboldened by their previous victories, the farmers' group started
to fence in and cultivate the land on the base last May. A few
weeks later, they encountered troops conducting military exercises
on their fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were great explosions, machine guns, big guns,''
Rodriguez said. ``Some commandos came to us with rifles in hand and
stopped our machines. They took down all the fence posts.''
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, the farmers were taking reporters to the base to
show them how the military was responding. By August, the farmers
began talking about the graves and cells that were on the base,
prompting an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are fed with basic grains, not guns and
munitions,'' Rodriguez said. ``We can no longer justify any more
aggression and marginalization by the army.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict has resulted in claims of death threats, as well as
accusations that one Honduran officer shot 87 cattle dead. It has
worried human rights advocates, who say the region is saturated
with AK-47 assault rifles left behind by the Contra army. They hope
the court ruling, as well as the investigations into just what lies
dormant in El Aguacate's earth, will end a sad and violent part of
their recent history.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers hope so, too, saying they want El Aguacate to become
a place that sustains life once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our land back,'' Rodriguez said. ``Then we can become
productive again. Then the soldiers of Aguacate can leave this land
and go to the border where the country needs their force. Or back
to their barracks.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
