<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WIRED-CITIES08-COX     10-07 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRED-CITIES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta among top Net-connected cities
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta ranks fifth among the nation's most
Internet-accessible cities, which makes it well-positioned to grow
economically in the coming years, according to a study by geography
specialists at Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   The other top five cities, in order, are Washington, D.C.,
Chicago, Dallas and New York. The rest of the top 10 are San Jose,
Calif., Los Angeles, Houston, San Francisco and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers measured ``accessibility'' by the number of Internet
connections to and from each city through 31 major commercial Net
backbones.
</P>
<P>
   Morton O'Kelly, co-author and professor of geography at OSU,
said the premise of the study was that high-ranking cities in the
survey have some advantages in the global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, cities with more linkages to the Internet backbone
will have faster access and more reliable connections to global
information,'' O'Kelly said. ``This enhanced access results in a
comparative advantage that will grow in importance with the
continuing global computerization of information.''
</P>
<P>
   The important Internet backbones mostly include giants like
AT&AMP;T, Sprint and others, as well as Internet service providers such
as MindSpring. These are all considered ``on-ramps'' to the big
Internet highways, O'Kelly said. Cities with the most connections
were rated as the most accessible.
</P>
<P>
   The combined domestic network contains 31 backbones encompassing
141 cities and 848 linkages, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   The cities with the major advantages in terms of Internet
accessibility include the four major national access points, he
said, namely San Francisco, Chicago, New York and Washington. Think
of these as the main entrances and exits to the Internet in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is interesting about Atlanta is that it ranks high even
though it is not an NAP,'' O'Kelly said. ``We found that what makes
Atlanta rank high is the volume of activity you see there as a kind
of communications crossroad, much like the highway and air traffic
grid for which the city is known.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet access picture changes constantly, O'Kelly said,
but to some extent strength begets strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find a peer influence where big communications companies
attract others,'' he said. ``And the presence of multiple sources
creates redundancy and reliability that is valued by customers, and
that value creates growth.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Kelly emphasized that the study essentially is a snapshot of
1997 information, so the conclusions are subject to aging and
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Engineers are constantly looking at this kind of information,
spotting holes and areas of weakness, and then setting about to
construct more capacity,'' O'Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that because policy-makers are gradually beginning to
appreciate the economic advantages of quality Internet access, they
are working to stimulate growth in the infrastructure across the
country and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our future work, we are taking a look at cities around the
world to assess Internet accessibility and measure their economic
responses to the advantages that many American cities enjoy,'' said
O'Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ohio State study, published in the current issue of the
journal Professional Geographer, the analysts found that cities in
the West were more Internet-accessible than cities in other
regions.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly strong, of course, were Silicon Valley and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results are not unexpected, given the growth of computer
technology and investment in the Internet in California over the
past decade,'' O'Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Many major centers adjoined other strong centers, he said, such
as Washington, which was bolstered by Virginia and Maryland suburbs
with strong Internet accessibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta was unique as a city somewhat isolated in the region
but still a focus of Internet activity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
