<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9897 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-850&AMP;ADD     10-07 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMPAIGN TRYING TO DEFINE `COMPASSIONATE CONSERVATIVE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON with FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For as long as Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has
been describing himself as a ``compassionate conservative,''
Republicans and Democrats alike have wondered whether the phrase
was a call for a flexible new ideology or an attempt to put a
friendlier face on an essentially unchanged philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's public statements, including his denunciation this week
of his party's focus on wealth, suggest a willingness to use his
commanding position in the Republican presidential race to
challenge some of the party's assumptions about what it stands for.
</P>
<P>
   But as he starts to set out specific positions, particularly on
high visibility issues like taxes and economic policy, Bush is by
no means abandoning the conservative principles that have defined
the party at least since the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is clearly attempting a delicate balancing act, seeking to
retain the faith of the party's conservative base even as he courts
the moderate swing voters he would need to win the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond political positioning, Bush's fuzziness may also
reflect the early stage of the campaign, when candidates are still
formulating policy positions, as well as some debate within his
campaign about how far he should tilt in either direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still a work in progress,'' said William A. Niskanen, an
economic adviser in the Reagan administration who is now chairman
of the Cato Institute, a conservative research organization in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail and in meetings with his policy advisers,
Bush emphasizes a traditional conservative belief in the power of
free markets and is as enthusiastic as any Reagan-era supply-sider
in calling for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   His economic advisers, many of whom served in the Reagan and
Bush administrations, are drawn from centers of orthodox
conservative thought like the Hoover Institution at Stanford
University and the American Enterprise Institute, a research
organization in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The basic thrust of his advisers remains reducing marginal tax
rates, a step that cuts tax bills proportionally more for the
wealthy, who pay the most taxes, than for middle- and lower-income
people. And they back specific tax cuts that Democrats have long
said are skewed to the rich, including the elimination of the
inheritance tax on large estates.
</P>
<P>
   Where Bush and his team seem to be taking a fresh approach is in
applying conservative orthodoxy in new ways.
</P>
<P>
   They point out, for example, that high marginal tax rates can be
more of a problem for a single mother working her way out of
poverty than for an investment banker.
</P>
<P>
   As workers move from income levels associated with the working
poor _ below $20,000 a year _ into middle-class income levels, they
often lose all or part of tax credits and breaks like the
earned-income tax credit, and enter higher-income tax brackets,
meaning that a big chunk of their additional earnings goes to
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers say the main policy idea behind ``compassionate
conservatism'' at this point is to help people in that kind of
situation, probably through an expansion of the earned-income tax
credit or through other changes to the tax code that would allow
low- to middle-income workers to take home more of what they earn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush understands and very much believes that high
marginal tax rates create enormous disincentives,'' said Lawrence
B. Lindsey, a former Federal Reserve governor who heads the
candidate's economic policy team. ``What may be new here is the
realization, which he's talked about on the stump, that high
marginal rates affect not only high-income people but a lot of
low-income people as well.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lindsey, Bush's economic team includes Michael
Boskin, who was chief economist in the Bush White House; John F.
Cogan, a former budget aide to President Reagan; Martin Feldstein,
a former Reagan administration chief economist; John B. Taylor, an
expert on monetary policy who worked on Bob Dole's 1996
presidential campaign, and R. Glenn Hubbard, who was a Treasury
Department official under President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the team say they consider themselves technicians,
simply taking the goals laid out by Bush and finding ways of
translating them into workable policies. Yet there is concern among
other Republicans working with Bush that the campaign will be too
tentative in trying to redefine the party, and will in effect miss
an opportunity to broaden the party's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Especially after the failure of the big Republican tax cut to
generate much public enthusiasm before it was vetoed by President
Clinton, they would like to see Bush support a tax plan that
clearly repositions the party toward the political center by
adopting some of the approaches supported by the Democrats,
including more tax breaks targeted to the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why it is so important for Governor Bush's plan to
lean in the direction of those left behind,'' said one adviser to
Bush, speaking on the condition of anonymity, ``is because it's the
right policy and the right politics if we want to recapture the
idea of being the party of the middle class.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Outside of his economic team, Bush's most influential advisers
include a number of advocates of fresh approaches to domestic
policy, including Mayor Steve Goldsmith of Indianapolis; Mike
Gerson, the governor's speechwriter, and Marvin Olasky, a
conservative theoretician who advocates harnessing faith-based
programs and charities to address social ills.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Bush effectively shot down a proposal by Republicans
in the House to delay payments to the working poor under the
earned-income tax credit program, saying Congress should not
balance the budget ``on the backs of the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   And this week he said that Republicans had too often ``focused
on the national economy, to the exclusion of ll else,'' and that
the strongest argument for conservative ideals should be ``that
they lead to greater justice, less suffering, more opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has angered some Republican members of Congress with his
criticism of how the party has conducted itself, and he has been
attacked by several of his rivals for the party's nomination,
including Steve Forbes and Gary Bauer, for being insufficiently
conservative on both economic and social policy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there has not been any widespread uprising against him by
conservatives, in part because of his big lead in the polls. And
his advisers suggest that unlike his father, Bush seems to have a
Reaganesque ability to communicate a conservative agenda in a
nonthreatening way that defuses Democratic attempts to portray the
Republican party as mean-spirited.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has publicly said he is a supply-sider, and when he says
that he says it with a passion that gives conservatives in the
Republican party more comfort than they get from candidates who are
viewed as more conservative,'' said Rep. Rob Portman, a Republican
from Ohio who is working with the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time he's comfortable focusing on issues like
charitable giving,'' Portman said. ``Perhaps what he is showing us
is that because of the power of his personality or the strength of
his passion, he can break through and persuade people that these
are not inconsistent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
