<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9898 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-INDIA-POLITICS-400(2T     10-07 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-400(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COALITION LED HINDU NATIONALIST PARTY WINS INDIAN ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The verdict of some 360 million Indian voters
was announced Thursday: The Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata
Party, once seen as the ugly, anti-Muslim face of Hindu revivalism,
won a clear victory as the leader of a centrist coalition of 24
parties that appears likely to offer India its most durable
government in several years.
</P>
<P>
   And the Congress Party, the once dominant, now faded political
force that had desperately hoped to make a comeback under Sonia
Gandhi, torchbearer of the Nehru-Gandhi dynasty, was handed the
most humiliating defeat it has ever suffered since India gained its
independence from Britain in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   The BJP did not actually increase the number of seats it holds
in Parliament, but it made several smart new alliances with rising
state-level parties that produced the coalition's larger majority.
By late Thursday night, the BJP and its allies had won 294 seats,
well past the bare majority needed among the Parliament's 543
elected seats. And they were expected to pick up a couple more
seats by the time counting is completed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for its allies' support, the BJP has promised that
it will not pursue the agenda that has raised the hackles of
Muslims and secularists alike, which includes building a Hindu
temple on the site of a 16th century mosque in Ayodhya that Hindu
militants tore down with sledgehammers and crowbars in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The previous incarnation of the Hindu nationalist-led coalition
had tottered along for 13 months until April, when a temperamental
former movie star, Jayalalitha Jayaram, yanked the 18 votes of her
regional party out from under it and caused the government to fall.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the alliance, which is expected to form a new
government next week, will have enough votes to survive even if a
couple of its more quixotic partners pull out.
</P>
<P>
   This extra measure of breathing room _ while not large _ may
give Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, a grandfatherly looking
moderate in the Hindu nationalist party, the strength to tackle
some of the stickiest issues that face this nation of 1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee, 72, has said he will try to bring India and Pakistan,
neighboring nuclear powers now almost completely estranged, back to
the bargaining table, as well as to improve the performance of the
economy in India, where 300 million people live in abject poverty.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee himself is a complex, ambiguous figure. He has
professed great admiration for India's first prime minister, the
Congress Party leader and confirmed secularist, Jawaharlal Nehru.
And he has described the destruction of the mosque in Ayodhya _ an
act that many blamed on other leaders of his party _ as a blunder.
</P>
<P>
   But for more than three decades Vajpayee has also been a
stalwart of the Hindu nationalist party, and his kindly face and
mild temperament have made acceptable the rise of a party that, in
religously diverse India, has pursued the idea that Hinduism should
define the national ethos.
</P>
<P>
   It was also Vajpayee who decided last year that India should
break an almost 25-year-old moratorium and conduct underground
nuclear tests, a move that inspired Pakistan to respond in kind.
Earlier this year he went on a peacemaking trip to Pakistan, then
acted forcefully to battle Pakistan-supported forces that occupied
Indian territory in the disputed state of Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee himself made no public remarks Thursday. And the
Congress Party president's, Mrs. Gandhi, never stepped outside her
fortresslike compound. Instead, the spin cycle of Indian politics
played out in marathon sessions on state television and the private
Star TV network, as officials from the alphabet soup of political
parties gabbed endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Congress Party leaders, some of whom had been claiming even
Wednesday that theirs would be the single largest party in
Parliament, worked hard to put the best face on their loss. They
pointed out that the party had won at least eight seats in India's
largest state, Uttar Pradesh, where they had been completely wiped
out in the last election, and had won decisively in the states of
Karnataka and Punjab.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing could disguise the dismal national tally. The
Congress Party, which had been disappointed last year when it won
only 140 seats in Parliament, had claimed only 109 by late Thursday
night, with the expectation that it would pick up a few more once
counting was done.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party headquarters here wore a deserted look
Thursday. And party officials privately admitted that they had
taken a terrible drubbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come back with our tail between our legs,'' said one
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``It's a shameful
defeat, the worst performance in Congress' history.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italian-born, politically inexperienced Mrs. Gandhi, whose
mother-in-law and husband both served as prime minister and were
both assassinated, had traveled the nation, but the party's
decrepit to nonexistent grass-roots organization in key north
Indian states was unable to translate popular enthusiasm into
victories.
</P>
<P>
   In her speeches, Mrs. Gandhi warned that the Bharatiya Janata
Party was a threat to secular harmony, but Vajpayee's genial style
and his party's promise to renounce religiously divisive issues
took the zing out of her words.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Mrs. Gandhi's intense shyness and the security
cordon that surrounded her _ she usually swooped down in a
helicopter to give her speech, and swooped away just as quickly _
kept her from developing the kind of organic rapport with people
that her mother-in-law, Indira, was famous for.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was typical. Rather than come out and face the public,
Mrs. Gandhi issued a stilted statement that acknowledged the
disappointing outcome. ``The result calls for introspection, frank
assessment and determined action,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Arun Jaitley, a spokesman for the Bharatiya Janata Party, said
the Congress Party's defeat proved what the Hindu nationalist
leaders had been saying about Mrs. Gandhi all through the campaign:
``The people don't want a foreigner as prime minister.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Gandhi's foreign origins _ she became an Indian citizen
in 1983 _ were not a decisive factor in either of the
constituencies where she sought, and won, election to Parliament.
(She will have to give up one of the seats.)
</P>
<P>
   ``That issue did not cut much ice,'' said Ambika Soni, a
Congress Party official who is close to Mrs. Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
   It was not Mrs. Gandhi's foreign birth, but the Congress Party's
inability to make strong alliances with regional political leaders,
combined with its own poor performance, that led to defeat. Mrs.
Gandhi's argument that only Congress could provide the stability
India needed simply no longer washed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bharatiya Janata Party trumpeted its success in ridding
Indian territory of Pakistan-backed forces, and that military
victory does seem to have lifted Vajpayee's popularity ratings. But
most voters were motivated by issues closer to home, often at the
state level.
</P>
<P>
   The alliances the Congress made with regional parties were
particularly ill-fated. It hooked up with two of India's most
entertaining, headstrong _ and many say corrupt _ politicians. Both
of them did badly. The party headed by Ms. Jayaram, the diva from
the southern state of Tamil Nadu, won a little more than half as
many seats as it had last time.
</P>
<P>
   And Laloo Prasad Yadav, the rustic politician from the cowherds
caste who made a career of poking his finger in the eye of the
upper castes, lost his own seat in Parliament and saw his party's
tally shrink by more than half.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party also paid dearly for the decision of Sharad
Pawar, a powerful leader in the large state of Maharashtra, to
leave the party over the issue of Mrs. Gandhi's foreign origins and
to start his own party. The Congress Party's tally in the state
declined sharply this time.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Bharatiya Janata Party made several successful
new alliances this year, most spectacularly with Chandrababu Naidu,
chief minister of the southern state of Andhra Pradesh and leader
of the regional Telugu Desam Party.
</P>
<P>
   Naidu, an aggressive economic reformer, won a big victory. He
and the BJP together dramatically increased their state tally. The
BJP also allied with the rivals of Ms. Jayaram in Tamil Nadu and of
Yadav in Bihar, and picked up a lot of seats in those states, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, the Hindu nationalists will have to share a
substantial amount of patronage and power with their regional
allies, and they will have to heed the sometimes unruly, insistent
demands of their partners for a say in how the country is governed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it seems likely that this stronger alliance will manage
to survive, if not for its full five-year term, at least for a
longer spell than last time.
</P>
<P>
   In Chandni Chowk, the teeming bazaar in Delhi that dates to
Mughal times, people said they hoped for a period of stable
government, but were skeptical after three elections in the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the coalition be united or will the partners pull the
legs off the chair?'' asked Rakesh Gupta, a cloth merchant who wore
a cell phone dangling from his belt.
</P>
<P>
   Parmanand Arora, a rickshaw driver, said he was looking to the
stars to give India political continuity. ``Even yesterday,'' he
said, ``I read in the newspaper that the astrologers said this
government will continue for five years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
