<HEADER>
A9900 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-TRUMP08-COX     10-07 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trump considers run for presidency with Reform Party backing
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ New York tycoon Donald Trump announced Thursday that
he has formed an exploratory committee to help him decide whether
to seek the Reform Party presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   If he decides to go for it, he knows who he wants as a running
mate: Oprah Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the brash real estate developer is the boldest yet
by an improbable cast _ including former professional wrestler and
Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, conservative Republican Pat Buchanan,
actor Warren Beatty and actress Cybill Shepherd _ who are said to
be considering making a bid for the Reform Party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is like going to the circus,'' University of Virginia
political scientist Larry Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Tolchin, a public policy professor at George Mason
University, said she sees political value in what promises to be a
dogfight for the 2000 Reform Party presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not think any of them can win (the presidency), but they
can be an awful nuisance and raise issues that might not otherwise
be talked about,'' said Tolchin, author of ``The Angry American:
How Voter Rage is Changing the Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think people are taking them seriously,'' she said. ''They
are entertainers, a very important part of society today.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet while potential celebrity candidates promise to pump
excitement into the presidential race, it also threatens greater
instability for the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Since Reform Party founder and Texas billionaire Ross Perot won
19 percent of the 1992 presidential vote, the party's sharp focus
on tax reform, balancing the federal budget and other economic
issues has wavered.
</P>
<P>
   The potential candidates for the Reform Party's 2000 nomination
are talking about potentially divisive social issues, including
health care reform and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Trump, a registered Republican who describes himself as socially
liberal, supports abortion rights. Buchanan, expected later this
month to jump from the Republican Party to seek the Reform Party
nomination, opposes abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a bad thing to shake up a campaign, but it is
probably not a good idea to throw a stick of dynamite,'' Sabato
said. ''Trump will shake it up; Buchanan is the stick of
dynamite.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Reform Party Chairman Anne Merkl said some in the party
worry how Buchanan's conservative social views may disrupt the
party's ''socially moderate'' posture.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to reach common ground'' among conflicting views, said
Merkl, who serves on the Reform Party's national executive
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Trump was scheduled to meet Thursday night with Ventura, the
Reform Party's leading elected official who recently came under
fire for remarks about religion and other controversial topics in a
Playboy interview.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura is trying to find a candidate he can back for the Reform
Party's nomination _ though some think he could run himself.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has the backing of another wing of the party, a loose
alliance with ties to Perot. A Republican presidential candidate in
1996, Buchanan met this week with Russell Verney, Perot's top
adviser and the Reform Party's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Former Connecticut Gov. Lowell Weicker has indicated he is
interested in seeking the nomination of a splinter group, the
American Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am sure we are going to be called the circus party,'' Merkl
said. ''But I think what people are going to have to do is sit back
and see what the candidates' views are.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump said he plans to decide by January or February whether to
seek the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview Thursday taped for broadcast on CNN's
``Larry King Live,'' Trump said Winfrey, the talk-show host, would
be his first choice for running mate. The two have not spoken about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she'd do it, she'd be fantastic,'' Trump said. ``I mean,
she's popular, she's brilliant, she's a wonderful woman.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fashion of a high-profile risk taker whose business and
martial successes and failures have grabbed national attention,
Trump is cocky in assessing his political chances.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing that could interest me is if I could win,'' he
said. ``I'm not talking about the nomination, I'm talking about the
whole megillah.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
