<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9904 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-TEST-BAN-HNS &LR;      10-07 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-BAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS SENATE HAS `MORAL RESPONSIBILITY' TO RATIFY NUCLEAR
TEST BAN TREATY  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Thursday that the Senate has
``a moral responsibility'' to ratify the nuclear test ban treaty as
he broadened his appeal to lawmakers to take more time to study the
issue before putting it to a scheduled vote Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican senators also deserted their leadership to
join with Clinton in urging that the Senate postpone consideration
of the controversial treaty even as lawmakers prepared to begin
debate on it Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, fearing certain defeat if the vote takes place next
week, called on the Senate to hold hearings to allow testimony from
religious leaders and nuclear experts who support the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to have a regular, orderly, substantive process that
gives all the people the necessary time to consider this on the
merit,'' Clinton said before leaving Washington on a three-day
Democratic Party fund-raising trip.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty a vital tool
``to strengthen our security'' and suggested that lawmakers have
``a moral responsibility'' to support its ratification. Passage of
the treaty requires two-thirds support of the Senate, or 67 votes.
But enough Republicans are standing together against it for now to
ensure its defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Future generations won't forgive us if we fail that
responsibility,'' the president said in his appeal to lawmakers to
give the treaty a full airing before holding a vote on it.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Republicans, led by Sens. James Jeffords of Vermont
and Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, joined in Clinton's appeal,
urging their colleagues to stand with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Senate is not ready to vote,'' Specter said on the
Senate floor. He called the treaty ``a very complex issue'' that
most members on both sides of the aisle have not yet taken the time
to analyze, and he warned that its defeat would be both an
embarrassment and a danger for the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to reject it out of hand on what appears to be a
very partisan vote, it could be disastrous for our country,''
Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   Rejection of the treaty would mark the first time ever that
Congress chose to kill an arms control accord that was negotiated
to help curb the proliferation of nuclear weapons. Such a
precedent, Jeffords said, could wipe out all the work by present
and past administrations, and lead to a new arms race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ratification of this treaty will improve our chances of
stopping the spread of nuclear weapons ... We owe it to our
children and grandchildren to add this important brick to the
foundation of international peace,'' said Jeffords.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords brought together a group of religious leaders and
nuclear experts with Clinton at the White House to emphasize the
importance of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The test ban treaty, which would extend the present ban on
atmospheric testing of nuclear weapons to underground testing as
well, was negotiated and signed by 154 nations under U.S.
leadership some three years ago. Since then only 44 of the
participating countries have ratified it. But Jeffords said many of
the others are waiting on the U.S. Senate to ratify the accord
before giving final approval to it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take leadership to lock up the commitment. The world
is looking to the United States and ... to the United States Senate
to show that leadership,'' Jeffords said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords and Specter are among only a handful of Republicans
prepared to cross the aisle and vote with most Democrats in support
of treaty. Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., the ranking Democrat on the
Foreign Relations Committee, said he doubted that even with
Republican support Democrats will be able to muster the 67 votes
needed for passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to kill it, I guess they can do it,'' Biden said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., surprised the
Democrats last week when he scheduled the treaty for a vote after
rejecting the administration's pleas for nearly two years to force
Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C., into
holding hearings on it.
</P>
<P>
   Helms opposes the treaty, as does many other Republicans,
including Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the leading GOP presidential
candidate, because of concerns that the ban on testing cannot be
enforced and wouldn't stop so-called rogue nations such as North
Korea and Iran from developing nuclear arsenals. They also worry
that it would interfere in U.S. efforts to maintain its own nuclear
edge in the world today.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony Thursday before the Senate Armed Service Committee,
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson rebuffed those claims, saying that
the treaty would not interfere with U.S. efforts to maintain and
improve the reliability of the nation's weapons system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters Thursday that even though there is no
sure way to prevent some nations from cheating, the inspections
would be allowed to help verify that testing is not taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Helms and other Republican opponents seem
determined to prevent any effort by the administration to postpone
a vote. Helms had asked Clinton to make his postponement request in
writing and to agree not to revive the issue until after the next
presidential race in return for a delay. But Clinton rejected that
idea.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement Thursday, Clinton cautioned Helms and other
lawmakers that it would be ``terrible mistake'' to play politics
with the test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is huge. This is bigger than party politics. This is
bigger than personal politics,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1947EDT &QL; 
