<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9905 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-AUTO-INSURE-BOS &LR;      10-07 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-AUTO-INSURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AG SAYS MOTORISTS FACE 0.7% INSURANCE HIKE IN 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly announced Thursday
that the state's auto insurers have privately agreed to a 0.7
percent increase in rates for next year, catching the other parties
involved in the rate negotiations off-guard.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which would end up boosting the average annual
premium for Massachusetts's 3.6 million drivers by $6, to $886, was
called ``premature'' by an insurance industry spokesman, while one
company official said it was a blatant publicity grab. The
agreement also was attacked by consumer advocates, who were hoping
for a rate cut of several percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for state Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt, who
officially sets the rates, said she would have no comment. ``She
doesn't have a reaction because there's nothing in-house to look
at,'' he said. ``Nothing's official until the commissioner signs
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Shea, chief of Reilly's public protection bureau, said
word of the settlement agreement was leaking out and he wanted to
make sure consumers had all the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a good deal for consumers,'' he said. ``It's
the same increase as last year.''
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates, backed up by the State Rating Bureau's
recommendation last week that rates be cut 6.1 percent, urged
Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt to reject the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auto rates usually come out around Christmas time, but if the
commissioner accepts this agreement it will be an early $20 million
Christmas present for the insurers,'' said Stephen D'Amato, a
Cambridge attorney and consumer advocate. His comments were echoed
by officials of the Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance company officials declined comment Thursday, although
sources said the industry was divided on whether a settlement was
in its best interests. Industry officials have said the last
several years that rates have been inadequate. Sources said Arbella
Mutual Insurance Co. of Quincy and Liberty Mutual Insurance of
Boston, two of the state's largest insurers, argued against a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is the lone state in the nation where all aspects
of auto insurance rates are set by the state insurance
commissioner. In setting the rates, the commissioner acts much like
a judge, overseeing a case pitting the Automobile Insurers Bureau
of Massachusetts against the attorney general and the State Rating
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   As with any court case, a settlement becomes attractive when the
outcome is uncertain. That seemed to be the case this year.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said the attorney general decided to settle because a minor
increase in rates was appropriate. But he also said this year's
case was uncertain because a Ruthardt ruling on industry profits in
this year's workers' compensation rate decision seemed to undermine
a pro-consumer ruling she made last year on auto insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't sure what we would get in the end with the
commissioner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance industry officials privately said the rate-setting
process is so politicized that a settlement, even if it's not the
optimum solution, is the safe approach.
</P>
<P>
   One official, speaking on condition that his name not be used,
said Ruthardt's contradictory rulings on industry profits were a
case in point. Last year, the official said, the commissioner took
the position that auto insurers are entitled to a lower profit
because investors view insurance stocks as safer investments than
US Treasury bills. In this year's workers' compensation case, which
has a far less public profile, she took the opposite approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fighting against a system that has a political agenda,''
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiated 0.7 percent increase falls roughly midway between
the rate requests of the industry and the State Rating Bureau, an
agency within the state's Insurance Division that advocates for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The industry earlier this year called for a 7.8 percent increase
in rates, while the State Rating Bureau called for a 6.1 percent
rate cut. Sources said the State Rating Bureau expressed a
willingness to accept a 0.9 percent increase earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance industry officials said it was too early to say
whether they will continue their practice of offering discounts off
of the state-set rates to good drivers and members of certain
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said the average good-driver discount declined from 9.2
percent last year to 6 percent this year. He said the attorney
general's office would be monitoring the discounts this year to
make sure good drivers are rewarded, but he acknowledged his office
has no control over the discounting process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
