A9910 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-GE-PCBS-BOS &LR;      10-07 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GE-PCBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GE TO SPEND $750M TO CLEAN UP PCBS IN HOUSATONIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Electric Co. will invest up to $750 million to clean up
PCB contamination caused by its old transformer plant in
Pittsfield, Mass. under a consent decree filed Thursday in US
District Court that ends years of wrangling over the company's duty
to restore the Housatonic River and other polluted areas.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 404-page agreement, signed by federal, state and local
officials as well as GE, the company will begin cleaning up the
half mile of the river immediately downstream from the long-closed
plant next week, with promises to clean up the rest of the river in
the years to come.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Connecticut-based company will complete the
cleanup of the 250-acre plant site, then turn it over to the city
of Pittsfield for redevelopment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This settlement ensures that the environment and public health
of the residents in the Pittsfield area will be protected,'' said
Carol Browner, administrator of the US Environmental Protection
Agency, which agreed not to declare the plant a federal hazardous
waste site in exchange for a negotiated cleanup settlement.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric officials praised the agreement as well,
although they predicted the total cost would be far less than $750
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like all settlements, this one required compromises from all
sides. But it shows that creative and constructive solutions can
emerge when government and business sit down to negotiate in good
faith,'' said Stephen D. Ramsay, GE's vice president for corporate
environmental programs.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, GE also agreed Thursday to spend $1 million on
environmental projects to settle allegations investigated by
Attorney General Thomas Reilly that the company failed to properly
report the PCB contamination in residential areas.
</P>
<P>
   The consent decree, which still must be approved by a federal
judge after a 60-day public comment period, lays out a detailed
blueprint to undo the damage from GE's longtime use of
polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs, as a transformer fluid before
the toxic chemicals were banned in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are not acutely toxic, longterm exposure to PCBs
has been linked to cancer in part because they tend to accumulate
and remain in human and animal tissues.
</P>
<P>
   Many projects described in the decree, such as the cleanup of
Allendale School, which neighbors the plant, are already under way,
and the company had already agreed in principle to carry out the
rest of the project. GE has spent an estimated $100 million on PCB
cleanup not included in the decree.
</P>
<P>
   However, top GE executives said they would not begin work on the
Housatonic River itself _ perhaps the most costly portion of the
job _ until the formal consent decree was filed, spelling out the
company's right to appeal cleanup requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not been willing to go forward with the work in the
river until this was signed,'' said EPA regional administrator John
DeVillars. ``Now, we will have crews deployed in the river next
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Government sources say the final pricetag of the cleanup is
likely to range between $250 million and $750 million, depending
mainly on how much cleanup is needed in the stretch of the
Housatonic River more than two miles downstream from the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Although the downstream section of the river is further from the
plant, federal officials have found PCB levels in ducks more than
200 times the safe level for human consumption. Government sources
said the total cost of removing PCBs more than 2 miles downstream
is likely to range from $100 million to $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Pittsfield may have been the happiest of all, since
they will get a long-awaited cleanup as well as 700,000 to one
million square feet of building space for future development from
the former GE complex.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsfield city council president Thomas E. Hickey, Jr., said
the city will develop ``one of the largest city center business
complexes in the commonwealth,'' finally turning years of disaster
to economic advantage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
