<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY08-COX     10-07 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Affordable child care aim of Bradley proposal
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Calling stay-at-home parents ``a luxury that most
families can't afford,'' Democratic presidential challenger Bill
Bradley on Thursday proposed new government investments in child
care.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley called for spending $2 billion a year in public-private
partnerships that would make child care more affordable to working
parents and improve child care facilities. He also wants to offer
$200 monthly stipends to senior citizens who work with children and
expand the Family and Medical Leave Act to cover 10 million more
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``A prosperity that fails to bolster families is a hollow and
unsustainable one,'' Bradley said in a speech in Peterborough, N.H.
``This proposal is not about big government, but it's about big
ideas and the courage to commit ourselves to finding a common sense
balance between family and work.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's child care speech was scheduled to come on the eve of
a crucial meeting in Los Angeles next week when AFL-CIO leaders are
likely to endorse a Democratic presidential candidate. Bradley
openly appealed to ``working families'' during his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   But his campaign officials on Thursday all but conceded that the
AFL-CIO, which Bradley had been aggressively courting, won't
endorse the former New Jersey senator. ``We think it's going to go
to Gore,'' said Bradley's spokesman, Eric Hauser.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of speeches to different unions and in closed-door
meetings with labor leaders, Bradley had sought to convince the
AFL-CIO leadership to at least withhold any endorsement until after
the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   But AFL-CIO President John Sweeney publicly pushed for Gore's
endorsement, even though some of the larger unions, such as the
Teamsters, wanted to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Having apparently lost the fight, Bradley's camp downplayed the
significance of labor's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder at this point whether it's just a paper
endorsement with as much internal division as there was,'' Hauser
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, however, picked up some good news in New Hampshire on
Thursday. A new statewide poll conducted by WNDS-TV and Franklin
Pierce College found Democrats favoring Bradley over Gore 42
percent to 35 percent, with a margin of error of 6 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   More troubling for the vice president, perhaps, was the poll's
finding that all voters would choose Bradley over Texas Gov. George
W. Bush, the GOP front-runner, 51 percent to 35 percent. Gore and
Bush were in a statistical dead heat, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Another survey for the Boston Herald and WCVB-TV showed Bradley
and Gore in a virtual tie. Four months ago, Gore led Bradley by a
dozen points.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's speech to students and teachers at Contoocoock Valley
High School in New Hampshire, site of the nation's first primary,
was intended to bolster Bradley's standing among rank and file
union members and other suburban voters.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bradley's child care initiative, local counties would
create public-private partnerships composed of state child care
agencies, day care centers, churches and educators. Forty percent
of the federal grants would go to improving existing child care
programs such as Head Start. The rest could be used for teacher
training, building new facilities or subsidizing the cost of child
care to help working parents.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley modeled his program on North Carolina's ``Smart Start''
program. It targets state resources to improving care for children
from birth to age 5, working through locally created public-private
partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a respectable start,'' said Helen Blank, child care
director at the Children's Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign was less impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to the most important issues facing America's
working families, like after-school care, the marriage penalty,
quality child care and real help with college, he falls short, and
even flat,'' said Kiki Moore, Gore's campaign spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding the Family and Medical Leave Act to cover businesses
with 25 or more employees (current law covers businesses with 50 or
more workers) was first proposed by President Clinton in his
January State of the Union speech. Gore also backs the expansion,
and has pledged to offer tax credits to businesses that offer
on-site day care and personal income tax credits for low-income
families.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also proposed spending $400 million a year on community
colleges, targeting the funds toward programs that retrain adults
to fill better paying jobs. Bradley said his $1.2 billion a year
initiative to give stipends to senior citizens who work as tutors
or care givers could attract more than 500,000 ``volunteers'' to
help in their communities when the program was fully funded in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he would fund the 10-year cost of his $2.6 billion
initiatives through non-Social Security surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Bradley said he sought to develop his proposals
recognizing that the ``6:30 dinner hour,'' which he fondly recalled
from his own childhood, doesn't exist in the new, global economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``While government shouldn't be meddling with your family's
dinner hour, it can and should be a catalyst for change,'' Bradley
said in his prepared remarks. ``Americans don't want new government
bureaucracies, but I think they do want government to understand
the enormous pressures and difficulties they face every day trying
to provide care for their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9913 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-KOCH-MAIN-COX     10-07 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOCH-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Witness: Koch may have cheated on measurements
 &HT;    By Fred Cohen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULSA, Okla. _ A witness for Palm Beacher William Koch's side in
his case against his brothers' huge oil company testified Thursday
that Koch Industries employees may have cheated when measuring
producers' tanks as well as the oil in them.
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses testified this week that they ``adjusted'' the
measurements taken to determine how much oil the company bought
from producers. The result, they said, was that the Wichita,
Kan.-based company usually got more oil than it paid for.
</P>
<P>
   Falsifying the measurement of a tank _ saying it is smaller than
it really is _ would have ensured overages for the company for
years, former employee Wayne Ramberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Suing on behalf of the United States of America and Indian
tribes, William Koch has alleged the company led by his brother
Charles systematically defrauded oil producers working leases on
federal and Indian land in the 1980s, costing the government and
Indians millions of dollars in royalties. William Koch stands to
collect as much as a third of any judgment against the company.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is the latest in a series he has brought against family
members and the company founded by his father. William Koch's twin
brother, David, has a home in Palm Beach and is the executive vice
president of Koch Industries. The $35 billion business is the
second-largest privately held company in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company says its error rate in measuring oil was well within
industry standards and that the ``gaugers'' who collected oil for
the company legitimately made adjustments to account for conditions
such as oil clinging to tank walls, excessive sediment on tank
bottoms and ``encrustation'' of tank walls. In cross examination,
the witnesses have agreed that some of the adjustments they made
were necessary for the company to avoid paying for oil it would not
have received.
</P>
<P>
   The company also points to the lack of participation in the case
by the Indians it supposedly cheated, and fact that independent
producers have not complained about its measurement practices.
</P>
<P>
   Ramberg of Billings, Mont., like some others who have testified
during the trial in U.S. District Court here, was fired. He had
worked for the company for 28 years and received a demotion and pay
cut before Koch Industries let him go in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Ramberg said that, as an operations foreman from 1979 to 1988,
he measured the circumference of about half a dozen oil tanks,
using a tape measure divided into hundredths of a foot. He said he
was instructed to ``shrink'' each tank by one to two hundredths of
a foot.
</P>
<P>
   Later he testified that this would result in the purchaser
getting ``more volume.''
</P>
<P>
   Than it pays for? plaintiff's lawyer Jim Stubblefield asked.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ramberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Every time that tank is bought?
</P>
<P>
   Yes.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs introduced as evidence a chart showing the
results of the remeasuring of several customers' tanks by a Koch
Industries employee. In all cases, the remeasurement found the tank
to be either the same size or larger than the first measurement.
</P>
<P>
   Ramberg said Koch Industries often would measure a customer's
tank only once, when it started buying oil from them.
</P>
<P>
   In cross-examination, Koch Industries chief attorney Clyde
Muchmore asked Ramberg if he knew how old the tanks were when they
were remeasured. He did not.
</P>
<P>
   Muchmore also asked Ramberg if he knew what happens to the
circumference of a tank over a period of years if it is repeatedly
emptied or filled. He did not.
</P>
<P>
   Ramberg also testified that, at the September 1988 meeting at
which the company issued the measurement policy and manuals, a Koch
Industries official suggested that he destroy records showing how
much more oil the company had received than it had paid for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerald (Burks, manager of Koch Industries' northern division)
said that if we had anything in the office that pertained to over
and short, it shouldn't be there,'' Ramberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what we had to do,'' he said. ``We didn't need those
reports any more.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ramberg said under questioning that he did not know what
happened to the reports and had no knowledge that they were
destroyed. Koch Industries lawyers later showed him what he said
were copies of the reports.
</P>
<P>
   Ramberg, like the other former ``gaugers'' _ employees who
measured oil Koch Industries bought, said he learned from other
gaugers. He said a September 1988 meeting in Wichita was the first
time the company provided a manual and formal policy on oil
measurement.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs presented a chart, Ramberg said, the company's
overages started dropping precipitously about the time of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The policy introduced at the meeting, Ramberg said, was ``to be
as accurate as possible and avoid losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
