<P>
   Ramberg said Koch Industries often would measure a customer's
tank only once, when it started buying oil from them.
</P>
<P>
   In cross-examination, Koch Industries chief attorney Clyde
Muchmore asked Ramberg if he knew how old the tanks were when they
were remeasured. He did not.
</P>
<P>
   Muchmore also asked Ramberg if he knew what happens to the
circumference of a tank over a period of years if it is repeatedly
emptied or filled. He did not.
</P>
<P>
   Ramberg also testified that, at the September 1988 meeting at
which the company issued the measurement policy and manuals, a Koch
Industries official suggested that he destroy records showing how
much more oil the company had received than it had paid for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerald (Burks, manager of Koch Industries' northern division)
said that if we had anything in the office that pertained to over
and short, it shouldn't be there,'' Ramberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what we had to do,'' he said. ``We didn't need those
reports any more.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ramberg said under questioning that he did not know what
happened to the reports and had no knowledge that they were
destroyed. Koch Industries lawyers later showed him what he said
were copies of the reports.
</P>
<P>
   Ramberg, like the other former ``gaugers'' _ employees who
measured oil Koch Industries bought, said he learned from other
gaugers. He said a September 1988 meeting in Wichita was the first
time the company provided a manual and formal policy on oil
measurement.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs presented a chart, Ramberg said, the company's
overages started dropping precipitously about the time of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The policy introduced at the meeting, Ramberg said, was ``to be
as accurate as possible and avoid losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
