<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9916 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CLINTON-TEAMSTERS-BOS     10-07 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TEAMSTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MEETS WITH TEAMSTER CHIEF HOFFA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With both his wife and his vice president facing
tough races in New York, President Clinton met here Thursday with
representives of a key state voter group: labor.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent 25 minutes chatting with influential union leader
James P. Hoffa, marking the first time since Franklin Roosevelt
that a US president has met with the head of the Teamsters Union.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the evening, Clinton was scheduled to speak before the
National Labor Research Association and to the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee. The latter event featured Dennis
Rivera, the powerful head of the city's biggest health care union.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he and Hoffa ``didn't talk that much about other
politics,'' and mainly discussed trade issues, including ``safety
provisions'' of the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions opposed NAFTA, a Clinton administration initiative,
arguing that US workers would lose their jobs to lower-paid labor
in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO, of which the Teamsters union is a member, is
tentatively scheduled to vote on a presidential candidate
endorsement next Wednesday, although there has been some discussion
about delaying the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still up in the air,'' said AFL-CIO spokeswoman Deborah
Dion.
</P>
<P>
   But Hoffa later said the possible endorsement at the AFL-CIO's
Los Angeles meeting was not discussed. ``Believe it or not it
didn't come up,'' Hoffa said, adding that it was too early to lean
toward a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Vice President Al Gore is meeting with labor union
people. ``I think it would be helpful for him to be more engaged
with the people who are running the large labor unions,'' Hoffa
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had been trying for several months to get a meeting with
Hoffa, who is the son of legendary and controversial Teamsters
leader James R. Hoffa. The elder Hoffa vanished in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   It was only ``scheduling'' that held up a Clinton-Hoffa get
together, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Former Senator Bill Bradley has been edging Gore in many
statewide polls, leading Gore to shake up his campaign and take the
surprising step of challenging Bradley to a series of debates.
</P>
<P>
   Losing a major labor endorsement would be a devastating
development for Gore, who normally would enjoy an institutional
advantage as a sitting vice president in a Democratic White House.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bradley downplayed the endorsement vote and
virtually conceded the win to Gore based on his status as vice
president. The two men _ both of whom supported NAFTA _ do not have
substantially different records on labor issues, said Bradley
spokesman Tony Wyche.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is meeting with labor leaders and Thursday in New
Hampshire unveiled a program for ``working families'' that included
such labor-friendly ideas as an expansion of the Family and Medical
Leave Act, and the creation of a new child care program.
</P>
<P>
   But more important than a major labor endorsement is the
grass-roots support of working people, Wyche said. ``We've been
actively competing for the support of working men and women,''
Wyche said.
</P>
<P>
   Aggressive labor support is also important to the campaiagn of
Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is exploring a possible Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   The active backing of Rivera _ who is both a prominent Latino
leader as well as a major union president _ could be especially
important to Mrs Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton angered many Puerto Rican leaders when she said the
clemency offer to members of the National Front for Liberation, a
Puerto Rican nationalist group, should be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   The labor vote is particularly important in New York State,
where Gore and Bradley are neck-and-neck in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll by the independent Marist Institute for Public
Opinion in Poughkeepsie shows that Bradley and Gore each has about
41 percent of voter support. However, Bradley fares much better
than Gore in a hypothetical matchup against the Republican
front-runner, Texas Governor George W. Bush, said Lee Miringoff,
director of the Marist Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Pitted against Bush, Bradley would win New York State 48 percent
to 38 percent, while Gore would garner only 44 percent of the vote
against Bush's 44 percent, Miringoff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a Democratic primary, it's very hard'' to win without labor
backing, Miringoff said. ``The votes are important, and the
endorsements are very important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
