<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-MUNITIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON SEES SHORTFALL IN PENTAGON MUNITIONS ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. said it now expects the Pentagon to order 20
percent fewer bombs and missiles than previously forecast to
replace munitions used in last spring's Yugoslavia air war.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest of a string of financial warnings by the
Lexington, Mass. defense contractor, Raytheon spokesman Dave Shea
said Thursday the company believes replenishment orders for
Tomahawk and Maverick missiles and other armaments will total about
$800 million, down from an earlier estimate of $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said the change resulted from a slower pace of orders from
the Pentagon. A Pentagon spokesman declined to discuss specific
weapons systems purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's update came as the company prepares to detail its
financial outlook at investment conferences scheduled next week in
New York and Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about Raytheon's revenue and earnings have grown since
September, when the company said it planned to take a charge of up
to $450 million for its third quarter, ending Sept. 30, primarily
beause of disappointing overseas orders. The company warned the
setbacks will lead to further job cuts in Massachusetts and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   News of the charge and cooling expectations about the air war's
benefits to Raytheon have helped drive the company's shares down
nearly 40 percent since July, when they reached a 12-month high of
76 9/16. Raytheon's widely traded Class B shares fell 1 to close at
46 1/16 in New York Stock Exchange trading Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts still keep ``buy'' ratings on the company.
Although Raytheon's fortunes are closely tied to overall defense
spending, analysts said the slipping replenishment schedule wan't a
matter of grave concern.
</P>
<P>
   But several said they are also waiting for the company to
solidify its financial picture. ``The recent weakness reflects
uncertainly about the earnings and cash-flow outlook,'' said Bear,
Stearns analyst Steven Binder, who has a ``neutral'' rating on the
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's latest revision adjusts a June forecast by company
chief executive Daniel Burnham that Raytheon expected about $1
billion worth of extra work over the next year to replace stocks of
the Navy's Tomahawk cruise missile, Air Force glider bombs and
Maverick air-to-ground missiles, and other munitions fired during
NATO's three-month air campaign over Serbia and Kosovo that ended
in June.
</P>
<P>
   In all, US forces used more than 25,000 bombs, of which 8,500
were precision-guided munitions made by Raytheon and other military
contractors. The Pentagon isn't yet saying exactly how many copies
of each weapon type it launched during the campaign, but expects to
spend around $1.3 billion to rebuild US military stockpiles in
Europe to levels meant to last through a 30-day war, according to
Pentagon spokesman Lieutenant Colonel Vic Warzinski.
</P>
<P>
   Some new business for Raytheon is already on the way that should
mitigate some financial concerns. For example, Congress has
allocated $431 million to upgrade older Tomahawk missiles with
advances such as satellite-based targeting systems and lightweight
titanium casings.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also will receive about $40 million for production of a
decoy pod known as the ALE-50, which is towed behind fighter planes
and bombers and sends out electronic signals to jam enemy missile
navigation devices.
</P>
<P>
   But for other weapons systems, there are ``things that are not
necessarily falling into place,'' said Raytheon's Shea, a spokesman
for Raytheon Systems Co., a Virginia-based military-contracting
unit.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Raytheon doesn't expect as many orders as it once
did for replacements for its Paveway laser-guided bombs or for
missiles such as the Maverick series. These missiles, along with
the Tomahawk, are built at Raytheon plants in Tucson, Ariz., using
some circuit cards and other components produced in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon still expects to receive a large chunk of $1.1 billion
that will be allocated among several defense contractors under a
federal arms replenishment bill, according to Shea.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Tomahawk and ALE-50 work, ``We believe we are
well-positioned to receive several hundred million in additional
revenue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Warzinski, the Pentagon spokesman, said he couldn't discuss
upcoming orders of individual weapons systems or Raytheon's
outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette analyst Joe Nadol said Raytheon
previously told him and other analysts it was backing away from the
$1 billion total for arms replenishment in connection with the NATO
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Nadol said he is more anxious to hear additional details about
the status of the company's overseas projects such as missile
defense work for Taiwan, and a European military radar project.
``That's the crux of the issue, in terms of their revenue
shortfall,'' Nadol said.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon hasn't quantified the additional impact that the lower
estimate for replenishment orders might have on third-quarter
earnings, scheduled to be released Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Nadol said he estimates Raytheon earned about 89 cents a share
in the third quarter, but added: ``I don't feel fully confident in
that (estimate), because they haven't given explicit guidance''
lately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0289 </DOCNO>
