u f BC-NY-CHASE-JOBS-575&AMP;ADD     10-07 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHASE-JOBS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASE TO MOVE 3,500 JOBS OUT OF NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Texas, Fla.)  (th) 
 By LESLIE EATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chase Manhattan Corp., the largest corporate employer
in New York City, is moving 10 percent of its jobs _ 3,500
positions _ to Florida, Texas and Massachusetts, the company told
its workers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   City officials and corporate consultants said they could not
remember a bigger relocation by a single company. But in the late
1980s, many Wall Street firms began moving their ``back office''
record-keeping and data processing jobs to New Jersey and Florida,
a trend that Chase is now catching up with.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning next year, Chase will move two entire back-office
units, from entry-level positions to technology workers to senior
managers, said Ken Herz, a spokesman for the company. One of the
businesses transfers money for companies; the other involves
tracking and processing stock and bond trades.
</P>
<P>
   By relocating its workers, the bank will cut its costs
significantly, Herz said, though he would not say how much money it
expected to save. Salaries, real estate costs, taxes,
telecommunications charges and utilities costs are all lower in
Tampa, Fla., and Dallas, where most of the jobs are to be
relocated.
</P>
<P>
   But the savings are so big that Chase did not even approach the
city for financial or logistical help to try to keep the jobs in
New York, Herz said. ``There was no way the city could come up with
enough money,'' he added. ``These are very significant savings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always sorry to see any jobs go,'' said Deputy Mayor
Randy Levine. But, he said, Chase has promised to keep its
headquarters and core business in the city and will be expanding
its other operations. The company, which Levine said was looking
for one million square feet, has been searching unsuccessfully for
space in which to expand.
</P>
<P>
   Technological advances have prompted banks to slash the number
of employees in the city over the last decade, as have mergers;
Chase gobbled up Chemical Bank and Manufacturers Hanover, among
others. Employment at depository institutions has fallen from
almost 175,000 in 1988 to about 110,000 today, according to the
state's Department of Labor.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the jobs that have disappeared were held by middle-class
people earning middle-income salaries, leading some economists and
government officials to worry that New York is becoming
increasingly a city of the very rich and very poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant worry, that all the middle-class finance jobs
are going, that the banks can't afford to keep them here,'' said
one former city official.
</P>
<P>
   The city government has offered financial incentives to large
companies that threatened to leave the city; Chase received $235
million in 1988, when it agreed to move many back-office employees
to Brooklyn, rather than New Jersey. It now has about 6,000
employees at Brooklyn's Metrotech Center office complex, which is
full.
</P>
<P>
   Some Metrotech jobs are among those that are being moved, Herz
said, adding that Chase planned to relocate other business units to
Metrotech to keep it full.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the employees whose jobs are being moved work at the tip
of Manhattan, at 4 New York Plaza and 55 Water St. While Chase said
it would offer to relocate many of those workers, several
interviewed Thursday said they were unlikely to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess if you're single or live with your parents, you could
pack up and move, but I can't,'' one middle-aged employee said.
``We constantly get letters from the chairman saying you're doing a
great job; now, we really feel betrayed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The city's Metrotech deal with Chase particularly rankled,
another employee said. ``It's a sorry state,'' he complained.
``Here's a major corporation that receives tax abatements from the
city, and part of that deal is to bring jobs to the city. Slowly
but surely, they move operations.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason that employees may be reluctant to relocate is that
their chances of finding work in New York City are unusually good,
corporate consultants said. The unemployment rate in the city is
6.9 percent, down from roughly 10 percent in early 1997, and many
companies are adding new jobs at a record pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people will find jobs in a couple of months,
definitely,'' said Dennis J. Donovan, a partner in the
Wadley-Donovan Group, which advises companies on relocations.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case in the late 1980s, when Merrill Lynch
moved 2,500 back-office jobs to Jersey City. Or, in the mid-1990s,
when several big financial firms threatened to move to Stamford,
Conn., and Swiss Bank actually did, taking 1,300 jobs with it.
Citigroup, which employs about 25,000 people in the city, has for
years had its stock custodial business in Tampa, a Citigroup
spokesman, Jack Morris, said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies have discovered that they can have administrative
tasks performed almost anywhere, even overseas, said Daniel
Malachuck, a partner at Arthur Andersen who specializes in business
location services.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, companies and their employees have
become far more optimistic about staying in New York City,
Malachuck said, and less inclined to move to another part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what the post-Rudy mind-set will be, but people
feel better about the city and their situation,'' he said. ``And
people have been to some of those other places.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
