<SLUG> BC-NY-GUILIANI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI TESTED BY FIRST AMENDMENT STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Say what you will about the mayor's taste in art, but
there's no doubting his relish for a good First Amendment fight.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the courtroom clash between Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
and the Brooklyn Museum of Art gets under way Friday, the mayor's
legal troops find themselves confronting an all too familiar
battlefield on which they have spilled much blood and lost nearly
every contest.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in 1994, Giuliani or his aides have been
sued in 21 cases involving claims of First Amendment rights by
adversaries that include taxi drivers, Latino police officers,
winter solstice worshipers, black protest marchers, Times Square
preachers, and magazine publishers.
</P>
<P>
   For all these fights, he has emerged victorious just once. He
lost or surrendered 15 times, with four cases still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Some see his persistence as political, others see it as a
character trait _ whether admirable or disturbing _ while others
are simply puzzled. Whatever the view, many agree the mayor has
long displayed a pattern when it comes to dealing with people whose
views he does not like.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the volume of the cases and the frequency of his defeats
_ both of which are unprecedented in New York _ have done little
apparent damage to his political standing, though it seems this
case might inflict a bit of harm.
</P>
<P>
   A poll, released Thursday by the Marist College Institute for
Public Opinion, shows a majority _ not just in liberal New York
City but across more conservative regions of the entire state _
disagrees with the mayor's stance on this controversy, and that
many have lowered their opinion of him because of it.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute, to be heard in federal court Friday, involves the
Brooklyn Museum of Art's ``Sensation'' exhibit, which opened to
record crowds last weekend and features several provocative works _
most notoriously, a painting of an African Virgin Mary decorated
with elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Giuliani, calling the painting ``disgusting'' and
``anti-Catholic,'' threatened to cut off city subsidies to the
museum if the exhibit were not cancelled. The museum's directors
refused to cave, and filed a federal lawsuit demanding a return of
the subsidy, citing the first amendment's protection of free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's lawyers have argued that the first amendment does
not protect public subsidies of speech, and that, as the museum
resides in a city-owned building, the mayor was entitled to act as
he did.
</P>
<P>
   Several constitutional specialists, including Lawrence Tribe of
Harvard University Law School, contend every applicable US Supreme
Court ruling supports the museum's position.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics see this case as being less about art (which
Giuliani has never fussed over before) or the upcoming Senate race
(for which he needs to solidify the Republican Party's conservative
base), than about Giuliani's sheer discomfort with protest.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, the longtime director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, filed his share of lawsuits against two previous
mayors _ Democrats David Dinkins and Edward Koch _ but he sees
Giuliani's regime as a departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of cases against him and the percentage of cases
he's lost are substantially higher than anything before,'' Siegel
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 cases that the mayor has lost during his six years in
office involved efforts to block cab drivers from forming a
procession to protest new taxi regulations, to forbid city
officials from speaking publicly about non-confidential matters, to
prevent two ``Million Youth March'' rallies, to prevent Socialist
candidates from collecting petition-signatures in city parks, to
prevent Winter Solstice celebrants from gathering on a city beach,
and to forbid New York Magazine from placing ads satirizing the
mayor on city buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few cases in the Koch and Dinkins years,'' Siegel
went on, ``but the question was where will they march, for how long
will they speak _ the parameters of the protest. In the Giuliani
years, it's a question of whether there will be a protest. It's
radically different.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederick A. O. Schwarz, a prominent Manhattan attorney, served
as Corporation Counsel _ the city's principal lawyer _ during the
Koch years. A few years ago, he was an ally of Giuliani's in his
one first-amendment victory, involving an attempt by the owners of
``adult-entertainment'' shops to quash a zoning regulation that
evicted them from Times Square and other areas of the city. Schwarz
represented the Times Square Business Improvement District in that
case, and made most of the oral arguments in several courts.
</P>
<P>
   However, on the museum case and many others, Schwarz thinks
Giuliani has gone too far. ``His attitude,'' Schwarz said, ``seems
to be: Do something that's ruthless and possibly popular in the
short term, without any regard that it's inconsistent with his
obligation to uphold the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   O. Peter Sherwood, corporation counsel under Dinkins, said, ``I
can't remember any case in which matters that (Dinkins) found
personally offensive resulted in the use of the corporate counsel
to prosecute them.''
</P>
<P>
   Press aides for Giuliani and Michael Hess, the current
corporation counsel, did not return calls asking for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the Marist poll, just 33 percent agreed with Giuliani's move
to cut off museum funds, while 59 percent opposed it. Even in
upstate New York, 54 percent disagreed with the move. Statewide, 30
percent said their opinion of the mayor declined because of his
position, while 21 percent said it rose. Those having an
``unfavorable'' view of Giuliani climbed to 39 percent _ from 30
percent three weeks ago _ matching the negative ratings of his
likely opponent in the Senate race, First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
