<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE'S A CRITIC
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a New York Review of Books essay praising  &UR; Frank Gehry &LR; ,
critic  &UR; Martin Filler &LR;  calls the architect's Guggenheim Museum in
Bilbao a masterwork. Filler, a major Gehry fan, writes that he &LR;  the
architect was considered and rejected for the San Francisco Museum
of Modern Art design (a job that went to  &UR; Mario Botta &LR; ) as well as
for the Museum of Contemporary Art and the Getty Center in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The insecure boards of directors of those museums,'' writes
Filler, ``fearful of seeming unsophisticated if they picked a
Californian, passed over the genius in their own backyard and
thereby missed the architectural opportunity of a lifetime that was
to be realized so stunningly at Bilbao. This was provincialism at
its worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Boards of other local museums seem to be similarly attracted to
architects from abroad. Italian  &UR; Gae Aulenti &LR;  has designed the new
Asian Art Museum; Swiss  &UR; Pierre de Meuron &LR;  is designing the new de
Young.
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Alain Gayot &LR; , publisher of a series of city restaurant
guides, says that when he combines a meal and an interview with a
prospective critic, the candidate gets an automatic turn-down for
several offenses. As listed in the Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
   Mishandling the dinner fork, ordering the same meal as Gayot,
``devouring the breadbasket before the entree is served,'' ordering
meat well done, and ordering Perrier, which the publisher thinks
``is only appropriate as an aperitif before dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A MAGOWAN ON HIS FAMILY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Robin Magowan &LR; , son of the late Safeway CEO  &UR; Robert Magowan &LR; ,
grandson of  &UR; Charles Merrill &LR;  of Merrill Lynch, etc., and brother
of San Francisco Giants owner  &UR; Peter Magowan &LR; , is the author of the
forthcoming ``Memoirs of a Minotaur'' (Story Line; $16.95
paperback).
</P>
<P>
   Robin, who grew up among the privileged classes in South
Hampton, went to a Swiss boarding school and Harvard, is a writer,
poet and professor of English literature. His book describes his
childhood, coming of age and lurid adventures with drugs and sex,
climaxing in an affair with  &UR; Nancy Ling Perry &LR; , one of the founders
of the Symbionese Liberation Army (which kidnapped  &UR; Patty Hearst &LR; ).
Perry was killed in the group's battle with police in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Magowan seems to despise his father, whom he describes as
tyrannical, bigoted and power-mad. ``One of my brothers had in his
college rooms, under the obligatory Mao poster of a rice field with
hoeing peasants, a blown-up photo of Father at his farewell
Caterpillar board meeting.'' Safeway was ``the left's most hated
company,'' writes Magowan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cesar Chavez  &LR; and grape workers had boycotted the chain on and
off for 15 years, he writes. But Chavez ``hadn't reckoned on my
father, who was not about to let himself be trampled by a bunch of
itinerant grapepickers. What would be next, Father asked, Polish
hams, Cuban cigars?''
</P>
<P>
   Magowan has nothing but praise for Peter, who began running
Safeway at 37, Robin writes, sharing with his father ``the
loneliness of having `no one I can talk things over with, no
friend.' ... When it became a choice of directing the Giants
baseball team he had helped save for San Francisco or continuing
with Safeway, Peter chose his boyhood idols.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Jon Rhine  &LR; writes in salon.com that rocker  &UR; Chris Isaak &LR; , who
lives in the Sunset District, is being stalked. Isaak's house was
set on fire on September 10; investigators determined that the
blaze was not an accident.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; George Hamilton &LR; , 60, told the New York Daily News that
 &UR; Danielle Steel &LR; , 52, is ``a very, very special and kind person, and
I really like her a lot,'' but denied a report that they'd been
seen smooching. He said that would be rude in public.
</P>
<P>
   _ 49ers fans may have been aghast, but  &UR; Kim Corbin &LR; , skipping
proponent, founder of www.iskip.com and planner of the Sunday Skip
in the Park on October 24, was delighted by Wednesday's headline on
a sports column: ``Young Should Skip This and Every Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a big fan of the handshake. I think it's barbaric and
especially in our times, and especially with medical reports. I
mean they have medical reports all the time. Shaking hands, you
catch colds, you catch the flu, you catch this, you catch all sorts
of things. Who knows what you don't catch.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Donald Trump on ``Dateline NBC.''
</P>
