<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOWITZKI READY FOR ROUND 2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ If it had been up to Dirk Nowitzki, he would have eased
into his rookie season with the excitement of a snail crawling down
a sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, fireworks exploded and trumpets blared because
Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson described Nowitzki as a
rookie-of-the-year candidate who could hit the NBA ground running.
</P>
<P>
   However, as many foreign players do during their NBA
indoctrination, Nowitzki looked lost and bewildered at times last
season. He might have been Nelson's hand-picked starter at small
forward for the Mavericks, but Nowitzki felt he was in no way ready
for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I was kind of thrown into the cold water, but coach
wanted to give me a chance, and I really respect that,'' Nowitzki
said yesterday. ``But maybe I wasn't really ready for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really play very good in the training camp. Maybe he
just gave it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson believes Nowitzki learned from a rookie campaign that saw
him average 8.2 points and 3.4 rebounds, and shoot 40.5 percent
from the field. Plus, the 7-footer from Germany played well during
the Mavericks' summer-league games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's much more comfortable this year than he was last year,''
Nelson said. ``You can tell he's like a veteran, although he's
still awful young. He knows what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson plans to play Nowitzki at small forward and power
forward, maybe a little at center. He also defended selecting
Nowitzki in last year's draft over an established player such as
Paul Pierce, who wound up starring with the Boston Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it because of size more than anything,'' Nelson said.
``We had 6-51/2, 6-6 guys, and we didn't have 7-footers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you think it was a good move or bad move, you don't
find 7-footers with his skills anywhere. And he's still 21, and
he's loaded with skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki is working to improve his defense and rebounding
skills, two of his primary weaknesses last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that he's ever going to be a stopper, but
neither are a lot of other guys out there,'' Nelson said. ``As long
as he tries defensively, that's all we can ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team concept kind of carries over. And we'll protect him
as best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to protect Nowitzki is to play him against second-line
players. Indeed, he said he doesn't mind playing second-fiddle to
Cedric Ceballos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ced is playing very well right now, so if he starts I don't
have a problem with that,'' Nowitzki said. ``He's making his shots,
and he's a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki isnursing a swollen thumb and index finger on his right
shooting hand. But nothing was more bruising than the three games
he did not play last season because of a coach's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was kind of frustrating, because in Germany there never
was a game where I didn't play at all,'' Nowitzki said. ``But at
those times last year, I didn't play very good in practice, and I
didn't play very good in the games that I got in, so I have to
respect that and just work hard in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, the NBA was as foreign to Nowitzki as he was to
the NBA. He didn't know what to expect when he arrived in Dallas,
except that Nelson had already super-hyped him to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the game at all,'' Nowitzki said. ``I didn't
know a single thing, like illegal defense. I'd never heard of that.
We played zone defenses in Germany, like in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I had to learn that in one week, and I didn't really pick
everything up. But now I know everything, so I'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson and the Mavericks are counting on it. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
