<HEADER>
A9941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-R-CONGRESS-CRUISE-SHI     10-07 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CONGRESS-CRUISE-SHIPS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROPICALE CREW TO BE EVALUATED ON ENGLISH FLUENCY DURING FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to correct category code and add art note)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Coast Guard is investigating whether crew
members aboard the Tropicale cruise ship spoke enough English to
assist passengers when a fire broke out on the ship in the Gulf of
Mexico last month.
</P>
<P>
   Rear Adm. Robert C. North, assistant Coast Guard commandant for
marine safety, told a congressional hearing Thursday that the
agency will ask 300 passengers aboard the Tropicale, owned by
Carnival Cruise Lines, to evaluate the performance of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   The ship, with 1,700 passengers and crew members, was adrift in
the gulf for almost two days after fire disabled the engines on
Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers, who had spent 11 hours at emergency stations,
complained afterward that some crew members did not speak English
well enough to provide safety instructions.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Hall, chairman of the National Transportation Safety
Board, testified that questions about the performance of crew
members have also been raised during an investigation of a fire
aboard another Carnival ship, the Ecstasy, in July 1998 off Miami
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's congressional hearing was called in response to
concerns about industry regulation after reports about illegal
dumping by cruise ships, sexual assaults on board ships and the two
fires.
</P>
<P>
   North and Hall gave the cruise industry generally high marks for
safety during testimony Thursday before the House Transportation
and Infrastructure Subcommittee on the Coast Guard and Maritime
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   But worries over the potential losses in a fire at sea have
grown as the size of cruise ships has mushroomed to 3,000
passengers and 1,500 or more crew members. Hall said the Tropicale
and Ecstasy fires should be wake up calls that the industry must do
more in terms of training and fire prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has adopted many fire-safety measures, including
sprinkler systems, smoke detectors, remote operation of fire doors
and improved detection systems. But the safety board said the smoke
detectors on cruise ships are not as effective because they sound
an alarm at a central location, rather than in passenger and crew
accommodations where the smoke is detected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediate warning of the presence of smoke is absolutely
essential to escape a fire,'' Hall testified.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia A. Colenda, president of the International Council of
Cruise Lines, an industry trade group, said crew members were
quickly sent to check on alarms that register at the central
location. She said alarms do not sound in cabins because they are
too often set off by accident, through cigarette smoking or even
hair spray.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore., said he did not understand why
ships could not use the same alarms that are in hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't tell me that smoke detectors wouldn't work in
cabins, too,'' DeFazio said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government cannot order installation of the smoke
detectors because the cruise ships serving U.S. ports fly foreign
flags and are regulated by the countries where they are flagged and
the International Maritime Organization. The maritime organization
was expected to debate the necessity of local-sounding alarms at
some point, but the resistance of the cruise companies would make
it difficult to mandate them.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard regularly inspects foreign-flagged ships that
sail in and out of U.S. ports, including monitoring fire drills.
But the government's jurisdiction over the industry is limited. For
instance, the safety board cannot investigate accidents that occur
outside U.S. territorial waters and crew qualifications are often
determined by unmonitored schools in foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   DeFazio said he had seen evidence that training schools in
countries like the Philippines are shams that sell the
certifications necessary for getting a job on a cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives me zero confidence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Colenda countered that the cruise lines inspect the
schools and that the Coast Guard observes crew performance during
on-board inspections. She said the trade association also operates
two schools in Florida to train crewmembers in firefighting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
