<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS FACE MUST-WIN GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH AND MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Facing the prospect of falling two games
behind Oklahoma in the Big 12 South Division standings makes
tomorrow's meeting ``even bigger than normal'' for Texas coaches
and players, said Longhorns defensive tackle Casey Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Texas (4-2, 1-1) trails Oklahoma (3-1, 1-0) by one-half game in
the division standings after last week's 35-17 loss to Kansas
State. The 23rd-ranked Longhorns also are a half-game behind Texas
Tech (2-2, 1-0), the only other South Division team without a
conference loss.
</P>
<P>
   A loss to Oklahoma would severely damage Texas' chances for
advancing to the Big 12 title game. But a victory, coupled with an
Oklahoma State triumph against Texas Tech tomorrow night, would put
the Longhorns atop the South Division standings. That makes this
Red River Shootout more pivotal than just another battle for
bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing two games in the conference race is not very good for
any team,'' Hampton said. ``There are a lot of good teams in the
South, and we need this victory a lot. That makes this game even
bigger than normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas coach Mack Brown agreed that more is riding on this game
than in 1998, when the Longhorns pounded the Sooners, 34-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectations are higher than they were last year at this
time,'' Brown said. ``We wanted to be a Top 10 football team today,
and we're not. We want to win the Big 12 South. We need to beat the
other people in the South to make that happen.'' \Nsubheds:Self
corrections A focus during Texas' workouts this week is reducing
penalties. The Longhorns were flagged eight times for 48 yards
against Kansas State, with four of them in crucial situations. The
offense had three false starts on third down. An offside penalty
wiped out a blocked punt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid stuff like that, there's no excuse for that,'' wide
receiver Ryan Nunez said.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Anthony Hicks agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there is a sense of urgency that we need to correct
our problems,'' Hicks said. ``We need to check that our i's are
dotted and that our t's are crossed in order to make sure it's a
good game.'' \Nsubheds:Secondary stress test Texas defensive backs,
who have shuffled three positions because of injuries since the
season opener, are wary of facing an Oklahoma team that averages
341.8 passing yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns lost their top two free safeties, Quentin Jammer
and Chris Butcher, to season-ending injuries Aug. 28 against North
Carolina State. Cornerback Joe Walker has been limited in recent
weeks with a sprained ankle and might not play against Oklahoma.
Yet Texas ranks sixth nationally in pass defense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't know, with all the personnel changes, if we feel
we can trust each other back there,'' cornerback Ahmad Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be an eye opener for us,'' free safety Lee
Jackson said. \Nsubheds:Home at last After struggling with his
football identity for three years, Oklahoma senior Brandon Daniels
is smiling, for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy. Everything's positive here,'' Daniels said. ``This
offense allows me to do a lot of different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels has settled in as the Sooners' slotback in coordinator
Mike Leach's new offense after various roles the past three seasons
as a receiver, a defensive back and a quarterback in an option
scheme under former coach John Blake.
</P>
<P>
   He ranks fourth in the Big 12 in receptions (13), sixth in
receiving yards per game (62) and is second nationally with a
40.83-yard kickoff return average following last week's 229-yard
performance against Notre Dame. He scored on an 89-yard return and
set up touchdowns with returns of 68 and 43 yards. He also caught
two passes for 29 yards, including a 15-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the best game I've had in four years,'' Daniels said.
``But I'd trade all of it if we had won.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
