<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SOONERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OU KEEPING QUIET ABOUT ITS DEFENSIVE PLANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ Considering the way Kansas State's aggressive
defensive attack hampered Texas quarterback Major Applewhite last
week, the popular assumption is that the word ``blitz'' dominated
Oklahoma's defensive meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it did. Then again, maybe it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to bring 'em and we'll drop off,'' Sooners
weakside linebacker Rocky Calmus said of his team's approach for
Texas. ``We're going to act like we're going to bring 'em ... keep
them guessing on every single play. Not just do one thing and let
them know what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma defensive coordinator Mike Stoops, who coordinated
K-State's defense last season, is mindful of the role the Wildcats'
blitz package played against Texas in helping force five sacks,
three interceptions and three fumble recoveries in the 35-17
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``K-State blitzed the hell out of them, that's pretty obvious,''
Stoops said. ``But I'm sure Texas will be well-prepared \Rfor the
blitz\S this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoops said not to expect the Sooners to blitz all afternoon in
an effort to harass Applewhite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas State's style is a little more aggressive than how we
play,'' he said. ``We're a little more conservative, a little more
straight-forward. We play a little more zone \Rpass\S coverage.
What we've got to do is be able to stop the run.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners are a little sensitive about their effort in run
defense against Notre Dame last week. The Irish gained 284 yards
rushing. Tailback Tony Fisher ran for 140 yards and quarterback
Jarious Jackson added 107, most on scrambles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a great chance to win if we stop the run against
Texas,'' Stoops said.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, Calmus said, is that Applewhite is no Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fact that Major isn't really a running threat,''
Calmus said. ``He's a little smaller and a little slower \Rthan the
235-pound Jackson\S, so we can concentrate on our pass drops _ but
the first thing is to stop the run. \RTexas\S has been having a
little trouble with the run, and I know they're going to come out
and try to establish it early. We need to make them start
throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle linebacker Torrance Marshall, a transfer who along with
Calmus and safety Rodney Rideau are the heart of OU's defense,
cautions that too much concentration on the Longhorns' running game
can be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like play-action,'' he pointed out. ``So we need to
prepare for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoops said the bottom line is that the Sooners need to play
better tomorrow than they did last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a chance against Texas if we play better defense,''
Stoops said. ``The sad part of it is, we had a chance \Ragainst
Notre Dame\S and played terrible. Couldn't get off the field and
still had a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We really only played about 35 minutes,'' Calmus said. ``We've
got to finish against Texas.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
