<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-HEALTH-CARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES PROTECTIONS FOR HMO CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Breaking a decade-long stalemate, the House
approved Thursday the most sweeping plan to expand federal
protections for medical consumers since the advent of health
maintenance organizations a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   In defying Republican leaders and passing the overhaul measure,
275-151, the House endorsed granting 161 million members of the
nation's health plans the right for the first time to sue their
providers for deaths and injuries resulting from poor care or
denied treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, a major blow to the insurance industry, will become
the centerpiece of negotiations as House, Senate and White House
representatives craft a final package of patient protections. A
renegade bloc of 68 Republicans rebuffed their leaders and joined
the nearly united Democratic minority to pass the bill.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, traveling in New York, echoed groups
representing doctors and patients as he hailed the measure's
passage and urged GOP leaders in Congress not to derail the
proposed overhaul during the final negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that America is no longer willing to allow unfeeling
practices of some health plans to add to the pain of injury or
disease,'' Clinton said. ``It proves that America is committed to
putting patients first.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the measure's future remains highly uncertain, as House
Republican leaders indicated they will continue to try to block the
provision they consider most onerous: the right to sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have created a system that is going to result in the
extortion of dollars from every employer in this country,'' said
Representative Tom A. Coburn, an Oklahoma Republican who sponsored
an alternative measure that GOP leaders hoped would prevail over
the more comprehensive overhaul. The alternative plan was rejected,
238-193.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate poses another obstacle to the House measure because
the Senate passed a weaker version of a patients' rights bill that
would cover only about 48 million consumers who are not enrolled in
HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet key Senate backers of the House version, citing the 68
Republicans who supported the measure, predicted they would
overcome resistance and keep the legislation largely intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a well-deserved defeat for the Republican extremists
in the House and their attempt to protect the profits of HMOs at
the expense of the patients' health,'' said Senator Edward M.
Kennedy. ``I'm convinced we will get a strong bill out of the
conference. A weak bill won't pass the House, and the president
won't sign one.''
</P>
<P>
   The House measure, addressing some of the most common complaints
aired by consumers in managed care programs, would guarantee access
to reasonable emergency care, permit patients to see pediatricians
and obstetricians without prior approval from their primary
doctors, and require routine care associated with clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Patients who are denied care or receive poor care could sue in
state courts after exhausting appeals in an independent review
process. Despite vehement objections from business and insurance
interests, there would be no limit on the amount of damages an
individual could receive.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, taking up the business leaders'
cause, appealed for less stringent regulations. ``We do not force
people to sue their way to better health care,'' Hastert said on
the House floor. ``We do not provide windfalls for the trial
lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   But each of three alternative measures that would have killed
the broader bill was defeated, as wary Republicans deserted Hastert
on an issue that could have potentially potent repercussions in
next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Horror stories abounded in the final hours of debate, as
supporters of the broadest overhaul measure recounted episodes in
which patients had died or suffered severe injuries because of
alleged abuses by health plans.
</P>
<P>
   In a striking scene, 7-year-old James Adams of Atlanta, who lost
his arms and legs to gangrene after his health plan required his
parents to drive him 70 miles to an emergency room with a high
fever, sat in the front row of the House chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had a finger and you pricked it, it would bleed,'' said
Representative Greg Ganske, a physician and Iowa Republican who
helped pressure GOP leaders to permit a vote on the overhaul bill.
``He's not an anecdote.''
</P>
<P>
   Every New England Democrat voted for the measure. The only
Republican from the region to support it was Representative
Christopher Shays of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The prime Republican sponsor of the measure, Representative
Charlie Norwood of Georgia, a physician and Vietnam veteran,
compared his long struggle against GOP leaders to pass the bill to
one of the toughest battles of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Moments before the final vote, Norwood said on the House floor,
``It's all been said and it's all been done, and what we need to do
now is mount the top of Hamburger Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Kicking off a news conference afterward, Norwood said, ``Ladies
and gentleman, we are now on top of Hamburger Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   But he predicted the Republican leaders would continue to try to
stymie him during the final negotiations. ``It may be a bloody war
in conference to try to get this thing right,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2027EDT &QL; 
