<HEADLINE>
HALL OF FAME IS FIRST HEADLINER AT RETAMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost every successful horse track has an event of some renown.
Churchill Downs has the Kentucky Derby. Oaklawn Park takes a full
week to present its Racing Festival of the South.
</P>
<P>
   Even a place like Penn National gets into the action. The
quality of the horses doesn't add up to much there, so the track's
front office lets the spotlight shine on the player with the annual
World Series of Handicapping.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie to find
its headliner event. Not to take anything away from either the
Texas Mile/Lone Star Park Derby or Lone Star Millions Day, but the
All-Star Jockey Championship became the track's top event
immediately upon the track's grand opening three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Success hasn't come as quickly at Sam Houston Race Park, but
that track has done an excellent job in building Texas Champions
Day into a fun day of competitive, memorable racing.
</P>
<P>
   Now it looks as if Retama Park near San Antonio has come up with
something. The new Texas Horse Racing Hall of Fame is the event
where the track can hang its hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we don't want to play this thing as something for Retama
Park,'' said Retama chairman Joe Straus Jr. ``It so happens that
it's located at Retama Park, but we want everyone to have a say in
how this thing is going to be run.''
</P>
<P>
   Among anyone who sits in the front offices at any of the Texas
racetracks, no one is as mindful of Texas' spot in racing history
as Straus or his brother David. As he sits in his office, Joe
Straus Jr. can look at a picture of his grandfather D.J. Straus,
who was a director of the horse racing meet at the San Antonio
International Fair Association in 1908.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in a picture of the winner's circle, in front of the
grandstand full of people,'' Straus said.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, the Hall of Fame will pack the stands. The first
induction class will be honored in a ceremony tonight at Retama.
</P>
<P>
   There possibly isn't a stronger inaugural class of inductees,
respectful of both the thoroughbred and quarter horse industries.
There's 1946 Triple Crown winner Assault, leading quarter-horse
sire Dash For Cash, legendary race mare Pan Zareta, the late Robert
Kleberg Jr. of the King Ranch, the late B.F. Phillips Jr., who
spearheaded the effort to bring racing back to Texas, and all-time
leading jockey Bill Shoemaker.
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with the proceedings Saturday at Retama, there
will be three races, each with purses exceeding $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   So the foundation has been set. There are two ways to make this
thing grow.
</P>
<P>
   One could take a while _ have an actual Hall-of-Fame building
constructed on the grounds at Retama. Straus said there's $100,000
in the bank for that so far, but much more is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea would be to have a museum of not only the recipients
\Rof the Hall of Fame induction\S, but also memorabilia and
pictures and something you could bring the kids to so you could get
them interested in horse racing,'' Straus said.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one step that could be taken immediately. A kiosk
could be assembled and moved between the tracks to showcase this
state's racing history. Ballots for racing fans to nominate the
next class of inductees could be a part of the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   As Straus says, that would allow ``everyone to have a say.''
PAN ZARETA STATUE
</P>
<P>
   Pan Zareta, who raced 151 times from 1912 to 1917, is a member
of the National Horse Racing Hall of Fame and will be inducted into
the new Texas Horse Racing Hall of Fame tonight at Retama Park. But
there's a move to have her honored near her birthplace in
Sweetwater.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetwater native Mel Harp is hoping to raise enough funds to
have a statue erected in that town. He can be reached by calling
(806) 745-8005 or by e-mail at LubbBuff &LR; aol.com
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's one of the best racehorses ever _ and that's agreed
upon _ and there's nothing in Sweetwater to honor her,'' Harp said.
</P>
<P>
   Harp said Robert Taylor has agreed to build the statue. Taylor
also sculpted the statue of the bear and the bull that stands in
front of the Chicago Board of Trade and the eagle clutching the
globe at the EDS headquarters in Dallas. LUKAS BUYS QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   Just a day after he won a quarter-horse stakes race for the
first time in 20 years, D. Wayne Lukas spent $315,000 on a Raise A
Secret yearling that topped the Pacific Coast Quarter Horse Racing
Association sale Sunday in Orange County, Calif. The previous day,
Worth A Look (Lukas trains and owns the horse with wife Laura) won
the $301,000 PCQHRA Breeders' Futurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very special victory because of what it means to my
wife,'' Lukas said. ``She handles our entire quarter-horse
operation on an everyday basis. I get a lot of enjoyment from the
sport, but I'm just a prop.'' CUP PREP FRENZY
</P>
<P>
   The next two weekends mark the final chances for serious prep
races heading into Breeders' Cup championship day, Nov. 6 at
Gulfstream Park. Keeneland opens tomorrow, and Joe Who is expected
to race in the $400,000 Shadwell Keeneland Turf Mile. Joe Who,
winner of the Eddie Read Handicap on the turf at Del Mar this
summer, is owned by Jim Helzer of Mansfield.
</P>
<P>
   Other racing action this weekend centers on the Oak Leaf Stakes
at Santa Anita on Saturday (undefeated 2-year-old filly Chilukki
races), and Belmont Park's Jockey Club Gold Cup (Behrens, owned by
Waco resident Bill Clifton, is favored) and the Beldame Stakes
(Silverbulletday is favored) on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   HORSES MORE THAN A HOBBY FOR LATEST NFL TEAM OWNER
</P>
<P>
   Bob McNair bid $700 million to convince the NFL to put a team in
Houston. Although it's uncertain how much of that actually will
come from McNair since he's still attracting investment partners,
this much we do know:
</P>
<P>
   His star filly can walk out onto the racetrack any day and win
some of his money back. That filly is Chilukki, who likely will be
one of the favorites to win the $1 million Breeders' Cup Juvenile
Fillies on Nov. 6 at Gulfstream Park.
</P>
<P>
   She'll definitely be the favorite if she wins the Oak Leaf
Stakes tomorrow at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know McNair, whose horses run under the ownership name
of Stonerside Stables, believe he will stay heavily involved in
horse racing even while serving as managing partner with the new
Houston football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the more he's in horse racing, the more he likes it,''
said Kentucky-based breeder Arthur Hancock III, who sold a yearling
colt in partnership with McNair for $4 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who also was a co-owner of 1997 Belmont champ Touch Gold
when he foiled Silver Charm's bid for the Triple Crown, funded much
of his bid for the NFL team by selling three power plants he held
an ownership in for $1 billion last year.
JOIN THE FRATERNITY
</P>
<P>
   Houston businessman Bob McNair won the bid for an NFL expansion
team Wednesday. He's not the only person to own a professional
sports team and prominent racehorses at the same time. Owner Pro
team Horse Biggest win Jack Kent Cooke Redskins Flying Continental
'90 Jockey Club Gold Cup Gene Klein Chargers Winning Colors '88
Kentucky Derby George Steinbrenner Yankees Diligence '97 Churchill
Downs Handicap nn
</P>
