<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9955 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MERRILL-ONLINE-ART-2N     10-07 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-ONLINE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: those investors. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Easily the most important of those changes _ despite all the
attention Merrill's decision to offer online trading has garnered _
is the current push to convert most customers to a fee-based
account Merrill calls Unlimited Advantage. For a prearranged cut of
their assets, Merrill will offer account holders access to all of
its online services, including research by its own analysts and
from Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. And those customers will be able to
make as many trades as they want, either electronically or through
a broker.
</P>
<P>
   One person close to Merrill's top management said he thinks the
impending rollout of online trading ``is the biggest nonevent
around.'' Other aspects of its new strategy, including using
technology to expand the firm's base of institutional clients and
shifting away from a reliance on commissions, are more critical to
Merrill's ability to compete as an independent firm amid a
consolidating industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else Merrill is attempting, the switch to
fee-based accounts augurs a transformation in the relationship
between the firm's brokers and their clients. For years, Merrill
has been pushing its brokers to shift more customers away from
paying commissions for every transaction to paying an annual fee
based on a small percentage of total assets. But many brokers
balked because they felt they had more control of their own
earnings in a commission-based system. Only about five percent of
Merrill's clients assets are in fee-based accounts.
</P>
<P>
   What were once mere encouragements is now turning into
ultimatums. Steffens and other Merrill executives routinely refer
to the impending extinction of brokers who don't adopt the new
approach. They laud Unlimited Advantage for aligning the brokers'
interests with the clients' interest, taking away much of the
incentive to induce clients to make excessive and unwanted trades,
a practice known as churning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of clients who will actually look at this
account as favorable because it minimizes the potential for
churning,'' said Moszkowski, the Salomon Smith Barney analyst. But
it also takes away some of the brokers' motivation to interact with
clients. Once a client's assets are in-house and producing a fee,
the broker's attention naturally will turn to gathering more from
somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   Moszkowski predicted that many Merrill customers, contrary to
brokers' fears, will end up paying more in fees than they
previously paid in commissions. Steffens said that is already
happening. He told brokers last week that 55 percent of the new
accounts are yielding more per dollar to the firm than it gets on
the typical transaction-based account.
</P>
<P>
   On average, Merrill keeps about 77 cents annually of every $100
invested at the firm. That cut has been sliding for decades,
Steffens said in an interview after giving a pep talk at a
technology conference last week in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate Merrill's predicament, Steffens drew a large X on
a napkin. The downward sloping line represented the decline of
Merrill's cut of the assets from 1.5 percent in 1985; the other
line depicted the rapid growth in assets from $188 billion in 1985
to its current $1.5 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been in a price decline for years,'' Steffens said.
Brokers concerned about the firm's latest price cut, he argued,
should focus instead on helping Merrill continue to make it up on
volume.
</P>
<P>
   One veteran Merrill broker said he is resigned to earning 30
percent less from clients with more than $1 million in their
accounts. To make up the difference, he said, he will have to spend
more time prospecting and less time cultivating existing clients.
</P>
<P>
   Some brokers are not so accepting, though. Merrill admits that
more brokers are defecting to rival firms this year, an increase it
pegs at about 10 percent over a normal year. Others are grousing
about what they think is a too-aggressive swing the firm has made
to compete with cut-rate competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Steffens shrugged off those reactions: ``As you make changes in
a business and a business model, lots of people would like to go
back to the way things were.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the ironies of Merrill's new approach is that it goes
much farther afield than Schwab has. Long seen as an innovator
among leading brokerage firms, Schwab has no plan to branch out
into electronic commerce beyond its core financial-services
businesses, said Daniel Leemon, a vice president who maps strategy
for Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   ``What customers on the Web don't need these days is to be
inundated with offers,'' Leemon said. ``We think that begins to
dilute what the brand means to people. I don't think anyone wants
to come to Schwab for an auction of their Beanie Babies.''
</P>
<P>
   But Merrill executives are resolute about the important role thecan play in helping customers, including about 450,000 small
businesses, manage their daily finances. Customers care as much
about saving money on their regular purchases as earning money on
their investments, said Randal Langdon, who oversees Merrill's
e-commerce operations.
</P>
<P>
   Langdon, once a top Merrill broker, beamed like a new father the
other day as he demonstrated how Merrill's new shopping website
could track down a copy of a children's book by Harry Potter for
just $2.99. ``That's $20 retail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill already is arranging discounts for business owners on
office supplies, and helping them auction off excess inventory over
the Internet. Steffens said Merrill will consider brokering group
purchases of other things business owners need, such as insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is basically build more complete
banking capabilities, so they keep bigger balances with us,''
Steffens said. ``This is not about selling books and airline
tickets; it's about building relationships.''
</P>
</TEXT>
