<HEADLINE>
'96 U.S. OLYMPIC TEAM SHOWED A HOST TEAM HAS EDGE
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEIDI PEDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIANJIN, China _ The Chinese gymnasts competing in the 1999
World Gymnastics Championships are aware of what a home-field
advantage can mean.
</P>
<P>
   All they need as evidence is the women's team competition at the
1996 Olympic Games. In Atlanta, the U.S. women won the team gold
against a Russian squad they could not defeat at a neutral site.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese gymnasts and coaches have expressed confidence that
they'll dominate the medal standings at this year's World
Championships, which begin Saturday and run through Oct. 16 in
Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
   More than medals are at stake, however. This year's meet serves
as the team qualifier to the 2000 Olympic Games. The top 12 men's
and women's teams in Tianjin earn the right to compete in Sydney,
Australia, next September.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 championship also presents the last chance before
Sydney for countries and gymnastics judges to see most, if not
quite all, of the top Olympic contenders at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot of drama. Everyone's going to try to
put their 2 cents in,'' U.S. men's gymnast Blaine Wilson said.
``Everyone wants to look good.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. teams obviously want to look better than they did at
the previous World Championships in 1997, when both the men and
women made poor showings. The women plummeted to sixth only a year
after winning the Olympic team gold, and the men barely qualified
for the six-country team finals before finishing fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men seem likely to repeat that performance in China, as
they will be without rising star Jason Gatson, who suffered torn
knee ligaments at the U.S. Championships in August. Wilson will be
joined on the team by 1996 Olympian John Roethlisberger, Dallas
native Sean Townsend, Yewki Tomita, Chris Young, Steve McCain and
alternate Jay Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women's team appears stronger than the 1997 squad, and
is probably in the running for fourth place in China. This team
will include top gymnasts who couldn't compete in 1997 because of
the meet's age limit of 16, including Elise Ray, Jamie Dantzscher
and Vanessa Atler. Back from 1997 are current U.S. champion Kristen
Maloney, Wichita Falls native Jennie Thompson and Jeanette Antolin.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women's team will have a difficult time defeating the
likes of Romania, Russia, China, despite the fact that Romania and
China have lost their top all-around performers to injury. But the
U.S. women should have no trouble making the team finals, and the
17-year-old Atler could win titles on floor and vault and has an
outside chance at an all-around medal. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
