<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9957 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-LOWES08-CO     10-07 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LOWES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bomb incidents investigated in N.C.
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach and Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ The parents of a man killed in a crash at Lowe's
Motor Speedway in May have been interviewed by the FBI in
connection with bombings at Lowe's stores in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   And speedway officials, after receiving a bomb threat at the
track, will increase security for Sunday's NASCAR race, which is
expected to draw approximately 150,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   FBI and local law-enforcement officials are investigating
whether the bomb incidents at the stores are linked to a May 1
crash at the speedway that killed three spectators and injured
eight.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of Randy Pyatte, who was killed when a tire flew
into the stands during an Indy Racing League event, confirmed that
they were interviewed by FBI agents on Oct. 2. Roger Pyatte, the
victim's father, said two agents arrived unannounced at his home in
Connelly Springs, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked us if we'd heard anything in the past that would
have related to any kind of threat to the track,'' Roger Pyatte
said. ``They asked me if I'd been treated fairly by the track. I
said it was hard to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Speedway officials) called us for the first three or four
weeks after the tragedy, but then they just stopped,'' he said.
``If people really cared, like they said they did, it seems like
they'd call you every once in a while to see how you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, Lowe's agreed to pay Speedway Motorsports Inc.
about $35 million for a 10-year lease on the track's naming rights.
SMI also owns Atlanta Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The Sept. 22 explosions at Lowe's stores in Asheboro and
Salisbury injured three people. Another bomb did not explode at a
Lowe's store in Concord, near Lowe's Motor Speedway. A bomb threat
to the speedway has been received by telephone, track spokesman
Jerry Gappens said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Beauchamp, the lawyer representing the Pyattes and the
estates of the other two men killed _ Dexter Mobley of Statesville,
N.C., and Jeffrey Patton of Connelly Springs _ confirmed that the
FBI had interviewed the Pyattes, but had not contacted the families
of the other victims.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials in Atlanta could not be reached for comment
Thursday, but an FBI spokesman told the Greensboro News &AMP; Record
last week that investigators are following hundreds of leads in the
case. The News &AMP; Record also reported through anonymous sources
that ``an aggrieved relative'' called Lowe's headquarters in
Wilkesboro before the bombings to complain that the organization
``had not done enough'' for the families of the victims. The
newspaper also reported that a letter received by the corporate
office shortly after the bombings stated that they would continue
until Lowe's ``did right'' by the families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the FBI is doing its job of following any and all
leads,'' Beauchamp said. ``I don't begrudge them for doing their
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Track officials have hired extra guards and promised a more
extensive search of race fans for all events, including Sunday's
UAW-GM Quality 500 race. The FBI, local authorities and the federal
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms will have more personnel to
monitor the area and will employ detection devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is going to be a long-lasting thing,'' said
H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler, president of Lowe's Motor Speedway.
``Hopefully, they will catch this guy. All the things that have
happened at NFL games in the past are happening at speedways now.
We have some great expertise already in place to look at those
things. We have had a number of bomb threats (in the past), all
totally nothing to them, but they are very disruptive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to alarm anybody, but just let them know it is
still safe to come out here,'' Gappens said. ``With the increased
awareness from what has been going on over the last two weeks, this
is probably the safest week we've ever had (because) awareness is
up. People are on the lookout for anything they see that is
suspicious or out of the ordinary. I think we're in good shape, and
it is going to be a great weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Childress Racing reopened its No. 31 shop for tourists
on Wednesday after being closed to the public for three work days.
Mike Skinner is the driver for the No. 31 Chevy, which has Lowe's
as a primary sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (drivers) got so much to do, we don't even think about
(bomb threats), and hopefully things are being taken care of,''
driver Wally Dallenbach said. ``You just think about why somebody
is doing it. That's what you shake your head about and say, like,
'Come on, man, get a life.' I think (security) will do a good job
this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It worries you that there are nuts out there that do stuff
like that,'' said Richard Petty, one of NASCAR's greatest drivers.
``You just hope that it doesn't happen here, and if it does, you
are on the other side of the race track. I don't think there's a
bigger percentage of crazy people these days, just more people.''
</P>
<P>
   The ATF is offering a $30,000 reward for information leading to
the arrest of the person or group responsible for the bombing
incidents. ATF officials have said that evidence indicates the same
person or group planted all three bombs at the Lowe's stores.
</P>
<P>
   The estates of all three victims have filed wrongful-death
lawsuits against SMI, the Indy Racing League and Wheeler. A court
date of Aug. 8 has been set tentatively for Mecklenburg County
Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
