<SLUG> BC-INDIA-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION RESULTS SHOW VOTERS' PRAGMATISM
</HEADLINE>
   (With INDIA-POLITICS) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Laloo Prasad Yadav, the canny son of an
illiterate cowherd, who ruled impoverished Bihar state for almost a
decade in the name of the poor and low caste but who failed to
improve their standard of living, lost his Parliament seat on
Wednesday. His National People's Party's share of seats also fell
precipitously.
</P>
<P>
   In sharp contrast, another state leader, Chandrababu Naidu, the
chief minister of Andhra Pradesh, who is credited with harnessing
the state bureaucracy to provide people with government services,
won a big victory, and his his Telugu Desam Party scored major
gains in state and national elections.
</P>
<P>
   In both states it appeared that the desire for decent jobs,
schools and health care _ and the candidates' success or failure in
meeting those expectations _ drove the results.
</P>
<P>
   Another demand _ for human dignity _ has been behind the rise of
the Bahujan Samaj Party, which has its voter base among the
untouchable castes, or Dalits. By late Thursday night, it had
increased its seats in Parliament to 14, from five, after expanding
its appeal by putting up candidates who were Muslims or from upper
and middle castes.
</P>
</TEXT>
