u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-07 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LET GEORGES DO IT
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush was in New York this week, and by the time he had
left, everybody here was speculating like mad about Gov. George
Pataki's chances of getting the Republican vice-presidential
nomination. This is no small matter for the state. Pataki is a
career politician with no place left to climb. If we don't find him
another job soon, he's going to turn into Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the signs are favorable. Pataki appeared to have his
hand surgically attached to Bush's arm during his three-day visit,
but nobody shooed him away. The Texas governor heaped praise on
Pataki's support for charter schools, a passion so intense that
after five years of his leadership New York already has three, each
nearly a month old.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I know what you non-New Yorkers are saying to yourselves:
``Hey, we have a governor in our state that we might like to get
rid of too. Why can't George W. Bush pick him/her for his running
mate?'' Obviously, everybody cannot foist his excess politicians on
Bush's ticket. Some are simply unsuitable. Your governor might be a
Democrat or a professional wrestler. Even among the remainder, none
have Pataki's range of advantages:
</P>
<P>
   _Synergy. Secret research by the Republican National Committee
reveals that the majority of independent voters, soccer moms and
first-time home buyers would support the GOP ticket in 2000 if it
was made up exclusively of men named George.
</P>
<P>
   _Mutual interests. Like Bush, Pataki does not have a clue about
foreign affairs, so they could cram together, perhaps quizzing each
other on heads of state and capital cities.
</P>
<P>
   _Shared history. Pataki went to Yale in the mid-'60s, a rite of
passage he once said mainly involved ``beer and rock 'n' roll.''
Bush was at Yale at almost exactly the same time, having almost
exactly the same experience. However, Pataki was also involved in
campus politics, and he might be able to fill in a few blanks for
Bush, who claims not to remember having heard about any antiwar
protests during his college days.
</P>
<P>
   _Diversity. Pataki is a lawyer, a profession that is shockingly
underrepresented in the current presidential field. Think about it
_ Bush, Bradley, Gore, McCain _ not an attorney in the bunch. What
would happen if somebody in the White House needed to know what a
tort was in the middle of the night? The only serious presidential
candidate this year with a law degree is Elizabeth Dole. Bush
could, of course, take the easy route and simply make Mrs. Dole his
running mate. But then good luck finding out what was going on in
New Haven between 1964 and '68.
</P>
<P>
   _Desire. No other governor can match Pataki in desire to become
vice president, possibly because no one else has to deal with the
New York State Legislature. The governor was so eager to make Bush
happy this week that he agreed to share the stage on several
occasions with his longtime nemesis, New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani. (Giuliani was equally intent on proving he could be
collegial. During four minutes of remarks at a Queens job center,
he managed to cram in seven favorable references to Pataki,
exceeding his entire output for 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   When Bush praised the pair as ``pillars of the strength of the
Republican Party here in New York'' who were going to help him win
the state primary, Pataki and Giuliani practically quivered with
determination. That could be dangerous. When somebody tells the New
York Republican Party to deliver a primary, the rank and file
generally regard that as a summons to kidnap the other contenders
and stuff them in a car trunk.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the vice-presidential nomination. A ticket in which
everyone shares the same name, sex, age, schooling and current job
would have untold advantages, not the least of which would be money
saved by releasing the same biography for both candidates. The only
possible competition I can imagine for Pataki might be George Bush
the former president, who has not only his son's name, schooling
and multiple home states, but also his DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki does have a few minor disadvantages. He is, for instance,
taller than Bush, and most presidential candidates prefer to be
able to look down on their running mates. But I suspect Pataki is
so eager to get out of Albany that he would readily agree to remain
slouched for the next eight years. (BOX)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
