<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WARRICKARREST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FSU All-American Warrick charged with theft
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Heisman Trophy hopes _ and perhaps college career
_ of All-American Peter Warrick were placed in limbo Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State coach Bobby Bowden indefinitely suspended Warrick,
a senior, after the receiver was arrested on a grand-theft charge
in Tallahassee, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Senior wide receiver Laveranues Coles was arrested on the same
charge in the same case and dismissed from the team.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick and Coles are free on bond. Their first court appearance
is Monday.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 Florida State (5-0) plays No. 19 Miami on Saturday in
Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested with the players was a department store cashier. Police
said Rachel Myrtil, 19, allowed Warrick and Coles to buy clothing
worth $412.38 for $21.40 on Sept. 29 at Dillard's department store.
They said Myrtil voided the purchase price in the cash register,
did a cost override and charged the players the lower total. An
off-duty police officer caught the transaction on the store's
surveillance system.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick told police that Myrtil did the same thing for him on
previous trips to the store.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick cannot return to the team until his case is resolved in
court. He also will have to satisfy conditions of the university's
Athletics Code of Conduct, athletics director Dave Hart said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, who has 36 catches for 508 yards and four touchdowns,
was the leading candidate for the Heisman.
</P>
<P>
   Coles has been in trouble before. In 1998 he was charged with
simple battery when he was accused of hitting his stepmother
outside her home. He did 150 hours of community service and was
suspended for the 1998 opener with Texas A&AMP;M. He missed the 1999
opener with Louisiana Tech while school officials investigated a
trip he took to Texas allegedly paid for by an agent. Coles
reimbursed the ticket price and was reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thinking this week has been that if Laveranues was charged,
I would permanently dismiss him from the team, and I have,'' Bowden
said. ``Peter ... has been such a hard worker and a good leader. It
makes this all the more disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick was charged with disorderly conduct and resisting arrest
after an altercation at a Tampa, Fla., fast-food restaurant in
1998. The charges were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
