<HEADER>
A9972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FRANKEL-INDICT-550&AMP;AD     10-07 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKEL-INDICT-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ATTORNEY'S OFFICE INDICTS FUGITIVE FINANCIER HELD IN GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ohio, Germany)  (th) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fugitive financier Martin R. Frankel, who fled the United
States and is now in a German prison, was indicted by a federal
grand jury Thursday on 36 counts of fraud, money laundering and
racketeering in a scheme that siphoned more than $200 million from
a group of Southern insurance companies and was used for his own
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment, sought by the U.S. Attorney's Office for the
District of Connecticut, is the latest turn in a bizarre tale in
which Frankel, 44, is accused of masterminding a complicated
financial plan that, for more than eight years, drained millions of
dollars from insurance companies and their policyholders. That
scheme ended in May when Frankel's Greenwich, Conn., mansion caught
fire and Frankel fled the country.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of an international manhunt, Frankel was captured in
a Hamburg hotel room by local police officers and an FBI agent in
September and was imprisoned there on charges of carrying a false
passport. Meanwhile, German authorities have been waiting for
American law enforcement officials to prepare more serious charges
against him.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment lays the groundwork for a formal extradition
process to begin. It is not known whether Frankel will fight
extradition. His financial assets have been frozen and he is now
being represented by Thomas Dennis, a public defender, who would
not comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh F. Keefe, Frankel's former lawyer, said Thursday that
Frankel was currently facing ``two lousy options,'' either
remaining in German prison or returning to America for trial. Keefe
said he was no longer Frankel's lawyer because of the freeze on
Frankel's assets. He added, however, that Frankel's condition
``varies from day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly,'' he continued, ``this is not a terrific place to be
for anyone and he is in a tough German prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Keefe added that, until this indictment, one of the grounds for
Frankel to oppose extradition had been that he had not been
formally charged with a crime. But Thursday's indictment ``lightens
the government's load,'' Keefe said. ``He will eventually be
extradicted back to America unless he waives it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers with the U.S. attorney's office declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment offers some new details concerning how Frankel
conducted his insurance scheme and where the money went. In
two-pages of single-spaced type, the indictment describes how
Frankel, using a Swiss bank account, converted the money from the
insurance company into his multimillion dollar Greenwich mansion,
and into diamonds, gold coins from the Vienna Philharmonic,
traveler's checks, numerous automobiles and ``at least'' one
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankel converted, stole and embezzled the majority of funds
for personal use,'' the indictment said. ``In total, in excess of
$200 million was converted, stolen and embezzled by Frankel through
the scheme and artifice to defraud.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also outlined how Frankel did business: He
created a trust, the Thunor Trust, that he used to acquire stakes
in a number of insurance companies and then took the assets of
these insurance companies by saying that the money would be
invested in safe assets, primarily U.S. government securities.
Instead, he kept the money.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He also provided the insurance companies with false profit and
loss statements and, in some cases, returned enough cash to the
companies to prevent detection of the scheme by state insurance
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also accuses him of controlling the St. Francis
of Assisi Foundation, which was to be used to acquire insurance
companies and use any profits for charitable causes. As part of
this fraud, Frankel even persuaded a high-level retired priest at
the Vatican to unwittingly back this charity.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the indictment lists a number of Wall Street firms
where Frankel maintained accounts. They included Dreyfus Corp.,
Prudential Securities and Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co., along with Banque
SCS Alliance in Switzerland. None of the firms are named in the
indictment and were listed simply as places were Frankel did
business.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Toledo, Ohio, Frankel agreed to a lifetime ban from
the securities business in an out-of-court settlement in 1992 with
the Securities and Exchange Commission. This came after he ran
afoul of financial regulators when a small investment fund he ran
generated steep losses for retirees who had entrusted their savings
to Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   But even before that agreement was final, he began the scheme
that lead to Thursday's indictment. Along the way, however, he
lived a lavish life, operating from inside his four-acre Greenwich
mansion, complete with walls of computer and trading equipment _
which was rarely used _ and staffed by women he recruited through
the Internet and help-wanted ads to be his personal assistants.
</P>
<P>
   About the time Frankel fled the country, his house caught fire.
While there, Greenwich firefighters found smoldering documents and
a ``to-do'' list in which item No. 1 said ``Launder Money.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel was in his Hamburg hotel room with a female companion,
diamonds and cash, when he was arrested Sept. 4. Up to that point,
he had traveled through Europe, often openly, with several female
friends, and he had lived in apartments and hotels arranged for him
by contacts in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   If Frankel returns to the United States, he would be brought
before Judge Holly B. Fitzsimmons in Bridgeport. Keefe, Frankel's
former lawyer, said Frankel has not been allowed by German
authorities to meet with his new American lawyer yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important,'' Keefe said, ``to remember that this man is
presumed innocent and has not yet had a chance to give his side of
the story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
