u s BC-BBN-METS-ADVANCE08-CO     10-07 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ADVANCE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Game 3 a must-see for Venezuelans
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Mets and Arizona Diamondbacks play a
baseball game tonight. For the entire nation of Venezuela, the
stakes are higher.
</P>
<P>
   After splitting the first two in Phoenix, the NL Division Series
shifts to Shea Stadium, where talk is incessant over a Subway
Series and the revived corpse that is the Mets. For Venezuela, it
is more than that. The nation's best hitter _ the Mets' Edgardo
Alfonzo _ squares off against the country's best starting pitcher _
Arizona's Omar Daal _ on an historic night.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela won't know which way to turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are going to root for Venezuela, for both,'' Daal
said. ``If I get (Alfonzo) out, I know they are going to be happy.
(He) gets a base hit, I know they are going to be happy too.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement is appropriate, for in the Latin American boom
that has hit the majors in recent seasons, no nation has increased
in presence more than Venezuela. What started with Luis Aparicio in
the 1950s, what Tony Armas continued in the 1970s and Andres
Galarraga and Ozzie Guillen kept going in the 1980s is now a flood
of young talent spreading across both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's Bob Abreu, Montreal's Ugueth Urbina, San Diego's
Carlos Hernandez, Tampa Bay's Wilson Alvarez, Florida's Alex
Gonzalez and the White Sox' Magglio Ordonez have fanned out into
the majors. Postseason rosters are dotted with Venezuelans Omar
Vizquel (Cleveland), Luis Sojo (Yankees), Atlanta's Guillen and
Eddie Perez and Alfonzo's teammate Roger Cedeno. Galarraga and
Houston's Richard Hidalgo would be there too, but for the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   But tonight's pair is the most sublime, particularly because of
Alfonzo's rise to the elite this season. In an MVP-type year, he
moved from third to his natural position at second base and posted
career-highs in runs (123), hits (191), doubles (41), home runs
(27), RBIs (106) and walks (85), batting .304 in the most
productive season ever by a Mets second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   His ninth-inning, two-out grand slam in Game 1 off Bobby
Chouinard immediately turned this series in New York's favor,
coming at a critical time when Mike Piazza's bat has fallen quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's gotten away from the thought that he's going to
be a guy who gets a single to right,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine
said. ``He's a guy who can do a lot more than that. That's kind of
been drummed into his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Daal had it drummed into his head he was a left-handed match-up
reliever during stints in the Los Angeles, Montreal and Toronto
organizations, where he was permitted only nine career starts in
205 big-league appearances dating back to 1993. But the
Diamondbacks made him the second pick of the expansion draft and
made him a starter after Joel Adamson went down two months into the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Going 16-8 this year (and 2-1 against the Mets), Daal's 3.65 was
the third lowest ERA by an NL left-hander. After a 3-4 start, he
finished second only to Randy Johnson in team wins, going 8-3 in
the second half. Though it all, he has held Alfonzo to three hits
in 12 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' Daal said, ``in the game, we are enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Venezuela, they are proud.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
