<SLUG> BC-TEN-MCENROE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McENROE HOPES TRIP TO ZIMBABWE WON'T SCARE OFF TOP U.S. PLAYERS 
 (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McEnroe, the colorful new U.S. Davis Cup captain, heard the
word Zimbabwe on Thursday and immediately began checking his cell
phone to see if the prime name on his wish list of Davis Cup
volunteers, Andre Agassi, had called in to cancel his opening round
reservations. He had not.
</P>
<P>
   But McEnroe, 40, was properly queasy after learning that the
first assignment of his celebrated captaincy will take place in
foreign territory in early February against a team of underdogs led
by Byron and Wayne Black. Zimbabwe, which stunned powerful
Australia in the opening round two years ago, upset Chile in the
1999 relegation round for the right to test itself next year in the
World Group.
</P>
<P>
   The United States fell to Australia in the quarterfinals in
Chestnut Hill, Mass., in July, a round Agassi boycotted and Pete
Sampras decorated for doubles only. Now the American team has drawn
Zimbabwe as its opener, a difficult sell for a new captain trying
to recruit players willing to sandwich a visit to Africa between
the Australian Open and a regular tour event in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The response of McEnroe, who spent Thursday spreading the Davis
Cup gospel, was predictable. He bashed the Davis Cup schedule,
resolved to see the competition confined to a single month by 2002,
and then pronounced himself confident that he and his as-yet
unannounced troops would prevail in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough travel trip, but I like our chances; it's like
David versus Goliath,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, with 31 Davis Cup championships and 188 World
Group victories, is an overwhelming favorite to advance to the
second round against Britain or the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McEnroe paled when advised that he would need a couple of
dozen shots for immunization purposes before making the first trek
to Africa by an American Davis Cup team, and he worried aloud that
the unglamorous locale might scare Sampras away from joining the
team. He has not yet committed himself to McEnroe's debut squad.
McEnroe joked that he had even resorted to prayer, so far to no
avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's critical that all the top players do play,'' said
McEnroe. ``I think he realizes it's the right thing to do, but he
may have different feelings, particularly when he sees the draw.''
</P>
<P>
   But the captain, a veteran of five Davis Cup championship teams,
cheered up when he realized that if he could not do sufficient
arm-twisting, he might just find himself on his 13th career Davis
Cup roster _ as a player. McEnroe was offended that Tom Gullikson,
the previous captain, refused to select him for doubles, and while
he admitted it might feel odd ``picking myself,'' he did not rule
it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure word is seeping out that our worst-case scenario has
just taken place,'' said McEnroe of the logistical nightmare
entailed by a opening round confrontation in Zimbabwe just a week
after the Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre's already committed; unless he's injured, he's stuck,''
said McEnroe, whose hiring last month was expedited when Agassi,
Sampras, Todd Martin and Jim Courier expressed interest in playing
for him. Now it's crunch time for McEnroe and his persuasive
powers: ``This will be a gut check for a couple of guys. We will
separate the men from the boys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
