<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW BAD IS PEDRO? MAYBE HE'LL PLAY CATCH SATURDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ This is the best the Red Sox could promise about
Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in there when Pedro was examined by the doctor,''
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said. ``He told him to let it calm down
a couple of days, then he'll probably try to play catch (Saturday).
That was his advice. Let's see if he can play catch (Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he can play catch. Hardly a reassuring scenario for a team
hoping to have its ace back one more time in its division series
against the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Morgan, the team doctor traveling with the team,
reiterated Thursday that Martinez has a muscle strain in the
midback area. The pitcher came out of the team's 3-2 loss in Game 1
after four innings after apparently sustaining the injury while
throwing a 96-mile-per-hour fastball to Jim Thome, the first batter
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is slight improvement today, but he does have persistent
pain,'' Morgan said in a statement released by the club Thursday
afternoon. ``He's undergoing treatment right now, which includes
ultrasound, anti-inflammatory medication and rest. His condition
status is day to day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is to start stretching (Friday) and light exercise .
... We'll observe his progress and we will reevaluate him
(Friday).''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez did not poke his head out of the Sox clubhouse before
the game. He surfaced in the dugout in a stocking cap, where he did
some robotic twitching in apparent imitation of someone giving
signs in the Indians dugout.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, limited his pregame remarks to a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some improvement from Thursday,'' Martinez said. ``I
feel better already. I really feel positive about it. Right now I
feel looser. In a few hours after treatment, I'm hoping to even
feel better. Right now I'm just busy working and I'm going to keep
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Lurking on the perimeter of the discussion of Martinez's health
were suspicions that it was Martinez's shoulder and not his back
that was ailing. Pitcher Rich Garces mentioned after the Game 1
loss Tuesday night that Martinez's shoulder had been bothering him,
and in the Cleveland dugout, similar talk had been heard from the
Red Sox side.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Martinez repeatedly denied Wednesday night that his
shoulder was involved, Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette took a
similar line on the club's $75 million investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hurt the back of his shoulder in July,'' Duquette said.
``This is in a lower area. It's not related at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had some fears that Martinez would be affected by the
cool weather. Game-time temperature Wednesday night was 49 degrees.
Kerrigan said that when he was with Montreal, manager Felipe Alou
once kept Martinez out of commission for 17 days because he didn't
want him pitching in the cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were concerned, going in,'' Duquette said. ``Pedro thrives
in warm weather and (cold weather) is always a concern when you get
into October.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams hasn't abandoned the hope that Martinez
will pitch again this season. Asked if it might be better to shut
him down, Williams said: ``I don't think we have to make that
decision today. I don't think we have to make that decision
tomorrow. Let's see how he feels. Let's get there first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
