NYT-10-07-99 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9982 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-HAMPTON08-     10-07 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HAMPTON08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hampton has Astros feeling confident
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In Mike Hampton's arm the Astros trust. That he takes
the ball in this afternoon's Game 3 of the Division Series against
the Braves is the club's ultimate security. An effort typical of
his sparkling season would put Houston on the cusp of the NLCS. And
Hampton would have it no other way.
</P>
<P>
   In short, this is what the Astros and Hampton wanted _ a chance
to get one game from eliminating the vaunted Braves with the ace on
the hill. When asked if there was anyone over Hampton he'd like to
have pitching today, manager Larry Dierker responded, ``Maybe Bob
Gibson.''
</P>
<P>
   That's as good an indication of the feel-good vibes Hampton
creates as anything. He finished the season 22-4 with a 2.90 ERA
and in serious Cy Young Award contention. If that's not enough,
Dierker pointed out that the team lost only five games in which
he's pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those games we took him out for a pinch-hitter or
because he didn't pitch that well,'' Dierker explained, ``but we
still usually did enough to win (29 of 34 starts). I can't remember
anybody _ including Bob Gibson _ with that high a winning
percentage.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton said he cannot remember being so excited about a
single-season performance like this season. Nor can he pinpoint
ever being so anxious to pitch as he is today. The magnitude of it
all does not frighten him; it thrills him, he insists, even though
failure could be damaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in pressure situations, you want to thrive in,'' Hampton
said. ``It's easy to get up for those type of games. If you do
well, you look great. But if you don't, you look like a guy who's
choked. So, it's a double-edged sword.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing Hampton is a similar endeavor. He has different velocity
on his fastball and stunning movement. His pitch placement usually
keeps batters off balance. He's grown from a predominant
heat-thrower determined to blow away hitters to a cunning pitcher
who uses a diverse arsenal to baffle opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier in my career,'' Hampton said, ``I was more of a
thrower. I threw a little harder. In jams I would turn it up. Now,
I can take a little off, get more movement on my pitches. That's
been the biggest key in not pressing. I try to pitch 90 to 95
percent rate where situations (come) and I need that little extra,
I still have it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It basically comes down to knowing abilities, just learning
throughout the years and pitching smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton clearly has a grasp of his skill. The Cy Young balloting
should be between him, Arizona's Randy Johnson and the Braves'
Kevin Millwood. If someone other than Hampton wins it, he figures
he'll never earn the coveted pitching award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've definitely had the best year I probably could possibly
have,'' he said. ``Everything has gone right. (So) I feel like I
have a chance, but I can't control those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
