</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ADVANCE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves ready to take out Hampton
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ This is what the Braves wanted _ a chance to make or
break the Division Series in Game 3 today against the Astros' best
pitcher, and arguably the best pitcher in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two game-winner Mike Hampton, the toughest pitcher to
beat in baseball this year this side of Pedro Martinez, is what
stands between the Braves and control of this Division Series,
which is back up for grabs after the Braves won 5-1 Wednesday to
even the best-of-five series 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly a best-case scenario, but after where the
Braves were sitting on Tuesday night following their 6-1 loss in
Game 1, this is good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come here to take out their best,'' Brian Jordan said.
``He's a Cy Young candidate. I think he's a winner. ... If we beat
Hampton tomorrow, the momentum will definitely be our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's NL Cy Young award winner will have something to say
about it. Tom Glavine may have the toughest stomach lining of any
member of the Braves staff, and he'll need it with the pivotal Game
3 pressure bearing down.
</P>
<P>
   With the way he's pitched lately, the Braves have to like their
chances, especially considering where he's pitching. Glavine, who
finished out his season with three consecutive wins, including two
in postseason-caliber games against the Mets, is 8-0 in his last 10
starts in the Astrodome, going back to June of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it,'' Glavine said. ``If for no other
reason than you don't want to be sitting on the bench with somebody
else pitching in a game like that. ... I feel good about the way
I've been throwing the ball the last three starts, probably as
confident taking the mound as I've been all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros beat the Braves only once in seven regular-season
meetings this year. Hampton was the guy to do it. He's many of the
Braves' choice for Cy Young, including Glavine and the Braves' top
candidate Kevin Millwood. Hampton is yet another left-hander who's
been compared to Glavine throughout his career. There's a point to
that. Both are groundball pitchers stubborn because they're around
the plate, but would rather walk a hitter than give him a decent
pitch to hit.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton has pitched Glavine-like of late, too, winning two
starts the Astros desperately needed to clinch their third
consecutive NL Central title.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
