<SLUG> BC-MA-POLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE VOTERS LEANING TOWARD BRADLEY: POLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With questions of electability already dogging Vice
President Al Gore, Clinton-friendly Massachusetts voters are
delivering him another blow: A new poll shows Democrat Bill Bradley
leading Republican George W. Bush here by 14 points, while Bush
leads Gore by 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide survey, taken by the University of Massachusets'
McCormack Institute, also shows Bradley running 8 points ahead of
Gore among Democratic primary voters, 43 to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The new survey marks an 11-point shift in Bradley's favor since
a UMass poll in June showed Gore leading the former New Jersey
senator, 38 to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Bradley's once longshot presidential candidacy
has started to surge, particularly in the Northeast. Recent polls
in New Hampshire and Rhode Island showed the two Democrats running
in dead heats, an astonishing turn-around given that only a few
months ago the vice president was expected to win handily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gore candidacy is in collapse in the Northeast,'' said Lou
DiNatale, director of UMass' McCormack Institute. ``This poll
confirms that at the very least this is going to be a race to the
convention. If the trend continues, it could even be a March
knockout by Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll _ taken Sept. 29 to Oct. 4 _ has a margin of error of
plus or minus 5 points among all 400 registered voters, and 6
points among the smaller sample of likely Democratic primary
voters.
</P>
<P>
   The survey shows Bradley attracting independent voters, women,
and high school and college graduates. In a race against Bush,
Bradley leads 48 to 34 percent, while Bush beats Gore, 46 to 39
percent. The Bradley survey comes in a state where Bill Clinton,
with Gore on his ticket, has rolled up some of his largest
electoral margins.
</P>
<P>
   On the state political level, the poll shows recent scandals in
Governor Paul Cellucci's administration have eroded the governor's
standing among voters. Cellucci's favorability has dropped 10
points since late June.
</P>
<P>
   The results show 59 percent of those surveyed approve of
Cellucci's performance. Another 29 percent disapprove, compared to
31 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's director of the Massachusetts Port Authority, Peter
Blute, was forced to resign in August after partying on a
state-funded ``booze cruise'' with lobbyists and young women.
Cellucci has also been criticized for the quality of some of his
appointments, including his selection of lobbyist Stephen Tocco to
head the board of higher education.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's findings in the presidential race also boost
Bradley's image as the strongest Democrat when he is paired against
another GOP contender, John McCain. Bradley holds a 25 percentage
lead over the Arizona Democrat, while McCain beat Gore with a 5
percent margin.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore may not score well in head-to-head contests with Bush
and Bradley, the vice president remains a relatively popular figure
among the Bay State's Democratic voters. Some 68 percent give him a
favorbale rating, while 25 percent rated him unfavorably. Another 7
percent offered no answer.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley gets a 70 percent favorably rating among the same group,
with only 8 percent rating him unfavorably. Another 22 percent had
no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   US Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who plans to seek his seventh full
term next year, is in a strong position with voters. In a trial
heat with Michael Sullivan, the Plymouth County district attorney
and likely possible Republican opponent, Kennedy receives 60
percent of the vote. Sullivan gets 23 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
