<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Stock Market And Social Security &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Wall Street for help may not solve Social Security's
potential problems, a group of researchers has found.
</P>
<P>
   Investing some Social Security taxes in the stock market will
not eliminate the program's projected deficit, they said. And under
some circumstances, the analysis concluded, it may even accelerate
it.
</P>
<P>
   Economists from Goldman Sachs, Invesco, Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter and J.P. Morgan did the research for the Committee on
Investment of Employee Benefit Assets, an association of corporate
pension plans based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The economists considered three environments in which 50 percent
to 75 percent of the current surplus in Social Security taxes would
be invested in stocks. They concluded that if the market performed
in historical patterns, the year in which Social Security, without
any other changes, would technically be out of money would be
delayed from 2034, the current official projection, to between 2038
and 2046.
</P>
<P>
   But if the stock market dropped 20 percent to 30 percent during
the next five years, Social Security could run into a deficit as
early as 2032, they said.
</P>
<P>
   _David Cay Johnston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Up the Philanthropy Food Chain &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Philanthropy is about to show up on some high-definition radar
screens.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, have
invited 150 leading donors, as well as young people and leaders of
foundations and other nonprofit groups, to the East Room on Oct. 22
for what is believed to be the first White House conference on
philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   The group will ``take a look at the tradition of philanthropy
and giving in this country and new ways of looking at it,'' said
Marsha Berry, Mrs. Clinton's director of communication.
</P>
<P>
   Also this month, America Online's AOL Foundation plans to
introduce a philanthropic Web portal, which will connect donors and
volunteers to nonprofit groups, and link those groups to resources
on topics like management and fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   The AOL Foundation has given a grant to the Benton Foundation in
Washington to help develop the site, called helping.org, and is
forming partnerships with nonprofit organizations to provide
content.
</P>
<P>
   A second philanthropic Web portal is also in the works. The
Surdna Foundation in New York has awarded $150,000 to Compumentor,
a nonprofit group in San Francisco, to create a technology portal
that will include links to help nonprofit groups find technical
assistance, donated and discounted software and information about
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   _Todd Cohen
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
