<SLUG> BC-WTO-CABINET-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABINET MEMBERS TO SELL VIRTUES OF FREE TRADE IN PRE-WTO VISITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three members of President Clinton's cabinet will
visit Washington state this month as part of a national effort to
talk up the benefits of global trade.
</P>
<P>
   The visits, which begin with a trip Friday by Transportation
Secretary Rodney Slater, are part of a broader effort by the
Clinton administration to sell its trade policy to the American
public in anticipation of the meeting of the World Trade
Organization in Seattle starting Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Protection Agency Administrator Carol Browner and
Labor Secretary Alexis Herman also have scheduled Seattle visits.
</P>
<P>
   The trips come in the wake of criticisms by Sen. Patty Murray,
D-Wash., and others of the administration's efforts to promote the
virtues of global trade.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the U.S. Trade Representative's office said they
expect Cabinet members, as well as top officials from the trade
representative's office, to fan out across the country over the
next seven weeks, promoting ``the benefits of trade and new
opportunities for American farmers and workers and families.''
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said in a
letter last week that the White House is looking for an opportunity
for Clinton to make a major trade speech prior to the Seattle
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Some Cabinet members, including Commerce Secretary Bill Daley
and Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, have been traveling on
trade issues for months, but the efforts are being stepped up in
light of the concerns expressed by some environmental and labor
groups about the benefits of the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said she was delighted by the plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Murray has urged the administration to make a forceful
case for the importance of trade, and sending Cabinet members and
asking USTR officials to go out around the country to articulate
the importance of trade is the strongest response we could have
hoped for,'' said Murray's spokeswoman, Tovah Ravitz.
</P>
<P>
   In a further effort to step up its courtship of concerned
constituencies, the White House this month will meet with groups
representing consumers, agriculture, labor, business and the
environmental movement, the U.S. Trade Representative's office
said. The Trade Representative's office said it has already been
consulting with many of those organizations for months about the
U.S. agenda for the WTO meeting, but that the White House visits
will provide a higher-profile opportunity for the groups to voice
their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. trade officials said it is possible that other Cabinet
members, including Daley and Glickman, could visit the state before
the WTO meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Daley and Glickman last week reported to the Senate Finance
Committee that U.S. trade policy has been a surprisingly tough sell
to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, who has made five stops on his ``Trade Globally, Prosper
Locally: The National Trade Education Tour,'' said ``to be frank
with you, this has not been an easy sell, as you know. Many people
see only layoffs, they don't see the payoff of this open trading
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Glickman, whose agency held 12 ``listening sessions'' around the
country in anticipation of the WTO meeting, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This education tour ... has been rather difficult and, at
times, very disappointing, to be frank with you,'' he said. ``The
lack of understanding, first of all, by people who should
understand the benefits of this trading system of ours and,
obviously, the difficulty of getting a positive story through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
