<HEADLINE>
ARRESTS IN YOGURT SLAYINGS REOPEN OLD WOUNDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Parents of the four teen-age girls slain in a
yogurt shop robbery in 1991 said this week's arrests of four young
men on capital murder charges suddenly reopened painful wounds that
may never heal.
</P>
<P>
   So doubtful were they that the case would ever be solved, one of
the parents said Thursday she long ago threw away a pamphlet for
crime victims about how to brace for an upcoming trial.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional news conference, the parents expressed relief
that the case was finally cracked by Austin police. But they
indicated that convictions and even the death penalty won't end
their grieving _ or lessen their resolve to improve workplace
safety for minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've got to face the fact that the actual people who did
this... that we have to look at someone who actually pulled the
trigger on our children. The anxiety level is very high,'' said
Barbara Ayres, mother of murder victims Jennifer Harbison, 17, and
Sarah Harbison, 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are really doing here is trying to beg you _ the press
and the public _ to not treat this as something to exploit, but to
respect our children's lives. It has not come to closure, and we
have not gone to court yet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   James Thomas, father of victim Eliza Hope Thomas, 17, said he's
gratified that arrests were made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, adaptation to loss of a loved one to homicide is a
difficult, gut-wrenching task, and I feel that I may accomplish
that someday,'' he said, adding, ``I will continue to need your
support as the matter makes its way through the legal process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my hope that bringing these people to justice will help
us all bring this episode to a close so we can get on with the good
things that we all do with our lives,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Harbison and Eliza Thomas worked at the shop in a
northwest Austin strip mall; Sarah Harbison and a friend, Amy
Ayers, 13, were visiting the other girls at the shop around closing
time on the night of Dec. 6, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the suspects provided written statements admitting they
cased the store earlier that day, propped a back door open and
returned after closing. With one of the suspects posted as a
lookout, the others robbed the store, bound and gagged the girls,
and shot each of them fatally in the head before setting the
business on fire, the confessions stated.
</P>
<P>
   Charged with four capital murder counts each are Maurice Pierce,
24, of Lewisville; Forrest Wellborn, 23, of Lockhart; Robert Burns
Springsteen Jr., 26, of Charleston, W.Va.; and Michael James Scott,
26, of Buda. All were arrested Wednesday and remained jailed,
pending indictment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to believe that anybody could do what someone
did to our girls, much less kids,'' Ayres said. ``It's just hard
for me to imagine that somebody is capable of doing that, and it's
hard for me to imagine that they have walked around this long ...''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, none of the parents expressed annoyance at Wednesday's
revelation that police had nabbed one of the suspects eight days
after the killings on a weapons charge and released him _ even
after he admitted the gun was used in the girls' slayings. At the
time, police said the then-juvenile's account was unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ayers, Amy's father, said early on in the investigation, FBI
criminal profilers suggested to him that the culprits may have been
young acquaintances of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we were prepared for that,'' Ayers said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the victims and suspects were of similar age, it's not
clear whether any of them knew each other.
</P>
<P>
   Ayers and his wife, Pam, said the arrests, which had been
reported as imminent several days ago, forced them to relive the
horror of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the starting point every time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doorbell rings,'' his wife added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dec. 6, 1991 _ that's where we start,'' said Ayres, who said
she felt no particular emotion when she saw the suspects faces for
the first time in newspapers and newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we want to know _ what happened. How it happened.
And what are we going to do as responsible adults so it doesn't
happen again. We want to know where these young people came from.
We want to know their background,'' Ayres said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to know how their lives got into murder _ how their
lifestyle became a murderous one. It's important to us. It's
important to people in Arkansas and Colorado and everyplace else
where they've had losses of life without good reason,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ayres and the others used proceeds from a legal settlement with
the shop owners to start a foundation called ``We Will Not Forget
SAJE`` _ the initials of the girls' first names. The organization
has lobbied for improved workplace security, especially where
minors are alone on duty, as their daughters were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we know exactly what happened, we will not be able to
protect the children that we have working now. That's our mission _
to protect the rest of the children who have a right to work and
are working,'' Ayres said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
