<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10TH MONTH, RED SOX COLLAPSES GO HAND IN HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The shadows grew long, the game got out of hand, and
back in New England, Wednesday's disappointment yielded to
Thursday's despair.
</P>
<P>
   Just what is it about October, New England's best month, that
brings out the worst in the Red Sox? The list of Sure Things In
Life now includes death, taxes, bad movies by Kevin Costner, and
Red Sox collapses in the 10th month.
</P>
<P>
   The estimable Peter Pascarelli, a Boston native now a reporter
for ESPN, walked around the batting cage before Thursday's 11-1
Cleveland win over Boston and said, ``Pedro is now day-to-day, and
Red Sox fans are century-to-century.''
</P>
<P>
   Time to bring in George W. Bush with the Alamo Speech. Or maybe
have Ms. Jimy Williams make game shirts with silkscreens of past
Red Sox world championship teams.
</P>
<P>
   So sad. Your Red Sox, this overachieving, hardscrabble band of
ballplayers, has been reduced to late-night monologue fodder. They
are the Susan Lucci of sport. Erica on ``All My Children'' is 1 for
19 at the Emmys, and the Sox are now 1 for 19 in postseason play
since Bruce Hurst beat the Mets in Game 5 of the 1986 World Series.
Who knew the fallout from Bill Buckner's error would carry into the
new millennium?
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Williams. ``Maybe I'll just get a hold of
George Herman (Ruth). I don't know. What do you want me to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The manager is deep into Bambino references as the sand runs out
on the Sox season. He's been carrying a Baby Ruth candy bar around
for good luck and noted that he was in room 1916 (the year the Babe
beat the Dodgers in the World Series) at the Sox hotel in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Like all those who came before them, the 1999 Boston ballplayers
insisted that they had nothing to do with their forefathers. All
the bad stuff happened before they became Red Sox. But like the
teams of '86, '88, '90, '95, and '98, the Red Sox of 1999 are
adding a chapter to the haunted playoff history of the franchise
(a.k.a. ``The Misses of October''), feeding the fickle fan base and
media monster that's devoured the Olde Towne Team since 1918.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. The Sons of Jimy Williams deserve better. This was a
team from which nothing was expected. They were resilient and
noble, winning 94 games and throwing off every challenge they
faced. But it would appear that nothing _ no measure of health,
heart, or heroism _ is bigger than the beast that stalks this team
when the leaves fall from the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Wakefield, a veteran of Sox postseason humblings at the
hands of the Indians in '95, '98, and '99, admitted, ``It's
frustrating, but you can't take away what we've accomplished all
year. It's unfair. This reminds me a lot of '95 when we played well
in the first game. I can't explain it. I don't know. We played 'em
well all year.'' Boston was 8-4 vs. Cleveland during the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   Sox frustrations aside, Cleveland has played near flawless
baseball in the first two games of the series. The Tribe have held
the Sox to three runs in 18 innings and gloved everything that
moved. Remember that these Indians are the first major league team
to score 1,000 runs in a season since the 1950 Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   There still is a chance, of course. The Sox could come home,
revert to regular-season form, and spank the Tribe twice _ forcing
a winner-take-all Game 5 Monday at Jacobs Field. But is there
anyone in New England, anyone in the Boston clubhouse, who believes
that is going to happen? With ace Pedro Martinez on the shelf with
a bad back? With Bret Saberhagen done for the series after one of
his worst outings of the year? With a Limp Bizkit lineup and
potential starters named Ramon Martinez, Kent Mercker, and
Undecided?
</P>
<P>
   Thursday at the Jake the Sox were exposed in ugly fashion. Jose
Offerman failed to turn a double play in the third, which opened
the gates. Saberhagen, who walked only 11 batters in 119 innings,
walked three in the third and did not leave before giving up a
whopping six runs. The Sox issued nine walks on the day.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen was replaced by John ``Way Back'' Wasdin. True to
form, Way Back yielded a grand slam to Jim Thome in the fourth and
the rout was on.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say about it?'' asked a frustrated Nomar
Garciaparra. ``The score speaks for itself. They just beat us. They
took it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the most lopsided loss in Boston's ghoulish postseason
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``A five-game series is almost unfair in a way,'' said center
fielder Darren Lewis. ``If you don't jump out right away, it's like
you're in a hole from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   And so they are. It is October and the Red Sox are where they
have been every October since World War I. They are one loss away
from elimination. The series resumes at 4 p.m. Saturday at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
