<HEADER>
A9993 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-ANNUITIES-$AD     10-07 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-ANNUITIES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVAMPING THE VARIABLE ANNUITY TO MAKE IT MORE COMPETITIVE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (af)  
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The variable annuity, that odd combination of mutual fund and
insurance policy, has picked up a reputation for being too complex
for most people to understand, not to mention overly expensive when
compared with a pure mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   But fairly straightforward variable annuities with low fees do
exist, and, lately, the costs for these basic models have fallen
even lower.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago, TIAA-CREF, which has been providing
pension plans for educators for decades, introduced a new variable
annuity for the general public with a fee of a little more than
one-third of one percent, or about one-sixth as much as the average
variable annuity.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Fidelity Investments, the big mutual fund
company, stopped charging a fee that most companies apply to
variable annuity accounts that are closed earlier than expected.
And the Vanguard Group, known for its low-cost mutual funds, shaved
a basis point _ one hundredth of a percentage point _ off the cost
of its already inexpensive variable annuities.
</P>
<P>
   All of these investments are aimed at the relatively
self-sufficient investor, and the companies that offer them pride
themselves on the annuities' simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   They work like this: People put their money into accounts that
in most respects are similar to mutual funds, with returns that
rise or fall with the market; indeed, many are run by fund
managers. A portion of the annual fee for the variable annuity pays
for life insurance that protects the investor's estate against a
dip in the market: if the investor dies, the heirs are assured of
getting at least the amount invested; if the investor lives, he or
she has to absorb any loss in value.
</P>
<P>
   Variable annuities also have an advantage that they share with
401(k) plans and similar accounts: earnings are tax-deferred.
Income tax is paid only when the money is withdrawn, and then at
the taxpayer's rate at that time. Money can be withdrawn from a
variable annuity all at once, in a few lump-sum payments or as a
stream of regular payments until death.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more expensive variable annuities go beyond
protecting just the invested principal, by guaranteeing minimum
annual growth of, say, 4 percent or 5 percent, regardless of what
the market does. Such annuities relieve worries about the market's
ups and downs, though given the long-term upward trend in the
market over recent decades, some investors may not see such
protection as necessary. The growth guarantee can be set up to
benefit the investor or the estate, with separate charges for each
option.
</P>
<P>
   So far, low-cost versions are just a tiny fraction of the
variable-annuity market. Industry analysts say TIAA-CREF and the
other low-cost operators are fighting for bigger shares of that
small pie, while holding out hope that the pie will grow.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say the tide does not seem to be running that way.
``If you look across the financial services field, there is a
movement toward advice,'' said Eric Speer, a specialist on variable
annuities for Tillinghast-Towers Perrin, the consulting firm.
``With variable annuities and mutual funds, more and more of the
business is being sold through adviser channels,'' rather than
directly.
</P>
<P>
   By selling a variable annuity, advisers _ typically brokers and
financial planners _ can make a commission of up to 7 percent from
the insurance company that offers the investment. That compares
with a commission of up to 5.75 percent for a mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   As with some mutual funds, customers pay the commission out of
pocket _ in part or in full, on a sliding scale _ only if they
redeem the annuity in less than five or seven years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, mainly because of the insurance features,
variable-annuity investors pay average annual fees of a little more
than 2 percent of the value of their investment, compared with 1.55
percent for the average stock mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   Like no-load mutual funds, though, low-cost variable annuities
pay no sales commissions, so advisers have no incentive to sell
them. Customers must do business directly with the annuity
companies, using the phone, the mails and computers. And while
cutting out the adviser keeps costs low _ the total cost of a
Vanguard annuity, for example, is just 0.57 percent a year _
legions of investors do not want to make the journey alone.
</P>
<P>
   The companies that pay commissions to advisers emphasize the
value of a broker's advice. Jim Folwell of Cerulli Associates, a
consulting firm in Boston, says that while it is difficult to put a
precise value on the advice, ``there is definitely some value added
when a good financial adviser can position you in the right
product.''
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates and the low-cost operators suggest that
the advice might not be all that valuable. It seems only natural,
they say, that brokers and financial planners would be inclined to
recommend annuities that offer them the most profit.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the critics say, that means selling less than the
best variable annuity available or selling one to customers who
should be investing in something else.
</P>
<P>
   For example, consumer advocates say investors should put money
into variable annuities only after they have already made the
maximum contributions to 401(k) programs, which are generally less
expensive. People who might need to withdraw money in less than
five to seven years should steer clear of variable annuities, the
consumer advocates say, because many companies charge penalties for
earlier withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   For those who are interested, the choice is not absolutely
between turning to a broker for guidance and doing it yourself,
said Dennis D. Foley, a vice president at TIAA-CREF who has
overseen variable annuities and mutual funds there for nearly 20
years. While he acknowledged that the low-cost investments may well
appeal to a more independent sort, his company and others that deal
directly with consumers will go over the details of their products
and help with a selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our people on the phones are well trained to help you make
your decision,'' he said. ``The same telephone centers handle
variable annuities and mutual funds. Our people are on salary, and
they are not motivated to steer clients into one product or the
other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
