<HEADLINE>
FOR WW II B-17 VETS, THIS IS THEIR FINAL MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Wilbur Richardson stooped under the plexiglas nose of
the B-17F parked at the Museum of Flight and stared at the gun
turret protruding from the belly of the restored World War II
bomber.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very cold in there,'' said the former staff sergeant
and gunner, now a 77-year-old retiree. ``On flights it usually was
minus-40 degrees and on one mission I saw it get down to 72 below
zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Three wizened comrades nodded, their eyes gleaming with
memories.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson hunched over to explain. ``We kept warm with
electrically heated suits, but in there your knees were in your
eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   They survived the hellish skies over Nazi-occupied Europe nearly
six decades ago, bombing German targets, suffering enormous losses
from anti-aircraft artillery and Luftwaffe fighters. They flew
missions lasting as long as 12 hours, often limping back to England
with engines shot away and blood on the decks. And as part of the
``Mighty Eighth'' Air Force, they formed bonds of friendship that
have endured to this day.
</P>
<P>
   But for the men of the 94th Bomb Group, U.S. Army Air Corps, the
end is in sight. Time has accomplished what the enemy could never
do, and by mutual agreement, the airmen are staging their their
last mission _ one final reunion _ in Seattle this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our average age is the mid-70s to early 80s,'' said reunion
coordinator Colin Storey, who as a 1st lieutenant survived 35
combat missions with the group. ``We've lost so many of our key
members.''
</P>
<P>
   Age and illness have shrunk the veterans group from 4,000 in
wartime to about 1,200 today. Only 320 veterans and about 400
family members made the trip to Seattle, Storey said.
</P>
<P>
   But long before the passage of time eroded their ranks, there
was the German army and air force to contend with.
</P>
<P>
   They were part of an aerial armada unprecedented in military
history and not duplicated since. Formed in 1942, the Eighth Air
Force by war's end in May 1945 had 350,000 airmen and support
personnel including 210,000 aircrew members. They suffered
horrendous losses, with 26,000 killed in action. According to
military historian Gerald Astor, the mortality rate of 12.38
percent was four times higher than the Marine Corps and six times
as severe as the Army.
</P>
<P>
   The 94th Bomb Group, with 186 Boeing-built B-17s, was one of 22
groups that flew the B-17. They lost more than 100 aircraft and
hundreds of personnel killed or taken prisoner in their three years
of combat, Storey said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Young shrugged when asked to recount his experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aircraft was easy to fly but it was rough on those
8-9-hour flights,'' the 83-year-old Texan said. ``You'd come back
with blisters on your hands after gripping the yoke so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Navigator Elmer Ruehlmann said his most vivid mission came in
early 1945 when he, Storey and eight crewmates lost two of four
engines to enemy flak over Geisen, Germany. Unable to maintain
altitude, they played hide-and-seek with German fighters for more
than three hours while flying ``from cloud to cloud'' before making
a safe landing in Belgium, said Ruehlmann, a Sequim resident.
</P>
<P>
   There were still a few hours left for reminiscing and laughter
before the final mission ends Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have our final banquet and closing ceremony,'' Storey
said. ``And that will be that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
