<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLEVELAND-THOME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOME IN TOP HOMER COMPANY IN OCTOBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Jim Thome has been a colossal failure in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   He's been to the playoffs for the past five seasons, and in that
time, the Indians first baseman and No. 5 hitter has managed a
pathetic .229 average, mustering a mere 36 hits in 157 at-bats.
True failure.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, 14 of those hits have been home runs, a total
surpassed by only three men, Hall of Famers all, in history: Mickey
Mantle (18), Reggie Jackson (18), and Babe Ruth (15). And four of
Thome's homers have come in consecutive games, dating back to last
year's American League Championship Series. And two of (italics)
those (end italics) have been grand slams, a feat matched by no one
in baseball history. Now that's colossal.
</P>
<P>
   This season's Division Series reunion with the Red Sox has been
typical Thome. He has two hits in the first two games -- a two-run
sixth-inning homer that tied the opener, paving the way for a 3-2
Cleveland comeback, and a fourth-inning grand slam Thursday that
put the final chokehold on an 11-1 manhandling of the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, Thome hasn't done a thing.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Indians fly to Boston on a 2-0 cloud in this
best-of-five series, be assured that this will not be a topic of
conversation: Why does Thome go boom or bust in October, either
hanging his head as he returns to the dugout or accepting a chorus
of salutes as he dances across home plate?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably one of those things that is best left
unexplained,'' said manager Mike Hargrove. ``Just be thankful that
it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Omar Vizquel, whose two-run triple off Bret Saberhagen in the
third inning Thursday erased a 1-0 deficit that the Indians soon
obliterated, believes Thome ``is probably a little more patient in
the postseason.''
</P>
<P>
   So patient that he'll only settle for homers?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of those things I can't explain,'' said Vizquel,
nodding in the direction of Thome's locker and speaking just loud
enough for his teammate to hear. ``Only Jim Thome can explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   No he can't. But that didn't prevent him from complementing his
eye black with a huge smile as he dressed a half-hour after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of happened during the season when I struck out 171
times,'' said Thome, neglecting to mention that he also batted .277
with 33 homers and 108 RBIs, a typical year for him. ``Seriously,
it's tough to explain. I'm fortunate to have good batters around me
and getting good pitches to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Thome was only one of several Indians who savored some
delectable pitches Thursday. Vizquel's triple was followed by
Roberto Alomar's run-scoring double and Harold Baines's three-run
homer in the six-run third off Bret Saberhagen. In the five-run
fourth, Thome launched a John Wasdin offering 384 feet into the
right-field bleachers for the slam that really was superfluous
except in a historical context.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hitting today was kind of contagious,'' said Thome.
``After Harold's three-run shot, everyone relaxed in the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the Thome household in heartland America, they're excited
about the company he's keeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until someone mentions (his place on the all-time postseason
homer list), I never think of it,'' he said. ``Being a kid from
Peoria, I never have thought about having my name mentioned in that
group. That's what my dad said -- it's kind of neat to have my name
mentioned with those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Thome may not give himself many opportunities, but he certainly
doesn't waste the ones he does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
