<SLUG> BC-FBO-STEPHENSVILLEFANS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Stephenville fans shake their loaded cans 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STACY FEDUCIA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEPHENVILLE, Texas _ The caravan of can fans left for Brownwood
this morning, around the time they should have been leaving for
work.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee cans, paint cans, a steel trash can, an oversized oil
drum on a hand-cranked spit and about 80 freon bottles filled with
scores of half-inch ball bearings rumbled down U.S. 377, intent on
transforming hallowed Gordon Wood Stadium into a venerable den of
din.
</P>
<P>
   ``Representatives of the Can Fan Club will be at the gates at
10:30 a.m., just to make sure we get a good place in line to get
the right seating location,'' explained Dennis Hakes, a dairy
farmer who is credited with starting the freon-bottle caucus of the
Original Can Fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The philosophy on can shaking depends on who we're playing,''
Hakes continued. ``For a team like Brownwood, we'll do about 30
minutes of pregame shaking on the sidelines so the other team can
see that they're not only playing our team, they're also playing
the stands.''
</P>
<P>
   When state No. 1-ranked Stephenville (5-0, 2-0) travels to
Brownwood (4-1, 1-1) tonight for the 62nd meeting of one of the
state's oldest rivalries, they will be playing out a story that
should be written in CAPITAL LETTERS, a story set to a soundtrack
of Scud missiles, a story of a man and his can.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1989 _ four years before Stephenville won the first of
its three Class 4A state championships and one year after the
Yellow Jackets had broken a 23-game losing streak to Brownwood with
a 7-7 tie _ and Dr. Steve Steed was sitting at his kitchen table,
lamenting the fact that Yellow Jackets games ``sounded like a
graveyard.''
</P>
<P>
   Having finished a snack of peanuts, Steed's son, T.J., replaced
the lid on the can and ``started to act like a 12-year-old, jumping
up and down screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   More than earache was born.
</P>
<P>
   Steed carried a sackful of coffee cans filled with nuts, bolts
and nails to a pregame tailgate party and offered them with simple
instructions: ``Anybody who has a can has to bring it back and
bring two more.''
</P>
<P>
   His garage became an assembly line, manned by bankers, truck
drivers, accountants, doctors, workers from FMC Fluid Control. He'd
return from work to find a year's worth of coffee cans on his front
porch. The local newspaper began running a ``Can Fan of the Week''
feature.
</P>
<P>
   The effort culminated in a drive yielding more than 700 cans to
be assembled for the Yellow Jackets' 1989 first-round playoff game
against Belton, but the line shut down at 250 when they ran out of
nuts, bolts and nails.
</P>
<P>
   FMC Fluid Control came to the rescue, donating almost 1,000
pounds of ball bearings, a tradition that has continued to this
day. In fact, FMC Fluid Control also built The Big Can _ the
Stephenville equivalent of a touchdown bell that is shaken after
every score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Year after year, we bring it into the plant and retrofit it
and put new ball bearings and grease in it,'' explained plant
manager John Moore, who also donates a case of earplugs for every
game. ``We could have 7,000 people in the stands and about 75
percent of them will have cans. Everybody becomes a real can fan
over the course of their lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, more than others: This being Texas, it was only a small
time _ four years _ before someone like Hakes would stumble upon a
freon bottle at the dairy and fire up his welder and lose what
schoolteachers call ``the inside voice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The little cans didn't make enough noise for us,'' said Hakes,
who does upper-body workouts with the Yellow Jackets football
players in order to rattle his bottle with maximum effect. ``We
started with singles, then we would weld 'em end-to-end and that's
a double-barrel, and we have some that are four across and those
are quadruple barrels. They only last about a season, because if
you're real vigorous, you know, the metal becomes kind of fatigued
and it doesn't ring as good.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: It doesn't produce the audible quality of a column
of tanks rolling by, which is something opponents have to consider
when they schedule Stephenville.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take the loudest jam box you can find and get a sound
effects soundtrack and play it the entire practice. That's how we
did it,'' Richland coach Bob Briscoe said of the preparation for
his 1999 season opener. ``We didn't copy the sound of the freon
bottles, but we had bombs and stampedes and nuclear explosions. To
be quite honest, when we got out there at the game, we didn't
notice the noise, but we've never done that for anybody but them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some schools have managed to silence the cans, only because of
community noise-pollution policies. Even then, the Stephenville Can
Fans have made their presence known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Round Rock wouldn't let noisemakers inside their stadium last
year,'' said Steed, the chairman of the business systems department
at Tarleton State. ``So, in protest, we took canned goods and left
them at the gate for their school to donate to charity because
we're going to take our cans.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, they took an estimated 10,000 cans to Texas Stadium
for the Class 4A state championship game against LaMarque.
Tonight's planned can cacophony against Brownwood could well
approach that, if not in number, then in decibel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different games require different levels of can-fan support,''
Stephenville head coach Art Briles said. ``As the playoffs come up,
they gear up and turn loose a little more. I think it'll be a
playoff-type atmosphere tonight. To us, the cans are music to our
ears.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as they remember the earplugs.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
