<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DAMS-ART-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY BUILDING A COALITION, UTILITY RESOLVES PRICKLY ISSUES ON DAMS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Idaho., Mont., Wash., Ore.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map and
small text of dams in Northwest whose license expires soon is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For decades in the Pacific Northwest, hydroelectric dams have
generated as much conflict as electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Many environmentalists, sports fishermen and Indian groups have
opposed the relicensing of such dams and have succeeded in getting
a few small ones to be taken down.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities, of course, backed by many of the businesses and
farmers who depend on the cheap power, want the dams relicensed and
left alone. To avoid serious negotiations with their opponents,
they have often opted for one-year license extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, one utility, Avista Corp., formerly the Washington Water
Power Co., has found a middle ground. Over a four-year period, it
hammered out a compromise with a multitude of environmental
organizations, sports fishing groups, Indian tribes and federal and
state agencies. Now it has an agreement to relicense two of its
largest hydroelectric dams, avoiding the confrontation and lawsuits
that have held up the process for scores of other dams.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which would run for 45 years, calls for a
wide-ranging, $225 million restoration program for fish and
wildlife. Avista filed its application with the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission last February and expects approval by early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has encouraged such an approach, called
alternative licensing, in recent years in order to speed up the
relicensing process _ an important issue because 11,500 megawatts
of hydroelectric power are up for renewal before 2010.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of the cases now before the federal agency have
used forms of alternative licensing, and the agency has issued
about five new licenses to utilities that have chosen the method.
</P>
<P>
   The collaborative effort by Avista is one of the largest and
most ambitious so far. ``They did a great job using this process,''
said Ann Miles, the chief of licensing for the commission's West
Branch.
</P>
<P>
   Larry La Bolle, the general manager of hydropower development at
Avista, who led the company's effort, said that until the recent
compromise, relicensing was far more confrontational. Groups that
opposed relicensing typically put their demands on the table, but
the utility, seeing the demands as unreasonable would do little
negotiating. Instead it kept getting one-year extensions from the
energy agency, which are allowed under its rules. There was ``very
little incentive to settle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he decided that over their longer term there were good
reasons to settle.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, having a clear license will let the utility
operate much more nimbly and keep its focus on the fast-changing
environment of deregulation, he said. For another, delaying tactics
like the one-year extensions often deepen the frustration of the
opposition, which digs in and often escalates its demands.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional battles have led to prolonged stalemates and
enormous costs. A study by the Idaho National Engineering
Laboratory in 1997, for example, found that regulatory actions on
hydropower nationwide had cost about $7 billion since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the longest cases, involving the Cushman project in
Washington state, the city of Tacoma has been seeking a new license
for more than 20 years. It is still locked in disputes with various
groups including the federal agency, which has said that in order
to get a new license the city must agree to add measures to protect
fish. The city regards the measures as too costly.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid such a deadlock on the Avista dams, La Bolle brought
all the parties together to see if their issues could be resolved.
Much was at stake for the utility: The two dams, the Cabinet Gorge,
with a capacity of 231 megawatts on the Clark Fork River in
northern Idaho, and Noxon Rapids, with 466 megawatts of capacity in
western Montana, make up 40 percent of the utility's generating
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   As an incentive and a measure of good will, the utility offered
to spend money to help fish and wildlife and to improve water
quality _ even before a new license was issued.
</P>
<P>
   It also adopted what it called a ``living license'' approach.
Instead of having everything locked in for 45 years, both sides can
seek to amend the deal, provided they can agree on the terms.
</P>
<P>
   There were also some perks. The utility paid expenses like
travel for most of the 100 people and 39 organizations that
eventually joined in. They included federal and state agencies from
Idaho and Montana, five Indian tribes, conservation organizations
and property owners.
</P>
<P>
   La Bolle said the most difficult task was to persuade two key
federal agencies, the Forest Service and the Fish and Wildlife
Service, to enter the agreement. Those agencies can order a utility
to mitigate its impact on wildlife and the environment, and were
reluctant to give up that power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally we viewed it skeptically,'' said Larry Lockard, a
biologist with the Fish and Wildlife Service. ``We have some
regulatory authority to get what we want.'' However, he added, that
power was largely useless in the absence of agreements, which
sometimes cannot be reached for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company's agreement to early implementation of all the
mitigation programs was really a big carrot for us,'' he said.
About $1 million is already being spent on passages that will allow
fish to swim past the dams, and on improvements in water quality.
</P>
<P>
   Another group that played a large role was Trout Unlimited, a
conservation group based in Washington, D.C., that seeks to help
restore trout and salmon mostly in the Northwest, where most
hydroelectric dams are located.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a lot of guts for them to do it,'' said Steven Moyer,
vice president for conservation at Trout Unlimited, referring to
Avista and La Bolle. ``They brought in groups that could very
confrontational.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew they couldn't avoid a fight,'' Moyer added. ``What
they decided is to have the fight in a small room with all the
stakeholders rather than in the press and in the courts, which is
the usual way.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the agreement calls for a $94 million restoration
program for bull trout.
</P>
<P>
   He said other utilities, like the Portland General Electric Co.,
which wants to relicense a dam on the Deschutes River in Oregon,
were trying the concept but were not as far along as Avista was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the right way to this,'' he added. ``It's a model
effort.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
