<SLUG> BC-TEST-BAN-TREATY-850&AMP;ADD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY TEST BAN COULD IMPAIR NUCLEAR-ARMS SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TEST-BAN-REACT.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT35 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The scientists in charge of maintaining the safety
and reliability of the nation's nuclear arsenal said Thursday that
they might not be able to do their job without nuclear tests that
would be outlawed under a test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The directors of the country's three nuclear weapons
laboratories testified that while the nation's nuclear stockpile is
safe and reliable now, the future is less sure because of budget
uncertainties, aging weapons, shortages of trained experts and a
science-based substitute for actual nuclear tests that will not be
fully ready for five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The tempered testimony by the scientists on the consequences of
Senate ratification of an accord banning underground nuclear tests
contrasted with the upbeat defense of the pact by their boss,
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who declared that the treaty
would help halt the spread of nuclear weapons, improve national
security and make Americans ``more safe in an uncertain world.''
</P>
<P>
   The scientists took pains to qualify each of those assertions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether on balance the effect of a test ban to retard
proliferation and further development of nuclear weapons is worth a
similar penalty on the U.S. nuclear arsenal is the real crux of the
dilemma,'' C. Paul Robinson, director of Sandia National
Laboratories in New Mexico, told the Senate Armed Services
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Since the United States suspended underground nuclear testing in
1992, it has relied on sophisticated computer models and
non-nuclear explosive tests to certify annually that the stockpile
is safe and reliable. Under a safeguard attached to the treaty, the
directors' failure to certify the stockpile would be grounds for
the United States to withdraw from the pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident in the stockpile today,'' said John C.
Browne, director of the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New
Mexico. ``The issue is whether we will have the people, the
capabilities and the national commitment to maintain this
confidence in the future when we expect to see more significant
changes in the weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The directors have reason for concern. The House this year cut
$600 million from the administration's $4.5 billion request for the
scientific testing regime, called the Stockpile Stewardship
Program. Senators prevailed to restore almost all the funding.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations of mismanagement and spying at the labs, new
mandatory lie-detector tests and restrictions on scientific
exchanges have hurt efforts to recruit new specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before long our nuclear-test veterans will be gone,'' said C.
Bruce Tarter, director of the Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory in California. ``Events over the past year are making it
more difficult to recruit and retain top-notch talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarter summed up the directors' overall assessment of the
stewardship program: ``It is an excellent bet, but it is not a sure
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The scientists' reservations go to the heart of doubts harbored
by Senate Republicans, who oppose the treaty and fear that it would
permanently limit America's ability to test and modernize its
nuclear weapons, while states like North Korea and Iraq cheated and
conducted low-level tests to help build crude nuclear bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United States scrupulously restricts itself to
zero-yield while other nations may conduct experiments up to the
threshold of international detectability, we will be at an
intolerable disadvantage,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., who heads the Armed Services Committee
and opposes the treaty, seized on the conflicting opinions,
reminding Richardson that the scientists' views ``are in many
respects contradictory of the remarks you had.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters concede that they do not have the 67 votes needed to
ratify the treaty. After hounding Republicans for months to bring
the treaty to a vote, Democrats are now trying to negotiate a
graceful way out.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate inched closer to breaking an impasse on a deal to
postpone a vote scheduled for next Tuesday or Wednesday as
Republicans weighed new concessions from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to meet one Republican demand, the White House formally
requested that Senate Republicans withdraw the treaty. In a
telephone interview, Sandy Berger, Clinton's national security
adviser, said that ``the treaty is so important and time is so
short for consideration that we should postpone the vote in order
to have full and thorough deliberations.''
</P>
<P>
   To address Republican fears that Democrats would wield the
treaty as a campaign issue next year, Daschle proposed that any
formal consideration of the accord would require prior approval of
Daschle and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   But four conservatives _ Sens. Tim Hutchinson of Arkansas, James
Inhofe of Oklahoma, Robert Smith of New Hampshire and Jeff Sessions
of Alabama _ vowed to block any attempt to cancel next week's vote.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the concessions were unlikely to avert a floor debate,
which Lott said would begin on Friday with 10 to 20 senators
speaking on the treaty.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, several Democratic and Republican senators
continued to negotiate a way to put off a near-certain defeat of
the treaty that supporters and critics said could deal the United
States a political and diplomatic embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Warner expressed confidence that political and procedural
hurdles could be surmounted. He joined a growing number of
Republicans seeking to postpone a vote, a group that includes Sens.
Pete Domenici of New Mexico, Ted Stevens of Alaska, Gordon Smith of
Oregon, Olympia Snowe of Maine, Fred Thompson of Tennessee and
Craig Thomas of Wyoming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
