<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-LINEUP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OATES TRIES TO BEEF UP RANGERS' LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Manager Johnny Oates' desperate search for offense
resulted in a massive overhaul of the Texas Rangers' lineup for
Game 2 of this Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton, who hit leadoff only twice this season,
occupied the top spot in the order Thursday night, and left fielder
Rusty Greer _ the Rangers' primary No. 3 hitter _ moved up a spot
with catcher Ivan Rodriguez batting third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great lineup,'' Oates said. ``I spent a lot of
time (Wednesday) night thinking about it. Rusty has been drawing a
lot of walks, and Clayton has had a pretty good second half against
left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, those two guys at the top can get on for our Nos. 3
and 4 hitters. I think it'll give us a chance to get out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates also benched center fielder Tom Goodwin, a left-handed
hitter, and started reserve outfielder Roberto Kelly against
Yankees left-hander Andy Pettitte. Kelly, a right-handed batter,
entered Thursday night's game hitting .105 (2-for-19) for his
career against Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about it is his career numbers against left-handers
are better than anybody I've got,'' Oates said. ``I think Kelly
gives us a chance to put a charge in one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly hit .358 this season against left-handers and owns a .314
average against lefties for his career, but the move did not come
without a sacrifice defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give up some range, but I need offense,'' Oates said.
``I'm looking for a run right now. There's no such thing as a 0-0
tie in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore remained in the lineup and batted
ninth despite hitting .163 this season against left-handers. Oates
went with McLemore instead of reserve infielder Luis Alicea because
Oates preferred a ``healthy second baseman hitting ninth at 100
percent as opposed to Alicea, who is 90 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicea hit .290 this season against left-handers, but his right
calf remains tender from a muscle pull suffered Sept. 13 at Kansas
City's Kauffman Stadium. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
