<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0012 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-PRIZE-2TAKES-     10-07 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-PRIZE-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL FUNDS FOR SPECIAL CUSTOMERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (Eds: The (star) word in online company should be replaced with the
symbol) 
(af) 
 By DANIEL AKST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who says gambling doesn't pay?
</P>
<P>
   The casino metaphor for investing is pretty tired, but in mutual
funds, there is yet another way in which the Street is emulating
the Strip: by granting exclusive access to specialized products as
a way to attract new business.
</P>
<P>
   In Las Vegas and other gambling centers, high rollers enjoy free
food, drink and accommodations, and even people like me find rooms
and restaurants surprisingly affordable. Of course, gaming losses
subsidize all this, but because I don't bet, I don't care.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street seems to be going the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Sign up for an online stock trading account with E(star)Trade,
for example, and you get access to what it calls the lowest-cost
technology-oriented index fund available. Intended to track the
Goldman Sachs Technology Index, this no-load fund has a relatively
modest expense ratio (for a technology fund, at least) of 0.85
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did this because it's the kind of fund our customers
want,'' said Joe Van Remortel, vice president of E(star)Trade Asset
Management, which develops mutual funds for its parent.
E(star)Trade is not ready to disclose figures, but Van Remortel
said the response had exceeded expectations. ``The customers love
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   E(star)Trade customers can expect further such offerings. Van
Remortel said the company had two new index funds in registration
with the Securities and Exchange Commission; like the technology
fund, both will be open only to E(star)Trade customers. One is an
electronic commerce fund, and the other is a broad-based
international fund. ``We'll probably do some more down the road,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the Web, Stockjungle.com, an investment-oriented
Web site, plans to offer its customers an apparently unique index
fund linked to the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500. The fund will charge
investors nothing _ no loads, management fees or expenses of any
kind, although it does have a 2 percent redemption fee for shares
held less than 120 days.
</P>
<P>
   Like the E(star)Trade technology fund, Stockjungle.com's S&AMP;P 500
index fund will provide reports, statements and so forth only
electronically, saving the expenses of printing and mailing.
</P>
<P>
   And Waterhouse Securities, another discount broker, offers its
customers, on an exclusive basis, the no-load Waterhouse Dow 30
fund. It aims to match the total return of the Dow Jones industrial
average _ and is one of only two such funds tracked by Morningstar
Inc., the Chicago financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   The Waterhouse Dow 30, of course, joins more than 8,500 mutual
funds of every stripe that Waterhouse offers from fund families
like Fidelity Investments, the Vanguard Group and Janus.
</P>
<P>
   When I first heard about these developments, I dismissed them as
curiosities. But the more I thought about them, the more they
seemed harbingers of something much bigger _ a trend toward the
commodification of mutual funds. Leaving aside the unusual nature
of these funds, their companies are granting access to a fund just
to sell you something else. It is similar to a supermarket selling
milk as a loss leader.
</P>
<P>
   If the idea catches on in mutual funds, it could change
radically how Americans think about investing _ not to mention how
the fund industry is structured.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Guillette, a consultant with Cerulli Associates, a
financial services consulting firm in Boston, considers the
funds-as-premiums idea as more an unusual marketing ploy than a
trend. Instead he points to a very different development: the
efforts of some mutual fund families to go upmarket.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Putnam Investments, for instance, has formed a partnership with
the Thomas H. Lee Co., a private equity investment firm, to offer a
range of financial products to affluent investors, perhaps
including a venture capital fund. Such vehicles are a far cry from
index investing.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Guillette acknowledges that it is becoming harder
for many funds to differentiate themselves. As a result, somebody
decides to use them as marketing giveaways. ``In a world that's
increasingly commodified,'' he said, ``that's how you draw
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the world of mutual funds wants to be perceived in
much the same way as Garrison Keillor's Lake Wobegon, where ``all
the children are above average.'' Judging from long-term
performance data, however, the opposite must be true. Over the long
haul, most fund managers cannot beat the market averages, and those
that do so for a while tend to drop back into the pack eventually.
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence that past performance is of little use in
predicting the future, suggesting that, unless you're clairvoyant,
it doesn't much matter which funds you select.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, your decisions about asset allocation are almost
always going to be more important to your performance than which
aggressive growth mid-cap mutual fund you choose.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there is good reason to treat mutual funds as
commodities: Once you decide how much to invest in the various
asset classes, you can buy the cheapest versions and hang on. This
isn't new.
</P>
<P>
   People like John C. Bogle, the former chief of Vanguard, have
suggested it for years, and there are signs that this Gospel of the
Sensible Investor is gaining adherents, judging from the growth of
index funds _ the ultimate in commodified funds _ in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   And is the idea of fund premiums really so different from that
of the American AAdvantage Mileage funds, which reward investors
with frequent-flier miles as well as investment returns? The funds'
flavors include stocks, bonds and money markets.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about the Aid Association for Lutherans? It offers a
family of mutual funds available exclusively to members of the
organization, although investors get the benefit of knowing that
their money is being plowed into companies meeting certain
social-responsibility standards.
</P>
<P>
   If the premiums idea catches on, the current flow of fund
advertisements, promoting investment performance and the
personalities running the money, could dry up, and the many
publications devoted to mutual fund rankings could disappear.
</P>
<P>
   The industry might instead emphasize partnerships with firms
that have access to large, loyal groups of members or customers.
Who will get the chance to sell mutual funds to the customers of
the Wal-Mart? To volunteer firefighters? To former Girl Scouts?
</P>
<P>
   AARP, the pick of the litter when it comes to affinity marketing
by virtue of its size and the wealth of its membership, offers
mutual funds managed by Scudder Kemper Investments. And the United
Services Automobile Association, widely known as USAA, seems to
have the inside track in providing mutual funds, as well as a host
of other financial services, to former members of the armed forces
and their families. But the company's funds are also open to
investors who haven't had anything to do with the military.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see all this going further.
</P>
<P>
   Will your credit union offer access to certain mutual funds when
you open an account? Will buying a Ford or Toyota open the door to
an index fund that charges no expenses whatsoever? Or, conversely,
will you get a Ford or Toyota by investing enough money in a given
fund? How about funds open only to the fraternal members of the
Knights of Pythias? Or current and former inmates of the federal
penitentiary system? The possibilities are mind-boggling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0015 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-STRATEGY-2TAK     10-07 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-STRATEGY-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE FUND MANAGERS IRRELEVANT? AN 18TH-CENTURY THEORY SUGGESTS NOT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Mass.)   (af)  
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The debate over index funds has been exceedingly lopsided.
Reason and common sense have been almost completely on the side of
those who advocate investing all of a portfolio in index funds.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics are familiar: Only a very small percentage of
actively managed stock funds perform as well as the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index _ just 6 percent, for example, over the last
five years (although they've had more success in the last two
quarters).
</P>
<P>
   And many people try to explain away those few funds that have
beaten the market by saying they have done so by chance alone.
After all, if several thousand monkeys threw darts at the stock
pages of the newspaper, some of them would beat the market, too.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is about to become a lot less lopsided. A new paper,
as yet unpublished, reveals that the case for indexing an entire
portfolio _ tying all of it to funds that track major market
indexes _ is a lot weaker than many people have thought.
</P>
<P>
   The study, titled ``Should Investors Avoid All Actively Managed
Mutual Funds? A Study in Bayesian Performance Evaluation,'' was
written by Klaas Baks, Andrew Metrick and Jessica Wachter. Metrick
is an assistant professor of finance at the Wharton School at the
University of Pennsylvania, and Baks and Ms. Wachter are graduate
students in economics at Brown University and Harvard,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is waist-high in statistics, the paper probably won't
prompt a stampede into actively managed mutual funds. But it should
turn upside down a lot of people's thinking about indexing.
</P>
<P>
   The first point that these academics make, if not particularly
original, is nevertheless one that is not often appreciated: Just
because most portfolio managers fail to beat the market
consistently doesn't mean that none do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big deal,'' an indexing absolutist might say. ``Even if the
rare money manager has the stock-picking prowess necessary to beat
the index, it doesn't alter the fact that he is in the extreme
minority, and that rational investors therefore ought to put their
whole portfolio into index funds.''
</P>
<P>
   That, according to the new paper, is precisely where the
absolutists are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The study's key assertion is that once it is conceded that even
a very small percentage of managers have the ability to beat the
market, it becomes irrational not to invest a significant portion
of an equity portfolio in their funds that have done so, on a
risk-adjusted basis, by the greatest amounts over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   The study relies on a type of statistical analysis pioneered by
the Rev. Thomas Bayes, an 18th century mathematician, whose theory
explains how probabilities should be updated in light of new
information.
</P>
<P>
   A nonfinancial example illustrates how a Bayesian analysis
works. Imagine that 10 percent of a coin dealer's inventory of
identical-looking coins are special _ they are weighted so that
when you toss them, they come up heads three-quarters of the time,
instead of just half. Suppose, too, that before buying a coin, you
are allowed to flip it to determine whether it is one of the trick
coins.
</P>
<P>
   But before flipping the first coin, you know that there's a 10
percent probability that it's one of the trick ones. That
probability will grow slightly after the first flip comes up heads
_ to 14.3 percent, according to the Bayes theorem. The probability
will continue to grow after each successive flip that comes up
heads. And though that probability will never reach 100 percent,
after enough flips, the majority of which come up heads, it becomes
a better than 50-50 proposition that the coin you're flipping is
one of the trick coins.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers used a similar process to measure the
probabilities that fund managers of 1,437 actively managed United
States diversified equity funds would beat benchmarks in the
future. It is a good analogy, because a superior fund manager won't
necessarily beat his or her benchmark all the time, just most of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of flipping coins, of course, the researchers looked at
a manager's performances in successive months relative to that of
the relevant benchmarks. And instead of the 10 percent initial
probability, used in the trick-coin example, the researchers used a
range of extremely conservative assumptions _ for example, that
just 1 in 5,000 portfolio managers had the ability to outperform a
benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this initial assumption gives you the base upon which
the subsequent probability data rest. In the coin example, it's a
given, but in looking at manager ability, the authors started with
extremely conservative probabilities in order to make a point.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the analogy pretty much holds up. The researchers
continually updated the probability that a given manager had the
ability to beat his or benchmark in light of his performance in
period after period. Even assuming that just two-hundredths of 1
percent of all fund managers had the talent to regularly beat the
market, it turns out that there were a few managers who performed
well enough to justify investing in their funds.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, though the study's extensive data base began in
1963, it ended in 1996. And its methodology is so complex that we
cannot update the data easily ourselves, so we don't know which of
today's fund managers have the highest probability of being market
beaters.
</P>
<P>
   But as of the end of 1996, and under the assumption that 1 in
5,000 can outperform, just five such managers, or teams, had funds
that beat their benchmarks by wide-enough margins to make them
worth betting on.
</P>
<P>
   Only one manager or team that made this cut through 1996 is
still managing the same fund: Ralph Wanger and Charles P. McQuiad
of the Acorn Fund, although Terance M. Hogan, who was also a
co-manager at the time, has left the fund. Those who are no longer
managing the funds cited in the study are Stephen A. Lieber of the
Evergreen Fund, Charles Albers of Guardian Park Avenue, Shelby
Davis of Davis New York Venture and Robert A. Lange of Lindner
Growth.
</P>
<P>
   As in the coin example, of course, we will never know with
certainty that these few select managers really have market-beating
ability _ no matter how many years they have been managing money
and by how much they have outperformed the market. But the
probabilities make it irrational not to bet on them, the study
argues.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding how much to invest with a particular manager depends,
in part, on the margin by which he has beaten the index.
</P>
<P>
   Before making that choice, consider what happens if you pick a
manager who, despite a stellar track record, turns out to be unable
to beat a relevant index going forward. It is safe to assume that
his stock picks will be no better or worse than random.
</P>
<P>
   This means that his performance over time should match the
market's before expenses, and lag behind it by an average of one
and a half percentage points a year after expenses and transaction
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that with the potential advantage of investing with a
manager who can beat the market by three percentage points or more
a year. To simplify a large part of the authors' study, so long as
there is greater than a 1-in-3 chance that she can do so, it makes
sense to invest with her rather than with an index fund.
</P>
<P>
   The authors, however, did not take taxes into account, so it is
impossible to know whether any managers would ``survive'' their
Bayesian analysis after accounting for the tax implications of
trading. So it makes sense to use actively managed funds only for
your tax-deferred accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But how much of those tax-deferred assets should you invest with
the best fund managers? It depends on how pessimistic you are about
the probability that managers, in general, have the ability to beat
their benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
   If you assume, for example, that only 1 in 5,000 fund managers
can do so, you should invest at least two-thirds of your equity
portfolio in the long-term, market-beating, actively managed
winners, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   If you assume that the ratio is 1 in 1,000, the case in favor of
investing in the very top actively managed funds becomes so
compelling that you should put all your equity position in them.
Unfortunately, there's not enough statistical data to decide which
assumption is more valid.
</P>
<P>
   Score one, finally, for active fund management. But remember
that this good news applies only to a very few managers _ those who
can pass the rigorous testing, and who in most cases have been
managing for a long time. Indeed, the authors found that it makes
no sense to invest in the vast majority of actively managed funds. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of The Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Annandale, Va. His column on investment
strategies appears every other week. E-mail:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
