<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ISSUES INJUNCTION IN TEXAS FOOTBALL PRAYER CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EDWARD HEGSTROM 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A federal judge issued an order Thursday allowing the
prayers to continue before Santa Fe High School home football games
through the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Sim Lake's order thrilled religious
activists in the small school district south of Houston, though it
also appeared to set the stage for a continuing controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ecstatic,`` said Marian Ward, 17, the Santa Fe student who
has been selected to lead the prayers. ``It's another step in the
right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is happy, though. Ward confirmed that civil rights
groups plan to protest at the Indians' game Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy stems from a lawsuit filed in 1995 on behalf of
two families with students in Santa Fe schools _ one Mormon and one
Catholic _ who objected to the prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans
ruled that nonsectarian prayer could be used in solemn events, such
as graduations at Santa Fe High School, but not at such events as
football games.
</P>
<P>
   Ward's family then filed another lawsuit last month, claiming
that prohibiting Ward from praying before the game constituted a
violation of her constitutional right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Lake on Thursday issued a preliminary injunction to allow the
prayers through the end of the season, extending the temporary
restraining order he issued last month.
</P>
<P>
   A trial on the issue has not been set.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she has become sort of a hero to people of faith in
Santa Fe, Ward replied, ``It's flattering, but this is not really
about me. It's about freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
