A0041 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS08-COX     10-07 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' Tobeck has handful vs. Saints' defense
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons center Robbie Tobeck could end up with a big
headache Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   During most games, he has nobody lined up over him and spends a
lot of time helping guards double-team opposing tackles.
</P>
<P>
   But the Saints often play a defense with players lined up
opposite the center and both guards. Tobeck will face La'Roi
Glover, a 6-foot-2, 285-pounder, who is tied for the team lead with
2 1/2 sacks. The Falcons tried to claim him off waivers when the
Raiders released him in 1997. Last season, Glover was a first
alternate to the Pro Bowl after leading the Saints with 10 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their nose tackle is pretty good; Robbie is going to have his
hands full,'' Falcons offensive line coach Art Shell said. ``And
the `Bear' (defense) puts you in a lot of single-block situations,
makes it hard to double guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobeck, who makes the line calls, is more concerned with the
entire unit. The Falcons line has been better in pass protection
than last season in giving up 10 sacks so far. But run blocking is
another story.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are averaging 71.5 yards rushing a game, next to
last in the NFL. The season-ending right knee injury to All-Pro
back Jamal Anderson has been the big loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to take anything away from our other backs, but Jamal made
some things happen,'' Shell said. ``Functionally, we've been OK in
pass protection, but our concern is run blocking. It's an attitude.
You've got to want to do it. Talking doesn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves replaced Calvin Collins before the season with
second-year player Bob Hallen. Hallen and Collins are alternating
at left guard, and starting right guard Gene Williams and reserve
Greg Bishop also are alternating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might make a call where I want a guy to do one thing and,
not being familiar with how we do things, a guy might do something
different,'' Tobeck said. ``We're talking all the time and getting
those things ironed out.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Saints line up with two tackles and two ends, they
blitz often. They lead the NFL with an average of five sacks per
game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Falcons' first concern is getting a running game
going, no matter who is at running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the running game, we're not using the techniques we used
last year,'' Tobeck said. ``We're not coming off the ball the same;
our steps are not the same; we're not doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
