<HEADER>
A0045 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-FENPHEN-SUIT-2TAKES-N     10-07 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FENPHEN-SUIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKER OF DIET PILL AGREES TO PAY $3.75 BILLION TO SETTLE LIABILITY
CASE
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Home Products Corp. agreed on Thursday to pay $3.75
billion to thousands of individuals who contend they were injured
by taking the popular diet pill combination fen-phen.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement _ one of the largest ever in a product
liability case _ people who used one of the diet drugs for 60 days
or less would be eligible for $30 to $60 prescription refunds,
while those who have a heart valve injury could receive as much
$1.5 million. While executives and industry analysts hailed the
agreement, which was widely expected, it does not shield American
Home Products from all fen-phen liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Some six million people took the diet drugs Pondomin, American
Home Products' brand name for fenfluramine, the ``fen'' in
fen-phen, and Redux, a similar drug. The drugs were hailed earlier
in the decade as miracle pills for obesity, as an alternative to
pure diet and exercise. Diet centers actively promoted the pills to
the obese and even people who wanted to lose a few pounds. In 1996,
doctors wrote 18 million prescriptions for the two drugs. But in
September 1997, the company removed the drugs from the market at
the request of the Food and Drug Administration after studies
linked them to heart valve damage.
</P>
<P>
   The two drugs, Pondimin and Redux, depressed appetite, while the
other drug in the combination, phentermine, increased the rate at
which calories are burned. Doctors at the Mayo Clinic reported that
the drugs may cause defects in the aortic or mitral valves.
</P>
<P>
   Since the drugs were pulled off the market, some 6,500 lawsuits,
encompassing 11,000 people, have been filed. Thursday's settlement
covers all of the six million who took fen-phen, but only those who
are found to have heart valve damage can collect an injury award.
The agreement, which must be approved by a federal judge, also has
some strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   It does not cover the 100 claims the company's faces from people
who contend fen-phen gave them primary pulmonary hypertension, an
often fatal lung illness. And if too many people _ a number
American Home Products did not define on Thursday _ choose to drop
out of the settlement, and pursue an individual lawsuit, the
company could scrap the agreement. Lawyers for fen-phen users said
on Thursday that was an unlikely outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made this settlement flexible so that more people will
participate in it,'' said Stanley Chesley, a partner with Waite,
Schneider, Bayless &AMP; Chesley in Cincinnati, one of the lead
plaintiff lawyers. ``The way this settlement is set up, the
consumers have no disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   For American Home Products, the settlement is the latest in a
series of moves over the last three months intended to resolve
long-standing problems.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the company agreed to pay $54 million to settle claims
of women who said they were not adequately warned about the side
effects of the company's Norplant birth control device. Just three
days ago, American Home Products announced that it would
restructure its agricultural division, slicing 700 positions from
the unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about the able efforts of our attorneys to bring
about the settlement,'' said John R. Stafford, chief executive
officer of American Home Products. ``The consumers of ours, who may
have been injured, the ones who used fen-phen for the long term,
which is a small percentage, the settlement gives them a quick and
fair resolution. I feel good about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiff lawyers who negotiated the settlement said the
agreement was especially comprehensive. The settlement, valued at
$3.75 billion before inflation, will be divided into two funds. One
fund, valued at $1 billion, will pay for drug refunds and medical
screening costs.
</P>
<P>
   The second fund, valued at $2.55 billion, will pay personal
injury claims, with awards ranging from $125,000 to $1.5 million.
The remaining $200 million from the $3.75 billion total has been
set aside for legal fees of medical monitoring claims.
</P>
<P>
   The fund will remain open for up to 16 years, leaving American
Home Products liable for a higher payout. Plaintiff lawyers
calculated on Thursday that with interest, American Home Products
could pay as much as $4.83 billion. That would put fen-phen as one
of the highest product injury settlements ever, dwarfing the $3.2
billion that Dow Corning paid last year to settle its silicone
breast implant claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with the $4 billion settlement, you have to say that
American Home Products pulled off a good settlement,'' said David
Saks, a managing director at Gruntal &AMP; Co. ``Some of the early
estimates were everywhere from $3 billion to $10 billion. The
company was stuck in a quicksand of uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   The fen-phen settlement also represents a bit of unusual legal
maneuvering. It is rare for a national class-action settlement to
allow participants to ``opt out,'' and pursue an individual case,
at three points during the course of litigation. Under the fen-phen
settlement, consumers can opt-out in the beginning, or when they
discover they have a heart value regurgitation during the screening
process.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Consumers can also drop out when they discover the amount of
their personal claim. When the outlines of the settlement began to
emerge three weeks ago, analysts expressed concern that American
Home Products was being too lenient. Consumers would still pursue
litigation, leaving the company to face a large amount of
liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the fen-phen settlement is not as lenient as first feared.
Consumers can drop out at three points, but if they do so at the
final two stages _ the screening process and the payout _ they
cannot seek punitive damages against American Home Products in an
individual case.
</P>
<P>
   While many plaintiff lawyers are thrilled with the settlement,
others are annoyed at some of its details. For consumers to receive
money from the personal injury fund, they must suffer heart valve
regurgitation that is measurable by a Food and Drug Administration
scale.
</P>
<P>
   People who seek money from the monitoring fund and have not used
fen-phen for more than 60 days can qualify for a refund in their
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The payments are not going to be large enough to cover medical
expenses for a large number of people,'' said Ed Blizzard, a
Houston attorney who represents fen-phen users. ``A large number of
people only receive money for what they paid for the drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, like other personal injury claims, provides a
sum for attorneys' fees. If the settlement is approved by the
court, some $429 million _ $200 million from the monitoring fund
and $229 million included in the personal injury fund. Chesley said
that he expected about 100 attorneys to collect fees.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products said on Thursday that it would take a
$3.92 billion after-tax charge against third-quarter earnings to
pay for the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were optimistic that the company's stock would increase
now that it had moved aggressively to put the fen-phen liabilities
behind it. Shares of American Home Product rose $3.5625, or 7.8
percent, Thursday to close at $48.6875.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
