<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SEWERS _  &LR; ``Rats,'' shouts Apollo Rojas from down the manhole near
the corner of Taylor and Eddy streets in the Tenderloin. ``A whole
nest of them.'' ``Rats,'' repeats Gene Chruszcz with a look of mock
horror, enjoying the miserable expression on my face. Chruszcz
(pronounced ``cruise''), 38, and Rojas, 53, are San Francisco's
only two full-time sewer inspectors. They have been amusing
themselves since the early morning preparing me for my first (and
last) foray into the city's underbelly. Final installment of
`Someone's Gotta Do It' series. By David Lazarus
</P>
