<SLUG> BC-MACROMEDIA-MACROMEDIA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Macromedia Picks Up Andromedia, Sets Shockwave Loose  &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Macromedia Inc., a mainstay of San Francisco's Multimedia Gulch,
yesterday agreed to buy privately held Andromedia for about $257
million in stock. Macromedia also said it plans to spin off its
online entertainment unit shockwave.com as an independent company.
<P>
   With the Andromedia acquisition, Macromedia hopes to move up the
e-commerce food chain by providing software that not only allows
clients to design Web sites, but also analyze the shopping habits
of consumers who visit those sites.
</P>
<P>
   Macromedia said that by melding its graphically rich Web
publishing applications with Andromedia's personalization and
customer profiling software, corporate clients will be able to
accurately measure the effectiveness of their Web sites and make
rapid design changes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Andromedia's software figures out whether a
company's Web site is attracting new or repeat visitors, which
promotions are driving users to the site, and which content
visitors are clicking on the most. Brian Allum, Macromedia's chief
operating officer, said that information can then be fed back to
the design team, which who  &LR; can ``build a Web site that provides a
higher return on investment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good strategic fit for Macromedia,'' said Hany Nada,
an analyst with U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray. ``It allows them to go
from being just a tools company to an Internet infrastructure
player, which promises a higher value in the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, however, wary investors pummeled the stock.
Macromedia shares fell $3.53, or more than 6 percent, to $51.44
yesterday. Still, the stock has tripled in value over the past
year. Nada said investors had several concerns, including the risks
associated with integrating Macromedia's applications with
Andromedia's. Software companies often run into technical and
financial trouble when they try to tie together product sets.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street also balked at Andromedia's high price tag, and the
negative impact the sale would have on Macromedias earning's over
the next several quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Andromedia, also based in San Francisco, was losing about $4.5
million per quarter, according to analysts. The company posted
revenue of $2.6 million in the six months ended June 30. Macromedia
officials said that all 125 employees at Andromedia would remain in
their jobs. Andromedia's chief executive Kent Godfrey will head up
business development and partnerships at Macromedia.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts still see plenty of upside in the deal. Specifically,
Macromedia will inherit a seasoned sales force that is accustomed
to knocking on the doors of Fortune 1,000 companies. Andromedia's
software, which typically costs tens of thousands of dollars, is
used by such companies as Audi, Intuit and Levi Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Macromedia wants to become more of an enterprise-type company,
and they needed a strong direct sales force to do that,'' said Greg
Vogel, an analyst with Banc of America Securities.
</P>
<P>
   This new corporate focus also means that Macromedia's
consumer-centric shockwave.com unit no longer meshes with the
company's mission. Macromedia said it has hired investment bank
Robertson Stephens to consider financial options for the company,
including a possible public offering early next year. The
shockwave.com site was launched in August as an entertainment
destination with downloadable music, games and other content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shockwave is a different business,'' said Macromedia chief
executive Rob Burgesss in an interview yesterday. ``It's an
entertainment company and we are a software company. You need to
run those two things as separate operations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
