<SLUG> BC-FBC-QUINCYCARTER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carter: Nothing wrong with his 4-0
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ It was first uttered in whispers early in the
season. But after Georgia's narrow escape against LSU on Saturday,
people were saying it out loud:
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong with Quincy Carter?''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs quarterback, touted in preseason reports as a
Heisman Trophy candidate, has not lived up to that billing in four
games. While fellow Heisman candidates Joe Hamilton of Georgia Tech
and Drew Brees of Purdue have been lighting it up statistically,
Carter has been, well, average.
</P>
<P>
   But the sophomore is quick to mention he has one thing neither
of those quarterbacks has _ an undefeated record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to stay in the (Heisman) race, if I was even in the
race as a sophomore. But as long as I'm 4-0 and we're winning, who
cares about that?'' Carter said. ``I think about Alabama and Jay
Barker, he was a winner. And (Tennessee's) Tee Martin was a winner
last year. As long as I'm labeled as a winner after the season,
I'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter puts that undefeated record, and his reputation, on the
line when the 10th-ranked Bulldogs visit No. 6 Tennessee on
Saturday night in a nationally televised game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big game for Quincy,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan
said. ``He's 0-3 against the `Big Three' (Tennessee, Florida and
Georgia Tech). As the starting quarterback at Georgia, that's what
you're judged by. We didn't give him any help last year (against
Tennessee). Hopefully, we can help him out Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's numbers are respectable. He has completed 56 percent of
his passes (77 of 137) for 900 yards, six touchdowns and just one
interception. He is third in the SEC in passing average (225 yards
per game) and total offense (248.8-yard average), and seventh in
passing efficiency. Carter has thrown 129 passes without an
interception.
</P>
<P>
   Carter has been hurt by the youth surrounding him. The Bulldogs
had to replace their top four receivers, two tackles and leading
rusher from last season, and the inexperience has been evident.
Unofficially, receivers have dropped two dozen passes, including 11
in one game. If they had held on to half of those, Carter's
completion percentage would be 65 and he would have untold
additional yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quincy's fine,'' Donnan said. ``He's done a good job as far as
being the guy everybody looks up to, being a leader. But we can't
just be the `Quincy Carter Show' and do what we have to do to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   That was evident against LSU on Saturday. Georgia relied more on
running back Jasper Sanks as the game wore on. The sophomore got 17
of his 27 carries in the second half and finished with 156 yards
rushing in the Bulldogs' 23-22 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia hopes to employ a similar strategy against the
defensive-minded Vols.
</P>
<P>
   ``My leadership ability is what we've got to have now,'' Carter
said. ``Jasper's going to carry us as long as we let him.
Hopefully, our passing game will come along.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Sanks' emergence, Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer
indicated Carter is the focus of his defensive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Carter is) a very fine athlete but also a very fine
quarterback. I think sometimes you need to distinguish the two,''
Fulmer said. ``We've got to pressure him and hope to make him throw
before he's ready to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers neutralized Carter last year by coming after him
with a series of blitz packages. Carter completed 14 of 37 passes
for 195 yards and threw three interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   But those who huddle with Carter remain confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way Quincy's playing,'' junior tackle Jonas
Jennings said. ``He's not getting caught up in the hype.
</P>
<P>
   Quincy Carter's a sophomore; he's got two more years to win the
Heisman. He knows it's all about winning games.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
