<SLUG> BC-CIRCUS-BAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE MAY BAN PERFORMING CIRCUS ANIMALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KRISTIN DIZON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Mayor Paul Schell wants to ban circus animals from
performing in Seattle, a move that would put the city at the
forefront of a national movement aimed at stopping the use of
exotic animals as entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Should the City Council agree, Seattle would be the largest city
in the country to outlaw circus animal performances.
</P>
<P>
   Schell said the issue was raised during his campaign for mayor
two years ago and that after dealing with other priorities, he's
ready for Seattle to set an example.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor plans to forward an ordinance to the City Council next
month after the general election.
</P>
<P>
   His proposed legislation, still in draft form, would ban either
the display of exotic and wild animals in city owned and operated
facilities, or entirely within city limits. Schell's advisers are
currently hammering out the scope and specifics of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you really limit it on private property and say, nowhere
in the city of Seattle can you do this?'' said Lisa Fitzhugh,
special assistant to the mayor. ``That's the debate _ how far can
we go?''
</P>
<P>
   National groups such as the Humane Society of the United States
and People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA) contend that
at best, circuses force wild animals into performing unnatural
tricks and living on the road. At worst, the animals are subjected
to abuse and cruelty, PETA and others say..
</P>
<P>
   They also cast exotic animals as a threat to public safety,
citing the deaths of 45 people killed since 1990 by captive
elephants alone.
</P>
<P>
   Circus operators deny such charges and say they treat their
animals well and adhere to the federal Animal Welfare Act, as well
as numerous state and local laws. They say there is no need for a
ban, which will deprive their audience of cherished entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The Ringling Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus as well as
Circus Gatti performed in Seattle this year. Ringling Brothers was
in town last month at Seattle Center's KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's proposed ban would prohibit the exhibition, act or
performance of eight broad categories of animals such as primates,
large cats, bears, elephants and non-domesticated hoofed mammals
such as zebras.
</P>
<P>
   It also would exempt reptiles, birds, dogs and cats, according
to Fitzhugh. Additionally, the wording will be crafted so that the
Woodland Park Zoo would not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Circuses are not the only wild animal displays that would be
affected, though they are the ban's main target. Exotic animals in
traveling petting zoos and those featured at photo opportunities in
malls or at fairs could be prohibited as well.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Canadian cities including Vancouver B.C., already
prohibit circus animal entertainment, and a handful of smaller
American cities have banned such performances, including Hollywood,
Fla., Takoma Park, Md., and Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, a bill, H.R. 2929 was introduced in Congress two
weeks ago that would prevent the use of elephants in traveling
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens for Cruelty-Free Entertainment, a local volunteer
group, has been instrumental in pushing for the Seattle ban. They
gave the city draft ordinance language and gathered endorsement
signatures from more than 400 businesses and individuals, including
members of the Nordstrom family and David Hancocks, former director
of the Woodland Park Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Garrison, elephant campaign coordinator for PETA, said the
country's attitude toward wild performing animals has shifted. Part
of that trend is a proliferation in circuses without animals, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, we'd see elephants being hooked and tigers
being whipped in the face and we never gave it a thought,'' she
said. ``Today, compassionate people don't want to support that
mistreatment of animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Ort-Mabry, a spokeswoman for Ringling Bros., said the
organization does not use any of those techniques in training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistreatment is never tolerated at Ringling Brothers,'' she
said. ``Our trainers devote their lives to these animals 24 hours a
day, seven days a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Ort-Mabry, who called the Ringling experience part of American
childhood, said the circus has enjoyed strong support in Seattle.
She said animals are an integral part of the Ringling presentation
and that in a recent nationwide survey, 70 percent of those queried
said animals were what draws them to the circus.
</P>
<P>
   Schell recalls trips to the circus as a child. But what he
remembers wasn't the lions, tigers or bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have fond memories of it, but it wasn't the animals doing
tricks,'' he said. ``It was the trapeze artists and other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Ort-Mabry, who called supporters of the ban a small, vocal
minority, promised that Ringling Bros. ``would oppose the
legislation and we would employ the appropriate tactics at the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   One group whom a ban would affect are the Shriners, a nationwide
fraternal organization. Jim Hart, secretary of the Seattle branch,
said the annual Shrine Circus raises between $60,000 and $100,000
for the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting more difficult because of the costs of putting it
on. I kind of wonder if it's worth it,'' Hart said. ``Laws are laws
and we'll live by the laws.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
