<HEADER>
A0060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TEST-BAN-REACT-550&AMP;AD     10-07 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-BAN-REACT-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIGHT OF U.S. TREATY VOTE EMERGES AT VIENNA PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TEST-BAN-TREATY.) 
(th) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Speakers at a conference convened to press for
ratification of the nuclear test-ban treaty, including two of the
holdouts, Russia and China, suggested Thursday that the ban might
founder if it was not approved by the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and Senate Republicans have
maneuvered all week in advance of the floor debate on the treaty
that is scheduled to start Friday. Both sides agree that the ban
faces near-certain defeat if it comes to a vote, so the main debate
has been whether, and how, to postpone the vote _ and keep the
treaty alive _ until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the delegates gathered at the ornate Hofburg Palace, the
sense was that if the treaty failed to clear Washington, it would
most likely fail to win enough support among other nuclear nations
to go into force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important that the U.S. does ratify this and sign up
in full,'' said Peter Hain, Britain's minister of state for foreign
and commonwealth affairs. ``It's about leadership in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, signed in New York on Sept.
24, 1996, has been signed by more than 150 countries. But for the
treaty to go into effect, 44 nations that are believed to have the
ability to build at least a crude bomb must both sign and ratify
it. So far, only 24 have ratified the ban, while some _ including
India, Pakistan and North Korea _ have yet to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Of those that have signed but not ratified the ban, the United
States, China and Russia are the most notable. Of the other major
nuclear powers, France and Britain have both signed and ratified
the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was organized by the United Nations under a
provision of the treaty that if it had not received the necessary
44 ratifications three years after it was signed, an international
conference ``facilitating its entry into force'' would be held.
</P>
<P>
   But while delegates took turns speaking in the Hofburg, most
eyes were on Washington, where the fate of the pact was really
being decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the U.S. ratifies the treaty, then Russia and China will
follow,'' said one senior diplomat. ``India and Pakistan will
follow them, and then we can isolate North Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan, which tested a nuclear device last year, has indicated
that it is waiting for India to sign, and for sanctions punishing
Pakistan for its test to be lifted. India missed this conference
because of its national elections, but other diplomats said it
would probably sign and ratify if the Big Five powers and Pakistan
do.
</P>
<P>
   But if the United States fails to ratify the treaty, diplomats
said, the steam will leak out of the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Britain and France both sent ministers rather than ambassadors
to underline how strongly they felt. ``I think it's important that
the Senate understand the eyes of the world are on them,'' Hain
said. ``It's not a domestic issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaukat Umer, Pakistan's ambassador in Vienna, said delegates
felt ``a certain sense of apprehension as to what will happen on
Tuesday,'' the day the Senate is scheduled to vote. ``If the
largest power is out of this, it's all over _ this treaty is
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China each made carefully worded speeches that
indicated they had prepared bills ratifying the treaty and were
poised to submit them to their parliaments.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Russia has consistently and firmly advocated and continues to
advocate a complete ban on nuclear weapon testing,'' the Moscow
delegation said in a brief statement. Its position on ratification
``is based on the assessment of the overall ratification process
including those states whose ratification is required.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Sha Zukang of China made a longer speech attacking
``negative developments'' for nonproliferation. Without naming the
countries involved, it criticized India and Pakistan for exploding
test bombs, the United States for considering an
anti-ballistic-missile system and NATO for bombing Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   China will continue to voluntarily abide by the treaty, he said,
but because of these negative developments, it will ``work to pick
up the ratification process as soon as practically possible.''
Afterward, while stressing that China would make its own decision,
Sha said, ``U.S. ratification will certainly facilitate Chinese
ratification.''
</P>
<P>
   Some delegations were so frustrated by the knowledge that the
Clinton administration badly wants the treaty passed but cannot
muster the two-thirds majority in the Senate that they discussed an
idea fairly unusual in diplomatic circles: writing a joint letter
directly to the Senate Republicans. But there were doubters,
including Sha, who said, ``I don't believe it's appropriate _ as
government delegations, we do business as governments.''
</P>
<P>
   Several delegates seemed mystified that hawkish Republicans
oppose the treaty. It was negotiated by a Republican president, and
polls show that 82 percent of Americans support it. It would freeze
the arms race while the United States enjoys a huge lead.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of paying 100 percent of the cost of the world's
second-most-sophisticated nuclear-test detection system (the
current American one), they said, the United States would pay only
25 percent for the world's most sophisticated one, with sensors
deep inside Russia, China, Iran and other nations where the United
States is not normally encouraged to gather data.
</P>
<P>
   The envisioned system would have 321 points gathering seismic,
infrasonic, hydroacoustic and radionuclide data. The preliminary
model is so good, boasted Wolfgang Hoffman, the executive secretary
of the commission overseeing it, that ``we knew exactly what was
happening in India and Pakistan'' when they carried out secret
tests. ``We were only 15 kilometers off spotting ground zero.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent test was even more accurate, he said. A bomb of 0.1
kiloton _ only a tenth of what the system has to detect _ was set
off in Kazakhstan and picked up in nine stations around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0061 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SEWER-SEWER_SFCHRON &LR;      10-07 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEWER-SEWER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 When Your Job Goes Down the Drain  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
``Rats,'' shouts Apollo Rojas from down the manhole near the corner
of Taylor and Eddy streets in the Tenderloin. ``A whole nest of
them.''
<P>
   ``Rats,'' repeats Gene Chruszcz with a look of mock horror,
enjoying the miserable expression on my face.
</P>
<P>
   Chruszcz (pronounced ``cruise''), 38, and Rojas, 53, are San
Francisco's only two full-time sewer inspectors. They have been
amusing themselves since the early morning preparing me for my
first (and last) foray into the city's underbelly.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas can be heard whooping and yelling down below.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's scaring them off,'' Chruszcz explains as he's lowered by
winch down the manhole.
</P>
<P>
   It's about 10 feet to the bottom. Watching from the street,
Charlie O'Neil, manager of sewer operations, shakes his head as
Chruszcz repositions his large frame to slither out of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offset manhole,'' O'Neil explains. For some reason _ O'Neil
has no idea why _ the original engineers designed this particular
entry to the underworld at a 90-degree angle. Most other manholes
open directly onto the sewer.
</P>
<P>
   I apprehensively check my harness and am clipped to the winch.
I'm wearing a bright orange jumpsuit, high rubber boots, a helmet,
surgical mask, gloves and assorted emergency gear.
</P>
<P>
   I feel decidedly underdressed.
</P>
<P>
   Readers who haven't yet finished breakfast may want to stop
right here. Things are about to get really, really yucky.
</P>
<P>
   The rungs down the manhole are long gone. Sewer workers seldom
use them anyway. Most rungs haven't been replaced since the sewer
was originally constructed nearly a century ago, and they now are
rusty and unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   The winch provides a soft landing amid the dirt and debris at
the bottom of the manhole. A narrow passage leads to the sewer,
where Chruszcz is waiting, twin lights shining from his helmet.
</P>
<P>
   The only way in is by crawling through, feet first.
</P>
<P>
   Cockroaches become visible, scurrying along the walls and
ceiling toward the lights on one's head. The roaches are 3, maybe 4
inches long.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to drop all over you,'' Chruszcz says. ``You
just brush them off.''
</P>
<P>
   The actual sewer is oval shaped, narrow at the bottom, wider up
top. It's 3 feet wide and ostensibly 5 feet high, though sand can
build up at the base, forcing inspectors to move about in a
constant crouch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Check this out,'' Chruszcz says, pointing a video camera down
the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   The sewer running beneath Eddy Street reaches a dead end at
Taylor. At the edge of the beam from Chruszcz's helmet, about a
dozen gray rats can be seen scurrying against the bricks. They're
the size of small weasels.
</P>
<P>
   Cornered, the rats turn to face their assailants. If it's a
nest, they'll attack to defend their young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go the other way,'' Chruszcz suggests.
</P>
<P>
   No one opposes the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown San Francisco has roughly 90 miles of 3-by-5 sewers,
the oldest part of the network. There are about 800 miles of newer
pipes crisscrossing the city elsewhere, most of which are routinely
inspected by camera-toting robots.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-by-5s, however, have to be surveyed on foot. That's
because a variety of obstacles can accumulate in the 100-year-old
tunnels, making passage difficult if not impossible for machines.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors are looking for cracks in the brickwork, broken
masonry, structural weakness or, worse, whole cave-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas' light is visible down the tunnel. Sewer inspectors always
work in pairs _ for efficiency as well as safety. Aside from the
vermin and waste materials, other potential hazards include toxic
gases, oxygen deficiency and, most common of all, injury by
slipping and falling in the muck.
</P>
<P>
   Chruszcz says sewer workers grow acclimated to the
disease-ridden environment and hardly ever get sick from their
travels in the underworld. For those new to the experience,
however, a day or two of intestinal troubles can be expected after
encountering all these microbes for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Swell. Something to look forward to.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas is performing the initial inspection. As he spots cracks
or other defects in the walls and ceiling, he marks them with spray
paint.
</P>
<P>
   Chruszcz follows with the video camera, making a visual record
of the surroundings with his own commentary on what he sees. The
tape and accompanying paperwork _ there's lots of paperwork _ will
go to the Department of Public Works for follow-up maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Heading away from the rats and the Taylor Street dead-end, the
base of the sewer quickly deepens with a dark, gooey slime that
envelops one's boots like pancake syrup.
</P>
<P>
   How horrible is it? Imagine the worst plumbing disaster you've
ever experienced. Now multiply by a million.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine walking in it. And smelling it. And breathing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys wouldn't do this,'' Chruszcz says with
considerable understatement. ``You can really wig out. But you get
used to it. It's like a little adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   So what would possibly compel a person to spend each and every
working day in such an environment? The money, obviously. Both
Chruszcz and Rojas make about $22 an hour, which each says is a
good deal more than they would pull down in, say, construction
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   With each sticky step deeper into the tunnel, the roaches become
thicker on the walls and ceiling. There must be thousands up ahead,
streaming toward the helmet lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets lots worse than this,'' Chruszcz says. ``I don't mind
if it's dirty. It's mobility I care about. You get on your hands
and knees, you start to worry.''
</P>
<P>
   It's awfully hard to imagine it being a lot worse than this. But
Chruszcz and Rojas agree that the city's absolute nastiest sewer
experiences are to be had below Chinatown and Fisherman's Wharf.
</P>
<P>
   It's the grease from the restaurants. It permeates one's hair
and clothing. It also serves as a smorgasbord for the rats and
roaches.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown has different challenges. ``When you're down here, you
go by some of the big hotels, with all their toilets and
restaurants, and the stuff comes out of the pipes like a jet,''
Chruszcz says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Engulfed,'' he adds. ``That'd be a horrible way to die.''
</P>
<P>
   If you live or work on the city's east side, there's a pretty
good chance that Chruszcz and Rojas have waded through your waste.
That's because after one flushes, all sewer-borne materials
gradually make their way to one of two treatment plants, one near
Cesar Chavez Street on the San Francisco Bay and the other facing
the ocean near the San Francisco Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   At the treatment plants, the waste goes through a series of
filters and purification processes before eventually emerging from
pipes either five miles into the bay or seven miles out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to urban myth, no one has ever seen an alligator or
crocodile down in the sewers. Chruszcz says he heard that a body
turned up in a pumping station a couple of years ago but admits
this may be just a story. He doesn't know anyone who actually saw
it.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Rojas said the strangest thing that has ever happened
to him was losing his previous partner in the tunnels beneath
Stockton Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was opening manholes and calling for him,'' Rojas
remembered. ``I could hear him yelling and screaming. Took an hour
to find him.'' Apparently, the poor guy kept wandering down
connecting tunnels as Rojas chased after him on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Chruszcz says it's unlikely anyone will get lost on this trip.
He and Rojas are inspecting only a few blocks and won't be making
any detours.
</P>
<P>
   But getting lost is the least of my concerns. With a nest of
angry rats to my rear, thousands of filthy, disgusting roaches
starting to drop onto my clothing, and standing ankle-deep in bile,
I'm finally rethinking my commitment to this series of articles.
</P>
<P>
   Before reaching the halfway point to the next manhole, I decide
that I've had enough and head back to the winch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't miss anything,'' Rojas says up on the surface
shortly afterward. ``The roaches were everywhere farther down. The
sewage level came up to your knees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all,'' Chruszcz says, stripping off his gloves, ``this
sewer wasn't that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   While they compare notes beside their truck, a street person
shambles over from the sidewalk and takes in the scene. He gazes at
the open manhole.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ain't going in there, are you?'' the man asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already did,'' Rojas answers.
</P>
<P>
   The street person, his clothes grimy and soiled, his skin and
hair a mess, gives the two sewer inspectors a look of amazement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man,'' he says, shaking his head. ``I wouldn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chruszcz and Rojas exchange a quick glance. They've heard it
before.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
