<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMAIL-EMAIL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Disappearing Inc. for E-Mail Keeps Messages Private  &HT;     Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Whether you're a CEO plotting to put a rival company out of
business or a mail room clerk sending a steamy, private e-mail to a
friend, a San Francisco startup has a new product that could help
protect your secrets: self-destructing e-mail.
<P>
   The appropriately named Disappearing Inc. has come up with
software that automatically makes sensitive or personal e-mail
unreadable after a specified time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're allowing companies to shred e-mail just like they've
been shredding confidential documents for years,'' said Rod Lehman,
a Disappearing Inc. vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Disappearing Inc. hopes its message resonates with companies
that may be worried about sensitive e-mail lingering around in a
computer for an unintended person, or worse, a lawyer, to discover.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates, whose old e-mail
messages about rival Netscape Communications Corp. were dredged up
to become a central part of the U.S. government's major antitrust
case against the Redmond, Wash., software giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this kind of system, where would it have left the
government's case?'' said Kerry C. Stackpole, president and chief
executive of the trade group Electronic Messaging Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Disappearing Inc. software is designed to work with any
e-mail program, such as Outlook, Netscape Mail or Eudora. It can be
programmed to scramble some or all messages, which are sent along
with a unique key code to unscramble the e-mail. Messages, however,
must be sent as attachments.
</P>
<P>
   If the recipient has installed Disappearing's program, the
message opens as a normal e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   If the recipient does not have Disappearing software, the
attachment launches a Web browser that automatically links to a
program on the Web that activates the decoding key.
</P>
<P>
   But the sender can program the software to destroy that key at
any time _ seconds, days or years later. E-mail messages that are
deleted can still exist on a computer hard drive, server or backup
tape and be retrieved later. But Disappearing officials claim
e-mail encrypted by their software would still be as unreadable as
shredded paper without the decoder key.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Rosema, one of the company's four co-founders and a former
asteroid tracker for the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory in
Pasadena, said only a government spy agency supercomputer would be
able to decode the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since in most of cases we're talking about people fishing for
dirt, they won't have the resources,'' Rosema said.
</P>
<P>
   The system isn't a safety net for beaming an e-mail to the wrong
person, since the text of the message can still be copied and
pasted to another file that won't disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Still, e-mail security is a problem, especially with electronic
messages now zooming along the Internet at a rate of about 7
trillion a year, Stackpole said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a danger than people realize,'' Stackpole said.
``The world should understand that e-mails are more like postcards
than letters. You send it out in the open. Having a secure
messaging system is a key component to be able to do e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Disappearing Inc. hopes to start selling its product to large
corporations in January, possibly for about $4 per month for each
computer user. Rosema said a consumer version may be ready later
next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
