u s BC-BKN-HAWKS08-COX     10-07 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glover slowly developing
 &HT;    By Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. _ Nearly a year has gone by since Dion
Glover's bright basketball future turned bleak in the agony of an
explosive knee injury that terminated his sophomore season at
Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   His career might have ended, except for the capable medical
staff at Georgia Tech. Instead, he's beginning his first training
camp with the Atlanta Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am on an NBA team, participating in training camp. I
would never have believed it,'' Glover said Thursday. ``I would
have thought I would still be doing rehab at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that the rookie, who will turn 21 on Oct.
22, is ready for the NBA, either physically or mentally. But he's
making progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``My lateral movement isn't what it should be, but that's
coming,'' he said. ``Physically, I'm fine. Coach (Lenny Wilkens) is
working me in slowly. There's no pressure on me, and I appreciate
Coach for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are Glover will start the season on the injured list.
After the heavy work of five practices, he limped noticeably early
Thursday afternoon. His lack of lateral mobility is glaring when he
is on defense, but he still has the glimpses of offensive explosion
that made him one of the ACC's most exciting players during his
season at Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question he's a big-time talent,'' Hawks general
manager Pete Babcock said. ``If we have to wait on Dion, we will.
But at some point this season, he could well be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   With Isaiah Rider and Jim Jackson playing ahead of him, the
former Cedar Grove High School star can take all the time he needs
to get ready. Meanwhile, Glover plays with an increasing sense of
freedom. But he does not yet have the instinctive explosiveness
that once underscored his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to reach the point where I do something and then I
realize I did it, not have to think about doing it,'' he said.
``That's got to happen first. This past week, I've been really
working on making quick cuts. I know it will all come back.''
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICE GUESTS
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame forward Alex English attended camp as a guest of
Babcock and offered advice to the team's three small forwards,
LaPhonso Ellis, Chris Crawford and Roshown McLeod. The Hawks could
pick up a few pointers from English, the seventh-leading scorer in
NBA history and the league's most prolific scorer during the
1980s.... The coaches from Southern Tech in Marietta, Ga., watched
the morning practice and former Minnesota coach Clem Haskins, an
assistant to coach Lenny Wilkens on the 1996 Olympic team, is
expected to attend some practice sessions over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   SHORT SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Ellis prevailed in a shooting game after an evening practice
when he floated home two half-court hook shots. Bimbo Coles was the
only other Hawk to sink a half-court shot, on a conventional
jumper.... In a scrimmage, Rider had a baseline runner blocked by
Dikembe Mutombo. Rider pointed to his own head, as if to say, ``I
remember who you are now.'' Next time down, he gave himself a lot
of room and sank a 3-pointer.... Among those trying out for the
team is former Oregon guard Terik Brown, whose father, Fred, played
for Wilkens' 1979 NBA championship team in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
