r s BC-HKN-FIGHTING-TEX     10-07 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FIGHTING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE A WAY OF LIFE IN THE NHL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _The replays are a chilling reminder and an
omen. Over and over, Mike Modano has watched himself tumble
headfirst and out-of-control into the end boards at Reunion Arena
on Saturday night, and he understands how fortunate he is to be
walking, maybe even to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   The injury has made the Stars' $6 million man reconsider the
price that he is willing to pay for the fame, fortune and celebrity
lifestyle that he enjoys as a superstar in the NHL, where fighting
is part of the game's tradition and random acts of violence seem to
occur as often as they do on city streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scares you and makes you wonder how much more can I take,''
Modano said in a news conference at the Dr Pepper StarCenter
yesterday. ``At times, I have second thoughts when I am by myself
and wonder how close it was. If this continues, I'm not going to
play anymore. I will quit before I can't react.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury to Modano, as well as incidents involving teammates
Darryl Sydor and Joe Nieuwendyk in Saturday night's game between
the Stars and Anaheim Mighty Ducks, have once again prompted debate
and inflamed passions about violence in hockey and whether the NHL
is doing enough to curb aggression.
</P>
<P>
   At the root of the debate is hockey's sanctioning of fighting.
Supporters say it is a necessary outlet for frustration and often
an honorable pursuit. Detractors argue that it condones violence
and sets a tone that has resulted in more flagrant acts that
jeopardize the careers of players and damage the image of the
league.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the bottom-line issue of whether fighting helps
hockey at the turnstiles. Spectators appear to enjoy fights; cable
and network TV newscasts often show fight highlights even if they
were isolated events that had no affect on the outcome of the game.
The NHL has passed stricter rules to penalize fighting, but has
stopped short of an outright ban.
</P>
<P>
   Even proponents of fighting, however, say that players in the
NHL are showing an increasing lack of respect for one another and
their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a league problem, but a player problem,'' said Glen
Sather, president and general manager of the Edmonton Oilers.''That
bothers me the most. There are so many players now, and that leads
to unfamiliarity. They wear helmets and masks and have a false
sense of security.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a violent game by nature, but players have to police
themselves. The players association should encourage the league to
suspend guys for more games instead of defending these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   From the original six-team league in which almost all the
players were native Canadians, the NHL has evolved into a 28-team
league with many players from the United States and Europe. A once
close-knit fraternity has become a melting pot of cultures and
languages, which can divide players. The discrepancy in salaries
can also ferment jealousy and lack of brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Even Teemu Selanne, the Ducks' superstar forward, empathizes
with Modano. ``Sometimes, its like a jungle out there,'' he said.
``I think we need more respect for each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most dangerous thing now is players going full speed and
trying to hurt somebody,'' Selanne continued. ``I think every
player should think, `how about if somebody did that to me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Modano said he plans to speak to NHL Players Association
officials about the incident in which Ducks defenseman Ruslan Salei
illegally pushed him from behind, knocking him awkwardly into the
boards. Modano suffered a concussion, broken nose and strained neck
ligaments. Salei was given a 10-game suspension without pay by the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players union and the owners have to get together to
change it,'' Modano said. ``It's turned into a vigilante mentality.
Do we have to wait for someone to be paralyzed or killed before the
league, teams and players come together and act?''
</P>
<P>
   Ducks defenseman Pascal Trepanier was suspended for five games
without pay for elbowing Nieuwendyk in the neck, and Jim McKenzie
was suspended four games without pay for punching Sydor repeatedly
in the back of the head as Sydor lay facedown on the ice. Sydor
suffered a hairline fracture of his left eye socket and is
sidelined indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with my wife and for sure, you think if it's all
worth it,'' Sydor said. ``You would like to get out \Rof the
sport\S and have fun after.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano and Sydor say that the suspensions could have been
tougher. The NHL says they fit the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The league says that it is cracking down on violence. It
attributes the perception that violence is increasing to increased
exposure through expansion and all-sports television networks that
sometimes show gore over goals. Players are also bigger and faster
than ever, making collisions more violent.
</P>
<P>
   NHL spokesman Frank Brown said that there were 51 suspensions
last season resulting from aggressive acts, costing players 147
games and $1.545 million in fines. Penalty minutes decreased by
5,000, and there were 344 fewer fights.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Campbell, a former player and coach, oversees fine and
punishment for the league, and knows the tricks of the trade as
director of hockey operations. The addition of a second referee for
all games this season is also seen as a deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said that Campbell took into account not only the
severity of the acts committed by the three Mighty Ducks, but the
history of each player before passing the suspensions. There is
also a provision in the rules that enables commissioner Gary
Bettman and Campbell to fine and suspend other team officials in
addition to the players involved. In theory, a coach or general
manager could be held accountable for what one of his players does
on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   But is this enough? The value of players cannot be measured only
in terms of games missed. For example, the combined annual salaries
of the three Ducks who were suspended is $1,850,000. Modano, Sydor
and Nieuwendyk (who was not sidelined) earn a combined $11 million
a year.
</P>
<P>
   It will take more than rules to change the players' mindset.
</P>
<P>
   Sather, who was a pugnacious player and coached the Oilers when
Wayne Gretzky was in his prime, was more upset that McKenzie had
violated the player code and attacked Sydor from behind, pounding
his head into the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What McKenzie did was premeditated,'' Sather said. ``It shows
a real lack of respect. I don't think Salei was trying to
intentionally injure Modano, although he has to be held accountable
for what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie's attack seemed reminiscent of the days of the Broad
Street Bullies in the 1970s when the Philadelphia Flyers terrorized
opponents. After a bench-clearing brawl in Toronto in 1975, Ontario
(Canada) attorney general Roy McMurtry vowed to prosecute hockey's
goons as he would anyone committing a similar act on the street.
Commissioner Clarence Campbell issued a familiar refrain: He blamed
increased television exposure and expansion for creating a
perception that violence was on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps coincidentally, the NHL adopted the third-man-in rule in
1976, in which a player intervening on behalf of a teammate
involved in a fight is ejected. Eleven years later, the league
addressed bench-clearing brawls, handing out automatic suspensions
for players who left the bench during a fight. McMurtry is often
credited for instigating the changes.
</P>
<P>
   But what will it take now to curb violence? Will the NHL
eventually ban fighting? Will it be the players who advocate
tougher punishment?
</P>
<P>
   Or will the Modano incident become yesterday's news?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to a point where players have to sit down and
really have a chat,'' said the Stars' Brian Skrudland. ``Hockey is
still a game and a game that when we all leave, we'd like to walk
away, not wheel our way out.''  &LR; tagtop:''Staff writers Mac Engel
and Jennifer Floyd and the Associated Press contributed to this
report.'' / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
