<HEADLINE>
ANTARCTICA IS MELTING, BUT HUMANS AREN'T RESPONSIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A massive portion of Antarctica is melting away, as global
warming doomsayers have long warned, but the scientists who proved
the meltdown say it has nothing to do with human-caused climate
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ice sheet has been retreating for the last seven or eight
thousand years,'' said Howard Conway, a University of Washington
geophysicist and lead author of a report in Friday's Science
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's long before we could have had anything to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most frequently cited catastrophic effects of global
warming is the predicted rise in worldwide sea levels by 15 to 20
feet should the massive West Antarctic Ice Sheet melt and flood the
planet's densely populated coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
   A complete melt-down of West Antarctica would submerge
significant portions of the world's coastal cities, completely
flooding vast lowland areas, including Florida and much of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Conway and colleagues at the UW and University of Maine reported
on evidence that the ice of West Antarctica is indeed melting and
has already retreated about 800 miles over the last 7,000 to 8,000
years. The edge of the ice sheet is shrinking at a rate of about
400 feet per year.
</P>
<P>
   But the ice sheet's melt-off began thousands of years ago, they
found, and has been progressing steadily without a driving force
like human industrial effluent or rapid changes in climate.
</P>
<P>
   Conway emphasized that the West Antarctic Ice Sheet could melt
faster if ocean temperatures rise as a result of human-caused
climate change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research doesn't say anything about what's been happening
within the last 100 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of other data to support the claim that the
climate is being significantly altered by industrial emissions and
other human activities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Earth's other massive ice sheets in Greenland and
East Antarctica, the West Antarctic Ice Sheet rests on land below
sea level. Scientists have long regarded it as susceptible to rapid
melting from an increase in ocean temperatures, but there hasn't
been much hard evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Finding solid evidence of melting and of the rate of recession
has been a major scientific challenge for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been called the grand unsolved problem of
glaciology,'' Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sea level of the world is controlled by the big ice sheets
so these are fairly important questions,'' said George Denton, a
University of Maine glacial geologist and one of the co-authors on
the paper.
</P>
<P>
   A rise in sea level some 14,000 years ago probably started the
meltdown in West Antarctica, the scientists say. That's when the
last Ice Age ended and the ice sheets that covered much of the
planet melted.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings can help resolve these questions, Denton said.
Other co-authors are UW geophysicists Ed Waddington and Tony Gades
and Denton's colleague Brenda Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Conway might have been considered an unlikely person
to solve a major scientific puzzle. The soft-spoken New Zealand
native is a former mountain climber who shifted from professional
guiding to glacier research after he helped Denton navigate an ice
field in Antarctica in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hired him as a guide to get us to an area where we did some
of the work that led to this paper,'' Denton said. ``He got
interested in the history of the Antarctic ice sheet ... and went
back to school for his degree.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Conway's team, two other scientific teams
published reports in Science providing further evidence of this
long-term meltdown of the West Antarctic Ice Sheet.
</P>
<P>
   A team led by Ian Joughin, a UW doctoral graduate now at the
California Institute of Technology, identified and reported on
``ice streams'' in West Antarctica _ rapid flowing internal
tributaries of ice and water that some believe could weaken the ice
sheet and lead to a catastrophic collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ackert Jr, at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
and his colleagues identified how much thicker the West Antarctic
Ice Sheet was 10,000 years ago by studying changes on the surface
of a volcano.
</P>
<P>
   The team led by Conway used two techniques to arrive at a
precise description of the recession of the ice sheet over the last
7,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Denton and Hall performed radiocarbon dating to determine the
time of death of algae and shells on land now free of ice. When the
ice sheet retreats, land that has been compressed by the massive
ice sheet rises up and large amounts of previously submerged sea
life dies off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rapid uplift takes place right after the ice recedes,'' Denton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The UW team used radar imaging to identify deformations in
sub-surface ice _ much like earthquake scientists use sonar to
detect fractures and potential faults in rock.
</P>
<P>
   The ice deformations, Waddington and Conway said, can be tracked
throughout the ice sheet and correlated with other data used to
identify the age and thicknesses of ancient layers.
</P>
<P>
   Using both sets of data, the UW and Maine scientists were able
to quantify and describe the historical retreat of the Ross Ice
Shelf over thousands of years in the Ross Sea area of West
Antarctica. Conway noted that most of the melting appears to have
taken place during a time of stable climate on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest chunk of ice on the planet that is so
susceptible to change,'' Conway said. ``What our findings indicate
is that it might keep melting no matter what we do about global
warming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
