<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCLE OF SHOOTING VICTIM ARRESTED AS SINGER'S MURDER TRIAL
CONTINUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UVALDE, Texas _ The bad blood between country singer Johnny
Rodriguez and the family of the man he is accused of killing was
evident in and out of the courtroom Thursday, as police confirmed
the victim's uncle was jailed for making a death threat.
</P>
<P>
   Uvalde County Sheriff Beaumont Watkins said Baltazar Borrego, an
uncle of shooting victim Israel ``Bosco'' Borrego, was arrested
Wednesday and is in the county jail for allegedly threatening to
kill a former lover. During the alleged threat, Baltazar Borrego
predicted Rodriguez ''would walk'' on murder charges, adding he
would kill the singer, Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, 47, is on trial in the Aug. 29, 1998, slaying of
Borrego after an all-night beer party. The singer's defense
attorneys claim Rodriguez shot Borrego, a convicted burglar, in
self-defense when he found him inside his mother's home in Sabinal.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, former Sabinal resident Arnulfo Avila testified the
dead man's older brother and a friend came to his home and pulled a
gun on him days after the shooting because he had attended the
party with Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Avila said he moved out of town because of the threat, but he
has heard that the brothers have continued to threaten anyone who
might testify for Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed by a prosecutor, he said he had not heard of any
specific threats involving the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want any problems,'' Avila then told defense attorneys
who asked if he was afraid of the Borrego clan.
</P>
<P>
   Avila, and Borrego's widow, mother and older brother were called
by District Attorney Tony Hackebeil to show the victim and
Rodriguez had a close relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney, in opening remarks to the jury Wednesday,
said Rodriguez shot Borrego while in a ``drunken stupor'' and
because he was mad the man was in his mother's house cooking
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he wasn't at his wife's, or my house, he was at
Johnny's,'' Alicia Borrego said of her slain son.
</P>
<P>
   She told the jury she went to the Rodriguez house on Pickford
street on three mornings to wake her son so he wouldn't miss work.
She said twice she walked into the unlocked house and slapped her
son awake, and one time she had to rouse Rodriguez who was, as
during the other visits, passed out drunk in a chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Come in, Alicia. Excuse the mess ... we partied too
long,''' she recalled, adding the table was littered with empty
beer cans and cigarette butts.
</P>
<P>
   Under defense questioning, Alicia Borrego acknowledged her son
had said Rodriguez's sister had warned him not to return to the
house. But she said the warning was directed toward a group of
people and ``not straight to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Meliton Borrego Jr., one of the victim's four brothers,
identified photographs taken in December 1997 of Rodriguez with his
arm around his brother's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes me, my brother and Johnny would party inside the
house,'' said Borrego, a 33-year-old construction worker. ``I
thought they were friends because I never did see them argue or
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a Sabinal police officer testified he arrived at
the Rodriguez residence shortly after 4 a.m. and saw a drunken
Rodriguez kicking Borrego as the shooting victim lay on the kitchen
floor.
</P>
<P>
   However, defense attorneys asked Dr. Robert C. Bux, the deputy
chief medical examiner for Bexar County, if he saw any bruises when
he conducted an autopsy on Borrego.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that scenario, I would expect there to be some marks,''
Bux testified.
</P>
<P>
   But he also agreed with prosecutor Hackebeil that because of
massive internal bleeding caused by the single gunshot wound _ more
than two quarts of blood pooled in the victim's abdomen _ he would
expect no bruising due to a lack of blood in the skin or muscle
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Bux said Borrego, whose blood alcohol content was 2 1/2 times
the legal limit, died of internal bleeding after a single
.357-caliber slug severed a vein in his back.
</P>
<P>
   Irma Rodriguez, a paramedic who responded to the shooting, told
how she had to strip the jeans and underwear from Borrego to find
the gunshot wound in his lower abdomen. As she did, two $20 bills
fell out of his pocket, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, defense attorney Alan Brown said the $40
was stolen from the Rodriguez home by Borrego, and ``that was the
fruits of his burglary.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Rodriguez was within his rights to shoot an intruder
to protect his property.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the law in Texas. You can stop a burglar at night,''
Brown said. ``You can use deadly force for criminal mischief at
night or theft at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Borrego's widow, Anita, testified the last time she saw her
husband was the night before the killing when she bought him a
six-pack of beer and dropped him off at his grandfather's house to
drink.
</P>
<P>
   The widow, who is now raising three children, fought tears as
she told the jury about her stormy marriage with the victim during
which she pressed charges against him for assault. But she defended
him and said he was not a violent person, and she was ``shocked''
when she learned he was shot by Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   But under defense questioning, she agreed it would be justified
to shoot a burglar if it appeared he intended to harm her or her
children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
