<SLUG> BC-JESUS-VIDEO08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jesus video: Deliverance by mail
 &HT;    By Ralph Ellis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A mass mailing in parts of metro Atlanta aims to
spread Christianity through the VCR.
</P>
<P>
   A group called the Jesus Video Project is sending a video
portraying the life of Jesus to 154,896 homes, at a cost of about
half a million dollars. Churches raised the money, and some are
promoting the mailing with signs out front and in members' yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to say: Here, check this out in your home at your
comfort level,'' said the Rev. Barry Odom, pastor of Braelinn
Baptist Church in Peachtree City. ``We want to get the message to
them and let them decide.''
</P>
<P>
   The video is being sent to every residential mailbox and post
office box in Fayette, Coweta, Meriwether, Heard, Banks and Jackson
counties. Videos also will go to three ZIP codes around Woodstock
in Cherokee County (30114, 30115 and 30142), one in northwest Cobb
County (30066) and one in Rabun County (30357).
</P>
<P>
   Bill Laycock, state director of the Jesus Video Project,
conceded that promoting Christianity in Georgia might be considered
a case of taking coal to Newcastle. In fact, the project's state
board of directors balked at Laycock's original suggestion to
attempt a statewide mailing. ``They said, `This is the Bible
Belt,''' Laycock said. ``They felt the money would be better spent
on our overseas projects.''
</P>
<P>
   But churches in the targeted areas asked for the mailing and
pressed ahead with fund-raising. The cost was paid by churches in
the participating counties and ZIP codes, with an assist from an
anonymous supporter who chipped in $200,000, Laycock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus,'' subtitled ``The Public Life of Jesus,'' was made by
producer John Heyman and released in 1979 for the Campus Crusade
for Christ. Organizers estimate 2 billion people have seen it.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, a businessman paid $3.3 million anonymously to
mail 1.7 million tapes to homes across Alabama. In Ohio, 385,000
videos were mailed out.
</P>
<P>
   The 83-minute film, which tells the story of Jesus as he is
born, teaches, is crucified and resurrected, ends with an
invitation to become a Christian.
</P>
<P>
   A card accompanying the video box can be mailed for contact with
churches.
</P>
<P>
   Ministers at participating churches said the video has been
warmly received. The Rev. Leslie Tuso, associate minister at
Mountain View United Methodist Church in Cobb County, said her
church would hold a prayer walk this weekend to celebrate the
mailing.
</P>
<P>
   Some Jewish members of B'nai Israel in Riverdale received the
video, Rabbi Julie Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly understand that the Christians who sent that are
trying to share very important things, for all the right reasons,''
Schwartz said. ``But for people who have a firm belief in another
faith, this doesn't have any effect on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom said supporters of the video don't want to be perceived as
pushy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out to tell anybody they're wrong,'' he said.
``We're taking the flip side and saying, `This may be what you're
looking for.' And all the time we're saying, `You have 100 percent
control. You can toss this in the trash. It's in your hands to
process.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
