<HEADER>
A0080 &Cx1f; taf-z
s x BC-MUTFUND-INTERNATIONAL     10-07 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-INTERNATIONAL-ART-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LONGER ALSO-RANS, OVERSEAS STOCKS SURPASS U.S. BRETHREN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Colo.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JOANNE LEGOMSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some managers of international funds are beginning to remember
what winning feels like. But just barely.
</P>
<P>
   For the third quarter, international stock funds _ which have by
and large lagged behind their domestic counterparts in recent years
_ managed a relatively slim, 2.06 percent gain, on average,
according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   But that was more than enough to beat the average United States
diversified stock fund, which was down 5.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the international equity funds stems largely from
the resurgence of two sectors _ Japanese stocks and gold-mining
issues _ that have been thrashed soundly for most of this decade.
The stocks of Japanese companies have risen this year on
perceptions that Japan's long-suffering economy has at least
bottomed out.
</P>
<P>
   While the Nikkei 225 index rose just 2.8 percent in the quarter,
the strengthening yen magnified the effect for United States funds
that invest in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   And shares of the gold-mining companies rallied in the last week
of the quarter, after European central banks announced that they
would limit their sales of the metal for the next five years. The
price of gold rose 11 percent, to $299 an ounce, between the Sept.
26 announcement and the end of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   (Morningstar considers precious-metals funds to be international
stock funds because of their high percentage of foreign gold
stocks.)
</P>
<P>
   Three managers of top-performing funds that invest abroad
discussed the stocks that made their funds winners this quarter and
_ in light of the heady run _ what they expect in the future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New Era for Japan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Japan Fund, with 92 percent of its $840.9 million in assets
in its namesake country, returned 29.5 percent for the quarter,
earning it the No.5 spot on the list of 712 international stock
funds tracked by Morningstar. The fund, the oldest Japanese stock
fund, returned 121.3 percent for the 12-month period, though just
7.2 percent annualized over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Its lead manager, Seung K. Kwak, 38, says he tries to capture
the extra return between other investors' short-term valuation of a
stock and his own assessment of the value three to four years in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   NTT Mobile Communications Network, Japan's dominant cellular
phone operator, was among the fund's biggest winners in the
quarter. Kwak bought shares at their initial offering last October
at 780,000 yen ($6,619) each. He said NTT Mobile, which has a
leading proprietary system for the transmission of wireless data,
has a lock on that market in Japan and huge potential to grow
elsewhere in Asia. The shares closed at 2.1 million yen ($19,828),
on Sept. 30, up 28 percent for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Another winner in the portfolio was Fuji Bank, which rose 52.4
percent. Kwak said the company's planned merger with the Industrial
Bank of Japan and Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, announced in August, would
bring economies of scale. ``It was one of the loser banks,'' Kwak
said, adding that the stock also received a lift from an infusion
of government funds in March and has reduced exposure to bad debts
_ most of which were related to a weak company in its keiretsu, or
business network.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the market's run-up, Kwak said, Japanese stocks are
still cheap relative to their underlying assets, sales and cash
flow. The prevailing high price-to-earnings ratio _ 49 at the end
of the quarter _ is a relic of management's historical fixation on
revenue growth at the expense of profit margins, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, Japanese companies are being managed for the bottom
line,'' he said. ``We are in the early stages of a new era of
modernization comparable to the Meiji era at the turn of the
century.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Going for the Gold &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the central banks, along with their
reiteration of the value of gold as a reserve asset, was music to
the ears of Bill Martin, portfolio manager of the $275 million
American Century Global Gold fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``New age investors view gold as a wasting asset that has no
place in their portfolios,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 35, said his fund, which ranked No.6 among international
funds in the quarter with a 28.9 percent return, is almost fully
invested in gold stocks. But within the sector, he tries to keep
the fund diversified along three lines.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio is spread out geographically, with 60 percent in
North American, 20 percent in South African and 20 percent in
Australian stocks. It has a mix of low- and high-cost producers.
And it includes companies with different strategies for hedging,
which locks in future prices. (Such strategies tend to be very
fluid.)
</P>
<P>
   The fund gained 5.3 percent in the 12 months ended Sept. 30,
though it has an annualized five-year loss of 11.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last quarter, its best performers were high-cost operators.
</P>
<P>
   One of his holdings, Anglogold Ltd. of Johannesburg, rose 45.4
percent in the quarter. Mines in South Africa tend to be deep, so
labor costs are high. Anglogold's average production cost is more
than $200 an ounce, Martin said. So when the price of gold rose,
its gross margins almost doubled.
</P>
<P>
   He also invested in Battle Mountain Gold, based in Houston. The
stock rose 30.8 percent in the quarter, to $3.1875. ``The company
has a lot of proven and probable reserves that become economic to
mine with gold at $300'' an ounce, Martin said. Such small gold
stocks usually trade at a more modest premium to their net asset
value than their larger-capitalization counterparts, but Martin
said that the gap narrowed during the recent run-up in gold prices.
</P>
<P>
   Another company in his portfolio, Newmont Mining, the global
gold miner based in Denver, rose 30.4 percent last quarter. Also a
high-cost producer, it should benefit from increasing output at a
year-old Indonesian mine, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking forward, he said that he was ``neutral to bullish'' on
gold. Though he said that it was too early to guess where the price
was headed, he thought it was unlikely to drop below $280 an ounce
for at least the next year. He said he was keeping an eye on what
he considered the two main near-term determinants of gold prices.
</P>
<P>
   First is the extent of ``short covering,'' or the purchase of
gold to pay back gold that was previously borrowed, either by
producers as part of their hedging strategies or by speculators.
The second is the demand for $300-an-ounce gold, especially among
jewelers, during the pre-Christmas buying period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Playing the Sector Game &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the world does business is changing,'' said Loretta
Morris, 46, co-manager of the $99 million Nicholas-Applegate
International Small Cap Growth fund, the No.19 international fund
for the quarter. ``There are a lot of great growth stories outside
the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morris is mostly invested in Continental Europe and Britain
(about 50 percent of the portfolio) and Asia (40 percent), the bulk
of that in Japan. But she said she focuses more on sectors and
industries than on country weightings.
</P>
<P>
   Her current emphasis is on service companies (about 27 percent
of the portfolio), which are consolidating, and technology (23
percent).
</P>
<P>
   The fund returned 19.1 percent last quarter, 73.2 percent for
the 12 months ended Sept. 30 and 22.3 percent annualized over five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Among the retailers Ms. Morris likes are two Japanese
category-killers: Kojima, which sells discounted consumer
electronics and appliances, and Fast Retailing, an American-style
apparel discounter. Both are benefiting from increased consumer
attention to pricing, Ms. Morris said. Their stocks rose 42.9
percent and 62.3 percent, respectively, in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morris has also made money in Havas Advertising of France,
Europe's second-largest advertising company. Its shares were up 7.7
percent in the quarter. She thinks the same forces that have
powered the growth in ad spending in the United States are in place
overseas: an increasing emphasis on product branding, rising
expenditures by Internet and cellular telephone companies, and
millennium-related promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Those trends also helped lift another of her stocks,
M6-Metropole Television, a French TV broadcaster, whose shares rose
14.8 percent in the quarter. Like the WB Network in the United
States, M6 has the kind of young viewers that advertisers love, Ms.
Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   She expects pending regulations that limit ad time on
government-owned stations to push ad rates higher for publicly held
broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morris also bought the American depository receipts of
Internet Initiative Japan, an Internet service company, at its
August initial offering at $23 each. They were up 104.4 percent as
of Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Morris said she was paring holdings in Japan a bit,
largely because of the price run-up, and adding more in Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
