<HEADLINE>
CITING SUPPORT, TRUMP FORMS EXPLORATORY COMMITTEE ON PRESIDENCY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Encouraged by ``amazing'' polls, ``unbelievable''
news media interest and a ``huge'' groundswell of public support,
Donald Trump deepened his flirtation with presidential politics
Thursday by appointing an exploratory committee to help him decide
whether his next big deal should be for 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   While exploratory committees may legally raise funds for
potential candidates, Trump said his would primarily be advisory _
telling him whether he could reasonably expect to win the White
House next year as the nominee of the Reform Party, whose leading
elected official is Jesse Ventura, the former wrestler who won the
Minnesota governorship in an upset last year.
</P>
<P>
   President Trump? If that seemed far-fetched, Trump was not
saying so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless I thought I could win the whole thing, I would have no
interest,'' Trump said in a telephone interview squeezed into a day
of television appearances, meetings with advisers and, Thursday
night, a dinner with Ventura. A 53-year-old real estate developer
and casino owner, Trump has never run for public office.
</P>
<P>
   In the byzantine realm of Reform Party politics, Trump and
Ventura are shaping up as allies in a fractious nomination fight
that could pit Trump against Pat Buchanan, who is expected to bolt
the Republican Party to bid for the Reform nomination. Buchanan is
supported by a loose alliance with ties to Ross Perot, the Texas
billionaire who is the party's founder.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts say a Buchanan candidacy would siphon
Republican support from Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who would
presumably prefer a race by Trump, who would have far less impact
on him. Trump, in capsule assessments Thursday, castigated Buchanan
but called Bush ``a strong front-runner.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump, whose name was raised by Ventura last month in the
preliminary skirmishing of a presidential campaign that, with more
than a year to go, is still in the stage of trial balloons and wild
guesses, may be as plausible as any of the actors, tycoons and
others being mentioned. He has name recognition and a net worth
estimated at $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking to raise money,'' Trump said, noting that, if
he runs, he will largely pay his own campaign bills. ``Fortunately,
I have plenty of money. That gives me one advantage over the
others. I wouldn't have to go through fund raising, with all the
obligations that involves. I wouldn't have to make deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump, saying he would decide early next year whether to run,
declined to identify the members of his exploratory committee,
whose main task seemed to be to advise him to go for it, and
perhaps to tell him how to win the internal struggle with Buchanan
for the Reform nomination. Merely appointing the panel gave fresh
momentum to Trump's budding campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He was on NBC's ``Today'' show Thursday and CNN's ``Larry King
Live'' Thursday night. On Wednesday night he appeared on
``Dateline'' on NBC. ``We have never seen such a barrage of calls
from the media and the press as in the last few weeks,'' he said.
``It's unbelievable.'' Referring to his possible run, he said,
``There is a lot of pressure to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited polls with ``amazing results,'' indicating ``that I'd
win, or do very well.'' Asked for specifics, he cited a poll by The
National Enquirer that showed him ``neck and neck'' with Bush. The
poll, he said, gave 39 percent to Bush, 37 percent to Trump and 24
percent to Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Trump, a Republican who called himself socially liberal but a
fiscal conservative, said he opposed gun control but favored tax
cuts, abortion rights, a strong national defense and health care
for all. His positions, he said, are detailed in his latest book,
``The America We Deserve,'' to be published in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking for straight talk,'' he said. ``They are
tired of politicians.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
