<HEADER>
A0085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-INDIANS-REDSOX-NY     10-07 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS CRUSH RED SOX, 11-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ For the Red Sox, their brief, shining moment in the
late-afternoon sun came around p.m. on Thursday and lasted for
about five minutes. After that, shadows and reality descended on
Jacobs Field as the power of the Indians eclipsed most Boston
hopes. When the game ended, around sundown, Cleveland had an 11-1
victory and a 2-0 lead in the three-of-five-game first-round
series.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians can clinch this American League division playoff
series in Fenway Park either Saturday or Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians won Thursday on home runs by Jim Thome and Harold
Baines and the pitching of Charles Nagy. The Red Sox lost with the
pitching of Bret Saberhagen, who said his problem was not his sore
right shoulder but his excitement. They were also hurt by two plays
involving Jose Offerman, one while running to second base, the
other while throwing a ball from there.
</P>
<P>
   The day ended with Boston's Jimy Williams invoking the name of
Babe Ruth, a strange choice for a man managing a team that has
suffered most of the century under the so-called Curse of the
Bambino. When someone asked Williams what he could do to improve a
lineup that has managed only three runs in two games, Williams used
Ruth's given names.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll get a hold of George Herman,'' he said. ``I don't
know. What do you want me to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he could also use Ruth as a pitcher, as the Red Sox did
before selling him to the Yankees in 1920. They sure could use some
pitching now. Even if Boston's ace, Pedro Martinez, recovers
quickly from his back injury and replaces his brother, Ramon, as
Saturday's starter, the Red Sox, who have lost 18 of their last 19
post-season games, would have difficulty winning three consecutive
days against the Central Division champions, the most productive
team in the last half-century, the first team since the 1950 Red
Sox to score more than 1,000 runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest keys is not to get too relaxed,'' said
Thome, whose fourth-inning grand slam off John Wasdin was his
second home run of the series. ``By no means are they going to lay
down and die.''
</P>
<P>
   But they are certainly checking in with the doctor. Martinez,
probable winner of the Cy Young award as A.L.'s best pitcher, left
Game 1 on Wednesday night after four innings with a sore back.
Although Martinez spoke words of hope on Thursday, the team doctor
sounded more pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some improvement,'' Martinez said. ``I feel better
already. I really feel positive about it. Right now I feel looser.
I'm going to keep working.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. William Morgan, traveling with the team, said: ``Pedro
has a muscle strain in the mid-back area. There is a slight
improvement today but he does have persistent pain. He's undergoing
treatment right now, which includes ultrasound, anti-inflammatory
medication and rest. The plan is to start stretching tomorrow and
light exercise tomorrow. We will re-evaluate him tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The game, before the usual capacity crowd, began at 4:10 p.m.
under blue skies in this jewel of a downtown ball park. Throughout
the afternoon, after lunchtime, fans in team clothing streamed
through the streets while office workers in business clothing
joined them. Cleveland won the opener on Wednesday night by coming
from behind for a 3-2 victory, and the civic buzz is growing here
for the first championship since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox took a 1-0 lead in the third inning on Thursday when
Offerman's two-out single scored Trot Nixon from second base. But
when the Indians cut off the throw from the outfield, Offerman got
caught between first and second and was tagged for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was not a critical blunder, but it served as an omen.
In the bottom of the inning, when Cleveland's Sandy Alomar hit a
potential double-play grounder to shortstop Nomar Garciaparra,
Offerman's throw on the pivot pulled first baseman Mike Stanley off
the base. It was the catalyst for a six-run inning, highlighted by
Baines's three-run home run that drove Saberhagen out and made the
score 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, the Indians added five runs, four on
Thome's blast off Wasdin. With a 10-run lead, Nagy cruised into the
twilight, working seven innings and giving up five hits before the
bullpen took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eleven runs was a great help,'' Nagy said. ``A lead like that,
you just want to throw strikes.'' He ended an interview by citing a
pitch late in the game that bounced to the plate after he slipped
on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my groove right there,'' Nagy said. ``Good dance
move.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood was less jovial for Saberhagen, 35, who spent three
stints on the disabled list this season and said earlier this week
that he might need shoulder surgery. He said he felt no pain on
Thursday and added: ``It felt very good. I shouldn't say too good,
but maybe too much adrenaline. Too excited.'' In 119 innings this
season, he walked only 11 batters. On Thursday, he walked three
batters in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not me, that's what really hurt,'' Saberhagen said of
the walks.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Baines' first-pitch swing, Saberhagen added: ``I made
a good pitch on Baines, down and away. He deposited it in right
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the series over all, Saberhagen said: ``The pressure is on
us. I know it's going to be a long flight home.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2144EDT &QL; 
