<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEARCHER-CONFLICTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL PANEL TO REVIEW RESEARCHER FUNDS CONFLICTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG AND ALISON BASS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Institute of Mental Health will review its policy
on conflicts after learning of a Brown University professor who
received hundreds of thousands of dollars from drug companies while
he was receiving federal funds to test new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Martin Keller issued favorable reports on the drugs and
Brown did not disclose the drug company payments to the federal
government, the Globe reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven E. Hyman, director of the NIMH, said Thursday that at
an upcoming advisory council meeting he would raise the issue of
how the institute can more effectively prevent financial conflicts
among federally funded academic researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Keller, a Newton, Mass. resident who is chief of psychiatry at
Brown, was paid more than $500,000 in consulting fees in 1998, most
of it from pharmaceutical companies whose drugs he touted in
medical journals and at conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Krimsky, a Tufts University professor studying the
effects of ties between academia and industry, said: If this case
``does not represent a conflict of interest that should be avoided,
then I don't know what such a conflict would be.'' Krimsky is a
nationally known science policy specialist who has been concerned
by what he sees as a loss of objectivity in research.
</P>
<P>
   Keller earned a total of $842,000 last year, according to
financial records, and more than half of his income came from the
pharmaceutical industry, including companies such as Pfizer Inc.,
Bristol-Myers Squibb, Wyeth-Ayerst, and Eli Lilly _ all of which
market antidepressants that Keller lauded in a series of research
reports.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Keller was receiving millions of dollars in funding
from the National Institute of Mental Health for research on
depression and ways to treat it. In 1998, for instance, Keller
authored an article in the journal Biological Psychiatry in which
he cited his federal study on depression and concluded that newer
antidepressants, including Serzone, Zoloft and Effexor, were all
effective medications for depression.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer, which makes Zoloft, paid Keller $218,000 in personal
income the same year; the psychiatrist also received $77,400 in
consulting fees from Bristol-Myers Squibb, which makes Serzone, and
$8,785 from Wyeth-Ayerst, which makes Effexor.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal regulations, scientists seeking US funds are
required to disclose to their research institutions any
``significant financial interests'' that could be affected by the
proposed study. Then it's up to the institutions to assess the
financial interests. If the institutions find a conflict, they must
report it to the US funding agency and protect the research from
bias, according to the 1995 regulations.
</P>
<P>
   But according to documents obtained by the Globe, Brown did not
notify NIMH of any financial conflict involving Keller.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Freid, Brown's executive vice president for public affairs
and university relations, defended Keller's and the university's
actions. Under university policy, she said, researchers must
indicate financial interest of greater than $10,000 and limit
outside consulting to one day a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made full disclosure in a timely manner. A committee
reviewed it,'' Freid said. ``The regulations do not require
notification. Our responsibility is to reduce, eliminate, and
manage potential conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   But Krimsky criticized both the federal regulations, for leaving
it up to research institutions to judge whether there's a conflict,
and Brown's interpretation of the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Freid said that ``our integrity and that of our scientists'' is
such an important factor to protect, that that alone ``is a pretty
strong interest to counter any potential conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller could not be reached Thursday despite messages left at
his office and home.
</P>
<P>
   The American Psychiatric Association announced this week it also
intends to investigate allegations that Keller did not fully
disclose money he received from pharmaceutical companies before
lauding their antidepressant drugs at the group's annual meeting in
1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
