<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0106 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-MURDERS-$ADV     10-07 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-MURDERS-$ADV10-4TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THREE AMERICAN ACTIVISTS WERE KILLED IN COLOMBIAN DRAMA OF
REBELS, OIL, INDIANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (A tilde is needed over n in Garcia-Pena, n in Briceno and n in
Cano) 
 
(For release Sunday, Oct. 10) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS PAJAROS, Venezuela _ To cross the Arauca River from Colombia
into this desolate patch of western Venezuela, you must borrow a
dugout canoe or swim the 100 yards. There are no ferries, no
bridge, no lifeguard to bail you out should the murky brown current
sweep you away.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much of anything, except for a few ducks and a field
flecked with cow dung. Yet the Venezuelan army lieutenant who has
agreed to show this American journalist around is clearly spooked.
</P>
<P>
   Trudging along the river's edge in an area known as Los Pajaros,
the lieutenant orders 15 soldiers to form a protective perimeter
around us. Crouching behind the bushes, they point their rifles
across the water at the invisible menace in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wander around here on my own, they will kidnap me,'' the
officer says.
</P>
<P>
   He is talking about the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia,
or FARC, the Marxist rebel group that dominates much of the
Colombian countryside. FARC rebels regularly slip into Venezuela to
escape the Colombian army, run guns and pull off kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
   It was one such cross-border caper by the FARC that spelled the
end for three Americans who were on a humanitarian mission to
Colombian Indian territory. The execution-style slayings of Terence
Freitas, Lahe'ena'e Gay and Ingrid Washinawatok blackened the
FARC's reputation around the world, outraged Washington and
threatened to derail a fragile peace process designed to end
Colombia's 35-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Why rebels chose to kill three Indian-rights activists who
shared many of the FARC's populist beliefs remains a mystery more
than half a year later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes against all the principles and teachings of the
FARC,'' says Daniel Garcia-Pena, a former Colombian government
peace commissioner who has dealt with the rebels. ``It was a major
screw-up.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 25 at about 10 a.m., two FARC guerrillas stopped a blue
Toyota pickup just outside the Colombian town of Cubara. Inside the
truck were Freitas, Gay and Washinawatok.
</P>
<P>
   They had just spent two weeks with the U'wa Indians. Largely
untouched by modern society, the U'wa are struggling to prevent
Occidental Petroleum Corp., the Los Angeles-based oil and gas
multinational, from drilling on what they consider sacred lands.
The Americans had ventured to their reservation in a show of
solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' says Liliana Obregon, a Colombian who was a
friend of Freitas'. ``It's such a scary country for outsiders that
usually people don't do something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Freitas, Gay and Washinawatok were inveterate globe-trotters
who thrived on grass-roots research. Together, they formed a kind
of dream team of the indigenous rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Freitas had done more than anyone to call attention to the
plight of the U'wa and had cobbled together a surprisingly
effective U'wa support group in the United States. He was just 24.
</P>
<P>
   Lahe'ena'e Gay, 39, was the descendent of a royal Hawaiian
family. She was an anthropologist, a writer and the founder of an
indigenous rights organization in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid Washinawatok, 41, a Menominee Indian from Wisconsin, was
a board member of the U.N.-affiliated International Indian Treaty
Council and a high-profile activist since high school.
</P>
<P>
   Bouncing along in the Toyota with their Indian hosts, the
Americans were on their way from the U'wa reservation to a nearby
airport to begin their trip back to the United States. They never
made the flight.
</P>
<P>
   The two guerrillas, who wore bandannas over their faces and
carried pistols, ordered the three Americans into a taxi.
Washinawatok and Gay kept quiet. Terry Freitas, who spoke Spanish,
tried to maintain his composure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry said: `Sure. No problem,''' recalls Roberto Cobaria, the
U'wa leader who had invited the Americans to visit and was in the
pickup. ``The guerrillas told us that they would be back in half an
hour. But it was a trick.''
</P>
<P>
   During the next week, the rebels marched their bedraggled
captives 40 miles east, then crossed the Arauca River into
Venezuela. On the morning of March 4, a farmer in Los Pajaros was
startled by a burst of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard 15 or 20 shots, and then everything was silent,'' says
Segundo Salamanca.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty yards from the river, Salamanca discovered three
blindfolded and bullet-pocked bodies lying face up in his cow
pasture. Tucked in the underwear of one was an American Express
card with the name Ingrid Washinawatok.
</P>
<P>
   Even in one of the most tumultuous corners of the world, the
triple murder was jaw-dropping.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of revolutionaries shoot two women and a young
guy?'' asks Ali El-Issa, Washinawatok's husband. ``It was like they
were shooting chickens in the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The killings occurred just as Colombian negotiators were
preparing for peace talks with the FARC, prompting critics to
charge that the guerrillas had revealed their true colors in this
cow pasture. On Capitol Hill, the bloodshed sparked calls for more
U.S. military aid to help the Colombian army take on the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Americans were mistaken for spies. Some say the
operation was a ploy by hard-line FARC commanders to sabotage the
peace process. Others call it the ugly endgame of a bitter power
struggle between the guerrillas and the U'wa Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to stonewalling by the FARC, such theories are little
more than shots in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   However, a look at events leading up to the slayings sheds light
on Colombia's lethal triangle of hell-bent revolutionaries,
multinational oil companies and newly enfranchised indigenous
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths of Freitas, Gay and Washinawatok also offer a
cautionary tale about true believers who, without fully realizing
the risks, followed their hearts to a hot zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry loved the way the U'wa lived, that they could live so
peacefully, and he thought it was worth protecting,'' Julie Freitas
said the day after burying her son. ``When I expressed that I was
concerned, Terry said: `Mom, I'll always come back.' And he always
did come back. I just didn't expect him to come back in a box.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand why three Americans would journey thousands of
miles and risk everything to safeguard a tribe of 5,000 Indians, a
visit to the U'wa reservation in the mountains of northeastern
Colombia seems key.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the U'wa are in such demand at overseas conferences
that they are constantly breezing through the Colombian capital of
Bogota on their way to the international airport.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Perez, president of the U'wa Traditional Authority, and
Roberto Cobaria, who just finished a five-year stint as president
of the U'wa Traditional Authority and was with the Americans when
they were abducted, agree to meet me.
</P>
<P>
   At the first interview, Perez slumps in a chair and drifts off
to sleep. At the second, Cobaria begins by filling his cheek with
coca leaves, the raw material for cocaine. He won't leave home
without them. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Cobaria charms people by sticking to his beliefs, by doing
things the U'wa way.
</P>
<P>
   His roundabout manner of conversing is because of the fact that
the U'wa have no written language. They sing and chant age-old
stories to establish their past. If you ask him a historical
question, he may start singing to refresh his memory.
</P>
<P>
   Such traits are examples of how the U'wa, unlike many of
Colombia's 82 indigenous groups, fiercely cling to their
traditions. Only a handful of U'wa have ever left the reservation.
Few speak fluent Spanish, because they have their own language,
with four dialects.
</P>
<P>
   Largely self-sufficient, the U'wa hunt, gather and fish. They
also work as seminomadic farmers who meticulously rotate their
crops to preserve the delicate ecosystem of the reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would not, for instance, cut down a tree for firewood
whose fruits are eaten by forest animals,'' wrote Ann Osborn, a
British anthropologist who lived with the U'wa for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The U'wa way of life, however, is not all pastoral bliss.
Tuberculosis, alcohol abuse and other ills are pervasive on their
reservation. And some U'wa customs, such as abandoning newborn
twins in the wild because they are viewed as bad omens, horrify
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
