<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0107 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-MURDERS-$ADV     10-07 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-MURDERS-$ADV10-2NDTAK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
LOS PAJAROS, Venezuela: horrify outsiders.
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the Spanish Conquest in the 1600s, the U'wa were pushed
into the Sierra Nevada de Cocuy mountain range near the present-day
Venezuelan border. The European invasion led the U'wa to make a
drastic decision.
</P>
<P>
   According to the tribe's oral history, to avoid enslavement by
the Spaniards, legions of U'wa put their children into clay pots
and flung them off a 1,400-foot precipice. Then, adults walked
backward off the edge after them. The spot came to be known as the
Cliff of Glory, and it was said that so many bodies piled up that
they changed the course of the river below.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a cultural strategy in which they preferred to commit
suicide rather than to surrender,'' says Gregorio Mesa, an U'wa
expert at the National University in Bogota. ``The U'wa say that
their god put them in this territory to take care of it. If they
can't do that, things get very complicated, and this is the
response.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, things are getting complicated for the U'wa.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the U'wa and their U.S. supporters portray
Occidental Petroleum as a modern-day conquistador.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute dates back to 1992, when Occidental purchased oil
exploration rights from the Colombian government for the Samore
block, which stretched across 494,000 acres and included the U'wa
reservation.
</P>
<P>
   The U'wa fear that an oil boom on their doorstep would invite
guerrilla violence and environmental havoc as well as jaded
outsiders and fast money that would destroy their way of life.
Tribal elders also contend that oil is ``the blood of Mother
Earth'' and that draining it from the ground would offend the gods.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the position taken by the U'wa puzzled Occidental.
Part of Colombia's Cano Limon pipeline, which began operating in
the mid-1980s and carries Occidental oil to the Caribbean coast, is
located close to the U'wa reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in that area for the longest time,'' says one
former Occidental executive who asked not to be named. ``We never
heard of these things when the pipeline was built, that oil is the
blood of Mother Earth. But how can you question it? You don't want
to be insensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, with engineers already conducting seismic studies in
the Samore block, the U'wa elders made a pronouncement.
</P>
<P>
   They declared that if Occidental goes forward with plans to
drill on their ancestral lands, the U'wa would return to the Cliff
of Glory en masse _ and jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our culture is not negotiable,'' says Cobaria, his cheek
bulging with coca. ``For the U'wa, it would be better for us to
die.''
</P>
<P>
   The apocalyptic threat put the U'wa on the map.
</P>
<P>
   And among those entranced by the story was a young man from
suburban Los Angeles named Terry Freitas.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from the University of California at Santa Cruz
with degrees in biology and environmental studies, Freitas worked
with Navajo Indians in Arizona who were involved in a dispute with
a mining company. But when he learned of the do-or-die U'wa
dogfight with Occidental, whose corporate headquarters are located
20 miles from the Freitas home, he dropped everything. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``He said he had a moral obligation to defend the U'wa,'' says
Ebaristo Tegria, an U'wa Indian and one of the tribe's legal
advisers. ``He said: `I feel guilty, because I'm from
California.'''
</P>
<P>
   Freitas made his first trip to the U'wa reservation in 1997 and
became fast friends with U'wa leader Roberto Cobaria. Later, he
brought Cobaria to Washington, where he managed to set up a meeting
between the Indian and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Freitas hounded U.S. activists to join the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were, of course, all burnt out and cynical about such
things, but Terry kept on insisting and pushing us,'' says Danny
Kennedy, director of the Berkeley, Calif.-based Project
Underground, which lobbies against oil development.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, seven environmental organizations formed the U'wa
Defense Working Group and named Freitas its coordinator. Mailings
went out. Web sites were launched. Donations trickled in. Actor
Leonardo DiCaprio wrote a check for $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Occidental's annual shareholder meetings in Los Angeles
became the site of boisterous pro-U'wa demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Meriage, an Occidental vice president and spokesman,
goes out of his way to praise Freitas' motives. But he also
suspects that some groups jumped on the U'wa bandwagon mainly to
raise money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have an issue, your fund-raising dries up,''
Meriage says. ``I think the U'wa issue from an activist standpoint
is kind of a godsend. It has elements of almost biblical
proportions, of David and Goliath.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, in the battle for hearts and minds, the U'wa seem to
have the upper hand. In 1998, Cobaria won the prestigious Goldman
Environmental Prize as well as Spain's Bartolome de las Casas Award
for the defense of indigenous rights in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``Oxy's reputation is being dragged through the
mud,'' says one oil industry analyst, using Occidental's nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the U'wa Defense Working Group, Meriage says that his
office has been flooded with mail from outraged Americans demanding
that Occidental leave the poor Indians alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get these letters coming in on recycled paper in envelopes
that have been reused and taped together with the old addresses
scratched out,'' he says. ``They think we ought to go back to
bicycles. They say: `Why don't you get into the windmill
business?'''
</P>
<P>
   In Colombia, such back-to-basics talk is akin to tilting at
windmills. Today, the Bogota government is making a stronger push
than ever for foreign oil companies like Occidental to drill new
wells.
</P>
<P>
   After major oil basins were discovered in the 1980s,
petrodollars cushioned the Colombian economy while other Latin
American nations suffered through recessions and hyperinflation.
Colombia now produces about 825,000 barrels of oil per day and
depends on petroleum for 25 percent of export earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, high production costs, guerrilla attacks
and better deals elsewhere have convinced many foreign firms that
their Colombian operations should be scaled back. The government
insists that unless new reserves are discovered, the nation will be
importing oil by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colombia can't be condemned to poverty. Oil is a fundamental
part of the economy,'' says Juan Carlos Ucros, a lawyer for
Occidental's Colombian branch.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most promising sites for the next major strike is
Occidental's Samore block. One oil analyst says that the chances
for a gusher at Samore may be 20 percent _ double the industry
average for unexplored regions. By some estimates, the basin may
hold up to 1.5 billion barrels of oil.
</P>
<P>
   For wildcatters, however, it's not just a jungle out there. It's
a war zone.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing multinational oil firms of making off with the wealth
of the nation, the FARC and the National Liberation Army, or ELN,
Colombia's second-largest guerrilla group, have gone on the attack.
Since 1986, the rebels have dynamited Colombian oil pipelines 630
times.
</P>
<P>
   After one ELN attack last year, the resulting oil slick caught
fire, killing 60 people in a rural hamlet. In another incident,
guerrillas grabbed two engineers working in the Samore block,
hanged them from a bridge and used them for target practice.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many ordinary Colombians no longer view oil as a
liquid cure-all. In fact, those living near pipelines often gripe
that they are worse off because of the threat of rebel attacks and
oil spills.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put in oil infrastructure, the guerrillas target it.
Then the government militarizes the area, and the folks that are
caught in the middle are the local people,'' says Shannon Wright of
the San Francisco-based Rainforest Action Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the cycle,'' she says. ``If you start laying pipeline
in U'wa territory, you will kick off a small war inside their
lands.''
</P>
<P>
   According to U'wa expert Gregorio Mesa, oil development has
degraded once-thriving Indian tribes, such as the Yarigue and the
Bari, in other parts of Colombia. ``It's not just due to petroleum,
but petroleum never comes alone,'' he says. ``It brings
colonization, new people, new customs.''
</P>
<P>
   Meriage points out, however, that Occidental provides locals
with jobs and scholarships and sponsors social development
projects. Colombia, he says, can't allow the FARC and ELN to drive
away foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet efforts to exploit the Samore block were botched from the
beginning. The Colombian government uncorked the controversy by
selling exploration rights without consulting the U'wa. Such talks
are required under the 1991 constitution, which mandates greater
autonomy for indigenous groups.
</P>
<P>
   Occidental tried to bring the U'wa on board, but the tribe's
leaders, claiming that the company had misled them, turned against
the project.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0108 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-MURDERS-$ADV     10-07 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-MURDERS-$ADV10-3RDTAK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
LOS PAJAROS, Venezuela: against the project
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eventually, a lawsuit was filed on behalf of the U'wa. After the
case ping-ponged around Colombia's legal system for two years, a
court ruled in 1997 that Occidental had the right to move ahead
with exploration.
</P>
<P>
   However, with protests mounting, Occidental announced last year
that it would give up exploration rights to 75 percent of the
Samore block, including the entire U'wa reservation. The company
then applied for a license to drill an appraisal well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The site we've selected is just off the main highway,''
Meriage says. ``This is not the rain forest.''
</P>
<P>
   But the U'wa say the drill site lies too close to their
reservation. They also claim that it is located on U'wa ``ancestral
territory,'' which their people roamed centuries ago but which is
not legally recognized as U'wa land.
</P>
<P>
   Exasperated Occidental officials point out that indigenous
groups once were present throughout Colombia. In theory, they say,
the entire nation could be considered ``ancestral territory'' and,
therefore, off-limits to development.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Occidental were to give up Samore _ lock, stock and 1.5
billion barrels _ Terry Freitas had come to the conclusion that
another petroleum company would likely take its place.
</P>
<P>
   For the long-term defense of the U'wa, he figured that schools
teaching traditional Indian values were critical. Thus in the
summer of 1998, he and U'wa leader Roberto Cobaria met with Ingrid
Washinawatok and Lahe'ena'e Gay in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The two women were members of Pacific Cultural Conservancy
International, an indigenous rights group based in Hawaii. Gay, the
group's founder, had just returned from Panama, where she had
helped several Indian tribes design their own schools.
</P>
<P>
   Impressed, Cobaria invited Gay and Washinawatok to the
reservation to plan something similar for the U'wa. Freitas would
be their guide and translator.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs, however, that their journey would be tempting
fate.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Freitas had received a rambling death threat in
Spanish on his telephone answering machine. And on a previous trip
to Colombia, he had been warned by the FARC to back off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had been told to get out of the country and not come
back,'' says a U.S. State Department official. ``He was in the U'wa
villages, and the FARC came and told him. They said they didn't
agree with his purpose for being there.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the FARC claims to be fighting on behalf of indigenous
groups and other ``oppressed'' Colombians, U'wa leaders accuse the
guerrillas of a litany of abuses _ from trespassing on their
territory to conscripting Indian boys.
</P>
<P>
   The FARC, in turn, views the emergence of strong indigenous
groups as a threat to its authority, the State Department official
says. The rebels likely marked Freitas as a meddling American who
was fomenting U'wa autonomy, the official adds.
</P>
<P>
   And in truth, the FARC may have little use for the resistance
shown by the U'wa to Occidental. Despite the guerrillas' own
dictums about the evils of foreign oil companies, the FARC has made
millions by kidnapping petroleum workers and blackmailing their
employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that the arrival of the oil companies is good for
the FARC, because it presents an opportunity for extortion,'' says
Juan Francisco Mesa, a lawyer for Free Country, a Bogota support
group for relatives of hostages.
</P>
<P>
   If the guerrillas seem more like desperados than freedom
fighters, that's because the FARC broke the mold for old-school
insurgents.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the Cuban revolution, the FARC was formed in 1964
and originally fought for social justice, land reform and a Marxist
state. But the organization has metamorphosed into a kind of
revolutionary-industrial complex.
</P>
<P>
   By kidnapping people for ransom, levying ``war taxes'' on
businesses and working in cahoots with drug traffickers, the FARC
earns up to $500 million annually, according to U.S. and Colombian
estimates. That positions the FARC among the most profitable
corporations in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   As the Cold War ended and other Latin American revolutionaries _
from Nicaragua's Sandinistas to Peru's Shining Path _ disarmed or
were defeated, the FARC's big bucks financed a great leap forward.
The FARC now has 15,000 foot soldiers grouped into 61 fronts.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, some 35,000 people, mainly civilians, have
been killed in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the FARC's rapid ascent has bred problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real breakdown of discipline within the movement,
and a lot of factions that operate on their own. Some are brutal
and hard-line. Others are much different,'' says Michael Shifter, a
senior fellow at the Inter-American Dialogue, a Washington think
tank.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most malevolent factions are the FARC's 10th and 45th
fronts, which moved into the eastern Colombian state of Arauca in
1996 with orders to fill the guerrillas' coffers. Experts describe
these two fronts as an assemblage of ruffians engaged in a
free-for-all of kidnappings and cocaine deals.
</P>
<P>
   They are commanded by German Briceno, who goes by the nom de
guerre Grannobles. Not known for his military prowess, Grannobles
was promoted mainly because he is the brother of Jorge Briceno, the
FARC's top military strategist, according to U.S. and Colombian
sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grannobles is not the brightest light in the force, but he's
brutally efficient,'' the State Department official says.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Freitas had no illusions about the rebels, but he was
intent on returning to the U'wa nation. Last November, he sent a
message to the FARC seeking assurance that he would be left alone.
</P>
<P>
   His go-between was an International Red Cross delegate in Arauca
state, who knew a local FARC commander. The guerrilla told the
delegate that he had no problem with Freitas' work.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the delegate says that he tried to discourage Freitas
from coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to warn Terry,'' the delegate says. ``His mistake
was to focus too much on the U'wa without better looking into the
socio-political reality of the area. Poor guy.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gay and Washinawatok, it was their first trip to Colombia.
If not exactly innocents abroad, they had a somewhat romantic view
of the FARC and little understanding of the deep rift between the
guerrillas and the U'wa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FARC was not a problem. That's what Lahe'ena'e thought,
because that's what she had been told,'' says John Livingstone,
Gay's husband.
</P>
<P>
   Washinawatok considered herself more a friend of the FARC than a
foe, says her husband, Ali El-Issa. After all, she had studied
Spanish in communist Cuba, where she had shaken hands with Fidel
Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ingrid wasn't worried about the FARC,'' El-Issa says. ``She
never thought the FARC would do anything to her.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the Americans had a grand old time with the
U'wa. They made dozens of friends as they toured communities and
received gifts of arrows and woven baskets.
</P>
<P>
   But back in New York, El-Issa was nervous. He knew that his wife
sometimes scoffed at danger as she went about her work. When she
made her final telephone call from Colombia, he admonished her to
play it safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Sweetheart, use your brain, not your sympathy.' She
said everything is fine, no problem. She told me: `Ali, I am with
my people. I feel like I am back on the reservation in
Wisconsin.'''
</P>
<P>
   That was Feb. 18. A week later, the guerrillas pulled Freitas,
Gay and Washinawatok from the Toyota pickup to begin the long march
to the killing field.
</P>
<P>
   U'wa leader Roberto Cobaria, who witnessed the abduction,
immediately sent a fax to the U.S. Embassy in Bogota explaining
what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, relatives and family friends worked around
the clock. They burned up the telephone lines and sent e-mail
messages to FARC contacts in Colombia, Mexico, Ecuador and Europe.
Several packed their bags for a possible trip to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all activists,'' says Dean Cycon, a lawyer and one of
Washinawatok's close friends. ``It's not like we're some family
sitting around waiting for the government to do something for us.
We immediately went into high gear.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, word that the three were in the hands of the FARC was
a relief. That's because when dealing with captives, the guerrillas
are generally more humane than drug traffickers, right-wing
paramilitaries and criminal gangs _ groups that also kidnap at will
in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   But Grannobles and his FARC units in Arauca are seen as the evil
exception.
</P>
<P>
   Also disturbing was the lack of any word from the FARC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would have welcomed a ransom demand _ anything that
would have said that there's a negotiation and that there is
time,'' says Jose Barreiro, another friend of Washinawatok's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
