<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0109 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-MURDERS-$ADV     10-07 1533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-MURDERS-$ADV10-4THTAK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
LOS PAJAROS, Venezuela: of Washinawatok's.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Officials at the U.S. Embassy in Bogota tried to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. government took as many steps as we could think of to
get the message to the FARC that this was very critical, and that,
in other words, `You've made a mistake. Let these people go,'''
says a U.S. official who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``But
they basically said: `We don't know anything.'``
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on the morning of March 4, the guerrillas in Arauca
told the Red Cross that FARC units in the region were holding
Freitas, Washinawatok and Gay. However, moments later, word came
that three bodies had turned up on the Venezuelan border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial report was of two male bodies and one woman. We
thought: This cannot be them. It doesn't match,'' Abby Reyes
recalls. ``One of us then talked directly with Venezuelan police.
One woman with an eagle tattoo, the other with a triangle. And one
young man with dark curly hair. It's them.''
</P>
<P>
   Interceptions of FARC radio messages by Colombian intelligence
agencies indicate that the kidnappers were suspicious of the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely these SOBs are from the CIA,'' Rafael, a member of the
FARC's 45th Front, says on a tape-recorded intercept the day after
the kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   FARC fighters are notoriously paranoid about foreigners, because
Washington supplies a huge amount of military aid to Colombia. At
any given time, there are 200 to 300 U.S. military advisers on the
ground assisting the army and police.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts say, it would have been simple for the
guerrillas to confirm the Americans' identities. Mesa, of Free
Country, points out that the rebels are old pros at compiling
profiles of hostages, which they later use to calculate the amount
of their ransom demands.
</P>
<P>
   Colombian gumshoes believe that the guerrillas knew exactly who
they were dealing with.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators contend that the FARC specifically targeted the
Americans and were tipped off about their travel plans by an U'wa
Indian informant. An official at the prosecutor-general's office in
Bogota claims that the guerrillas planned all along to do away with
the Americans in order to intimidate the U'wa and scare off other
foreign activists.
</P>
<P>
   Another scenario comes from Colombian army chief Jorge Enrique
Mora. Deep in the jungle, he says, Ingrid Washinawatok was
apparently bitten by a spider and became extremely ill. Saddled
with a sick hostage and on the run from an army offensive, the FARC
may have panicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think to take care of the problem, they decided to kill all
three,'' Mora says.
</P>
<P>
   In a Feb. 27 radio intercept, Grannobles, the FARC leader in
Arauca, and another guerrilla discuss how a woman was bitten by a
spider and taken to a clinic for treatment but how nothing could be
done for her.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Rafael says to Grannobles: ``Tell the boss that
there are two women and a man, and that one is at the point of
dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Grannobles then offers a reply that intelligence officials
interpret as an order to execute the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the fertilizer factory they sell cyanide, which is a mortal
poison. Buy a kilo, and apply it to the three, and make sure to
water them well.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor-general's office has indicted Grannobles, who is
named as the ``intellectual author'' of the triple homicide, as
well as the suspected U'wa informant. But Mora believes that
Grannobles' brother, Jorge Briceno, was also involved.
</P>
<P>
   Briceno, the FARC's second most powerful commander, is believed
to oppose negotiations with the government, because the war has
been profitable for the rebels. Killing the Americans, analysts
say, may have been a way to anger the U.S. government, which has
backed the peace process, and to sabotage the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The radio intercepts indicate that Briceno might have signed off
on the executions, with the caveat that they be carried out on the
other side of the Arauca River in Venezuelan territory.
</P>
<P>
   On March 2, two days before the slayings, Grannobles tells the
guerrilla Rafael: ``The boss authorized the thing, but it's got to
be done on the other side so as not to leave any evidence. ... Take
care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   With its arbitrary decrees and draconian sentences, the FARC's
jungle justice may seem hopelessly out of balance. That's why few
people in the United States or Colombia take FARC spokesman Raul
Reyes seriously when he pledges that there will be a day of
reckoning.
</P>
<P>
   For example, instead of pinpointing top-echelon commanders like
Grannobles or Jorge Briceno, the FARC initially blamed the killings
on a rebel named Gildardo. But Mora, the army chief, says that
Gildardo doesn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes insists that the culprits could face a firing squad. But
Olga Marin, Reyes' wife and a prominent FARC member, says that the
guilty will atone for their sins through forced labor and, if they
are illiterate, by learning how to read.
</P>
<P>
   All along, the FARC has ignored requests by the families of the
victims for a coherent account of what happened. When asked about
the case, Jorge Briceno recently complained: ``Three gringos die,
and it turns into a major brouhaha.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the bloodletting was, indeed, a watershed.
</P>
<P>
   It led to an immediate cutoff in contacts between the Clinton
administration and the guerrillas shortly after the first-ever
meeting, held in Costa Rica, between a State Department official
and a FARC representative.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans cited the slayings as another reason
to beef up U.S. assistance to the Colombian army. Lawmakers are now
studying the Bogota government's request for $1.5 billion in aid
from the United States, much of which would go toward fighting the
FARC.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, several Americans have endorsed an open-door policy
and have traveled to FARC territory to find out more.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most bizarre meetings, Richard Grasso, the
president of the New York Stock Exchange, spent several hours with
Raul Reyes talking about the slayings, the war and the future of
Colombia. Upon leaving, the two men embraced, and Grasso invited
Reyes to visit Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of such ice-breaking encounters argue that keeping
the guerrillas isolated only abets their violent ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rebels are in a separate world,'' says Michael Shifter of
the Inter-American Dialogue. ``So it's crucial to take advantage of
every opportunity to give them a sense of how the world works. This
will break down the narrow mentality that they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Shifter and others believe that the killings led to an internal
debate within the FARC and possibly strengthened the hand of
moderate rebel leaders who support the peace process. Still, 10
months after formal talks were supposed to start, the rebels have
yet to negotiate, and the war rages on.
</P>
<P>
   The calamity in Colombia also led to some corporate soul
searching at Occidental Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Terry Freitas was difficult to ignore, since his
body lay at a funeral home a half-block from Occidental
headquarters before being flown to New Mexico for burial. Amid a
new round of pro-U'wa demonstrations in April, 13 percent of
Occidental shareholders voted for a resolution to carry out a
risk-analysis study of the Samore oil project.
</P>
<P>
   But Occidental spokesman Lawrence Meriage insists that the
company will go forward with its drilling plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't really changed our focus,'' Meriage says of the
murders. ``I'm convinced that the tack we've been on from the very
beginning has been an honorable one.''
</P>
<P>
   The project received a partial go-ahead last month, when the
Colombian government approved Occidental's request for a permit to
drill an appraisal well just outside the U'wa reservation. Drilling
is expected to begin next year.
</P>
<P>
   Critics question the timing of the decision, which came just one
month after the government nearly quadrupled the size of the U'wa
reservation _ from 150,000 acres to 543,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   But at a September news conference, Environmental Minister Juan
Mayr denied suggestions that enlarging the reservation was a
calculated move to win U'wa support for the oil project. The
expansion, he argued, would guarantee the survival of the U'wa
culture in the face of petroleum development.
</P>
<P>
   U'wa lawyer Ebaristo Tegria disagrees and insists that
collective suicide remains an option for the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Hawaii, John Livingstone continues the work of his
wife, Lahe'ena'e Gay, at Pacific Cultural Conservancy
International.
</P>
<P>
   In Wisconsin, Ingrid Washinawatok, who left behind a 14-year-old
son, is buried on Menominee Indian lands. There are plans to
establish an Indian research center in her honor.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Freitas' funeral was held on Michael Gold's ranch in New
Mexico. His body was wrapped in sage leaves and red cloth, then
gently lowered into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Among the U'wa, Freitas lives on as part of the tribe's oral
history, which takes a full two weeks to sing.
</P>
<P>
   In the final verse, the U'wa intone the memory of an American
who came to help, leaving his family in the north crying.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
