<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0110 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-LINEUP-HNS     10-07 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-LINEUP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Derek Bell spent the first two games of the National League
Division Series cheering for his teammates, razzing Braves third
baseman Chipper Jones from the bench and otherwise adjusting to his
role as a $5 million cheerleader.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today he'll get a chance to do what he's paid quite handsomely
to do.
</P>
<P>
   Because lefthander Tom Glavine will start for the Braves, Astros
manager Larry Dierker will tweak his outfield alignment, starting
two righthanded hitters who were in the dugout in Atlanta _ Bell in
right field and Matt Mieske in left.
</P>
<P>
   Bell wasn't sure he would see his name in the starting lineup
after he was benched during the last week of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That definitely went through my mind,'' said Bell, who
struggled through the worst season of his career in 1999. ``I
wasn't sure I was going to get to play again. That just goes to
show that if you keep the right attitude and the right frame of
mind, things will work out in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker is hoping his lineup change will work out in the end.
Bell and Mieske will replace Stan Javier and Daryle Ward,
respectively. Ward never has faced Glavine, and Javier has only two
hits in 27 career at-bats against the Braves lefthander.
</P>
<P>
   Mieske, whom the Astros acquired in a trade with the Seattle
Mariners in June, was brought to Houston for situations such as
this. He hit .354 against lefthanders this season, which is
indicative of the way he has performed against lefties throughout
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I anticipated a situation like this going into the playoffs,
because I knew we would be facing Tom Glavine if we played the
Braves or Randy Johnson and Omar Daal if we played the
Diamondbacks,'' said Mieske, who was slowed by back problems over
the final month of the season. ``I figured I'd get to play at some
point. It's just a thrill to be starting a playoff game, and I'm
looking forward to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was traded, I knew there was a good chance this team
was going to the playoffs, and I specifically thought of situations
just like this. It's a big game, but I'm not going to approach
anything differently. I know I'm ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons Bell was benched was because Dierker and
general manager Gerry Hunsicker didn't believe he was ready to play
every day after missing two weeks with pulled rib-cage muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has had only one at-bat since Sept. 28, Bell
believes he's ready to help his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to get the chance to play again,'' said Bell, who
hit a career-low .236 this season. ``I've been taking a lot of
extra batting practice, and I feel like I'm ready to help the team.
No matter what happens, I know that everyone in this clubhouse is
going to be behind me, and that feels good.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of team we have, and that's why I was trying
to stay positive and support the guys when I wasn't playing. I
wasn't going to give up on them just because of the kind of season
I had. How could I give up on them when they never turned their
back on me?''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bell and Mieske view today as an opportunity to make a
larger contribution to the team, but even if they're back on the
bench Saturday when righthander John Smoltz starts, they will
continue to contribute in any way they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may just be a role player or bench player or whatever phrase
you want to use, but there's a lot of satisfaction in this job,''
Mieske said. ``There are a lot of guys who play every day who would
love to be playing in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a chance to win this thing, and I'll take that
opportunity any day, no matter what my role is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
