<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0112 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BO     10-07 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS ROUT RED SOX, 11-1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  CLEVELAND _ The debate over when Pedro Martinez makes his
next start could be a short one.
</P>
<P>
   Try Opening Day 2000.
</P>
<P>
   If Martinez isn't sidelined first by his bad back, he may be
rendered obsolete by the Cleveland Indians. The Indians seized a
2-0 Division Series advantage over the reeling Red Sox with an 11-1
bashing here Thursday that began in late-afternoon shadows and
ended in darkness, the proper coda for the worst postseason defeat
ever absorbed by the Olde Towne Team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 'em right where we want 'em,'' said shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra, masking his disappointment behind a show of hollow
bravado. ``We're exactly where we want to be. They feel good about
themselves, and we're going home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nothing you can say. The score speaks for
itself. They really beat us. They took it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, whose older brother Ramon is all that stands between
the Red Sox and elimination in Game 3 after their 18th loss in
their last 19 postseason outings, was neither guaranteeing another
start nor conceding defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a loser,'' he said. ``I expect to win the next time.''
</P>
<P>
   All season, Pedro the Younger has said his goal was to extend
this season deeper into October than the Sox did last year, when
they were ousted by the Indians in four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try,'' he said, ``but you can't help Mother Nature. If it's
meant not to happen, it's meant not to happen. But there's still
time. Plenty of chances. Plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   Those chances evaporated quickly for Bret Saberhagen, a profile
in courage so many times in two years with the Sox, but a portrait
of frustration Thursday. Saberhagen walked more batters (3) in the
Indians' six-run third inning than he did in all but two of his 22
starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cranky shoulder? No, Saberhagen said. Blame it more on a crack
in composure. ``I maybe felt, I don't know, I shouldn't say too
good,'' Saberhagen said, ``but maybe I had too much adrenaline
going. I was a little too excited. It just didn't happen today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox once again paid dearly for careless defense. Second
baseman Jose Offerman's inability to turn a double play in the
third inning was not as flagrant a mistake as third baseman John
Valentin's throwing error in Game 1, but it ultimately had
consequences even more devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman threw high to first baseman Mike Stanley after taking
Nomar Garciaparra's feed on Sandy Alomar's routine grounder.
Instead of two on and nobody out, Alomar reached safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on first and I'm thinking, `We've got a cripple on first
and a cripple at bat,'' said Fryman, who is playing with a brace on
his right knee to protect a torn ligament while Alomar missed 125
games this season after knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a double play for sure. Sandy just hustled
and it turned out to be a big play in the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Kenny Lofton, worked Saberhagen for a
full-count walk on a 10-pitch at-bat, and Omar Vizquel followed
with a two-run triple into a sun-drenched right-field corner, just
out of the reach of rookie Trot Nixon. Gone was the Red Sox' 1-0
lead, created by Nixon's double and Offerman's single in the top of
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   On deck, more carnage, which tends to happen against the
Indians, the team of a thousand runs. Robbie Alomar lashed a double
to right, scoring Vizquel to make it 3-1. Jim Thome walked. Harold
Baines, the 40-year-old Cleveland DH born when Ike was still
President, followed with a three-run home run.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen was finished, and so were the Sox. An inning later,
John Wasdin gave up a grand slam to Thome, and they might as well
have invoked the 10-run rule as Indians starter Charles Nagy, of
the Fairfield, Conn., Nagys, breezed through a Sox lineup that has
scored three runs and managed 11 hits, seven of them singles, in
two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team with a 10-run lead in the (fourth) inning, their
pitching is going to be pretty good,'' said catcher Jason Varitek,
who has no hits in eight at-bats in the No. 3 hole, his best effort
dying on the track in left fielder David Justice's glove in the
first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Even Garciaparra, the Indian slayer, went out quietly, failing
to get the ball out of the infield in three trips. By the time the
Sox arrived at their last at-bats, Lou Merloni was the Sox cleanup
hitter in Garciaparra's place. The Framingham Kid popped out to
Robbie Alomar to end the game, and the Sox headed for home, with
any designs of returning dependent on winning two games this
weekend at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The task of extending autumn falls Saturday on a pitcher whose
first name is Nomar spelled backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to go and score some runs, take some pressure off
our pitching,'' Varitek said. ``Go out there and battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Lineup changes? Williams already tried that Thursday, benching
the bollixed Belleville Basher, Brian Daubach, and Darren Lewis,
the sore-wristed center fielder, in favor of Butch Huskey and Damon
Buford. Net gain on those moves? Oh for six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, maybe I'll get a hold of George Herman,'' said
Williams, invoking the formal name of the Babe after an afternoon
in which the Indians made like the '27 Yankees, abetted by nine
walks by Sox pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want me to do, boys and girls? I'm going to bring
the same group that brung us.''
</P>
<P>
   Will that be enough?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up, 2-0,'' Robbie Alomar said, ``but there's still a
long way to go. One of the reasons the Red Sox are here is they
have a great team. Teams have been down 2-0 and come back before.''
</P>
<P>
   But never the Red Sox. Not in this century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
