<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0118 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-MUNICIPALS-2T     10-07 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-MUNICIPALS-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUNICIPAL BONDS CAN PROVIDE A HEDGE WITH LIMITED THORNS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Minn., Ill., Calif.)   (af)  
 By ABBY SCHULTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, the headlines and the total return figures for municipal
bonds the last 12 months have made for ugly reading. Do the math,
though, and munis and muni bond funds come up a pretty attractive
buy.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal bond prices have been beaten down by a global flight
to supersafe Treasury bonds, booming equity markets and the whiff
of flat-tax talk in the presidential election campaign, according
to David W. Baldt, portfolio manager of Morgan Grenfell's municipal
bond funds. (Proposals like those for a flat tax would generally
strip municipals of their tax advantage over other bonds.)
</P>
<P>
   As a result, yields on municipals are now very attractive for
investors who want to limit risk in their portfolios, and they
compare favorably with Treasuries. On Sept. 30, top-quality 30-year
munis yielded 5.70 percent, on average, or 94.4 percent of the
yield on a 30-year Treasury bond, before taking taxes into account.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, muni bond yields are only 82 percent to 85 percent
of Treasury yields, said Steven D. Harrop, a portfolio manager at
Strong Capital Management in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Because municipal bond interest is not taxable for most
investors, after-tax yields work out very much in the munis' favor:
to beat that average yield on a 30-year triple-A rated muni after
taxes, a taxable investment like a Treasury bond would have to
yield 7.9 percent for investors in the 28 percent tax bracket or
8.9 percent for those in the 36 percent bracket; the actual long
bond yield that day was just 6.04 percent. (To find a
taxable-equivalent yield, subtract your tax rate from 1 and divide
the remainder into the yield.)
</P>
<P>
   The next question for investors is how best to buy municipals _
and the answer is not simple. Buying bonds directly, rather than
investing through a bond mutual fund, makes sense for investors who
want to hold the investment to maturity and recoup their principal
on that date. Investors who want a more flexible vehicle might
choose a fund instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a bond fund, there is no `maturity,''' noted David P.
Dresbach, a certified financial planner in St. Paul. Managers of
open-end mutual funds trade securities almost every day as money
flows in and out of the fund, and the portfolio is always being
refreshed with new bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Buying bonds directly also means a bigger commitment of money.
Bonds generally cost at least $5,000 apiece and should be traded in
lots of at least $20,000 to get better prices. Experts say an
adequately diversified portfolio requires $100,000 or more. Bond
funds, of course, provide such economies of scale _ and generally
require small minimum investments.
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration is credit risk. Muni bonds come in all
credit ratings, from sterling to junk, and some are not even rated
by independent agencies. Researching such bonds is possible for
professional managers but impractical for many investors, Dresbach
said.
</P>
<P>
   So a bond fund may be the answer for someone who does not have
$100,000 to commit to municipals or does not want exposure to
unknown risks. A fund can also offer greater flexibility and
opportunity to realize capital appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   If a bond fund is right for you, there is another fork in the
road: Should you choose an open-end fund, one whose price reflects
its net asset value, or a closed-end fund, which trades like a
stock?
</P>
<P>
   ``For most investors, it makes sense to start off simple and
work with the open-end fund,'' says Eric Jacobson, associate editor
at Morningstar Inc., the financial publisher in Chicago. He said
closed-end funds, which trade like stocks, were more suitable for
investors with sizable muni portfolios and plenty of time to study
their quirks.
</P>
<P>
   Open-end funds are often grouped by geography: funds that
concentrate on bonds from a single state and national funds that
buy munis from anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
