<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0120 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-MUNICIPALS-2N     10-07 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-MUNICIPALS-2NDTAKE-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: from anywhere.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Single-state funds provide investors in that state with income
that is free of federal, state and any city income taxes. They are
especially attractive for investors in high-tax states like New
York and California; they offer no advantage over national funds
for anyone not subject to that state's income tax.
</P>
<P>
   But single-state funds can have two disadvantages. Trouble in
that state's economy or politics, like the bankruptcy of Orange
County, Calif., in 1994, can send them sinking. And because demand
for municipal bonds is highest in states where taxes are highest,
muni yields in those states tend to be lower than elsewhere,
sometimes low enough to undo the benefit of the state-tax
exemption, said Harrop at Strong, whose company offers only
national funds.
</P>
<P>
   Both state and national funds may be divided into categories
based on the maturities of their bonds, from money market to long
term. Yields are higher with longer maturities, but so are the
risks that investors will be exposed to price volatility or locked
into interest rates that do not keep pace with inflation.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting offshoot of the national-fund category is the
high-yield muni fund, so called because its portfolio tilts heavily
toward bonds with low-credit ratings or none at all _ in other
words, the least expensive and riskiest bonds. About 87 percent of
the $98 million portfolio of Heartland High Yield Municipal Bond,
for instance, is in nonrated securities, according to Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   Baldt at Morgan Grenfell said most investors should give these
types of funds a wide berth because they de-emphasize a goal of
most bond funds _ preservation of principal.
</P>
<P>
   With a muni fund, he said, ``you are really not looking to shoot
the lights out with high returns.'' High-yield bonds are
speculative but their historical returns are far below those of the
stock market, he added, and they usually do not outpace
higher-rated bonds by enough to be worth the added risk.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobson at Morningstar says some high-yield managers find
good buys. ``You want to try to identify a fund with a good record
of managing its credit risk in the past,'' he said. One sign is
whether a fund's net asset value has ever eroded sharply. If it
has, find out from the fund if defaulted bonds were the reason,
Jacobson said, though he added that such information is not the
easiest to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their open-end cousins, closed-end funds trade on
exchanges through brokers just as stocks do. That is where the
quirks come in: most closed-end funds trade at a discount to their
net asset value and are best bought in the secondary market, not
when first issued. The discount bolsters the effective yield of the
fund, just as buying a bond at a price below face value increases
its yield.
</P>
<P>
   Many closed-end funds are leveraged to further strengthen their
yield, meaning that they borrow money at short-term rates, usually
by selling shares of preferred stock, and use the proceeds to buy
longer-term, higher-yielding investments. The difference between
the two turns into added yield for fund shareholders, said Jeffrey
Kratz, director of exchange-traded fund marketing at John Nuveen &AMP;
Co. in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, closed-end funds typically yield a
percentage point more than their open-end counterparts. But the
leverage also amplifies the funds' vulnerability to interest rate
risk compared with that of open-end funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
