First, she acts. Then, every night after the show, she helps to
sell her homemade vanilla cupcakes in the lobby. ``It's great,''
Ms. Sedaris says. ``And I go home with 25 bucks in my pocket.''
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- TANDEM-BIKES-B&AMP;W, 10-07 --
Participants in an annual Tandem Weekend ride, starting in
Millville, N.J., and covering more than 50 miles. A good road
tandem bike starts at more than $2,000, and the best models run
$5,000 or more. (Allen St. John/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Oct. 7, 1999 --
ONLINE-RETAILERS-ART-BOS, 10-07 -- From left, John Burke, director
of network and operations for toysmart.com; Wayne Teres, toysmart's
director of logistics and Devdutt Yellurkar, chief executive of
Yantra Corp., in toysmart.com's warehouse. ``People try a Web site
once, and if they have a problem, they never come back,'' said
Yellurkar, whose company helps Web sites such as toysmart.com
manage their warehouses. (Tom Landers/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- HOME-TRENDS-COX, 10-07 --
Reggie Glow is latest in a collection of kid-resistant floor
coverings manufactured by Shaw Industries in Dalton, Ga. Reggie
Glow, a berber-style, loop-pile carpet, has designs that glow in
the dark. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- HARVARD-VENTURA-BOS,
10-07 --Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota, center, talks to members
of the Harvard football team on Wednesday. On the heels of his
candid and explosive interview with Playboy Magazine, Minnesota's
maverick governor brought his politics-cum-entertainment to the
august halls of Harvard University's John F. Kennedy School of
Government. (Bill Brett/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- CONGRESS-CRUISE-SHIPS,
10-07 -- Jim Hall, chairman of the National Transportation Safety
Board, listens to Marjorie Murtagh, also from the NTSB, during
their appearance before the House Subcommittee on Coast Guard and
Maritime Transportation on Thursday. The committee is looking into
the cruise ship industry's overall record on security, medical care
and environmental compliance. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) FOXBORO, Mass. -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS, 10-07
-- Ty Law hangs on to Marvin Harrison of the Indianapolis Colts
during a game last month. In Law's eyes, the season is a 15-round
heavyweight fight. There's no room for rest and relaxation. He
doesn't like the way he's played in the Patriots' 4-0 start. He
doesn't particularly care for the zone defenses the Patriots have
been playing, which have taken him out of his true element:
man-on-man coverage. But he's not mad at anyone but himself,
because he feels he simply hasn't played as well as he should have.
(Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- WEB-TRAFFIC-BOS,
10-07 -- Paul Sagan, president of Akamai Technologies Inc. and a
second cousin of Carl Sagan, the late astronomer, in the control
room of his company earlier this week. On Saturday millions of
people worldwide are expected to log on to their computers for
NetAid, a seven-hour concert billed by its promoters as the largest
Internet event in history. A mathematical equation which is part of
a program belonging to Akamai Technologies Inc. is expected to keep
the concert broadcast from crashing online. (Janet Knott/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- MOZART-EFFECT-BOS,
10-07 -- Evan Brothers naps with his stuffed animal at Les Petits
Nursery school last Friday as the sounds of classical music filled
the room. Classical music has been a 30-year staple at the school
where director Debra Nickerson says it helps the kids nap. (David
L. Ryan/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CAMBRIDGE, Mass -- Oct. 7, 1999 --
COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS, 10-07 -- John Hargrave and Jay Stevens
during the filming of ``Computer Stew,'' one of their shows for the
internet, last Monday. The daily show is filmed in the offices of
ZDNet, an on-line publisher of technology news. Hargrave convinced
the firm's executives to sponsor the show, which he began producing
on April Fools' Day. The show debuted officially this month.
(Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
