<P>
   (NYT42) BOSTON -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- HAWKING-TOUR-BOS, 10-07 -- Dr.
Stephen Hawking uses a computer to speak to Maggie King, 6, a
patient at Children's Hospital, during a visit on Thursday.
Hawking, 57, who suffers from Lou Gehrig's disease, or amyotrophic
lateral sclerosis (ALS), visited the hospital for a couple of hours
to learn about the latest in communication aids for the disabled as
well as to do a little role-modeling. (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) EL AGUACATE, Honduras -- Oct. 7, 1999 --
HONDURAS-GUERILLAS, 10-07 -- Bones and traces of human blood have
been discovered in this cramped and roofless red brick building,
once part of what was once Honduras's longest and busiest military
airstrip. The debate over El Aguacate's cold war history has been
revived as Honduran officials have started investigating assertions
that such sites were home to torture chambers and clandestine
graves. (David Gonzalez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- COLLEGES-ECONOMY-2,
10-07 --The groundbreaking ceremony in Kendall Square for a new
facility for Biogen, the biotech company. The building, to be
completed by spring 2001, will accommodate 400 new employees and
will roughly double Biogen's research and development laboratory
capacity. (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) ALEXANDRIA, Va. -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- POWELL-YOUTH, 09-30
-- Gen. Colin Powell, the former chairman of the Joints Chief of
Staff, in his office during an interview last week. The retired
four-star general, credited by many for victory in the Gulf War, is
learning a lesson in humility. Critics say the charity he leads,
America's Promise - The Alliance for Youth, has inflated its
results, and the organization concedes it will have to operate well
beyond its original deadline to achieve its goals. (Shana Raab/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) UNDATED -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- MILITARY-CYBER-WARFARE, 10-07
-- Adm. Harold W. Gehman, Jr., in an undated file photo. The
Defense Department on Thursday appointed Gehman as head of the
Joint Forces Command which will coordinate military actions against
any hostile activity targeting the U.S. including biological,
chemical or nuclear attacks. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- TEST-BAN-TREATY-2, 10-07
-- Sen. Jesse Helms, R-S.C., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, during a news conference on Wednesday. With
the Senate poised to reject a treaty banning nuclear weapons tests,
the Clinton administration appealed Thursday for a delay in the
vote so it can try to muster support for it. Helms, a leading
critic of the treaty, on Thursday said Clinton must withdraw the
treaty from consideration until after next year's presidential
election if he wants next Tuesday's scheduled vote called off.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
