<P>
   (NYT29) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- COLLEGES-ECONOMY,
10-07 -- An artist's rendering of Biogen's new 210,000-square-foot
research and development building. The new building, to be
completed by Spring 2001, will accommodate 400 new employees and
will roughly double Biogen's research and development laboratory
capacity. Across America, researchers say, high-tech is creating
localized boomlets like the one in Kendall Square, which houses not
only biotech companies like Biogen, but software and other
companies. (Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WINTER HAVEN, Fla. -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- DUCK-CROSSING,
10-07 -- Ducks cross a yard in this central Florida city on
Thursday. It is not unusual to see ducks crossing through yards in
this neighborhood, which is between two lakes, but residents are
always amazed at how close to the sign the duck crossings
frequently take place. (Paul Johnson/The Lakeland Ledger) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) McCOOK, Ill. -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 10
-- BIZ-PROFILE-LYNCH, 10-07 -- Michael W. Lynch, the chairman of
McCook Metals, with rolled metal products at the company's plant, a
former Reynolds aluminum mill in McCook, just west of Chicago.
``I'm a street fighter, and if someone tells me I can't do
something, I get an endorphin rush,'' says Lynch, 39. (Steve
Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) TOKYO -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 10 --
MUTFUND-INTERNATIONAL, 10-07 -- Seung K. Kwak manages the Japan
Fund, up 121.3 percent in the 12 months through Sept. 30. Kwak, 38,
says he tries to capture the extra return between other investors'
short-term valuation of a stock and his own assessment of the value
three to four years in the future. (Stuart Isett/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) CLARK FORK, Mont. -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
10 -- BIZ-DAMS-B&AMP;W, 10-07 -- Noxon Rapids, a 466-megawatt dam on
the Clark Fork River in Montana, is owned by the Avista Corp. Noxon
and another Avista dam on the Clark Fork, Cabinet Gorge in Idaho,
are at the center of a complex and unusual licensing agreement.
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) CHICAGO -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 10 --
MUTFUND-OVERVIEW-2, 10-07 -- Robert Sanborn, portfolio manager of
the Oakmark Fund in Chicago, says investors would be better off
with an index fund or an actively managed fund rather than a
``closet index'' fund. ``Having a guy manage a closet index fund,
charging active fees, is a very poor value,'' he says. (Steve
Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) MALVERN, Pa. -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 10
-- MUTFUND-OVERVIEW-1, 10-07 -- John C. Bogle, the founder of the
Vanguard Group, objects to the practice of mimicking index funds.
``If it looks like a duck, walks like a duck, quacks like a duck,
it's probably a duck,'' he says. ``You're paying a ton more, and
you're getting more turnover, which is a horrible tax expense, and
you're getting fees that are extremely difficult to justify.'' (Tim
Shaffer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) CHICAGO -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 10 --
MUTFUND-MANAGERS-3, 10-07 -- Andrew S. Cupps, manager of the Strong
Enterprise fund, looks for leaders in growing industries,
``companies that can capitalize on opportunities in a changing
world.'' Last quarter, he found winners in new technology. (Steve
Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) STAMFORD, Conn. -- Oct. 7, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
10 -- MUTFUND-MANAGERS-2, 10-07 -- ``This year is the exact
opposite of last year, when you wanted to own the big safe
havens,'' says Mary Lisanti, who manages Northstar Special.
