<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-SYPHILIS-ART-NYT &LR;      10-07 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SYPHILIS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. STANDS POISED TO VANQUISH SYPHILIS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the nation's syphilis rate at the lowest level
since the government began keeping statistics in 1941, federal
health officials said Thursday that they believed they could
eliminate the disease from the United States in the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Just 6,993 cases of syphilis were recorded last year, down from
8,556 in 1997 and from 50,578 in 1990, when the disease last
reached its peak, according to the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta. The national rate dropped 19 percent from
1997 to 1998, to 2.6 cases per 100,000 people from 3.2 cases per
100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The disease control centers said half of all syphilis cases were
concentrated in 28 of the nation's 3,100 counties, which gives
public health officials an edge in curbing the disease by tracking
down infected people and treating them.
</P>
<P>
   The agency attributed the decline to prevention efforts,
including those aimed at reducing the spread of AIDS. And for
reasons scientists cannot quite explain, the disease runs in cycles
of seven to 10 years; the cycle is now at its low ebb. The goal is
to keep it from ever rising again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stars are aligned for us to get this done,'' Dr. Jeffrey
Koplan, director of the CDC, said in an interview on Wednesday.
``For a modern, industrialized wealthy nation to tolerate the
continued transmission of this disease should be unacceptable. We
don't have to have it here.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other countries, including Canada, England, Sweden and
Denmark, have already eliminated syphilis, a centuries-old disease
that can be treated easily, and cheaply, with a single dose of
penicillin. (Remarkably, unlike many other bacteria, syphilis has
never developed antibiotic resistance.)
</P>
<P>
   To move the United States closer to its goal of elimination,
Koplan announced a new effort Thursday, focusing on 33 states and
cities with either a heavy burden of syphilis or a high potential
for re-emergence.
</P>
<P>
   The agency estimates that the effort will cost $37 million each
year for the next five years, said Dr. Judith Wasserheit, who
directs the CDC's Division of Sexually Transmitted Disease
Prevention. But Dr. Wasserheit said the direct and indirect costs
of syphilis, which can be spread from mother to child and also
helps spread the AIDS virus, were nearly $1 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are really going to put syphilis up on the shelf next to
diseases like cholera or malaria that are no longer a threat in
this country,'' she said, ``we have got to act now.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing its new program, the agency identified the 28
counties with the highest numbers of syphilis cases. Baltimore was
first, with 456 cases, followed by Cook County, Ill., which
includes Chicago, with 364 cases, and Shelby County, Tenn.
(Memphis), with 343 cases. New York did not make the list; it was
ranked 44th among cities with more than 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Syphilis is caused by a spirochete, a kind of bacterium. Its
first symptoms are genital sores, but the sores go away without
treatment and patients often do not realize they are infected. Six
weeks to several months later, patients experience a rash, which
fades if left untreated. The disease can then recur later in life,
causing heart damage, blindness and, ultimately, dementia.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the obvious public health benefits, wiping out syphilis
is important to the government for two reasons. First, the Clinton
administration has made eliminating racial disparities in disease
one of its top priorities, and in syphilis the disparity is
especially stark.
</P>
<P>
   According to the CDC, African-Americans are 34 times as likely
as whites to be reported with syphilis; this gap has narrowed from
as much as 64 times as high earlier in the decade. The rate for
blacks in 1998 was 17.1 cases per 100,000 people; for whites, it
was 0.5 per 100,000. In addition, African-American babies account
for nearly two-thirds of all cases of congenital syphilis.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, syphilis was at the center of perhaps the most
infamous episode in the history of medical research sponsored by
the government: the notorious Tuskegee experiment, in which poor
black men with the disease were recruited by federal health
researchers and then left untreated. In 1997, President Clinton
issued a formal apology to the few remaining survivors of the
experiment, which began in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   The memory of Tuskegee, and the distrust it engenders, resonates
strongly among African-Americans, said Dr. Stephanie Bailey,
director of the county health department in Nashville. ``I go and
present this data'' on syphilis ``to our black communities,
especially our religious leaders, and they bring up Tuskegee,'' Dr.
Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Dr. Bailey noticed the number of cases going
up in Nashville. So she drew church and school leaders, public
health officers and court officials into an antisyphilis campaign.
The cases seemed to be concentrated among prostitutes and crack
users; among the tactics the authorities used was to test the blood
of anyone jailed for crimes related to sex and drugs. They
identified 110 new cases that way.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wasserheit of the CDC said the government frittered away an
opportunity to eliminate syphilis in 1955. That year, just 6,454
cases were reported. Thinking the epidemic was over, government
officials cut financing for syphilis prevention by 85 percent, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' she said, ``was the beginning of a progressive
increase.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
