r s BC-BBA-BAINES-TEX     10-07 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BAINES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAINES HAS GOOD LUCK, AND A BIT OF PLUCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Harold Baines called himself lucky twice yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   He's lucky, he said, to be a member of the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   And he was lucky to hit a three-run homer against Bret
Saberhagen, the key blow in the 11-1 victory against the Boston Red
Sox that gave the Indians a 2-0 lead in the Division Series and put
them one victory away from advancing to the American League
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Baines is half right. He is fortunate to be with the Indians,
considering he spent most of the season with the Baltimore Orioles,
baseball's ultimate underachievers.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles were going nowhere, so on Aug. 27, they traded the
40-year-old designated hitter to the Indians, perennial AL Central
Division champions and championship contenders.
</P>
<P>
   To go from a team just playing out the season to one that has
World Series aspirations certainly can be considered good luck.
</P>
<P>
   But about that homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got the ball over the middle of the plate, and I was
fortunate enough to hit it,'' Baines said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Baines has made a long career out of similar blows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to add a professional hitter,'' Indians manager
Mike Hargrove said. ``There are guys that are absolutely pure good
hitters, and Harold brings that to the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Baines' ``fortunate'' home run came on a first-pitch fastball
after Saberhagen had walked Jim Thome. The pitcher already had
given up three runs and three walks in the inning, and Baines has
been around long enough to know he would try to get ahead in the
count.
</P>
<P>
   He got the pitch he expected. It was low but over the middle of
the plate, and Baines hit it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I made a really good pitch on Baines,'' Saberhagen
said. ``He's a good hitter, and he deposited it.''
</P>
<P>
   The home run turned a pretty good three-run inning into a
back-breaking six-run inning and gave the Indians a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harold got the home run, and I think it relaxed our dugout a
little bit,'' said Thome, who hit a grand slam the next inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was Baines' fifth career postseason home run, and the second
of his two hits in the game. He is 4-for-7 in the two games of this
series, improving his career playoff average to .341.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky? To be with the Indians, certainly. To hit the home run?
Probably not.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      10-07 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADING ENVIRONMENTALISTS PUT SUPPORT AND MONEY BEHIND GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vice President Al Gore, who prides himself for his
environmental record, was stung last month when an environmental
group, Friends of the Earth, endorsed former Sen. Bill Bradley, his
rival for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday some of Gore's supporters struck back, holding a
fund-raising lunch in midtown Manhattan that featured endorsements
from some leading New York environmentalists, including Robert F.
Kennedy Jr. and Lawrence Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our last best chance to save the planet,'' said Kennedy,
the oldest son of former Sen. Robert F. Kennedy and an
environmental lawyer, as he urged his audience to focus full time
on the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put down your litigation,'' he told the roughly 100
environmental leaders, many of them lawyers, who gave $1,000 each
to Gore. ``Put down your lobbying. Forget about Albany. Forget
about anything else you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller, the nephew of former Gov. Nelson Rockefeller and
also an environmental lawyer _ and a Republican _ said he was
crossing party lines to support Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to put party labels aside and put our kids' future
first and the earth's future,'' he said, calling Gore ``an
environmental champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Both said that Gore, author of ``Earth in the Balance,'' had led
the fight to protect air and water quality and to clean up toxic
waste sites. They also lauded him for his efforts to combat global
warming and increase the fuel efficiency of cars without increasing
the costs, and for his ``livability agenda'' to reduce traffic jams
and preserve open space.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said later that Thursday's event was held in part to
counter the Friends of the Earth's endorsement of Bradley, who the
group said was more effective in pushing environmental matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was among the events that brought us together,'' Kennedy
said, citing these others: ``Gore's getting a raw deal in the
press, that George W.'s getting a free ride and sometimes your
friends have to stand up when there's a lot of momentum against
you.'' The reference was to polls showing that Bradley is running
even, if not ahead, of the vice president in crucial states like
New York and New Hampshire and that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
the Republican front-runner, maintains a solid lead over both
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of comparing Gore's record with that of Bradley, the
Gore supporters _ and Gore himself _ compared it with that of Bush,
whose state is home to a quarter of the nation's oil refineries and
two-thirds of its chemical industries.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that Houston was overtaking Los Angeles as the city
with the worst smog in America. ``Under Governor Bush, Texas has
ranked No. 1 in America for carcinogens in the air, No. 1 in
America for toxic releases into the air, into the water and into
the soil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush had received financial backing from polluters who
opposed environmental regulations. ``That kind of approach cannot
be taken into the White House,'' Gore said, describing Bush as ``a
person who carries water _ dirty water _ for the chemical
industry.'' As applause erupted, Gore said: ``I'm going to tell it
like it is!''
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClellan, a spokesman for Bush, defended his
environmental record. Under Bush, he said, Texas has planned to
reduce air emissions by 250,000 tons annually, the equivalent of
removing 5.5 million cars from the road. He also said that Gore,
whom President George Bush once labeled ``ozone man,'' had ``a long
history of weird and extreme environmental ideas,'' including his
support for the Kyoto global-warming treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the vice president seemed to have Bradley on his mind as
he uttered some thoughts throughout his environmental speech about
``authenticity.'' Bradley supporters frequently cite that quality
as a strength in comparison with Gore, who is often criticized as
overcalculating and cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that everyone had an ``obligation to be authentic and
to integrate all the different parts of our lives into a coherent
and authentic expression of who we are and what's most important in
our lives.'' He said he had worked on environmental issues for a
long time, but then referred without elaboration to a challenge in
his personal life that forced him to think about environmental
policy anew.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks seemed to reflect his current struggle to try to
reveal more about himself in his campaign stump speech, which he
did not deliver Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as in our personal lives when we find out how to be
authentic and speak from the heart, it turns out to be easier than
any other way of being,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers Unit Endorses Gore
</P>
<P>
   The political committee of the nation's largest labor union, the
National Education Association, endorsed Gore Thursday to be the
Democratic nominee for president _ with the expectation that the
association's executive board would issue the official endorsement
of him Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the union, which has 2.5 million members, comes
after the nation's other large teachers union, the million-member
American Federation of Teachers, endorsed Gore on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The National Education Association is not part of the AFL-CIO,
which will debate at its convention next week whether to endorse
Gore. But an endorsement by the education association, because of
its membership and the size of its political action fund, is
expected to be a major boost for Gore in his race against Bradley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
