u f BC-LADN-BUSINESS &LR;      10-07 0259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUSINESS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Friday, Oct. 8 and thereafter. The stories will carry the ``f''
financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For questions
about stories, please contact Elizabeth Ferry Slocum at the Daily
News at (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   MANN-MONEY (Los Angeles) -- Alfred Mann, the biotech pioneer who
founded two multi-billion dollar companies and made international
headlines last year when he donated $100 million to both USC and
UCLA, is at it again. By Chris Sieroty and Jason Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-CONVENTION (Los Angeles) -- Nearly 1,000 union members are
expected to attend this weekend's biennial AFL-CIO convention at
the Los Angeles Convention Center, which begins Friday. Gov. Gray
Davis and the Rev. Jesse Jackson are among the well-known expected
to address one of the nation's largest unions. By Jason Takenouchi.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-BAILOUT (Los Angeles) -- Warner Bros. has decided to bail
out of its fledgling foreign theme park business, a year after
selling its dozen Six Flags sites in the United States. The studio
announced late Wednesday a $180 million deal with Six Flags buyer
Premiere Parks to sell its three-year-old Movie World theme park in
Germany and its yet-to-be-opened Movie World in Spain, along with
licensing the Looney Tunes, DC Comics and Cartoon Network
characters for use in Europe and Latin America. By Dave McNary.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
