<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Friday, Oct. 8 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please
contact Elizabeth Ferry Slocum at the Daily News at (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   WINDS-THREAT (Los Angeles) -- Strong shifting Santa Ana winds
blew through the Southland, toppling trees, boosting fire danger
and causing isolated power outages. For allergy sufferers, Thursday
was about as bad as it gets. The winds were expected to continue
Friday, with temperatures increasing about 10 degrees. No fires
broke out by Thursday afternoon, but so far this year, five times
as much acreage has burned as compared to last year. By Harrison
Sheppard. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BELMONT-TESTIMONY (Los Angeles) -- In the wake of tests showing
greater concentrations of deadly hydrogen sulfide in the ground
below the Belmont Learning Center, Los Angeles Unified
Superintendent Ruben Zacarias and school board member David
Tokofsky are scheduled to testify before a commission weighing the
merits of competing the environmentally plagued high school. By
Beth Barrett. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   ADAIR-GLARE (Los Angeles) -- During a confrontation in the San
Fernando Court bathroom, Jeannie Adair's mother-in-law told the
woman accused of killing her husband that she would ``burn for
this.'' The remarks prompted a delay in the trial, as the judge
ordered the mother-in-law to stay 500 feet away from the courthouse
for the duration of the trial. By Philip Browne. (Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MANN-MONEY (Los Angeles) -- Alfred Mann, the biotech pioneer who
founded two multi-billion dollar companies and made international
headlines last year when he donated $100 million to both USC and
UCLA, is at it again. By Chris Sieroty and Jason Cohen. (Will move
in the ``f'' financial news file.)
