<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0147 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-INQUIRY-800&AMP;AD     10-07 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INQUIRY-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA INVESTIGATING ITS BANKS FOR ROLE IN SUSPICIOUS CASH
MOVEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The nation's top tax official said that his
investigation was pointing to a single Russian bank as the
architect of the transfer of billions of dollars into accounts
under investigation in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Pochinok, the chief of the Russian State Tax Service,
declined to name the bank. But he said in an interview that a small
group of Russian businessmen appeared to have pioneered the
practice of sending money through the Bank of New York accounts
that are under investigation by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is one main bank that was at least the
ideological center,'' Pochinok said in an interview. ``The
operations were all done in a similar way. And a number of firms
are connected with the people at this bank.'' The transfers
themselves were carried out by a number of banks, and he said that
a least 10 of them are under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the money-moving schemes, Pochinok said, was to hide
income from the Russian tax authorities and avoid Russian taxes and
tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is looking at a group of accounts at the Bank of New
York that American authorities say moved nearly $7 billion out of
Russia. On Tuesday, a federal indictment was unsealed in Manhattan
charging three small American companies and three Russian
immigrants with illegally operating a money transferring business.
The bank, which is cooperating with the investigation, has not been
accused of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Since news of the federal investigation at the Bank of New York
surfaced in August, Russia's response has taken several turns. At
first, government officials dismissed the charges as a political
campaign by Republicans in Congress to isolate Russia. They also
brushed them off as an attempt to embarrass the Clinton
administration, especially Vice President Al Gore, who has touted
his personal relationship with Viktor Chernomyrdin, a former prime
minister of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Kremlin's aim appears to be to remove the taint of
corruption that has hurt all Russian businessman. The Russian
government has come under pressure by the United States to assist
its investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian anticorruption campaign has also raised concerns
here that the government may be looking for a convenient target or
scapegoat to put the inquiry behind it and divert attention from
allegations of kickbacks to the government that are unrelated to
the banking investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The tax agency has conducted two well-publicized raids on
Russian banks. While Pochinok has said he is investigating about 10
banks, he said Thursday that he plans to check more banks next
week. He declined to name all of them, saying they might sue the
government for libel unless the authorities had proof.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was concerned that some would destroy their computer
and paper records before his investigators could get to them.
Computer records at the first bank to be raided, Flamingo Bank of
Moscow, seem to have been tampered with, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That bank is the subject of a criminal investigation that opened
last week. On Tuesday, police raided Sobin Bank, which has had a
long and lucrative relationship with the Russian government and is
owned by powerful business interests.
</P>
<P>
   Pochinok said that investigators focused on Sobin Bank after
discovering payments made to the bank by Flamingo. A third bank,
Depozitarno-Kliringovy Bank, has also come under suspicion by tax
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   These banks, in turn, have links with other Russian banks and
businesses, which may also become targets of the Russian
investigation. All have denied any violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just following the path of the money,'' Pochinok said.
</P>
<P>
   As the head of the State Tax Service, Pochinok is charged with
finding violations of Russian tax laws. Pochinok said he has
received no help from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Russian investigation has already uncovered a huge
number of transactions that went through the Bank of New York
account established by Benex International Co., which the FBI said
handled nearly $5 billion of the $7 billion in Russian funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great number of banks had relations with the Bank of New
York,'' Pochinok said. ``The majority of these are normal interbank
relations. Unfortunately, among these operations there are some
that were used to evade taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An enormous number of deals were made through Benex,'' he
added. ``And I have not uncovered all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pochinok said that Benex appeared to be well known to Russian
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I can tell, everyone knew that this firm could be
used to send money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the suspicions transactions uncovered by Russian
investigators do not involve money laundering by criminal groups,
but efforts to avoid Russian tariffs and taxes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The schemes, Pochinok said, took several forms. In transactions
between Russian companies, for example, payments were made using a
series of offshore banks, the Benex accounts at the Bank of New
York and several Russian banks, he explained. ``The idea of this
scheme is conceal the source of the money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In another scheme, importers dodged tariffs by understating the
value of the goods bought from foreign suppliers. The importers
then made under-the-table payments to their foreign suppliers
through the Benex accounts.
</P>
<P>
   A third scheme, which was more popular before last year's
economic crisis, was used to hide the high prices paid for Moscow
apartments, Pochinok said. For a buyer wanting to pay $300,000 for
an apartment, for example, the official price might be set at
$30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You transfer $30,000, and $270,000 you send to the Bank of New
York account to go to the sellers,'' he explained. ``You are not
interested to show that you have this kind of money, and the seller
is not eager to pay the taxes from the sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Pochinok said that many transactions involving the Bank of New
York were legal. To find a violation, he said the authorities must
prove two things: the illegal export of hard currency and tax
evasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, we know we will be able to prove it,'' he said.
``But for this we have to pin down the entire chain.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Russian authorities have taken their first steps to
investigate the allegations pertaining to the Bank of New York, it
is still unclear how far the inquiry will go. Powerful political
interests have often shielded the banks from disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   But Pochinok insisted his inquiry would go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are adding several more to the list, and beginning next
week will check several more,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
