<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-     10-07 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN.: N.H., N.Y., N.J.)  
 BRADLEY WANTS MORE SPENDING TO EASE STRESSES ON FAMILIES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PETERBOROUGH, N.H. _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley offered his
prescription for the stresses on families of global economic
competition, calling Thursday for $3.6 billion a year in new
federal spending to expand day-care services, improve community
colleges and encourage the elderly to work with children.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in a crowded high school gym in this rustic mountain
hamlet, Bradley said the idyllic ``Norman Rockwell'' world he had
known as a child in Missouri had all but disappeared, replaced by a
high-pressure economy that often forced both parents to work and
left them little time for their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new global economy just doesn't care about the 6:30
dinner,'' Bradley told more than 1,000 students and supporters.
``It doesn't care that you don't know how to use a computer. The
global economy isn't worrying about you at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's speech came at a time when he is battling his lone
rival for the Democratic presidential nomination, Vice President Al
Gore, for the support of labor unions. Leaders of the AFL-CIO, are
debating whether to issue an endorsement at the labor federation's
meeting next week.
</P>
<P>
   Like the vice president, Bradley has come under heavy criticism
from many labor leaders for supporting trade policies, including
the North American Free Trade Agreement, that have spurred global
competition and caused, they say, layoffs and other economic
dislocations for American workers.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Bradley, a former New York Knick forward who went on
to represent New Jersey for three terms in the Senate, asserted
that he understood the strains of juggling parenthood with work,
describing how he prepared frozen dinners for his daughter in
Washington while his wife, Ernestine, taught college courses back
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took the oath of office, I raised my right hand high,
but in my left hand I held Theresa Anne,'' he said, referring to
his daughter, the couple's only child.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's speech, the second of four major policy addresses he
plans to make this fall, came a week after Bradley outlined his
proposal for extending health insurance to most Americans. Though
Bradley has criticized Gore for taking an ``incremental'' approach
to fixing the nation's problems, the plan he outlined Thursday
seemed relatively modest in scope, and included these elements:
</P>
<P>
   --The creation of a $2-billion-a-year program to finance day
care and other programs for the preschool children of working
parents of all income levels. Modeled after a North Carolina
program called ``Smart Start,'' Bradley's plan would allow
committees of local officials, business leaders, child-care workers
and parents to allocate the federal grants. The money could also be
spent counseling or education programs.
</P>
<P>
   --Giving $400 million a year in grants to community colleges, an
increase of nearly a third over current federal support. The money
could be used to improve programs intended to place students in
jobs in the local economy or to retrain older workers whose jobs
have changed or been eliminated by technological advancements. ``A
pair of strong hands are not what they used to be,'' Bradley said.
``Now those hands have to be able to use a keyboard.''
</P>
<P>
   --$200-a-month stipends to the elderly for working 15 hours a
week with young people in approved programs like tutoring or
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   --Expanding the Family and Medical Leave Act, which requires
employers with 50 or more employees to give workers up to 12 weeks
of unpaid leave a year for reasons like child-birth or family
illnesses. Bradley would expand the law to cover employers with 25
or more workers, bringing an additional 12 million people into its
reach. He would also require employers to give workers 24 unpaid
hours a year for less-pressing situations, like parent-teacher
conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has called for a similar expansion of the leave act, as
well as for increasing federal subsidies for day-care services. He
has proposed providing tax incentives to companies that offer
day-care services. And he has called for eliminating the so-called
marriage penalty that causes spouses filing joint returns to pay
higher taxes than single people.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls have shown Bradley and Gore in a dead heat in New
Hampshire, the site of the nation's first primary next February.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bradley received a standing ovation from the students,
who sat on bleachers in the rear of the gym, it was clear many of
them had no idea who he was. To underscore that point, the
principal, Susan Dell, said in her introduction of the candidate
that not a single student in one ninth grade class had heard of
Bradley, despite his candidacy and place in the basketball Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably would know this guy if he ever had played
basketball,'' one of the students told his teacher, Ms. Dell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
