<SLUG> BC-FED-POLICY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED RECONSIDERS POLICY OF DISCLOSING TILT ON RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (af)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Concerned that its latest attempt to be more open
might be confusing investors as much as helping them, the Federal
Reserve is reviewing its new practice of disclosing once-secret
decisions about tilting policy toward raising or reducing interest
rates, the central bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed said it had established a committee to study ways to
clarify the meaning of the statement the central bank issues at the
conclusion of each policy meeting. Since May, the Fed has used the
statement not only to disclose any immediate changes to monetary
policy, but also to say whether it had adopted a ``bias,'' a formal
decision that it sees a possible need to raise or lower rates in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   But it has never been clear _ to investors who bet fortunes
based on their reading of likely interest rate moves, or to Fed
officials themselves _ whether the adoption of a bias is a clear
expression of the central bank's intent to shift policy within a
month or two or a much vaguer warning.
</P>
<P>
   The establishment of the committee was disclosed in the minutes
of the Aug. 24 Fed meeting, where the central bank pushed its
benchmark federal funds target rate up by a quarter-point, to 5.25
percent, as a protective move against a possible resurgence of
inflation pressures. The minutes showed that the rate hike was
approved by a vote of 9-1.
</P>
<P>
   The lone dissenter was Robert D. McTeer Jr., president of the
Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas, who has become a leading advocate
of the theory that the economy is capable of higher rates of
noninflationary growth, in part because of huge investments by
business in efficiency-enhancing technology.
</P>
<P>
   McTeer had also dissented from the Fed's previous quarter- point
rate increase, in June. The minutes of the August meeting stated
that McTeer believed ``that positive supply-side forces will
continue to damp the impact of strong demand on output prices and
that productivity gains will continue to damp the effect of higher
wages on unit labor costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The minutes said the review of how the Fed discloses its policy
bias would be led by Roger W. Ferguson Jr., the central bank's vice
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Fed said it had adopted a bias toward tightening, a
step it followed with an interest rate increase in June. At the
June 30 meeting, it moved to a neutral bias, which many investors
took to mean that the Fed had no intention of raising rates at its
next meeting, in August.
</P>
<P>
   But in August, the Fed tightened again, and again said it had a
neutral bias. At its latest meeting, on Tuesday, the Fed held rates
steady, and moved to a tightening bias, although it added that the
adoption of the bias should not be seen as a ``commitment to
near-term action.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Fed, noted at the August
meeting that ``the sentence relating to the directive was subject
to differing interpretations,'' and that the decision to make
immediate announcements about ``significant changes in the symmetry
or asymmetry in the directive had made it desirable to clarify its
meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what steps the committee may recommend to clear up
the confusion, although the minutes said the Fed was not
contemplating dropping the new practice altogether. The committee
is expected to report back by spring. In addition to Ferguson, it
is made up of all the Federal Reserve governors except Greenspan,
plus the presidents of three Reserve banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
