<HEADLINE>
ANAHEIM EXPECTS NO RETALIATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim players say they aren't worried about
retaliation from the Stars for hits by Ruslan Salei, Pascal
Trepanier and Jim McKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   At least not on this go around.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Rusty \RSalei\S had played, he's got to expect he'll get
hit,'' Mighty Ducks goalie Guy Hebert said. ``But I don't think
they'll go after Paul \RKariya\S or Teemu \RSelanne\S. I think
they'll probably play a more physical game, but I think they
respect Paul and Teemu.''
</P>
<P>
   Selanne said he hoped that Stars players wouldn't target him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do anything,'' Selanne said. Enforcer to start Winger
Chris Murray is the closest thing the Stars have to an enforcer,
and Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said he will make his first start
tonight against an Anaheim team that sent Mike Modano to the
hospital on a stretcher less than a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence?
</P>
<P>
   ``People can read into it whatever they want, but I'm a hockey
player first, and I'm going to go out and help the hockey team
win,'' Murray said. ``I was going to play sooner or later, and
\Rtonight\S is as good as any.''
</P>
<P>
   With Murray playing tonight, injured winger Grant Marshall's
debut will be tomorrow against San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Murray skated both days in Anaheim and said while he was
physically ready to play he'd rather begin in a place where the ice
isn't quite as bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ice is pretty bad,'' Marshall said of Arrowhead Pond.
``But I guess the biggest thing is I don't know if I can go back to
back right now. So I'll play \Rtomorrow\S and evaluate how I did in
the game and how I felt and go from there.'' Tough stars Stars
winger Mike Keane said the biggest change in the Stars' game might
be in the way the stars play instead of the way the enforcers and
tough guys play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll see the stars getting their elbows up, their
sticks up,'' Keane said. ``They're going to have to be ready and
realize that those cheap shots may be coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Message received, according to Stars winger Brett Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, you have to protect yourself,'' Hull said. ``You
say it before every game. If that guy comes at you make him eat
your Easton, and he won't come back at you again.''
</P>
<P>
   Easton, of course, is a brand of hockey equipment. Line doctor
The doctor was back at work yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock was once again cutting and pasting his
lines.
</P>
<P>
   He had Joe Nieuwendyk back with his usual linemates of Pavel
Patera and Jamie Langenbrunner while Guy Carbonneau took Mike
Modano's spot centering the No. 1 line of Brett Hull and Jere
Lehtinen. Brian Skrudland jumped into Carbonneau's spot centering
the line with Juha Lind and Blake Sloan. The fourth line was Derek
Plante, Mike Keane and Chris Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``As they said, the bingo king has juggled again,'' Hitchcock
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
