<HEADER>
A0159 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-PERFORM-2TAKE     10-07 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-PERFORM-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A ROUGH QUARTER, A SMALL VICTORY FOR STOCK-PICKING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seismic shifts are often imperceptible in the stock market until
well after they have taken hold. But 1999 is looking more and more
like the year that index mutual funds lost their star quality.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index lost
6.5 percent of its value, while the average United States
diversified stock fund had a smaller loss _ 5.08 percent. Not much
for active fund managers to crow about, but outperformance
nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   And encouragingly, for the first time since the early 1990s,
outperformance was the rule, not the exception among the managers.
According to Lipper Inc., more than half _ 57 percent _ beat their
market benchmarks in the quarter. For all of 1998, only one-fourth
of them did.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that actual stock-picking will make a comeback among
fund managers, who for years made money simply by buying those
stocks that had been rising the most? Perhaps. But temper that
possibility with this fact: in the most recent quarter, successful
stock-picking was confined to just two sectors, technology and
precious metals _ a sign that the overall market has been an
unrewarding place to invest of late.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the desultory market, most stock funds closed out the
quarter in negative territory. Specialized stock funds did better
than their diversified brethren, losing only 2.28 percent over all
in the quarter. But funds that invested in value stocks got
hammered, some losing as much as 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only international equity funds managed to show a gain _ 2.06
percent, on average. This was largely attributable to the rebound
in Japanese equities.
</P>
<P>
   After years in which the same handful of stocks turned up in the
top-performing mutual fund portfolios, the third quarter of 1999
gave investors fresh blood. Of the six stock funds that topped the
performance list in the quarter, not one counted Microsoft, Intel,
Cisco Systems, Lucent Technologies or America Online as major
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the top-performing funds in the most recent quarter
hold relatively obscure and smaller companies. The biggest holding
of the Strong Enterprise fund, a mid-cap growth fund that returned
19.51 percent, the best of all diversified stock funds, is Applied
Materials, a familiar name in semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   But its other top stocks include less-known names like PRI
Automation, a five-year-old company that helps semiconductor makers
automate their factories, and Sandisk, a maker of data storage
products. The No.2 fund, Van Wagoner Emerging Growth, returned
18.46 percent in the quarter. Its largest holding is Com21, a cable
modem company.
</P>
<P>
   These holdings reflect the overall market's sole pocket of
consistent strength in the quarter _ technology. Christine A.
Callies, investment strategist at Credit Suisse First Boston,
pointed out that through Sept. 27, technology was the only sector
in the S&AMP;P 500 that had increased in value during the previous 10
weeks. Eight other big sectors, including financial companies,
utilities and basic materials makers, deteriorated during that
period.
</P>
<P>
   Rising stocks were in a distinct minority. According to Salomon
Smith Barney, as of Sept. 28, NASDAQ stocks had declined almost 35
percent, on average, from their 52-week highs. New York Stock
Exchange stocks had fallen almost 28 percent, on average, and
shares in the S&AMP;P had dropped by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More alarming, 52.1 percent of NASDAQ stocks were down 30
percent or more from their 52-week highs by Sept. 28, compared with
37.5 percent of Big Board stocks and 33.2 percent of the S&AMP;P.
Investors who didn't happen to be in technology stocks felt a lot
of this pain.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the price of gold spiked late in September, bringing
funds in that sector an average gain of 20.35 percent for the
period, did technology stocks get some competition.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Several developments damaged the overall market during the
quarter. The Federal Reserve Board raised interest rates twice over
the summer, for a total of half a percentage point. And the
weakening of the dollar, particularly against the Japanese yen,
coupled with rising commodity prices, raised fears that inflation
may recur.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than buying on the market's dips, investors slowed
their mutual fund investments as summer drew to a close. Investors
put $9.2 billion into stock funds in August, a decline of 25.7
percent from July. And Robert Adler, president of AMG Data
Services, said September's fund flows were still lower. Adler said
that most of the fresh money was still going into
big-capitalization index funds and large-cap growth funds.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown in flows may indicate that investors are finally
growing wary of stocks. Ms. Callies pointed out that in the postwar
era, investors make broad shifts in their asset allocations once
every 15 years or so.
</P>
<P>
   The asset allocation change that began in 1982, with the onset
of a bull market in stocks, is now 17 years old. As a result, Ms.
Callies speculated that the era of equity investments may be
ending.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that money is flowing less freely into stock
funds, mutual funds' cash holdings are low _ by Ms. Callies's
reckoning, at 4.8 percent, which she puts at the extreme low end of
the long-term range.
</P>
<P>
   As the market indexes have skidded, it is somewhat surprising
that managers are not building up cash to protect their portfolios
from being hurt by a flood of redemptions. Instead, fund managers
may be staying fully invested in stocks to try to jump-start their
returns.
</P>
<P>
   If the performance of well-known large-capitalization stocks is
beginning to flag, it would fit a pattern _ identified by analysts
at Sanford C.Bernstein &AMP; Co. _ that typically afflicts growth
stocks. In short, growth stocks do not remain growth stocks for
long.
</P>
<P>
   According to the firm's study, which looked at stocks between
1965 and 1998, only 42 percent of all growth stocks remained hot
growers for more than five years, while only 19 percent stayed
high-growth for more than 10 years. Over 20 years, only 5 percent
of growth stocks kept up their steam.
</P>
<P>
   The hurdles are even higher for technology companies. In that
sector, less than one in three growth stocks will remain
top-performers for more than five years. Looking out 10 years, the
share drops to 11 percent As for 20 years, only 3 percent made the
grade.
</P>
<P>
   The firm concluded that technology stocks _ the ones now holding
up the market _ were among the least reliable of growth companies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pouring of money into technology funds, Adler of AMG
Data Services sees a rising level of caution over all. He pointed
to the activity in high-yield corporate bond funds as evidence.
``There is an indication in the numbers that an aversion to risk is
beginning to evolve among investors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, after the Russian debt default, he added,
``high-yield bond funds showed terrific inflows.'' Not today. In 10
of the last 11 weeks, there have been net redemptions from
high-yield bond funds, reflecting investor concern about risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That continuous type of negative activity,'' Adler recalled,
``has only been experienced twice before'' _ when the Federal
Reserve raised interest rates in 1994 and in the Russian default.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, bond funds have been hurt by rising interest rates
and inflation fears. Only those funds investing in international
bonds did well, benefiting mightily from the weaker dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2223EDT &QL; 
