<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN CENTRAL BANK LEAVES INTEREST RATE UNCHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The European Central Bank decided not to
stop Europe's party Thursday, but it bluntly warned that it would
probably move soon to slow things down.
</P>
<P>
   Despite steadily increasing concern about inflationary pressures
in Europe, the central bank chose to leave its core interest rate
unchanged at 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the bank's president, Wim Duisenberg, issued his clearest
and most emphatic statement that the 11-nation euro-zone needed to
be cooled down and that a tighter monetary policy was almost
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have now had a truly accommodative monetary policy for more
than a year,'' Duisenberg said after a meeting of the bank's board
of governors here Thursday. He said the bank was now looking ahead
to ``a monetary strategy that is conducive to sustainable,
non-inflationary growth. That is something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors, who had thought the bank might raise interest rates
Thursday, initially reacted by pushing down the value of the euro,
Europe's new common currency.
</P>
<P>
   But they reversed course after absorbing Duisenberg's
unambiguously hawkish remarks, which apparently convinced investors
that a tougher policy would come sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   The euro ended the day up against the dollar, settling in New
York at $1.07100 compared with $1.06970 Wednesday. Major European
stock markets also ended higher, as investors apparently chose to
focus more on Europe's vibrant economy rather than the prospect of
higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   London's blue-chip index rose 1.69 percent, while Frankfurt's
main index rose 1.23 percent and France's rose 1.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The European Central Bank's decision paralleled a similar
verdict Thursday at the Bank of England, which left British rates
unchanged at 5.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It also meshed with an almost identical stance adopted by the
United States Federal Reserve Board on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   European bankers have been looking for guidance amid a welter of
sometimes conflicting data. The bank dramatically reduced its core
rate from 3 percent to 2.5 percent in April, because the European
economy had stalled and seemed dangerously close to a recession.
</P>
<P>
   But the outlook has brightened measurably in the last several
months, partly because Asian countries are recovering from the
financial crisis that first gripped that region two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Most forecasters expect the European Union economy to grow about
2.1 percent this year and nearly 3 percent next year. Exports and
industrial production are picking up in many countries, and
joblessness has creeped downward from more than 10 percent to about
9.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But bankers also see a growing body of warning signs. Businesses
and consumers are borrowing money at a much more rapid rate, with
private-sector credit expanding 10.7 percent in August. The money
supply, which is considered a barometer of inflationary pressure,
has climbed somewhat faster than the central bank would like. And
consumer prices have been nudged upward by big increases in oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Duisenberg now seems convinced that the main threat is inflation
and, by extension, the credibility of the euro in world markets.
Higher rates would tend to strengthen the European currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-NYTIMES-COLUMNIST-ART     10-07 0259
</HEADER>
