u a BC-OHIO-GUNSUIT-NYT &LR;      10-07 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-GUNSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DISMISSES CINCINNATI'S SUIT ON GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (th) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A state judge in Cincinnati dismissed the city's lawsuit against
the firearms industry Thursday, saying the city was improperly
asking a court to change the way guns are designed, marketed and
distributed, something only a legislature could do.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was the first dismissal of one of the lawsuits
brought against gun manufacturers by 28 cities and counties over
the past year, lawyers for the gun industry said.
</P>
<P>
   Though it represented a victory for gun makers, lawyers for
several cities said their cases were based on different strategies
and state laws so the ruling would have little bearing.
</P>
<P>
   The decision also came within days of two unfavorable court
decisions for the gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Judge Meredith A. Jury of U.S. Bankruptcy Court in
Riverside, Calif., ruled that a gun maker could not avoid municipal
lawsuits by filing for bankruptcy protection. The judge, ruling in
the case of Davis Industries, one of several Los Angeles-area gun
makers that have been sued, said a company could not use the
bankruptcy laws to avoid a city's efforts to exercise its
regulatory or police powers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a California appeals court said the gun makers could
be held liable when their products were used in a criminal
shooting, the first such decision in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate development, United Parcel Service, which ships
about 75 percent of the guns from manufacturers to wholesalers and
dealers, said it would now require that all guns be shipped by its
next-day service instead of its less-expensive ground delivery
service.
</P>
<P>
   The change, made because of a concern about the increasing
threat of litigation and because of several incidents involving
theft of guns, will increase costs for gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   The state judge in Cincinnati, Robert P. Ruehlman, said the
city's claims were vague, unsupported by precedent and ``an
improper attempt to have this court substitute its judgment for
that of the legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati had based its suit largely on the charge that gun
makers had failed to incorporate sufficient safety devices, like
trigger locks. But Ruehlman ruled, as almost all judges had in the
past, that guns were legal products and that the manufacturer could
not be held liable when the guns functioned as intended, even if
they killed people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge's ruling shows how flawed these cities' claims
are,'' said Anne Kimball, a lawyer for Smith &AMP; Wesson and Sturm,
Ruger &AMP; Co., two of the largest gun makers in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from several cities said privately that they had filed
the suits to have the issue decided by urban juries familiar with
gun violence, rather than by legislators who are often influenced
by the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Owen Clements, chief of special litigation for the San Francisco
City Attorney's Office, said Ruehlman's decision would not alter
his city's suit, because it is based on a California law that
prohibits harmful, unfair or deceptive business practices and is
not a negligence suit.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for other cities said the safety issue that was central
to the Cincinnati case was a lesser part of their cases, which were
based more on questions of marketing and distribution and on public
nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ruehlman also dismissed the city's assertion that
the gun makers had created a public nuisance by the way they
marketed and distributed firearms, often selling large numbers of
guns to dealers in areas with lax gun control laws knowing they
would be resold in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The judge wrote, ``public nuisance simply does not apply to the
design, manufacture and distribution of a lawful product.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
