<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE BEING ONE-HIT, ASTROS EXPRESS CONFIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Houston, we have a ... reason to be happy:
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is coming back.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen is gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are facing Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   While cautiously cognizant of Glavine's Cy Young resume, popular
Nike commercial and recent mastery over them, the Astros are
thrilled to be facing any Atlanta Braves pitcher not named Kevin
Millwood today in Game 3 of their National League Divisional
Series, at 3 p.m. in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand how Glavine has handled us in the past,'' said
Astros manager Larry Dierker, ``but the only way he can be better
than Millwood is to no-hit us.''
</P>
<P>
   With their spin-doctoring in high gear and their glasses
half-full, the Astros spent yesterday's workout forgetting
Millwood's one-hitter in Game 2 and preparing to face a pitcher in
Game 3 who is 8-0 with a 1.35 ERA in his past 10 starts at the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason those guys won 103 games,'' Houston first
baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``They've got guys who can one-hit you
every night. Tom has the talent to throw a similar game at us, so
we've got to be ready to take it up a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseless against Millwood's pin-point fastball and nasty
curve, the Astros suffered the worst offensive performance in the
franchise's 25-game postseason history. They managed the one hit _
a second-inning homer by Ken Caminiti _ and sent only six balls out
of the infield. Millwood's gem was baseball's first postseason
complete-game, one-hitter since Boston's Jim Lonborg threw one in
the 1967 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, 2-7 combined in the 1997, '98 and '99 playoffs, is
planning its rebound around energy from an expected sellout at the
Astrodome and another clutch pitching performance from Mike
Hampton. Capping a 22-4 season that thrust him into Cy Young Award
contention, the left-hander beat the Cincinnati Reds and Los
Angeles Dodgers in crucial games last week to help Houston clinch
its third consecutive Central Division title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very confident,'' Bagwell said. ``We're in good shape.
We got a split against Atlanta and come home with Mike on the
mound. We couldn't ask for much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dierker, ``They've got a great staff, but I don't know if
I'd rather have anyone else on the mound for me in this spot than
Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros also realize they have to get production from
offensive leaders Bagwell and second baseman Craig Biggio to win
this series. Without contributions from Moises Alou (hurt in spring
training) and Derek Bell (only 12 homers), those two carried the
Astros through the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But Bagwell and Biggio had dismal performances the past two
Octobers, combining to go 6-for-49, and they have again gone
silent. They went a combined 2-for-16 at Turner Field with four
strikeouts and no runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're too good of players not to break out of it sooner or
later,'' Dierker said. ``Those guys are the reason we're here, and
I know they'll keep competing and plugging away and helping us find
ways to win.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
