<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-IPO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBVAN IS DELAYING ITS OFFERING OF STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Ill., Wash.)   (af)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Webvan Group, an online grocer with big advance billing,
temporarily shelved a public offering of its stock Thursday, not
because it had more selling to do to investors, but because it had
done too much already.
</P>
<P>
   In what may be a cautionary tale to other promising online
ventures, the company appears to have run afoul of regulators by
giving out unpublished information in a conference call.
</P>
<P>
   Disclosures about a company's condition and prospects are common
as executives court money managers and other big investors in the
days leading up to a stock offering. But disclosing information not
in the public filings may violate securities laws, lawyers and Wall
Street analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan and its underwriter, Goldman, Sachs, issued a brief
statement Thursday saying that the Securities and Exchange
Commission and Webvan ``have agreed to a cooling-off period prior
to the commencement of the offering.''
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to comment about when the stock offering
might be revived. Neither the company nor the SEC would comment on
who initiated the cooling-off period.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan is not the first company to postpone a public stock
offering after it was found to have disclosed information not
revealed in the prospectus filed with regulators, said John Heine,
an SEC spokesman, though he declined to elaborate on the Webvan
case specifically.
</P>
<P>
   Brian C. Oakes, a senior Internet analyst with Lehman Brothers,
suggested that the SEC could be sending a message that would have
longer-term ramifications for the market for new issues. Regulators
may be seeking to address the discrepancies in information
presented to individual investors and institutional investors who
are invited to the so-called road shows ahead of public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   In these presentations, companies describe _ some would say hype
_ their offerings by presenting additional impressions of the
business' prospects. Oakes made clear that he was not criticizing
the Webvan offering in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plenty of good quality Internet companies going
public but also plenty of overhyped Internet companies going
public,'' he said. ``The SEC is trying to let the facts speak for
themselves, rather than the hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Webvan, founded by Louis Borders, the founder of Borders Books,
has created a buzz even beyond that typical of Internet start-ups.
Though it only began delivering groceries in May, and in only a
handful of markets, its valuation could be $4 billion if it
succeeds with plans to sell 25 million shares at $11 to $13 in its
public offering. The offering had been scheduled for this week.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which filed its offering document on Aug. 6, began
presentations to institutional investors in personal meetings and
in conference calls the week of Sept. 20.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Adam Lashinsky, a reporter for the Internet
financial publication TheStreet.com, dialed into one of the calls.
Lashinsky said he identified himself by name and by his
organization, but not as a journalist, and was permitted to stay on
the call.
</P>
<P>
   Lashinsky said Webvan went on to describe to call participants
information not included in the documents it filed with regulators.
Among the details he said were provided by Webvan _ and not
included in the prospectus _ were that each of the 26 distribution
centers it is building would generate $300 million in annual
revenue, and that it planned to expand into Chicago and Seattle
next year.
</P>
<P>
   According to Borders and Kevin Czinger, the company's chief
financial officer, Webvan's operating margins will be 12 percent,
compared with 4 percent for the typical supermarket, Lashinksy
wrote in his column for TheStreet.com. In an interview Thursday,
Lashinsky said the company offered these details in what appeared
to be a ``prepared statement'' rather than in a question-and-answer
session.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction is important. Lawyers and analysts said it was
not uncommon for companies on a road show to clarify information in
a prospectus. But they said that regulators might view any
violations in that action as more egregious if the company
unilaterally offered institutional investors information not found
in the public documents.
</P>
<P>
   Under securities law, a company making a public offering is
required either to register with the SEC or, in rare instances, to
obtain an exemption from registration. Companies that register are
required to disclose material information so that potential
investors can have a fair and equal opportunity to make an informed
decision about whether to invest.
</P>
<P>
   Companies also tend to voluntarily adopt ``quiet periods'' in
the several months before and after an initial public offering. In
those periods, executives do not discuss the company's financial
prospects publicly. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
