<SLUG> BC-R-REVLON-NORRIS-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: WANT TO LOSE SOME MONEY? INVEST IN A PERELMAN COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add graphic note)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To hear George Fellows tell it, everything is going great at
Revlon Inc. Market share is rising, and consumers love the
company's cosmetics. Investors should be happy that the company is
dealing with a huge inventory problem that is in no way its fault.
</P>
<P>
   But Fellows, Revlon's president, acknowledges that investors
aren't happy. In the week since Revlon disclosed the inventory
problem, its stock has plunged 41 percent, to $10.75, even after
bouncing back $2 Thursday. The prices of Revlon junk bonds have
also fallen sharply.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy to tell whether Fellow's optimism _ he forecasts
that the company will have positive operating cash flow next year _
is justified. But it is clear that Revlon's near-term prospects
hinge on the kindness of the banks that have lent the company lots
of money.
</P>
<P>
   As the bank negotiations begin, say people briefed on Revlon's
finances, the company has $100 million in cash, which should be
enough to get it through the year, but just $35 million in unused
credit lines.
</P>
<P>
   At best, the banks will charge a higher interest rate, something
that will further damage the company's already weak cash-flow
outlook. At worst, they could pull the plug. Fellows is confident
the banks will cooperate, and he notes that Revlon expects to raise
$500 million by selling some subsidiaries soon.
</P>
<P>
   That Revlon is in this situation is a testament to how poorly
things have gone for the company in the 13 years since Ronald O.
Perelman took control after a bitter takeover battle. The takeover
left Revlon saddled with debt, a situation that has not improved
with time. The debt has risen every year since Revlon went public
again, at $24 a share, in 1996. Operating cash flow since the end
of 1996 has registered a negative $99 million.
</P>
<P>
   But even that figure may overstate how well Revlon has done. The
stores that sell its products now have shelves bulging with unsold
merchandise. So last week Revlon said it would all but quit
shipping products for the rest of this year and delay the
introduction of new products. That has put the company in violation
of loan covenants, giving the banks their new leverage.
</P>
<P>
   Fellows vigorously denies that the inventory problem might be an
indication that Revlon stuffed inventory into its customers'
warehouses to bolster reported profits. He says the stores have
simply used computers to manage their inventories more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Perelman owns 83 percent of Revlon, but his economic stake is
not that large. Twenty million of his 42 million shares are pledged
to secure $770 million in zero-coupon bonds that come due in March
2001. He could walk away from those bonds _ now trading at less
than 30 percent of face value _ and still keep control of the
company.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Perelman, Howard Gittis, said Thursday that
Perelman had faith in Revlon, which he called ``his most important
holding, if not from a financial standpoint, at least from a
reputational one.''
</P>
<P>
   That reputation was suffering even before Revlon encountered its
latest woes. In the 1990s, four companies owned by Perelman have
gone public, raising a total of $456 million. Each of the stocks
has lost value.
</P>
<P>
   Had the buyers put the money into the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index instead, they would now have more than $1.1 billion
instead of about $260 million.
</P>
<P>
   This decade has had one of the greatest bull markets ever. Those
who invested in Perelman's companies missed it. Call it the
Perelman Penalty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
