</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HENDERSON IN OCTOBER _ AHHH, STOLEN MOMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the last 23 games Rickey Henderson played during
the season, he was on base 33 times. He tried to steal eight times
and was successful five times. In the first two playoff games
against the Arizona Diamondbacks, Henderson was on base six times
with hits and walks. He tried to steal five times and was
successful five times.
</P>
<P>
   Why has the Mets' leadoff hitter undergone such a startling
base-stealing transformation?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Rickey time,'' he told a member of the Mets' family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rickey time'' is October, or more precisely post-season games
in October. ``Rickey's a big-game player,'' said Steve Phillips,
the Mets' general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Though he cannot be mistaken for the man known as Mr. October,
Henderson nevertheless has invited coverage by as much mustard as
Reggie Jackson ever required. But while Jackson invited the ire of
others for his often pompous proclamations, Henderson has induced
consternation among his managers and teammates for his periodic
slowdowns.
</P>
<P>
   All they can do in those instances is shrug and say weakly,
``That's Rickey.'' But this is Rickey, too:
</P>
<P>
   Game 1: walk, stolen base, run; walk, stolen base.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2: single, stolen base, run; single, stolen base; walk,
stolen base.
</P>
<P>
   In the 7-1 loss in the second game, Henderson was the Mets'
offense, setting records for stolen bases in a division series game
and in a division series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played two of the best games the last two that I've seen
him play and he's had a great year,'' Bobby Valentine, the Mets'
manager, said Thursday. ``I've seen Rickey play his entire career
and I don't know if he's ever played better start to finish, but in
those last two he was a force to be reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's performance is no coincidence, Valentine added. ``He
enjoys the spotlight,'' the manager added. ``When it's on, he's
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates of the 40-year-old left fielder readily agree.
``That's Rickey,'' Darryl Hamilton said. ``I can honestly say he
loves this. He loves the fact that he's in New York and the media
attention is high. He thrives on that. He's a different ballplayer
when it comes to the playoffs. He's unusual. Some guys don't like
the pressure, all the attention, but he does.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Mets can appreciate Henderson's post-season effort and
benefit from it, Kelly Stinnett, the Diamondbacks' catcher, has to
deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rickey is the greatest base stealer of all-time,'' he said.
``He's so good at anticipating. It seems like he knows when we're
throwing a breaking ball, and that's when he runs. When that
happens, I've got no chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett was hopeful that he would get help in Games 3 and 4 at
Shea Stadium on Friday and Saturday. Arizona will start two-left
handed pitchers, Omar Daal and Brian Anderson, who Stinnett said
are proficient at holding runners on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to keep Rickey close because he gets such great
jumps,'' Stinnett said. ``He times the pitchers. The pitcher just
flinches and he's gone. The thing with Rickey is, you know he's
going to get his bags. You just have to make it as hard as you can
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's performance is nothing new. Baseball's
career-leading base stealer, he had 25 stolen bases in his previous
post-season appearances covering three World Series, five league
championship series and two division series.
</P>
<P>
   His most noteworthy series was the league playoff for Oakland
against Toronto in 1989. He had a total of eight steals in four of
the five games, including four in Game 2, and in the one game in
which he didn't steal he hit two home runs and drove in four runs.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Mets were losing the second game in Arizona from the
third inning on, Henderson played it straight. The night before,
however, he was at his impish best. After he stole second in the
third inning, he took a giant step toward the mound, toying with
the humorless Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He later said he was just ``trying to scare him a little bit.''
This, he added, is ``just a fun time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rickey definitely has personality,'' Valentine said, ``and he
has a style that's all Rickey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically we have a bunch of guys who are workmen-like, who go
about their business in a rather professional way but also without
much flamboyancy. Rickey has brought a balancing act to that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Henderson doesn't always make it fun for his managers,
confounding them with his inexplicable slowdowns. Two weeks ago in
Atlanta, Henderson was on first base with the Mets leading, 2-1,
when Edgardo Alfonzo lashed a double to left field. First,
Henderson coasted into third instead of running hard and possibly
scoring. Then he ignored the coach's stop sign and decided he would
try to score. He didn't; he was thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   In August, he had another incident in which he didn't run hard,
that time on a fly ball off the left-field fence leading off the
ninth inning. Had he run from the start, he might have had a triple
and more easily scored the tying run. But he had to stop at second
and never moved from there as the Mets lost.
</P>
<P>
   Mookie Wilson, the Mets' first base coach, was asked after
Henderson's five-for-five performance if he could explain what
makes Rickey run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes when he feels like it,'' Wilson said. ``I don't know
what goes through Rickey's mind. I don't know why he does what he
does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2241EDT &QL; 
