<HEADLINE>
RED SOX, SABERHAGEN LOSE CONTROL, FALL TO INDIANS
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Cleveland Indians, possessors of the best lineup
in the land, usually don't need much help when it comes to scoring
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the outfit that scored 1,009 runs during the regular
season _ the best in baseball since 1950 _ is quite capable of
doing damage. Give us your best stuff, they snarl, and we'll shove
it down your throat.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2 of the American League Division Series, though, they
received aid from an unlikely source as they pounded the Boston Red
Sox, 11-1, Thursday at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox starter Bret Saberhagen's normally impeccable control
deserted him, and the Indians parlayed three walks into a six-run
third inning that started the rout. Omar Vizquel drove in two of
the runs with a triple and Harold Baines hit a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the pitcher is not having a good day and makes mistakes,
chances are he's going to pay for it,'' said Indians third baseman
Travis Fryman, who drew the first walk.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians also made reliever John Wasdin pay for his three
walks in the fourth inning when they scored five more runs, four of
them on a grand slam by Jim Thome. That was more than enough
support for starter Charles Nagy, who held the Red Sox to one run
in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians took a 2-0 lead in the best-of-five series, and are
one victory away from advancing to the American League Championship
Series for the fourth time in the past five years. The Red Sox,
meanwhile, face elimination as the series resumes Saturday in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not done yet,'' Red Sox manager Jimy Williams said.
``It's not over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   There were suggestions that it was over when Red Sox ace Pedro
Martinez left after four innings of Game 1 because of a strained
muscle in his back, allowing the Indians to rally for a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Williams reminded everyone before Game 2, though, that his team
still was in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got Saberhagen going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't just whistling in a graveyard. Saberhagen was 10-6
with a 2.95 earned-run average and would have ranked second in the
league in ERA, behind Martinez, if he had pitched enough innings to
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   What made Saberhagen so good this season was his control. He did
not walk a batter in 14 of his 22 starts, and walked only 11
batters in 119 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Fryman drew walk No. 12 to lead off the third, and after Sandy
Alomar hit into a force play that would have been a double play if
not for Jose Offerman's high throw to first base _ Kenny Lofton got
No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Being a control pitcher means more than just throwing strikes.
It's also putting the ball where you want to in the strike zone,
and Saberhagen didn't do that either. He threw a fat pitch that
Vizquel pulled just out of the reach of right-fielder Trot Nixon
for a triple that scored Alomar and Lofton and gave the Indians a
2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Alomar, the next batter, got a high fastball that he
pulled to right for a double that scored Vizquel. After Manny
Ramirez flied out, Saberhagen issued the third walk of the inning,
this one to Thome.
</P>
<P>
   Baines then went to the plate expecting a fastball, and he got
one on the first pitch. It was down, but over the middle of the
plate, and Baines hit it into the seats for a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't make some pitches when I had to,'' Saberhagen
said. ``Walking three guys in a game, that's not me and that's what
really hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   What really hurts is going to Boston with a two-game deficit
against the most prolific offense in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The momentum is going our way, but by no means are they going
to lay down and die,'' Thome said. ``We've got to still be focused
and just try to wrap it up.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
