<HEADLINE>
CORNELL TO RECEIVE $100 MILLION GIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An anonymous donor has pledged $100 million to help Cornell
University revamp undergraduate housing, Cornell's president,
Hunter R. Rawlings III, is to announce Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell has already embarked on a plan to build two dormitories
for freshmen and bring all its freshmen together on its North
Campus. The new gift will help Cornell turn its sights to housing
for the rest of its undergraduates and the creation of what it
calls a ``living-learning community'' for them on its West Campus.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell hopes to improve undergraduate education and to
integrate its white students and its minority students more fully.
Over the past two decades, the West Campus of Cornell became
occupied mostly by white students, while the other part, the North
Campus, attracted many of the school's minority students.
</P>
<P>
   The Ithaca, N.Y., university hoped to bridge some of those
racial and ethnic divisions by grouping its first-year students
together. That plan, announced in 1997, is also aimed at making the
dormitories a more explicit part of the educational process _ by
holding seminars in a dormitory, for example _ following a pattern
used by other universities, including Harvard and Yale.
</P>
<P>
   The anonymous gift is expected to cover about half of the cost
of the new dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second $100 million gift Cornell has received. Last
year, Sanford and Joan Weill pledged $100 million to support
Cornell's medical school, which was renamed the Weill Medical
College. It was among the two dozen largest gifts to higher
education.
</P>
<P>
   The housing changes are part of Cornell's effort to make
undergraduate education a priority amid criticism that research
universities put graduate students first. Cornell plans to invest
$500 million in programs and financial aid for undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlings is also to announce that the university has raised $136
million of the $150 million it needs to have by Dec. 31 to earn a
$50 million matching grant. The money will be used for scholarships
and to maintain Cornell's ``need-blind'' admissions policy, under
which students are admitted without regard to financial need and
then provided with the financial support they need to attend the
college. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
