<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT SETS BRISK PACE IN NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 47 of Clinton shaking hands with James P.
Hoffa is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers may make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY and STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton came to New York Thursday to pay
tribute to two political constituencies that had proved central to
his electoral success _ labor unions and gay rights advocates _ and
now loom as critical to the political future of Clinton's wife and
his vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of two hours, and in the space of two city blocks,
Clinton spoke at a dinner in honor of James P. Hoffa, the president
of the teamsters' union, and moved on to a fund-raiser for New
York's most prominent gay rights group, the Empire State Pride
Agenda. In both places, Clinton drew an exuberant reaction from
audiences that have, as often as not, been viewed as a political
liability by candidates and officeholders over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for making New York the biggest, strongest union
city in America,'' Clinton declared to the cheers of labor leaders.
And when Clinton mentioned the guest of honor's name, he was
overwhelmed by shouts of ``Hoffa, Hoffa, Hoffa!''
</P>
<P>
   Labor and gay rights organizations have proved to be reliable
parts of Clinton's political base. But given the extent to which
those groups have been the subject of Republican attack over the
past 10 years, Clinton's appearances suggest the freedom he feels
as he approaches the end of his second term, and his evident
interest in helping Vice President Al Gore, who is running for
president, and Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is all but running for
the Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton left the dinner, Hoffa told the audience, ``I got
a good idea speaking to the president: Why don't we all get
together and back Hillary Clinton as senator for the state of New
York?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance at the Hilton Hotel at the tribute to Hoffa
was the first time that a president had appeared so publicly with
the much investigated teamsters' union since Franklin D. Roosevelt
spoke at one of its conventions more than 50 years ago. Clinton
drew cheers from the audience as he shook hands with Hoffa, who has
been a leading opponent of an immediate endorsement of Gore in the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that I wanted to do when the vice president
and I came into office was to change the way that America thought
about labor,'' Clinton said. ``I was so sick and tired of more than
a decade of people trying to make unions the whipping boy of
whatever it was that was wrong with America.''
</P>
<P>
   One issue of particular concern to his labor audience was the
North American Free Trade Agreement and its call to allow Mexican
trucks to drive freely in the United States. Clinton indicated that
he shared their concern because American officials have found that
two-thirds of Mexican trucks are not safe.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Clinton moved a block west to the annual dinner of
the Empire State Pride Agenda at the Sheraton. Clinton is one of
several candidates who have, over the years, turned to gay rights
organizations for campaign contributions. But in this case, the
president was the draw rather than beneficiary of a dinner that
organizers said would raise $1 million for lobbying and political
candidates sympathetic to gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech to the Empire State Pride Agenda was his third
appearance as president in a public setting before a gay rights
group. His attendance was testimony to the growing influence of gay
voters in New York elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``At our second annual dinner, we were wondering if David
Dinkins would show up,'' said Jeff Sorof, the co-chairman of the
organization, referring to New York's former mayor. ``This is quite
a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also did what he typically does on his frequent visits
to New York: raise money for the Democratic Party. In this case, he
was the featured speaker at a fund-raiser Thursday for the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The president appeared in New York alone. Mrs. Clinton was in
Italy. Gore was in New York, but he and Clinton did not cross
paths.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton attended the dinner for Hoffa just four days before the
AFL-CIO, which includes the teamsters, holds a convention in Los
Angeles, where several union leaders are urging an endorsement of
Gore over Bill Bradley, the former senator from New Jersey. It is
far from certain that Gore's supporters can command the two-thirds
majority needed to endorse him.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa has urged other labor leaders to hold off on an
endorsement to see whether the administration will give assurances
on trade barriers and other matters. Among Hoffa's concerns is
persuading the government to end its decade-long supervision of the
union, which has been imposed to end corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner was sponsored by the Labor Research Association, a
consulting group that advises unions. For decades, presidents have
shied away from the union because of its history of corruption. But
federal officials said that the 1.4 million-member union is
significantly cleaner after a decade of supervision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
