<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' SALLEY GLAD TO BE BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA _ John Salley didn't have to come back to this.
The ice bags, the medical tape, the sweat, the aches and bruises.
But listen to the unretired 10-year NBA veteran, and it's clear he
needs this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have never left, this feels so good,'' Salley said
Thursday, after a morning practice at UC Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after retiring, three championship rings on his
hand, Salley is back in training camp, a partially guaranteed
contract in hand as he tries to win a roster spot with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   A budding television career could have supported Salley, but it
failed to satisfy him. Returning to the court was surprisingly
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's second nature,'' he said. ``I feel like Mike Tyson, right
out of prison _ about to beat somebody's butt.''
</P>
<P>
   The jovial 6-foot-11 forward lets out a big laugh. But he turns
serious when it's suggested that, at 35 years old, long past his
glory years with the Detroit Pistons and Chicago Bulls, he might be
a long shot to make this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a long shot,'' he said. ``There's only two guys on
this team that ever ran the triangle offense _ me and A.C. (Green).
I'm a close-shot. I can bring a lot to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Salley has an intimate understanding of coach Phil Jackson's
system, having played for him in 1995-96. He also can play power
forward and center, positions where the Lakers are thin. A
stringent Tae Bo regiment has kept him in good shape. Only the
Lakers' crowded roster poses a potential obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   But bet on Salley sticking _ and making an impact on the Lakers'
young stars. He's already giving daily advice to 21-year-old Kobe
Bryant and 27-year-old Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be close to Kobe, hopefully save him 10 maybe 12
years on his game,'' he said. ``Every day I teach Shaq a new
trick.... all that Kevin McHale stuff he terrorized me with.''
</P>
<P>
   Salley lobbied Del Harris for a tryout last season, but the
lockout-shortened season wasn't conducive to a comeback. He had
offers from Vancouver and the Pistons but wanted a shot at a fourth
championship _ and the chance to be the first player in history to
win titles with three teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even went to a Laker game one time and sat on the court and
watched, (and thought) `This is where I need to be,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he's left behind his NBA on NBC gig and his role as host of
the family game show, ``I Can't Believe You Said That,'' trading
suit-and-tie for a practice jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I want to do, this is what I've been doing since
I was 6 years old,'' he said. ``There's a great movie called
`Sunset Boulevard,' and she said, `It's not a comeback, it's a
return.' That's what I'm looking at. I'm ready for my close-up.''
</P>
<P>
   UC-ya: This is the Lakers' second training camp at UCSB in the
last 10 months, and it's probably their last here period.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers owner Jerry Buss would like to return to Hawaii, while
Jackson is leaning toward El Segundo _ site of the team's new
practice facility, still under construction. Jackson's Bulls
trained in Chicago at the team's Berto Center, and he'd like to
follow suit here.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson prefers his players take about a month off, then train
the rest of the summer at the team's facility, under supervision of
team trainers. Staying home for training camp provides continuity
for Jackson's offseason program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've held out the enticement of going to Hawaii, and I just
said, no, I don't know if Hawaii is the right spot for us,'' he
said. ``We'll see how we do this year, if we have a great year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
