<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TROOPER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROOPER IN SHOOTING SUES STATE, SAYING HE WAS UNFIT FOR DUTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (af)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ In an unusual legal tack, a state trooper
charged with attempted murder in a shooting during a routine
traffic stop on the New Jersey Turnpike last year is suing the
state and his commanders for allowing him to work even though, he
claims, he was emotionally unfit for duty.
</P>
<P>
   The civil suit, filed on Sept. 28 by the trooper, James Kenna,
seeks to place responsibility for the shooting with his superior
officers. The suit says that Kenna's commanders and the force's
physician negligently allowed him to work on the day of the
shooting even though he was still scarred by ``severe psychological
trauma'' from another turnpike confrontation one month earlier. The
suit was first reported in Thursday's Star-Ledger of Newark.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 7, a grand jury indicted Kenna, 28, and fellow trooper
John Hogan, 29, on charges of attempted murder and assault. The
indictment accused the two troopers, who are both white, of firing
11 bullets into the van, which was carrying four black and Hispanic
men, all unarmed, at a traffic stop near Washington Township on
April 23, 1998. Three of the men in the van were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The troopers have repeatedly said that their fusillade was
justified because the van had begun rolling backward toward them,
forcing them to fire to protect their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But in his civil suit in state superior court here, Kenna seems
to back away from that claim, recasting his role in the shooting as
a result of emotional instability caused, he said, by an assault he
suffered on March 18.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, according to the suit, during a routine traffic
stop on the turnpike, Kenna was knocked to the ground by one of a
stopped vehicle's passengers, who then climbed into the police
cruiser and tried to drive over him. When Kenna tried to fire his
gun at the suspect, the suit claims, the weapon jammed.
</P>
<P>
   In the days after the incident, Kenna experienced psychological
trauma, the suit alleges, although it does not give any examples of
his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent examinations by state police doctors, which are
required after such incidents, found him fit for duty, the suit
says. Their failure to diagnose severe mental stress ``created a
reasonably foreseeable risk,'' according to the suit, that he would
use his gun again ``if confronted with a potentially threatening
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general's office said it received a copy of
the lawsuit Wednesday, but would not comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Arseneault, the lawyer defending Kenna against the state's
criminal charges, said he had no role in his client's civil suit
and would not comment Thursday, except to say that his client had
filed the suit on his own behalf. Hogan's lawyer, Robert
Galantucci, also declined to discuss the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Kenna's civil suit, known as a cross claim, is typically
employed by defendants seeking to deflect court-imposed monetary
claims onto a third party, like the defendant's employer, said
Frank Askin, a law professor at Rutgers University Law School. ``It
would protect him against a financial judgment,'' Askin said.
``It's a perfectly appropriate procedural device.''
</P>
<P>
   The two troopers, who have been suspended without pay since
April, face civil suits filed by the three wounded passengers from
the van.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawyers said it was unusual for a defendant in a criminal
indictment to try to shift blame to an employer though a civil
claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me their versions are changing,'' said Wayne D.
Greenfeder, a lawyer representing Rayshawn Brown, 22, one of the
men injured in the van shooting last year. ``Originally they said
the shooting was totally justified. Now it seems like he's trying
to say that the shooting was caused at least in part by the state,
for allowing him to remain a trooper with a gun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
