<HEADER>
A0192 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     10-07 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ CARRIES EVEN MORE BAGGAGE NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA _ Assists are going to be a bigger part of
Shaquille O'Neal's game this season. First-year Lakers coach Phil
Jackson has made that clear.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the 7-foot center was simply practicing on reporters
the other day, feeding us the same way he'll feed Kobe Bryant and
Glen Rice come the start of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he did during his summer vacation, O'Neal could have
said he acquainted himself with the triangle offense that Jackson
is installing with the help of its architect, Tex Winter.
</P>
<P>
   He might have said he spent long afternoons in the gym shooting
free throws.
</P>
<P>
   He could have fleshed out the weight regimen that has added
obvious definition to his arms, which already were bigger around
than any Laker girl's waist.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, O'Neal flicked his critics an easy story angle, the
journalistic equivalent of a fast-break pass, as if daring us to
run with it. He said he didn't bone up on the triangle offense,
didn't concentrate on his free-throw shooting, didn't change his
diet, didn't do much except ``lift a lot of weights and chill
out.''
</P>
<P>
   He was either being disarmingly honest or disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he was telling the truth or merely telling his critics
what he thought we'd write, anyway, the result was a slam dunk.
O'Neal cast himself in an unfavorable light, pumped-up pecs and
all.
</P>
<P>
   The muscle definition in O'Neal's arms is the first thing his
teammates noticed when they reconvened earlier this week. ``His
arms are definitely bigger,'' said forward Rick Fox. ``It's crazy
to think he got stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's downright foolhardly. Jackson asked O'Neal to slim
down specifically because the 30 pounds the player has put on since
turning pro places extra stress on the back and knees and invites
nagging injuries.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's rationale was as long as he added muscle, his weight
was immaterial.
</P>
<P>
   His joints will see about that. Muscle, fat, it's all just
pounds to them. If they could speak, they'd surely say, ``Lighten
up, Shaq!''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal lost 54 games to injuries in his first three seasons with
the Lakers. It doesn't take a coaching genius to recognize O'Neal
is no good to the team in street clothes.
</P>
<P>
   You also don't have to be class valedictorian to figure out if
you prepare for the college boards, the actual exam isn't likely to
be as overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the triangle offense is supposedly harder to
grasp than advanced trigonometry. O'Neal said he didn't see any
reason to study the preparatory packet Jackson mailed to every
Laker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is basketball,'' O'Neal said. ``It really can't be
that hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, and free throws are designed to be pretty easy, too.
O'Neal is shooting 53.6 percent from the foul line in his NBA
career, but he claimed not to have lost any sweat over it this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it's just a concentration thing,'' O'Neal said. ``It's
a fact I'm not a good free-throw shooter. If you want to write
about that, go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, it's not as though lapses of concentration are a
kind of chronic illness. They can be treated, through repetition
and resolve. Dodgers shortstop Mark Grudzielanek wasn't a very good
defensive shortstop in 1998. Rather than throw up his hands in
defeat, he sought the help of former ballplayer Bucky Dent over the
winter and his fielding was vastly improved this year.
</P>
<P>
   We know questions about his free-throw shooting must be a pain
for O'Neal to field over and over and over.
</P>
<P>
   But the more he acts as though he doesn't care, the harder
O'Neal's free-throw shooting is to ignore. Some of his teammates
think with Shaq it's just that, an act. They believe he did more
over the summer than he's letting on.
</P>
<P>
   For example, O'Neal never let slip that he placed a telephone
call to Detroit _ to Larry Drew, who helped teach the triangle
offense to the Lakers' summer league team.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's his free-throw technique, which has looked better
in the first couple of practices.
</P>
<P>
   And for all of O'Neal's jokes about dreaming of Krispy Kreme
doughnuts, he left a table of the glazed goodies untouched during
media day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq seems to be learning the art of war,'' Fox said, smiling
slyly. ``Deflect attention from yourself. Don't let people know
what you're doing. For a person like him who lives in a fishbowl,
that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   If O'Neal thought the scrutiny was suffocating in his first
three seasons in L.A., he hasn't experienced anything yet. The
hiring of Jackson raised expectations and reduced the number of
scapegoats to a solitary one.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers don't win at least 60 games and battle San Antonio
and Portland for Western Conference supremacy, O'Neal will take
more abuse from the public than he does nightly in the paint from
opponents. He'll have to absorb more hurtful shots than he did last
year for his fourth-quarter disappearing acts and ghastly foul
shooting and stubborn insistence on shooting despite being double-
and triple-teamed.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal didn't fall out of the Brinks truck just yesterday. He
has to understand this season _ his eighth in the league _ will go
a long way toward sculpting his legacy. He had three months to mold
himself in the image Jackson prescribed for him, to get ready for
his career close-up.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson wanted O'Neal to come to camp weighing considerably less
than the 335 pounds he was carrying at the start of last season.
O'Neal showed up a bulked-up 340 and blithely announced, ``I'm
ready to be real receptive to what Phil's saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, better late than never. If Jackson didn't comprehend the
breadth of the challenge he was taking on when he accepted the job
in June, he surely does now. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
