</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIH-SLOAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL INSTITUTES OF HEALTH CHIEF TO HEAD SLOAN-KETTERING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG and JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Harold Varmus, the Nobel Prize-winning molecular biologist
who has presided over the National Institutes of Health during the
greatest expansion in its 112-year history, told President Clinton
on Thursday that he would resign at the end of the year to become
president and chief executive of Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer
Center in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   When he left the University of California at San Francisco to go
to Washington six years ago, Varmus had never run anything larger
than a research laboratory. His tenure at the NIH was blessed by a
good economy and an explosion in biomedical research, and he took
advantage of both to persuade Congress to increase the agency's
budget vastly, to nearly $15.6 billion this year from $10.3 billion
in 1993, with a $2 billion increase last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   At Sloan-Kettering, Varmus, 59, will meet entirely new
challenges. He is a basic scientist _ he won ``the Prize,'' as he
calls it, in 1989 for the discovery of a family of cancer-causing
genes.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, he will be forced to face something perhaps even
more intractable than a divided Congress: a rapidly evolving payer
system in which managed care, so far mostly disdained by the
hospital, rules. He will now also find himself dealing with
insurance payment contracts and market share wars.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Varmus suggests that Memorial Sloan-Kettering
is hoping to move in a new direction. Its president, Dr. Paul
Marks, 73, who is retiring, developed the center's research base,
but now, its directors say, they hope to merge that research better
with cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Varmus was selected foremost for his clinical talents, said Dr.
William Hoskins, the deputy physician-in-chief of disease
management at Sloan-Kettering, who served on the search committee.
``Most of us in cancer realize the time is ripe to begin the
process of bringing the lab to the bedside,'' he said. ``I think he
has the vision to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years many area hospitals have elbowed their way into
cancer care, drawing on a huge base of patients who increasingly
must pay for their treatment under programs of health maintenance
organizations. Marks, who often hobnobbed with famous donors and
patients, has shown little interest in this issue, focusing instead
on the development of the center's research arm and endowment.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Varmus said that while he had mixed
emotions about leaving the NIH, he was ready for a change after six
years of government work. ``I wanted to run another organization,''
he said, ``and be in a position to see the fruits of 25 or 30 years
of cancer research in the lab come to fulfillment.''
</P>
<P>
   When Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and human services,
suggested Varmus for the NIH director's job, what most people knew
about him was that he had won the Nobel Prize, that he wore rumpled
clothes (he still does) and rode his bicycle 12 miles to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people didn't know if he had the temperament to do the
political work, because it's an enormously political job,'' said
Dr. Herbert Pardes, dean of the College of Physicians and Surgeons
at Columbia University. ``I think he outperformed the most
optimistic expectations that anybody had.''
</P>
<P>
   He is credited with lifting flagging morale among scientists,
both inside and outside the agency, by recruiting some of the best
minds in academia to the NIH.
</P>
<P>
   And Varmus proved himself an adroit politician, keeping a low
profile as he navigated such tricky ethical issues as the
still-unsettled question of whether the government should pay for
research on human embryonic stem cells.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday, Shalala said Varmus' appointment to NIH
was ``one of the greatest accomplishments of this administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Varmus told the directors of the NIH that he was leaving during
a staff meeting Thursday morning. The meeting was emotional, said
Dr. Richard Klausner, director of the National Cancer Institute.
``There was a sense of the passing of an era, an era about which we
all feel very good.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was not universal approval of Varmus' leadership.
Patient advocacy groups often complained that with his interest in
basic science, Varmus did not pay enough attention to their needs
and complained bitterly at his refusal to finance research on
specific diseases. Varmus' philosophy was that ``a rising tide
lifts all boats.'' He believed that an understanding of how cells
work and other matters of human biology would lead to discoveries
in all diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message out of NIH to the disease groups always seemed to
be, `Well, everything we do here benefits everything,' '' said
William Schmidt, a spokesman for the Juvenile Diabetes Foundation.
``Of course, that was very difficult for people to buy. It just
didn't sell well with our constituency.''
</P>
<P>
   And it also did not sell well with the Institute of Medicine, an
independent research arm of the National Academy of Sciences. In a
report last year, the Institute criticized the NIH for not paying
enough attention to patients and urged the federal health agency to
more systematically consider the deaths and suffering caused by
specific diseases when setting its research priorities.
</P>
<P>
   At Memorial Sloan-Kettering, Varmus will be greeted
enthusiastically, said Dr. Raymond Warrell Jr., an attending
physician and member of Sloan-Kettering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clinical staff is hugely excited,'' he said. ``The biggest
challenge is to integrate basic science programs to the direct care
of patients with cancer as quickly as possible. It is a challenge
that many cancer centers have faced and the fact that he faced them
on a national level is a huge plus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
