r s BC-BBN-ASTROS-NOTES-TEX     10-07 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS INTENT ON KEEPING CHIPPER JONES IN CHECK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Learning from the recent mistakes of manager Bobby
Valentine and his New York Mets, the Houston Astros are determined
not to let Atlanta Braves third baseman Chipper Jones beat them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hits a bad pitch, we'll tip our hat to him,'' Astros
pitching coach Vern Ruhle said. ``But he's not going to see a lot
of fastballs across the heart of the plate if we can help it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones burned the Mets by hitting four home runs in a key
three-game sweep that helped the Braves clinch the National League
East title. In the first two games against the Astros, he has one
hit and has walked three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting a little frustrating because I'm not even getting
strikes on 3-0,'' said Jones, whom the Astros even walked to load
the bases in Game 1 in order to face cleanup hitter Ryan Klesko.
``I've got to be patient and wait for my spots. We've got too many
good hitters for them to pitch around me every time. Sooner or
later they'll pitch to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we don't want to do is let Chipper beat us because
he's proven all year to team that he will do it,'' Ruhle said.
Football fever Although they are in the midst of a playoff series,
the Astros were bumped to almost a footnote in the frenzied
aftermath of Houston getting an NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   Energy billionaire Bob McNair went to the NFL owners meetings in
Atlanta and brought back an expansion franchise. All the Astros
brought home from Atlanta was a 1-1 split.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for the city,'' Astros second basemen Craig Biggio
said. ``It was a real shame for these fans when the Oilers left.
They deserve better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Houston team will play in a $310 million stadium being
built next to the Astrodome, giving the city two retractable-roof
stadiums by 2002. The Astros will move into downtown Enron Stadium,
also with an adjustable ceiling, next April. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Though almost 3,000 tickets remained late Thursday afternoon,
the Astros expect a sellout of almost 60,000 on Friday. ``It was
kind of a shame to see all those empty seats in Atlanta,'' said
Astros third baseman Ken Caminiti, referring to the 10,000
vacancies in Games 1 and 2 at Turner Field. ``I expect this house
to be full and rockin'.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Loud or not, the Braves don't exactly fear the Astrodome.
Atlanta is 39-16 in Houston since 1991, including 3-1 this season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Astros Outfielder Derek Bell, who had only 12 home runs and 66
runs batted in, might get a start against left-handed Tom Glavine
on Friday after sitting out the first two games in favor of Daryle
Ward. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
