<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-DEFENSE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS AND WHITE HOUSE COMPROMISE ON ELEMENTS OF SPENDING
MEASURE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS first 4 grafs with compromise; SUBS headline, ELIMINATES
clause from 7th graf) 
(ATTN: Fla.)  (rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the first sign of a break in a bitter standoff,
the White House and Congress compromised on changes in a $82
billion spending bill Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The talks between President Clinton's budget number-crunchers
and members of Congress on a bill for veterans, housing, space
exploration and other agencies led to additions of 60,000 housing
vouchers for working-class families, $100 million for NASA and $115
million for business enterprise zones and community development
programs.
</P>
<P>
   That money would be offset by cuts in housing and urban
development programs.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official called the talks ``the first significant
development'' in what has been a dialogue of the deaf between
President Clinton and Republicans in Congress over nearly $600
billion in spending bills. The talks lifted the president's veto
threat and appeared r the air for future negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of its budget battles, Congress has found the money
for seven luxury aircraft for the Pentagon's top commanders.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of obtaining and operating the aircraft over 20 years
comes to about $1 billion, according to the Pentagon, which never
formally requested the funds.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon spending bill allows the military buy a 737-300
jetliner and lease six smaller executive-class Gulfstream V jets to
ferry top commanders from base to base, said senior members of the
House Appropriations Committee's defense panel.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of leasing the Gulfstream jets is about $50 million a
year. They would serve the nation's nine top-ranking military
commanders-in-chief, eight of whom are based in the United States.
They now are flown in Boeing 707s. The cost of buying the 737,
which seats 126, is $63 million. It is for Marine Corps Gen.
Anthony Zinni and his successors at Central Command, which has
headquarters in Tampa, Fla., and is responsible for the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Congress was sure Thursday exactly how much money is
in the Pentagon spending bill for the 2000 fiscal year, although it
appears to be about $268 billion, not counting a separately
approved $1.8 billion military pay raise. That would be an increase
of more than $17 billion over the 1999 fiscal year, the biggest
such spending boost for the military in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Senior House and Senate negotiators approved the Pentagon bill
in a closed-door conference on Wednesday night. But their
colleagues were still requesting that money be added to the bill on
Wednesday afternoon, and their aides were still writing the bill
this evening.
</P>
<P>
   The two most senior House members at the conference, Rep. Jerry
Lewis, R-Calif., and John Murtha, D- Pa., said Thursday the bill
included $467 million for further research and development of the
Army's Comanche helicopter, which has been plagued by cost overruns
and technical problems and is on course to become the most
expensive helicopter in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question whether that baby can fly,'' Lewis said. The
Comanche program _ a $37 billion project to build 1,292 helicopters
_ will consume more than half of the Army's budget for aircraft
when the aircraft start rolling off the assembly line nine years
from now, the Army concedes.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Murtha confirmed that the Senate majority leader,
Trent Lott of Mississippi, had convinced the House to add $375
million for an aircraft carrier to be built in his home state. ``We
try to take care of leadership whenever we can,'' Murtha said.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha said the Air Force would never be able to build 339 F-22
jet fighters, as it plans. The House-Senate conference approved
$2.5 billion in research and development funds for the aircraft,
but insisted that prototypes pass stringent flight tests before the
$200 million jet goes into full production.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not ever going to build the numbers they want to
build,'' said Murtha. ``They'll be lucky if they'll be able to get
two wings _ that's about 140 airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon wants to build three new types of fighter jets _
the F-22, the Joint Strike Fighter and an improved F-18 _ at a
total cost of $350 billion. Murtha described this as ``a $350
billion problem'' that cannot be solved without cutting costs or
dramatically increasing military spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``These prices are outrageous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the $17 billion increase for the Pentagon, many of
the other spending bills for government agencies are being cut or
frozen by Congress. The military spending increase, combined with
caps, or spending limits, enacted in 1997, is creating intense
pressure for Congress to dip into surplus Social Security funds,
which it has pledged to protect, in order to finance government
agencies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Republicans are now weighing new across-the-board spending cuts
in domestic programs to protect the Social Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   About $7 billion in the Pentagon bill will be designated as
``emergency spending'' to evade the caps. Congress also has put the
emergency label, usually reserved for wars and natural disasters,
on $8.7 billion in agricultural aid and $4.5 billion to finance the
2000 census. That technically takes those billions off the books,
but the money has to come from somewhere _ arguably, the Social
Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of that argument, congressional aides said that the
``emergency'' designation for the census appropriation _ widely
ridiculed, because the Constitution commands that the census be
taken every decade _ soon may be removed.
</P>
<P>
   In other legislative action, the Senate Thursday night passed,
by a 73--25 vote, a $91.7 billion spending bill for the Labor,
Health and Human Services and Education departments. The bill
includes $18.5 billion drawn from a projected budget surplus for
the 2001 fiscal year. That is more money than Congress ever has
spent with advance appropriations in a single year, much less a
single bill.
</P>
<P>
   Though the measure actually increases spending for some
programs, President Clinton has vowed to veto it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
