u w BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-ART-1     10-07 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE ADOPTS PATIENTS' RIGHTS BILL OVER OPPOSITION OF GOP LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS 5th graf and second graf from end of 1st take for
clarification; adds new 2nd, 3rd grafs to 2ndtake and subs 4th graf
to add details on vote; deletes grafs 5-8 from original 2ndtake;
adds 6 grafs to end with background/details of House/Senate
bills.) (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By a surprisingly lopsided vote, the House of
Representatives passed a bill on Thursday to give patients a wide
range of new rights, including the right to sue health insurance
plans that cause injury by denying care or by providing substandard
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, 275-151, was a stunning rebuff to House Republican
leaders. Sixty-eight Republicans defied their leadership and voted
for the bill, despite pleas from Speaker Dennis Hastert, who said
he vehemently opposed the measure because it could lead to a flood
of lawsuits against health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's vote was the most serious setback for Hastert since
he became speaker nine months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, strongly supported by President Clinton, would
set uniform national standards for health insurance, a field
regulated mainly by the states for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Senate passed a bill providing patients with a more
limited set of rights. It differs from the House measure in two big
ways. Many provisions of the Senate bill would apply to only 48
million people, whereas the House bill would cover 161 million
people. And the Senate measure would not expand the right to sue
HMOs. Complicating the House-Senate conference that is to reconcile
the two versions, the House measure passed Thursday will be tied to
tax breaks passed on Wednesday that are opposed by Democrats and
the White House. Democrats said the tax breaks could jeopardize the
passage of any bill coming out of conference.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill on managed care was drafted by two of the most
stubborn and tenacious members of Congress, Reps. Charlie Norwood,
R-Ga., and John Dingell, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in New York City on Thursday for a fund-raiser,
congratulated the House. ``The passage of this bill represents a
major victory for every family in every health plan,'' he said.
But, he added, when House and Senate negotiators try to thrash out
their differences, ``Republican leaders must resist the urge to
weaken the patient protections guaranteed in the Norwood-Dingell
bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Rejoicing with supporters after the final vote, Dingell, who has
served in the House since 1955, said, ``This was as fine a piece of
work as I've ever seen in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   But the House Democratic leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri,
said the bill could get bogged down in negotiations with the
Senate. ``I'm worried that this bill will go into a conference
committee that never ends, and nothing happens,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would guarantee patients access to emergency care
and medical specialists; would let them appeal coverage decisions
to an independent board, and would prohibit HMOs from retaliating
against doctors who fight for the needs of their patients.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also make it much easier for patients to sue
health plans in state courts for injuries caused by the denial of
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1974,'' Norwood said, ``managed-care insurance plans
have enjoyed a near-total immunity from any legal accountability
for injuring and killing the citizens of this country for monetary
gain. No thinking, feeling American can agree to let that stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican who voted for the Norwood-Dingell bill, Rep.
Merrill Cook of Utah, said: ``If Americans have the right to sue
for a damaged fence or an unsafe toy, they should have the right to
sue if their life or health has been endangered. Doctors already
face liability, but often their decisions are forced upon them by
an insurance plan. It's only fair that insurance plans be held to
the same accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Hastert said, ``Under the Norwood-Dingell legislation,
trial lawyers will be given unprecedented new rights to sue at any
time for any reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep, Thomas J. Bliley Jr., R-Va., said, ``Patients need care,
not courts.'' The same lawyers who sued tobacco companies and gun
manufacturers are planning to file similar lawsuits against HMOs
and employers who provide health benefits to their employees,
Bliley said.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill defining patients' rights was bundled together
with a bill, passed by the House on Wednesday, to create tax breaks
to help individuals and small businesses buy health insurance.
Republicans strongly support the tax breaks, which could cost more
than $40 billion over 10 years, but Clinton and other Democrats
said the benefits would go mainly to a small number of healthy,
affluent people.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Democrats expressed concern about these costs on
Wednesday. But Clinton relieved some of the concern on Thursday
when he said, in a letter to House Democrats, that he would not
sign any legislation ``unless its costs are fully offset by the
conference committee.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's vote was a rare triumph of bipartisanship in a House
chamber that has been torn apart by bitter partisan strife for more
than four years. In that same period, Norwood, a dentist, fought
the leadership of his own party and a well-financed coalition of
insurance companies and businesses of all sizes, to get a
managed-care bill through the House.
</P>
<P>
   In a House where the outcome of most votes is clear before they
are taken, Thursday was unusual in that no one could confidently
predict the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   When Norwood's victory arrived, it came in a rush, with nearly
one-third of his fellow Republicans supporting the bill. Lawmakers
piled up ``yes'' votes so quickly that a majority was reached in
the first five minutes of the 15-minute voting period. Cheers went
up as the tally in favor of the bill passed 218.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 12 House Republicans from New York, all six
Republicans from New Jersey and one of the two Republicans from
Connecticut, Christopher Shays, voted for the bill, as did 206
Democrats and 1 independent. Two Democrats, Collin Peterson of
Minnesota and Virgil H. Goode Jr. of Virginia, joined 149
Republicans in voting against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs have helped employers control the cost of care, but in the
process they have infuriated many patients and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwood-Dingell bill was supported by many consumer
advocates and labor unions. But doctors and nurses made the
difference. The American Medical Association lobbied hard for the
bill. And Dr. Greg Ganske, R-Iowa, a surgeon, was a tireless
champion of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have rebelled against the constraints of managed care
because they feel that HMOs have compromised their decision-making
and their professional autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 238-193, the House on Thursday rejected a
substitute bill offered as an alternative by the House Republican
leaders. Twenty-nine Republicans joined almost all the Democrats in
opposing this bill, written by Reps. Tom Coburn of Oklahoma and
John Shadegg of Arizona, both Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Coburn-Shadegg bill would have provided patients with a
limited right to sue HMOs in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed on Thursday would pierce the shield of immunity
provided to many HMOs by a federal law, the Employee Retirement
Income Security Act of 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Under this statute, courts have repeatedly rejected lawsuits
that relate directly to the administration of claims under an
employee-benefit plan. But in the last two years, judges have
become more receptive to lawsuits seeking damages from HMOs on the
theory that the quality of care was inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every provision of the House bill, including the right to
sue, has been enacted in some form by one or more states.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate bills address similar issues. But doctors
and consumer groups prefer the House version because it applies to
more people and sets more stringent standards.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills say that if an HMO denies a claim for benefits, the
patient could have the decision reviewed by an independent panel of
medical experts.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House bill, if a health insurance plan tries to
control the costs of prescription drugs by establishing a list of
recommended medications, it must allow patients to get other drugs
that are medically necessary. The Senate bill has a narrower
provision.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill also stipulates that HMOs must pay the routine
costs of care for patients who enroll in certain clinical trials
testing drugs. The comparable Senate provision applies only to
clinical trials of anticancer drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills would prevent health plans from interfering with a
doctor's ability to discuss all treatment options with patients.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House bill, consumers in a group health plan could,
for an additional premium, buy coverage allowing them to use
doctors outside the network of physicians established by their
health plan. The Senate bill has a similar requirement, but many
employers would be exempt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
