<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0333 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-SCENE     10-07 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE HEARS GRIM TALES ABOUT MANAGED CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Texas, Wis., Mo., Iowa, Tenn., Calif., Ariz., S.C.)  (See also CONGRESS-HEALTH) 
(js) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One after another, the lawmakers told anecdotes
about constituents who had been harmed when they were denied
coverage by their health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Kind, D-Wis., told of a ``young family in Western
Wisconsin'' in which a little girl died after she was denied a
treatment for brain cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson-Lee, D-Texas, told of ``little Steve Olson''
who could not have a CAT scan he needed.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri, the Democratic leader,
described how in the 1970s, before managed care became widespread,
his young son was thought to have terminal cancer. But a doctor
tried an experimental treatment, and it saved the boy's life.
Gephardt wondered whether an HMO would permit such treatment today.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the end of the afternoon, Rep. Greg Ganske, R-Iowa,
trumped them all.
</P>
<P>
   He brought a guest onto the House floor, a 7-year-old boy from
Georgia, James Adams, who has artificial legs and no hands, and
with the boy seated in the front row in shorts and a tank top,
Ganske told his story.
</P>
<P>
   When James was 5 months old, Ganske said, he developed a high
fever. His mother called the family's HMO and was told to go not to
the local hospital but to another one 70 miles away. Halfway there,
the boy went into cardiac arrest. He was revived at the hospital,
but gangrene had set in, and it cost him both hands and both feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not an anecdote,'' declared Ganske, who is a surgeon.
``We need to fix this problem so these kinds of cases don't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The presentation may not have changed any votes, but it took the
wind out of the debate. No one else seemed to agree when the next
speaker, Rep. Van Hilleary, R-Tenn., complained that bringing the
boy onto the floor of the House ``borders on exploitation.''
</P>
<P>
   The managed-care industry was the subject of relentless scorn
Thursday before the House voted, 275-151, to give its patients a
wide range of new rights. No one rose to the industry's defense, to
say that rising medical expenses were destroying corporate profits
and draining the federal budget until managed care clamped down on
costs a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the House of Representatives was concerned, the cost
of health care, one of the central political questions facing the
country, was a subject for another time and another place. On
Thursday, the members were responding to the concern of their
constituents that if they or their loved ones get sick, they might
be denied treatment they need.
</P>
<P>
   It was taken as a given that health maintenance organizations
are remote bullies run by greedy bureaucrats. The only question was
what to do about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all been there ourselves, and we've seen our
constituents there,'' said Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the majority
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The patients' well-being,'' Armey said, ``comes before the
doctors, comes before the trial lawyers, comes before the health
care providers, comes before everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody in the House agreed. But then Armey got to his main
point. ``How could anybody,'' he asked, ``say to a distressed
husband or father or mother or daughter, we give you our promise
that six months from now or maybe a year, we'll get you on the
docket, and we'll let the lawyers and the judges decide.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of lawsuits was what divided Armey and almost all
the other Republicans from the solid bank of Democrats and, on the
crucial midday vote, from a couple of dozen Republican allies like
Ganske and Rep. Charlie Norwood of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   It gave Republicans the opportunity to vent their venom over
trial lawyers, who are major contributors to Democratic politicians
and the bete noire of the business interests that are the
Republicans' most important donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trial lawyers will be given unprecedented new rights to sue
any time for any reason in any venue,'' said Speaker J. Dennis
Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas of California declared, ``If you want to meet a
trial lawyer, follow an ambulance.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative John Shadegg of Arizona accused Democrats of
wanting to ``let the tort lawyers get rich and drive Cadillacs and
Lexuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers are hardly more popular nowadays than health maintenance
organizations, and in the past, such attacks have proved fruitful
for Republicans. That was the case, for instance, on measures to
limit lawsuits over faulty products and against the tobacco
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyer-bashing was not nearly enough today. There was
applause from Democrats when congressman Norwood, a folksy dentist
from eastern Georgia who is loyal to the Republican leadership on
every issue except managed-care regulation, said, ``If you make a
decision and the patient dies, then you need to be liable.''
</P>
<P>
   And by the end of the day, after it became clear that
Republicans had lost the battle, some were making jokes about the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a lawyer seeking punitive damages,'' said Rep.
Lindsey Graham of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Then he looked across the well of the House at congressman
Norwood and remarked: ``One thing I'm not going to do when I leave
here is go practice dentistry. So I don't appreciate all these
doctors trying to rewrite the liability law.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
