<SLUG> BC-WARNER-BAILOUT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER SELLS REMAINING THEME PARK BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. -- Warner Bros. has decided to bail out of its
fledgling foreign theme park business, a year after selling its
dozen Six Flags sites in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The studio this week announced a $180 million deal in which Six
Flags buyer Premiere Parks also will acquire the 3-year-old Movie
World theme park in Germany and the yet-to-open Movie World in
Spain. The deal also includes licensing rights to use Looney Tunes,
DC Comics and Cartoon Network characters in European and Latin
American parks.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement reflects Burbank-based Warner's strategy of
expanding use of its brand names. The studio granted Premiere,
which will have 35 theme parks worldwide when the deal is
completed, exclusive domestic license rights for its characters at
theme parks in the $1.9 billion Six Flags buyout last year.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic deal included the Six Flags California complex of
Magic Mountain and Hurricane Harbor in Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased to expand our successful theme park
partnership with Premiere Parks, the leading regional theme park
operator in the world,'' said Warner Chairman Barry Meyer in a
written statement. ``It enables us to further grow in the global
theme park industry while showcasing our characters on an even
larger scale.''
</P>
<P>
   A Warner spokeswoman said Premiere will offer employment to 40
staffers at the Glendale-based Warner Bros. International
Recreation Enterprises who have been working on construction and
design of the Spanish theme park for a 2002 opening. Nick Winslow,
chairman of the operation, has resigned to pursue other
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma City-based Premiere officials said they expect to meet
analysts' earnings estimates for the rest of this year and noted
there has been explosive growth at the four U.S. parks, including
Marine World in Vallejo, converted to the Six Flags format with
Warner and DC characters. The parks have posted 22 percent gains in
attendance and a 31 percent gain in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Premiere stock rose $2.875 to $30.438 a share Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991007.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
