<HEADLINE>
WOODSON QUESTIONABLE AFTER INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Pro Bowl strong safety Darren Woodson was forced
to leave practice with a sprained left ankle Thursday and is being
listed as ``questionable'' for Sunday's game at Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being that it is a Thursday injury is probably the biggest
concern,'' Dallas Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer said. ``We'll just
have to see how it is in the morning. It'll be a day-to-day
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodson, who suffered the injury when his foot was stepped on
during a passing drill, walked off the practice field and
immediately went inside to receive treatment.
</P>
<P>
   If Woodson is unable to play Sunday, Izell Reese is expected to
join George Teague as the Cowboys safeties. Reese, a second-year
player,has not started an NFL game. The backup would then be Singor
Mobley. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Cornerback Kevin Smith took a step closer Thursday to starting
at left corner against the Eagles. With Kevin Mathis nursing a knee
sprain that is expected to keep him out this week, Smith has come
back from a bulging disk in his back just in time. Coach Chan
Gailey confirmed that Smith can start, but that the coaches ``will
keep an eye on him'' for fatigue because of his layoff. Smith
hasn't played since the Aug. 9 Hall of Fame game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Right guard Everett McIver (strained hamstring) surprised
Gailey with the amount of team practice he was able to get in
Thursday. McIver's response today to the extended activity will be
a key. ``It's getting closer on him, closer than I thought,'' said
Gailey, adding there's ``an outside chance'' that McIver could suit
up against Philadelphia. Meanwhile, Tom Myslinski is taking most of
the repetitions at right guard.
</P>
<P>
   _ Right tackle Erik Williams (strained quadriceps) had a full
day of practice, a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cowboys' Oct. 31 game at Indianapolis has been moved to
3:15 p.m., by Fox TV. It originally was scheduled for noon. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
