<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD HASN'T BEEN KIND TO USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC coach Paul Hackett has tried just about
everything to prepare his team for the road.
</P>
<P>
   He first broached the subject back in August during training
camp. Then he used loudspeakers in practice to simulate crowd
noise.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he will skip the traditional Friday walk-through practice
inside Arizona's 56,500-seat stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett has tried just about everything because little has
changed the Trojans' luck so far. Since Hackett arrived, USC has
not distinguished itself on the road, compiling a lackluster 3-4
record.
</P>
<P>
   If you take out victories against traditional weaklings, the
Trojans are 0-4 in that span, failing to beat a single opponent
with a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans get their latest test Saturday, when they play
Arizona in Tucson. It's another opportunity for USC to prove it can
go into a hostile stadium and defeat a team that isn't considered a
pushover.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do it at some point. We will. When? I don't
know,'' Hackett said. ``You want to win a tough road game. That's
something you've got to get done if you're going to be a contender.
This is a momentum game.''
</P>
<P>
   It has to be, because the Trojans self-destructed two weeks ago
in Oregon, losing 33-30 in triple overtime and depriving themselves
of the biggest road win of the Hackett era.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Oregon game was so important for us. We knew it was a
chance to overcome (the stigma),'' Hackett said. ``More from a
coaching than player thought process.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no such worries when Hackett was an assistant at USC
in 1978, and the Trojans went to Alabama and defeated the
No.1-ranked Crimson Tide 24-14.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest struggles are not solely a Hackett phenomenon.
USC is just 5-8 in its past 13 conference road games since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the last time the Trojans defeated a top-25 team on
the road was in 1995, when they defeated Arizona 31-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the past guys have been intimidated or scared a
little bit,'' tailback Chad Morton said. ``I think times have
changed. Guys want to play on the road. I know I love playing on
the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans just don't seem to play well. It certainly didn't
look as though USC was road-tested against Oregon, when it
committed a school-record 21 penalties, including six false starts
by the offensive line in noisy Autzen Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Morton said that experience could propel the Trojans against
Arizona, no matter how loud the crowd might become in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the penalties, no one was arguing in Oregon. It
was something special in the huddle,'' Morton said. ``It made me
feel proud. Especially going to Arizona. It's going to help us in
that environment.''
</P>
<P>
   USC will take all the help it can get, and it's not just Hackett
who is concerned about becoming road kill again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about it a lot lately,'' quarterback Mike
Van Raaphorst said. ``We've had some heartbreaks and blowouts. It's
not the fact we didn't play well or play hard. I think we need to
take care of our business and have fewer penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is the answer to the Trojans' road woes? Nerves?
Distractions? The on-going penalty problem? Strange grass?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can say it's easy to lose focus, but I can't
pinpoint anything because if I could, we'd correct it,'' free
safety David Gibson said. ``It's like going to a foreign land and
winning a war.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (3-1, 1-1) are aware that every time they go into a
difficult road game, somebody anticipates something negative will
happen. Arizona's fans will no doubt be happy to see some miscues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're waiting for us to screw up,'' offensive tackle Travis
Claridge said. ``We have to use it to our advantage. We can use
Oregon as an experience game. A lot of the young guys hadn't played
in a noisy stadium.The only thing we have to prove is we can win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a breakthrough win if we get it.''
</P>
<P>
   No small feat, based on recent history.
</P>
<P>
   The plethora of penalties in Oregon has raised hopes within the
team that if it can avoid another meltdown, the Trojans should have
a good chance to end their drought with a victory over the
Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans have little impact. It's all us,'' linebacker Zeke
Moreno said. ``We made penalties and mental mistakes against
Oregon.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to see the silver lining, Morton was encouraged by
the way USC rallied behind Van Raaphorst after Carson Palmer broke
his collarbone. The Trojans came back from a 20-10 deficit against
Oregon and took a 23-20 lead in the final period before the Ducks
kicked a field goal with 30 seconds remaining to send the game into
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel we did face the worst situation we've ever been
in,'' Morton said. ``To come from behind like we did in the fourth
quarter, we're prepared for anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
