<HEADLINE>
STATE FARM HALTS DISPUTED PLAN FOR COVERAGE OF AUTO REPAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (bl)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Having lost a $456 million jury verdict Monday, State
Farm, the nation's largest auto insurer, announced Thursday that it
would temporarily require that all crash repairs on its
policyholders' automobiles be done with parts produced by auto
manufacturers or their affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   An Illinois jury decided Monday that State Farm had breached its
contract with policyholders by insisting that body shops use parts
that are not factory authorized, which tend to be less expensive.
Lawyers for the group of policyholders that sued had contended that
the generic parts did not fit as well and were of worse quality
than parts authorized by the auto manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Jack North, State Farm's senior vice president for auto
insurance claims, said that while the company still planned to
appeal the verdict, the policy was being changed immediately to
prevent confusion among State Farm's 36 million auto policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   He said that State Farm had not decided how long the new policy
would be in place, and added that the company's costs would begin
to rise if it required the use of more expensive parts for long.
</P>
<P>
   Because State Farm is a mutual insurance company, it is owned by
its policyholders and passes along its profits or losses to them in
the form of higher or lower rates. North said State Farm had
reserves to cover losses, and had no current plans to raise rates
to rebuild those reserves if its appeal of Monday's verdict was
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Nealey, one of the lawyers who sued State Farm, said the
insurer had acted appropriately Thursday. Independent producers of
substitute parts should treat the company's decision as a warning
to improve quality, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over State Farm's repair-payment policies coincides
with a move by auto manufacturers to spin off their auto parts
divisions into independent companies. General Motors' auto parts
unit became independent in May, while Ford Motor Co. is in
negotiations with the United Automobile Workers union this week
over Ford's plans to turn its auto parts business into a separate
company. The UAW told Ford on Wednesday that it would call a strike
at 11:59 p.m. Friday if disputes over parts' workers job security
and compensation cannot be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler AG and most of the Japanese automakers already
buy most of their parts from independent companies. The products
from these independent companies are sold as ``factory-authorized''
parts even though the manufacturers have not made them.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all manufacturers, however, continue to make their own
sheet metal parts, like hoods and roofs. Some of the fiercest
disputes between insurers and policy holders have been over whether
substitutes for these parts are truly identical. Sheet metal parts
are stamped out of huge sheets of steel using giant metal dies, and
substitute parts are not made using the same dies.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups have tended to advocate the use of substitute
parts, contending that their availability prevents auto
manufacturers from charging exorbitant prices for replacement
parts.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Gillis, the automotive expert at the Consumer Federation of
America, on Thursday warned that State Farm's decision would
eventually result in higher insurance premiums.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I think that is just more evidence of the chilling effect that
this lawsuit is going to have on the consumer,'' said Gillis, who
is also the executive director of the Certified Auto Parts
Association, a nonprofit group that sets standards for parts that
are not factory authorized. ``This means that the consumer is going
to immediately have to start paying more for crash repairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers who sued State Farm have said that they might sue
other insurers and the association next.
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois jury verdict applies to insurance claims filed from
July 31, 1987, to Feb. 23, 1998. Included are $243.7 million in
direct damages and another $212.4 for ``installation damages,'' the
estimated cost to replace the generic parts.
</P>
<P>
   A separate portion of the verdict, alleging fraud by State Farm,
must still be decided by the judge, John Speroni, who could also
assess hundred of millions of dollars in punitive damages and
damages for fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Fees for the lawyers who filed the class-action case still must
be decided by the court.
</P>
</TEXT>
