<HEADLINE>
TIME IS OF THE ESSENCE, EXCEPT FOR YANKS AND RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball is a timeless game, a pastoral endeavor unbound by the
tyranny of a ticking clock. Nine innings can stretch to eternity,
often joyfully. But the charms of timelessness can yield to a sense
of the never-ending and that pushing the final buzzer would be an
act of mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Not that a long baseball game is by definition numbingly dull or
a short game necessarily taut with tension. Yet as Game 1 of the
Texas Rangers-New York Yankees division series Tuesday night
slogged toward a length of 3 hours and 37 minutes, it was evident
that the Yankees' 8-0 triumph was a classic exercise in ennui.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only in the fifth inning and this game is creeping up on
two hours _ and I underline creeping,'' said Bob Costas, who called
the game for NBC.
</P>
<P>
   It was the longest playoff game of this post-season, 24 minutes
longer than the New York Mets-Arizona Diamondbacks series opener
later that night and 84 minutes longer than the one-hitter by the
Atlanta Braves' Kevin Millwood against the Houston Astros in Game 2
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees play long games, the longest in baseball _ an
average of 3:08 _ 4 minutes longer than Cleveland's, 15 minutes
longer than the major league average, and exactly the time it has
taken to complete a game this season in the National Football
League, which sports a 60-minute clock.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees score oodles of runs (900, third in the American
League); their hitters force pitchers into deep ball-strike counts,
a skill mastered by second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, and generate a
lot of bases on balls (718, second in the league). This takes time,
and sometimes it's exciting and competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees are a better team, get more hits, send up more
players in an inning and inspire more pitching changes than
others,'' said Steve Hirdt, the executive vice president of the
Elias Sports Bureau, baseball's official statistician. ``The teams
that get a lot of walks play the longest games.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoring 900 runs in a season, as the Yankees did this year, adds
minutes to baseball's invisible clock. And forcing managers to
amble from the dugout (they never run, do they?) to pull their
pitchers once, twice, three times or more in a game adds up. After
a while, you get real time.
</P>
<P>
   And so, on Tuesday night, 306 pitches were thrown, 171 by the
four Rangers' pitchers, 135 by the Yankees' Orlando (El Duque)
Hernandez and Jeff Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Those 306 pitches were seven more than the total thrown during
Game 2 of the Mets-Arizona series, yet that game _ with two more
hits (14 to the Yankees-Rangers' 12), but five fewer walks (9
versus 14) _ required less time to play.
</P>
<P>
   What made the Texas-Yankees game so slow?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the lopsided score. Maybe it was Juan Gonzalez's
fault. After each pitch, the Texas slugger stepped from the
batter's box. Every batter these days thinks the advent of a new
pitch requires a promenade. But Gonzalez, the two-time AL most
valuable player, takes epic strolls, for he is a serial loiterer.
He typically leaves the box with a bit of gardening with his
spikes, steps back, strolls, swings his bat a little, then returns
where he belongs. No umpire urged him back to the box Tuesday
night. His average dawdle: 14 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez outdid the Yankees' leader in dillydallying: Knoblauch.
His habitual perambulations entail a brief spell of crucial
dirt-kicking (three times), a ritual bow and touching of his shins,
tugging his batting gloves and a final return to the chalked
rectangle. Average dawdle: 11 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, it is worth mentioning that the Yankees' Paul
O'Neill and the Rangers' Ivan Rodriguez are modest promenaders,
usually departing the batter's box after a pitch for a mere five
seconds apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Some pitchers work quickly; some others are deliberate. Sele and
Hernandez broke no mound speed records Tuesday night. Mostly, they
took 15 to 20 seconds between pitches (time between getting the
ball from the catcher to the start of their windups). A simple
five-second reduction in their between-pitch contemplations would
have cut more than 15 minutes from the game.
</P>
<P>
   If El Duque had not shaken off catcher Jorge Posada's signs five
times, he would have saved nearly 90 seconds spent when his
dithering resulted in batters dallying out of the box. And
Hernandez could have cut another 24 seconds from his workday by
reducing his high leg kick, which made his quirky windup last 0.2
seconds longer than Sele's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many adjectives can be used to describe this game,'' Costas
said late in the game. ``Brisk would not be one of them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (The only time unavoidably lost in the game came when the
Yankees' yoda, Don Zimmer, was hit on the head by a foul ball
batted by Knoblauch. The game was held up for 3 minutes 20 seconds
as Zimmer was led to the clubhouse.)
</P>
<P>
   The inevitable result of the Yankees' clubbing of the Rangers
was Texas manager Johnny Oates' four pitching changes. Such moves
should not require an average 3:15 to execute, but here, managers
and players shouldn't be blamed. The culprit is greed. A reliever
trotting in to take eight warm-up pitches should not be a
miniseries. But when Oates removed Sele, then Tim Crabtree, then
Mike Venafro, his slow saunter to the mound needed 30 seconds, but
his appearance cued more than two minutes of commercials.
Thankfully, he made his next pitching change totally within a
commercial break.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's game will very likely be remembered for Bernie
Williams' six runs batted in, on a single, a double and a home run
(could he have run out that dinger a little faster, saving a few
seconds?). But it was not a memorable game, not when precious time
was frittered away by a batter's kicking away the dirt like a bull
about to charge a matador, or by a pitcher's slowing down his
windup from two seconds to five seconds simply because he had
runners on base. That crazy El Duque.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a great post-season game that lasts a long time,''
Hirdt said, ``the last thing you think is, `Boy, that was
boring.'''
</P>
<P>
   Better luck next time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
