<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE EMBASSY URGES CONGRESS TO END PROBE LINKED TO PHOENIX
CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
WASHINGTON _ Officials at the Chinese Embassy have tried to get
congressional investigators to back off from their probe of the
corpora tion that owns the COFCO Chinese Cultural Center in
Phoenix.
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to federal investigators in the case, the Chinese
officials warned investigators that the probe could jeopardize tens
of millions of dollars in Chinese purchases of U.S. grain.
</P>
<P>
   COFCO, the China National Cereals, Oils and Foodstuffs Import &AMP;
Ex port Corp., is owned by the Chinese government and is listed by
Fortune magazine as one of the world's 500 largest corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese also warned U.S. offi cials against relying on
information provided by Jianwei Ding, a former COFCO executive who
lives in Phoe nix and is seeking political asylum, said James
Wilson, chief counsel of the House Committee on Govern ment Reform.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Dan Burton, R-Ind., on Oct. 7 sharply
criticized embassy officials Shi Jianxin and Ci Bin for attempts to
influence the investigation into allegations that COFCO's top
executive in Phoenix sought to buy influence with a State
Department official.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an understatement to say that our meeting with Chinese
Embassy officials heightened our concerns,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never heard of embassy officials coming to a
congressional committee trying to discredit a wit ness. It is very
inappropriate, and it raises a lot of questions.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Kevin Binger, staff director of Burton's committee,
the two Chinese diplomats ``made a highly improper request of us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They conveyed a clear message that they wanted the committee
to end the investigation of COFCO and Elizabeth Mann (COFCO's top
ex ecutive in Phoenix),'' Binger said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Chinese also strongly implied that if the
investi gation continued, relations between the two countries could
be damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Ci Bin denied the claim that the embassy had used veiled threats
that the investigation could lead to can cellation of COFCO's
purchases of millions of tons of U.S. grain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no such intention to influence (the investigation),''
said Ci Bin, the embassy's first secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to let them know that this guy, Ding, is not a
good one. If you rely on what he says, maybe he gives you trouble,
because he lies all the time,'' Ci Bin said.
</P>
<P>
   However, committee investigators say that they regard Ding to be
a reliable source and that they have found independent verification
for much of what he has told them about the Phoenix operations of
COFCO.
</P>
<P>
   In July, a committee report stated that COFCO's top executive in
Phoe nix, Elizabeth Mann, provided gifts to a U.S. embassy official
in Beijing in an attempt to influence him to grant visas for travel
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The committee investigation was triggered by articles in The
Arizona Republic. The paper reported that former embassy official
Charles Par ish had improperly accepted gifts from Mann, a native
of China and a naturalized U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Mann and Ding have been engaged in a series of legal battles
ever since Ding, in 1996, told the Arizona Attorney General's
Office that Mann had rigged a pair of corrupt real estate
transactions on the 24-acre 44th Street site where the cultural
center was built.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations led to an investi gation that was aborted when
the proposed deals were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Ding, a COFCO executive at the time, refused a transfer back to
Beijing and filed for political asylum. He says that Mann would use
her political connections to have him ``jailed, tortured or
killed'' if he was forced back to China. An attorney for Mann calls
the claim ``silly and absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mann has won two judgments against Ding in Maricopa
County Superior Court, accusing him of cheating COFCO out of about
$40,000. Her attorneys are also providing information to the
Immigration and Naturalization Service attorney in Phoenix, who is
attempting to have Ding deported.
</P>
<P>
   Burton on Oct. 7 expressed concern about Ding's safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way he should be returned to China,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Committee investigators said this week that Chinese Embassy
officials contacted them after the committee issued a subpoena for
a broad range of COFCO documents.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is particularly inter ested in Mann's ties to
Parish, the former embassy official in Beijing. They are also
interested in Parish's connections with Johnny Chung, a
Chinese-American businessman who is at the center of a Democratic
Party fund-raising scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Chung told Burton's investigators this summer that he saw a
Chinese beer company executive hand Parish a bag of cash while
Parish was directing the visa section of the U.S. Embassy in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   When the Chinese Embassy officials met with congressional
investigators last month, they said Ding was living a lavish
lifestyle. James Wilson said the officials said Ding had bought two
luxury cars.
</P>
<P>
   Ci Bin said Oct. 7 that Elizabeth Mann had informed the embassy
that Ding owned not only the luxury cars but also an expensive
house.
</P>
<P>
   Ding, who delivers newspapers for The Arizona Republic, called
the claims ``ludicrous.'' He said he and his wife, an insurance
company employee, are buying a secondhand, 1998 Nissan pickup truck
with $1,000 down and leasing a Toyota Corolla for $200 a month. He
said the rent on their two-bedroom Phoenix apartment is about $530
a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why the embassy just believes Elizabeth Mann
without talking to me,'' Ding said. ``I would love to talk with
them. I am not hiding.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
