<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
 
McEWAN   IS WAITING IN THE WINGS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A month ago, Scott McEwan was third on UCLA's
quarterback depth chart and rarely practiced with the starting
offense. Now, he's one tackle from taking command.
</P>
<P>
   If starter Cory Paus gets hurt _ not unreasonable, given his
bruised ribs _ McEwan will play significant minutes for the first
time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Is he ready?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, he'll be fine,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``He
knows what's going on. He knows the game plan. The problem is with
live bullets coming at you. That's when guys get unraveled.''
</P>
<P>
   McEwan, a sophomore from Thousand Oaks, has played sparingly in
two games and thrown one college pass, an incomplete against Ohio
State. As the backup, he takes 20 percent of the snaps in practice
_ not nearly enough to gain rhythm or confidence. And that's a
controlled situation: Quarterbacks are not touched in practice,
much less tackled.
</P>
<P>
   How will McEwan respond to a punishing hit? How will he respond
to a blitz, or zone coverage, or an interception?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's comfortable, he can hurt a defense,'' offensive
coordinator Al Borges said. ``But I told him it's not just about a
classroom, it's about being in a lab. That's what games are, a lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``In class, you go through a syllabus. Now, he has to
successfully dissect a corpse. And he has to do it under pressure,
with incredible scrutiny, in front of a lot of people. You have to
be fearless.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Tailback DeShaun Foster (sprained ankle) has been
upgraded from doubtful to questionable. Defensive tackle Anthony
Fletcher (sprained foot) is also questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Fletcher) will be able to go,'' Toledo said. ``Same
thing with DeShaun. But we'll have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming on strong: Linebacker Marcus Reese, a Parade All-American
from San Jose, has been one of UCLA's most impressive rookies.
</P>
<P>
   He's the second-string weakside linebacker (behind Ryan Nece)
and an important component to the pass defense _ both for his
blitzing ability and coverage skills. He's also fifth on the team
in tackles (22) despite playing fewer snaps than the players ranked
ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very instinctive player,'' linebackers coach Marc Dove
said. ``He's a good tackler, he's a physical player, and he
separates from blocks very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Review of the Week: Defensive tackle Pete Holland, a history
major and six-time member of the director's honor roll, has agreed
to review a book each week for the Daily News. This week: ``Mr.
X'', by Peter Straub.
</P>
<P>
   ```Mr. X' is Straub's most-recent tale of fantastic and macabre
paranormality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before his mother's death, protagonist Ned Dunstan returns to
his hometown of Edgerton, Ill., where she reveals his father's real
name. The short trip evolves into a longer stay, as Dunstan
discovers the secrets of Edgerton's society and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book is somewhat compelling, but it falls short of
Straub's masterworks, `Mystery' and `Ghost Story.' As usual,
Straub's characters develop identities all their own. But in this
case, the confusing names and dates bog down the tale.''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 sacks (out of four).!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
