<SLUG> BC-FORTIER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSSIBLE RELEASE OF FORTIER RAISES QUESTIONS,
 SPARKS IRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX _ The blast ripped out an eye, put a large hole in his
head, severed ligaments in his wrist and left more than 100 other
cuts on his body.
<TEXT>
<P>
   So excuse Martin Cash if he's more than a little miffed.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Fortier, Timothy McVeigh's former best buddy, could be
getting out of prison Oct. 8 after serving four years for his role
in the worst domestic attack in U.S. history, the murder of 168
people in the bombing of the Murrah Federal Building in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see, Mr. Fortier helped sell and store stolen weapons
for McVeigh, his wife made a false ID for McVeigh and McVeigh told
them how he was going to set up the bomb in the truck,'' Cash said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fortiers don't sound like inno cent little doves, do
they?''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Paul Heath, another survivor, put it, ``trying to say
Fortier is not like McVeigh is like saying Herman Goering is not
like Adolph Hitler.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fortier, a former Kingman resi dent, has the trump card. He
was the federal government's star witness in the trials of McVeigh,
who was sentenced to death, and Terry Nich ols, who was sentenced
to life in prison, and cut a deal that sentenced him to 12 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors also never estab lished that Michael Fortier
or his wife knew that $2,000 in proceeds from the stolen weapons,
which Fortier gave to McVeigh, would be used in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appellate court ruled in June that Fortier should have
been sentenced under involuntary man slaughter, rather than
first-degree murder, statutes. He has served the maximum 51 months
on the lesser crime.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the bombing survivors contend, however, that U.S.
District Judge Thomas VanBebbee has the latitude to resentence
Fortier Oct. 8 to the original 12 years, given the extraordinary
nature of the truck-bomb attack and death toll.
</P>
<P>
   There are other issues to sort out if Fortier is released:
</P>
<P>
   Will he be able to profit from the bombing with a book or TV con
tract? Shortly after the bombing, he boasted to friends of his
desire to make money from his knowledge of events leading up to the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   How much money in fines and restitution will he have to pay? He
originally was assessed a $200,000 fine and ordered to make $4,100
in restitution to Roger Moore of Ar kansas, whose gun collection
was stolen by Nichols to get money for bomb materials.
</P>
<P>
   Will Fortier hide out in the federal witness protection program?
Death threats against Fortier, his family and attorney Michael
McGuire have been commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he walks, and I hope it won't be in Oklahoma, I want him to
live his life with his own name so we can all see what happens to
him,'' said Cash, who was working on the fifth floor of the Murrah
building on the day of the bombing, April 19, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Fortier, who allowed McVeigh to occasionally live in his
Kingman-area trailer in the two years after they both got out of
the Army, was convicted of conspiracy and trans portation of stolen
weapons, lying to the FBI and not telling law officers of McVeigh's
bombing plans.
</P>
<P>
   How deeply involved Fortier was has been a subject of
conjecture.
</P>
<P>
   In one court document, U.S. Attor ney Patrick Ryan noted that
Fortier ``did not willfully agree to use a weapon of mass
destruction'' while at the same time ``took action including the
transportation and sale of stolen firearms that facilitated the
bombing conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an extremely fine line, families of the bombing victims
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway you look at it, he's basi cally a co-conspirator,''
said Marsha Kight, whose daughter died in the blast. ``We want him
to do the entire 12 years, but it's so frustrating because even the
federal government wants to adjust his sentence down ward.''
</P>
<P>
   Four months before the bombing, Fortier accompanied McVeigh to a
storage shed in Council Grove, Kan., where he left 20 to 25 guns
stolen from Moore. The two also stopped in downtown Oklahoma City,
where McVeigh detailed his bombing plans. Back in Kingman, McVeigh
stacked soup cans on the trailer floor to demonstrate how he would
build the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   But there were many problems be tween Fortier and McVeigh.
</P>
<P>
   Fortier rejected McVeigh's offer to join the conspiracy in
September 1994. Fortier later refused to go with McVeigh to the
desert to test the detonation of a milk jug filled with ammonium
nitrate.
</P>
<P>
   While living with the Fortiers much of the time in the two
months before the bombing, McVeigh unsuccess fully tried to recruit
Fortier, court records say.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, McVeigh moved to sev eral Kingman hotels and cut off
contact with Fortier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
