u f BC-BRITAIN-U.S.-ELECTRIC     10-07 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-U.S.-ELECTRICITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S NATIONAL GRID TO SEEK MORE ACQUISITIONAS IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Northeast, Ore., Britain)   (bl)  
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David H. Jones, the group chief executive of National
Grid Group PLC of Britain, which has already agreed to buy a large
utility in New England, said Thursday that his company would seek
more acquisitions in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   He said in an interview that he would not begin his drive to
gain control of other utilities in the region until the Securities
and Exchange Commission approved his company's agreement, announced
in December, to acquire the New England Electric System for $3.2
billion. He added that he expected approval by early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said his company was not yet negotiating with utilities in
the Northeast but that his staff was gathering background on
companies that he might want to acquire.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was in New York on Thursday to attend a ceremony listing
National Grid Group's American depository receipts on the New York
Stock Exchange. ADRs of National Grid rose $3.75 Thursday, to
$38.125.
</P>
<P>
   The foray of National Grid, Britain's largest power-transmission
company, into New England was one of the first significant moves by
British utilities to bring their experience in coping with
deregulation to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to open utilities to competition in the United States
has been slower and more limited than in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking that they had an advantage, companies like National
Grid and Scottish Power PLC are seeking to build their presence in
the United States, particularly in regions where the states are
deregulating the utility industry.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish Power distributes electricity throughout Britain and is
in the midst of a drive to become a big seller of power to
consumers not in its traditional territory.
</P>
<P>
   The company on Thursday won approval from Oregon regulators to
buy Pacificorp for $6.4 billion, a deal that was announced in
December. There are other regulatory hurdles, however.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish Power wants Pacificorp, which is based in Portland,
Ore., for its coal-fired plants, which produce cheap power that can
be marketed to Western states like California as they open their
markets to outside competitors.
</P>
<P>
   National Grid's strategy is different in that it will primarily
distribute electricity and other services to customers in the
Northeast. In acquiring New England Electric, National Grid will
gain control of a large transmission system. In addition, New
England Electric announced in February that it would acquire
Eastern Utilities Associates for $634 million. That will result in
a combined company that has 1.6 million customers in Massachusetts,
Rhode Island and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the goal was to bring down the operating costs of the
utilities once they were merged.
</P>
<P>
   He said that his company had found many ways to get more
electricity to flow through existing lines by upgrading equipment
and using ways of servicing the system without shutting down power
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Under one method used in Britain, line workers are suspended
from helicopters and work on power lines while electricity keeps
flowing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
