u w BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-AD-NY     10-07 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH PLANS DEPICT LAWYERS AS THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CONGRESS-HEALTH) 
(js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a new 30-second commercial that the American Association
of Health Plans, the major managed care industry group, began
broadcasting in Washington this week. The commercial focuses on the
right to sue, the most contentious provision in the main patients
rights' bill, sponsored by Rep. John D. Dingell, D-Mich., and Rep.
Charlie Norwood, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Producer:
</P>
<P>
   Mark Goodin and The Murphy Pintak Gautier Hudome Agency Inc.
</P>
<P>
   On the Screen:
</P>
<P>
   The commercial opens with ominous music that instantly stirs
memories of the movie ``Jaws.'' A shark is swimming through a
school of fish toward a camera. The camera zooms in on the shark
surfacing, then fades to black. A shot of the Capitol appears, with
the urging to ``call Congress today.'' That image is replaced by a
shark devouring bloody bait. The shark swims off, and the screen
fades to black.
</P>
<P>
   The Script:
</P>
<P>
   Announcer: ``America's richest trial lawyers are circling _ and
your health plan is the bait. Trial lawyers are pressuring Congress
for new ways to sue your health plan. Think that won't hurt you?
Better think again. If trial lawyers get their way, health care for
millions of Americans could simply disappear. Call Congress today.
Tell them to protect your family's health care from the trial
lawyer feeding frenzy. Because if the trial lawyers win, working
families lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Accuracy:
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry asserts that the Dingell-Norwood bill,
by opening the industry to expensive lawsuits, would increase the
cost of insurance and thus result in a loss of coverage, because
employers would drop it or employees would decide it was too
costly.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office, analyzing an earlier patients'
rights bill, estimated that it would raise premium costs by 4.8
percent a month over five years, with the right to sue accounting
for 1.4 percent of that. (The monthly cost for an individual with
group coverage in 1999 was about $170.) Norwood estimates that his
bill would raise costs by an average of 3 percent a month. Diane
Rowland, an analyst at the Kaiser Family Foundation, a health
research group, said other studies had suggested that a right to
sue could result in a ``very, very modest cost increase in
premiums.''
</P>
<P>
   Scorecard:
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry is trying to redefine a brutal
political battle that has allowed supporters of patients' rights to
seize the populist high ground. Those supporters have argued that
health maintenance organizations and other health plans ought to be
held accountable _ in court, if need be _ when they deny needed
care and a patient suffers as a result. But this commercial argues
that health plans are not the enemy _ lawyers are. The commercial
argues that those lawyers, in the primal image of the shark, will
enrich themselves in lawsuits to the point where health insurance
will simply become too expensive for ``working families.'' The
industry lost a major battle with the House passage of the
Dingell-Norwood bill Thursday, and this commercial begins to frame
the issue for the conference committee, where the measure is to be
reconciled with the Senate version. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Robin Toner
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
