<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GADZURIC BACK, BUT ARE HIS KNEES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Bruins began their preseason conditioning
program Monday afternoon with center Dan Gadzuric, tender knees and
all, darting around Pauley Pavilion with his teammates. How long
that lasts may determine the course of UCLA's season.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially, Gadzuric is one of the most dominating players in
the Pac-10. He's a 6-10 sophomore with a hulking presence and
extraordinary athleticism. But Gadzuric has the knees of someone
twice his age, with chronic tendinitis in both and surgically
repaired meniscus in his left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Structurally, his (left) knee is fine in terms of recovering
from the surgery,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``The tendinitis
is something he'll have to learn to cope with.''
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric, who averaged 8.6 points and 5.7 rebounds, tore the
lateral mensicus in practice Feb. 24. He had arthroscopic surgery
the next day and missed the NCAA Tournament loss to Detroit. He
recovered in time to attend two summer camps for big men and, for
the moment, he's at full speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a catch-22,'' Lavin said. ``If he does too much, he'll
wear his knees out. But he has to do enough to stay sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   Good and bad: NCAA rules prohibit conditioning programs until
fall classes begin. For UCLA, that's this week _ meaning the Bruins
are 4-6 weeks behind semester-system schools such as Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will have just two weeks of conditioning before
practice starts Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two ways to look at it,'' Lavin said. ``When you win
the national championship, people say it's because UCLA was fresher
late in the season. When you lose in the first round, people say
UCLA wasn't in as good condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Back and bigger: Sophomore guard Billy Knight spent last season
lifting weights and recovering from a groin injury. He has returned
15 pounds bigger and a step quicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``His redshirt year really helped,'' Lavin said. ``He worked as
hard as anybody in the offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Roster stuff: Junior forward Todd Ramasar may miss the season
because of an injured left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Ramasar, junior Ryan Bailey and senior Sean Farnham are on
scholarship this season.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting update: The Bruins have three scholarships available
as the 1999-2000 recruiting season heats up, but that would change
if Gadzuric and 6-10 forward Jerome Moiso turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin's emphasis is frontcourt players _ including Bill Walton's
son, Chris _ but the Bruins will be highly selective. The junior
class is one of the best in Southern California in years, and UCLA
already has a commitment from Mater Dei junior guard Cedric
Bozeman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got nine perimeter guys and three post players,'' Lavin
said. ``One of our goals is to load up with five or six guys who
are 6-10 or bigger.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-99 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
