<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS LOOK TO HAMPTON TO SHUT DOWN BRAVES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Back on their home field, and with their best pitcher
ready, the Houston Astros said Thursday that they liked their
position heading into Friday's encounter with the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   With the best-of-5 series tied, 1-1, the Astros will send Mike
Hampton to the mound shortly after 4 p.m. Eastern time. Game 3 has
all the makings of a pitcher's duel, with Hampton (22-4), a Cy
Young Award candidate, opposing Tom Glavine (14-11), a two-time Cy
Young winner who has won his last eight decisions at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   For the Astros, the outcome will be an emotional lift or a
severe blow. Houston was 29-5 this season when Hampton started, and
manager Larry Dierker struggled to think of another pitcher he
would prefer to have for an important game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Bob Gibson in his prime,'' Dierker said with a smile.
``Mike's our guy, the guy we usually win with. We've got good
pitching, but if you ask the guys out on the field who they feel
most comfortable with, I think they'd say Hampton.''
</P>
<P>
   A 27-year-old left-hander with excellent control, Hampton
elevated himself this year to the level of the game's best
pitchers. He had an 11-game winning streak, the longest in the
major leagues, and since June 4 has gone 17-2.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton won his only start against the Braves this season, 10-4,
and the Braves touched him for three runs in seven innings. But
that was in May. The atmosphere Friday will be far more intense,
and Hampton was looking forward to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a pressure situation, it's easy to get up,'' he said. ``If
you do well, you look great. If not, you look like a guy that's
choked. It's a double-edged sword. Those are the ones that test
your character.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros will also be tested by Glavine, who knows how to win
big games. With his lengthy winning streak in the Astrodome, how
sad will Glavine be to see the Astros move into a new stadium next
year?
</P>
<P>
   ``For selfish reasons, I'm disappointed to see it go,'' Glavine
said of the Astrodome. ``I've had good success there. That's one of
the few parks you go into and feel like it's more of a pitcher's
advantage than a hitter's advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Atlanta's past success against Houston is
another obstacle for the Astros to overcome. The Braves were 6-1
overall against Houston this season, and 3-1 in the Astrodome. The
Braves retain the swagger and confidence that comes from winning
eight division championships in the 1990s, and with John Smoltz
scheduled to pitch Game 4, the Braves have another top-flight
pitcher waiting no matter what happens on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that this series is going to be tough for
us, because they play well in our park,'' Dierker said. ``This is a
pitcher's park and they're a pitching team.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Astros Thursday refused to believe that Atlanta held the
psychological edge. Houston has been eliminated in the first round
of the playoffs the last two years, but after splitting the first
two games of this series in Atlanta, the Astros believe they are in
position to pull off an upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would've been nice to win both games in Atlanta, but
looking at the big picture, that may have been a little
unrealistic,'' said Ken Caminiti, the third baseman, who has hit a
home run in each of the last two games. ``Winning Game 1 is
important, and I don't think anyone on our team is thinking about
what has happened in the past. We're loose and we're playing good
baseball. We're facing a great team, but we feel very good about
ourselves.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
