<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMETICS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: SEPHORA PLANS A CAMPAIGN TO RAISE ITS PROFILE AMONG
CONSUMERS. 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 BY STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Through the centuries, beauty has inspired philosophical musings
from ``Beauty's but skin deep'' (John Davies of Hereford, 1616) to
``Beauty is in the eye of the beholder'' (Margaret Wolfe
Hungerford, 1878) to ``Beauty's where you find it'' (Madonna,
1990). Now comes an advertising and marketing blitz seeking to add
``Beauty is how you see it'' to that list of pithy sayings.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase is the theme of an ambitious campaign to raise
awareness for Sephora, a nontraditional retailer owned since 1997
by the luxury goods powerhouse LVMH-Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton.
Sephora specializes in selling higher-priced cosmetics and
fragrances in ways intended to be significantly different from the
conventional methods of department stores.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, at Sephora's 219 stores in Europe and the United
States, products are arranged alphabetically rather than segregated
by manufacturer, the popular promotional tool known as ``gift with
purchase'' has been eliminated and customers are encouraged to
sample items like lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   Sephora and the New York office of DDB Worldwide Communications
Group, the Omnicom Group unit that became the retailer's agency
early last month, are introducing the campaign to coincide with two
events planned for October 14: the opening of a big store in
Rockefeller Center in Manhattan and the revamping of the Sephora
World Wide Web site (www.sephora.com) to add electronic commerce
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been very effective in public relations but were
reluctant to invest much in advertising,'' said Howard Meitiner,
president and chief executive for the Sephora Americas and
Asian-Pacific operations, who is based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with the advent of the E-commerce site, the competitive
marketplace and our opening larger, more important stores,'' he
added, ``we found it was time to take our message to the
consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Sephora plans to spend $25 million on the campaign, which began
last week with ``teaser'' ads and is scheduled to run for 16
months. DDB was selected after a review that began in early summer,
which involved asking several agencies for ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign proposed by DDB ``distanced itself from all the
others presented to us to such a degree that they immediately
became the front-runner,'' said Steve Bock, executive vice
president for merchandising and marketing at Sephora.
</P>
<P>
   ``They instantly understood the concept of Sephora,'' he added.
``We didn't want ads with another beautiful woman. We wanted
something as distinctive as Sephora.''
</P>
<P>
   The DDB idea was to center the campaign on images resembling the
inkblots familiar from Rorschach tests, reproduced in a spectrum of
colors representing the colors found in the Sephora stores and
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rorschach represents the personal interpretation of
beauty,'' said Di Walker, the associate creative director at DDB
who is the art director on the campaign. ``The power is in the
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   To test whether the inkblots were too ethereal, nebulous or
complicated for a sales pitch, Ms. Walker and Kate Murphy _ her
copywriter partner on the campaign, also an associate creative
director at DDB _ showed mock-ups of the ads to Manhattan
pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   ``People knew they were supposed to `see' into them,'' Ms.
Murphy said. ``Some saw a turtle, some a face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' she added, ``and it helped us refine the
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The ersatz Rorschachs _ say that three times fast _ are
accompanied by brief sentences meant to reflect that ``there's a
mystery surrounding Sephora because it's a new concept,'' Ms.
Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one ad asks: ``Have you ever wondered what other
people see? Does it really matter?'' A second ad declares ``What's
so amazing about you is that no one else is.'' A third promises
that Sephora stores offer ``hundreds of skin care lines, an
infinite number of cosmetics and your imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   One ad, devoted to the Web site, declares that it offers
``virtually every'' product in categories like eye shadow, nail
color and fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We carry products from around the world,'' said Jim Kenney,
acting chief executive at Sephora.com. ``We're celebrating global
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The inkblot is ``a global symbol of self-interpretation,'' he
added, ``that will catch people's eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which will run in metropolitan New York and in
national media, includes television commercials; ads in magazines
like Details, Elle, Interview, Harper's Bazaar, Marie Claire, New
York, Paper, Vogue and YM; posters on telephone kiosks, buses and
taxicabs; postcard ads from Max Racks and Hot Stamps, and inkblot
images projected onto buildings by a company called Off the Wall
Projections.
</P>
<P>
   The new Rockefeller Center store, at 21,000 square feet, is
intended to be the Sephora worldwide flagship outlet. It is one of
37 stores in this country; plans call for more than 50 to be open
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Sephora has two other stores in Manhattan. The first opened last
year in SoHo and the second opened last week in Times Square, next
to the new street-front studio for ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little concern about the midtown Sephora stores being
so close to each other, given that retailers like Gap and Starbucks
can be found every few blocks in crowded urban markets.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the chains can merge to form a retail giant,
Gaphorbucks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
