<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MOVES TO CURB DEVELOPMENT ON NATIONAL FOREST LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Western states, Va., W.Va.)   (bl)  
 By DAVID STOUT   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton wants the Forest Service to draft
a plan to protect up to 40 million acres of national forest land in
35 states from commercial development, a White House official said
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the president would announce the plan next
week. It will be in the form of a directive that requires no
approval from Congress, although some lawmakers from Western states
are almost certain to try to undo the directive by legislation, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The official said Clinton was taking the action ``to preserve a
lot of pristine forest that might otherwise be turned into
something else.'' The proposal would be a major initiative in land
preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The president's intentions were reported in Thursday's
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the lands in question were ``spread out across
the country'' and included some tracts in Virginia and West
Virginia. But vast stretches of the forest territories lie in the
West, and a plan to keep them away from loggers and builders is
sure to foment spirited debate over the environment vs. the economy
and the federal government's right to tell states how to treat land
within their borders.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's directive to the Forest Service will ask for an
environmental analysis on how best to safeguard those reaches of
forest land still undeveloped, the White House official said. He
said the president's decision was not motivated by a desire to
protect endangered birds or animals but simply to leave as big a
legacy of unspoiled land as he could.
</P>
<P>
   Forest land that is still undeveloped, or ``roadless,'' is often
the most valuable to the timber industry. Conversely, many
environmentalists say that keeping forests empty of roads is the
best way to keep them full of trees.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, members of Congress from Western states have
complained bitterly about economic hardships that they say are
caused by conservation-minded politicians who know too little of
life outside of Washington, let alone far west of the Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to visit the George Washington National
Forest in Virginia on Wednesday, and the White House official said
the announcement might be made then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
