<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0359 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-NYT     10-07 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST HOW SEXY DOES A WOMAN WANT TO LOOK? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ There are always big thoughts to think as a fashion
season winds down: how designers translated the work of their
predecessors, which editors had the newest Prada bags a dozen hours
after they appeared on the runway, how Ivana Trump (seated in the
front row Wednesday) would look in Alexander McQueen's studded
wrestling helmet for Givenchy.
</P>
<P>
   But the question that usually trumps the others boils down to
sex and to what extent designers read and misread how adventurously
women want to emphasize it. At a basic level, fashion offers women
a range of sexual poses _ ravenous, assured, aloof, hesitant,
indifferent. As the spring collections conclude here Friday, after
a week of hot pants, lace-up stiletto boots and halter tops, it
would be easy to say that those who showed had a narrow idea _ a
very ``Cinemax late at night'' idea _ of how a woman wants to
present herself.
</P>
<P>
   But that would be a lazy statement. McQueen at Givenchy and
Stella McCartney at Chloe put sex in the forefront, but they did so
in a considered, literate way that many young American designers
can't quite manage. By comparison, the clothes that fill the
boutiques of NoLIta in Manhattan seem as sophisticated as a
Tupperware party: sequined knee-length skirts and dainty
three-quarter-sleeve cardigans, the kinds of clothes that young
women reading ``The Girls' Guide to Hunting and Fishing'' would
wear to impress their girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   McQueen's Givenchy show created a world of invulnerability.
Turning the Carrousel du Louvre into a mock high-school gym,
McQueen played with a notion of cool sexual bravura, the kind you
might see among teen-age girls riding the subway after school. They
own the town, they intimate, and you wish you could, too.
</P>
<P>
   McQueen's missteps _ bright yellow mesh athletic wear, that
goofy wrestling helmet _ might be written off as building blocks
for his message. Above it all were his confident suits, with their
masterly cuts, along with lots of leather and sleek racing
sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that the atmosphere McQueen creates at his shows
is so at odds with that of the Givenchy stores. Entering the
Givenchy shop on the Rue du Faubourg-St.-Honore after seeing his
show is like going to a Marilyn Manson concert, then visiting the
singer at home, only to find that he lives in a chintz-splattered
colonial in Scarsdale. The shop is stuffy and unhip, to say the
least, and appears to have little of what's shown on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours before the Givenchy show, Ms. McCartney sent out a
collection for Chloe that in the hands of many other designers
would make women look as though they ``date,'' in the 10th Avenue
sense of the word. Ms. McCartney offered more of the glamorously
tailored wide-bottom trousers and delicate dresses for which she is
famous. But more strikingly, mere strings of fake diamonds were
turned into bare tops and tight, frayed white-denim short shorts.
Silk halters were done up with fake jewels, too.
</P>
<P>
   How she didn't fall off the balance beam is a bit of a mystery,
but it might have something to do with the fact that Ms. McCartney
has a keen understanding of the contemporary young woman _ and a
sense of humor, too. She knows that sometimes women want to be
objectified. Why else would they wear strips of jewelry over their
breasts and think they were sufficiently clothed to leave the
house? But she also knows that they want to  &UR; appear &LR;  as if they're
above all that. So throw on some white jeans with that racy top,
which is how Ms. McCartney presented it.
</P>
<P>
   Her ironic take on the whole subject came through in T-shirts
that depicted bent-kneed topless women, the kind that might be
tattooed on the arm of a longshoreman.
</P>
<P>
   When Rei Kawakubo of Comme des Garcons presented her show
earlier in the week, it wasn't sex that was on the program _ that's
not her metier _ but femininity. In recent seasons, she has
increasingly explored notions of what the world interprets as
feminine. On Tuesday, she showed a collection striking in its
wonderfully saturated colors: deep pinks, purples, bright greens.
Central, too, were elaborate ruffles resembling the crepe paper
flowers schoolchildren make.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Ms. Kawakubo's clothes left one to marvel at how they
were made. She applied her inventive spirit to patterns, lining
jackets and coats with fabric cut larger than the exteriors and
scrunching it underneath. The resulting garments almost appeared to
be blossoming.
</P>
<P>
   Femininity was what Martine Sitbon, a minimalist at heart, aimed
for, too. Before her show Wednesday, she said she wanted to capture
the sense of possibility young women feel before they go out at
night. ``It's exactly the moment when girls are together, putting
on their makeup, and they don't know what will happen,'' she said.
``I wanted this collection to be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The sorority sister, ``maybe I'll meet Johnny Depp tonight,''
mood was not achieved, however. Ms. Sitbon, who had stunning
clothes in her fall collection, showed somber skirts, geometric
satin patchwork jackets and dresses that looked as though they were
forcing themselves to have a good time. Some of the clothes were
styled with blue pantyhose that would surely make the wearer feel
out of place at a party rather than the life of it.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone understands what it means to be the life of the party
it is Emanuel Ungaro, who spent the 1970s feverishly mixing prints
for women who probably didn't go anywhere that wasn't Biarritz. The
Ungaro woman lived for the action, and if a shadily financed
boyfriend was picking up the checks, well, all the better. With
Donna Summer blaring, Ungaro re-embraced the world of the revolving
mirrored ball. There were big tropical prints and polka dots, lots
of asymmetrical chiffon. Disco can be an objectionable subject, but
there's something harmless, altogether honest, about someone like
Ungaro invoking it. ``I'm reviving myself,'' he joked at his
atelier the day before the show.
</P>
<P>
   Sexiness that's elegant seems to be the goal of Cristina Ortiz,
a former Prada designer who has been redirecting the house of
Lanvin. Ms. Ortiz seemed freed a bit from her rigid shapes of last
season. Her show Wednesday offered fitted red cotton dresses and
coats, some bare backs, low-slung trousers and a beautiful skirt
made up of thin, glimmering triangular tiles. A woman would not go
to Lanvin to outfit her wildest self, but if that unabashed self
isn't surfacing as much as it used to, a pair of Ms. Ortiz's
needlepoint hip-huggers might be just bold enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
