<HEADLINE>
WELDON CASE, 78, FORMER CHAIRMAN AND CHIEF EXECUTIVE OF ALLTEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Weldon W. Case, the former chairman and chief executive of the
Alltel Corp., died on Sept. 30 at Boca Raton Community Hospital in
Florida. He was 78 and lived in Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure, an Alltel spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Case was born in Hudson, Ohio, where his family owned the local
telephone company. In 1910, his grandfather, Weldon C. Wood, was
among the first telephone company executives to bury phone cables
underground rather than hang them on poles.
</P>
<P>
   Case joined the company, the Hudson Underground Telephone Co.,
at 14 as a member of the line crew and worked his way up to general
manager and president. Hudson Underground eventually became known
as the Western Reserve Telephone Co.
</P>
<P>
   The days of the independent small-town operator, however, were
numbered. In 1960, Case combined five small Ohio telephone
companies into a holding company called Mid-Continent Telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect the attrition of smaller companies to continue at an
even smarter pace,'' he told the New York Society of Security
Analysts in 1963. At that point, Mid-Continent owned nine Ohio
companies that served 95,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, it merged with the Allied Telephone Co. of Little Rock,
Ark., forming Alltel. Case was chairman and chief executive until
he retired in 1991. At that point, the company had a million
customers in 19 states.
</P>
<P>
   Case attended Case Institute of Technology and Ohio Wesleyan
University.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Beatrice Kuhn Case; two brothers,
Nelson H. Case and Theodore H. Case, both of Carmel, Calif.; two
sons, Thomas W. Case of Little Rock and William R. Case of
Columbus, Ohio; four grandchildren, and three great-grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
