<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS' GOALIE EJECTED IN 7-5 LOSS TO PENGUINS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In their first meeting since the
elimination of the New Jersey Devils by the Pittsburgh Penguins in
the first round of the playoffs last spring, New Jersey lost its
goaltender to an ejection early, then spent the rest of the game
trying to catch up as the Penguins went on to a 7-5 victory
Thursday night before a Continental Arena crowd of 17,507.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur, the goaltender, slashed Matthew Barnaby in the
late stages of the first period and was ejected for the first time
in his career. The Devils, in their home opener, fell behind twice
by two goals and failed to fully recover.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Bombardir, Bobby Holik, Jason Arnott, Brian Rolston and
Sergei Brylin scored the goals for the Devils, who are now even for
the season after winning the season opener last Saturday in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Alexsei Morozov led the Penguins with a natural hat trick, the
first of his career, before the game was 12 minutes 39 seconds old.
</P>
<P>
   Jiri Slegr, Jaromir Jagr, Robert Lang and Alexsei Kovalev also
scored goals for the Penguins, who also lost their starting
goaltender, Tom Barrasso, in the first period, to a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur was given a five-minute major and a game misconduct for
slashing Barnaby to the right of the net in a sequence in which
Barnaby and Brodeur collided behind the goal with 5:28 left in the
first period.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur's ejection came after he faced eight shots and allowed
three goals, all to Morozov, who registered his hat trick in a span
from 5:27 to 12:39. It was the first hat trick in Morozov's career
and the first the Devils allowed at home since Mario Lemieux's, on
Oct. 28, 1995, in a 5-3 loss to the Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   Barrasso aggravated his knee 8:22 into the game, when he
sprawled to his left with a crowd in front. Barrasso allowed a goal
on two shots and his place was taken by Peter Skudra, who was
Barrasso's backup last season.
</P>
<P>
   Morozov's first goal of the season matched Bombardir's goal for
New Jersey, which came 36 seconds into the game on a blast from the
right circle that beat Barrasso on the first shot he faced.
</P>
<P>
   A giveaway by the Devils in their zone led to Morozov's second
goal, 11:44 into the period. Morozov completed his hat trick 54
seconds later with a backhander immediately after Robert Lang won a
faceoff from Sergei Nemchinov.
</P>
<P>
   Holik narrowed the gap for the Devils with his third goal of the
season, at 2:35 of the middle session, on a second effort in front
of Skudra. But the Penguins widened the lead to two goals again 37
seconds later, with Slegr's first of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Power-play goals by Arnott and Rolston just over two minutes
apart tied the score for the Devils. Arnott's came on a two-man
advantage as the Penguins kept taking penalty after penalty.
Pittsburgh incurred five minor penalties in five minutes midway
through the period and paid the price. Jagr and Lang scored their
first goals of the season late in the second period to re-establish
a two goal lead for the Penguins, 6-4, as the wild game swung into
the the third period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
