<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-07 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0371 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ELLIS-TEX     10-07 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ELLIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUCHDOWNS, BIG PLAYS PULL COWBOYS' ELLIS OUT OF HIS SHELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The differences between Greg Ellis' rookie
campaign in 1998 and his start to the 1999 season seem endless.
</P>
<P>
   Two-and-a-half sacks in three games make surpassing the
personally disappointing three he recorded last season virtually a
given.
</P>
<P>
   Two astonishing touchdown returns, an 87-yard interception jaunt
against the Falcons and a team-record 98-yard fumble rumble against
the Cardinals, have quieted the
Cowboys-should-have-picked-Vikings-receiver-Randy Moss talk.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis's defensive line mates have taken to calling him Mr. TD.
And Cowboys cornerback/punt returner/preacher Deion Sanders wants
to teach him a touchdown dance.
</P>
<P>
   However, the change Ellis likes best is at home, where his wife,
Tangie, no longer has to tiptoe around a sulking husband.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis _ respected so much by Texas coach Mack Brown (his former
college coach at North Carolina) that Brown said he would consider
allowing Ellis to adopt his children if something ever happened to
him and his wife _ knew he wasn't himself last season.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted his unyielding desire to succeed, the thought that
he was letting ``Mr. (Jerry) Jones'' down because of his paltry
sack totals after being the eighth pick in 1998 draft, and the Moss
reference drove him into a shell at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't go home yelling and screaming,'' Ellis said. ``I just
sheltered myself away and wanted to be alone. We've been together
since high school. She knows me. My actions and the way I would go
about things at home let her know I wasn't happy. I'm sure she got
tired of me crying about not getting enough sacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Three games into the 1999 season, he has come out of his shell.
His two touchdowns _ legendary Cowboys defensive ends Ed Jones and
Harvey Martin played a combined 26 seasons without scoring a
touchdown _ have turned him into an instant star.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ellis refuses to get caught up in the hype. He said he
understands that the season is young and that he has a long way to
go to reach his goal of becoming a Pro Bowl-caliber performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those long runs capture the fans' attention,'' Ellis said.
``That's good. However, the most important thing is to improve as a
football player. I feel I'm making progress, getting more pressure
on the quarterback and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything Ellis is doing is what the Cowboys coaches are noting
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a lot of notoriety for the big plays,'' Cowboys coach
Chan Gailey said. ``But the thing most impressive about Greg is how
he has really paid attention to the details of the position. He's
made dramatic improvement in a lot of areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the improvement was expected, said Cowboys assistant
defensive line coach Jim Jeffcoat, who said better play was bound
to come from a player a year older and a year wiser in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffcoat also emphasized that Ellis was far from a bust last
season when he became the first rookie defensive lineman to start
the season opener for the Cowboys since Hall of Fame member Bob
Lilly in 1961. Ellis started 16 games and became the first rookie
to lead the defensive line in tackles (63) and quarterback
pressures (22).
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys didn't seem to view the minuscule sack numbers as a
big deal either, considering that the defensive scheme called for
Ellis to focus on stopping the run rather than pressuring the
quarterback. Jeffcoat said Ellis, though listed as a defensive end,
was more of a ``third defensive tackle,'' positioned inside the
offensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis repeatedly heard such rationale during the season and
during individual player evaluations after the playoff loss to the
Cardinals in January. However, the 6-foot-6, 286-pounder, who
surpassed Hall of Fame linebacker Lawrence Taylor as the all-time
sack leader at North Carolina, still played the shell game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just beat myself up,'' Ellis said. ``The coaches told me I
had a good rookie year. But I wasn't satisfied with it. I was like,
`Man I wanted to get more sacks.' I am really critical of myself.
I'm one of those guys that doesn't have to have a coach yelling in
his ear because I yell at myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Already considered a hard worker who avidly studies game film _
Ellis has a video library in his home of all his games and opposing
offensive tackles _ the personal dissatisfaction of his rookie
campaign resulted in an off-season of even harder work and more
study of film.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking he gained too much weight as a rookie, Ellis trimmed 10
pounds off his playing weight and reduced his 40-yard dash time
from 4.7 seconds to 4.6.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weight doesn't seem like a whole lot, but it is to me,''
Ellis said. ``I feel lighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Also helping hasten his improvement was the team's move back to
a traditional 4-3 defensive alignment from the overshifted 4-3
scheme they used last season. Jeffcoat said Ellis is succeeding
more because he is being used to his fullest ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got him in a position to attack the quarterback and be more
of a playmaker,'' Jeffcoat said. ``He's not in there battling a
340-pound tackle head up. He's on the edge outside the tight end or
the tackle like he was in college.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, who plays tackle in the Cowboys' nickel pass-rush unit,
has recorded 13 tackles, a forced fumble and four quarterback
pressures to go with the sacks and touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But, more importantly, owner Jones' safe pick is no longer
considered a bust. Ellis has justified the Cowboys' faith that he
was not only the safe pick in the 1998 draft, but the right pick.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Ellis is proving what the Cowboys always thought:
that he is a great player as well as a great person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with his play from the standpoint of him being the
eighth pick in the draft,'' Jones said. ``He makes us look good.
Greg Ellis is a player. He is going to be a great player for a long
time to come.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Tangie's sake, the shell game has ended. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
